<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOXY STRATEGY PAID OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ After the Travis Knight tryout, the Dennis
Rodman experiment, a dash of Robert Horry and heavy doses of J.R.
Reid, the Los Angeles Lakers' season-long game of power-forward
roulette continued Wednesday. And the spinning wheel settled on an
unlikely candidate to take on the Spurs' Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Fox. All 6 feet, 7 inches and 242 pounds of him. Bodying up
against the 7 feet and 255 pounds of Duncan, the Spurs' second-year
forward and MVP candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The goofy part is it worked.
</P>
<P>
   Until Duncan's game-winning jumpshot _ when Fox was on the bench
_ Duncan had made 7 of 18 shots for 19 points, hardly a devastating
performance. Most of those misses came with Fox guarding Duncan,
swiping the ball from him twice. In the second and third quarters,
Duncan was 2 for 9 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not only happy with (Fox's defense), but I think J.R.
(Reid) did a good job on him, too,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``We
did a much better job _ we were much more aggressive in our drops
and digs, we were much more aggressive in our traps. Even though we
still messed it up now and again, we were much more
aggressive-minded defensively throughout the entire ballgame than
we were in Game 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a small forward who's also spent long minutes at shooting
guard, is more than happy to take on the task of slowing the
multitalented Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty confident that I can play adequate post
defense,'' he said. ``I would say that we had some success. It
wasn't great success _ we didn't come away with the win. But if I'm
asked to do that again, I welcome that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis said the Lakers will use the small lineup again and try
to exploit it further, especially on offense, where Duncan has to
step away from the basket to guard the quicker Fox on the
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do a very good job of getting Rick involved to put
pressure on Duncan,'' Rambis said. ``That's something to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis is mulling one other unique lineup, but he won't say what
it is. The Lakers have already used 6-7 Kobe Bryant at point guard
once and might do it again.
</P>
<P>
   __ History: In the L.A. era, the Lakers have been down 0-2 in a
series 14 times. They came back to win the series only once, in the
1969 Western Division Finals against San Francisco. In 1995 the
Lakers were also down 0-2 to San Antonio in the conference
semifinals, and lost 4-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
