<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5659 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROYALS-OWNERSHIP-KAN &LR;      05-21 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYALS-OWNERSHIP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DELAY APPEAR LIKELY IN ROYALS OWNERSHIP DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Miles Prentice got half a loaf Thursday when
his proposal to buy the Kansas City Royals was placed on Major
League Baseball's ownership committee agenda but not on the agenda
for the big meeting of all baseball owners.
</P>
<P>
   That means it is unlikely that Prentice's bid will be approved
June 10 when baseball owners meet. It also implies that some owners
have questions about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice called the development ``another step of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Royals President Mike Herman said he remained optimistic and
said no baseball owners had told him they objected to Prentice.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the development was a bit of a letdown. Prentice
and the Royals had hoped the team's sale could get its final
blessing in three weeks. Now, a delay of months or at least weeks
appears likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is disappointing,'' said Joe McGuff, a Royals director.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's ownership committee, made up of eight major-league
owners and three league officials, studies proposed ownership
changes and sends its recommendation to the general meeting of all
baseball owners, typically the following day. That's when the final
votes are taken. That meeting is in three weeks in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the ownership committee wants to talk about the
Prentice deal but has not committed to send it up for a final vote
implies that some owners have serious questions, said Doug Pappas,
an official with the Society for American Baseball Research in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't take it as a good sign,'' Pappas said. ``If this
were a deal that was going to sail through, I think they could do
it both in the same meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, he does not think the owners are
looking for reasons to turn down the Prentice deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they would like to have a solid, stable ownership
group there,'' Pappas said. ``To the extent they do raise
objections, I don't think they would be doing it just for the sake
of sabotaging the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman said he had heard no serious objections, only questions
about money. Because the Royals have lost money in the past,
baseball owners want some assurance that the Prentice group is
sturdy enough to withstand losses without collapsing or triggering
an ownership crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice has worked out what he has termed ``a mechanism'' to
solve possible money problems in the future. He hasn't made that
public.
</P>
<P>
   Herman thinks the ownership committee wants that mechanism
explained in detail.
</P>
<P>
   Herman said he and Royals Chairman David Glass planned to fly to
Pittsburgh to meet with the ownership committee.
</P>
<P>
   Herman said: ``What we've heard is, `Can you show their ability
to finance and keep a team in Kansas City?' I think Miles has
addressed it. I see no reason why it won't go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman said he spoke to Bill Bartholomay of the Atlanta Braves,
who is chairman of the ownership committee, ``and Bill was very
encouraged and pleased. I said, `Is there anything we should be
prepared for to be asked?' And he said, `No. The usual types of
questions will be asked.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Prentice has not been invited to the meeting of the ownership
committee but would go if asked, said Prentice's spokesman, Michael
Grimaldi.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice said the development Thursday ``is another step of
progress toward completion of our investor group's goal to acquire
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Royals fans have expressed to me their natural impatience
with the process,'' he said. ``But it's an irrefutable truth that
progress takes time. We have said from the beginning, more than a
year ago, that we believe in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals have been without a permanent owner since Ewing M.
Kauffman died in 1993. Prentice's $75 million bid for the Royals
was approved by Royals directors last November after a long search.
Since then, the bid has been awaiting approval from baseball
owners.
</P>
<P>
   On a separate matter, Herman said the Royals were still intent
on trading at least one of their top-paid players so the team would
have money to pay for draft picks next month.
</P>
<P>
   The right deal hasn't turned up, but he thinks it will. ``It's a
seller's market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By dumping one or two big salaries, the Royals would have enough
money to sign the six players they will pick in the first two
rounds of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Herman estimates that the Royals will need $7 million to $8
million to sign those prospects. The Royals have already spent $2.7
million to sign pitcher Jeff Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I've got to get the payroll down to sign those players,''
Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   He was reluctant to name any player who could be traded, but the
candidates are not secret.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-paid players and their reported salaries this year:
Kevin Appier, $4.8 million; Jeff King, $4 million; Jeff Montgomery,
$2.5 million; and Hipolito Pichardo, $2.5 million. Pichardo is out
for the season after surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
