<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5661 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-ROBINSON-HN     05-21 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ROBINSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ Shaquille O'Neal just knew what David Robinson was
going to do. He just knew the San Antonio center was going to lob
up another outside jumper.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robinson glanced at the clock, which was winding down in Game 2
of the Western Conference semifinals game against the Lakers, and
nearly everyone in the Alamodome crowd of 33,293 warily eyed the
clock with him.
</P>
<P>
   There was just over a minute to play, and the score was tied.
And Robinson had the ball. O'Neal crouched, because he knew
Robinson was going to let it fly any second.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson twitched, tensing as if to shoot, and O'Neal pounced.
But there was no jumper. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal in the air, Robinson made his move. He went
baseline, curled around the basket and threw down a two-handed slam
that left the backboard rattling and put the Spurs up 75-73 with a
minute left.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs would hold on to win 79-76, taking a 2-0 lead in the
best-of-seven series that resumes Saturday in Los Angeles, but
Robinson's play would be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, everyone was talking about Tim Duncan's short jump hook
with 8.4 seconds left that gave the Spurs their last lead, and how
the Lakers' Kobe Bryant went from hero to goat in the space of 36
seconds, missing two free throws, turning the ball over and then
missing a running 3-point attempt as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson's play was just as big.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge play,'' the Spurs' Mario Elie said. ``Shaq's a
big guy, and David has to utilize his talents against him. David is
very quick, and he did a great job pump-faking Shaq. But that's
what a veteran team does _ just make plays in key situations. And
that's what David did. I guess he's tired of hearing it from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. After the slam, Robinson even showed a little emotion,
clenching his fists and giving them just the slightest, tiniest
pump.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost as if Robinson was trying emotionalism on for
size, like a kid venturing out toward the end of the diving board,
taking those first, furtive bounces, just to see what it's like.
</P>
<P>
   Not because he's a 7-1 cold fish. Quite the opposite. It's just
that Robinson abhors anything that might embarrass or show up an
opponent. And he hates calling attention to himself, so he keeps
his demeanor reserved, regardless of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Referees make a bad call? Most of the time Robinson will just
jog downcourt and get ready for the next play. Tense situation in a
big game? You probably couldn't tell by looking at Robinson, who is
usually the great stoneface.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wear my emotions on my sleeve like an Avery (Johnson)
or a Mario,'' Robinson, 33, said. ``That's just not my style. It's
not my style to spit on the court and to curse the referees out.
That's not my thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the referees decide what the game is. I think
you decide what the game is. I'm going to be my own worst critic
when I come out here. I just don't believe in dancing around when
you're 20 points down and you get a dunk. I don't think that's
basketball. I don't think that means anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that stoic demeanor that gets him grief from fans, who want
their heroes to be fist-pumping, screaming, smack-talking.
</P>
<P>
   He's the exact opposite of O'Neal, the Lakers center/cottage
industry. No tattoos. No rap songs. He's not an actor, even though
if you've seen one of O'Neal's movies (and chances are you
haven't), you probably would say he's not an actor, either.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, Robinson is a basketball player. Period.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personality is such that I think of this as a job,''
Robinson said of his NBA career. ``I think of it as, `I have to
come out here and work myself, I have to work my body, I have to
get myself ready.' And it's fun when things work out and you start
getting guys to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   There are times, though, when Robinson feels out of place. Or
perhaps it would be more accurate to say he feels out of time.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson sometimes winces at the images he sees on TV. Hot-dog
plays. Wagging taunting fingers in an opponent's face after a
blocked shot. Prancing and preening after a dunk _ even though your
team trails by 20 points. Individualism sells in the NBA, and it
sells big.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way the world is,'' Robinson said, shrugging.
``That's just the way the world is. People like the flamboyant
guys. They like the guys who don't like to pass and do all the
crazy stuff. That stuff, I guess, is more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to Robinson. No, that's not the way Robinson believes it
should be done, and if there's one thing that goes a long way on
the Admiral's ship, it's belief.
</P>
<P>
   Belief in God, fair play and teamwork. Belief in doing things
the right way, as an individual and a team. All of which makes
Robinson an anachronism. And Robinson sometimes thinks he belongs
to another era.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit,'' Robinson said. ``Believing in the team thing
and winning and building instead of hiring a mercenary. You have a
Charles Barkley or a Scottie Pippen on the block, and you try to
get your championship right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think that's how you build teams. I think all the
winning teams I've seen have worked together, went through some
challenges; they lost some games, but then they finally figured it
out and got the right team together.''
</P>
<P>
   Something the Spurs have never done. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Since his first game with the Spurs in 1989, Robinson has played
for seven coaches _ Larry Brown, Bob Bass, Jerry Tarkanian
(remember him?), Rex Hughes, John Lucas, Bob Hill and current boss
Gregg Popovich _ all of whom wanted something different from the
versatile Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way he has won a scoring title (1994, when he averaged
29.8 points), a Most Valuable Player Award (1995) and a Defensive
Player of the Year Award (1992), but he has never won an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   And Robinson thinks that might be partly the Spurs' fault,
because they've never stuck with a system long enough to develop
into a consistent force in the league, like the Jazz has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years my role has changed from this to that to this
to that,'' Robinson said. ``You may say that (his versatility) is
not a problem, but when we don't win, it becomes my problem. When
you get a team together and you can build it and work at it. For
example, look at Utah. Karl Malone is limited in some ways, but,
shoot, they've used him the same way for the last 15 years and now
they're at a point where they execute without thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been able to refine what he does in that system. But for
me, that's been one of the hard things. We're switching from system
to system, and it gets to the point where it's almost, `OK, so what
do you want me to do today, coach?' And that's a tough situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Like when Duncan arrived as the No. 1 pick in the 1997 NBA
draft. Robinson, coming off a season in which he played just six
games because of back and knee problems, was asked to step out of
the post to accommodate the 7-foot Duncan. By doing so, Robinson
gave up more than his position on the floor _ he surrendered shots
and gave up his role as the No. 1 offensive option. And remember,
he was just four years removed from leading the league in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   They meshed well last season, with Duncan averaging 21.1 points
and Robinson 21.6, but this season Robinson was asked to take on
more of a defensive presence and give up more of his offensive
game.
</P>
<P>
   The transition has worked for the Spurs, who won 31 of their
last 36 regular-season games this year and captured the home-court
advantage throughout the playoffs. Duncan averaged 21.7 points and
Robinson a career-low 15.8, but the Spurs are winning, and that's
all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we've come a long way as a team, and I've come a
long way figuring out what to do with this groove,'' Robinson said.
``But obviously there's a lot of things I have to figure out,
especially with my game, where I was getting the ball down there in
the post so much, and now I get a lot of face-up shots, so I need
to get a feel as to when to take those shots. I still don't think I
have a great feel for that, but I'm getting there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
