u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT &LR;      05-21 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 GRAND SLAMS BY VENTURA SPARK METS VICTORIES IN DOUBLEHEADER
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Theirs were the two faces and divergent moods of the
New York Mets on Thursday: pitcher Al Leiter stalking off the mound
after each inning, his face etched with a grimace, muttering oaths
of frustration to himself, nearly every pitch a struggle while
Robin Ventura floated effortlessly around the bases after two
nearly identical grand slams.
</P>
<P>
   Staked to a 4-0 lead from Ventura's first-inning slam in the
first game of the Mets' doubleheader against Milwaukee (the second
came in the second game, a 10-1 Mets victory) and buoyed by the
productive Mets bats, Leiter took full advantage of his wide margin
for error, pitching poorly but still getting the win in a 11-10
Mets victory that featured 25 total hits and one game-ending throw
to the plate to nab what would have been the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Leiter's second win against four losses in nine
starts. Although the sweep of the double-header indicated that the
Mets' bats are at last very much alive _ they hit six home runs
(two by Benny Agbayani, who was 4-4 in the first game) and had 24
hits in two games _ they did little to assauge concern that the
pitcher the Mets need if they are to make a legitimate run at the
post-season is up to the task. In five innings, he gave up six runs
on nine hits. In 55 innings pitched this season, Leiter has allowed
42 runs (39 earned) on 64 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Words only go so far,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``You
need action and the win today was action. Regardless of how it
looked or how tough it was to get, he's going home with one more
win than he had before.''
</P>
<P>
   During Leiter's struggles, Masato Yoshii has emerged,
unexpectedly, as the Mets' most consistent starter. He faltered
early in the season, but with a shift on the pitching rubber, he
has won his last three starts and on Thursday night, in the second
game of the double header, Yoshii (4-3) gave up just one run on
eight hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   He was the beneficiary of Ventura's second grand slam, to almost
exactly the same spot over the right field wall as the first one.
It gave the Mets (23-18) a 9-0 lead in the fourth inning and made
Ventura the first person in major league history to hit a grand
slam in each game of a double header. Ventura is now an incredible
6-9 (.667) this season with the bases loaded with 12 RBI and in his
career has 134 RBI in 118 at-bats with the bases loaded. In 1995,
while he was with the White Sox, Ventura hit two grand slams in one
game, but last night, he said, was better than that feat.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's different because it affects two games,'' Ventura said.
``It's a little more satisfying. It's a good day to have a double
header.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ventura's numbers are staggering, then Leiter's are simply
surprising. Leiter's ERA has ballooned to 6.38, but he, and the
organization, insist that his stuff is as good as last year. On
Thursday night, Leiter self-destructed in every possible way. There
were wild pitches, full counts, a hit batsman, and hit after hit
after hit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his clear agitation throughout his outing, a visibly
relieved Leiter professed only happiness afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ''So many times, it's good effort, seven innings, one run and
nothing to show for it,'' Leiter said. ``Wins are precious and I'll
take a win anytime. I believe if I continue to do what I'm doing,
things will turn. Hopefully, from now on, the jam shots will be
caught and the goofiness during games will go my way.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of goofiness in the first game, and it remained
Leiter's for the taking because his counterpart, the Brewers' Jim
Abbott (who took the loss to drop to 0-5), was equally ineffective
and because both teams' hitters feasted on the messy pitches served
up by every pitcher who dared take the mound. Leiter gave up three
runs in the third inning and another in the fourth to tie the
score.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets got a run back in the fourth, but in the fifth, his
final inning, Leiter crumbled again. He gave up a leadoff single to
Cirillo, then hit Bernitz in the back. Grissom and Hughes both
flied out. But Ochoa, the number seven batter, hit a double to
right center that scored two to give the Brewers a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   While Leiter struggled, the rest of the Mets reveled in nearly
non-stop success at the plate. They retook the lead in the bottom
of the fifth when Agbayani hit a three-run homer off Milwaukee
reliever Steve Falteisek. In the next inning, Piazza hit a 1-0
changeup 418 feet to dead center to extend the lead to 10-6.
Agbayani, who was called up from Norfolk when Bobby Bonilla went on
the disabled list, hit his second home run in the seventh inning to
up the lead to 11-6. Agbayani is batting .519 and his four RBIs was
a career high.
</P>
<P>
   ''Benny is the player of the week, I guess,'' Valentine said.
``I wasn't going to bring him up just to pinch hit. There was a
starting opportunity and he's made the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Brewers scored three in the eighth, and only a
spectacular play on the final out of the game saved Leiter's
precarious win. With two out and two on against reliever John
Franco, pinch hitter Sean Berry lofted what looked to be an easy
pop fly to Alfonzo. But Alfonzo dropped the ball and Grissom came
around to score. Ochoa, though, was not running hard because he had
lost a shoe. Roger Cedeno's throw from shallow right field nailed
Ochoa, who would have been the 11th run, by two feet at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura grinned sheepishly after the long night trying to
explain his home runs. And finally, there was a smile on Leiter's
face, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
