<HEADLINE>
CHURCH HAS BEEN A SANCTUARY FOR SEATTLE'S JAPANESE AMERICAN
COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Above the altar at Japanese Baptist Church of Seattle,
near a row of windows lighting the six-sided sanctuary, hangs a
framed piece of Japanese calligraphy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kamiwa ai nari,'' the words read. Translated, the expression
is simple yet profound: ``God is love.''
</P>
<P>
   That message has comforted Seattle's first Japanese Christian
congregation over the past century, through waves of immigration,
periods of war, changes in location and shifts in demographics.
</P>
<P>
   The red brick church on the corner of Broadway and East Spruce
Street, once the heart of the Japanese American community, will
celebrate its 100th anniversary starting Friday. Thc &LR; i!5 of the
three-day event is ``Pass the Torch to New Generations.''
</P>
<P>
   In theHJR9lierIQ
</P>
</TEXT>
