A5671 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXSIDE-LADN-(SLA     05-21 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXSIDE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA NOT AMONG THE ELITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ If anyone has the perspective to evaluate Oscar De
La Hoya's place in history, it's Emanuel Steward, who trained De La
Hoya and Tommy Hearns and saw Sugar Ray Leonard, Marvin Hagler and
Roberto Duran from the opposite corner.
</P>
<P>
   How would the Golden Boy have fit in with that bunch? Well, let
Steward deliver the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the talent to be right with them,'' he said. ``But he
hasn't developed into a complete professional fighter. They're a
little better all around than Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so frustrating. He's so talented, but he does basically
the same thing all the time. I'd rather see his upper body rolling
and twisting like Leonard and those guys used to do. He could fit
in with those guys, but I don't know if he could beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   So why hasn't De La Hoya developed?
</P>
<P>
   Steward points to his trainer, Robert Alcazar. Alcazar has
worked with De La Hoya since his amateur days but doesn't have the
experience of the top trainers.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya and his advisors seem to believe the same thing:
They've brought in three more-seasoned trainers to lend their
expertise. However, Gil Clancy, the latest addition, will not be
asked back after Saturday's fight against Oba Carr.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, some believe, De La Hoya will be training himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Alcazar has the ability to take Oscar to the
level he needs to go,'' Steward said. ``There are certain things he
needs to do, and Alcazar doesn't have the knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Alcazar is) his daddy's longtime buddy. To keep peace, Oscar
almost has to stay with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward, who worked with De La Hoya for two fights before he was
dismissed because he clashed with the fighter's father, Joel De La
Hoya, believes De La Hoya will improve naturally as he continues to
fight top-level opponents.
</P>
<P>
   However, that will only go so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can a fighter develop on his own? Not as a rule,'' Steward
said. ``It's frustrating. It really is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
