<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ WORKS ON CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers left-hander Carlos Perez lost
6 mph off his fastball and lost his control, which has led to the
worst start of his four-year career.
</P>
<P>
   The club is hoping Perez's 18-minute bullpen session in front of
pitching coach Charlie Hough and Dodgers pitching coordinator Jim
Benedict solved the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict spent four seasons in the same capacity with the
Montreal Expos when Perez was pitching north of the border. He said
Perez's struggles aren't new.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the maintenance of Carlos Perez,'' Benedict said
before the Dodgers and Houston Astros played Thursday at Dodger
Stadium. ``We were trying to create an angle for the ball's flight
from the release point to the catcher's glove. He was flying open.
It's a result of coming off the (pitching) rubber too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll lose deception. If you don't have deception, 91 (mph)
becomes 85, and the changeup is something that is very visual.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez normally throws a fastball 91 or 92 mph, but Hough said
he's been clocked in the low 80s his past few starts. That's also
made Perez's changeup, his best pitch, more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   It has caused Perez to start the season 1-5 with 6.63 ERA. He
lasted only 31/3 innings in his last outing, giving up six runs on
five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm too quick in my legs,'' said Perez, who starts
Sunday against St. Louis. ``I'm only using my arm, and that's why I
had no velocity. That's why I also (lost) velocity later in the
game. It also hurts my control.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez said he'll throw bullpen sessions between starts,
something he normally doesn't do, in an effort to remain sharp.
</P>
<P>
   __ Osuna surgery successful: Recently disabled right-handed
reliever Antonio Osuna underwent successful surgery to remove a
bone spur from his pitching elbow Thursday at Centinela Hospital
Medical Center. The surgery was performed by team physicians Dr.
Frank Jobe and Dr. Ralph Gambardella.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who had a bone spur removed from the same spot last
September, is expected to miss two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a small piece of bone outgrown in the back of the
elbow,'' Dr. Jobe said. ``It's more like a pea in your shoe, stuck
there. It looked more like a piece he broke off after the last
surgery. It would kind of pinch him after he extended his elbow.
That's where the pain came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he'll be able to return to his regular method of
throwing. I thought his ligaments were in good shape. I think he'll
be fine now that we've got this rock out of his shoe.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Pena gets start: Lefty Mike Hampton started for Houston,
which means catcher Todd Hundley sat. So rookie Angel Pena,
recalled Tuesday from Triple-A Albuquerque, got his first start.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he isn't concerned about the
offensive output from Pena, who hit .231 during six games last
season with the Dodgers, but rather Pena's defensive prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it looks like his setup got a little more polished
from the spring,'' Johnson said. ``I liked his setup and it's
gotten better. That part of the game _ the blocking, the throwing
is pretty good. I was impressed with some of his signal-calling,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitting Hundley has started one game against
left-handers and is hitless in nine at-bats from the right side.
Johnson said Pena will start Sunday against St. Louis lefty Darren
Oliver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
