<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-ANNIVERSARY-SP     05-21 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-ANNIVERSARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH HAS BEEN A SANCTUARY FOR SEATTLE'S JAPANESE AMERICAN
COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Above the altar at Japanese Baptist Church of Seattle,
near a row of windows lighting the six-sided sanctuary, hangs a
framed piece of Japanese calligraphy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kamiwa ai nari,'' the words read. Translated, the expression
is simple yet profound: ``God is love.''
</P>
<P>
   That message has comforted Seattle's first Japanese Christian
congregation over the past century, through waves of immigration,
periods of war, changes in location and shifts in demographics.
</P>
<P>
   The red brick church on the corner of Broadway and East Spruce
Street, once the heart of the Japanese American community, will
celebrate its 100th anniversary starting Friday. The theme of the
three-day event is ``Pass the Torch to New Generations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier part of the century, prejudice kept people of
Japanese ancestry from gathering in certain areas, said Hisako
Arakawa, the church moderator, or president.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't go downtown. Most of them lived around this area
since the Depression days,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not just for (Japanese) Baptist people, but for all Japanese
people, this was the place to congregate.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven immigrants, including the Rev. Fukumatsu Okazaki, who
served for more than 30 years, organized the church on May 23,
1899. Offering services in Japanese, the church added about 100
converts in its first decade.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the congregation counts about 200 regulars for services
in Japanese and English.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Japanese American community in general, interracial
families are increasingly common at the church. And like other
congregations borne by an ethnic group, the culture is interwoven
in the fabric of church life.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked in some corners of the church are graceful ikebana flower
arrangements. The pine tree in the courtyard behind the altar is
pruned in a classical Japanese style. Wood-frame windows with
rice-paper panes adorn the memorial chapel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potlucks are the best,'' member Andy Iwata said,
salivating at the thought of sushi and teriyaki, along with
American foods.
</P>
<P>
   For Jane Cho, whose grandparents were among the early members,
the church has ``always felt like home,'' even when she lived away
from Seattle. The Japanese Baptist Church was ``where my faith
grew,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry of the church over the years reflected changes in
Japanese American society.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, the church helped female Japanese
immigrants, including the ``picture brides'' coming to Seattle to
marry Japanese men with whom they had exchanged photographs.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13 hotels and rooming houses that catered to Japanese men
at the time, ``no safe and decent place could be found for a
woman,'' according to an article by the American Baptist Home
Mission Society.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Okazaki's wife, Yoshiko, opened a Christian
residence known as Fujin Home, which later became a training center
for young married couples and provided classes in English and on
the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The church first met on Jefferson and Jackson streets, then on
Washington Street, where young Japanese living in the church
dormitory would get homesick hearing the train whistles from Union
Station. The church moved to its present site in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Members organized Scout troops and competed in church league
athletics, filling shelves with trophies.
</P>
<P>
   When people of Japanese ancestry on the West Coast were
imprisoned in the hysteria following Japan's bombing of Pearl
Harbor in 1941, church members were among those sent to a barren
camp at Minidoka, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in hard times, they had their faith in God,'' Arakawa
said. ``They had this determination.''
</P>
<P>
   When the war ended, the church's denomination _ now known as
American Baptist Churches in the U.S.A. _ didn't want the Japanese
Baptist Church to re-establish, perhaps for safety reasons, Arakawa
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Emery ``Andy'' Andrews, a Caucasian, was adamant
that the church survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the major denominations after World War II wanted to
assimilate all the ethnic minority groups, especially Japanese
Americans,'' said the Rev. Paul Nagano, pastor from 1971 to 1986.
``I thought, `No, we've got to affirm who we are. We should take
pride in our backgrounds as Japanese Americans.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Alfred Van Selow, the current pastor, said reaching
people of different ethnic backgrounds requires cultural
sensitivity without dilution of the Gospel message.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be very certain that you do not mistake culture
for faith,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While church members once lived mostly in the neighborhood, the
congregation now is far flung, with worshipers coming from as far
as the Washinton communities of Fall City, Lynnwood and Winslow.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to the future, the congregation is attempting to reach
out more to younger families and to its surrounding community,
where the ethnic mix includes an influx of Southeast Asians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a large Nisei (second-generation Japanese American)
population in the church, but we also have to look at what we need
to do to serve the community,'' Iwata said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might not be a Japanese Baptist Church in the next 100
years. We have to look at that realistically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
