<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5689 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASTOR-MOOREHEAD-SPI &LR;      05-21 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTOR-MOOREHEAD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERS CHANGE STANCE ON SEXUAL MISCONDUCT ALLEGATIONS AGAINST
EX-PASTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Elders of Overlake Christian Church now have
testimony that supports allegations of sexual misconduct against
the Rev. Bob Moorehead, who resigned last year from Washington
state's largest congregation amid a cloud of suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   The elders have heard from multiple witnesses to corroborate at
least some of the allegations leveled against Moorehead, according
to a letter sent Thursday to members of the Redmond, Wash., church.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the elders dismissed allegations of sexual misconduct
against Moorehead by 17 men because they said the incidents
couldn't be substantiated by eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But since Moorehead stepped down last June, ``the eldership has
received testimony that meets the biblical standard of multiple
witnesses,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   The elders said they ``reviewed the entire matter and
unanimously concluded that Pastor Bob Moorehead did violate the
scriptural standards of trust, self-control, purity and Godly
character required for the office of elder and pastor'' at
Overlake.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 elders, who serve as the church's governing body, met
several weeks ago with Moorehead, presented him with the new
testimony and asked him to acknowledge their conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chose to reject the appeal for his acknowledgment,'' the
Rev. Rick Kingham, Moorehead's successor, said Thursday. Moorehead,
who steadfastly denied the accusations in the past, now lives in
Florida. Efforts to reach him Thursday night for comment were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the elders publicly acknowledged in their
letter that they were prepared to ask for Moorehead's resignation
last year _ even before receiving the latest evidence _ ``because
his reputation and witness in the community (were) damaged beyond
repair.''
</P>
<P>
   The elders did not talk earlier about asking Moorehead to quit
because ``at the point Pastor Bob resigned, there was not the need
to say it,'' Kingham said.
</P>
<P>
   Moorehead's decision to step down ``was not because the elders
pressed him to do that. That was of his own choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingham, who also serves as an elder, was not at Overlake when
the elders investigated Moorehead.
</P>
<P>
   The elders also announced a new written policy and procedure to
follow when any serious allegations are made against an elder,
pastor or other staff member. No written policy previously existed
that adequately addressed the issue, Kingham said.
</P>
<P>
   Any serious allegation brought against a church staff member or
elder, including the senior pastor, ``will cause that person to be
immediately suspended pending a full investigation,'' the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kingham said the policy and procedures are intended to be as
``user-friendly'' as possible because of the discomfort members may
have in accusing a church leader of misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sinclair, a former pastor at Overlake, left the church in
1997 over concerns about Moorehead's conduct. Asked for comment
Thursday night on the elder's letter, Sinclair said, ``I think it's
a good start, but it's just a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingham said it was critical for Overlake ``to bring some
closure to this issue. It's been going on for a period of time. For
the spiritual health of the church, the elders felt it was
important to make a statement, especially in light of the
conclusions that came.''
</P>
<P>
   The elders struck a conciliatory tone in their letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ordinary and fallible men earnestly seeking God's will
and endeavoring to do what is right,'' they wrote. ``Where we have
failed to correctly perceive God's will, we are sorry and seek your
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Godly leadership to which elders are called requires that
they seek wisdom, righteousness and unanimity in every decision. A
great deal of prayer accompanies our decision-making process. Our
greatest desire is to serve you, our church family, in a
God-honoring way.''
</P>
<P>
   About 4,500 people regularly attend Sunday services at Overlake.
</P>
<P>
   Moorehead came under scrutiny starting in late 1997 when it was
publicly disclosed that he had been arrested in Daytona Beach,
Fla., in July 1996 and charged with masturbating in a public
restroom.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were dropped under controversial circumstances, but
the disclosure of his arrest prompted several men to come forward
last year with allegations that Moorehead sexually molested them
during adult baptism and wedding ceremonies in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The elders hired a private investigator who reported that 17 men
made accusations. But the elders said scripture required at least
one witness for an allegation to be substantiated.
</P>
<P>
   That interpretation drew criticism from other pastors and Bible
scholars. Some elders later said they followed a correct process,
but had made mistakes and that their actions were open to scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the accusations in the investigator's report stemmed
from alleged incidents in the '70s, elder Gary Scott said last
year. Of the 17 men making direct accusations, one group included
those who said they were groped or fondled, another group believed
they were the victims of incidental sexual touching and a third
concluded that Moorehead attempted to touch them inappropriately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
