<HEADLINE>
BROAD, NFL WILL DISCUSS ALTERNATIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ With a meeting scheduled for early next week with
NFL owners, Eli Broad said he will present four alternatives to
area parking problems and has reduced the proposed size of the
Coliseum to 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Coliseum would still be expandable to 80,000 for Super
Bowls, and USC games against UCLA and Notre Dame, by adding
temporary seats.
</P>
<P>
   Broad, the billionaire who joined Ed Roski Jr. to lead the New
Coliseum effort, said Thursday his group has also developed answers
to NFL concerns about financing, marketing and stadium design, and
will present them at the ownership meetings in Atlanta on Monday.
Broad said his proposals will help distance his group from rival
Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to conclude that we could be finished in time for
the 2002 fall season,'' Broad said.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL awarded Los Angeles a conditional expansion franchise
last March and selected the Coliseum as the stadium site six weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   That left Ovitz, who had championed Carson as his preferred
stadium site, at a major disadvantage in trying to suddenly
formulate new plans for the Coliseum. He did not return phone calls
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said he has also hired one of the country's top
advertising firms, Deutch-LA Inc., to formulate a marketing
program.
</P>
<P>
   He met with NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue earlier this week to
discuss the package his group will present to the NFL expansion
committee Monday night. Ovitz will also present his new plans.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has given Los Angeles until Sept. 15 to meet its various
requirements, or said the expansion franchise would shift to
Houston. Broad would like the NFL to announce the franchise fee and
new owner at next week's meetings to meet the September deadline,
but he said it might now be unlikely to happen in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said his four parking solutions included an
all-underground proposal, which Ovitz has promoted, but said that
plan would cost $270 million. The renovation of the Coliseum is
expected to cost $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their call,'' Broad said. ``We do not recommend going to
this underground parking scheme that someone else is proposing. But
we're prepared to do it if that's what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad said his group will recommend one of the four plans that
would cost between $80 million and $90 million, and include a
parking structure. He said the current environmental-impact report
allows for one parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   John Semcken, executive vice president of the New Coliseum
group, said the structure would combine with previous parking plans
to provide 17,500 spaces. The NFL had talked about having as many
as 27,000 parking spaces at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said the one-structure plan would include using some USC
parking and a shuttle service to empty lots downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of other things that are going on,'' Broad
said. ``There is a possibility that the Blue Line could be extended
to the Coliseum, which would allow fans from Long Beach and/or the
Valley, not to have to drive downtown at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL implied it was not fully satisfied with the Roski-Broad
rennovation for the Coliseum when it opened up stadium-design
plans, but Semcken said his group had made only minor changes in
their plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing they were concerned about in our design was,
because of the size of our market, they felt we should have more
club seats than the 15,000 we originally proposed,'' Semcken said.
``So we increased that number to 17,200. Other than that, it wasn't
a major change in the design.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad said he will present a detailed financial plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will show a hefty amount of equity _ at least $400
million,'' he said. ``The financial plan will also show what we can
accomplish in terms of some public support. The parking will be
used not only for the Coliseum but the museums and might be part of
a park-and-ride situation and some other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad also mentioned he plans to meet with former Denver Broncos
quarterback John Elway for a second time to discuss the possibility
of the former player becoming team president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
