<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THAT NOISE YOU HEARD WAS IMPORTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You could hear they were New Yorkers even before
spotting the orange and blue colors supporting the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Loud and familiar and pointed, these fans made up fully one
quarter of Thursday night's sellout crowd of 22,558 in the looming
Georgia Dome. They gave a verbal touch of Noo Yawk as the Knicks
humbled the home team, 77-70, to make it two straight in their
second-round playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   The New York fans outyelled their counterparts about the same
way that Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby _ the two lithe athletes
Ernie Grunfeld acquired _ cut through the weary Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   The game itself was a stinker, with Patrick Ewing deploying
himself as a decoy on leaden legs, Allan Houston unable to get off
a good shot, and Steve Smith of the Hawks barely able to get off
the ground. And this is only the second round at the end of the
short, grim season.
</P>
<P>
   At least the New York fans were up for it. When Camby made a
Pippenesque flying dunk late in the game, it was as if he had done
it in Madison Square Garden. And when the Hawks could not even
reach the rim in the final minute, the resounding chant of ``Air
ball! Air ball!'' echoed throughout the dome.
</P>
<P>
   Who were these people? Some of them were transplanted New
Yorkers, brought here by the vicissitudes of transient corporate
life. Others were current New Yorkers who realized they had a
better shot at buying tickets here than at the fat-cat emporium on
Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Estrella from the Washington Heights section of Manhattan
had bought his tickets on the Internet and flown down, via Dallas,
for $250, a bargain for Knicks tickets up north. He even brought
along his nephew.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Brown from Freeport, N.Y., said he drove down. Constantin
Marta from Howard Beach in Queens and Marco Buono from Mineola,
N.Y., couldn't stay away. There were fans wearing Starks jerseys,
Ewing jerseys, Houston jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Even factoring in the air fare, some of them were probably
saving money over what they would have to pay the friendly gents in
the shadows around the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to have fans behind you,'' said Chris Childs, who
did most of the work at point guard. ``Now we go home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same in Miami for the first game,'' Chris Dudley
noted the other day. ``There were guys with KNICKS painted on their
chests, just like Yankee fans. I think it helps us.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Hawks were not amused that Knicks' fans could
dominate the crowd of 18,513 during a 100-92 victory by the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' said Tyrone Corbin. ``It's in our home
building, and they're cheering for the other team. But it happens.
We can't get wrapped up in it.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a depressing playoff game by the home team would
prompt a massive volley of boos _ just to show that New Yorkers
care, in our own surly way. On Thursday night, many of the home
fans left in the final five minutes, leaving the people in blue and
orange to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that the Hawks are merely using the dome
while their new arena is being constructed just up the hill. The
Hawks also play some games at Georgia Tech, which produces an
identity crisis among fans, who never know where they are parking
or sitting.
</P>
<P>
   The man from Congo, Dikembe Mutombo is of the opinion that
Atlanta fans ``do not care for games,'' but he is only judging from
the tepid reception to his sport. For example, Ted Turner has not
been here for any of the five playoff games _ and he owns the team.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, of course, is that there is only one sport down here,
and that is the sport called ``foo'ball.'' The Falcons rarely fill
the dome's 71,000 seats, and the National Hockey League is
returning here, after failing once before. And the Braves, one of
the great baseball teams of the decade, do not always sell out
their playoff games, either.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the diffused nature of Atlanta, with its
_ shall we say? _ modest downtown, and suburbs that sprawl out to
Gingrich Country and beyond, dependent on clogged interstates.
Turner, the visionary, adamantly insisted on placing the new arena
next to the CNN building, rather than in the `burbs, but downtown
sports events do not produce much of a buzz.
</P>
<P>
   The way Sprewell and Camby outran the Hawks _ and the way
Knicks' fans outrooted Atlanta fans _ they probably can seal up the
dome, until it's time for foo'ball.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
