<HEADLINE>
ARTESIA HIGH STANDOUT PICKS UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Jason Kapono's performance on the
basketball court was fairly predictable during his Artesia High
career. No matter who the opponent was, there was little doubt
Kapono would deliver his usual 20-plus points, 10 rebounds, six
assists and overall stellar play night in and night out for the
Pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   So when the time came for Kapono to announce his collegiate
plans, you would think that he would stay true to form, right?
Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that's sure to be viewed as shocking to some, the
6-foot-8 standout announced that he would be following in the
footsteps of Artesia alums Ed and Charles O'Bannon and attend UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by parents Joe and Joni Kapono, sister Jillian, Pioneers
coach Wayne Merino and an estimated 40 supporters at Legend's
restaurant in the Belmont Shore section of Long Beach, Kapono chose
the Bruins over Missouri, which was thought to be a heavy favorite
during the recruiting process, ahead of Arizona and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in Los Angeles, I always watched UCLA play and I
dreamed about playing for the Bruins,'' Kapono said. ``I've also
dreamed about being able to contribute to my college team as a
freshman. This past summer, when the recruiting process began, I
didn't include them on my short list of schools because I didn't
see that happening at UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   But once the Bruins failed to sign two of the prep frontcourt
players they coveted _ Juneau, Alaska, power forward Carlos Boozer
and swingman Kareem Rush of Kansas City, and a pair of frontcourt
players decided to transfer from the school _ Kapono knew he had a
chance to step in and play immediately at one of the forward
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I feel that not only can I contribute at UCLA, but I can
contribute immediately,'' Kapono said. ``It's time to follow my
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapono rewrote the record books during his four-year stay at
Artesia. He's the school's all-time leader in points (2,678) and
several other categories. As a senior, he averaged 23.5 points, 9.0
rebounds, 7.6 assists and 3.3 steals in leading the Pioneers to a
second consecutive Southern Section Division I-AA title.
</P>
<P>
   A McDonald's All-American and Parade Magazine first-team
All-American, Kapono was the second-leading vote getter in the Long
Beach Press-Telegram's Best in the West basketball poll, and was
one of three players who finished as unanimous selections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
