<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BCS WILL REVAMP SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK GIRARDOT  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Bowl Championship Series proved anything last season, it
was that there is still no way to settle the debate over which
college football team is the nation's best.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS hopes to silence some of its critics this season by
adding two new computer formulas to its scoring system, officials
said this week.
</P>
<P>
   It will also tweak some of the more complicated aspects of the
rating system and likely give even more weight to a team's strength
of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this does is bring in more diversity and lessens the
impact of one individual computer poll,'' said Roy Kramer,
commissioner of the Southeastern Conference and mastermind of the
BCS.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS promises college football fans that the top two teams in
the country will play for the national championship during New
Year's week. In its current configuration the championship game
rotates among the Sugar, Orange, Fiesta and Rose bowls.
</P>
<P>
   This year the championship was played at the Fiesta Bowl. The
Rose Bowl will host in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Before being joined by the Rose Bowl, the BCS was called the
Bowl Alliance and relied mostly on The Associated Press media poll
and the USA Today-ESPN coaches poll to determine which teams would
play in the Sugar, Orange and Fiesta bowls.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the 1998 season, BCS standings were determined by a
combination of national polls, won-loss records, strength of
competition and computer rankings. After crunching all the numbers,
the BCS assigned each team a score. The lower a team's score, the
higher its BCS ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the BCS uses computer rankings from the New York
Times, the Seattle Times and college sports guru Jeff Sagarin of
Boston. Still the system can't get a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   One example: Through games of Nov. 21, the three computers came
up with three different No.1 teams _ UCLA, Kansas State and Florida
State _ while the coaches and writers had Tennessee and Kansas
State as their top choices. Because of its schedule strength and
the fact the Vols were undefeated, Tennessee got the top seed.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 82 other computer rankings available on the
Internet. Although most arrive at similar conclusions as to the top
team, filling in the blanks below is a free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS needs to determine which of those ranking systems best
fits its needs, Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   But, BCS officials also believe the computers currently in use
may have some built-in bias, according to Jack French, CEO of the
Tournament of Roses Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felt that last year there was some regional
discrimination and by adding some computers from the South or the
Southwest it might reduce the number of comments along those
lines,'' French said.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said the region where a computer ranking is generated
could become a factor in the BCS decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each computer has various factors that they consider,'' Kramer
said. ``The goal is to get all of the various factors together. It
would be to our advantage to have a group of diverse computer
rankings to give you the best possible composite ranking.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said the revamped BCS will be unveiled in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it worked extremely well the first year,'' he said.
``Whatever changes we have will be there because we just want to
add to the excitement of college football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
