<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5700 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-BOX-LADN     05-21 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-BOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PHANTOM' LANDS BELOW BOX-OFFICE ESTIMATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Force turned out be powerful indeed but
hardly overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's opening of ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom
Menace'' grossed $28.5 million at 2,970 U.S. theaters -- a
single-day record but far short of the $40 million-plus some
analysts predicted. Trackers offered mostly good news/bad news
reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number is quite disappointing because it's quite a bit
below consensus forecasts,'' said Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum's Barry
Hyman, who had predicted a $40 million box office take earlier this
week. ``On the other hand, I wouldn't be concerned if I were George
Lucas. Getting over $28 million in one day is still tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   The total, aided considerably by 2,011 shows starting a minute
after midnight, bested by 9 percent the single-day high of $26.1
million set by ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' generated ticket sales of 5.6 million; the
average theater took in $9,610 and sold nearly 2,000 tickets.
</P>
<P>
   It also in one day nearly matched the $28.6 million taken in by
``Titanic'' in its first three days in December 1997. But in a
business that thrives on hype, the combination of unenthusiastic
reviews and box office results below expectations underscore the
growing probability that ``Phantom Menace'' will not match the $601
million domestic total for ``Titanic'' nor its $1.8 billion
worldwide take.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, who issued a $42 million forecast Wednesday,
said issuing opening-day predictions is tricky because moviegoers
can be dissuaded from attending for a wide variety of reasons.
``The main thing that held down attendance was that Wednesday was
still not a holiday,'' he said. ``We were counting on the public to
be less morally responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a trio of factors led to the opening-day gross not
matching the inflated predictions:
</P>
<P>
   --The massive advance sales, which led to sellouts at the 12:01
a.m. and early-evening shows, did not translate into sell-outs for
the rest of the day. ``All these reports of soldout shows and huge
lines clearly made a lot of people decide to wait,'' said Linda
Bannister, analyst with Edward Jones in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day of a movie isn't like a piece of fruit that will
go bad if you don't eat it right away,'' agreed Kevin Skislock of
Laguna Research Partners. ``Today was the first day I thought about
even trying. So this may have been a victim of its own success
because everyone was expecting if they went they would not be able
to get a ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   --Heavy rains fell on the Northeast on Wednesday night. ``There
was horrendous weather on the East Coast, serious rain from Philly
to Boston for most of the evening and it wasn't just a drizzle
either,'' Hyman said. ``There were only 15 or 20 people in line at
some theaters last night in midtown Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   --The strong work ethic in Middle America and small towns held
down grosses for midnight and daytime shows. ``People want to see
it but I don't think we had a lot of people around St. Louis who
took off from work,'' Bannister said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than focus solely on the dark side, analysts emphasized
that setting a box office record at midweek on a nonholiday was an
impressive accomplishment. Lucas and 20th Century Fox decided in
March to move opening day from Friday to Wednesday in order to give
hard-core fans first crack at ``Phantom Menace'' and make it easier
for families with children to see the film on its first weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the first-day total is something for Lucas to be very
proud of,'' Bannister said. ``I think the expectations were out of
line.''
</P>
<P>
   David Davis, an entertainment analyst with investment bank
Houlihan Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin, agreed. ``I don't see anything
negative about the opening-day figure,'' he said. ``I still think
it's well-positioned to be one of the top two releases of all time.
There is going to be massive repeat viewing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum held on to his forecast that the movie will hit $135
million in the first five days and a final gross between $375
million and $410 million, citing the strong positive responses from
audiences. ``The word of mouth is far better than the reviews,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The current record for best five-day opening is ``Lost World''
with $92.7 million while ``Independence Day'' owns the mark for top
five-day debut for a movie opening on a Wednesday, with $85
million.
</P>
<P>
   Movie analyst Arthur Rockwell said it's still unclear how well
the movie will play once serious competition arrives. ``Clearly,
this is going to break records this week, but the question is what
kind of legs it will have,'' he added. ``One would still expect it
will dominate the early part of summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Fox distribution head Tom Sherak has a bullish
outlook. ``We're going to see the audience spread out this weekend
to a lot of kids and families because people know they'll be able
to get in,'' he said. ``This movie is going to take us on a roller
coaster ride and we're holding on for dear life.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
