<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL CHIMES IN TO BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The euphoria from pinch-hitter Tripp Cromer's
two-out, game-tying solo homer in the ninth inning against Houston
Astros closer Billy Wagner lasted less than half an inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was quickly transplanted by dejection after the Los Angeles
Dodgers' Jeff Shaw yielded a run-scoring double to Derek Bell in
the 10th inning as the Astros won 4-3 Thursday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cromer hit six homers in spring training, but had just two hits
this season. Wagner hadn't allowed a homer, nor did he blow a save
in his first 11 chances this season. So on a 2-2 pitch Cromer hit a
long homer into the left field bleachers to tie the score 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   But before Shaw could record an out in the top of the 10th
inning Craig Biggio walked and Bell doubled to the right-center to
give the Astros a 3-2 lead. An error by Dodgers third baseman
Adrian Beltre on Jeff Bagwell's grounder and a sacrifice fly from
Ken Caminiti made it 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner (1-1) recorded his first win while Shaw (1-2) lost for
the second time in the last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi hit a solo homer in the 10th for the Dodgers' third
run.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took a 2-1 lead in the top of the ninth by more
unconventional means thanks to a few miscues from Dodgers rookie
catcher Angel Pena. Houston's Carl Everett walked in the ninth,
stole second with one out and moved to third when Pena's throw went
into center field. Everett then scored on Alan Mills' wild pitch,
though it could have been blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Mills struck out Paul Bako but the ball went through Pena's legs
to allow Bako to go to first and Everett to score and break a 1-1
tie.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the strangest thing that happened on the base paths.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros stood on
third after apparently stealing second and moving up a base when
the catcher Bako's throw went into center field. It put the tying
run on third with one out of a one-run game.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until home plate umpire Ed Montague ruled batter's
interference on Devon White and also ruled Karros out.
</P>
<P>
   Inning over.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight night the Dodgers had a stolen base
taken away for batter's interference, but when it happened
Wednesday it was overshadowed by Kevin Brown's masterful eight
innings.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's 5-2 win, Adrian Beltre stole second but was sent
back to first when it was ruled Mondesi interfered with catcher
Tony Eusebio's throw to second.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, it threatened to destroy what was a
magnificent appearance by right-hander Chan Ho Park. The only run
he allowed came off Everett's bat, a solo homer to right field that
gave Houston a 1-0 lead in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's 430-foot blast landed in the orange seats on the
stadium's loge level, marking the sixth time in the 38-year history
of Dodger Stadium a home run landed on the loge level.
</P>
<P>
   Park wasn't as splendid as Kevin Brown was the night before, but
his seven innings of five-hit ball was a welcomed sight for the
Dodgers. Park's unwillingness to use his fastball in his previous
two starts brought the ire of Dodgers manager Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who entered the game 3-3 with a 5.32 ERA, used it against
the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the first five innings, Houston had at least one
baserunner. Twice the Astros had a runner on third with less than
two outs and didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Park struck out Bagwell and got Ken
Caminiti to pop to shortstop to strand Biggio at third. An inning
later Everett homered to give Houston a 1-0 lead but after Bako
doubled with one out, Eric Young saved a run with a diving stop on
Tim Bogar's grounder. Park struck out Mike Hampton to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Park's best escape came in the fourth. Richard Hildago
doubled with one out, Bako walked and Bogar was hit by a pitch to
load the bases. But a bit of fortune smiled Park's way for a
change.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton checked his swing on an inside pitch, but hit a slow
roller to Park, who threw to Pena at the plate for the first out.
Pena threw to first to complete the double play.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hampton was throwing a similar game as Park, allowing
baserunners but never in a string to cause damage. He allowed seven
hits and walked five, but allowed one run and struck out five.
</P>
</TEXT>
