</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT RED SOX, 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Confidence had been replaced by self-deprecation in the
New York Yankees' clubhouse. Tino Martinez lounged in front of his
locker before batting practice on Thursday and joked that he could
not stand to watch ESPN highlights anymore, because it was as if
everybody except him was driving the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, often convinced that he will never get another
hit, asked a broadcaster if his network was looking to hire a
baseball analyst _ immediately. But Martinez, O'Neill and their
brethren could laugh at themselves because they knew a slump was
probably a temporary condition for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   They did not extricate themselves from their collective hitting
problems against Boston on Thursday night, but they did enough to
win: pitcher Orlando Hernandez found his control in the third
inning and held the Red Sox to two hits over eight innings, as the
Yankees eked out a 3-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   This was as big a victory, said pitcher David Cone, as you can
have in May. It was the Yankees' first victory since the return of
Manager Joe Torre, it prevented Boston from sweeping the three-game
series and it enabled the Yankees (22-17) to pull within a
half-game of first-place Boston. ``It felt like a must-win
situation,'' Yankee shortstop Derek Jeter said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good time for Hernandez to rediscover his control,
which reappeared in the third inning. The right-hander had walked
two of the first six batters he faced and had labored through the
second inning, needing 21 pitches. But with a one-ball, no-strike
count on Boston's Jason Varitek leading off the third inning,
Hernandez spun a curveball for a strike. And he kept throwing
curveballs for strikes, any time he wanted, and this prevented the
Boston hitters from leaning on his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada, his catcher, saw Hernandez's intensity early, from
the way he stared in at the hitters, from the way he concentrated.
After the first inning, Hernandez returned to the Yankee dugout,
looked up at the lineup card posted on the wall and asked, ``Who's
coming up next inning?''
</P>
<P>
   Posada had never seen him do this before; Hernandez has always
pitched instinctively, never really worrying about the relative
strengths or weaknesses of the opposing hitters, insisting they
adjust to him. On Thursday night Hernandez made his own
adjustments, created a plan and a strategy, and with his control
buried the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who allowed 18 runs over 14 innings in his three
previous starts, did not allow any walks in his final six innings
tonight, and his control was so spectacular that by the seventh and
eighth innings, El Duque had expanded the strike zone being called
by Greg Kosc, the home-plate umpire. Two of the final three hitters
he faced took called third strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from their recent failures, the Yankees' hitters
provided just enough. Overeager at the plate recently, the Yankees
demonstrated some patience against Boston's Mark Portugal, and for
this they were rewarded. Martinez drew a walk leading off the fifth
inning, moved to second and then third on ground balls, bringing
Chad Curtis to the plate with a .150 batting average, more than a
month removed from his last hit with a runner in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing pitchers have exploited Curtis by throwing breaking
balls to the outside corner, and to combat this, Curtis moved
forward in the batter's box, his arms looming over home plate like
branches on a maple tree. Once Portugal reached a 3-2 count on
Curtis, Varitek, the Boston catcher, called for an inside fastball
_ he wanted to jam Curtis _ and set his target.
</P>
<P>
   But Portugal badly missed the bull's-eye: his fastball drifted
over the outside corner and Curtis whacked a single to right field,
his first hit with a runner in scoring position since April 9 and
the Yankees' first run in 14 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch was hit by a pitch to start the sixth inning and
eventually scored, and after the Red Sox cut the lead to 2-1 in the
seventh, Bernie Williams blasted a home run to center field, into
the face of a strong wind; he had to crush the ball, Jeter said
later, to hit the ball out tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's run was his second in 13 games. Jeter has no runs
batted in in his last eight games. O'Neill has no extra-base hits
in his last 12 games, and has hit into three double plays and
collected two rbi Williams' home run was his second extra-base hit
in his last 13 games, and the first home run hit by the Yankees'
3-4-5 batters _ O'Neill, Williams, Martinez _ since May 4. Scott
Brosius has no rbi in his last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez's outing gave them a chance. Mariano Rivera took
over in the ninth inning and with two on and two out, Jeter walked
the ball to the mound and slammed it into the glove of Rivera
before he pitched to Reggie Jefferson. ``Strike this guy out,''
Jeter said, quite seriously, and with a high fastball, Rivera
finished off Jefferson. Finally, the Yankees could remember what it
felt like to shake hands. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
