<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-SEATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES WEARY BUT RELIEVED TO BE IN NEW HOME IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISE OLSEN AND KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATAC, Wash. _ They were threatened and chased from their homes
in war-torn Kosovo. On Thursday night, after a two-week stopover at
an Army camp in New Jersey, Xhavit Korqa and his family touched
down at Sea-Tac Airport, one of three refugee families resettled in
cities across the nation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I thank the American government that took the
initiative to save us from the bloody hand of the Serbian regime,
to save my family and my children,'' said Xhavit Korqa, an auto
mechanic and bus driver from Gnjilane, a small town about 25 miles
from Pristina, the capital of Kosovo province in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Korqa and his wife, Magbule, and their three daughters and two
sons were greeted by a throng of reporters and their host family.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through a translator, Korqa said he and his family
hoped to find work and a school for their children, ages 6 to 17.
Despite their long journey and exhaustion, the family managed
smiles last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Korqas are the first of an estimated 300 Kosovar refugees
expected to resettle in Washington state in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle was one of three cities Thursday to receive the first
families leaving Fort Dix, N.J., where 3,300 Kosovar refugees have
lived since fleeing their battle-torn homeland in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The three families, 18 people in all, learned only on Wednesday
that they would be moving from Fort Dix to apartments in Sarasota,
Fla., Boise, Idaho, and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Korqas will stay first in the Burien, Wash., home of Karleen
and Bruce Kennedy, before moving in to their own place.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedys, who were given 24 hours' notice to prepare for
their guests, rushed to Costco to buy bulk groceries for what will
be a much bigger household.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just anxious for their arrival and hope that we can be a
little beacon of hope in their lives,'' Karleen Kennedy said. ``We
hope to help them to see that there are people who care about them
here even though it's hard to be a refugee in America.''
</P>
<P>
   A series of coincidences put the Albanians in the Kennedys' home
Thursday night. The Kennedys were the first family to volunteer to
host a family through their church, John Knox Presbyterian. The
church was one of the first to offer to sponsor refugees through
World Relief Inc., a Seattle resettlement agency.
</P>
<P>
   For the Kennedys, this is the sixth time they will welcome a
refugee family into their home. The Kennedys first hosted a
Vietnamese family in 1975 after the fall of Saigon. Every
Christmas, Cambodians, Vietnamese, Laotians, Bosnians and Romanians
gather at the Kennedys' _ their first home in America _ for a
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Each family's experience is different, Karleen Kennedy said. She
said she's looking forward to getting to know the Korqas _ though
at first, that will be through a translator, or elaborate charades.
</P>
<P>
   She wonders if the adjustment will be even harder for them, if
like many other Kosovars, they are determined to return home
someday.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, 20,000 refugees are expected to be brought to the
United States, though it is hoped that many will go back
eventually. The Korqas, while expressing gratitude for their warm
welcome, said they want someday to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Five different agencies in Seattle are working to line up group
and individual sponsors and volunteers to help refugee families.
More than 300 refugees are expected to arrive in the Puget Sound
area in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   World Relief Inc. also expects to resettle another 100 or
refugees in the Tri-Cities and Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   Many ethnic CLD9%n refugees fled at gunpoint, forced out of
their homes in Kosovo by Yugoslav forces. Often they had only
minutes to leave. Up to 800,000 Kosovars are reported to have fled
or been forced out.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next week, volunteers from the Kennedys' church, John
Knox Presbyterian, will help ferry the family to doctors'
appointments, to schools so their children can get enrolled and to
government offices _ rituals that mark the entry into American life
for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the world feels smaller, said Toby Wilson, an associate
pastor at John Knox who is helping the Kennedys. ``It's kind of fun
to be able to be a part of them starting again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The New York Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
