A5752 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZEDILLO-VISIT-SFCHRON     05-21 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEDILLO-VISIT-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: ZEDILLO VISIT A TRIUMPH OF SYMBOL OVER SUBSTANCE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ California Gov. Gray Davis and Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo wrapped up a three-day swing through the state
Thursday, a trip full of political symbolism and the promise of
lucrative business deals.
</P>
<P>
   No major developments were announced, despite attempts by both
sides to hype some minor initiatives and repackage others that
already exist.
</P>
<P>
   But the two leaders forged a tight cross-border alliance that is
likely to reshape California's economy and politics for many years
to come.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, they met with audiences whose ranks included
billionaires and top corporate executives, telling them that
Southern California and Mexico's Baja California are on the verge
of becoming a single integrated economy, which Zedillo said will be
``the most dynamic economic growth area of the world for the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Take advantage of these new opportunities,'' Zedillo said,
noting that Mexico has recently become California's biggest trading
partner. ``California and Mexico are now partners _ we are now one
market and one area of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the movers and shakers in San Diego and elsewhere during
the trip were Carlos Slim, Mexico's richest man, and nearly the
entire roster of Mexico's business elite, many of whom have
invested in California. Others included Los Angeles-based
supermarket king Ron Burkle, one of Davis' biggest campaign
contributors last year.
</P>
<P>
   As he had throughout Zedillo's trip, Davis used the occasion to
say that the Mexican leader's visit was bringing immediate economic
benefits to California. But in the company of such economic titans,
the deals that he announced seemed modest by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Davis claimed that luring the U.S. headquarters of
Telmex, Slim's huge telephone company, from Houston to San Diego
would bring 500 new jobs to California. However, company officials
have acknowledged that all but 20 of those jobs would have been
created anyway, even without the headquarters move.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said he will create 15 international trade centers at
community colleges throughout the state to train small firms for
Mexico trade. But Davis' move merely retools an existing program,
called the Centers for International Trade and Development, that
has operated successfully since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Other initiatives announced by Davis included: a high-speed
Internet link between California and Mexican universities; a joint
program to help Mexico fight agricultural pests; and a decision by
the El Segundo-based toymaker Mattel Inc. to open a new, $30
million factory in the northeast Mexico city of Monterrey.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the talk of quick benefits for California, the main
result of Davis' new Mexico gambit may be a further division of the
border economy between the white-collar north and the blue-collar
south.
</P>
<P>
   North of the border, corporations are establishing their head
offices and laboratories; south of the border, in Tijuana and
Mexicali, they are building their assembly plants, known as
maquiladoras, to take advantage of low wages and
government-enforced labor peace.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Zedillo said they plan to expand an existing program
of sending joint foreign trade missions to Asian nations. The
delegations, composed of government representatives from California
and Baja California, urge foreign investors to put corporate
headquarters north of the border and factory jobs south of it.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts say that although Mexico is the state's largest
export destination, the statistics may be misleading. According to
U.S. statistics, 73 percent of exports are sent to the
maquiladoras, where they are assembled and then reimported to
California and other states in a revolving-door process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were the maquiladoras to be removed from the equation,
Mexico's importance as a trading partner would be dramatically
diminished,'' said Jock O'Connell, an international business
consultant and expert on California's international trade policy.
``We're our own best customers.''
</P>
<P>
   If the maquiladora trade were eliminated, Mexico would drop to
11th place among California's trading partners. But O'Connell and
Mexican officials say the maquiladoras are gradually evolving from
unskilled assembly work to complex, high-tech manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of immediate specifics, it's very hard to tell the
results of this trip,'' said Herminio Blanco, Mexico's secretary of
commerce. ``But the real results will come in the months and years
ahead. This visit is giving the green light to all sorts of
economic relationships between companies across the border.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the economic benefits from the trip for average
Californians are likely to be limited in the near future, Davis is
likely to reap immediate political gains. Zedillo's repeated
expressions of support for the governor over his controversial move
to continue the state's legal defense of Proposition 187 appears to
have stopped a backlash from the state's Latino voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis has made a lucky move,'' said Raul Hinojosa, director of
the North American Integration and Development Center at the
University of California at Los Angeles. ``He's saved himself
politically with Latinos by getting Zedillo to pull back the
wolves. Latinos are now going to give him the benefit of the doubt,
and see how mediation will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa said that although the governor will emerge a winner,
the state as a whole will also win. ``From now on, relations with
Mexico are going to have to be center stage for any California
state government. There's been a tectonic shift.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This trip is all about Proposition 187. A Wilson-style hard
line against Latinos will not be tolerated anymore,'' he said.
``We've turned the corner on that type of politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
