<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5807 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLA-WAR-$ADV23-COX     05-21 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLA-WAR-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HAVANA COLA: AS GOOD AS THE REAL THING?
 &HT;    With Photos available in International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    With COLA-WAR-$ADV23.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Coca-Cola may be America's most popular soft drink, yet
Orlando housewife America Vaughan(CQ both) is eager to point out
how her new soda, Havana Cola, is different.
</P>
<P>
   It has a citric taste, she says, with the distinctive touch of
Key lime. And although Havana Cola's can is red -- like Coca-Cola's
-- its shade is a candy-apple one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a different taste, and I think a better one,'' boasts
Vaughan, a 48-year-old mother of four. ``I believe once people try
it they'll pull a switcheroo.''
</P>
<P>
   If sheer exuberance were an asset, Vaughan -- who's never run a
business before -- would already be a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   But exuberance alone may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   By launching a new soft drink, Vaughan has taken the plunge into
the already crowded and hostile American beverage industry, one
that's filled with ample examples of prodigiousness.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers in the United States already down more soft drinks
than in any other country outside of Mexico, leaving the Coca-Cola
Co. and the Pepsi-Cola Co. battling for every smidgen of market
share they can find.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Two together enjoy more than 75 percent of market share
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And they have decades worth of advertising know-how to make sure
sales keep climbing.
</P>
<P>
   So with the average American currently drinking more than 800
servings of soda a year, industry experts doubt that the U.S.
market can yield much more growth -- unless it's at someone else's
expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``A uniquely flavored brand has the potential of getting a niche
in some regional markets, but beyond that I think the challenge
would be a herculean one,'' said John Sicher, editor of Beverage
Digest, an industry newsletter based in Bedford Hills, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are already so many soft drinks,'' he said. ``I think
people have plenty of choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vaughan's not the type to be easily deterred.
</P>
<P>
   Since it went on the market last November, she has sold some
75,000 cans of Havana Cola. Tens of thousands more have been given
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a nice clean taste that will liberate the taste buds,
and people just love it,'' the Cuban-born Vaughan beams, ``so I
think it's going to do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The product has started to win a faithful following in Florida,
one which Vaughan hopes will grow to include customers in several
other states.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she scored perhaps her biggest coup yet when
Houston-based Sysco Corp., the nation's largest marketer and
distributor of food-service products, agreed to distribute Havana
Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan is so emboldened by her product's potential that she's
striking out with another risky venture: the development of a diet
version of Havana Cola with the help of a chemist in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Dead serious, she says her goal is to earn 3 percent of the cola
market in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That's news to Atlanta-based Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, I guess I'm aware of the product, but not all that
much,'' said Cocal Cola spokeswoman Polly Howes, emphasizing,
though, that Coca-Cola welcomes any and all competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there is plenty of room for anyone out there who
wants to get into this business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Havana Cola's currently available at restaurants and small
grocery stores across central and south Florida, including several
in Miami and Orlando. Barnie's Coffee and Tea Co. has agreed to
sell it, as has the Latin Quarter, a new restaurant at Universal
Studios in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the Havana restaurant in West Palm Beach, Fla.
call it their ``house soda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The drink is selling really well,'' said Rafael Perez,
Havana's assistant owner. ``Everyone who tries it wants more.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for Havana Cola was born by happenstance in the Florida
Keys, where Vaughan and her children often vacationed in the 1980s.
While there, her brother, who didn't always like to drink alcohol,
would mix Cuba Libres minus the rum, a taste the whole family
enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always enjoyed the taste of cola and lime,'' she said.
``I thought, 'Why not share the taste with others'?''
</P>
<P>
   In her native Cuba -- which she left in the 1960s for the United
States -- cola splashed with lime juice was a popular drink.
</P>
<P>
   She spent months refining that cola-and-lime taste in her
Orlando kitchen, experimenting on friends and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, she finally felt the time was ripe to launch her own
company. She did some research at the public library and called the
U.S. Department of Commerce to find out how to register a
trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan said her son, Greg, 23, came up with the name Havana
Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were in the Floriday Keys we would see a lot of Cuban
rafters trying to make it to Florida, and so my son became very
interested in Cuba and came up with the name,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Before it can become a registered trademark, a product's name
must be published in a weekly government trademark magazine, giving
objectors a chance to notify the commerce department's patent and
trademark office.
</P>
<P>
   One early hitch developed after attorneys representing Havana
Club rum opposed registration of the name Havana Cola in early
1995, fearing consumers might be confused by the products' similar
names.
</P>
<P>
   Havana Club backed down, though, in late 1997, and Havana Cola
was registered as a trademark by August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She was then free to sign up with a bottler, and start locating
sales outlets.
</P>
<P>
   But the road ahead will be a tough one, as even major national
brands have gone from hot to not in just a few years.
</P>
<P>
   For example, California Cooler, the brand that sparked the wine
cooler craze that spread in the 1980s, faded rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   And the industry's major players are adding new products all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has developed a host of new drinks, including a
citrus-flavored one called Surge. Royal Crown Co. has come up with
a drink called RC Edge it dubs a ``power cola'' loaded with extra
caffeine and other energy boosters.
</P>
<P>
   But far from shrinking from the challenge, Vaughan has launched
a publicity blitzkrieg in Florida that's already fomented a buzz
about her cola.
</P>
<P>
   In March, she set up a promotional booth at the popular Carnaval
Miami festival. Vaughan crowned a Miss Havana Cola at the booth, a
Colombian named Lexdiana Ortiz. In April, the cola was the featured
beverage at a three-day, dead-fish-throwing contest -- known as a
mullet toss -- near Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Havana Cola logo also will be featured on Ron Burkett's race
car when he competes June 19 in the Slim Jim NASCAR race at the
Lanier National Speedway in Gainesville, Ga. One of her neighbors
is a friend of Burkett's -- now a big fan of the drink.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vaughan continues to give away free samples of Havana
Cola everywhere she can.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my belief that people's palates have a very good
memory,'' Vaughan said. ``If I give them a taste, you can bet
they'll be back for more.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
