<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-JURAGUA-$ADV22-C     05-21 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-JURAGUA-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CUBA-RUSSIA DEAL TO BUILD NUCLEAR PLANT IN CUBA DOWNPLAYED BY
SKEPTICS
 &HT;    With JURAGUA-TIMELINE-$ADV22.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., May 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For Cuba watchers, it has become a familiar pattern:
Cuba and Russia announce a deal to jump-start construction of the
mothballed Juragua nuclear power plant on the communist island.
</P>
<P>
   Then, due to prohibitive costs -- it would take an estimated
$650 million to $1 billion to finish the project -- construction
never resumes.
</P>
<P>
   The latest such announcement came May 14, when Cuba and Russia
declared that they had reached agreement on forming a joint venture
to complete the plant and its first reactor.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was part of a trade deal that allows Cuba to swap
its sugar for Russia's oil.
</P>
<P>
   But similar declarations have been made before -- perhaps four
times in seven years -- leading experts on the project to downplay
its significance, as well as reiterate their insistence that the
plant will likely never be completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement is meaningless,'' said Jonathan
Benjamin-Alvarado, a University of Georgia professor writing a book
on the Juragua (pronounced ``HUR-ra-gwa'') project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing more than two very poor and economically
strangled countries trying to consummate an agreement that is
mostly hollow and fiction,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He said the signing of such agreements has become almost as
reliable as Christmas, although no progress has ever been made in
arranging actual financing.
</P>
<P>
   Construction on the plant was launched in 1982 with the hopes of
alleviating the chronic electricity shortages that still plague
many parts of Cuba. But construction stalled 10 years later with
the collapse of the Soviet Union, Cuba's main benefactor, after
more than $1 billion had been pumped into it.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, Cuban officials announce that work will resume,
but even Cuban President Fidel Castro said last year that prospects
for the project looked bleak, and that Cuba would start searching
for alternative energy sources.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarado said Cuba has recently built small geothermal energy
plants tapping into steam from deep wells to provide reliable
electricity in areas frequented by tourists, such as Varadero,
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Juragua project is opposed by U.S. officials -- and
especially conservatives in Congress -- who worry about the
prospects of a Chernobyl-like disaster 240 miles away from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   They say Cuba lacks safety standards and a mature regulatory
body to oversee Juragua, which utilizes old Soviet technology.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they worry that a leak could spew radiation as far
west as Texas and as far east as Washington, D.C. with the brunt
falling on Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Many American nuclear experts, though, say the Juragua plant is
conservatively designed and is safer than Ukraine's ill-fated
Chernobyl plant because it has a containment wall.
</P>
<P>
   But the potential threat has prompted the Pentagon to spend $2
million this year on a radiation-monitoring system to collect air
samples scattered across Florida, Mexico and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear physicists at Florida State University have spent the
last two months collecting and analyzing air samples. Four other
air-monitoring stations are scheduled to be established in states
along the Gulf of Mexico within the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   But experts familiar with the Juragua project say the U.S.
government is wasting its money protecting citizens from something
that doesn't yet exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan borders on lunacy because no one even knows if the
Juragua plant will ever be finished,'' said Thomas Cochran, a
senior scientist with the Natural Resources Defense Council, a
Washington-based environmental lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   Even a U.S. State Department official told Cox Newspapers this
week that the plan would appear to be a waste of money if its sole
purpose was to monitor radiation from the Juragua plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see no evidence that the Juragua project is moving forward
or that any financing is being made available,'' said the official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran, who has visited the Juragua plant twice, said that even
if construction resumed today, it would take four to six years to
complete the plant. He said the Pentagon's radiation-monitoring
scheme -- if needed -- could be up and running within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby Kemper, the chairman of the FSU physics department, agreed
that a baseline for the project will likely be finished within a
year.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the May 14 announcement made by Cuba and
Russia proves the radiation-monitoring project is valuable and must
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really just insurance because we really don't know
what these countries are going to do from one minute to the next,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Lt. Col. Bill Darley, spokesman for the U.S.
Department of Defense, said the radiation-monitoring stations are
being established ``out of prudence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba has always stated an intention to complete the plant,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed, though, that no country is in a position to provide
the kind of financing that's needed to finish the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The May 14 agreement was signed by Russian Trade Minister Georgy
Gabuniya and Cuban Foreign Trade Minister Ricardo Cabrisas.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Juragua plant, Cuban officials this week
agreed that the lack of financing was a major obstacle to finishing
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish we could work with the Americans on it,'' said Carlos
Fernandez de Cossio of the Foreign Relations Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Georgia's Alvarado, who's visited Cuba five
times to research the project, said buildings at the Juragua site
are 70 percent complete, but that the ``instrumentation and
control'' system -- the most important part of the project -- is
only about 20 percent complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be completed but it is difficult to conceive how
anyone would get a return on an investment of this size,'' he said.
``Many international firms from Italy, Spain, Brazil, and France
have taken a look at this project, and walked away.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
