<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A TIMELINE FOR THE JURAGUA NUCLEAR PLANT
 &HT;    With CUBA-JURAGUA-$ADV22.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., May 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIMELINE: THE JURAGUA NUCLEAR POWER PLANT IN CUBA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Late 1970s -- Cuba and Russia agree to build a nuclear power
plant, with a Soviet-designed reactor, near Cienfuegos, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1982 -- Construction on the nuclear plant begins.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1992 -- Construction ends due to financial difficulties
brought on by the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1996 -- Ansaldo, a nuclear firm from Italy, does a feasibility
study and determines it will cost up to $750 million to complete
the nuclear plant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1996 -- In a 1996 law, the U.S. Congress declares the project
an ``act of aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1998 -- Cuban President Fidel Castro announces that Cuba will
look for energy alternatives to replace nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1999 -- Pentagon pays $2 million to establish several
radiation-monitoring stations around Florida in case Cuba's nuclear
plant is ever finished and has an accident.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 14, 1999 -- Cuba and Russia agree again to complete
construction of the nuclear plant.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
