<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-$ADV23-COX     05-21 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM KOSOVO: KLA FIGHTS THE SERBS AND ITS OWN RAGTAG
IMAGE
 &HT;    With Photos; mug of Holmes.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Kosare is midway between
Tropoje, in northern Albania, and Decani, Kosovo, to the north and
east across the border.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSARE, Kosovo _ The hard-faced soldiers lining the perimeter of
the guerrilla army base stood at the ready, fingers on the triggers
of their AK-47 assault rifles, prepared to mow down an attacking
Serb force.
</P>
<P>
   But the immediate purpose of the Kosovo Liberation Army troops
standing guard in their mountain compound was to serve as targets
for us, a dozen visiting foreign correspondents and cameramen
escorted by the KLA from Albania into the southwestern highlands of
Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA wanted us to see their remote base at Kosare (pronounced
ko-SHAR-ah) and talk to their earnest soldiers. They wanted us to
document their military toehold in the face of claims from Belgrade
that the armed resistance movement has been eliminated, along with
the 800,000 refugees who have been pushed out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence was plain to see in the dense Kosovo forest,
shadowed by towering, snow-dappled peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Here, a mile inside Kosovo from the Albanian border, the rebels
exist.
</P>
<P>
   They also bleed.
</P>
<P>
   A sudden artillery duel with the Serbs that left three KLA
soldiers seriously wounded wasn't part of the KLA's publicity plan.
But it was all too genuine.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has discovered, as has NATO since it began its daily
bombing campaign on March 24, that conquering Yugoslavia's army and
security forces is not an easy task.
</P>
<P>
   A loose collection of clan-led militias before the NATO air war
began, the KLA lacks sufficient training, heavy armament and
vehicles hearty enough to handle the rugged mountain tracks.
Ammunition and other supplies from Albania are often moved on
horseback or tractor cart (the latter was our mode of travel in one
leg of our journey into Kosovo).
</P>
<P>
   But they seem to have plenty of rifles and bullets, light
artillery and mortars captured from the Serbs. They also are armed
with a firm devotion to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not afraid to kill or be killed because we fight for
what we believe in, to free our homeland,'' said 18-year-old Roland
Rama, a student from the Kosovo's provincial capital, Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken young man cradling his rifle to his chest, Rama
has been stationed at the base for a month but has yet to use his
weapon in battle. He peered at the horizon, listening longingly to
the echoes of artillery fire and the pop-pop-pop of automatic
rifles from the forward positions.
</P>
<P>
   While KLA and Serb foot patrols on occasion skirmish in close
proximity, the combat here is primarily limited to artillery and
snipers positioned in opposing mountain ridges. For the past 40
days or so, the result is a standoff that is producing casualties
on both sides
</P>
<P>
   The KLA's 138th brigade, based at Kosare, a former Serb police
barracks, has had three firefights with Serb forces in as many
days. The rebels managed to push another 300 to 500 yards into
Kosovo, only to retreat in the teeth of superior firepower from the
Yugoslav army and police units. The gains and losses are slight
real estate that do not essentially change the equation.
</P>
<P>
   This is an authentic corner of the war over Kosovo, albeit at
the moment an inconsequential one. Nothing the KLA does in the next
few days or week is likely to have a bearing on when Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic might capitulate or when NATO will end
its air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the KLA is in a race against time to establish itself firmly
as an organized fighting force in Kosovo, and as a real player to
be included in a diplomatic formula for peace. The more land it can
control before a settlement is imposed on Yugoslavia, the more
clout it could bring to the table. (The current diplomatic
framework agreed upon in the U.S.-brokered Rambouillet peace
proposal calls for the KLA to be disarmed.)
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has been using the ramshackle Kosare base, a two-story
brick building pockmarked by holes from shelling and small-arms
fire, as a launch pad for efforts to break open a corridor deeper
into Kosovo. They control the territory that runs about a mile
between the base and the Albania border, providing a supply line of
men and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The strategic aim is to link up with pockets of the KLA who
never left the province, but who retreated deeper into the
mountains and away from the towns and villages being brutally swept
by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   If the guerrilla army at Kosare can break through, it could gain
territory and re-supply ammunition to soldiers already in Kosovo, a
province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are striving to further organize our forces and bring
forward more troops to get rid of these Serb positions once and for
all,'' said Xhafer Gashi, the deputy commander in charge of
security and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   During our visit last week(CQ), three KLA fighters were
seriously wounded during artillery exchanges with Serb forces dug
in about a mile away. It is not a convenient place to be injured.
The only exit into Albania runs over deeply rutted dirt roads cut
through the torturously steep mountains. The nearest hospital,
poorly supplied, is hours away.
</P>
<P>
   In tactical terms, NATO provides help in the form of its air
attacks on the Serb positions. It is inadvertent air support for
the KLA ground troops. Despite rumors of cooperation, there seems
to be no coordination between NATO jets and the guerrilla fighters
on the ground other than the fact that they share common targets.
</P>
<P>
   But since the KLA has been always outmanned and outgunned by the
Serbs, NATO has helped to equal the playing field. Yugoslav forces
probably could easily retake the base at Kosare, according to
Western military observers in Albania, but they dare not because if
they moved in mass, they would make their positions known to NATO
warplanes, and be struck.
</P>
<P>
   But from the KLA's perspective, this is a separate war apart
from NATO. The KLA has its own agenda and claims it will not give
up until Kosovo achieves independence from Yugoslavia, something
any diplomatic solution between NATO and Belgrade is not likely to
include.
</P>
<P>
   In the lush woods and blossoming mountain pastures along the
border with Albania, there is no talk of cease-fires or peace
negotiations, only of war and victory.
</P>
<P>
   As we hiked about three miles out of Kosovo to a KLA training
base near the Albanian border town of Papaj, we passed new recruits
going in. Some of them are volunteers from America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Most are young men from Kosovo who were pushed out of the
province by the same cleansing of ethnic Albanians that produced
the masses of refugees in neighboring Albania, Macedonia and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters walked in platoon-sized, single-file columns. They
were dressed in green camouflage uniforms and each with a rifle and
banana-shaped clip of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   They, as we, passed the result of Serb shelling in recent days:
large bomb craters along the road, splintered trees in the hills
and the carcasses of several dead horses. Our KLA guide pointed out
one wide hole in the ground where he said three guerrilla soldiers
died in an artillery barrage a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers walking by appeared excited and scared, like
stereotypes from a B war movie, raw recruits eager to get into the
action and frightened by the prospect of what was just around the
bend. Some flinched as the sound of outgoing artillery from a
nearby KLA position issued a thunderous, bone-rattling roar as a
shell was launched; others just smiled and gave us the thumbs-up
sign.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kosare base, the KLA commanders had made a conspicuous
effort to impress upon us that this makeshift army now pursues the
war as a well-oiled military machine.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the young men headed to battle left a sense that the
propaganda may not yet be completely true, but the passion and
sense of purpose are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not like it was before, when we had bad organization and
no vehicles and poor equipment,'' said Nevruz Hasani, a former
schoolteacher from Junik in Kosovo who, at 38, is a veteran among
the fighters we saw that day. ``Now it is really a pleasure to
fight because we feel we are equal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers foreign correspondent Charles W. Holmes was the
only American among a dozen journalists recently taken into
embattled Kosovo province by the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
