<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5836 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TOLEDO-COX     05-21 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TOLEDO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toledo: A Spanish city full of spirituality, art and lots of
history
 &HT;    By BOB RUFF
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After returning from Spain, I was watching sports on TV when the
commentator yelled, ``Holy Toledo, what a play!'' I had just been
in Toledo. Not the one in Ohio, but Spain's religious capital, its
spiritual center, its holy city. Is that where the expression
originated?
</P>
<P>
   Toledo (pronounced tow-LED-oh in Spanish) is 1 1/2 hours south
of Madrid by train. Approaching the city, which is on the banks of
the River Tajo, and seeing its skyline, makes one eager to get
there. Miraculously preserved from the effects of the modern world,
this castled city retains the atmosphere and structure of an old
medieval fortress. Churches, museums, hotels, shops, restaurants
and parks blend together in a maze of narrow stone streets that beg
to be explored.
</P>
<P>
   While Toledo is an ancient city, it is no museum piece. A modern
city exists around and among the precious antiquity. In the city's
main square, where the buses pull up with tourists, there is a
Museum Santa Cruz, old-fashioned eateries and a McDonald's. Walking
the winding streets, one finds the old and new mixed together as if
it were planned that way all along.
</P>
<P>
   The first written testimony, by the Roman historian, Tito Tivio,
describes ``Toletum'' as a small fortified town. Being at the
crossroads of the Spanish peninsula, the city was strategically
important for controlling this country. The Visigoth kings made it
the capital of their kingdom in the sixth century AD, giving it the
name, ``The Royal City.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic people called it ``Tolaitola'' during their rule;
the 10th-century mosque, Crist de la Luz, is the oldest building
preserved intact. King Alfonso VI of Castille reconquered the city
in 1085, making it the capital of his kingdom. This began Toledo's
most glorious era, and it was during this period that Christians,
Jews and Muslims lived together in relative harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo remained the capital of Spain until 1561, when Felipe II
moved the government to Madrid. The Catholic Church, however, kept
the seat of the primate in Toledo, where it remains to this day.
</P>
<P>
   In 1577, Domenico Theotocopoulos arrived in Toledo from Rome.
The Italians there, not being able to pronounce his name (Try
saying it aloud. See what I mean?) just called him ``El Greco'' _
literally, ``The Greek.'' This 36-year-old artist, a native of the
island of Crete, and perhaps the greatest mannerist of his day,
would live and paint in Toledo until his death in 1614. His work
adorns the city, and if these treasures were all Toledo had to
offer, it would be worth the journey just to gaze at these
wonderful masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Churches and museums throughout the city house his art,
including the El Greco Museum, which adjoins the artist's home.
Although El Greco became Toledo's most famous adopted son, many
other works of the old masters can be found here, including Goya.
This city is an art lover's paradise, filled with museums and old
churches that house vast collections.
</P>
<P>
   Waking up on a weekday morning, one hears the sounds of people
hurrying to work and young children laughing on the way to school.
This city is no relic preserved for tourism. It is humming with
daily life. On the weekend, festivals in and around the city add to
the excitement. Traditional dancers fill the main square, to the
delight of locals and tourists alike. Almost anything one cares to
do or see is within walking distance.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has been declared, in its entirely, a part of the
Heritage of Humanity. Few cities can compare with the varied
architectural styles found here. Arabic, Mudejar, Gothic and
Renaissance buildings are mixed together with many monuments,
making every corner turned a new experience.
</P>
<P>
   While there are too many architectural treasures to relate in
one story, the most significant building of the city is the great
cathedral. The dominant structure of the city's skyline, it was
built to commemorate the victory over the Muslims in the Battle of
Las Navas de Toloso in 1212. Construction began in 1221 and the
main structure was completed in 1493 in the time of Cardinal
Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   His successors, the great patron-prelates, thanks to their large
financial resources, continued to enrich and furnish the cathedral,
adding chapels, jewels, paintings, organs, altar pieces, codexes
and sculptures, converting it to one of the most opulent churches
in Christendom.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Gothic cathedrals, the front was planned to have two
symmetrical towers but only the one that holds the 20-ton bell was
completed. The companion tower is covered with an octagonal tambour
and a lovely dome built by Jorge Manuel, El Greco's son.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo is world-renown for its sword making. In fact, the U.S.
military has its swords manufactured here. Many of these factories
offer tours and have large gift shops where one can purchase or
order a custom-made sword from any era in history. I opted for a
letter opener shaped like a sword.
</P>
<P>
   This city is the capital of the province of La Mancha, and of
Don Quixote. There is no lack of statues of this famous mythical
figure in the local souvenir shops. In fact, one can buy a
full-size Don Quixote. In this case I opted for a T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing over the River on the St. Martin bridge, I watch the
sun set on this incredibly beautiful medieval city. Whether part of
a visit to Iberia, or as one's only destination, this castled city
will make one realize why Toledo will always be revered and
considered holy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
