<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5871 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN22-COX     05-21 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Did even Honest Abe fudge in defending a client?
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Now that modern technology and DNA
evidence have confirmed that Thomas Jefferson, our third president
and a founding father, has a few skeletons in his closet, and after
learning several other White House residents are guilty of
indiscretions not included on their campaign resumes, I was further
shaken by a letter from Neal Dettmering, a prominent Douglasville
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   A while back, I wrote a column about my brilliant defense of
Helen Adams in a mock trial staged in our eighth-grade civics
class. Helen had been identified by witnesses who swore they saw
her going into Mr. Durham's chicken house at night, and emerging
with two laying hens. I was her court-appointed defender.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution appeared to have an airtight case until I, the
budding Clarence Darrow, stumbled across an account of how Abraham
Lincoln, when he was a young lawyer in Illinois, had gotten an
accused murderer off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant had been charged with stabbing a man to death in a
late-night street fight. Like my client, he had been identified by
witnesses who claimed to have seen him do the deed. Lincoln,
wondering how they could see so unerringly at night, maneuvered
them into testifying that they were helped by light of a full moon.
</P>
<P>
   He then produced an almanac showing there was no moon on the
night of the murder. His client was acquitted. Hoping for the same
luck in my case, I consulted an almanac. There was no moon on the
night Helen was accused of stealing chickens. Using Mr. Lincoln's
tactics, I led prosecution witnesses into testifying how they had
clearly recognized her in the moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   After I produced the almanac, the jury quickly voted for
acquittal. Ferrol Sams, the presiding judge and a real lawyer, said
later he considered issuing a directed verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Dettmering, a native Fayette Countian who went on to play
football at Auburn before going to law school, wrote to say that my
account of the almanac cases had come to his attention, and perhaps
there might be an added twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I attended a seminar on trial tactics and evidence, including
how to get publications accepted as evidence,'' he wrote. ``The
seminar speaker added a postscript to Mr. Lincoln's Illinois murder
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that in the original transcript of the trial the
almanac Mr. Lincoln produced was described as having a blue cover,
and that subsequent research determined there was no almanac with a
blue cover published anywhere at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So there is speculation that the almanac publisher was Lincoln
himself!''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know. I'd hate to think Honest Abe cheated, even as a
young lawyer. You'd think judges and jurors of that time, being
mostly rural folks, would know when the moon fulled without relying
on an almanac. But strange things happen in courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The most astonishing not guilty verdict _ before O.J. Simpson _
I know about came several years ago in a local court. Two young
hoodlums had broken into the home of an elderly lady. She was
robbed and badly beaten. The whereabouts of one assailant was
unknown. The other had been arrested, positively identified by the
victim and had made a confession.
</P>
<P>
   The court appointed the late Howard Handley to defend him. Mr.
Handley was a brilliant courtroom lawyer, but despite his best
efforts, the accused was plainly headed for a lengthy prison
sentence. After finishing his closing argument, Mr. Handley was
obviously surprised and baffled when the defendant asked to take
the stand.
</P>
<P>
   The young man proceeded to spin a yarn about how the other
fellow, whereabouts unknown and unavailable for questioning, had
pulled a pistol and forced him, at gunpoint, under threat of death,
to participate in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The jury deliberated for several hours before returning a
verdict of not guilty. Mr. Handley seemed to be in shock when I
went up to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with the verdict,'' I said, ``but you won an
impossible case.''
</P>
<P>
   We were joined by several jurors. ``Mr. Handley,'' one inquired,
``when did you learn about the gun?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What gun?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun that the other person used to make him commit the
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that gun!'' said Mr. Handley. ``I learned about it at the
exact moment you did.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers do get surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago one of my partners defended a guy for stealing a
hunting dog,'' Dettmering wrote. ``When the fellow was acquitted he
was so excited that right there in front of the judge and jury he
blurted out: `Does that mean I get to keep the dog?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
