   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-TOBACCO _ At a gathering of American Cancer Society
affiliates in Atlanta this week, the big topic is evil tobacco and
how companies are luring new smokers, particularly young people, in
foreign countries. In Poland, for instance, the most popular
selling brand is Lady Di cigarettes. While the U.S. has limited
billboards and sales to young people, most foreign countries
haven't, and they're exchanging information on what works to slow
cigarette sales. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   LOWCHOLESTEROL-MARGARINE _ The people in white lab coats have
pulled another fast one on Nature, by creating margarine-like
spread that actually lowers cholesterol levels. Two brands of
cholesterol-reducing spreads have been approved by federal
officials within the past month. On Monday the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration approved Benecol, manufactured by McNeil Consumer
Healthcare, a division of Johnson &AMP; Johnson. Three weeks ago, the
FDA signed off on Take Control, made by Lipton. Both will be on
store shelves next week.(Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   NEWBISHOP _ Advance on the installation of the new Atlanta
bishop of the Greek Orthodox Church set for Saturday. (White,
Atlanta journal-Constitution). 12. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-INNOVATION _ATLANTA _Forget the craft sticks, markers
and paper; throw out the ditto sheets. At a half dozen Atlanta
congregations and at churches across the nation, Sunday School is
becoming an experience not to be missed. Congregations searching
for ways to revive declining family attendance are latching on to
an innovative ministries program called Cornerstones, that uses the
theory of multiple intelligences to teach Bible stories. (Rakoczy,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
