<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD22-COX     05-21 0314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It grows on trees, but not all wood works outdoors
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the more vexing questions to confront a
woodworker is which wood to use for an outdoor project.
</P>
<P>
   Of course you can use any wood strong enough to suit the purpose
if you paint it, but painting often goes crossgrain to someone who
is accustomed to making indoor furniture in lovely wood selected
and finished to show off its natural beauty.
</P>
<P>
   I have constructed only one such project _ a pair of Adirondack
chairs. I built them in white oak.
</P>
<P>
   Oh my, those things were a beast to build. The oak was so hard
that screws kept breaking off in it. But they came out looking very
nice. They did not look nice for long, however. They turned gray,
which I expected, but it is a blotchy, sickly-looking gray.
</P>
<P>
   You will still find lots of folks recommending oak for outdoor
things, but I wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The only reasonably available choices that remain, as far as I
know, are redwood, cedar, mahogany and teak.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar isn't very strong. It's also splintery. I've never made
anything of redwood, but it ought to be fairly good if great
strength isn't required.
</P>
<P>
   Mahogany, like oak, has been widely used in the ship-building
trade, especially for trim. It ought to be pretty good, but it will
also be pretty expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The best wood for outdoor use is probably teak. It's strong and
stable and will weather to a pleasant gray color. It will also cost
an arm and part of a leg and it is very tough on edged tools
because of its unusually high silica content.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the stuff made for redwood, and perhaps for cedar, I
know of no finish that will really protect a wood's natural color
when left outdoors. They will all turn gray.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
