<P>
   SIERRA-CLUB (San Francisco) _ David Brower, the old
environmental lion, is roaring again. At age 86, he's running for
the presidency of the Sierra Club, aiming, he says, to revitalize
an organization that has become clubby, fearful of risk and
preoccupied with procedure. The club's directors will elect a new
president Saturday. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   ZEDILLO-CALIF (Los Angeles) _ Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
and California Gov. Gray Davis concluded a three-day tour of the
state by visiting Breed Street Elementary School, a fitting place
to celebrate the growing influence of Mexican-Americans in
California.
</P>
<P>
   BEEDIES-CIGARETTES (San Francisco) _ A flavored, filterless
Indian cigarette often smuggled into the United States has become
trendy among local teens who mistakenly believe that it's harmless,
according to a study by San Francisco youths that has caught the
attention of the Federal Trade Commission. By ERIC DRUDIS.
</P>
<P>
   DEA-MARIJUANA (San Francisco) _ Sex, lies and audio tape. John
Dalton, indicted for criminal conspiracy in connection with a
marijuana growing operation, claims the charges against him should
be dismissed because he claims that DEA agent Mark Nelson, 37, set
him up by first threatening, then seducing Dalton's then-wife
Victoria Horstman, 40, convincing her to install a tape recorder in
the Dalton bedroom. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
