   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ For serious computer game players,
there was only one type of video card worth considering for 3-D
graphics six months ago _ one that used the Voodoo2 chip from 3Dfx
Interactive. That was then. This is now. While it can be argued
that, for now, the Voodoo3 remains the fastest 3-D card out there,
it may not hold that claim for long. And, it may no longer be the
best 3-D game option. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   With: COMPUTER-HELPLINE
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING-SHORTAGE (San Francisco) _ Some new numbers confirm what
most San Francisco Bay Area residents already know: We are in the
midst of a housing crisis with San Francisco's middle class bearing
the brunt of the shortage. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STARWARS-GEEK (Undated) _ With the arrival of ``Episode I:
The Phantom Menace,'' Star Wars mania has hit the cultural
landscape with all the force of, well, the Force. A certain segment
of the world's population will remain impervious to the full effect
of this mania. But there are others for whom ``Star Wars'' was
something else altogether. Let's call them, for simplicity's sake,
Jedi geeks (we know who we are). By KEN FOUNTAIN.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CAPSHAW-PROFILE (Undated) _ ``The Love Letter,'' which Kate
Capshaw developed and co-produced, is her most significant role
since ... well, since she won the heart and hand of director Steven
Spielberg while starring in his ``Indiana Jones and the Temple of
Doom.'' But the film's debut butts heads with ``Star Wars: Episode
I _ The Phantom Menace.'' The Love Letter could be slaughtered.
Capshaw is not looking at it that way. She thinks there might be a
lot of viewers who crave a romance rather than a ``Star Wars.'' By
LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CLEOPATRA (Undated) _ ``Cleopatra,'' an extravagant
miniseries that in many ways is more of an original than a remake,
airs Sunday and Monday on ABC. This production can't be done small,
and the latest Hallmark Entertainment version is no exception: The
cost for the four-hour television movie is in the neighborhood of
$33 million, including an impressive lineup of acting talent. By
MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LOVE (Undated) _ Maybe it's the mawkishly generic
title, or maybe that it's been programmed as the distaff ``Phantom
Menace'' alternative, but ``The Love Letter'' is a movie you
dislike on principle. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
