<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5956 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHICAL-WAR-HNS &LR;      05-21 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHICAL-WAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JUST WAR OR JUST IRRESPONSIBLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALEX A. VARDAMIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, Calif. _ Prime Minister Tony Blair, the fiery warrior,
advises widening the war in the Balkans by introducing ground
forces, while bellicose President Clinton's faith in aerial
bombardment remains unswerving.
</P>
<P>
   Both are adamant in pursuing their ``just war'' against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic. However, another Englishman may offer
sounder guidance. In ``Henry VI,'' William Shakespeare wrote:
``Thrice is he arm'd that hath his quarrel just, And he but naked,
though lock'd up in steel, Whose conscience with injustice is
corrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   In its relentless bombing of Yugoslavia, is NATO thrice arm'd or
naked? Are our two warrior chieftains morally exposed? Are they
conducting a just war? Both Blair and Clinton draw moral lessons
from World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Blair spurns Neville Chamberlain, the arch-appeaser. Clinton
insists that if Franklin Delano Roosevelt had intervened early
against Hitler, the Holocaust might have been prevented.
</P>
<P>
   World War II, both agree, was a ``Just War.'' They compare it to
their struggle with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But is this Balkan battle really a just war, in the theological
and ethical sense? Or is it merely a feel-good public relations
war? Since armed conflict inevitably causes vast destruction and
slaughter, it is justified, in the tradition of Augustine and
Thomas Aquinas, only if it meets certain criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Theologians have agreed upon five ethical standards that must be
met before a civilized nation, or alliance, has the moral right to
start a war.
</P>
<P>
   _ First and foremost, there must be a just cause to wage war.
The North Atlantic Treaty Organization found it in the ethnic
cleansing of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. However, when the war
began, the flood of refugees was largely potential. It did not
begin, at a catastrophic level, until the first bombs fell.
</P>
<P>
   _ The aims of the war must be controlled by just intent. Early
on, Blair and Clinton said that they had to attack Yugoslavia in
order to preserve the credibility of NATO. Extending the power of a
military alliance and augmenting American influence in Europe is
dubious moral justification for waging war.
</P>
<P>
   _ The decision to go to war must be made as a last resort after
every other reasonable means of settlement have failed. Diplomacy
requires patience. Rambouillet was a hasty ultimatum to Serbia and
not a serious attempt at negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   _ The decision to go to war must be made by a legitimate
authority. To ignore this principle is to invite primitive blood
feuds and gang warfare. Neither the United Nations nor the U.S.
Congress sanctioned this war. NATO, a defensive organization,
violated its own charter by intervening, militarily, in a civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   _ A just war requires a reasonable prospect of success. The
means used by NATO, around-the-clock bombing, or even a land
invasion, is hardly likely to promote the only justifiable end,
ethnic harmony in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Once a war begins, two criteria must govern the conduct of
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discrimination must be observed. A belligerent must avoid harm
to civilians and refrain from wanton violence. The hundreds of
innocent civilians who have been pulverized, incinerated and
dismembered prove that it is hard to achieve discrimination from
15,000 feet. NATO's desire to avoid pilot casualties increases the
horrific carnage that is euphemistically called collateral damage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Proportionality must be observed. If a war does more harm than
good, it is ethically indefensible. Over 10,000 munitions have been
dropped upon a small country. Unexploded bombs drift in the
Adriatic. Stability in the Balkans teeters on the brink.
</P>
<P>
   The human, physical, environmental and political devastation
caused by the NATO war is disproportionate to the goal of pacifying
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the failure to meet any of the just war criteria,
NATO insists that its war with Yugoslavia is legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   The allies emphasize that the enemy, Milosevic, is an evil thug,
responsible for the murder, rape, plunder and displacement of
Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is more to the picture than Western spin. The Serbs
tell another story. They emphasize the mangled, charred corpses of
innocent civilians. They remind us that the Kosovo Liberation Army,
too, has blood-stained hands. They speak of ecological devastation.
But what they conceal might be even more gruesome.
</P>
<P>
   NATO killed nearly a hundred refugees in the village of Korisa
because of a mistake in targeting. Imagine how many hundreds of
young Yugoslav draftees, asleep in barracks far from the
battlefield, have been intentionally blown to bits every night by
NATO smart bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Truth lies somewhere between the propaganda of either side.
</P>
<P>
   Did years of Serb discrimination of the Kosovars or weeks of
NATO bombing cause the worse humanitarian catastrophe? Have torches
in the hands of paramilitaries or cluster bombs dropped from B-52s
destroyed more homes? Have more young Albanian men been shot by
Serbs than young Serb men been incinerated by NATO bombs? Is death
from a bullet fired at close range more a violation of human rights
than the risk-free, systematic ``degradation'' of Milosevic's
military from three miles up? Does the bombing campaign in the
Balkans really constitute a just war?
</P>
<P>
   NATO's leaders insist it must ``win'' at all costs. But at what
moral price? Shakespeare might have foreseen the bare rumps of our
warrior chieftains peeking through rusty, corrupted armor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex A. Vardamis, a retired colonel, is the former director for
European studies at the Army War College.)
</P>
</TEXT>
