<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5960 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CLEOPATRA-HNS &LR;      05-21 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CLEOPATRA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXTRAVAGANT `CLEOPATRA' MAKES WASHINGTON LOOK TRIVIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is what politics should be all about. None of this
mamby-pamby special prosecutor stuff and powerless intern
mistresses and hoary howls of outrage from adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   No, in the old, old days the head of state had affairs with
another head of state, and there was none of that ``I did not have
sexual relations with that woman'' stuff. And back then, political
backstabbing was no figurative term.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in some fratricide, double-dealing, triple-dealing and
coalitions that shift faster than the Sahara in a sandstorm and you
have the story of Cleopatra.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story worth retelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleopatra,'' the extravagant miniseries that in many ways is
more of an original than a remake, will air Sunday and Monday at 9
p.m. Eastern on ABC (check local listings).
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleopatra'' can't be done small, and the latest Hallmark
Entertainment version for ABC is no exception: The cost for the
four-hour television movie is in the neighborhood of $33 million.
We are talking almost three ``ER'' episodes here.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the 1963 movie version, a disaster of epic
proportions starring Elizabeth Taylor, Richard Burton and Rex
Harrison, cost $44 million (after an original budget of $3
million). That would make it the most expensive movie ever,
according to various sources, since in contemporary dollars that
translates to somewhere around $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new miniseries also engages in some wretched excess in the
best sense of the word. Filmed in Morocco and London, Hallmark
boasts that the set for the city of Alexandria measured a
quarter-mile. One ton of copper was used to make jewelry and
costumes, including breastplates. In the largest of scenes 1,000
extras and 600 horses were used. This is a televised DeMilling.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the versions in 1917 (a silent movie), 1934 (which Cecil
B. DeMille actually made, starring Claudette Colbert) and 1963, the
updated ``Cleopatra'' portrays the Egyptian queen as much more than
just an evil seductress.
</P>
<P>
   In her eyes and body, sex is a weapon, a political weapon, and
she wields it deftly and often. The difference is, her actions are
founded in the belief that what she does, she does for her country.
She is as smart in the boardroom as in the bedroom, a Cleopatra for
1990s sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are titans of history and literature: Julius
Caesar, Marc Antony, Octavian, Brutus and, of course, the Egyptian
ruler. And ABC and Hallmark Entertainment have also assembled an
impressive lineup, from Timothy Dalton (the former James Bond, as
Caesar), Billy Zane (Cal Hockley of ``Titanic,'' as Marc Antony),
Rupert Graves (``A Room with a View,'' as Octavian, also called
Octavius), to director Franc Roddam (``Quadrophenia'') and
executive producer Robert Halmi Sr. Most of Halmi's recent
miniseries (``Gulliver's Travels,'' ``The Odyssey,'' ``Alice in
Wonderland'') have been masterful-event television. ``Cleopatra''
is a worthy addition to this lineage.
</P>
<P>
   But who plays Cleopatra? Well, the long-dead monarch needed a
makeover, free of preconceptions, the filmmakers said. Enter
relative newcomer Leonor Varela, an exotic Chilean raised in
Colorado who now calls where else? Paris her home.
</P>
<P>
   Varela, who previously appeared with another ``Titanic'' alum,
Leonardo DiCaprio, in ``The Man In the Iron Mask,'' plays the queen
as someone willing to play any and all angles to keep Egypt at
least semi-autonomous from Rome even at the risk of being branded
``the Whore of the Nile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are you, Cleopatra?'' Caesar asks her before bedding her.
``Are you someone I can trust?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Egypt,'' she replies, ``and Egypt is yours for one night
only.''
</P>
<P>
   And ours for two nights.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His e-mail address
is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
