<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5973 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STARWARS-GEEK-HN     05-21 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STARWARS-GEEK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE CONFESSIONS OF A CERTIFIED JEDI GEEK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEN FOUNTAIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Star Wars,
</P>
<P>
   nothin' but Star Wars ...''
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Murray's ``Saturday Night Live'' lounge-singer
character sang those inane lyrics to John Williams' ``Star Wars''
theme music, he was lampooning the hold the original movie had on
American (and world) popular culture for months after its May 1977
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' was then a pervasive phenomenon that could have
been described the way Obi-Wan Kenobi described the Force: ``an
energy field created by all living things; it surrounds us, it
penetrates us, it binds the galaxy together.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, 22 years later, Murray may have to warm up his vocal chords
and put on his leisure suit again. With the arrival of ``Episode I:
The Phantom Menace,'' ``Star Wars'' mania has hit the cultural
landscape with all the force of, well, the Force.
</P>
<P>
   A certain segment of the world's population (they may number in
the dozens) will remain impervious to the full effect of this
mania. To them, George Lucas' original movie was an exciting,
well-produced science-fiction adventure with great special effects
and fake-looking aliens _ remember the bat-faced creature begging
for a drink in the cantina scene? _ nothing more, nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   But there are others for whom ``Star Wars'' was something else
altogether. Let's call them, for simplicity's sake, Jedi geeks (we
know who we are).
</P>
<P>
   For us, ``Star Wars'' (and its sequels, ``The Empire Strikes
Back'' and ``Return of the Jedi'') was a fable for the Space Age, a
myth on the order of ``The Iliad.'' Between scenes of galactic
destruction, it imparted the wisdom of the ages to our
adolescence-addled minds.
</P>
<P>
   To us, merely watching the movie several (or several dozen)
times wasn't enough. We read the novelizations, the
behind-the-scenes books, the comic books. Yes, we bought the action
figures. A few years later, we even listened to the 13-part
National Public Radio version (let's see them try that with ``The
Matrix.'')
</P>
<P>
   We learned that in addition to shamelessly borrowing from
sources as diverse as ``Flash Gordon,'' Hollywood westerns and
Akira Kurosawa films, Lucas was heavily influenced by esteemed
mythology professor James Campbell's seminal book, ``The Hero With
a Thousand Faces.'' Lucas took the basic structure of the hero
myths of various cultures across the globe _ which Campbell called
``the hero's journey'' _ and refashioned it in a futuristic setting
that, while technologically far ahead of our own, was still ``a
long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   This mythological sense was created on many levels:
</P>
<P>
   _ Small pieces of dialogue, such as the early scene when the
persnickety 'droid C-3PO addresses hero Luke Skywalker as ``Sir
Luke,'' echoing the Arthurian legends.
</P>
<P>
   _ The clearly delineated characters representing Good and Evil.
</P>
<P>
   _ Williams' rousing score, patterned after the Romantic-era
Norse epic operas of Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   _ Darth Vader, in his black robes and breath mask, looking for
all the world (or solar system) like the Black Knight.
</P>
<P>
   But the thing that really sealed the deal was the lightsaber.
When Ben Kenobi gave Luke his father's weapon, and Luke set it
alight with that great whoosh, our hearts leapt to our throats. A
sword made of laser-light. How cool could you get?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the references were easy to spot. Obi-Wan Kenobi was
clearly patterned after Merlin the magician, with some samurai
master thrown in for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Others were harder to catch. We learned that the Death Star
trash compactor was the dark, dank place that (according to
Campbell) the Hero must enter before emerging again into the light
(as in the biblical story of Jonah in the belly of the whale).
</P>
<P>
   Yoda, the Jedi Master who took Kenobi's place in ``Empire,'' was
the equivalent of the small gnomes who guide the Hero through his
perilous journey. But the puppet-makers who fashioned him also gave
Yoda the eyes of Albert Einstein, to enhance the little green guy's
sage status.
</P>
<P>
   It was Yoda who gave voice to the Saga's (we Jedi geeks always
refer to the films as the Saga) most profound tenets:
</P>
<P>
   ``Always in motion is the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Jedi uses the Force only for defense, never for attack.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course: ``Try not. Do, or do not. There is no try.''
(The last was quoted fairly recently in the ultra-hip ``Chasing
Amy.'')
</P>
<P>
   This is the thing that noninitiates don't get about the Saga's
hold on us Jedi geeks. To those of us growing up in the
freewheeling, post-Watergate Me Decade of the 1970s and the early
'80s, the films were discussing, in an entertaining way, what the
politicians call ``values.''
</P>
<P>
   To wit:
</P>
<P>
   If an evil Galactic Empire is about to use its most fearsome
weapon against a ragtag group of rebels (including a beautiful
princess), you help out, even if the odds against you are abysmal
and even if you've just been given the equivalent of the Texas
Lotto.
</P>
<P>
   If your best friend has been flash-frozen in a block of metal
and is being held captive by a 3000-pound slug, you must help your
friend. It's just that simple.
</P>
<P>
   If the worst villain in the galaxy, who has previously cut off
your hand, turns out to be your father, well, you might cut off his
hand, too, but you still give him a chance to redeem himself.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, most of us aren't presented with such dilemmas very
often. Still, the basic messages are universal: courage in the face
of wrong-doing; loyalty to friends and family; taking
responsibility; compassion. Or, as Spike Lee put it, ``Do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
