<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE LETTER' ISN'T A BAD GREETING CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's the mawkishly generic title, or maybe that it's been
programmed as the distaff ``Phantom Menace'' alternative, but ``The
Love Letter'' is a movie you dislike on principle.
</P>
<P>
   So damn director Peter Chan and the nook-and-cranny whimsy of
Maria Maggenti's script for disarming skeptics with a lack of
saccharine and an ensemble in equal refusal to leave things sugary.
Cute, however, is another story.
</P>
<P>
   But when sanguine, dewy-eyed and dreamy conversations about the
rapture of two people sharing an ``epistolary relationship'' end in
lascivious barbs, it's difficult to fault this film for
occasionally wandering into pleasantville. Throughout the script,
there are salty exchanges between Kate Capshaw's lonely bookstore
owner and her man-hungry best friend Janet (Ellen DeGeneres at her
sublimely Thelma Ritter-est).
</P>
<P>
   Helen (Capshaw) starts having fantasies about a letter she found
jammed between the cushions of her sofa, fixating on the idea of
the man who could have sent it. Soon people are catching the letter
like a cold, finding it hanging around Helen's store, reading it
and falling in love with the writer. This is one of those New
England sleepy towns where no one locks doors, the eccentrics ride
bikes and it wouldn't be surprising if Jessica Fletcher has a
charge account at Pop's.
</P>
<P>
   There's a classy, subversive polish to all this familiarity that
snaps the pap into shapely storytelling, thriving on conveniences
and contrivances. Only you don't see the film for the cheeky
statement on real love it is until you know who the author and
addressee of said love letter are.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chan makes a formidable, attractive Hollywood debut
with a film whose subject rivals his own Hong Kong work in its
sophisticated dances of disconnect between the romantically
challenged. He seems frighteningly content early on being swamped
in Nora Ephronica with old-heads like Roy Orbison and Louis
Armstrong telling you how to feel on the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Like the pro-literacy Ephron and www.webphobic.org movie
industry, ``Love Letter'' finds the Olde Book Shoppes as the last
sanctuary of mental purity, cultural cleanliness and Luddite
romanticization. But Chan tempers the restlessness with less pep
and pop than Ephron (``You've Got Mail'') and a larger reserve of
confidence and self-control that similarly delays the inevitable
long enough for archetypes to grow into characters.
</P>
<P>
   Capshaw has been trying for two decades to parlay that
Hollywood-Golden-Age name and her seductively angular face into
something more than Dame Spielberg and the ersatz fame that
follows. The closest she's come is darkly slinking off with '89's
``Black Rain.'' Here, she's effortlessly withdrawn and as appealing
as she's been on film. The spindly, inspired, entirely brilliant
Tom Everett Scott as Helen's love-struck employee persuades Capshaw
to loosen up.
</P>
<P>
   And a post-``Ellen'' DeGeneres slings one-liners the way the
less articulate flip birds. The cast also features Scotswoman
Geraldine McEwan and fidgety pixie Julianne Nicholson, as the
candied feminist Scott's character uses her to get close to Helen.
</P>
<P>
   The only stiff is Tom Selleck, playing a fireman also burning
for Helen, who always seems to be acting with commercial breaks in
mind. By the time Blythe Danner and Gloria Stuart as Helen's mom
and granny wander into town and the piano in great Luis Baclav's
otherwise fantastic score starts twinkling intermittently, ``Love
Letter'' is already as suspiciously confabulated as an long-form
Hallmark ad. But Chan, Maggenti and Co. infuse it with the rankled
wit of a Shoebox Greeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
