<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5996 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-ACTORS-LADN     05-21 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-ACTORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EPISODE I' FILM NOTHING LIKE BEING THERE FOR ACTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Critics may complain that there's less life in the
human elements of ``Star Wars: Episode One _ The Phantom Menace''
than in the computer-generated ones.
</P>
<P>
   But the actors who worked on the movie beg to differ. They say
making George Lucas' follow-up to his influential science-fiction
trilogy was a fantastic experience.
</P>
<P>
   When it wasn't driving them nuts, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I showed up on this set, the hardest job I had was to
stop grinning,'' says Samuel L. Jackson, a ``Star Wars'' fan since
he saw the first New York screening of the original film in 1977.
``It was, `Look at this!' I walk into my dressing room, Jedi
outfits, put one on, stand in front of the mirror, went, `Yeaaah.'
A guy comes over and says, `Pick a lightsaber.' I take one _ boom!
_ put it on. Walk on the set and there's Yoda. I said, `OK! Here we
go.'''
</P>
<P>
   To put it more succinctly: ``All of it was cool,'' according to
Jake Lloyd, the 10-year-old actor who plays Anakin Skywalker in
``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``Phantom Menace'' demanded the most of its actors'
imaginations and stamina. Shot in England, Italy and the Tunisian
Sahara, incorporating an unprecedented 2,000 computer effects shots
and packed to bursting with weird creatures, machines, costumes and
environments, it was a tough job just to keep up with.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, it seemed like I was just going to have the best
summer ever, but it was so much harder than I expected,'' notes
Natalie Portman, who plays the heroic _ and outlandishly wardrobed
_ teen-age space queen Amidala. ``I really liked the people that I
worked with, and George is wonderful, but we worked really long
days, we were in the desert for a long time, and I had to wear ...
not the greatest costumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have done harder things for money,'' she notes with a
laugh, ``but it wasn't as big of a breeze as I thought it was going
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Liam Neeson, who plays veteran Jedi Knight Qui-Gon Jinn in the
prequel, has numerous scenes with alien co-stars who were
completely generated by computers long after he'd filmed his parts.
In many of those cases _ such as with the elastic-limbed,
hyperactive Gungan Jar Jar Binks or the crude, hovering junkyard
owner Watto _ actors were on the set impersonating the creatures.
</P>
<P>
   But it was still a challenge to play against essentially unknown
quantities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to act with something that isn't there,'' notes the
towering Irishman, who's more accustomed to playing notable
historic figures (Oskar Schindler, Michael Collins, Oscar Wilde) on
screen and stage. ``Yet there's a technique to it. My main
consideration was that I didn't want to be like those early, early
science fiction films where you see the hero with a glassy-eyed
stare, trying to fight some huge ant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were anxious to get some kind of input from in back of the
camera,'' Neeson continues. ``Sometimes, little colored pingpong
balls helped focus the eyes. Yet you didn't always want to do that,
because in real life your eyes go all around the room when you're
talking to someone. For the first couple of weeks, that was
tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Even trickier was a climactic lightsaber fight pitting Qui-Gon
and Ewan McGregor's youthful Obi-Wan Kenobi against Darth Maul, a
devil-headed villain played by stuntman Ray Park. More vigorous
than the swordfights in the original trilogy, this confrontation
required intense acrobatics as well as a more elaborate
choreography, since Darth Maul's laser blades shoot out in two
opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a problem finding time to rehearse it, and I especially
love to rehearse something which can potentially be dangerous,''
says Neeson, who did his share of swashbuckling in the likes of
``Excalibur,'' ``The Bounty'' and ``Rob Roy.'' ``The `Rob Roy'
fight was rehearsed for 10 weeks. But (`Menace' stunt coordinator)
Nick Gillard and Ray Park were absolutely superb. Ray not only had
to play Darth Maul, he learned my moves and Ewan's moves, so
anytime we'd get stuck or couldn't remember the balletic step or
whatever it was, Ray could always show us the way. It was like a
very intricate dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dance _ breakdancing, to be exact _ was the major component of
Ahmed Best's performance. That and some Charlie Chaplin, Jackie
Chan and Buster Keaton. Best was both the stand-in and model for
the computer animated Jar Jar, and also provided the creature's
mostly indecipherable, hard-to-warm-up-to voice track.
</P>
<P>
   ``No accent!'' insists Best, a native New Yorker of Caribbean
heritage. ``I mean, I dunno, I guess there is an accent because
everybody has been hearing one. But it's completely unintentional.
There was no Caribbean in it, no Jamaican, no patois, no Creole, no
French, no German, no nothin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Jar Jar's body language is another unique form of expression.
Best came up with all of the clumsy amphibian's jellyfish
movements, then modeled them for lead animator Rob Coleman after
the fact in the computer studio. While on the actual set, Best wore
a complete Jar Jar costume, sans only the floppy, uncontrollable
ears.
</P>
<P>
   This made jumping around like a fool difficult enough. But in
Tunisia, where scenes set on the desert planet Tatooine were
filmed, Best says the latex costume added some 80 degrees to the
already scorching, triple-digit temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cool because I was so hot, it was easy to shoot laser
beams out of my eyes,'' Best jokes. ``Actually, what you see here
is completely digital animated; I really didn't survive!''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extreme demands, Best claims that ``every day was
fun. I didn't have a bad moment on the set. There's no dirt in
`Star Wars: Episode I.' Isn't that shocking? Everybody was really
happy, as far as I could tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who has a small, sedentary role as Jedi Council member
Mace Windu, claims he would've been pleased just to play a guy in a
nondescript Stormtrooper uniform. But even though his ``Star Wars''
enthusiasm knows few bounds, he repeatedly expressed the hope that
he'll get some real action in the prequel sequels.
</P>
<P>
   And if there's a dark side to his encounter with the Force,
Jackson indicated that the idea of computer-manipulated performers
does not sit well with this acting Jedi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The synthespians,'' the Oscar-nominated star of ``Pulp
Fiction'' says dismissively. ``I don't think you can get a
synthespian to do what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Oscar nominee Neeson does not echo Jackson's sassy
confidence. Indeed, he recently said that he was quitting movie
work; he now claims that statement was made in jest and anger, but
it was definitely a reaction to the dehumanizing demands of modern
high-tech moviemaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult to constantly have to hit marks and be
careful about what you're doing with your arms and such,'' Neeson
reports. ``If you make the slightest wrong move, you might knock
something that's going to be there in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   The final result, though, was worth it _ even if it does come
with its own unique frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the movie,'' Neeson says. ``But I've only
seen it once. It's like being very hungry and somebody brings you a
tray of all your favorite foods, but you just have time to grab the
french fries before it's taken away. I need to see it a few more
time to digest it.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger actors are predictably more enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome; there are whole scenes that didn't even enter
into my mind the first time I saw it,'' says Israel-born Portman,
who was not a ``Star Wars'' fan before she started taking in
multiple screenings of ``Phantom Menace.'' ``I was just so amazed
by all the scenery that I got distracted. I didn't recognize 99
percent of the settings; it's funny to watch yourself walking
around a place that you've never been to. It's a huge exercise in
imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it. All of it,'' young Lloyd concludes, having seen
the movie three times. And counting. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-MAYWEATHER-BOS &LR;      05-21 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MAYWEATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FLOYD MAYWEATHER JR., A BRIGHTER FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Floyd Mayweather Jr. should have known life was
going to be a little different for him the day his dad got shot in
the leg while he was holding his son. The shooter was Floyd Jr.'s
mother. Floyd Jr. was a year old.
</P>
<P>
   Things have been kind of hectic ever since.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Floyd Sr. was four months removed from losing a
tough bout to Sugar Ray Leonard in which he broke his hand early
and lost consciousness late. In the middle he did pretty well,
which sums up the way most of his career went in boxing. Pretty
well in the middle. Not so good at the end.
</P>
<P>
   The same has not held true for his only son, however. Floyd Jr.
went on to steadfastly follow in his father's footsteps when they
led to a boxing ring, but studiously avoided the ones that led his
father to bullet holes and a federal prison in Michigan. Just call
it a boxer's story. A family story. Just don't call it a Kodak
moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to make the mistakes I made,'' Floyd Sr. said
as he prepared his undefeated son for Sataurday night's third
defense of the World Boxing Council super featherweight title they
won together last October, 24 months after Junior came out of the
Olympic Games and nine months after Senior came out of the prison
cell where he'd resided the past 5 1/2 years. ``I made enough for
both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The son was 16 and already a highly ranked amateur when his
father made the biggest mistake of his life and was convicted of
conspiring to traffic in drugs, large detergent boxes filled with
cocaine being central to the case. He was sentenced to 5 1/2 years
in prison and did them all, and while he was away, his boy grew
into a man, a young man who would become a 1996 Olympic bronze
medalist, a three-time National Golden Gloves champion, and a
budding professional who would make his debut Oct. 11, 1996,
without his father in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so much about doing the time as it was losing the
time,'' Floyd Sr. said. ``I'd trained him since he was a baby. He
was boxing doorknobs when he was a kid. I used to take him to the
gym and put him on my shoulders so he could hit the bags. Then I
missed so many moments.''
</P>
<P>
   He missed his boy becoming the first American Olympian to beat a
Cuban fighter in 20 years, but he heard about it. He missed him get
robbed of the chance to fight for gold in Atlanta in 1996 and
settle for a bronze medal, but he heard about it. He missed his pro
debut, a second-round knockout of Roberto Apodaca in Las Vegas, but
he heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   Heard about all the moments he missed but saw none of them, no
TV in prison available on the nights young Floyd began to move
farther along in boxing than old Floyd ever reached.
</P>
<P>
   All he had were his memories and the days his son would come to
visit, days that were hard on the old fighter and the young
fighter, as well. Hard on the father and on the son, even though
the son works hard to hide the hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at it as he was gone away for a while but he'd be
back,'' Mayweather said Thursday. ``It wasn't that hard for me to
deal with. When he wasn't part of my life, I did what he wanted me
to do. I kept winning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the father was away, life went on. The son continued to
fight under the occasionally watchful eyes of his uncles, two-time
world champion Roger Mayweather and longtime professional Jeff. He
continued to fight even without his father to take him to the Tawsi
Gym in Grand Rapids any more like he did in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   He kept fighting and he kept winning, going 84-6 as an amateur
and 13-0 as an professional before his father finally came back to
him last year. Yet when he's honest about it, Floyd Mayweather Jr.
had to admit those days were hard to deal with. Hard for the father
and harder for the son. Hard the way a boxing life can be hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me become a man,'' Mayweather said. ``It hurt when he
told me he was going away. I needed him so much some times it hurt
inside. It hurt until he came back. But there was no more crying
after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your father's locked up, he don't want to see his son, who
he taught to be a man, crying. But things happen for a reason. I
saw my father's downfall. I learned to stay away from drugs. I
learned if you didn't, you end up dead or in jail. I feel I know
how to deal with pressure better than anybody because I faced it
since I was young.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad went to prison and I went on and won a world
championship and he was right there in my corner. He's been down a
bad road but he's back now to make sure I do the right things.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he's done nothing but. After the Olympics, Mayweather
signed a promotional deal with Bob Arum that paid him a $100,000
bonus plus living expenses in Las Vegas and a guarantee that he
would earn at least $100,000 his first year and $150,000 his
second. Eight days short of his second year as a prizefighter, his
father was training him again and he was destroying a game super
featherweight champion named Genaro Hernandez, who had never lost
at 130 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fight most people thought young Mayweather was not yet
ready for. Hernandez was considered the class of the 130-pound
division, having lost only once when he moved up to fight Oscar De
La Hoya at 135, while Mayweather had had only 17 professional
fights.
</P>
<P>
   His father laughed at the skeptics, promising that the world
would see Hernandez ``isn't crap.'' His son backed up his words,
making Hernandez look that way until the fight was stopped with the
dethroned champion sitting on his stool and declining to continue
after eight rounds.
</P>
<P>
   One fight later, the father thrust the son back in against
highly regarded Angel Manfredy in a tough match many felt was
coming too soon. Manfredy lasted only two rounds. Unlike many
people, Floyd Mayweather Sr. was not surprised. Just as he is not
surprised today that his boy is considered among the top fighters
in the world at 22, an undefeated world champion who seems in
little jeopardy when he fights a replacement named Justin Juuko
because his original opponent, Goyo Vargas, pulled out 72 hours
before their match was scheduled to be broadcast on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   The father knows things happen in boxing and in life so he is
unfazed by the ups and the downs, just as he is unfazed at the
possibility that all this celebrity is rushing in too fast on his
young son.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of success that has undone a lot of fighters.
Frankly, it took far less to undo the father, who once was the No.
1-ranked welterweight in the world but never stayed there long
enough to get a title shot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Mayweather Sr. strokes his wrinkled face for a moment as
he ponders what the son has accomplished with him, then without
him, and now with him once again, and nods his head. Yes, he seems
to be saying, the world can overwhelm a young man with talent and
the belief that nothing can stop him but it won't. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's pound for pound the best fighter in the end,''
Mayweather said of his son. ``Some people are surprised by what's
happened to Little Floyd but I knew it was going to happen. None of
this was a secret to me. Even in the years I was away, I always
felt Floyd was destined to be a world champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch him some times in the gym when we're training and it's
like he's the whole family rolled into one. One minute he'll tuck
his chin behind his shoulder like I did. Then he'll throw a hard
jab or a big hook like Roger did. Or he'll slip punches the way
Jeff used to. He's become the best of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take my career seriously. I wasted my talent. That's
why I get on his ass. He can be more than just a good fighter. He
can be a great fighter. I can honestly say he's the whole
package.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say at 22 that Floyd Mayweather Jr. already is. He was
selected fighter of the year by both KO and Ring magazines last
year, the sport's two most high-profile bibles. He is included in
many of the pound-for-pound top 10 rankings and is considered the
leading 130-pound fighter in the world today.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing loves Floyd Mayweather at the moment. And then there's
his opinion of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm the one bringing all the charisma to the 130- pound
weight class,'' young Mayweather said. ``I've fought the best guys
out there. I know Saturday night Oscar fights the main event but I
feel like it's a doubleheader. I feel I'm a main event, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to overshadow Oscar but I feel I'm the best
fighter in the world, just like he feels he's the best fighter in
the world. I learned how to become a champion. You work hard and
hit your opponent first, fast and often. I did it in a year and 11
months because I listened. If you listen and you put it together,
see what you come up with?''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, you can come up with a boxing family's story. A
story of hard luck, hard punches, and heart. A story, in the end,
of survival. It's a son's story . . . and a father's.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, my son is one of the best fighters in the
world,'' the father said Thursday, the pride clear in his face.
``So I don't want him to blow his chance. This is his journey. I'm
just glad to share it.''
</P>
<P>
   As glad as his son is to share it with him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
