<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-HIGH-COURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT SELECTION PANEL CAN RESHAPE BAY STATE COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Over the next two years, Governor Paul Cellucci will
have the chance to reshape the state Supreme Judicial Court,
replacing four of seven judges on what is one of the most respected
courts in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Acutely aware of his power to influence the future of the
state's highest court, the governor has assembled a group of nine
lawyers, headed by former US Attorney Wayne Budd, to recruit and
select the best candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he wanted the group to find great legal minds who
will ``apply the law, not make it.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics already nervous about the sway the Republican
administration could have on the SJC _ the oldest appellate court
in the Western hemisphere _ said Cellucci was trying to hide behind
the added layer of headhunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has pretty much made up his mind that he wants
judges of a certain ideological stripe, and in picking a diverse
committee of lawyers to enlist applicants and to screen them, I
think he's trying to give himself political cover,'' said Boston
defense lawyer Harvey Silverglate.
</P>
<P>
   But Budd disagreed. ``If I believed we were being asked to serve
as political cover, I'm sure I would not wish to serve and I'm sure
the other members would feel the same. Trust me,'' Budd said.
</P>
<P>
   The former federal prosecutor, now New England group president
at Bell Atlantic Corp., said he had been cleared of potential
ethical conflicts in dealing with the SJC, whose decisions could
impact the telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, who has the final say over SJC appointments, justified
the new commission. He said the existing nominating committee,
which will remain in place, would have a hard time filling four
posts in such a short time frame, especially given the weight and
permanency of the decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do want to move quickly and there's a lot of work that
needs to be done,'' Cellucci said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Charles Fried will step down June 30 to return to
Harvard Law School, and Chief Justice Herbert Wilkins will retire
Aug. 31. Cellucci hopes to fill both positions immediately. Also,
faced with mandatory retirement at age 70, Justice Neil Lynch will
leave in June 2000, and Justice Ruth Abrams in December 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Francis W. Sargent was the last governor to have so many SJC
appointments, officials say, with six vacancies between 1969 and
1972, when he named the current chief justice to the panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has the authority to shape this court for the
next two decades,'' said Lauren Stiller Rikleen, president of the
Boston Bar Association. ``That is just very historically
significant and very crucial to the future of the courts of
Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he wanted the new judges to reflect the diversity
of the state. The panel now comprises two white women, one black
man, and four white men.
</P>
<P>
   After signing an executive order establishing the volunteer
commission, Cellucci said he faced an ``awesome responsibility of
appointing the majority of the SJC,'' and he vowed to ``not apply
any sort of narrow ideological litmus test.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone could be nominated who's opposed to the death
penalty,'' added Cellucci, who is in favor of capital punishment.
``I'm just looking for top-notch legal minds. . . . They'll be
serving on the court long after I finish my term for governor.''
</P>
<P>
   He also praised the volunteer commission _ and downplayed any
potential conflict of interest Budd could face _ saying it is a
group with integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The commission members are: Budd; Michael Angelini, chairman of
Bowditch &AMP; Dewey in Worcester; Ronald Cass, Dean of Boston
University Law School; Robert Cordy, managing partner at McDermott,
Will &AMP; Emery of Boston; Ellen Kearns of Epstein, Becker &AMP; Green of
Boston; William Lee, senior partner at Hale &AMP; Dorr of Boston; Nancy
Frankel Pelletier of Robinson, Donovan, Madden &AMP; Barry of
Springfield; Regina Pisa, managing partner at Goodwin, Procter &AMP;
Hoar of Boston; and Ellen Zack of McLellan &AMP; Zack of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Silverglate said it was not necessarily a good idea to have only
lawyers, albeit from diverse legal specialties and races, help
choose the justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the governor is enlisting input it would be a good idea to
have nonlawyers,'' he said. ``Lawyers get myopic about what it
takes to make a good judge.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stiller Rikleen of the bar association disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all share enormous intellectual firepower,'' she said.
``These are very bright lawyers. . .(Cellucci) seems to have
touched all the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   The SJC has oversight of the Board of Bar overseers, the
Commission on Judicial Conduct, and the Massachusetts Mental Health
Legal Advisors' Committee, among other agencies. The single
justices also decide about 800 cases a year and the full bench
renders about 265 written decisions annually.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of deadlines for applications is June 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
