<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACTION OF INDIANAPOLIS BOSS WAS OFF TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone must have sent the Indianapolis Racing League a copy of
the US Constitution, specifically the First Amendment, which
prohibits the most powerful institution on the planet, the US
government, from interfering with the freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe someone informed IRL president and founder Tony George
about the modern-day repercussions of meddling in media business.
</P>
<P>
   There's no other way to explain George's sudden retreat Thursday
after banning a Sports Illustrated writer from the Indianapolis
500. George didn't like a photograph published with a May 10th
story about three fans killed by flying debris May 1 at the
VisionAire 500 in Concord, N.C., and denied credentials to SI's Ed
Hinton. Well, Hinton can now cover the event, but the cost of his
reinstatement to the IRL boss was the national revelation that
George isn't the god he thinks he is.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, the Founding Fathers had no idea journalism would
become part of a trillion-dollar entertainment conglomerate, one
that would spend millions, sometimes billions, on sports properties
that, in essence, are without the slightest hint of social
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   But laws are laws, and time has a way of transforming even
celebrity gossip into ``journalism,'' and auto racing into a very
wide world of sports.
</P>
<P>
   The races are not particularly evil, but it is one of the few
sporting events in America in which fans can actually die from
watching.
</P>
<P>
   The crash at the VisionAire 500 rocketed debris, including a
tire, over a 15-foot fence and into the packed grandstand, killing
three and critically injuring a 9-year-old girl and eight others.
Last July, a similiar accident occurred, leaving three dead and six
injured during a race at the Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Those tragic events were news by any definition, and deserved
all due coverage. Sports Illustrated thought so and published a
story by Hinton under the headline ``Fatal Attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinton argued persuasively that the two tragedies within the
last nine months deserved immediate attention. ``Either incident
without the other might have passed into memory as a grievous
fluke,'' Hinton wrote. ``Together they should ignite a public
outcry that doesn't dissipate until track officials devise a plan
to prevent further episodes of this nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinton offered possible solutions, including building higher
fences and prohibiting open-wheel cars from racing on high speed
oval tracks. Some of Hinton's suggestions have already been
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the story was a photograph of two of the three
bodies, covered in sheets, lying on the blood-stained concrete
aisles. On the next page, the magazine ran a full-page Valvoline
advertisement. The ad featured four guys working under the hood of
a car with the caption: ``You're born. You die. In between you work
on cars. We should all be so lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRL brass took umbrage over the photograph, and took the
unusual step of barring Hinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The photograph in Sports Illustrated was very tasteless and
offensive, not only to the family of the deceased but to many
people, including us,'' IRL spokesman Fred Nation told the
Associated Press. ``The total coverage of the story, we thought,
was offensive and inaccurate, and that's why we took the action we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the photograph was horrifying, but then again so was
the tragedy. The placement of the ad, well, was plain stupid.
</P>
<P>
   But to pull the credentials of a writer who had nothing to do
with the headline or ad and everything to do with trying to ensure
auto racing fans a little safety at the track is lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, that what's some of the owners of sports
properties have become _ lunatics.
</P>
<P>
   While IRL officials are trying to assign stories at national
sports magazines, they also have their hands out, trying to squeeze
a few more million dollars from television networks to broadcast
their events.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they successfully negotiated a $4 million increase in
their rights fee with ABC. That's incredible, especially
considering the ratings for the Indy 500 have dropped by 35 percent
over the last three years. The drop is largely the result of
George's decision three years ago to start his own league, leaving
CART out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the First Amendment is not the right piece of paper to
send to the IRL as a reminder of its mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe NASCAR's financial statements and television ratings would
be more instructive. George sorely needs lessons in marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, let's just ignore the IRL all together _ at least
until the next tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not giving up
</P>
<P>
   CNN/SI's ``Page One with Nick Charles'' scores a nice interview
with injured Patriots running back Robert Edwards, who tells
Charles he might play again. ``Yeah, I hear people,'' he Edwards
said. ``They come up and talk to me and I hear them whispering.
They see my knee and say that I am not coming back. He can't
recover from that. But you know that's dumb. They don't know what's
inside of me. I've got the Lord on my side.'' Edwards goes on to
say that playing in the NFL was his childhood dream. ``That dream
has been kind of altered,'' he said. ``But I feel like it's not
over. It hasn't ended.'' . . . NBC has busy a lineup this weekend
with five NBA playoff games. Dick Enberg and Bill Walton call the 3
p.m. Utah-Portland game and Bob Costas and Doug Collins work the
San Antonio-LA Lakers game at 5 p.m. Saturday. Indiana plays in
Philadelphia on Sunday at 12:30 p.m. with Mike Breen and Matt
Guokas working. Tom Hammond, Steve Jones, and Walton work the 3
p.m. Atlanta-New York game. The last game of the tripleheader is
San Antonio at Los Angeles with Costas and Collins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
