<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-CAPSHAW-PROFILE-     05-21 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CAPSHAW-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPSHAW SENDS `LOVE LETTERS' TO VIEWERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Kate Capshaw crazy, or crazy like a fox?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love Letter,'' which Capshaw developed and co-produced, is
her most significant role since ... well, since she won the heart
and hand of director Steven Spielberg while starring in his
``Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   But the film opening this weekend, butting heads with ``Star
Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' which opened Wednesday as
the most anticipated movie since ``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love Letter'' could be slaughtered by ``The Phantom
Menace'' at the box office. Then again, if a lot of movie-goers are
turned away from sold-out Star Wars screenings, they might opt for
a less-crowded picture playing in the auditorium next door. Like
``The Love Letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Capshaw is not looking at it that way. She thinks there might be
a lot of viewers who crave a romance rather than a ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone loves a love story,'' Capshaw said, calling
from Los Angeles to talk about her first film as a producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A romance makes you feel warm and good. If you're not involved
in a love relationship, it makes you want one, I believe. And
that's nice, because it does feel good to have a warm hug and
someone who listens.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, we'll buy that, but we're not sure how many people
will brave the ``Star Wars'' crowds to get a movie hug.
</P>
<P>
   Capshaw, who did her own telephoning rather than having a helper
place the call, was running a little behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I get through here, I have to pick up my kids,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Capshaw and Spielberg are noted for being hands-on parents with
their seven children, even when they are working on films. Not
surprisingly, Capshaw usually gets a lot more of the at-home duties
than her more famous partner, even though she has been working more
steadily than it might seem _ about 20 films or TV movies since
``Temple of Doom'' in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   But for the seven weeks that Capshaw acted in ``The Love
Letter,'' it was her husband who mainly held down the fort at home.
</P>
<P>
   Capshaw's career was on the rise when she met Spielberg. But
since their romance and marriage, she has definitely been ``Mrs.
Spielberg.'' Does she now feel an urge to let her own light shine?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't,'' she said, with little hesitation. ``I
actually don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never was a very ambitious actress, and I don't feel ...
Maybe the world might look at us and think I'm in his shadow. But
because I'm in the world with him, it's my perception that counts.
And I don't feel like I'm in his shadow because he's such a great
partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so collaborative. He doesn't go to work and make his
movies and come home and eat dinner. I'm on his movie sets, and
he's bringing scripts home. A good deal of our dialogue is around
his creative life, which involves and includes me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Capshaw who bought the rights to Cathleen Schine's novel
``The Love Letter.'' When Spielberg saw what she was working on, he
asked if she planned to offer the project to his company,
DreamWorks. She said, no, it was a small film. Spielberg asked if
DreamWorks could at least pass on it (consider it) first. Instead
of passing, the company picked up the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband's no fool,'' Capshaw said with a laugh. ``Because
the idea came from within the family, he was able to purchase (it
for development) and at least keep it very close, before it went
somewhere else. He actually thinks he's quite clever that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Love Letter,'' Capshaw plays Helen, a bookstore owner
in the small New England town of Loblolly by the Sea. Helen has
given up on love: it's just not for her.
</P>
<P>
   Then she discovers a passionate love letter _ no envelope, no
signature _ in her shop. Suddenly, she is looking at every man she
knows with different eyes, which makes each of the guys see her in
a new way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something magical about the letter that is sort of
transformative,'' Capshaw said. ``It casts a spell of some sort.
People get giddy; they blush; their hearts start to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell a child they have a beautiful voice, they sing
louder and more. I believe it's the same with love. If someone
tells you you're lovable, you become more lovable.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see the letter, and each reader believes it is written to
him or her. All of which creates a series of confusions, bruised
feelings and unexpected entanglements. Helen becomes involved with
a much younger man, one of her employees (Tom Everett Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most charming ingredients of the book was that the
well-controlled, ordered, quite satisfied Helen could get undone by
a young man, who really pulls the rug out from under her,'' Capshaw
said.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, Helen becomes aware of an old suitor, a rather
shy fireman played by Tom Selleck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom was always the first idea for me,'' said Capshaw, who
participated in all the casting choices. ``Tom feels small-town.
Maybe because he was on television, and TV people are in your
living room, he feels very familiar, like someone you'd bump into.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want the Tom Selleck with the mustache _ gorgeous,
cool. We wanted the big glasses, silly fireman, suspenders. It
wasn't an attempt to make him less appealing, but to sink him into
this community. And he can play that guy who tries to do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love Letter'' strives for an almost dreamlike quality
about romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love stories are hard to make,'' Capshaw said. ``Romantic
comedies are really hard to make. They made it look so easy back in
the '40s when there were a hundred (romantic films) a year.''
</P>
<P>
   She gives a little breathy, ironic laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to hit a note that feels real but not so real
that it's mundane or depressing or insignificant. Love is so
personal. Audiences want to fall in love, but if you hit a false
note, you can lose them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 3 p.m. in California, time for Capshaw to get the kids.
But since her film was about to take on the ``Star Wars'' empire of
George Lucas, a close friend of Capshaw and Spielberg, I asked if
she remembered the first time she saw the original ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief silence in which Capshaw took a deep breath.
Almost inaudibly, she whispered, ``I've never seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, like a naughty child running away from a confession, she
yelled, ``Bye,'' and with a laugh she was gone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
