<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPRECIATE-ALFRED-ART     05-21 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRECIATE-ALFRED-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM ALFRED: WRITER, BELOVED MENTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN AND MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Alfred, a playwright, poet, and scholar whose literate
observations about Irish-American life graced the Broadway stage,
and whose pedagogic devotion graced the lives of thousands of
Harvard College students, died at his home in Cambridge, Mass.
Wednesday. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``Hogan's Goat'' and other plays, Mr. Alfred
joined the Harvard faculty in 1954 as a medievalist. He quickly
became one of the college's most popular and versatile teachers,
branching out from ``Beowulf'' to teach drama, poetry, and
screenwriting.
</P>
<P>
   A 1969 book about Harvard named Mr. Alfred as the college's most
sought-after professor, in part for once having given a midterm
exam on ``Bonnie and Clyde.'' Even in retirement (he left Harvard
in 1991) and in failing health, Mr. Alfred continued to tutor one
Harvard student a year _ and to open his doors to countless other
intellectual proteges who came to regard his Athens Street house as
a kind of one-stop continuing education center.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Alfred once said that his great love was the Roman Catholic
Church; he attended Mass nearly every day. But his other great love
was actress Faye Dunaway, who starred in the 1965 off-Broadway
production of ``Hogan's Goat,'' Mr. Alfred's play about
Irish-American politicians, when she was still a Boston University
student. And Dunaway adored Mr. Alfred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just latched on to him and wouldn't let go,'' she said in a
1996 Boston Globe interview. ``This man changes your life with how
he looks at human behavior and play writing. He's taught me how to
work. How to investigate material. How to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mr. Alfred of their first meeting, ``It was as if the
goddess Aphrodite had appeared in the rehearsal hall.'' Not only
did the then-unknown actress get the part, but she became one of
Mr. Alfred's most cherished friends. In 1982, having established
herself as a Hollywood star, Dunaway returned to the Broadway stage
in ``The Curse of an Aching Heart,'' a play written by Mr. Alfred
in collaboration with Dunaway.
</P>
<P>
   American Repertory Theatre director Robert Brustein reviewed
``Hogan's Goat'' for The New Republic and recalled Thursday ``the
geniality of the writing and the person behind it. It was unusually
literate yet not an academic play, a tough-minded one with a deep
feeling for human encounters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Brustein came to Harvard in 1979, ``Bill extended the hand
of friendship, and it was appreciated because theater didn't mean
much to Harvard then,'' Brustein added. ``He probably befriended
more Harvard undergraduates than any teacher in the school's
history.'' Last year, the ART bestowed on Mr. Alfred its equivalent
of a lifetime-achievement award.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Alfred grew up in Brooklyn, N.Y., where his father laid
bricks and his mother worked as a telephone operator. Graduating
from Brooklyn College in 1948, he got his master's and doctoral
degrees from Harvard, where he later held the Abbott Lawrence
Lowell humanities professorship. He also served in the US Army tank
corps in World War II. At Harvard, he cultivated close friendships
with Robert Lowell, Archibald MacLeish, and Seamus Heaney, among
others, and had a profound influence on the likes of Tommy Lee
Jones, Stockard Channing, and John Lithgow.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Alfred's published works included ``The Annunciation
Rosary,'' ``Agamemnon,'' ``Cry for Us All,'' ``Nothing Doing,'' and
many poems and scholarly articles. When he died he was working on
his memoirs, a project friends indicate they will try to bring to
completion. Among his awards were the New York Drama Desk Award.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Mr. Alfred helped organize a benefit for the Poet's
Theater of Cambridge. At the time, he said his goal was to ``drive
home the importance of words,'' a goal he championed far from the
limelight of Hollywood celebrity. Harvard College senior Sam
Speedie was Mr. Alfred's designated tutee this year. In 1970, Mr.
Alfred taught Speedie's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the last true gentleman of Western society,'' Speedie
said Thursday. ``He focused on a writer's strengths, which was
unusual for a writer of his accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishments aside, Mr. Alfred was equally revered for his
gentle mien and generosity of spirit. He often strolled around
Putnam Square in Cambridge like a vision from another era. His pale
complexion, set off by a gray or blue suit, and the omnipresent hat
_ fedora in winter, boater in summer _ gave Mr. Alfred the
appearance of a character out of one of the turn-of-the-century
novels he so adored. His daily walks were punctuated by a tip of
the hat and a smile for anyone inquiring about his own health or
about the latest ART production.
</P>
<P>
   While Mr. Alfred's dress was formal, his personality was not. He
was, among other things, a true friend to the homeless. Each day,
the dispossessed would show up at Mr. Alfred's house, where he
would ask how their evening had gone and whether they'd like some
tea. Then he'd reach into a jar he kept by the door and hand over a
dollar or two.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Alfred is survived by a half brother, Vincent Allfrey; a
niece, Allison Allfrey; and a nephew, Richard Allfrey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
