<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM, ON THE BLOCK, IN PUBLIC SPAT WITH EX-STAR MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The one thing we know without doubt about the case at hand: This
is no time for a struggling investment firm to get hit with a mud
pie.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrim, Baxter &AMP; Associates, a once-hot money management firm
owned by Boston's United Asset Management Corp., is locking horns
in Superior Court with one of its star managers, who wants to jump
ship and run money at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   A non-compete clause in the employment contract signed by James
McCall is at the core of their dispute. But the big picture is
crowded with many other complications, most importantly the ongoing
efforts of UAM to sell Pilgrim, Baxter amid a relentless stream of
bad news.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has already signaled his willingness to play rough. His
suit is peppered with references to the lackluster recent
investment performance of firm cofounder Gary Pilgrim, claims of
nepotism benefiting daughters of another cofounder, Harold Baxter,
and comments about plunging morale as shareholders pull money out
of the company's PBHG funds.
</P>
<P>
   A Pilgrim spokesman said only that allegations in the lawsuit
``will be answered fully and are an attempt to break a valid and
enforcable contract.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't know if his claims are true. As a practical matter, it
doesn't make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers have been trying to slip the chains of employment
contracts to work elsewhere for many years. In the past, deals
almost always have been struck privately.
</P>
<P>
   Employers that have secured non-competes may enjoy the legal
upper hand, but even when they win in court they usually lose in
the real world. Recent cases that have spilled into public view
make our point.
</P>
<P>
   Wellington Management Co. went through a public trial in
Middlesex Superior Court against manager Arnold Schneider, the
first Wellington partner ever to get the boot by his own
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Wellington won its case in court based on the non-compete signed
by Schneider, who had attracted several old institutional clients
to a new firm he started. But Schneider still wound up with most of
those customers and Wellington took a series of public lumps in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   McCall's departure from Pilgrim, Baxter couldn't come at a worse
time. Gary Pilgrim and the PBHG Growth fund he managed helped make
the firm famous, but McCall has been the star of recent times.
</P>
<P>
   UAM bought Pilgrim, Baxter for an estimated $135 million in
1995, when the investment management conglomerate was riding high.
It seemed like a smart move right out of the box: Pilgrim, Baxter
assets under management ballooned from about $4 billion to $15
billion and even skeptical columns like this one called Gary
Pilgrim a ``stock-picking wizard.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall had joined Pilgrim, Baxter as an unknown bank investment
manager months before the firm was sold to UAM. This was the kind
of career move we dream about, moving from a $175,000-a-year job to
become a money manager earning more than $1 million within two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, customers have been fleeing from Pilgram, Baxter.
Redemptions outpaced sales by $2 billion last year and another $1
billion in the first quarter of 1999, according to Financial
Research Corp. Only three fund firms suffered steeper business
declines last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Pilgrim's PBHG Growth fund was one of the firm's worst
bleeders. Net outflows amounted to $1.5 billion last year and
another $543 million in the first quarter of this year, according
to FRC. The fund, which once invested almost $9 billion, had $3.3
billion under management on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several funds managed by McCall, particularly those
that bought large stocks, were shooting out the lights. His PBHG
Large Cap 20 fund earned 67.8 percent last year and 33 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   McCall's lawsuit beefs that he was getting the short end of the
bonus stick in 1997 as his funds performed well while Harold
Baxter's daughter Christine was getting the highest bonus even
though her fund was losing ground.
</P>
<P>
   His suit also rehashes press accounts about how Harold Baxter
gummed up a deal for UAM to sell Pilgrim, Baxter to Nationwide
Financial Services but doesn't offer any new proof. Former Fidelity
executive Paul Hondros, who had been recruited to lead a Pilgrim,
Baxter sales reorganization, left shortly after the Nationwide deal
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, UAM has dispatched Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. to find another
buyer for Pilgrim, Baxter. Whoever buys the firm certainly won't
get McCall as part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine UAM and Pilgrim, Baxter win their case, which is
entirely possible. What will they win? Perhaps McCall will be
prohibited from joining a big firm like Merrill until his contract
expires in 2002 or someone will pay to make the problem go away.
Those seem to be the options.
</P>
<P>
   Now think of all the damage the case can do to UAM and Pilgrim,
Baxter in the middle of a hobbled campaign to sell the company.
It's the last thing in the world they need.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
