<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TORRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BECOME A MANAGEABLE SITUATION FOR TORRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When you listen to Joe Torre, it's easy to forget the
Yankees came to Boston and promptly fell out of first place. He is
the eye of a hurricane, a calming force. Sooner or later you knew
his Bronx Bombers would right the ship, and they took steps toward
that with a 3-1 victory over the Sox at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   After two straight losses, Torre was the winning manager for the
first time since a four-game sweep of San Diego in the World Series
last October.
</P>
<P>
   Boston still maintains a half-game lead in the American League
East over New York after winning two of three games in the May
showdown. The teams will meet again next week in New York. But when
they do, the Sox will be facing a more relaxed Yankee team, chiefly
because of Torre, who returned to the helm Monday after prostate
cancer surgery. His presence _ win or lose _ takes a lot of weight
off everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distractions are gone,'' he said Thursday night. ``I don't
know if it's as much renewed confidence as it is that the puzzle
has been put back together. Everybody is here. I'm surprised how
quickly I feel comfortable in a uniform. It doesn't feel like I
ever took it off, and yet the time away seemed like an eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were any doubts that Torre could handle the catbird
seat again with professional ease, rest assured he can. Before the
game he took on all comers from the media brigade that is always
present when the Yankees and Red Sox meet. He made no promises of
an immediate return to greatness of the Yankee team that won 114
regular-season games last year. But he did promise they'd be
relaxed and play hard. With the talent the Yankees have, that's a
formula for winning.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't worried that a recent stretch in which the Yankees
lost seven of eight had put New York a game and a half behind the
Red Sox. They had only five hits Tuesday night, but received a
stellar two-hit performance from Orlando Hernandez, who had lost
three of his last four starts. It wasn't the same El Duque. He's
one of Torre's guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put it all together,'' said Torre. ``We went up in the same
elevator last night. We had watched a frustrating game the first
night and got beat up the next night. He knew what his job was
tonight. And I knew he was capable of accomplishing what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to start panicking after only two days on the job. I
know we're going to hit. These guys have hit all their lives.
They're not going to all of a sudden stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching has to be the key. You can't freeze the ball. You
have to get 27 outs sometime. I've been on the other side of the
fence. Sometimes you really wonder if you're ever going to get 27
outs. We haven't gone through this for a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   His calmness under fire should surprise no one who knows Torre.
A lesser man might have taken six months off to recover from the
surgery. There were no miracles in the victory. The Yankees got
good pitching, good defense, and scored enough runs to win. That's
how you break out of a slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get a lot of hitting tonight,'' he said. ``But we
played well except for one play in left-center. It feels great to
win again. It's something we can build upon. Until now, the concern
was always for me when I saw them on a regular basis at home. When
you coming back? How you doing? I think mainly it was that there
was somebody missing _ not that they were going to play the game
differently. I think this just put their minds at ease. I'd like to
get used to that again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been pressing. But with Torre back, they figure
to grow in confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Roger Clemens coming back (Friday) will give us a
lift. It might help David (Cone) lead the club back. Starting
pitching is what any success is going to be based upon. At least it
always has been since I've been here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll stress having a little fun. I think we can find the
rhythm. But it's a matter of handling the responsibility. With
Roger on the disabled list, David Cone has had to do it himself and
he's done a hell of a job. The good clubs are the ones that fight
their way out of it. If we can't fight our way out, we're not as
good I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   A big plus, said Torre, is that because of daily talks with
bench coach Don Zimmer, he doesn't really feel that far away.
Zimmer will be there alongside for as long as he wants. But there
is no doubt as to who is running the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty well tied into everything that has happened,'' said
Torre. ``But I missed sitting in the dugout talking to the media
and watching the players come in. We still have a lot of people out
there who will gradually contribute to having a good pitching staff
but who are not going to be the ones who will eventually lead your
pitching staff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
