<HEADLINE>
REDHOOK ALE AD HAS A TOUCH OF FROST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Budweiser ads have starred frogs and lizards. Created by Heater
Advertising of Boston, a new TV ad for Redhook Ale features the
poetry of Robert Frost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something there is that doesn't love a wall,'' intones the
ad's voiceover as a hearty stone mason piles boulder onto boulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger Hopkins builds stone walls like Robert Frost wrote
about,'' the voiceover continues. ``When he's done, he goes for the
solid taste of Redhook, a well-built beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Redhook seemed to burst on the scene during the microbrewery
craze of the early 1990s. For a while, such brands as Redhook, Sam
Adams, and Pete's Wicked Ale were all the rage. Then sales
flattened in 1997, though the fortunes of Sam Adams' parent, Boston
Beer Co., have since improved.
</P>
<P>
   Now a booming economy and an increase in the vital beer-drinking
population of twentysomethings have brewers hoping for a rebound.
With a new brewery in Portsmouth, N.H., Redhook has identified
three key cities for an ad campaign designed to increase brand
awareness: Boston, San Francisco, and its hometown of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where library books per capita are high, our beer sells
well,'' said Redhook chairman Paul S. Shipman, explaining in part
the reason for using Frost as an ad copywriter. In places where
there is ``political open-mindedness'' and plenty of college
campuses, a ``well-built beer'' is most appreciated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Radio ads feature a guitar maker and a Native American who
builds log cabins by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch Cos., makers of Budweiser and Michelob, own a
minority stake in Redhook Ale Brewery Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Most beer ads are about ``boys behaving badly,'' said Heater
chairman Bill Heater. But Redhook is ``not a party beer. . . It's a
quality beer for people who can read.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the rest of the sneaker industry zigs, Puma zags.
</P>
<P>
   Most big sneaker companies, such as Nike Inc. and Reebok
International Ltd., have reduced the number of sports stars they
employ as product endorsers. Over time, the public seems to have
grown immune to the sales pitches of most super jocks.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop Puma, whose North American office is based in
Westford, from signing up boxing champ Oscar De La Hoya. De La Hoya
joins Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams, pro basketball rookie
Vince Carter, and tennis player Serena Williams in the stable of
Puma endorsers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when sporting brands are shying away from athletes'
endorsements, Puma's ability to identify athletes before their
prime is proving to be an integral part of the brand's current
success,'' Puma said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Brodeur Porter Novelli, one of New England's
largest public relations firms, said this week it has acquired
Beaupre &AMP; Co. Public Relations Inc. of Portsmouth, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Cofounder Andy Beaupre said he was persuaded to sell his firm
because his clients were requesting services that only a larger PR
firm such as Brodeur can provide. Beaupre had revenues of $4
million last year; Brodeur had global revenues of $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Beaupre &AMP; Co. will retain its name and autonomy, and Andy
Beaupre will join Brodeur's management team. Both firms specialize
in serving high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New England's other large PR firm had some new business to
announce this week. Weber Public Relations Worldwide of Cambridge
said it had been selected by Ernst &AMP; Young LLP to provide
``brand-building support.'' One of Ernst &AMP; Young's divisions has
been a Weber client for about a year. Now Weber has PR
responsibilities for the entire company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
