<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-SHORTAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY CONFIRMS SEVERE HOUSING SHORTAGE IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco area is in the throes of a
chronic housing shortage that has hit middle- and low-income people
particularly had, according to a new study by a business
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that out of a projected need for 182,542 housing
units in the San Francisco Bay area, only 101,490 had been built
since 1988. For those in lower-income brackets, that shortfall was
even more severe. Out of a projected need of 36,672 units, only
some 9,759 units were built.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a housing crisis in the Bay area today,'' Sunne Wright
McPeak, president and chief executive of the Bay Area Council, said
in a release accompanying the study. ``There simply isn't enough
housing to accommodate the numbers of people moving here for
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The study used housing need projections published in 1989 by the
Association of Bay Area Governments, which at the time sought to
set a bottom line on housing needs for anticipated population
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The council is a public policy organization supported by
businesses. The study released Thursday is based on housing needs
in 50 municipalities in the Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lack housing that is affordable to the work force and that
is located near job centers,'' McPeak said. ``This is why workers
and their families have been forced to the fringes of the Bay
area.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, 4,581 units were needed by San
Francisco's moderate-income population, defined as those making 80
to 120 percent of median income for San Francisco. But only 163
units were built for this income group since 1988. According to the
National Association of Home Builders, San Francisco's
single-family median income in the final quarter of 1998 was
$68,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis is hitting those folks that keep things going,''
McPeak said. ``They're our teachers, firefighters, retail store
workers and nurses.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, those in the above-moderate income category, making
121 percent and up of the area's median income, had 56 percent of
their housing needs met, with 5,271 units built with 9,352 needed.
</P>
<P>
   The study comes as no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pretty much confirms what anyone commuting already knows,''
said Cynthia Kroll, a regional economist with the Fisher Center for
Real Estate and Urban Economics at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Kroll said the housing shortage started in the early 1990s, when
a sluggish economy slowed new housing construction. When the
economy heated up, housing markets were caught short.
</P>
<P>
   That shortfall continues, added Kroll, because of construction
time lags and local zoning and density laws, which restrict the
supply of housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Housing growth doesn't always coincide with job growth,''
Kroll said. ``And you're seeing that in a very exaggerated way
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
