A6025 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV23     05-21 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV23-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK TO SPLIT RETIREMENT PORTFOLIO INTO TWO POOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 23, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a 50-year-old single woman and I have just resigned my
position as a faculty member at a nursing school and will be moving
to Florida. My salary will drop considerably, to about $35,000 or
$40,000. I hope to continue to save for retirement, but not at the
current rate. I now contribute $150 a week to a 403(b) plan and
will do so until August of this year. This account was worth
$37,500 at the beginning of the year with $12,200 in Fidelity Blue
Chip, $5,000 in Fidelity Contrafund, $13,600 in Fidelity
Equity-Income and the rest in Fidelity Magellan. I also have a
rollover IRA with Fidelity, worth $127,000 at the start of
February, with no ongoing contributions. This holds $17,000 in
Magellan, $22,300 in Contrafund, $38,000 in Equity Income, $12,500
in Growth Company, $7,000 in Investment Grade Bond, and the rest in
Blue Chip Growth. Assuming I am able to add only $200 a month after
relocating, what can I expect to have in 15 years? Is my fund mix
appropriate? I don't mind some risk, but this represents most of
the money I have. I sold my house here and realized a net gain of
$40,000; I have not decided if I will buy another home or not _ I
already own a home in Florida, which will be paid off in 12 years.
What kind of income stream might I except at age 65? I expect to
receive about $1,000 a month from Social Security. If I decide not
to buy another home, how should I invest the $40,000?
</P>
<P>
   R.S., Brockton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's begin with the math. For all of these calculations I'm
going to presume that you will achieve average annual portfolio
returns of 10 percent. By the end of August with your continued
$150 weekly contributions to the 403(b), that account plus the
rollover IRA would be worth $180,814. During the next 172 months
until you reach age 65, presuming 200 monthly contributions, the
combined accounts would grow to $783,155.
</P>
<P>
   What can you expect as an income stream from such a nest egg?
Well, what I'd like to see you do upon retirement is to separate
the portfolio into two pools _ one to supply you with an income
stream, and another to generate capital growth to protect you
against inflation in the later years of your retirement. Let's say
you devoted $200,000 of your savings to capital growth, leaving you
with just over $583,000 to generate your income stream.
</P>
<P>
   It's reasonable to presume that a diversified fixed-income
portfolio would yield you about 6.5 percent in your retirement
years; thus you could expect an income stream of about $37,900 a
year, and with steady growth in the value of the additional
$200,000 that you have invested for continued growth. The effect of
this is that, with Social Security added in, you would have an
annual income stream of nearly $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for the portfolio, I tally just 4.3 percent that isn't in
large-cap domestic stock funds. You have no substantial level of
diversification. With the exception of that 4.3 percent in the
Investment Grade Bond, all of your money is invested in the same
market sector. Moving into different market sector wouldn't
increase your risk _ in fact, it would likely have the opposite
effect, since different market sectors tend to move at different
paces.
</P>
<P>
   I would suggest that you move about $30,000 to Fidelity Puritan,
which holds about one-third of its assets on the fixed-income side,
and accordingly would reduce risk. I would then move about $15,000
to Fidelity Select Health Care, which would increase risk, but also
put your money in one of the market sectors I feel is poised for
solid long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I would put $15,000 each into Fidelity Mid-Cap Growth and
Small Cap Stock funds, both moves designed to give you exposure to
additional market sectors. Finally, I would move $10,000 to
Fidelity International Growth and Income, giving you exposure to
yet another market sector. The effect of all these moves would be
to reduce your reliance upon the domestic large-cap stocks from
more than 95 percent of the portfolio to about 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide not to buy more real estate, I think I'd just put
that $40,000 in a solid fixed-income fund such as Fidelity
Government Securities, calculating that you will enjoy having a
solid and sizable chunk of your savings at the conservative end of
the investment spectrum, and that if you left it there until you
retired, it would then represent a $102,873 wild-card _ funds you
could use for travel, other treats, or simply to boost your
everyday standard of living. That growth projection presumed
reinvestment of all dividends, and annual portfolio growth of 6.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You have received a couple of letters regarding the Vanguard
GNMA fund, and you pointed out the possibility of a negative yield
for any given year. This certainly would concern someone cashing in
shares, but what about the retiree who relies on the interest
payments for his income? In other words, how much would the monthly
return be expected to fluctuate over the years, on an investment of
$100,000? Would a Vanguard bond fund be a better investment?
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Foxborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, we have a problem with terminology. When a fund such
as Vanguard GNMA has a bad year, which all such funds tend to do
about twice in any given decade, it is the total return that goes
into the red. The yield, which represents the amount of the
distributions from income on the securities held by the fund, keeps
rolling on in. As for fluctuation in yield, let's look at the
record. In the last decade, the high level of annual distribution
for Vanguard GNMA was 88 cents per share in 1989, and the low was
65 cents in 1993. Income distributions for 1998 were 69 cents per
share. (In addition, in two years of the last decade the fund has
made small capital gains distributions _ 1 cent in 1994 and 1.2
cents per share last year.)
</P>
<P>
   Generally, you can expect the yield on this and other GNMA funds
_ and bond funds in general to slowly trail interest rates in
general, but since the payments of both principal and interest on
the securities which underlie the fund's holdings are guaranteed by
the federal government, you will not see sharp swings in the
month-to-month dividend checks. If you invested $100,000 in
Vanguard GNMA at the price prevailing as this is written, you could
expect a monthly dividend check of about $536. I think the Vanguard
GNMA fund is a better investment than any of the comparable
intermediate-term bond funds at this point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
