<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNSHOWS-LOOPHOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVISION TAKES AIM AT GUN SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gun-control advocates and federal agents have long
complained that gun shows are traveling arms bazaars where
cash-and-carry is the rule, and a loophole in federal law makes it
easy for anyone _ gang member, felon or fugitive _ to buy a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   In a report this year, the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco,
and Firearms wrote, ``A review of criminal investigations . . .
reveals a wide variety of violations occurring at guns shows and
substantial numbers of firearms associated with gun shows being
used in drug crimes and crimes of violence, as well as being passed
illegally to juveniles.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Senate Democrats pushed through changes in the federal
gun control law aimed at closing a loophole that allows all
firearms _ handguns, semiautomatic assault weapons, shotguns, and
rifles _ to be bought and sold off the books at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The provision, sponsored by Senator Frank Lautenberg, a Democrat
of New Jersey, proposes to change law by requiring that all sales
at gun shows be conducted through a licensed dealer who would
perform a background check on the buyer and imposing up to a
three-day waiting period on purchases. It also would require
gun-show promoters to register with the ATF and inform vendors of
the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, only licensed dealers must run background
checks to determine whether purchasers should be barred from buying
a gun because they fall into a ``prohibited category,'' such as a
felon or fugitive, outlined in the 1993 Brady law.
</P>
<P>
   Private dealers and collectors _ those who do not earn their
principal income from buying and selling guns _ are not required to
be licensed and are free to sell guns without following the
background checks, waiting periods, and record-keeping requirements
mandated by the Brady law.
</P>
<P>
   ``These background checks have kept thousands of guns out of the
hands of criminals and others who have no business owning guns,''
Senator Edward M. Kennedy said Thursday on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates and the ATF have complained that private
gun dealers deliberately exploit the loophole at gun shows by using
their special ``exempt'' status as a selling point, advertising
with signs that say, ``No background checks required; we need only
to know where you live and how old you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Lautenberg provision, private dealers would be
required to use federally licensed dealers to do background checks
on their behalf when selling a weapon. However, the legislation
would not apply to purchases of weapons through newspaper ads and
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Even while the majority of people attending gun shows are
law-abiding citizens, gun shows and flea markets have long served
as a mecca for those who want to sell a weapon used in a crime or
buy one they could not purchase in a retail gun shop because of
their record.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by Handgun Control Inc., a Washington
organization led by James Brady, the former White House press
secretary who was seriously wounded during an assassination attempt
on President Reagan, dozens of notorious criminals have bought and
sold firearms at gun shows, including Branch Davidian leader David
Koresh, Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh, and Hank Earl Carr, a
convicted felon who killed three policemen in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, the teenage gunmen who killed a dozen students
and a teacher a month ago at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., used guns acquired at a local gun show.
</P>
<P>
   It is still uncertain whether the House will adopt similar
provisions and whether the bill will be signed into law.
Gun-control advocates warn that if the loophole is not fixed,
unregulated gun sales will continue to fuel violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of all the attention focused on them, especially by
kids, gun shows will just become more popular, more notorious, and
an even greater source for crime guns,'' said Kristen Rand, senior
counsel for the Violence Policy Center, a gun-control research
group that first uncovered the loophole in its 1996 report, ``Gun
Shows in America: Tupperware Parties for Criminals.'' ``It really
is a huge threat.''
</P>
<P>
   But the National Rifle Association, a lobby representing gun
owners, disagreed, saying the Lautenberg measure would put a
greater burden on lawful gun owners buying and selling firearms.
The NRA also cast a skeptical eye on the Clinton administration's
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, the Clinton-Gore administration is papering over a
shameful record of not enforcing existing gun laws,'' said Wayne
LaPierre, NRA executive vice president, and James J. Baker, the
NRA's chief lobbyist, in a statement released after the close
Senate vote. ``Now they want more gun laws they won't enforce. The
federal courts won't want to try these cases. It's more
made-for-television lawmaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA might have a point. There are no federal laws regulating
gun shows, and it is unofficial ATF policy to stay away from
conducting surveillance or enforcing the law at gun shows unless
there is compelling evidence to suggest gun trafficking is taking
place, according to ATF agents speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   They said the agency is understaffed and could not cover even
half of the 4,000 shows held annually in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The administration says it is trying to change that by
requesting money for more agents in this year's budget, according
to Justice Department spokesman Brian Steel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
