<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WEST-BANK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE UNCERTAIN FOR JEWS ON WEST BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHILO SETTLEMENT, West Bank _ As a dry wind swept through a
cluster of five trailer homes on a hilltop, overlooking the rocky,
terraced terrain, Shmuel Kohen declared, ``We are here to protect
the land that God gave us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days after Ehud Barak's landslide election victory over
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, the future for Jewish settlers,
like Kohen, is more uncertain than ever.
</P>
<P>
   If Barak makes good on campaign promises to move forward on the
peace process, he will have to put a stop to settlement activity in
the West Bank, political observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's government gave some tacit support to the settlers'
view that the West Bank, where about 150,000 Jewish settlers have
staked a claim among 1.2 million Palestinians, is part of ``eretz
Israel, or the biblical land of Israel, and that the Jewish right
to that land is ordained in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, a tough-talking former general, is also an unorthodox
Labor politician. He pull won the largest margin of victory for any
prime minister in 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials say he comes to the office with less ideological
baggage on peace talks than did Netanyahu, and with a more
practical approach to security for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The public, right and left alike, appears to trust him on the
issue. Barak won about 25 percent of the vote among settlers in the
West Bank, a traditionally nationalist crowd that viewed Labor's
previous leaders as mortal enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Kohen, a hard-line settler with a knitted kippah and the long
side curls of the strictly observant Orthodox, said he had voted
for Netanyahu, but reluctantly. When asked about Barak, he said:
``Barak knows the importance of us being here. He knows that we are
here for the security of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohen admitted that the far right had suffered a terrible defeat
in the elections.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the settlers had led indirectly to Netanyahu's
defeat. They felt he had betrayed them by moving forward on the
peace agreement hammered out last fall at the Wye River Plantation
in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by the mosque minarets and stone homes of Palestinian
villages, Kohen's encampment is what he calls a satellite of the
Shilo settlement two miles away.
</P>
<P>
   He said the hilltop where the five trailers lie has been named
``Achia,''which Kohen says refers to a biblical prophet who hailed
from these hills. The trailers ring a water tower next to which a
one-room synogogue is being built.
</P>
<P>
   Six Israeli soldiers were also camped out in a nearby steel
bunker, shouldering automatic rifles and listening to Janis Joplin
belt out ``Take A Piece of My Heart.'' The Netanyahu government
says that the soldiers had been put there to protect the settlers,
and that their presence becomes an example of how the settlements
``create facts on the ground,'' as the settlers put it.
</P>
<P>
   The area falls within a swath of land that is under shared
Palestinian and Israeli control, and one of the areas that would be
likely to shift to full Palestinian control in troop withdrawals
outlined in the Wye agreement, which became deadlocked under
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   This small settlement is one of more than two dozen that sprang
up in the West Bank in the final months of Netanyahu's government.
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon went as far as to urge settlers to
``occupy every hilltop'' before Israel moved any further in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The settlements effectively break the contiguity of Palestinian
villages and become Israeli security outposts in the middle of the
small circles of full Palestinian control that dot roughly 10
percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Galia Golan, a spokeswoman for Peace Now, which is lobbying
Barak to remove settlers like Kohen, also has faith that Barak will
understand the peace camp's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settler movement lost in these elections,'' said Golan,
whose group is made of Israelis and Palestinians who support the
peace process. ``We think Barak understands these settlements are
illegal and that for the peace process to move forward they'll have
to be dismantled.''
</P>
<P>
   People as far apart politically as Kohen and Golan, unfocused as
they seem, appear to show that for now, Israelis can view Barak as
they want to. This is possible because Barak took a tough but vague
line on security issues in the campaign, and the Israeli media did
not make him define his positions.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Barak, who is preparing to take office within six
weeks, seems to have momentum to forge ahead, not only in the
Palestinian peace process, but on the Syrian track as well.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has vowed to pull Israeli troops out of the security zone
they occupy in South Lebanon. Such a move would help to pave the
way to a peace agreement with Syria. Some Israeli political
observers have even advanced the idea that Barak could possibly
return the Golan Heights, the region that Israel captured from
Syria in the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his first interviews as prime minister-elect, Barak
responded to a question about the future of West Bank settlements
by saying: ``There are places which I know we will have to make
hard decisions about. That is one of the reasons why I need a broad
government. Then the public can more easily accept the decisions,
and the other side expects to get less.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked more generally about his view of peace, Barak told the
Israeli newspaper Yediot Ahronot, ``I feel like I am a sober
person, a realist, a person who reaches peace not by studying the
visions of the later days of the prophets, but through confronting
reality. I believe in peace from a position of strength, not
fear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
