<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACEDONIA-PRESSURES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC ANIMOSITIES WORSENING IN MACEDONIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOULA VLAHOU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Nina Karagiozova is retired, but that does
not mean she is not working hard.
</P>
<P>
   She washes dishes, makes beds and sweeps floors _ not for her
family but for foreigners now occupying her two-bedroom home on the
edge of Macedonia's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Like hundreds, perhaps thousands, of other Macedonians,
Karagiozova moved into a modest apartment and rented her family's
home for $1,000-a-month _ up to three times the local rate _ to a
foreign organization, one of hundreds brought to Macedonia by the
war in nearby Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Igor Stefanovski, 25, a taxi driver, saves every dollar or
German mark he earns from driving foreigners around for $100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Both say the income in foreign currency is their only source of
security at a time when their tiny nation could be ready to erupt.
</P>
<P>
   Warfare in nearby Kosovo, a potential ethnic time bomb at home
and a plummeting economy have combined to shake the very foundation
of this tiny backwater _ the only former Yugoslavian republic to
break away without bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is in the Army,'' she said. ``I am very afraid for him
and for all of us. . . . We live from day to day now,'' said the
55-year-old Karagiozova, a former employee at an import-export
firm. ``I feel like we're in prison here,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   She is afraid of Serbia retaliating because Macedonia has
accommodated NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia's future, analysts say, lies with having closer links
to the European Union. For the moment, however, the government is
setting short-term goals to survive.
</P>
<P>
   It finally persuaded the international community helping the
refugees to stop importing most supplies and buy Macedonian
produced goods ranging from toothpaste to bottled water. This at
least is some compensation for NATO bombs in Yugoslavia _ which was
once Macedonia's economic lifeline. Macedonia's Chamber of Commerce
estimates that some businesses suffered a 50 percent loss and that
50 to 60 percent of the work force could become jobless. Before the
Kosovo crisis, Macedonia's unemployment rate was near 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Macedonia is not helped in time and if the promised aid
from developed countries does not arrive, it may experience
economic collapse, which nobody wishes. And I think that this is a
scenario for destabilization of the Macedonian state,'' said Deputy
Prime Minister Dosta Dimovska.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has said that it will give Macedonia $21
million in aid; others have agreed to loan it millions more and
still others have started investing in the creaky economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the greatest concern is Macedonia's volatile demographic mix
between ethnic Albanians and the majority Slavs _ the same makeup
that shattered Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanian and Slav Macedonian leaders have desperately
tried to tame the mutual animosity between the two groups,
particularly by the Slav Macedonians.
</P>
<P>
   But with the addition of nearly a quarter million Kosovo
Albanian refugees, the demographic balance is tilting. Conservative
government figures placed the ethnic Albanian population at 21
percent before the refugee crisis. Ethnic Albanians and others set
the figure now at 30 percent or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Now this shift in demographics could give more weight to those
in the Albanian minority who want greater autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a democratic country. But Macedonians and the
Albanians don't like each other. But we have learned to tolerate
each other,'' said political analyst Saso Ordanovski.
</P>
<P>
   Although efforts by political leaders from both groups have so
far succeeded in avoiding violent clashes, signs of intolerance are
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the primarily Slav part of Skopje, residents say they get
nervous when they see cars with license plates from Kosovo. The
government won't allow the UN High Commissioner for Refugees to
expand the camps. Work documents for Kosovar Albanians are only
good until the end of the month. At police checkpoints and border
crossings, Kosovar Albanians are questioned at length and sometimes
harassed. Brawls between the two groups are common, and in some
neighborhoods the graffiti speak loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cure for Albanians is Dr. Professor Vojislav Seselj,''
said big block letters on an apartment building. The ``doctor,'' a
notorious leader of a Serb paramilitary group during the Bosnian
war, made hateful public statements, including an assertion that
the Serbs would take out the eyes of Croats with a rusty spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ``is doing good for his
country. He will clean his country of all Albanians who make the
trouble all these years. What are we going to do now? Do you think
that the refugees will go back?'' said Stefanovski, the taxi
driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a guy who will take away all these refugees from our
country and make the Albanians love this country. As long as they
want to separate from Macedonia, Albanians are no good for
Macedonia'' Stefanovski said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6046 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-21 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO RELIEF WORKERS FACE CHAOS, GRIM SCENES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Four weeks ago,'' David Pryor told his Harvard students
Wednesday, ``I wasn't sure where Albania was.'' He knows now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get sick in Albania,'' was his first advice. Following
three weeks work in the Balkans with the International Rescue
Committee, the former US senator from Arkansas returned to finish
up a post-Senate Kennedy School fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably 70 refugee camps in Albania, holding about
700,000 refugees,'' he began. There are 135 different NGO's
(non-governmental organizations) trying to help, but the system, or
lack of system, makes it chaotic, with a lot of black-marketeering,
theft, profiteering, and sheer confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 problem I see is water, water, water,'' Pryor told a
luncheon audience. ``They're about to run out of water. . . . in
about 60 days, they'll be on the brink.''
</P>
<P>
   He told former Wyoming senator Alan Simpson, his colleague for
18 years in the Senate, that the US Army Corps of Engineers could
do a useful bit of work with water to head off ``the No. 2 problem,
the potential for epidemics and disease, with the lack of sanitary
facilities,'' which will worsen as the heat of the summer breeds
bacteria and all the diseases of crowding, contagion, and
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   The relief workers are often overwhelmed by the scale of the
Serb-instigated tidal wave that dislocated a million Kosovar
Albanians, he said. What's really needed in Pryor's mind is ``a
benevolent dictator,'' to sort out the upheaval and set groups to
appropriate tasks.
</P>
<P>
   He told of some undoubted success stories, like The Flying
Doctors out of Atlanta, a group of docs, nurses, and a dentist _
who ``pulled 140 teeth in one afternoon, some without anaesthetic,
with 40 or 50 people sitting around watching.''
</P>
<P>
   But the overall picture is grim, he said, and left him with a
feeling that it is perhaps best for workers to narrow their focus
and adopt a village or a bunch of refugee kids and work on a
smaller scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might consider adopting a village,'' Pryor told his
audience, which included two men just back from Albania and Dr.
Anne Goldfeld of the Center for Blood Research, who leaves Tuesday
for Tirana for the American Refugee Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Durant, the ARC board member from Mass. General, said
the problem with relief work, which he's done since Vietnam, is
``we keep reinventing the wheel every single time.'' There are 66
million refugees worldwide at the present time, he said, but what
preys most frequently on refugees' psyches is ``separation anxiety
_ `where's my husband, where's my son?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Lucas, who helped the ARC staff negotiate the Albanian
bureaucracy till his return one week earlier, acknowledged the
scene on the ground in the camps is one of ``mass confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to motivate the Kosovars to get organized to help
themselves because of shock, trauma, cultural differences, as well
as ethnic, religious, and class rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, who used to chair the Senate's immigration and refugee
subcommittee, had some scorching words for bureaucracy. ``The UN
High Commissioner's Office for refugees is bureaucracy up the rear
end,'' said Simpson, and changes in US laws to grant refugees
government money meant a lot of immigrants lie or cheat to obtain
benefits. ``We need to redefine the word `refugee,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor noted that Albania is said to have more Mercedeses per
capita than anyplace else. Lucas said many of them are stolen, or
restolen, in a land where you cannot get car insurance.
</P>
<P>
   For Pryor, the lingering image was one of troubled children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw a playground or a play area for children, not
one,'' he said. He suggested the Harvard students consider
volunteering to help the refugee kids, who are kept under close
control by their anxious parents.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts are being made by Microsoft, IBM, and others to
computerize camp records, to attach names and temporary addresses
to information-age lists to lessen the confusion and anxiety over
missing relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might consider adopting a camp,'' said Pryor, whose fellow
Harvard fellow, former South Carolina governor David Beasley, is in
Macedonia now doing similar work. Pryor showed drawings made by
Kosovar kids, typically illustrating their house being torched or
Serbs shooting or shelling Albanian families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Albanians call the Serbs `The Black Hand,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he was leaving Tirana, said Pryor, the last camp he visited
was one of 3,000 refugees, who'd stood in long lines behind a truck
carrying oranges. One refugee, one orange. As he turned to go, said
Pryor, a boy about 10 motioned for him to wait. The kid ran off to
his tent, then ran back, clutching his orange, which he proudly
presented to the American.
</P>
<P>
   Hefting the orange in his hand, Pryor concluded: ``I'm going to
keep that orange for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
