<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO RELIEF WORKERS FACE CHAOS, GRIM SCENES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Four weeks ago,'' David Pryor told his Harvard students
Wednesday, ``I wasn't sure where Albania was.'' He knows now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get sick in Albania,'' was his first advice. Following
three weeks work in the Balkans with the International Rescue
Committee, the former US senator from Arkansas returned to finish
up a post-Senate Kennedy School fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably 70 refugee camps in Albania, holding about
700,000 refugees,'' he began. There are 135 different NGO's
(non-governmental organizations) trying to help, but the system, or
lack of system, makes it chaotic, with a lot of black-marketeering,
theft, profiteering, and sheer confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 problem I see is water, water, water,'' Pryor told a
luncheon audience. ``They're about to run out of water. . . . in
about 60 days, they'll be on the brink.''
</P>
<P>
   He told former Wyoming senator Alan Simpson, his colleague for
18 years in the Senate, that the US Army Corps of Engineers could
do a useful bit of work with water to head off ``the No. 2 problem,
the potential for epidemics and disease, with the lack of sanitary
facilities,'' which will worsen as the heat of the summer breeds
bacteria and all the diseases of crowding, contagion, and
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   The relief workers are often overwhelmed by the scale of the
Serb-instigated tidal wave that dislocated a million Kosovar
Albanians, he said. What's really needed in Pryor's mind is ``a
benevolent dictator,'' to sort out the upheaval and set groups to
appropriate tasks.
</P>
<P>
   He told of some undoubted success stories, like The Flying
Doctors out of Atlanta, a group of docs, nurses, and a dentist _
who ``pulled 140 teeth in one afternoon, some without anaesthetic,
with 40 or 50 people sitting around watching.''
</P>
<P>
   But the overall picture is grim, he said, and left him with a
feeling that it is perhaps best for workers to narrow their focus
and adopt a village or a bunch of refugee kids and work on a
smaller scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might consider adopting a village,'' Pryor told his
audience, which included two men just back from Albania and Dr.
Anne Goldfeld of the Center for Blood Research, who leaves Tuesday
for Tirana for the American Refugee Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Durant, the ARC board member from Mass. General, said
the problem with relief work, which he's done since Vietnam, is
``we keep reinventing the wheel every single time.'' There are 66
million refugees worldwide at the present time, he said, but what
preys most frequently on refugees' psyches is ``separation anxiety
_ `where's my husband, where's my son?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Lucas, who helped the ARC staff negotiate the Albanian
bureaucracy till his return one week earlier, acknowledged the
scene on the ground in the camps is one of ``mass confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to motivate the Kosovars to get organized to help
themselves because of shock, trauma, cultural differences, as well
as ethnic, religious, and class rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, who used to chair the Senate's immigration and refugee
subcommittee, had some scorching words for bureaucracy. ``The UN
High Commissioner's Office for refugees is bureaucracy up the rear
end,'' said Simpson, and changes in US laws to grant refugees
government money meant a lot of immigrants lie or cheat to obtain
benefits. ``We need to redefine the word `refugee,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor noted that Albania is said to have more Mercedeses per
capita than anyplace else. Lucas said many of them are stolen, or
restolen, in a land where you cannot get car insurance.
</P>
<P>
   For Pryor, the lingering image was one of troubled children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw a playground or a play area for children, not
one,'' he said. He suggested the Harvard students consider
volunteering to help the refugee kids, who are kept under close
control by their anxious parents.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts are being made by Microsoft, IBM, and others to
computerize camp records, to attach names and temporary addresses
to information-age lists to lessen the confusion and anxiety over
missing relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might consider adopting a camp,'' said Pryor, whose fellow
Harvard fellow, former South Carolina governor David Beasley, is in
Macedonia now doing similar work. Pryor showed drawings made by
Kosovar kids, typically illustrating their house being torched or
Serbs shooting or shelling Albanian families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Albanians call the Serbs `The Black Hand,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he was leaving Tirana, said Pryor, the last camp he visited
was one of 3,000 refugees, who'd stood in long lines behind a truck
carrying oranges. One refugee, one orange. As he turned to go, said
Pryor, a boy about 10 motioned for him to wait. The kid ran off to
his tent, then ran back, clutching his orange, which he proudly
presented to the American.
</P>
<P>
   Hefting the orange in his hand, Pryor concluded: ``I'm going to
keep that orange for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
