<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     05-21 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV23-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CURE FOR GAPS IN HARDWOOD FLOOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 23, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My new Canadian maple floorboards are separating. Is there a
cure?
</P>
<P>
   BILL HOYSGAARD, Sherburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no cure; well, there is, except it entails taking up
the boards in winter, and relaying them tight. The reason they
should be laid in winter is that they are at their dryest and
smallest at that time. They should be laid tight so that in summer,
when they take up moisture and expand they will become even
tighter. Then, when in winter they dry out and shrink, the gaps
will not show.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing will fill the gaps because the boards are tongued and
grooved, and the gaps are too shallow for anything to fill
properly. A wood strip filler works only with square-edged (not
tongued-and-grooved) boards.
</P>
<P>
   A way to disguise the gaps is also involved: Sand the floor to
the bare wood, stain the floor and the gaps a medium to dark color,
and revarnish. The gaps will be the same color as the boards, and
simply will not show as much.
</P>
<P>
   Some people recommend filling the gaps with a mix of glue and
sawdust of the maple. That may work for a while, but it hardens,
then breaks up as the boards expand and contract, making the gaps
look worse than ever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My porch ceiling is made of plywood sheets, and I can see the
seams. Can I caulk them and paint? What is good for a new ceiling?
</P>
<P>
   STEVE FUSI, Bedford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Caulk the seams this way, which will work best if there is an
actual gap in the seams: Put a bead of caulk (from a caulking
cartridge) in the seam and press it in with your fingers, scraping
and wiping off excess. This will give a smooth, even surface for
painting. Or, cover the seams with a double-edged molding; it will
make everything neat and paintable.
</P>
<P>
   For a new ceiling, install 1 x 6 cedar boards, tongued and
grooved with V-joints. They do not have to be finished; they will
darken with age, but that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am doing indoor projects that are creating dust and debris,
which I would like to keep out of the rest of the house. Is there a
kind of zipper system that will encase the project while work is
being done?
</P>
<P>
   W. W., Martha's Vineyard, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is a new tent system for sale that allows you to zip
polyethylene around the project to prevent dust and debris from
getting all over the house. It is called Zipwall: 122 Jason St.,
Arlington, MA 02174, 800-718-2255. Two poles cost $139; you provide
the polyethylene.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My bed is on wheels, which I have been pushing back and forth
to make it for 36 years. The wheels have worn deep grooves right in
the wood. Is there a way I can replace that wood, which is regular
hardwood flooring?
</P>
<P>
   CLAIRE O'BRIEN, Newburyport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure there is, but it will take a carpenter with some
gumption and imagination to cut them out and replace them properly.
If the grooves are parallel to the boards, you may have to take
only one or two boards out. If the grooves are crossing the boards;
that is, are at right angles to the boards, you will have to
replace more boards.
</P>
<P>
   But to remove them, cut the tongue of one board by inserting a
chisel between boards and giving the chisel a whack with a hammer.
If you have to replace a short board, then you will have to cut the
board short with a very sharp chisel, and hope that you get a good
square edge. Replace the grooved boards with new hardwood; the new
boards may be narrower than the old, so you may have to cut them to
fit. Use square-edged boards for ease of installation; then finish
them as necessary and you're home free. Well, not free; this work
will not be inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: Make sure the wheels or casters are turning
properly; replace them if necessary. It sounds as if the wheels or
casters were not turning and were scraping into the wood. And, to
prevent further grooving, consider putting one of those desk chair
floor mats made of heavy plastic under the bed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A piece of Tupperware melted on a hot stove burner. How can I
remove it?
</P>
<P>
   LESLIE HAUSMAN, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Heat got the plastic on the burner; heat will remove it. Turn
on the burner and scrape the softened plastic with a wood spatula
or other scraper made of wood. You could use a metal scraper, but
try to avoid metal except to remove residue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to put a nice tool shed in my yard, but the
ready-made ones I found in stores are $2,000. Can I build it myself
for less?
</P>
<P>
   TONY BISCHIA, Norfolk, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Certainly, for maybe half (the materials; you don't count
your labor). Get plans from Craft Patterns (630-587-9650 or
800-747-1429). Build a proper concrete foundation or secure the
shed on concrete piers or pressure-treated posts. You can set the
shed on concrete blocks on the ground, but the shed will move in
winter; your only hope is that the shed will move evenly up and
down, and not get all skewed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
