<SLUG> BC-TV-CLEOPATRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLEOPATRA' PILES ON THE CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
CLEOPATRA 
Starring: Leonor Varela, Timothy Dalton, Billy Zane, Rupert Graves 
Directed by: Franc Roddam 
On: ABC 
Time: Sunday and Monday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The camera loves Timothy Dalton's chin, with its smooth,
cavernous, and surprisingly expressive dimple. In the new
``Cleopatra,'' Dalton maximizes that formidable chin, using it
along with his heavy, inky brow to make his Julius Caesar into a
big, angry, toga-wearing hunk of passion. Like the rest of this
two-part miniseries, he is cheesy in an amusing, high-strung,
overblown sort of way, and the movie suffers after he's stabbed to
death at the end of part one.
</P>
<P>
   But there's plenty of garish melodrama and spectacle to be found
elsewhere in this story of the Queen of Egypt. Filmed some 36 years
after Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton's wonderfully awful
version, ABC's ``Cleopatra'' is a bit of fun network camp that can
only be appreciated when approached with low expectations and a
good sense of humor. From Rupert Graves' poufy 1970s hairdo as
Octavian to the soft-porn lovemaking between Cleopatra and Marc
Antony, it's all silliness in (and out of) robes and breastplates,
with enough amateurish acting and grade-B dialogue to keep the
boredom at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The script is particularly bloated, with the sort of Cecil B.
DeMille-sized lines that absolutely require overacting. Cleopatra
is forever making pushy comments like, ``You are nothing to me,''
and ``I am the Queen of Egypt, and you are in my palace. Now step
aside.'' After Caesar's death, the stronger, wiser Queen falls in
love with Antony, who takes her hand and says, ``Do you feel this
beating heart? That's life you feel.'' As they deliver these
clunkers, the leading actors are always clutching at one another
out of love and hate, and in one typical scene Caesar segues from
choking Cleopatra with his bare hands to hugging her lovingly.
Meanwhile, the supporting actors _ Caesar's generals, in particular
_ yell out their dull military instructions with an almost
high-school-stage-production blankness, as though they had 10
minutes to prepare for their performances. Occasionally, if you
listen carefully, you can hear the script lapse into contemporary
affect, as Caesar looks at Cleopatra's young brother saying, ``And
you are . . .?''
</P>
<P>
   The first night of ``Cleopatra'' revolves around the Queen's
efforts to save Egypt by hooking up with Caesar _ hooking being the
right word, since she consults with a prostitute on how to ensnare
and hold onto him. Once he is killed, she spends the part two
glomming onto Antony, who is younger and, we gather indirectly,
better in bed. Thankfully, the moviemakers have kept all the
political plotting and battle strategies EZ-to-read, allowing the
focus to remain on the gaudier romantic activities and, of course,
the big-budget pageantry. The movie tries hard to be one of those
``lavish'' TV events, and some of the settings are indeed lush and
realistic. But a number of backdrops _ mostly those involving boats
(do actors get nauseous on a see-saw?) _ are quite obviously fake.
</P>
<P>
   As Cleopatra, newcomer Varela is incredibly miscast. She's too
petulant, and in no way believably commanding as she dresses down
powerhouses like Caesar and Antony. Leading the army screaming,
``The future of Egypt depends on it,'' she's like a 10-year-old
girl acting in front of the mirror. Her Cleopatra is all nervous
posing with bold attitude, and never the real thing. While she fits
into the tacky spirit of this production, her pouty French accent
quickly becomes annoying. Billy Zane, Kate Winslet's fiance in
``Titanic,'' mostly plays it straight as Antony, loyal friend to
Caesar, and loyal (and horny) lover to Cleopatra. It's only toward
the end of part two that he's able to loosen up, as he washes away
his despair in a downward spiral of liquor and free women. Alas,
Zane pales next to the gravel-voiced authority of Dalton, who can
chew scenery with the best of them. He could never equal the brio
of Dalton's victorious Caesar, who rises topless from a steaming
pool in slow-motion exclaiming, ``Dictator for life!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
