A6068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-21 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS ARE BARRED FROM RISKY JOBS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ During a recent local investigation of wage and hour
violations in the roofing industry, investigators from the U.S.
Department of Labor were driving from one job site to another when
they spotted what appeared to be a teen-ager working on a saw at a
concrete company.
</P>
<P>
   The boy turned out to be 16. Allowing someone that young to
operate a power-driven saw is a violation of wage and hour laws,
said Shirley Gardner, district director of the Wage and Hour
Division of the U.S. Department of Labor in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It's not uncommon for investigators to stumble upon those kind
of child labor violations, said Gardner. Many employers are unaware
that there are federal restrictions on the number of hours, time of
day and the types of work that teens can do.
</P>
<P>
   Grocery stores are some of the most frequent violators because
they often have teen-age workers operate paper baling machines,
Gardner said. That problem is so common that Gardner will be
investigating a chain that reportedly allows its teen employees to
operate the paper baler and work an excessive number of hours.
</P>
<P>
   Several grocers have been caught before and should know better,
said Gardner, who is working off a tip.
</P>
<P>
   While many small employers aren't as familiar with child labor
violations, the problem isn't limited to them.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Sears Roebuck and Co. agreed to pay a
$325,000 penalty to settle allegations that it violated child labor
laws by letting teens operate electrical machinery or work too many
hours. A Labor Department investigation uncovered 227 children who
were working at Sears in violation of child labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide sting, in which wage and hour offices were asked
to visit one of their local Sears stores, uncovered problems at a
store in Houston. There, a 17-year-old employee was operating a
freight elevator in violation of child labor rules against
operating a hoisting apparatus, Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the investigation, Sears will check its stores to
locate trouble spots and beef up its supervisory training program,
according to Paula Davis, spokeswoman for Sears in Chicago. The
chain employs 11,000 teens under the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PARENTS SHOULD ASK ABOUT TASKS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sears also will give parents of its teen-age employees
information about what to look for in a good employer and the
importance of asking their children what kind of work they're
doing. That way, a parent could spot a potential problem _ a child
being asked, for example, to drive a forklift.
</P>
<P>
   Parents also can visit the work site, Gardner said. Employers
shouldn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   Frank S. Manitzas, an employment lawyer who handles a lot of
wage and hour cases with Akin Gump Strauss Hauer &AMP; Feld in San
Antonio, said he can't remember a single instance in his 38 years
of experience of a parent supplying a tip that led to a violation.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a good idea, he said. If parents hear something that
doesn't sound right _ like a 16-year-old operating a power-driven
meat grinder _ they could talk to the employer, who should
straighten out the situation immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Or a parent could call the Wage and Hour division.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said child labor is the agency's priority. It tries to
respond to such complaints the same day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOURS CAN BE A VIOLATION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a partial list for parents of jobs that no one under 18
is supposed to do:
</P>
<P>
   _ Manufacture explosives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Drive a motor vehicle to make deliveries, such as pizza or
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mine coal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Operate power-driven woodworking machines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Operate a hoisting apparatus like a forklift.
</P>
<P>
   _ Operate metal, punching or shearing machines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Operate paper machines such as box crushers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roofing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Excavation, if the holes are deeper than 4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Another common violation is working teens more hours or later in
the night than federal law allows, Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   During the school term, 14- and 15-year-olds can't work past 7
p.m. Nor can they work more than three hours a day and 18 hours a
week. On a non-school day, they can work eight hours _ but still no
more than 18 in a week.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, 14- and 15-year-olds can work up to 40 hours
a week _ but no more than eight hours a day or after 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Once they turn 16, there is no limit under federal law to the
number of hours they can work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6070 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LOVE-LETTER-BOS     05-21 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LOVE-LETTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LOVE LETTER' DELIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LOVE LETTER 
Directed by: Peter Ho-Sun Chan 
Screenplay by: Maria Maggenti (novel: Cathleen Schine) 
Starring: Kate Capshaw, Blythe Danner, Ellen DeGeneres, Geraldine
McEwan, Julianne Nicholson, Tom Everett Scott, Tom Selleck, Gloria
Stuart 
Running time: 90 minutes 
Rated: R (some sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Love Letter'' is what an astute friend of mine calls a
village comedy. That is, a merry boil of characters snooping into
one another's business as if it's their birthright just because
they've known one another for years. This, of course, gives rise to
a lot of concealment and secrets. Which, of course, means more than
a few juicy misunderstandings. Usually, this kind of film comes
from, and is done to perfection by, countries like Ireland and the
Czech Republic. But ``The Love Letter'' transports the recipe from
Hollywood to New England and turns it into the kind of flavorful
clambake that defines summer escapist entertainment. The kind you
want to escape to, that is, and not from, as is so often and so
lugubriously the case.
</P>
<P>
   It's built around a tried-and-true _ and in this case foolproof
_ plot device, the love letter of the title. We don't learn until
the end who wrote it, and to whom. Until then, all we see is
various people finding it in turn and, human nature being what it
is, never entertaining the slightest flicker of doubt that it was
meant for them. You do have to cut the film some slack and believe
that each one who discovers the letter would refrain from hiding it
away and would leave it lying around for the next person to find.
But indulgence seems a small price to pay for the tasty screenful
of performances that push off from the mischievous missive.
</P>
<P>
   It's centered on Kate Capshaw's single mom, who runs a bookstore
and keeps a tight rein on her life until she finds the letter and
it sets her mind racing. In this case, it races to Tom Everett
Scott's hunky young summer clerk, who has already made it clear
with the odd sheepdog look that he's interested. He doesn't seem to
possess the command of language available to the letter writer, but
she's willing to give him the benefit of the doubt. By doing so,
however, she might ruin her chances with town fireman Tom Selleck's
single dad, an old flame of hers who's still carrying a torch. It
might put a crimp in her friendship with Ellen DeGeneres's shop
assistant and confidante. It might also drain some of the sunshine
from the smile of Julianne Nicholson's adorably spunky clerk, who
admires what she sees as the stand-alone feminism of Capshaw's
Helen.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Stuart (as Helen's grandmother), Blythe Danner (as
Helen's mother) and Geraldine McEwen (as the town eccentric) add
spice and character to the mix, too. DeGeneres has fun with what I
can't help thinking of as the Eve Arden role and Selleck continues
to impress as an actor, following his winning performance in ``In &AMP;
Out'' with his character here, a convincingly feelingful if not
especially articulate man. But mostly ``The Love Letter'' is
Capshaw's show, without seeming too obviously to be so. She
reinforces the impression that she's doing much more interesting
work than she ever did in her ``Indiana Jones'' days.
</P>
<P>
   She's remaking her persona, emerging as one of the most
persuasive proponents of jangly but big-hearted sympathetic women.
Building on her warm, wayward mom in ``How to Make an American
Quilt,'' her tempestuous rancher in ``Locusts,'' and her generous
and unpredictable romantic adventuress in ``The Alarmist,'' she
makes the erosion of her control-freak routine in the face of
romantic yearning seem funny and simpatico. Maria Maggenti's script
keeps things bright and humane and Peter Ho-Sun Chan makes an
auspicious directorial debut, calling forth enough behavioral
nuance and underplaying to keep the film from being capsized by its
sometimes overbearing music. All that and Rockport, too, at its
most picturesquely alluring. ``The Love Letter'' is a winning
romantic confection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
