<HEADER>
A6071 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TREKKIES-BOS &LR;      05-21 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TREKKIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TREKKIES' CHARTS A PHENOMENON'S COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TREKKIES 
A documentary by Roger Nygard 
Running time: 88 minutes 
Rated: PG (nothing objectionable) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making fun of ``Trekkies,'' those get-a-lifers obsessed with all
things ``Star Trek,'' has always been rather like shooting fish in
a barrel. It's just too easy, too obvious a target. Who doesn't
laugh at the thought of people greeting each other with Vulcan
handshakes or in mumbo-jumbo Klingon, or adults driving around with
``Starfleet Academy'' window stickers on their cars?
</P>
<P>
   So it says an awful lot about Roger Nygard's often-hilarious
look at the 30-years-and-counting ``Star Trek'' phenomenon, and its
fans in particular, that ``Trekkies'' never really feels like an
88-minute put-down. It's all pretty funny, to be sure, but Nygard
isn't so much interested in making fun of Trekkies, as he is in
taking a light-hearted look at their particular world, and just how
far some have gone to honor their favorite television show. In
``Trekkies,'' you can laugh with them, even as you're laughing at
them.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps only Elvis fans rival Trekkies in devotion. But whereas
Presley fanatics usually make annual sojourns to Graceland, there's
a ``Star Trek'' convention held somewhere in the world every
weekend of the year. And Trekkies have become such a part of the
cultural lexicon, they are the only fans listed by name in the
Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly an official definition is needed for some of the fans
introduced in the film. There's Dr. Denis Bourguignon a Florida
dentist who not only calls his office ``Starbase Dental,'' and has
it decorated with all kinds of memorabilia, but wears his ``Star
Trek'' uniform while he works. His entire staff _ it's a
requirement for the job _ and family also wear the colors of the
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   There's Gabriel Koerner, a 14-year-old in Bakersfield, Calif.,
who has attended 28 conventions in eight years, and is planning his
own ``Star Trek'' movie, complete with redesigned, hand-sewn
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Barbara Adams, who earned her 15 minutes of fame a
few years back when she wore her Starfleet commander's uniform
every day while in the jury pool at the Whitewater trial. It wasn't
a gag; Adams, a lieutenant commander of her local Trekkies club in
Arkansas, wears her uniform, with badges and phaser, everywhere.
Beam me up, Scotty, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide through Trekkie-dom is Denise Crosby, who played Lt.
Tasha Yar on ``Star Trek: The Next Generation.'' When she joined
the series, she quickly realized she was ``part of something larger
than a new TV series. I was becoming part of a phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Crosby attends the conventions, as do many of the stars from the
original ``Star Trek,'' including DeForrest Kelley (Dr. ``Bones''
McCoy), George Takei (Sulu), James Doohan (Scotty), and Nichelle
Nichols (Lt. Uhuru). Like most folks, the cast members first
thought Trekkies were a little loony, and that the whole thing
would wither and fade. Instead, they've watched it grow each year
with a new generation of fans.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the fans are tech-heads, others are attracted to
``Star Trek,'' because the show, even in the 1960s, promoted
racial, ethnic, and gender diversity. Nichols, one of the first
black actresses featured on television in a non-stereotypic role,
recalls a story told by a black woman who said that when, as a
child, she first saw Lt. Uhuru, she screamed through her house,
``There's a black lady on TV, and she ain't no maid.'' That
youngster grew up to be Whoopi Goldberg, who would herself appear
in ``Star Trek: Generations.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible not to laugh at the people translating the Bible
into Klingon, a fabricated language which sounds a bit like German,
or the man who wishes he could afford to have his ears surgically
altered to resemble Mr. Spock's. But really, what makes their
obsession any more bizarre than people who eat, sleep and drink
golf, meticulously chart every Red Sox statistic, or spend their
weekends perusing yard sales to complete their Fiestaware
collections? It may fall short of common definitions of normalcy,
but as a film, ``Trekkies'' sure beats sleeping outside for days to
see a mediocre movie about some galaxy far, far away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
