<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ELIOT-BOS &LR;      05-21 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ELIOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF `PRAYING INDIANS,' WAR AND ONE MAN'S MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
JOHN ELIOT'S MISSION TO THE INDIANS BEFORE KING PHILIP'S WAR 
By Richard W. Cogley 
Harvard University Press, 331 pp., $45 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In December 1675, the Puritan missionary John Eliot visited the
Indians who had been interned on Deer Island as King Philip's War
inflamed Eastern Massachusetts. As Daniel Gookin, the colony's
superintendent of Indian affairs who accompanied Eliot, reported,
``the island was bleak and cold'' and as for the 500 men, women,
and children they found there, ``their wigwams (were) poor and
thin, their clothes few and thin.''
</P>
<P>
   They were not allies of King Philip, whose Algonquian warriors
had already forced the English to abandon their westernmost
settlements. They were ``praying Indians,'' the native people whom
Eliot had been laboring for some 30 years to convert to Puritan
Christianity and for whom he had established ``praying towns''
north and west of Boston. But the Massachusetts General Court had
ordered them removed from their towns and taken to Deer Island
``for their and our security.''
</P>
<P>
   The oddly cumbersome, 10-word title of Richard Cogley's book
focuses attention on the intersection of Eliot's mission, perhaps
the most positive religious endeavor of the young Puritan colony,
and the devastating conflict that threatened to break the
colonists' fragile hold in New England.
</P>
<P>
   If the mission represented a noble effort to enable the two
races to live together, the war, particularly its impact on Eliot's
converts, ``signaled the failure of the English and the native
peoples to live together peaceably,'' as historian Jill Lepore has
noted in ``The Name of War.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogley, an associate professor of religious studies at Southern
Methodist University, has carefully traced Eliot's missionary
activities, placing them in the context of Colonial politics _ and
Colonial relations with the mother country _ and judiciously
considered their role in causing the war that effectively brought
them to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Cogley also makes it clear that Eliot was not out to destroy
Indian culture, but was actually interested in fostering the
survival of the native Massachusett language _ which he learned,
``in contrast to virtually all other colonists in prewar
Massachusetts'' _ and of many native customs, particularly the use
of herbal remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 14 years from the arrival of the Puritans in Boston
in 1630 to the establishment of the mission in 1644 may seem a
short interval, considering the other and more pressing concerns
that would have required the settlers' attention, Cogley sees ``the
major historical problem'' as not why they waited so long, ``but
why the colony began it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the submission of six Algonquian sachems to the colony's
General Court in March 1644 that ``was the decisive event'' in
establishing the mission. The sachems apparently acted in order to
secure the protection of the English from rival tribes. It was
also, Cogley suggests, a recognition of Puritan righteousness, and
it prompted the General Court to require them to receive religious
instruction. Eliot apparently thought he would be just the first in
a series of rotating missionaries, but such was not to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   By the time war broke out in 1675, 14 praying towns had been
established and contained a population of about 1,200. In the more
established ones closer to Boston, such as Natick, many Indians
farmed along English models but, Cogley notes, ``many features of
the natives' old ways also survived.''
</P>
<P>
   But the native settlements were feeling the pressure of Colonial
expansion, which led to disputes over land, notably between the
Plymouth Colony and the Algonquians, led by Metacom, whom the
colonists knew as King Philip.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot attempted to mediate the quarrel, but _ in the greatest of
ironies _ his ``peace initiative,'' writes Cogley,
``inadvertently'' led to war.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Eliot's peace initiative, commissioners from
Massachusetts and Connecticut were to mediate the dispute between
Metacom and Plymouth. But they imposed humiliating conditions on
Metacom, which required him to submit to Plymouth under threat of
invasion. And the triggering event was the subsequent murder of one
of Eliot's disciples, John Sassamon, who had urged Metacom to
submit to mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Cogley's emphasis on the mission rather than the missionary
leaves Eliot a somewhat shadowy figure. That aside, ``John Eliot's
Mission'' is a major contribution to an understanding of
English-Indian relations during the first half-century of Colonial
settlement _ relations that promised so much but had so tragic an
outcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
