<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GET-REAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GAY TEEN STORY WITH PLEASANT SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
GET REAL 
Written by: Patrick Wilde (based on his play, ``What's Wrong With
Angry?'') 
Directed by: Simon Shore 
Starring: Ben Silverstone, Brad Gorton, Charlotte Brittain, Stacy
A. Hart, Jacquetta May, David Lumsden 
Running time: 110 minutes 
Rated: R (sexual situations, strong language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Carter is gay. That this is not a source of hand-wringing
and teeth-gnashing for the 16-year-old is the first, but not the
only, pleasant surprise in ``Get Real,'' a refreshing new film from
Simon Shore. This movie, which screenwriter Patrick Wilde adapted
from his play, ``What's Wrong with Angry?,'' is less about coming
out than about the hardships of all teenagers trying to find their
place in the world as they stumble toward adulthood. Throughout,
the film feels real and familiar without being hackneyed, and in
this movie year packed with adolescent angst, ``Get Real,'' easily
emerges as the best of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Steven, winningly played by Ben Silverstone, has known since age
11 that he was ``dodgy,'' or gay. He's at peace with his sexuality,
although it is something he has shared only with his best friend,
Linda (Charlotte Brittain). But he longs for meaningful
companionship beyond the clandestine trysts he has with older men
in public bathrooms at a local park.
</P>
<P>
   Like his school chums, Steven spends his energies pacifying his
parents, although his mother (Jacquetta May) isn't as clueless as
he thinks. He doesn't so much lie to them as let them believe what
they want _ such as a love of soccer is the explanation for all
those photos of handsome soccer stars covering his bedroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   But it's just as well, since he's consumed with amorous thoughts
of John Dixon (Brad Gorton). With his sexy smile and curly hair,
John is an Oxford-bound upperclassman, the school hunk described by
Linda as ``sex on legs.'' Indeed, he is quite the dish. John is a
tall, popular, athletic eyeful _ everything Steven isn't. It's
usually John's lunkheaded jock buddies who taunt Steven's sensitive
nature.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Steven is that rare thing in film _ a confident teenager.
When he discovers that he unknowingly cruised John at the park
tearoom _ all conversations occur courtesy of written notes passed
through a bathroom stall gloryhole _ Steven never shies away from
pursuing a relationship with the most popular boy at school. Their
relationship begins haltingly, sweetly as they try negotiating the
unsteady terrain of young love.
</P>
<P>
   But John is still wrestling with his sexuality. He is a prisoner
of his popularity, bound to live up to the expectations of his pals
who demand an accessible god to worship. While Steven wants
everyone to know about his burgeoning relationship, John can't even
bring himself to say hello to Steven at school.
</P>
<P>
   It's to Wilde's credit that the film's outcome is never
completely obvious. Steven and John's relationship seems doomed,
yet perhaps strong enough to survive peer pressure and homophobia.
Most of the cast hits the right notes. Gorton is heartbreaking as
the conflicted John, and Brittain deserves special mention for
sprucing up a role that began as a cruel punchline and has become a
cliched film staple _ the zaftig, unlucky-in-love gal pal of a gay
teen or man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6079 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MATTHEWS-BOS &LR;      05-21 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MATTHEWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVE MATTHEWS LIVES TO TOUR, AND INVITES FRIENDS TO COME ALONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dave Matthews doesn't play games. He doesn't have to, based on
his phenomenal popularity of the past few years. He's done it his
way by touring, touring, touring _ and by sticking to beliefs that
might be termed idealistic. Matthews simply believes that music is
a bridge to other people, not a way to feel superior to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems that a lot of times there's a sense of
competition in this business,'' says Matthews. ``It seems like such
an odd place to have it in music. I don't know if it comes out of
the industry or what, but there's too much talk of who's better or
who's valid or who's contemporary? Who cares? Get a life.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Matthews assembled his summer stadium lineup.
The bill features the Dave Matthews Band, '60s Latin-rockers
Santana, and '90s hip-hop/rockers the Roots. Some of the
competitive individuals Matthews is talking about might find it an
unwieldy bill, but he isn't about to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted a good show, that was our focus,'' Matthews,
31, says recently from a tour stop in Detroit. ``I just think it's
a great lineup. It's a couple different generations of music. And
Santana is a great live band. Most people in the states probably
don't know that they tour all of the time. They're constantly
working. They still sell out huge shows in South America and
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Consistent with Matthews's all-embracing philosophy, he expects
the groups on the bill will jam together. ``With Carlos Santana,
we've played and written together. So I can't think of a reason we
wouldn't play with him,'' says Matthews. ``I'm sure there will be
some sort of exchange with Carlos and the Roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, if there's people around to jump onstage,
we'll bring them on,'' says Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews is lumped in with the ``jam band'' movement, but he,
frankly, takes issue with that phrase. ``The jam band thing is a
funny phenomenon,'' he says. ``I don't think we ever thought of
ourselves as a jam band. It's not anything I ever think about. I
think when a lot of people say `jam band,' they're trying to be
derogatory. It can be sort of a flippant remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it means a `live band,' as opposed to a band that goes
on tour reluctantly to back up an album, then I suppose we
certainly are,'' says Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia-based group includes the South African-born
Matthews, Cajun-spiced violinist Boyd Tinsley, saxophonist Leroi
Moore, bassist Stefan Lessard, and drummer Carter Beauford. They're
touring as a back-to-basics five-piece unit this year, after going
out last summer with guitarist Tim Reynolds (with whom Matthews
just released an album as a side project) and South African penny
whistler Big Voice Jack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll change as the tour goes on,'' Matthews says. ``But it's
nice right now to have the five of us. The dynamic sort of grows.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Phish and the Allman Brothers, the Matthews Band has also
reached a point where it doesn't have to release a new album to
tour. The crowds come based on the reputation of the live shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good about where we're at right now,'' Matthews
says. ``How can I not? We'll just stay on the road and try to keep
it fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   He anticipates that the group may release a live album later
this year (``if we can find a tape we like''), then another studio
disc next year. But the focus, as always, is road work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stop touring when we are in the studio, but aside from
that, we never really stop touring,'' he says. ``So we've been
lucky not to get into this album/tour, album/tour thing. When
people say, `Oh, you're going out to support this new album' when
we do have new albums, I say, `Well, I guess so. We're not in the
studio, so what else are we going to do? I have a job. I should do
it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews, whose hits include the consumer satire ``Too Much,''
the protest song ``Don't Drink the Water'' (about Native American
rights), and the romantic ``Crash Into Me,'' has come up with a
signature fusion of percussive rock, jazz, and roots music. It's
not a fusion commonly associated with stadiums, but Matthews, whose
band played its first-ever stadium date at Foxboro last year, is
getting accustomed to these oversized settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've been getting more comfortable,'' he says. ``If
there's an audience there, I'm not opposed to playing in
(stadiums), as long as we can supply people with a show, and as
long as people don't leave bummed out by it. I don't think that
happened last year and hopefully it won't happen this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of large crowds, Matthews also has signed on to play
the 30th anniversary of the Woodstock Festival in Rome, N.Y.,
during the weekend of July 23-25. ``I love to play; that's the
principal reason we're doing it,'' he says. ``And there's a lot of
great bands there, so it should be a great show. My initial
reaction when asked was `no,' but somehow my `no' went through the
pipeline and came out a `yes' at the other end, so I'll make the
best of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no disrespect to the whole thing at all,'' he says of
Woodstock. ``It was a case of `Do you want to fly in from (a gig
in) Texas to New York to play, then fly back to Texas to play
another show the next night?' Well, no. I'd prefer to fly to
Shangri-La for a day off. I'd like to go sip some tea. But no, off
we go to that beautiful concrete block up near the original place.
But as I say, we'll make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as Matthews is performing somewhere, you get the sense
that he'll be happy. Nor is he out there gouging fans with the high
ticket prices that have become all too common at some superstar
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems only fair to keep ticket prices low,'' says Matthews.
``We used to charge $5, and now we're at $25. It's a long way from
when we charged $5, but I don't think we're going to be charging
$150 any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   So Matthews is not going to play a New Year's Eve gig and charge
$1,500 a ticket like the Eagles?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I think I just may go sit under the stars and not do a
thing on New Year's Eve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
