<HEADER>
A6080 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      05-21 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL D'S NESS SHOWS HIS SENSITIVE SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even a self-respecting punk has to step out sometimes. Look at
Mike Ness, the front man for Social Distortion. He's a punk legend
through his work with the slamming Social D, but he just released
his first solo album, the surprising ``Cheating at Solitaire,''
which busts into styles as diverse as primitive rock, stomping
rockabilly, darkly haunting country, covers of Bob Dylan and Hank
Williams songs, and even some bluegrass and a smokey jazz ballad or
two. All of it high quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show people that I could do more than one thing,''
says Ness. ``Primarily, Social Distortion has been a punk band. We
have evolved and brought in other styles, but it's still one style
to me. So this is to show people, and show myself, that I can do
other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ness will make another Social Distortion album in the future,
but for now, he's with a hand-picked solo group. They play a few
Social D tunes (``I think the crowd would be disappointed if I
didn't''), but they'll feature the new ``Solitaire'' album, which
is one of the best solo discs so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ness's take on it: ``I feel like I brought roots music to punk
with Social Distortion, and I think on this new record that I
brought the attitude and angst of punk to roots.''
</P>
<P>
   He also shows a different emotional side. He's known as a tough
guy, but on the new disc he's a tough guy with a heart. He wraps
his deep, somewhat ravaged voice around a number of original songs
that start with the protagonist on the run or in jail, but end with
regret and tears. ``Look for the one with watery eyes,'' he sings
in the title track. His covers of weepy country hit ``You Win
Again'' (by Hank Williams) and the Johnny Cash-identified ``Long
Black Veil'' are stunning.
</P>
<P>
   Ness once did a Cash song with Social Distortion, namely ``Ring
of Fire,'' but ``it had to be fast in order for us to pull it off.
I wanted to get away from those restrictions on this new record.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, though. Most of the record still rocks. Of
particular interest is his rockin' cover of Dylan's ``Don't Think
Twice,'' which has been earning airplay. ``I'm a big Dylan fan.
He's right up there with the Rolling Stones for me,'' says Ness.
</P>
<P>
   The Lynn, Mass. native grew up in Orange County, Calif. His dad
was into country and bluegrass, his mom into folk, and his uncles
were ``like greaser guys who turned me on to Rolling Stones records
. . . I heard all of that before I ever heard the Sex Pistols.''
</P>
<P>
   Ness pulled in some illustrious guests on his new disc _ Bruce
Springsteen and Brian Setzer. Springsteen sings backup and plays
some lead guitar on the gritty ``Misery Loves Company.'' Guitarist
Setzer embellishes ``Crime Don't Pay.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Springsteen: ``I met Bruce a couple of times in LA. He
told me he was a huge fan and that blew me away. I think he said in
a Rolling Stone magazine article that (Social Distortion's)
`Somewhere Between Heaven and Hell' was the best record of that
year. . . So when I asked him to join this solo project, he jumped
aboard with nothing but enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Setzer: ``I heard he liked my vibe and wanted to meet
me,'' says Ness. ``And then he came in, and we smoked a cigar, and
went out and played. It was like, `Wow, what an inspiring session
that was!' This was a rewarding record to make.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fairbairn remembered: Bruce Fairbairn, who produced Aerosmith's
top-selling comeback albums ``Pump'' and ``Get a Grip,'' as well as
records for Bon Jovi, Van Halen, and AC/DC, was found dead Monday
in his Vancouver home. He was 49. He apparently died in his sleep,
but no official reason has been given.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an incredible guy,'' says Tim Collins, who managed
Aerosmith during the two albums that Fairbairn produced. ``He was
always cool, calm, collected. . . . And he danced really well
between the record company's desire for a hit, and the artistic
integrity of the creators.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairbairn made a lot of money during his career, Collins adds,
but ``he used to drive an old VW bus.'' His contract also
stipulated the need for free time at night ``so he could coach his
kids' soccer team. His family was his priority,'' added Collins.
Fairbairn had three sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music industry has lost a great one,'' says Collins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ministry has a new album, ``Dark Side of the Spoon,'' due June
8, followed by a US tour in August. . . . Paul McCartney and Pink
Floyd guitarist David Gilmour jammed on a bunch of oldies (by Carl
Perkins and Gene Vincent, among others) for an album McCartney has
decided to release in July. It will also have two new McCartney
songs. . . . Richard Thompson releases a new CD, ``Mock tudor,''
Aug. 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
