<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL TV: NEW SHOWS BY THE SAME NAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great Fred Allen once said that ``Imitation is the sincerest
form of television.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall, however, TV's most talented writer-producers won't
have to imitate anyone but themselves, because they will control a
huge and possibly unprecedented chunk of the prime-time schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a dozen of the new shows unveiled to advertisers this
week are the creations of producers who already have shows on the
air. In other words, in a medium already starved for originality, a
handful of top producers will control nearly 20 hours of prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   They will wield that power because network programmers are
terrified of losing even more audience share by gambling on
unproven talent, especially with both production costs and the
failure rate of new shows higher than ever. When coupled with the
array of newsmagazines that gobble up the rest of prime time, this
concentration of TV entertainment power in the hands of a small
fraternity of producers makes it exceptionally difficult for a new
voice to break through on series television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Network executives have taken the programming Hippocratic
oath: First, do no harm,'' remarked John Rash, a senior vice
president at Campbell Mithun Esty of Minneapolis, which buys TV
time for advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When viewers were more loyal to network television, trying new
producers and writers was an easier task,'' added Rash, who
attended the networks' ``upfront'' presentation of the fall lineup
in New York this week. ``This year, the decisions generally have
been safe, with nothing that is going to transcend the medium and
go into the general consciousness in the way that `ER' has, or land
on the cover of Time magazine the way `Ally McBeal' did.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, a breakthrough show is exactly what television
needs at this moment, according to Robert J. Thompson, director of
Syracuse University's Center for the Study of Popular Television.
``People keep complaining that we're seeing the same old stuff, and
network television is desperately in need of a new Great Idea,''
said Thompson. ``We're not going to get the next Great Idea by
giving contracts to the same people.''
</P>
<P>
   But in television, the bottom line is the bottom line. Whatever
the creative consequences, networks want to send reassuring signals
of stability to advertisers, who will be more apt to pony up big
money if brand names like John Wells of ``ER,'' Dick Wolf of ``Law
and Order,'' or Chris Carter of ``The X-Files'' are behind a new
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the shows are going to be of that kind of quality, that
would absolutely make it a little easier for advertisers to spend
their money,'' said Tracey Riener, an associate media director at
Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopoulos, a Boston advertising agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's stability in the sense that the networks will probably
stick with their programs longer than they would with an unproven
producer,'' said Riener. ``There's not a lot of new here; the
impression during the upfront was status quo. But having proven
winners is better than having 20 new shows where you can't tell the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a track record has always been important in
television. Also, it cannot be denied that many of the established
voices who are creating the new shows _ Wells, Wolf, Carter, David
E. Kelley of ``The Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' Aaron Sorkin of
``Sports Night'' _ have more than justified network confidence in
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is these guys have produced some of the finest
moments in the history of television,'' said Thompson. ``We're
definitely seeing a period where going for the auteur is the order
of the day. Kelley and (Steven) Bochco are the equivalent of
Hitchcock and John Ford in their time. Seeing what David Kelley has
been able to churn out in a brief career, it would be silly not to
give him a chance to see what else he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But who are the next Wolfs and Kelleys and Bochcos?'' he
asked. ``That is what the networks are perhaps not so successful
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some analysts question whether, given that the top
producers often write many of the scripts for their shows, they
will simply be spread too thin. That effect was seen on ``Frasier''
this year as its writer-producers were distracted by their efforts
on the disastrous ``Encore! Encore!'' In addition, there is the
issue of whether there will be enough diverse styles on television,
since the producers in question are all white males, or whether
they will become formulaic under the pressure of having to produce
so much.
</P>
<P>
   To Steven Stark, author of ``Glued to the Set,'' the reliance on
the same established producers to fill up the TV schedule
illustrates the supply-and-demand quandary created by the explosion
of new broadcast networks and cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened is the talent pool has been incredibly diluted
at a time when they have to create three times as many shows,''
said Stark. ``So they're trying to take the creative people they
know are good, and overtax them. What you end up with is a diluted
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the dominant writer-producers are gambling that
they can deliver another winner. John Wells, of NBC's ``ER,'' will
add two more dramas to the Peacock Network: a drama set inside the
White House and titled ``The West Wing,'' which will be written by
Aaron Sorkin (who scripted ``The American President'' before
creating ``Sports Night''), and ``Third Watch,'' a drama about New
York cops, paramedics, and firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley will launch the detective drama ``Snoops'' on ABC and a
half-hour version of ``Ally McBeal'' on Fox while retaining
involvement in the hourlong version of ``Ally,'' CBS's ``Chicago
Hope,'' and ABC's ``The Practice. Chris Carter, creator of ``The
X-Files,'' will oversee his new creation, ``Harsh Realm,'' on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf of NBC's ``Law and Order'' will create a spinoff called
``Special Victims Unit,'' about crimes against women and children.
Wolf is also slated to launch ``D.C.,'' a timely drama about
Washington interns, on the WB network in midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Levitan, creator and executive producer of NBC's ``Just
Shoot Me,'' will launch another show on the network, ``Stark Raving
Mad,'' about a horror novelist and his harried editor. Kevin
Williamson, who gave the world ``Dawson's Creek'' on the WB
network, will try his hand on ABC with ``Wasteland,'' a drama about
six friends in their 20s living in New York. Joss Whedon, the
writer-producer behind ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' on the WB, will
oversee a new spinoff on the network titled ``Angel.'' Bochco of
ABC's ``NYPD Blue'' is slated to launch an urban medical drama
called ``City of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Also journeying back to the future will be Ed Zwick and Marshall
Herskovitz, the team behind ``thirtysomething'' and ``My So-Called
Life,'' will launch ``Once and Again'' on ABC, a drama about
divorced parents reentering the dating world.
</P>
</TEXT>
