   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories and photos on the
continuing crisis over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Talks over Kosovo are ended with Strobe
Talbott, the deputy secretary of state, saying he'll return next
week.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The Yugoslav foreign minister
insists that the United Nations, not NATO, be the key player in
settlement. He says: ``Read my lips. It's not about NATO, it's
about U.N.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Tirana, Albania) _ The Kosovo rebel group, the
KLA, which says that Russians are fighting in Kosovo, announces
that it has killed one and shows his body, according to Russian
television. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Dateline to kum) _ Military developments on
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SMALLPOX (United Nations) _ The World Health Organization will
postpone until 2002 destruction of the last stocks of the smallpox
virus in laboratories. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-IMMIG (Berlin) _ The upper house of Germany's parliament
approves a new nationality law making it easier for immigrants to
become German citizens. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-TERROR (Rome) _ Folo on the murder Thursday of a senior
government adviser by a leftist terrorist group. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ The battle over gun control shifts
to the House. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VACATION (Washington) _ A White House memo the politics
of vacation planning. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-IMPACT (Orange, N.J.) _ With lottery machines as
prevalent as cash registers in 38 states and $35 billion bet on
them each year, the most prevalent purveyor of betting games in
America is no longer the corner bookmaker. Instead, it is state
governments _ the same entities that for years outlawed gambling.
The impact that state lotteries are having on communities around
the country has been a major focus of the National Gambling Impact
Study Commission, which is examining the social and economic
consequences of gambling. It is in communities like Orange where
the lottery is a dominant force and many poor and modest wage
earners are devoted to an endless search for winning numbers. By
Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   A Special Report, 3900 words, plus an abridged version of about
2000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Conyers, Ga.) _ Folo on Thursday's school
shooting in an Atlanta suburb which left six students injured. By
David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly Religion Column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Developments on the trial of police
officers charged with brutalizing Abner Louima, a Hatian immigrant,
while he was in custody. By Joseph P. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM-ITALIA (Rome) _ The tender deadline is today for
Olivetti's hostile $65 billion bid for Telecom Italia. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   PROTEST-SHIP (Vladivostok, Russia) _ A freighter owned by a
union of sailors, truckers, longshoremen and others is making an
round-the-world voyage to fight the registration of ships under
``flags of convenience'' _ countries other than the place of
ownership. Of the world's 85,500 self-propelled cargo vessels of
100 gross tons or greater, some 16,000 are registered in the 27
countries that the union lists as flags of convenience. The union
says such vessels have poor safety records, frequently do not pay
employees, and sometimes abandon sailors in distant ports when
aging ships get too expensive to run. By Russell Working. (1525
words)
</P>
<P>
   VITAMIN-ROCHE (Basle, Switzerland) _ Looking at the impact of
the vitamin price-fixing settlement on Roche.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 11 a.m., stocks were slightly lower. The
Dow was down 14 points, the S&AMP;P 500 down 4 points, the Nasdaq
composite down 20 points. Euoprean stocks were little changed; in
Asia, the Nikkei rose 0.6 percent, while the Hang Seng fell 0.8
percent At midday, the 30-year Treasury bond is little changed,
yieldign 5.81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-AOL (Washington) _ AOL chief Steve Case is deposed in
the Microsoft antitrust trial. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Japan's giant banks report record losses
for the latest fiscal year. The poor performance stems largely from
the banks' efforts to clean their books by writing off bad loans,
but the losses were still larger than expected as regulators force
banks to follow stricter rules for evaluating bad loans and to
create a deeper cushion of reserves. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis's ``Abroad at Home.''
</P>
