<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MACEDONIA-PRESURES (Skopkje, Macedonia) _ Warfare in nearby
Kosovo, a potential ethnic time bomb at home and a plummeting
economy have combined to shake the very foundation of this tiny
backwater _ the only former Yugoslavian republic to break away
without bloodshed. By Toula Vlahou. 875 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WEST-BANK (Shilo Settlement, West Bank) _ In the days
after Ehud Barak's election victory, the future for Jewish settlers
on the West Bank is more uncertain than ever. By Charles M.
Sennott. 995 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUNSHOWS-LOOPHOLES (Washington) _ Gun-control advocates and
federal agents have long complained that gun shows are traveling
arms bazaars where cash-and-carry is the rule, and a loophole in
federal law makes it easy for anyone to buy a weapon. By Louise D.
Palmer. 970 words.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-HIGH-COURT (Boston) _ Paul Cellucci will get to choose four
members of the Supreme Judicial Court over the next two years, now
one of the most respected in the nation. By Tina Cassidy. 870
