<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6102 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SENATE-$ADV23     05-21 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON CAN LOOK TO WOMEN IN NEW YORK TO BOOST SENATE BID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 23)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, accelerating
preparations for a likely Senate race in New York in 2000, is
counting on broad support from women voters to help her win the
seat held by retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is showcasing ties with prominent women in New York on
Monday during her ninth visit to the state since Jan. 1 as she lays
the groundwork for what is widely expected to be her announcement
in mid-June that she is forming an exploratory committee to raise
funds for her Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to reach a final decision during a Memorial
Day vacation with President Clinton and the couple's daughter
Chelsea at White Oak Plantation in Yulee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of an exploratory committee would enable the first
lady to raise funds to finance her campaign through private
contributions. Republicans have criticized her for traveling to New
York on Air Force planes at taxpayers' expense.
</P>
<P>
   One former senior White House adviser who remains close to
Clinton said she is ``nudging toward running. She's much closer
than I ever thought possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans two additional trips to the state in early June
and a politically-valuable trip to Israel later in the month.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is expected to seek the
Republican nomination for the Senate seat. New York Gov. George
Pataki has scheduled an announcement on Monday about his own
political future, sparking speculation that he also might seek the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   During her visit Monday, Clinton is expected to raise more than
$1 million at two fund raising events. She will appear at a $1,000
per person fund raiser for Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., the veteran
six-term House member who has vowed to seek the same Senate seat if
Clinton declines to run.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also will appear at an exclusive $10,000 per person
fundraiser at a private residence in Manhattan. The $500,000
expected to be raised there will go to the Democratic Senate
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also plans to take part in a book party honoring Matilda
Cuomo and her new book, ``The Person Who Changed My Life.'' Cuomo,
wife of former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, asked Clinton to write
the forward for the book.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also is taking part in an awards gala at Lincoln
Center where the Americans for the Arts will honor her and two
prominent patrons of the arts _ Brooke Astor and Agnes Gund.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's multiple appearances with prominent women in New York
underscores her ongoing effort to highlight her commitment to
issues of concern to women voters, including child care for working
women, the role of women in society and strengthening public
education.
</P>
<P>
   William Schneider, a public opinion specialist at the American
Enterprise Institute in Washington, D.C., says Clinton is already
reaping a windfall from women voters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women who are Democrats and independents really have a reason
to vote for her,'' says Schneider. ``They want to make a statement
about how she has been wronged and support her effort to strike out
on her own.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider added: ``Supporting her sticks a thumb in the eye of
the Republican Congress, as if they're saying, `Take that, you
middle-aged, conservative old white men.'''
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show sizable support for the first lady in
a hypothetical Senate race against Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinnipiac College Poll completed April 20 shows Clinton
leading Giuliani among women by 17 percentage points _ 54 to 37
percent _ a margin that more than accounts for her eight percentage
point lead over Giuliani among all voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women always vote a little more for Democrats, but in
Hillary's case, it's not just the gap, it's a chasm,'' says Maurice
Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Mandel, director of the Eagleton Institute of Politics at
Rutgers University in New Jersey, predicts that Clinton will
continue to benefit from an edge among women voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent anyone can predict anything in politics and
elections this far ahead, I'd have to say that if Hillary Clinton
runs for the Senate from New York, she will benefit from the gender
gap.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women voters helped propel Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., to
victory last fall over incumbent Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.
Schumer won the votes of 59 percent of the women compared to
D'Amato's 40 percent share, more than accounting for the Democrat's
55 percent to 45 percent victory over D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Women exceed men in New York not just in voting registration,
but also in actually turning out to vote. According to a U.S.
Census Bureau survey taken after the 1996 election, 52.3 percent of
those who voted in 1996 were women.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Malcolm, president of Emily's List which raises money and
bankrolls pro-abortion women running as Democrats, says her network
will support Clinton in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm says a Clinton-Giuliani race would be decided in the
suburbs where independent minded so-called ``soccer Moms'' are
often the deciding factor in close races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary will do better upstate than Democrats usually do, and
Giuliani will do better in (New York City) than Republicans usually
do,'' Malcolm said. ``So the battle will be in suburbia, among
suburban women.''
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine DeAngelo, president of the New York State Federation
of Republican Women, said Clinton may be underestimating the
pitfalls of a New York candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think that just because she's a woman, she's got all the
woman in New York state behind her,'' DeAngelo said. ``I think
she'll be in for a big fight,''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of the National Republican
Senatorial Committee, echoed the sentiment: ``The best day
(Clinton) has will be the day before she announces.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to formation of the exploratory committee, Clinton
plans to continue her efforts to forge close ties with the main
Democratic constituencies that she would rely upon in a Senate
race. The first lady plans a trip to Israel in June to become the
first member of the first family to meet in Israel with
newly-elected Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been working for months to ease the concerns of some
Jewish Americans who expressed worry over her remarks at a meeting
in Davos, Switzerland, last year when she voiced support for an
independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Democrat with ties to the party organization said
Clinton has spent hours on the telephone with Democratic county
chairman and other local Democrats and has contacted more than 100
prominent Democrats. Those names were suggested to her by Moynihan,
Democratic state party leader Judith Hope and Harold Ickes, the
former White House deputy chief of staff heading up the exploratory
phase of her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Also working behind the scenes is Susan Thomases, a friend of
Clinton's since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.1com) (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at
202-298-6920 and via E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
