<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEDILLO-CALIF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEDILLO TOUTS TRADE RELATIONS IN CALIFORNIA VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo earned a
doctorate in economics at Yale, where he argued that Mexico's
staggering national debt was the result of government
irresponsibility. A former banker and financial bureaucrat, the
bespectacled Zedillo appears most at ease citing trade statistics
and unemployment figures.
</P>
<P>
   Economics is his life.
</P>
<P>
   So while journalists and demonstrators wanted to ask Zedillo
about immigration policy during his visit to California this week,
the Mexican president and California Gov. Gray Davis have focused
most of their attention on strengthening their trade relationship
after eight years of strained relations under former Gov. Pete
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade between California and Mexico has increased 17 percent
each year, even when our political leaders were not talking to each
other,'' Zedillo told business and political leaders Wednesday in
Los Angeles. ``Think what would have happened if we had been on
speaking terms. Seventeen percent is very little _ we can do much
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo and Davis, a Democrat, announced several trade-related
ventures, including the opening of a new Mattel Inc. toy factory in
Monterrey, Mexico. The California company plans to invest $30
million in the new factory, which is scheduled to open in November.
It will employ 2,500 Mexicans, displacing the company's current
factory in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also announced the state would set up 15 California-based
Mexican Trade Centers at community colleges around the state. The
trade centers will offer intensive 5-day seminars on how to do
business in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   These gestures were small. Like the announcement two months ago
that the Mexican state telephone company would open a field office
in San Diego, the Mattel factory opening was in the works well
before Davis was inaugurated in January.
</P>
<P>
   But both Zedillo and Davis said the real focus should be on the
potential markets. California sells about $13.3 billion a year in
electronics and computers to Mexico every year.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo has been continually assuring California audiences that
he is making economic and social reforms in Mexico, where 100
million people still struggle with poverty and produce a relatively
small $335 billion in goods and services, compared to California's
$1 trillion economy with 33 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future,'' Davis told Spanish-language TV, ``California
and Mexico will be one nation state, just like the mayors of
Tijuana and San Diego consider that region to be one area.''
</P>
<P>
   While Zedillo said he looks at the lost opportunities during the
Wilson administration, not what got accomplished, others saw trade
between California and Mexico double under the Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the rhetoric was, whatever the political situation,
the true reality is that trade relations were never better under
Governor Wilson,'' said Rosario Marin, a former Wilson aide.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo made his first trip to the heart of California's
Hispanic community Wednesday, but he stayed mostly out of reach of
Hispanic immigrants and Mexican workers who live here. The trip was
more about the friendship between Zedillo, Davis and Hispanic
leaders in California who have for years been ignored by the
Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, the son of a construction foreman and movie house candy
vendor, still owns a home just five blocks from the California
border, where he grew up attending public schools and selling cans
to help his family.
</P>
<P>
   A noted movie buff, Zedillo spoke of feeling immense pride when
director James Cameron opened the movie ``Titanic'' in Mexico City
a week after the New York premiere, and thanked the Mexican people
for their help on the picture. The epic movie was filmed in Baja,
and many of the sets were built by Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo said he wanted to see more partnerships like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economics is very important,'' Zedillo said, ``but it's not
everything. The other good reason I am here is because I want
Californians and Mexicans to communicate with each other, to
understand each other in friendly ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
