<P>
   &UR; MOST SERB MILITARY STILL UNDAMAGED, NATO NOW ADMITS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By STEPHEN CASTLE, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ More than two-thirds of Serbia's tanks and heavy
artillery inside Kosovo are still intact, NATO admitted Wednesday,
raising the prospect of many weeks of further bombardment before
the military capacity of Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic is
rendered ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Despite greater success in the last two weeks of the air
campaign and reports of discipline beginning to disintegrate, NATO
concedes that the Serbs still have a formidable fighting force left
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's military spokesman, General Walter Jertz, said Wednesday
that the alliance had ``struck'' _ rather than destroyed _ 31
percent of Serbia's heavy forces, a nuance which means there is no
evidence of destruction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (425 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-NATO-ADMITS-FAILURE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVAR LIBERATION ARMY FEARS NATO BETRAYAL &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By KIM SENGUPTA, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TIRANA _ NATO's reluctance to send in ground forces against the
Serbs is creating a sense of foreboding among the Kosovar
Liberation Army, who fear they will be let down.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters in the organization report a mood of creeping pessimism
and worries that the West's desire to avoid a land war may lead to
a compromise peace deal falling far short of an independent Kosovo,
or even a NATO protectorate. Instead it may end up by leaving
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic with powers to interfere... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (675 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-KLA-JUDAS-KISS?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `TRAGIC FATE' NOW AWAITS MONTENEGRO &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By STEVE CRAWSHAW, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic Thursday tightened the
noose on Montenegro, the smaller Yugoslav republic which has
repeatedly been at odds with Belgrade. The republic is slipping
constantly closer towards war.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army set up checkpoints at all Montenegro's main
border crossings. ``It's getting worse. They want to throttle us,''
one government official said... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (550 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-NOOSE-AROUND-MONTENEGRO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNICEF SETS UP `CHILD-FRIENDLY SPACES' IN ALBANIAN CAMPS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By KIM SENGUPTA, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TIRANA _ She was a beautiful little girl, just 18 months old,
who had been loved. She was found alone and crying on the steps of
a mosque in Kukes. The only words she said were ``mother, truck,
KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   The little girl, who was given the name Atdhetare, was just one
of several hundred children who have arrived at Albania and
Macedonia without any adults after being ``cleansed'' from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   They are being looked after by adoptive families with the mostly
forlorn hope of ever being reunited with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in recognition of the need to care and counsel these
lost boys and girls as well as 160,000 other children in refugee
camps, the U.N. children's body UNICEF and the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees signed an agreement in Tirana to
establish ``Child-Friendly Spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   The centers in 20 camps in Albania will provide education,
sports and other aspects of childhood which have been missing. The
children also receive psychological counselling about their
traumatic experiences... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (600 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WAR-KIDS-`SAFE-HAVENS'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATO'S MOST POTENT ENEMY LIVES IN WASHINGTON, NOT BELGRADE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANNE MCELVOY, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The closing lines of Robert Southey's poem, ``The Battle of
Blenheim,'' spring to mind, In them, a small boy quizzes his
grandfather over the fate of the doomed 600 cavalrymen: ``What good
came of it at last?'' quoth little Peterkin, ``Ah, that I cannot
tell,'' said he, ``But t'was a famous victory.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, we are watching NATO alliance being destroyed by its
creators, the Americans... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: Note 350-word OPTIONAL TRIM; Total uncut,
1,200) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-SPINELESS-CLINTON-NATO-550&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GHOSTS OF FAILURES PAST SPOOK AMERICAN WARMONGERS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANDREW MARSHALL &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like police officers moving spectators away from a
nasty accident, spin-doctors and officials in both Britain and the
U.S. were shooing reporters away from the idea of a transatlantic
split Monday _ ``Nothing to see here; move along.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ringing endorsements of NATO solidarity Monday from
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Foreign Minister Robin Cook
cannot hide a growing and disturbing fact: Washington and London
risk putting themselves on a collision course over the question of
sending infantry into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just still-raw memories of Vietnam or political
cowardice that militates against the aggressive use of ground
forces to win the war.
</P>
<P>
   Militarily, the ghost of Bosnia still stalks the corridors in
Washington and London... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: Note THREE OPTIONAL TRIMS, totaling 325 words.
Total uncut version is 1,200) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WAR-GHOSTS-HAUNT-US-475&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
