<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOOSE-AROUND-MONTENEGRO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRAGIC FATE' NOW AWAITS MONTENEGRO  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This urgent 550-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By STEVE CRAWSHAW  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic Thursday tightened the
noose on Montenegro, the smaller Yugoslav republic which has
repeatedly been at odds with Belgrade. The republic is slipping
constantly closer towards war.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army set up checkpoints at all Montenegro's main
border crossings. ``It's getting worse. They want to throttle us,''
one government official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin president, Milo Djukanovic, warned that there
should be no ``dual power.'' But such dual power _ where government
forces and the army argue it out between themselves _ is exactly
what Montenegro now faces.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic accused ``top Yugoslav army officers'' in the
republic of wanting to serve ``the dictatorship in Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in Montenegro fear that a coup is just around the corner _
a coup which would almost certainly be followed by civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrin television showed army bunkers with newly set up
machine-gun positions at checkpoints along the coastal road towards
the border with Croatia. The deputy prime minister, Dragisa Burzan,
travelled to the coastal town of Herceg Novi to try to negotiate
the removal of the army roadblocks, but without apparent success.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials also said that tanks and heavy artillery
are now positioned around the town of Cetinje. Hundreds of soldiers
have moved in recent days into the town, the old Montenegrin royal
capital and a heartland of Montenegrin nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Cetinje has been virtually an army-free zone,
apparently because the troops were still wary of provoking head-on
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, the Cetinjans are determined not to be cowed. What was
officially described as a ``fairly tense situation'' arose when
Yugoslav soldiers demanded rooms in a hotel in the town, only to be
told that none were available.
</P>
<P>
   Miodrag Vukovic, a presidential adviser, warned of the ``tragic
fate'' now facing Montenegro, especially in view of the ``new media
and political campaign'' launched by Serbia against Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   From the Montenegrin point of view, the pattern is nightmarishly
clear. On the one hand, their independent standpoint cannot be
tolerated by Belgrade. On the other hand, further conflict in
Montenegro might help to distract Serbs from rebelling against
their own government.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Independent this month, President
Djukanovic made it clear that Montenegro would certainly seek to
break away from Serbia if, as seems increasingly likely, Milosevic
remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   In those circumstances, he said, a single Yugoslav federation
was ``not feasible.'' Djukanovic acknowledged that such a breakaway
would almost certainly be accompanied by civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro was an independent kingdom before union with Serbia
in 1918.
</P>
<P>
   The army this week turned back an Italian truck of humanitarian
aid, after confiscating the aid itself. Two truckloads of French
medical and food aid were confiscated over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The current tensions may recede again in the next few days, for
the moment at least. But none of the underlying difficulties seem
likely to be solved.
</P>
<P>
   Control over Montenegro's borders has in recent weeks been
ambivalent, at best. The Montenegrin government seeks to allow
foreigners into the country. But the army does not recognize the
government's authority to issue entry papers.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin government has tried hard to remain uninvolved
in the war with NATO. For Belgrade, this merely compounds the
Montenegrins' offense. The Montenegrins are now accused of
``treachery.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 550-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
