<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEA-MARIJUANA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEA AGENT ADMITS INVOLVEMENT WITH WIFE OF SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sex, lies and tape recordings.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Drug Enforcement Administration has kept John
Dalton in federal prison for the past 2 1/2 years, the Mendocino
County machinist says.
</P>
<P>
   Blaming a federal agent's seduction of his wife for his plight,
Dalton is arguing in U.S. District Court in San Francisco that the
government's conduct is so outrageous that the charges against him
should be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, 44, was indicted in October 1996 for involvement in a
continuing criminal conspiracy _ masterminding an industrial-scale
marijuana operation in Mendocino County in Northern California _
plus seven counts of growing marijuana for sale and one of witness
tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, who has no criminal record, faces a sentence of up to
life in prison if convicted on the conspiracy count and five years
to life on some of the marijuana counts. He is being held without
bail.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and Dalton's lawyer, J. Tony Serra, will submit
legal arguments to U.S. District Judge Susan Illston before she
rules on the motion to dismiss the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton contends the charges against him should be dismissed
because DEA agent Mark Nelson, 37, set him up by first threatening,
then seducing Dalton's then-wife Victoria Horstman, 40, convincing
her that she was a ``special agent,'' and persuading her to install
a tape recorder in the Dalton bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Horstman testified she supplied the DEA with pillow-talk tape
recordings containing allegedly incriminating admissions about the
marijuana business.
</P>
<P>
   Serra, a redoubtable courtroom battler for underdogs, hammered
Nelson and Horstman for nearly eight hours this week with questions
aimed at demonstrating they had an illicit sexual relationship
which, in the end, victimized Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson and Horstman admitted snuggling and French kissing _ once
_ but said their physical relationship went no further.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, on the witness stand, refused to answer several
questions, invoking his constitutional right against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, a DEA agent for 13 years, began enlisting Horstman _ an
admitted alcoholic _ as an informant in 1992. During his agency's
investigation of Dalton, Nelson gave Horstman a special agent
number and supplied her with $4,800 in moving and other expenses,
plus tape recording equipment for her bedroom and purse.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1994, Nelson blindfolded Horstman and drove her to
a DEA ``safe house'' near Ukiah to fingerprint her, without
informing his supervisors, in what he admitted was a violation of
agency policy.
</P>
<P>
   Before the fingerprinting, the agent and Horstman testified,
they engaged in some heavy petting, which culminated with a tongue
kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said that he went too far in cultivating Horstman as an
informant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stupid,'' he said. But ``I thought it was important
enough to establish contact with her. That's why I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   He blamed himself for initiating the physical contact, which
occurred when his wife was pregnant with their second child.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson denied manipulating Horstman for his own sexual and
career purposes by threatening to charge her with laundering
Dalton's drug money through the credit union where she worked. But
Horstman testified the laundering charge was mentioned. And her
son, Joshua Corrigan, 20, of Oakdale, testified his mother said she
was cooperating with the DEA out of fear of going to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Horstman admitted that Nelson drove her to an attorney's office
to file for divorce from Dalton, but said the divorce was her own
idea _ an assertion contradicted by her son and her former best
friend, Chohni Baird. Baird testified she believed only the DEA's
interference prevented Horstman's reconciliation with Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   Horstman, weeping frequently and complaining that the years of
her marriage to Dalton were so traumatic that she couldn't recall
what happened, said she willingly cooperated with the DEA, in large
part because she wanted to escape a physically abusive
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Horstman said that it was she, not Nelson, who was most
responsible for the touching and kissing in the DEA's safe house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in desperate need of a human touch. I initiated it. And
the minute we did it, I knew it was wrong. I froze. I never should
have called (Nelson) in the first place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was ``my knight in shining armor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Horstman denied on the witness stand that she was
coerced, manipulated by, fearful of or seduced by Nelson, she
nevertheless wrote two letters to Nelson's DEA supervisors stating
just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   On the stand this week, Horstman said she typed the letters only
because her husband threatened to harm her if she didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was John. That wasn't me,'' she said under questioning by
Serra. ``He interrogated and beat me, because he wanted a
scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Horstman later recanted the accusations made in her letters to
the DEA.
</P>
<P>
   Horstman denied inflicting injuries on herself to support her
charges of spousal abuse and said that a Ukiah police report which
indicated that she had struck Dalton in the face with a baseball
bat was wrong in fact.
</P>
</TEXT>
