<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Saturday, May 22.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOOK (Undated) _ How do books influence public
policy, or more specifically, how do some books come to be read by
policy makers while others are not? Consider the case of President
Clinton and Robert D. Kaplan's ``Balkan Ghosts,'' a book that the
writers Richard Reeves and Elizabeth Drew say profoundly shaped the
President's thinking on the limitations of intervention in a part
of the world where ethnic feuds have deep roots. By Michael T.
Kaufman. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   ORTHODOX-RABBI (Undated) _ The nasty battle over the legacy of
Rabbi Joseph Dov Soloveitchik. By Samuel G. Freedman. (1525 words)
</P>
<P>
   BREASTS (Undated) _ One way of looking at breasts _ other than
head on, from underneath or in profile _ is to see them as public
property. They never fully belong to the women who live with them.
They arrive as uninvited buds and slowly blossom into a social
concern. And now two new breast books have arrived. As if the
breast has not had its share of shelf space, two new breast books
have arrived. ``Master Breasts'' presents breast photographs with
text by Francine Prose, Karen Finley, Dario Fo and Charles Simic.
``At the Breast'' by Linda Blum, a sociologist, is about the
history and ideology of American breast-feeding. By Sarah Boxer.
(750 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
