<HEADER>
A6228 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     05-21 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PANICKED RUSH TO `DO SOMETHING'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``They've got to do SOMETHING.''
</P>
<P>
   Boiled down to its purest essence, that is the mantra inspiring
the frenzy of on-again, off-again, on-again gun legislation gushing
out of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Calls from constituents to congressional offices are flooding
switchboards and swamping support staff. Lawmakers can hardly tell
sic 'em from come here, they've been pulled in so many different
directions in the wake of the Littleton, Colo., disaster. One can
only imagine the pressure today, one day after yet another troubled
youth opened fire in yet another American high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to do SOMETHING.''
</P>
<P>
   It is what drove House Speaker Dennis Hastert to raise the
suggestion this week that the legal age for buying handguns should
be raised from 18 to 21. Under current federal law, it is already a
crime for licensed firearms dealers to sell handguns to anyone
under 21.
</P>
<P>
   To quote Alan Korwin, author of ``Gun Laws of America,'' ``If
you want to fix the laws, it helps to know what they are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to do SOMETHING.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what motivated Vice President Al Gore to cast the
tie-breaking vote to require background checks on all transactions
at gun shows, whether the seller is a licensed dealer or a private
collector. Good idea? Perhaps. One little problem _ the FBI's
instant check system isn't exactly a 1-800 number that anyone can
dial up. It takes an access code, and those only go to federally
licensed firearms dealers. Welcome, new bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to do SOMETHING.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what prompted the safety lock requirement that includes the
inane provision that if a gun owner doesn't use a safety lock and
the firearm is stolen and then used in a crime, she can be held
liable.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the gun owner lives alone and therefore has
absolutely no need for trigger locks to keep the firearm safe from
... who, her cat? Never mind that someone else would have to commit
heaven knows how many other crimes to illegally enter the
residence, steal the gun and then use it in another crime. The gun
owner will be in deep yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to do SOMETHING.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what motivated President Clinton and members of both
parties to call for making sure that violent juvenile offenders are
never allowed to own firearms in their lifetimes. Good idea. One
problem: The feds don't control juvenile records _ the states do.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Constitution gives Congress no authority whatsoever
over crimes committed by juveniles within a single state. And
juvenile records, by state statute, are sealed. In a practical,
real-world, constitutional sense, how is this supposed to work?
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to do SOMETHING.''
</P>
<P>
   But is more legislation the answer? At least 41 federal laws
were violated in the Columbine High School incident a month ago.
Forty-one existing laws. Obtaining guns and ammunition through
bogus means. Possession of explosives with malicious intent.
Possession of bomb-making materials. Possession of a firearm by a
minor without the federally required permission slip from a parent
or guardian. Conspiracy to commit a felony. Providing a handgun to
a minor. Manufacture and possession of a non-federally approved
weapon _ two separate counts for that sawed-off shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   And those are just some of the laws violated before a shot was
fired or an explosive was detonated. Does anyone truly believe that
more laws are the answer to preventing this inexplicable blackening
of a heart and total disregard for rules of conduct in a civilized
society?
</P>
<P>
   Americans are frustrated and scared for their children, and they
are showing their fear by railing at their elected representatives
to do something or else. But panic on the part of lawmakers who
fear for their re-election chances is a very poor reason for
enacting redundant, unnecessary and in some cases unconstitutional
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   A true leader would be someone who calls for a thorough review
of existing laws _ on federal and state levels _ to see exactly
what's already on the books. A true leader would be someone who
encourages Americans to focus on their own lives and actions and
how they can regain control instead of looking to the Capitol to
legislate that which cannot be legislated: morality, personal
responsibility, kindness, compassion, humanity.
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't the biggest bunch of wishful thinking to come down
the pike.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to do something, DON'T THEY?''
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is a senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact her by e-mail at:
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by telephone at (817) 390-7599.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6236 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOHAWK-HAIRCUT-$ADV23     05-21 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOHAWK-HAIRCUT-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR REBEL STREAK IS SHOWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 23)  
(lh) 
 By KEVIN BISCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Thinking of killing the president?''
</P>
<P>
   I have been asked this by many people lately. And I can't really
blame them. When I catch my reflection in a window, even I see a
stranger. Not just someone unknown. Someone strange. I don't need
antipsychotic drugs or shock therapy to tame the wild-man look. I
just need a barber who can mow down the strip of hair bisecting my
head.
</P>
<P>
   I am wearing the world's most provocative haircut: a Mohawk.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, the Mohawk is showing signs of a revival.
Alexander McQueen sent a couple down the runway for his fall 1998
ready-to-wear collection in London. Up-and-coming actors Matthew
Lillard and Adrian Brody have both worn Mohawks for roles, and the
July issue of Details magazine is to feature a model with a Mohawk
in a beach-wear story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the haircut to have for ages between 15 and 30,'' said
Ward Stegerhoek, the creative director of Bumble and Bumble, a
midtown salon with a Hollywood clientele.
</P>
<P>
   The Mohawk _ the word is an Algonquian term meaning
``man-eater'' _ has been favored for years by people seeking to
make a strong impression. In December 1773, for instance, American
patriots disguised as Mohawk Indians dumped 342 chests of tea into
the Boston Harbor _ the Boston Tea Party.
</P>
<P>
   For exactly these reasons, it was adopted by members of the punk
movement in the 1970s. Worn colored and stuck up with Krazy Glue or
spray starch, it was not only an affront to the flowing peasant
styles of the time, but also defiant even of gravity. It was a
declaration of youth on a rampage.
</P>
<P>
   The late-1990s version is no longer just for rebels without a
cause; it has been neatened up and reinvented for men, including
some with day jobs, who just want to look as if they have a
rebellious streak. Stegerhoek, who recently styled one for a
magazine shoot, explained: ``To bring it to a man who can still
wear a suit, the sides aren't completely shaved. They are just
trimmed very short. And there is a longer section in the center
that is just short and choppy. The proportions have come a lot
closer, and that's made it a much more handsome look.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, lay off the greasy kid stuff. Go natural.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Peddle, a scout for the Next modeling agency, discovered
the power of a Mohawk during the eight months he wore one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got through airports really quickly,'' Peddle said, no mean
advantage when his job has him flying 15 times a month. ``People
would literally clear a path for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, on a whim that was a year in the making, I walked
into Ginger Rose on East Houston Street, a salon with a neon
clipper and pictures of dazzling heads of cropped hair hanging in
the window. I entered with a messy pompadour and left with a strip
of hair an inch and a half wide, dividing two bald sides of my
head. Over the following weeks, I kept a diary of peoples'
responses to my Mohawk. They were typically pro or con _ and rarely
neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, April 9
</P>
<P>
   As I am disconnected before a Movie Phone ticket order can be
confirmed, I angrily pound the receiver into the keypad of a pay
phone on University Place. I have done this with normal hair
before, but this time, people stare disapprovingly at me. To them,
I am an anarchist declaring war on Ma Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The Mohawk magnifies things, making even small actions highly
charged. When I politely order lunch at Les Deux Gamins on Waverly
Place, there is mild shock on people's faces at my clear
articulation. At St. Marks Bookshop, where I browse through a copy
of Richardson _ an art magazine that specializes in high-toned
pornography _ I don't feel the urge to hide the cover. Since I
already look like a rebel, it is excusable to act like one. The
more conspicuous I am, the less self-conscious I feel.
</P>
<P>
   On a sidewalk in the East Village, I pass Jesse Camp, the MTV
host who has ululated his way through a year on television after
winning a ``Wanna Be a VJ'' contest. With his nappy spikes, he is
nobody's slouch in the hair department. He locks eyes on my Mohawk,
and gives me a look that suggests he knows me, or should.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, April 13
</P>
<P>
   As I pass Coney Island High, the punk-rock landmark on St. Marks
Place, the young man sitting on a stool at the door at 1 a.m. says:
``Come on in, brother. Support the cause.'' Just because I'm
advertising my authority complex _ perhaps working at home gives
this character trait room to grow _ doesn't mean I like a single
Dead Kennedys song.
</P>
<P>
   Riding the subway, I try an experiment. With my nose in the
paper, I randomly look up in any direction. Invariably, I lock eyes
with someone who has been staring at my head. They quickly look
away, except infants and the very old, who return my gaze blankly
or gleefully.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, April 15
</P>
<P>
   I drop by the opening reception of the Alfred Hitchcock
retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art. A woman with hair dyed
white and black like Cruella De Vil's keeps looking at me. Perhaps
she's trying to figure out who the new strange-haired kid in town
is.
</P>
<P>
   A paparazzo clicks a few shots of me. Or rather, he clicks shots
of the Guy With the Mohawk, since paparazzi never photograph me
normally.
</P>
<P>
   I have stumbled onto some foolish middling degree of fame _ the
kind that former cast members of ``The Real World'' must enjoy.
Sometimes people want to touch my head, and I don't deny them the
pleasure. At a party in the East Village, after 20 minutes of
conversation, a woman abruptly asks, ``Want to make out?'' (This,
like the paparazzi's attention, is also new. Note to self: keep
Mohawk through Labor Day.)
</P>
<P>
   Introducing myself turns out to be a quaint formality, like
thank-you cards. It's nice if you do it, but not really necessary.
</P>
<P>
   As one of my friends says, ``Who knew that having an edge would
be so easy?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Friday, April 16
</P>
<P>
   At breakfast in the East Village, I overhear another diner say
to his companions with their backs to me, ``Don't look now.'' He
imitates a Mohawk, brushing open palms on the side of this head and
drawing an imaginary strip down the center.
</P>
<P>
   That night in Chelsea, I attend a party with very stylishly
coiffed European men and women. I am out with my friend Dave, who
with a head full of blond dreadlocks usually makes me look like the
straight man. Now we are some kind of strange hair cabal. I spot a
woman standing alone in the kitchen, and after fixing myself a
drink, I lean against the counter and survey the party from her
vantage point. Before I can say a word, she bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, April 21
</P>
<P>
   Walking home in the late afternoon, I give a great, leonine
yawn. A full block later, at Orchard and Houston Streets, I run
into a friend, who says: ``Didn't your mother ever teach you to
cover your mouth when you yawn? I saw you from two blocks away.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, it seems, is noticing me from two blocks away, and
they do their best to give me a wide berth. I am no longer jostled
on the street, something I noticed on this day when someone did
bump me. It seemed like such an invasion that I sneered at him.
</P>
<P>
   One bonus to having a Mohawk is that panhandlers no longer pipe
up as I walk by. Either I look like a low-percentage hit, or they
figure I am not worth taking a risk over. But there are other
equally unwanted comments directed at me on the street. ``You
talking to me?'' people love to ask, imitating Travis Bickle from
``Taxi Driver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going to dye it?'' is another favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, and stand out like a sore thumb?'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, April 24
</P>
<P>
   At an Upper East Side party in an apartment off Fifth Avenue, I
fear that the isolation of the previous weekend's party in Chelsea
is going to be even greater. For the most part, I am right. When
I'm not talking to the two people I knew when I arrived, I am
staring at the bookcases, studying the reading choices of our
hostess.
</P>
<P>
   I notice a trend. Most people wait for someone else to talk to
me, and then feel emboldened to join in. This is what a woman named
Jolie does. After about 20 minutes of chatter about careers and
such, she says, ``You know, you really don't look like a freak.''
The hostess chimes in, ``I bet he's really normal, and that's why
he has that haircut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget shy,'' I add.
</P>
<P>
   She taps her nose.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, April 25
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice hair, dude,'' a guy calls from his fire escape on
Elizabeth Street as I walk beneath him. By now, I am used to this,
just as I am used to being smiled at when I walk into stores. At
the Lotus Club, a cafe on the Lower East Side that I have visited
every day for a year, I am given a free cup of coffee for the first
time. The counter man even remembers how I take it _ iced, with a
splash of milk.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he remembers how the Guy With the Mohawk takes it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
