<HEADER>
A6240 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     05-21 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU WANT ART, GO TO A MUSEUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have more than 500 megabytes of art files
from my old computer that I want to transfer to the new one. I'm
wondering if there is any way to transfer stuff via modems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Piles O' Files
</P>
<P>
   DEAR PILES: Sure there is, as long as you have a couple of days
with nothing better to do. Pack a couple of sandwiches, brew up a
pot of joe, call yourself with some terminal program, start a file
transfer and sit back and watch that progress bar inch along like a
``Star Wars'' ticket line.
</P>
<P>
   Or, you could do the sensible thing. Just hook up your two
computers with a cable and copy all your dirty pictures, uh, ``art
files,'' from one to the other. It shouldn't take an hour. And if
you have Windows 95 or better on both machines, you already have
the software. It's called Direct Cable Connection, and it's in
Accessories. If it's not, go to the Windows Setup tab in Add/Remove
Programs and install it. It requires networking support and file
sharing, which you add in the Network section of the Control Panel.
</P>
<P>
   One of your computers will be able to view the other's drives as
folders it can share. Then use Windows Explorer to move all those
Pam Anderson videos to the new machine.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you want to make things a heck of a lot easier, go
buy a program like Laplink or pcAnywhere, which actually comes with
the cable you need. Direct Cable Connection is notoriously balky,
and there's a good chance you'll pound one of the two machines to
death with a hammer long before you get the files to transfer.
Maybe both.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Can you please refer me to some location that
has an archive of your previous columns? _ No Accounting for Taste
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TASTE: Try looking in the closet in the back bedroom of my
mother's house, right under the box of used dress shields. C'mon,
now, if I put all the old stuff where people could get at it,
eventually somebody would figure out that I just recycle everything
every three or four months, and that would terribly embarrass my
editor, who's supposed to be reading this stuff instead of always
slipping out to have her nails done.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: When I turn on the computer, I get the
following: ``Error starting program. A required DLL file,
Pncrt.dll, was not found.'' OK. What have I done wrong?
</P>
<P>
   _ It's All My Fault
</P>
<P>
   DEAR ALL: What you did wrong was believing that Windows could
actually run forever without its wheels falling off.
</P>
<P>
   The thing you're missing is a support file for RealPlayer, the
audio/video player. No telling what gobbled it up. Could be a bad
installation. Could be an accidental deletion. Could be Windows
doing its normal self-destruct routine. The safest thing to do now
is to uninstall RealPlayer, then reinstall it. Go to Add/Remove
Programs in the Control Panel, then click on the Windows Setup Tab.
RealPlayer is under Internet Tools.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, just go to www.real.com and get the latest version.
And remember: It's always Windows' fault. Always. Even that nasty
business with Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Won't you answer letters in a way that is more
pleasant, leaving out the ridicule?
</P>
<P>
   _ MISS MANNERS
</P>
<P>
   Dear Miss: What kind of a pinheaded question is that?
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay _ who is a very, very
bad man _ offers occasionally accurate advice about most things
electronic. He can be reached on Internet at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817) 390-7257.
In real life he is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
