<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-CLUB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD WARRIOR HOPES TO LEAD SIERRA CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ David Brower, the old environmental lion, is
roaring again.
</P>
<P>
   At age 86, he's running for the presidency of the Sierra Club,
aiming, he says, to revitalize an organization that has become
clubby, fearful of risk and preoccupied with procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Brower's 14 co-directors on the Sierra Club board, who will
elect a new president on Saturday, are all his spiritual children.
He was transforming the Sierra Club from a nonpolitical group of
mostly affluent backpackers into a mighty environmental lobby
before many of them were born.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, as he freely acknowledges, he's the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues are loath to criticize Brower publicly, but
conversations with club activists leave the impression that many
believe he's had his day, won't pay sufficient attention to the
nuts and bolts of club affairs _ and may be on an ego trip.
</P>
<P>
   Brower's bid to lead the 550,000 members of the century-old
Sierra Club is consistent with the bold moves that characterized
his 17 years as its executive director. His tenure was marked by
epic environmental victories, such as the creation of nine national
parks and seashores, and preventing the damming of the Grand
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1969 the board _ of which he is now a voting member _
fired him because he was unmanageable. Brower repeatedly made
policy and financial decisions without consulting the board, even
as he increased the conservation organization's membership nearly a
hundredfold and its influence by at least that much.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent electronic mail message to friends, Brower observed
that he is often compared to Sierra Club founder John Muir and that
he's already 10 years older than Muir when he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having waited so long to be president of his club, I ought to
hurry. I'd like to do my best to make sure there will be a lot of
people helping achieve some of Muir's goals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brower said that ``what's worrying me is that the board is more
concerned with procedure than substance. There's practically no
talk about what's happening to Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Directors have become ``much too at ease about closed-door
sessions. They don't want democracy to interfere with process,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants to see the Sierra Club's staff decentralized,
its outreach program strengthened, its book program _ which he
initiated _ revitalized, and directors' closed-door sessions
opened. He also wants the board of directors to work on issues that
would enable environmentalists to build new political coalitions,
such as those that might target the revitalizing of U.S. railroads.
</P>
<P>
   And he sounds his recurring theme: ``No more club cop-outs. ...
Anyone who knows (Sierra Club history) knows the shame and
unnecessary destruction wrought by compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Brower has often said that the worst decision he ever made as
executive director _ one which had him contemplating suicide _ was
to recommend the compromise on the Colorado River system which
permitted construction of Glen Canyon Dam. The Sierra Club is now
involved in a campaign to drain Lake Powell and tear down that dam.
</P>
<P>
   The coolness toward Brower's presidential candidacy may have
less to do with his chronic contentiousness than with a general
feeling that the club under past President Adam Werbach and current
President Chuck McGrady is running smoothly and in the right
direction, albeit more slowly than some members would like.
</P>
<P>
   That Brower is likely to be denied his desire to head the club
with which he has been associated for 65 years ``is unfortunate and
in no way meant to minimize his accomplishments,'' said Besty
Gaines, a Sierra Club director from Bozeman, Mont. ``I really
admire Mr. Brower. He's an amazing figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Ferenstein, a director from Missoula, Mont., agreed.
``He's a wonderful person, but I don't think he wants to handle the
administrative side of it,'' she said, adding that McGrady, a North
Carolinian who is running for re-election, ``is a really good
person, and he's done more to pilot the Sierra Club in a positive
way than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Brower acknowledges that he has no intention of being a hands-on
administrator. ``It is my intention to de-emphasize the role of the
president'' and club staffers and to let real power be exercised by
directors, who are elected by the members.
</P>
<P>
   Brower's run for the Sierra Club presidency is his second _ he
lost his first bid last year _ and he concedes that ``at this
point, I don't see enough votes. I'm afraid I'll miss again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
