<HEADER>
A6251 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCULPTUREGARDEN-TEX     05-21 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCULPTUREGARDEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SCULPTURE GARDEN TAKES SHAPE AT THE NATIONAL GALLERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sculpture garden, a museum without walls, has
been a dream of staff and officials at the National Gallery of Art
for more than 30 years. On Sunday, that dream becomes real, when
the National Gallery of Art Sculpture Garden opens to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The new garden features 17 pieces of cutting-edge art, set amid
manicured greenery and surrounding a fountain and pool. It occupies
more than six acres at Seventh Street and Constitution Avenue,
adjacent to the gallery. The museum, in turn, is one of several
lining the parklike Mall that links the Capitol and the Washington
Monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proud to bring to the nation these significant works of
sculpture in one of the few outdoor settings of this magnitude in
the country,'' gallery director Earl A. Powell III said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the artists represented are Joan Miro, David Smith, Lucas
Samaras, Tony Smith, Louise Bourgeois, Roy Lichtenstein, Alexander
Calder, Claes Oldenburg and Coosje van Bruggen, and Isamu Noguchi.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture garden cost $13 million to build, excluding the
amount paid for the artwork. The Washington-based Morris and
Gwendolyn Cafritz Foundation contributed $10 million, with the rest
coming from private funds. Named for a pair of philanthropists and
art lovers, the Cafritz Foundation also purchased seven of the 10
new sculptures. Six other works have been moved from elsewhere in
the gallery, and one is on loan.
</P>
<P>
   Money given by the Nancy Lee and Perry Bass Fund of Fort Worth
was used to buy Samaras' ``Chair Transformation,'' a
gravity-defying stack of leaning chairs. Powell would not disclose
the cost of any artwork or say how much money came from the Bass
fund.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the sculpture garden is one of the most historic
events for the museum since it opened in 1941, Powell said. He
described the setting as a ``new forum for appreciating
20th-century sculpture'' and a ``perfect marriage between landscape
and art.''
</P>
<P>
   From a playful rendition of a 20-foot-tall typewriter eraser to
a menacing spider measuring 9 feet by 27 feet, the sculpture garden
touches on some of the diversity of modern sculpture and evokes
myriad emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really aiming for a dynamic, richly textured variation
of modern sculpture,'' said Marla Prather, the gallery's curator of
20th-century art. She said the prospect of the landscape changing
with the seasons was an exciting element in designing the garden
and anticipating how art will live outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   The fountain and reflecting pool, the focal point of the site,
will be converted to a skating rink in winter, replacing an earlier
rink. Adding to the viewing experience will be a cafe with indoor
and outdoor seating, expected to open in the fall. There is seating
all around the fountain and throughout the garden, including one of
the sculptures itself: Scott Burton's ``Six-Part Seating,'' a group
of red-granite seats that face each other in a circle.
</P>
<P>
   In a break from the traditional museum experience, the public
will be allowed to walk up to, around and under most of the
sculptures and even touch them, although museum officials are still
unsure how that will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try to dissuade too much touching,'' Prather said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they touch or not, though, visitors are sure to be
absorbed, fascinated, amused and even repelled by some of the
works.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptures include:
</P>
<P>
   ``Typewriter Eraser, Scale X'' (1999), by Oldenburg and van
Bruggen. An eraser was one of Oldenburg's favorite childhood
playthings in his father's office in Sweden. In this giant
rendition, the painted steel and fiberglass sculpture is placed so
that the brush bristles playfully point to the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chair Transformation No. 20B'' (1996), by Samaras. ``A work
that defies all the conventions of balance,'' according to Prather.
The stacked chairs appear to lean back and forth simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spider'' (1996/1998), by Bourgeois. The spider is depicted
here as both nurturing and menacing. It is part of the artist's
spider series, which explores themes of childhood memory and loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinker on a Rock'' (1997), by Barry Flanagan. The artist here
plays with Rodin's classic by depicting the figure as a hare.
Flanagan has made the hare a signature for his work, often using it
to poke fun at tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puellae'' (1992), by Magdalena Abakanowicz. A disquieting
assembly of 30 bronze figures of pre-adolescent girls, the work was
inspired by a story about a group of children found frozen to death
in cattle cars as they were transported from Poland to Germany in
1942.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheval Rouge (Red Horse)'' (1974), by Calder. On loan from the
Calder Foundation in New York, this is a bold, aggressive portrayal
of a horse made of painted sheet metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``House I'' (1996/1998), by Lichtenstein: A whimsical,
two-dimensional house, the sculpture is outlined in black and
colored in the artist's signature primary colors. ``It's like
having a cartoon in the middle of the garden,'' Prather said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   National Gallery of Art Sculpture Garden
</P>
<P>
   Opens Sunday: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays through Saturdays and 11
a.m.-6 p.m. Sundays, Seventh Street and Constitution Avenue,
Washington, D.C. It is closed Dec. 25 and Jan. 1
</P>
<P>
   Admission: Free
</P>
<P>
   Information: (202) 737-4215
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
