<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV23-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBIN A HARD ACT TO FOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 23, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is worth pointing out, midst the virtually wall-to-wall
praise which marks Robert Rubin's departure from high government
service, that his tenure as Treasury Secretary proves several
useful points:
</P>
<P>
   --Being smart, tough and modest can bring great professional
success.
</P>
<P>
   --Deft tugs on the levers of government can actually improve the
performance of the economy, contrary to the hoarse complaints of
the right-wingers that government can never do anything right.
</P>
<P>
   --It never hurts to get lucky from time to time, just so long as
you don't start counting on it.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of greasy journalism and downmarket triumphalism in
the media generally, a gentleman of principle and probity can have
a remarkable influence on the affairs of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The name ``Rubin'' and the word ``scandal'' never appeared in
the same sentence in the millions of words gushing out of
Washington. The man who'd made millions as a Wall Street trader
over 26 years of outguessing the markets completed his public
service without a smudge.
</P>
<P>
   He was the cabinet member in charge of the money; the
government's money, the public's money in the larger sense, and, in
the largest sense, the world's money. On his watch, the markets
prospered, the Dow Jones average tripled, inflation went aneroxic,
and Main Street discovered Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Rubin era was the century's Golden Decade, for just about
everything except gold, and oil, and some other commodities, as
information became the coin of the realm, displacing the ``stuff''
that used to move mountains and make millionaires, who are now too
numerous to catalogue.
</P>
<P>
   America's dizzying prosperity did not reach down to the bottom
rungs of the economic ladder. It never does reach all the way down.
But both Rubin and President Clinton noted the plight of the
left-behind in their parting remarks, even if the financial experts
and the journalistis generally did not bother to include those in
their summary of Rubin's accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Our relative wealth is the envy of the planet. In a recent paper
World Bank President James Wolfensohn and Nobel Prize economist
Amartya Sen sketched the plight of the bottom half of the globe's
peoples: ``Three billion people live on less than two dollars a
day, 1.3 billion (one human out of four) do not have clean water,
130 million children do not go to school, and 40,000 children die
every day because of hunger-related diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   They made a plea for more social safety nets worldwide, a cause
Rubin endorsed throughout his tenure, even as he remained the
hard-eyed market supremacists' favorite bureaucrat. Rubin had a
genuine knack for inspiring trust. Along with Alan Greenspan, the
Federal Reserve chieftan who is Wall Street's reigning heavyweight
champ, Rubin and his deputy, Lawrence Summers, 44, became the Three
Musketeers of the Clinton era, nerdy swashbucklers triumphing
routinely.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico goes belly up? No problem. Rubin works out a rescue
package, and all the bills get paid. Wall Street has a bellyache,
and the stock market dumps seven percent in one day? Here, take a
Bob Rubin steady-as-she-goes pill, with a few purred words about
the strength of the US ``fundamentals.'' Asia trembles, and the
tigers start falling like dominoes? Dr. Bob is there with asprin,
soft words, and wise counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese still can't get it right. Their weak political
system is incapable of bringing to heel an essentially crooked,
unbalanced, corrupt financial system. Some argue that the post-war
makeover imposed on Japan by the United States a half-century ago
crunched them into an essentially-coercive, unnatural system.
Clearly, Tokyo cannot find its Rubin, never mind its Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   And while you'll rarely hear a kind word for Bill Clinton from
the gang that profits most off the economy, or commenting upon it,
the old Arkansas hillbilly must have done something right here, or
at the least, he didn't screw it up. When I asked Bill Bradley
recently how much credit the Clinton-Gore team deserved for the
nation's prosperity, the Olde Princetonian ticked off a half-dozen
reasons for same, never mentioning the words ``Clinton'' or
``Gore.'' But Bradley did praise Rubin, Greenspan and Summers.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if Summers, described as brilliant but
brittle, can replicate Rubin's run as his successor. Summers was
only 28 when he became the youngest Harvard professor ever to win
tenure. For that alone, he'll be hated by hundreds of thousands of
envious graduate students. How will the markets take to Summers?
</P>
<P>
   To the Treasury-Secretary-designate, I commend the words of
Herman Hickman, football coach at Yale, when asked how he'd handle
restive alumni. ``The alumni,'' decreed Herm, ``should be kept
sullen, but not mutinous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
