<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, May 22, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICY (Washington) _ Between the two options that
President Clinton has declared unacceptable _ doing nothing or
all-out war _ the White House has devised a new kind of warfare for
Yugoslavia. It is a calibrated war, enabled by high-tech weaponry,
shaped by the flickering light of opinion polls and shackled by
fear that a few American combat deaths could turn the public
against any military intervention in an obscure placed called
Kosovo. By Blaine Harden and John Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Talks over Kosovo are ended with Strobe
Talbott, the deputy secretary of state, saying he'll return next
week.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIE-DONATE (Washington) _ Charlie Trie, Little Rock
restaurateur and longtime friend of Clinton, whose donations to
Democrats were returned, pleads guilty to obstruction and campaign
related offenses and agrees to cooperate with federal authorities.
By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-MARIJUANA (Washington) _ In an effort to promote research
into the medical benefits of marijuana, the Clinton administration
has decided to begin selling government-grown marijuana to
scientists who want to study the drug but who have previously been
unable to do so because they lacked the required relationship with
the National Institutes of Health. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-IMPACT (Orange, N.J.) _ With lottery machines as
prevalent as cash registers in 38 states and $35 billion bet on
them each year, the most prevalent purveyor of betting games in
America is no longer the corner bookmaker. Instead, it is state
governments _ the same entities that for years outlawed gambling.
The impact that state lotteries are having on communities around
the country has been a major focus of the National Gambling Impact
Study Commission, which is examining the social and economic
consequences of gambling. It is in communities like Orange where
the lottery is a dominant force and many poor and modest wage
earners are devoted to an endless search for winning numbers. By
Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   A Special Report, 3900 words, plus an abridged version of about
2000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS-IMPACT (Boston) _ A handful of relatively little
noticed provisions in the crime bill passed by the Senate Thursday
may do as much or more to curb the flow of illegal guns to
criminals and juveniles than the much debated measures that require
child safety locks and background checks at gun shows, senior
Treasury Department officials say. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-COMMUNITY (Littleton, Colo.) _ As Columbine High
School approaches the end of the school year, the commuinity finds
itself struggling not only with its tragedy, but also with how to
reclaim its privacy. What it's like to live at the center of a news
event. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
</TEXT>
