<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, May 23, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ORCHARD-FASHION (New York) _ What was the woman in the
lime-green and gray suit, with shoulders sharp enough to poke an
eye out, doing in the middle of Orchard Street? The suit came from
Marcesa, one of the traditional ``I can get it for you wholesale''
stores on Orchard. Well, she was a fashion model; Orchard Street
had been temporarily fitted with an elevated catwalk, and the
garish green power suit was the tartly affectionate statement of
Ben Sturgill, a participant in the Orchard Street Style Slam last
Sunday. By David Colman. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MOHAWK-HAIRCUT (Undated) _ Believe it or not, the Mohawk is
showing signs of a revival. Alexander McQueen sent a couple down
the runway for his fall 1998 ready-to-wear collection in London.
The up-and-coming actors Matthew Lillard and Adrian Brody have both
worn Mohawks for roles, and the July issue of Details magazine is
to feature a model with a Mohawk in a beach-wear story. By Kevin
Bisch.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-KIMHEIRSTON (New York) _ I know being fabulous is a
full-time occupation,'' Gregory Crewdson, an artist, said recently.
``But what exactly does she do?'' That seems to be the $100,000
question whenever Kim Heirston's name is mentioned. Neither a
collector nor a dealer, neither a curator nor a gallery owner, Ms.
Heirston, 35, is an art adviser, coaching the rich on how to spend
their fortunes on fine art. Ms. Heirston seems well suited to a
career that is equal parts socializing and commerce. At 6 feet
tall, she cut a striking figure as she glided into the contemporary
art sale at Sotheby's last Tuesday evening. By Elizabeth Hayt.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TEENAGE-CONSULTANTS (New York) _ Looking for new and improved
ways to separate teen-agers from their money, the DuPont Co. has
moved beyond the typical practice of buying information on
teen-agers' brand, celebrity and sitcom preferences culled by
marketing companies specializing in teenagers. Like a growing
number of companies, including Levis and M&AMP;M/Mars, DuPont is hiring
teen-agers as consultants. By Penelope Green.
</P>
<P>
   HAMPTONS-CELEBS-LAND (New York) _ In the Hamptons people are
preparing for the summer season by marshalling an army of front-end
loaders, bulldozers and dump trucks. They're pursuing the area's
latest trend: transforming the area's generally flat topography
into rolling hills, ridges and ponds, in some cases landscapes more
typical of an estate in Greenwich, Conn. or New Jersey hunt
country. By Monique P. Yazigi. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Herefordshire, England) _ A few hair-raising
miles along a narrow road from Ludlow Castle, an 11th-century ruin
in west-central England, one comes upon a garden of great
distinction, the unlikely centerpiece of which is a magnificent
display of echinacea, North America's native purple coneflower. The
planting of echinacea in this garden at Elton Hall has been
designated a ``national collection'' by England's National Council
for the Conservation of Plants and Gardens, which is dedicated to
preserving the gene pool of garden plants. By Marty Ross.
</P>
