<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN ALBANIA, INTERNET PROVIDES NATIVES, REFUGEES WINDOW TO
OUTSIDE WORLD
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ In a small room one floor up from a narrow,
muddy street here in Albania's capital, you can rent a window on
the world for $3 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   For Leohora Lutolli, a 21-year-old refugee from Kosovo, the
Internet cafe Fastech provides the only outside connection she has
in a world that has unraveled so suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Serb forces forced Lutolli from her home in Kosovo's
provincial capital of Pristina at gunpoint. On Friday, she was
furiously writing e-mails to her friends who were scattered in the
exodus.
</P>
<P>
   While the Internet is becoming a common accessory in the West,
in Albania, which until 1989 was one of the world's most isolated
societies; it provides a dizzying amount of access to the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Kosovo, particularly in cities such as Pristina, the
computer culture is far better established. Many refugees coming
across the border ask reporters and aid workers awaiting them to
send e-mails to loved ones to let them know they're OK.
</P>
<P>
   And now Albania, which seems to be just awakening from a 50-year
sleep, is finding its way to the World Wide Web. ``Before a year
ago, there was no local Internet provider,'' said Sokol Bardhi, who
has worked at Fastech since it opened a few days before NATO began
bombing Yugoslavia in late March. ``Now there are three, maybe
four.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the new providers is AOL _ Albania On Line _ which has
been running frequent commercials on local television touting its
access to its American cousin with the same initials.
</P>
<P>
   But computers are still an expensive luxury in Europe's poorest
country, and the Internet remains beyond the reach of most
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Fastech -- the city's only place where people can go online for
an hourly rate -- intends to change that by providing a way to surf
the Web relatively inexpensively. In this former communist state,
Fastech is a fresh blossom of the fledgling free market. ``It has
been successful,'' Bardhi said. ``But this isn't what we planned.
We just wanted to sell the computers. This just happened and the
people like it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first floor of the small block building Friday,
foreigners as well as young Albanians typed messages and read
replies on the half-dozen computer terminals. The place has become
a favorite of journalists because local hotels charge up to $8 a
minute to plug in a modem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have many university students who have friends they
can e-mail,'' Bardhi said.
</P>
<P>
   For Lutolli, the Internet provides a more immediate and vital
purpose. ``There is no other way that I can talk to (fellow
refugees, friends and relatives), to see who is dead and who is
alive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
