<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6281 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV23-     05-21 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DABS OF AMERICAN ROMANCE IN AN ENGLISH GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 23)  
(lh) 
 By MARTY ROSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEREFORDSHIRE, England _ A few hair-raising miles along a narrow
road from Ludlow Castle, an 11th-century ruin in west-central
England, one comes upon a garden of great distinction, the unlikely
centerpiece of which is a magnificent display of echinacea, North
America's native purple coneflower.
</P>
<P>
   The planting of echinacea in this garden at Elton Hall has been
designated a ``national collection'' by England's National Council
for the Conservation of Plants and Gardens, which is dedicated to
preserving the gene pool of garden plants. Five species and 24
cultivated varieties of echinacea thrive at Elton Hall, planted in
drifts and dabs of color in an extraordinary garden surrounded by a
fine, lacy young beech hedge.
</P>
<P>
   Purple coneflowers are members of the daisy family, the
compositae/asteraceae, one of the plant world's largest groups,
with 21,000 species. The genus echinacea is one of the smallest,
with only nine species but around 50 cultivated hybrids. They are
vigorous perennial plants with rough, handsome, deep green foliage.
The flowers' elongated petals, usually purple but also pink or
white, radiate from spiky, green-orange seed heads.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Brooks, 28, the gardener at Elton Hall, who created the
collection, has never been to America, so he has never seen
coneflowers in the prairies and open woodlands, where they
naturally flourish. He learned about them on busman's holidays in
Britain, visiting late-summer gardens. Coneflowers reach their peak
late in the season, when the bloom is likely to be off most of the
roses and the exuberant greenness of the garden demands more
assertive flowers.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 600 national collections in England, including
collections of trees, shrubs, annual and perennial flowers, bulbs
and vines. Brooks also holds a national collection of rudbeckia
(black-eyed Susans), with 25 species and 13 cultivars represented
at Elton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   His echinacea and rudbeckia were grown from seed and cuttings
from all over the world. They were sent to him by the National
Wildflower Research Center in Texas; botanic gardens in North
Carolina, Illinois, Romania, Lithuania and Switzerland, and friends
and colleagues in England, Holland and France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really a clue why I collect,'' said Brooks, who is
just a few years out of the horticulture program at Pershore and
Hindlip College, in Worcestershire. Plant collectors often enjoy
the challenge of growing rare and difficult species, but Brooks
specializes in coneflowers because they are so easy to grow. ``They
self-seeded, and that's one indication that they are good for the
garden,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of the garden at Elton Hall run to the 18th century,
when the sprawling estate was the home of Thomas Andrew Knight
(1759-1838), a founder of what is now the Royal Horticultural
Society. There are still a few ancient cherry trees on the
property, but little else remained of Knight's garden when the
present owners, James and Anne Hepworth, bought the estate 15 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hepworth is much given to garden ornament: he has filled the
five-acre garden with curiosities _ classical columns; an enormous
stone puffin on a plinth; miscellaneous lichen-encrusted capitals,
busts and urns; a terra-cotta palm tree, and not a few statuary
elephants. There is a small Moorish palace inhabited by sheep, and
the low brick crenelations of a fort _ the merest folly _ rise
mysteriously out of the lawn behind the house.
</P>
<P>
   Hepworth's eclectic collections presented his gardener with a
formidable challenge. ``I wanted to bring it all together,'' Brooks
said. He drew a line from the brick fort to a venerable cedar, and
bisected this important axis with a path to a charming little
temple in the Gothic style. The two lines come together in the
center of what Brooks calls the ``collection garden,'' where the
coneflowers and black-eyed Susans are planted among other tall
perennials and ornamental grasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the contrast of the formal structure with the loose,
informal plants,'' he said. ``Luckily, it all worked out
perfectly.'' Word of this exuberant and romantic garden has spread
quickly: 500 visitors came to view the echinacea collection one day
last September when the garden was open to the public. (Information
is available by fax: 011-44-1568-770-753.)
</P>
<P>
   The name echinacea is derived from the Greek word for
``hedgehog'' or ``sea urchin,'' in reference to the spiny seed
heads. The petals may be single or double and may fall swirling
away from the cones, like a schoolgirl's pleated skirt, or stand
out horizontally, more like a daisy.
</P>
<P>
   The most common species are Echinacea purpurea, E. pallida and
E. angustifolia. One rare species, E. paradoxa, has yellow petals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very fond of the natural form of the wild species,
especially E. pallida, which has long twisted petals,'' Brooks
said. The petals of his striking and extremely rare Tennessee
coneflower, E. tennesseensis, jut upward around the seed head.
</P>
<P>
   Coneflowers thrive in well-drained soil in sunny gardens, and
once established they are very tolerant of drought and neglect.
Brooks mulches his plants with leaf mold, but he does not recommend
fertilizer, particularly for large varieties, which can easily
reach about 4 feet tall in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   A number of smaller echinacea varieties that produce many
flowers on branched stems have been recently introduced. Brooks
likes Augustkoningin, introduced by Piet Oudolf, a Dutch breeder.
One of the compact new hybrids is E. purpurea Magnus, hybridized in
Sweden; it was recognized as the Perennial Plant Association's
plant of the year in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coneflowers look after themselves, really, once they are
planted,'' Brooks said, but he has a backup collection, just in
case, growing in rows in the vegetable garden at Elton Hall. The
blooms are quite pretty there with the cabbages, at that.
</P>
<P>
   Most garden shops and mail-order suppliers sell two or three
coneflowers _ Magnus, White Swan, and E. purpurea are all easy to
find _ but the choices then narrow drastically. One of the best
selections is available from Thompson &AMP; Morgan, P.O. Box 1308,
Jackson, NJ 08527; (800) 274-7333; free catalog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
