<HEADER>
A6283 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YADDO-AUTHORS-$ADV23-     05-21 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YADDO-AUTHORS-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCOLIC RETREAT OFFERED SETTING FOR WORDS, TALES IN '40S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 23)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Writer John Malcolm Brinnin shed his
shirt and bent to peel off his pants, when a stranger interrupted
his morning sunbath on a secluded Yaddo patio.
</P>
<P>
   A clanging chime from the heavy terrace door broadcast the man's
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, shut up,'' Truman Capote said to the jangling door. ``May
I join you?'' Capote was breaking the rules. Social calls to other
rooms at this artists colony were banned before 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Capote, 21, was one of Yaddo's youngest guests. It was
the height of Yaddo's Southern period, led by the writers Carson
McCullers, Eudora Welty and Katherine Anne Porter, who had several
stays between them. Other artists at the artists colony during the
1940s included Langston Hughes, Flannery O'Connor, Robert Lowell,
Granville Hicks, Henri Cartier-Bresson, Eleanor Clark, Patricia
Highsmith, Theodore Roethke, Alfred Kazin and Marguerite Young.
</P>
<P>
   It was Capote's magnetic energy that permeated the lush parlors
and white pines of the sprawling Saratoga Springs estate, which to
this day provides a picturesque retreat for artists.
</P>
<P>
   He wove hilarious dining room tales, served martinis in his
Gothic tower room, broke house rules with abandon and had love
affairs with Newton Arvin and Howard Doughty. Doughty wanted their
tryst kept quiet, but Capote was nothing if not indiscreet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little one has been talking again,'' Doughty dryly
remarked.``He's responsible for turning the summer into a dance of
bees,'' Brinnin wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Guests plotted to share Capote's dinner table. Life magazine
featured the new author in a July issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air was thick with untellable romance, on a scale close to
legend, as to both grandeur and tragedy,'' Eleanor Clark wrote of
Yaddo.
</P>
<P>
   How could it have been otherwise?
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1843, Edgar Allan Poe is said to have penned ``The
Raven'' on this muse-infused property. Later, industrialist Spencer
Trask built a 55-room fin-de-siecle mansion for his poet wife
Katrina. After their four children died, Katrina had a vision of a
permanent artist's refuge. In 1926, four years after her death,
Yaddo opened to invited guests.
</P>
<P>
   Into this posh summer camp came great authors with great themes,
heavy symbolism and larger-than-life neuroses. They resided, free
of charge, for periods of six weeks to several months.
</P>
<P>
   At the helm, Executive Director Elizabeth Ames ran the colony
and selected the guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than Malcolm's (critic Malcolm Cowley) word and a few
published stories, I have little to recommend me,'' John Cheever
wrote to Ames in 1933. He became a frequent visitor, the captain of
Yaddo's Lake George motorboat and a member of the board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summer was long enough to get to know one another,'' wrote
Welty, who came at Porter's urging. ``Karnig Nalbandian and Colin
McPhee were installed in the same farmhouse where Katherine Anne
Porter and I were, so we had our own little neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some tensions. Porter disliked McCullers and
complained of her amateurish card shuffling in the game room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not see beginning or end to the commotion that
mysteriously possessed them,'' wrote Alfred Kazin of the writers at
Yaddo.
</P>
<P>
   At night, for kicks, the group played murder in the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the murderer,'' Lerman recalled in George Plimpton's
oral biography of Capote. ``I knew exactly what victim I wanted.
Truman. Everybody flew from room to room screeching, hiding here,
hiding there. Carson adored it. ... Finally, I lured Truman into my
closet. I strangled him. He screamed, `Oh, you, I'll get you for
this! I'll never trust you again!' It was absolutely thrilling; his
scream went up several octaves above and several octaves below: It
was the full rage of Truman. It was the manly Truman, the female
Truman, it was the works. I think the scream haunts Yaddo still.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, they managed to write chunks of their classic
works. Porter penned part of what would become ``Ship of Fools.''
Capote wrote much of his novel ``Other Voices, Other Rooms.''
McCullers wrote ``Member of the Wedding,'' which she dedicated to
Ames, Yaddo's director.
</P>
<P>
   Or they stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Porter put off several projects, including a preface to one of
Welty's books, and instead bought a dilapidated clapboard farmhouse
outside town and her first car, a Buick, which Welty helped her
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Welty had her own blocks. ``I couldn't work in Yaddo. Everybody
had a sign on their door saying, `Silence, writer at work.' I read
my proofs, but I couldn't write in there. Everything was so tense,
so exalted. So I walked into Saratoga, and to the races, and took
pictures in Saratoga. And I would bring home groceries for
Katherine Anne to cook with, and so we had a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Capote routinely got into hot water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I knew it was too good to last; I'm in trouble, and it's
all Leo's fault,'' he wrote his editor after a written scolding
from Yaddo director Ames for scaring Lerman with a snake.
</P>
<P>
   Of Ames, he wrote: ``She was always going around spying, seeing
who was working and not working and what everybody was up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Later years brought more writers, more romance, and more
prize-winning authorship.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, Elizabeth Ames' stewardship was questioned in a nasty
public spat when Robert Lowell, Elizabeth Hardwick, Flannery
O'Connor and Edward Maisel accused Ames of being a communist
sympathizer and demanded her dismissal. At issue: Ames' friendship
with writer Agnes Smedley, an expert on Chinese communism and
frequent Yaddo guest. The Yaddo board rejected their claims but
stripped Ames of her power to select guests.
</P>
<P>
   Backing Ames were Cheever, Clark, Kazin, Kappo Phelan and
several others. They accused the Lowell-O'Connor group of hysterics
and anti-civil libertarianism.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, Yaddo memories were powerful and long-lived.
Patricia Highsmith, who spent just two months there in 1948, called
it the defining event of her professional life. She completed her
first published novel, ``Strangers on a Train,'' and later
bequeathed nearly $4 million to the retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I miss you-all at Yaddo! My stay there was most pleasant
and helpful to me,'' Langston Hughes wrote. `` And I am very happy
to have had the privilege of being there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The old Yaddo magic, some would say,'' wrote Clark, ``although
usually we just mean by that that we worked a little better, for a
little while, than we would have otherwise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
