<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-$ADV     05-21 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SPINMEISTERS HELP ELECT ISRAEL'S NEW LEADER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, May 23) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The television cameras were on, the videotape
machine was rolling and Adisu Massala, an Ethiopian immigrant to
Israel, was screaming into the microphone about the discrimination
he felt in the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Ehud Barak, then Labor's candidate for prime
minister, stood meekly by with an embarrassed half-grin frozen on
his face.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Barak has defeated incumbent Benjamin Netanyahu by 12
percentage points, in what for Israel amounted to a landslide
victory last Monday, Stanley Greenberg, one of Barak's U.S.
advisers, can joke about the incident. But when the incident
happened last fall during the Labor convention, he wasn't laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst thing I've ever seen in politics,'' Greenberg
recalled. ``I was sure that our numbers were going to plummet.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's polling numbers didn't go down. They were already low.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenberg and colleagues James Carville and Robert Shrum,
all veteran U.S. campaign managers, knew they had a challenge if
their Israeli client was going to win. They had to turn Barak, a
military man seemingly ill-at-ease in public and definitely not
good on camera, into a strong leader who would appeal to the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   They were up against not only Netanyahu, a past master of the
television soundbite, but also Netanyahu's adviser, American Arthur
Finkelstein, who engineered Netanyahu's 1996 come-from-behind
victory against Labor leader Shimon Peres with the slogan ``Peres
will divide Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   To put Barak more at ease in public, the Americans brought out
his wife, Nava, with whom friends say Barak is deeply in love, so
that Israelis could see the obvious affection he has for her. The
Americans also practiced with him in front of the camera. They
scheduled dozens of street appearances, so the voters could meet
him and realize his off-camera charm.
</P>
<P>
   And they pounded the message home through repeated campaign ads
that Barak was the most decorated military man in Israel's history,
the mastermind of multiple antiterrorist operations, including the
one that rescued passengers of a hijacked Sabena airlines flight in
the 1970s _ in short, someone to whom Israelis could entrust their
security.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the U.S. spinmeisters watched Barak's numbers climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a point where he did not continue to rise in
the polls,'' Greenberg said. ``The more exposure he had, the more
people warmed to him as somebody who could lead Israel. The more
they saw him, the more respect they had, the more they liked him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Americans arrived, there has been some skepticism here
whether foreign campaign advisers _ even Americans who know Israel
fairly well _ are capable of understanding the intricacies of
Israel's political culture well enough to be effective. Any
Israeli, for instance, could have told Greenberg that loud public
diatribes like Massala's are par for the campaign course, blown up
in the media one day and forgotten the next.
</P>
<P>
   The Massala incident, in fact, wasn't the only one that
confounded the Americans. They were stumped again just two weeks
before the elections, when Tiki Dayan, a famous actress-singer,
called Israel's market vendors ``rabble'' at a left-wing rally that
Barak's handlers had urged him to skip.
</P>
<P>
   The incident raised a furor because Israelis interpreted the
comment as a slur against the country's Sephardic Jews _ most of
whom are blue-collar workers who hail from Middle Eastern countries
_ delivered by a member the European-descended elite, the Ashkenazi
Jews, who form the backbone of the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really delicate issue in Israel,'' said Tal
Silberstein, the Israeli point-man on the Barak campaign team.
``Labor has been known for years for being condescending toward the
Sephardic voters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard for American consultants to understand this
internal racism in Israel and the way it affects voting patterns,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Americans didn't understand the subtleties of
Israel's social divide or the checkered history behind the bumper
stickers that began to appear with the slogan, ``I am proud
rabble,`` they knew the answer: ``rapid response.`` Immediately,
they put Barak on television to denounce Dayan's words.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Carville and his associates maintain, a campaign _
any campaign _ is always won using the same basic formula: closely
monitoring of public opinion, crafting simple slogans that jibe
with the polls, and then hammering those slogans home, again and
again, until people remember them.
</P>
<P>
   The Barak campaign's polling, for instance, showed that the
Labor Party suffered from a perception among many Israelis that it
was made up of a group of elitists who looked down on the Sephardic
Jews and who were too willing to concede territory to Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   To distance himself from these images, Barak and his campaign
handlers decided to merge Labor with two other parties, one
Sephardic and one made up of religious moderates. They named the
new coalition One Israel.
</P>
<P>
   To make the break from the Labor Party complete, Barak set up a
separate headquarters for the coalition in another part of Tel Aviv
and kept veteran Laborites and peace architects Shimon Peres and
Yossi Beilin, whom Israeli's most associate with the left's
readiness to give up land, out of the campaign limelight. Barak had
a new image of a centrist leader who could unite the people.
</P>
<P>
   While those strategies undoubtedly helped sweep Barak into
office, he was aided in no small measure by Netanyahu's own
fumbles, both during the five-month campaign and the Likud leader's
three years in office.
</P>
<P>
   Likud Party officials acknowledged last week that many of their
own ad campaigns simply backfired. A television spot showing a
bombed-out bus and declaring that only Netanyahu could keep
Israelis secure, for instance, brought allegations of
``scare-mongering'' from the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ad campaign was very bad,'' admitted one Likud official
who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``They didn't convince anyone
to vote for us. The bus ad in particular was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans also found that Netanyahu's record in office would
help their man. In three years, the prime minister had managed to
alienate most of his political allies and anger many of his voters.
Greenberg's own polls showed that nearly one in three voters who
cast ballots for Barak voted not for the Labor leader, but against
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they've won, Barak's advisers say they knew all along
that some of Netanyahu tactics, like the bus ad, would backfire.
</P>
<P>
   Before the campaign moved into full swing, they spent a lot of
time and money producing ads they thought the other side would
make. Then they used them to test public reaction in so-called
``focus groups'' that represented pools of voters.
</P>
<P>
   When the Netanyahu campaign's bus ad aired on television,
Silberstein said, Barak's handlers were ``very happy.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Our findings suggested that the ad wouldn't work,'' he said.
``With Barak's record, it's almost impossible to allege that he
won't keep Israel's security.''
</P>
<P>
   By this time, the ``Barak bio,`` the ad that pounded his
impressive military record into voters' heads and the one his spin
advisers said was the most effective, had been running for days.
The ad was persuasive, polls showed, particularly among Russian
immigrants, who make up a large part of Israel's swing vote and who
tend to vote for right-wing candidates who emphasize issues of
security.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before the election, Greenberg recalled, he was given
the results of a poll that showed Barak ahead by 14 percentage
points. He called Shrum and told him he was assuming the poll was
wrong and was throwing it out.
</P>
<P>
   Then the next poll came in.
</P>
<P>
   It, too, showed Barak with the same 14-point lead. Soon,
Israel's press, responding to polls of its own, predicted victory
for a man who only months before they had derided as too stiff, too
shy and bumbling in public to ever beat Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Three days before Election Day, the U.S. consultants were so
confident of their success that Carville flew home to the United
States to see his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we were going to win,'' Greenberg smiled. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
