<HEADLINE>
TOUGH EARLY-ROUND MATCHES POSSIBLE AT ROLAND GARROS 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By KATHLEEN McELROY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The French Open draw has created a couple of intriguing _
potentially dangerous _ early matches for both the top-ranked men's
and women's players.
</P>
<P>
   The draw, which was conducted Friday in Paris, pits two former
champions at Roland Garros in the men's first round: top-seeded
Yevgeny Kafelnikov, the 1996 champion, against Michael Chang, the
winner 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Neither player is on a roll as the tournament begins Monday in
southwest Paris. Kafelnikov is ranked No. 1 but has been in a slump
since winning the Australian Open in January. On Friday he lost to
little-known Mariano Zabaleta of Argentina in the semifinals of an
Austrian event.
</P>
<P>
   Chang was 17 when he became the youngest male Grand Slam
champion with his French Open victory in 1989. But he has yet to
win another Grand Slam title and now is down to No. 50 in the ATP
computer ranking, having slipped since an injury-plagued season
last year. Kafelnikov leads their series by 3-0, but the two have
never met on clay.
</P>
<P>
   The most anticipated early-round match in the women's draw might
occur in the second round, where top-ranked Martina Hingis could
face Amelie Mauresmo, the French player she beat the Australian
Open final earlier this year. Hingis later came under fire for
making what were considered anti-gay remarks about Mauresmo. When
the two played indoors in Paris a month later, the French crowd
loudly cheered as their countrywoman defeated Hingis in three sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a soccer match; it could have been France against
Brazil,'' Hingis said after the loss. ``They were incredible, even
if they were against me.''
</P>
<P>
   The matchup at Roland Garros could provide similar sparks, but
first Hingis has to get past face Amanda Hopmans of the Netherlands
while Mauresmo opens against Tara Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   The top half of the women's draw has Hingis, the Williams
sisters, Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario, the defending champion, and Jana
Novotna. Second-seeded Lindsay Davenport, who is overcoming a
left-wrist injury, anchors the lower half, along with former
champions Steffi Graf and Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams, winner of the German and Italian Open titles on
clay, opens against Alexandra Fusai of France but could face
Natasha Zvereva, a French Open finalist in 1988, in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-seeded Sanchez-Vicario will open against Mirjana
Lucic of Croatia, who has been slowed by injuries all year. Monica
Seles, a three-time champion and last year's finalist, has a
first-round match against China's Fang Li. Steffi Graf, who has
five French Open titles, will face Maggie Maleeva.
</P>
<P>
   In other first-round matchups, fourth-seeded Carlos Moya, the
defending men's champion, will face Markus Hipfl, an Austrian
playing in his first Grand Slam event. Also in Moya's section of
the draw are Thomas Muster, who won the 1995 French Open, and Andre
Agassi, a two-time finalist. Agassi, who is suffering from a
shoulder injury, opens against 39th-ranked Franco Squillari, who
won earlier this month at Munich and upset Moya at Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Second-ranked Pete Sampras, in search of the one Grand Slam
title he has not won, starts against Juan Antonio Marin, a
88th-ranked Costa Rican. The two have never played.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is in the same half of the draw with Pat Rafter, who
defeated him, 6-3, 7-5, Friday at the World Team Cup in Dusseldorf,
Germany. Rafter opens against 17-year-old Roger Federer, the junior
world champion from Switzerland. Federer is ranked only 114th but
defeated Moya earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
