<HEADLINE>
`MELROSE PLACE': TIME TO MOVE ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, May 24)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Melrose Place'' earned its stripes back in 1994, when it
brought Kimberly Shaw Mancini back from the dead. This neat
resurrection was a godsend to those of us who couldn't get enough
of the show's camp, poolside villainy. Sure, Heather Locklear's
Amanda thrilled us with her wicked ways, issuing divisive commands
without mussing her perfectly blow-dried hair. But Kimberly wasn't
just your run-of-the-mill bitch icon: She was a deranged,
hallucinating sicko who once won early graduation from a No More
Victims camp after breaking the sergeant's arm. What ``Melrose''
fan can forget the ne plus ultra of Kimberly scenes, when she
pulled off her wig to reveal a shaved head lined with a gruesome
scar?
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days. By 1996, ``Melrose Place'' had passed its
peak, and its best bad moments revolved around Lisa Rinna's sloppy,
I've-just-been-smacked lip job. The cheesy magic was gone for good,
and the show proceeded into a late '90s blur of generic pretty
faces and repetitive plot contortions. Once operatic in its wacky
melodrama, ``Melrose Place'' aged into a chaotic and pedestrian
effort that lost the power to build suspense from week to week.
After years of shameless toying with conventional soap themes such
as incest, infertility, alcoholism, adoption, and amnesia, the
``Melrose'' writers seemed to have no gall left in them.
</P>
<P>
   And so ``Melrose Place'' leaves the air after seven seasons
without a chorus of grief, the sort of viewer mourning that greets
the cancellation of beloved shows such as ``Homicide.'' After all,
most of us know that ``Melrose'' has been on life support for too
long now, and that it deserves to find peace in the graveyard of
dead series.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the finale, which Fox has been promoting for months,
promises to be worth watching. Not because all those specific
questions will be answered: Did Amanda beat Kent to death, as Eve
pictured in her hypnosis? Will Jane tell Kyle that she's pregnant?
Is Ryan's daughter dead? Are Peter and Amanda going to end up
together? No, the real attraction of the finale is finding out
whether the writers will dare to go over the top for old time's
sake _ an earthquake, perhaps (wouldn't it be fun to watch those
stucco courtyard walls come tumbling down?) or maybe the return of
Kimberly (again).
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to forget that Aaron Spelling's series began its life
as a dud, a stiff, issue-oriented cousin to another Spelling
production, ``Beverly Hills 90210.'' The idea was to pit a group of
shiny, happy twentysomethings against demons such as unemployment
and dating, but when the show failed to generate ratings for Fox,
the social realism was dumped in favor of conscience-free glitz.
Midway through the first season, Spelling drafted ``Dynasty'' alum
Locklear to spearhead the new approach, and we never looked back.
Locklear's power-hungry Amanda brought everyone into the moral
gutter with her, dividing and conquering Alison and Billy and then
Jo and Jake, who traded in his integrity to become her paramour.
Dutiful husband Michael Mancini was remade into a randy, adulterous
blackmailer, and Jane Mancini became temperamental enough to throw
the wedding china at him.
</P>
<P>
   Even the cliffhangers got garish, with Alison fleeing her own
wedding and Kimberly donning a blond Jane wig to run over Michael
in Jane's car. And it no longer mattered that most of the actors
were limited, most notably Andrew Shue and Locklear herself, whose
B-level technique is amusingly mediocre. During its best phase, the
object of ``Melrose Place'' was pure back-stabbing, hair-pulling,
death-defying fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
