<SLUG> BC-READINESS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MORE AIRCRAFT, PILOTS GROUNDED FOR LACK OF PARTS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the latest sign of declining military readiness,
a spare parts shortage is grounding more Air Force planes, which
are then cannibalized for parts to keep other aircraft in flying
condition, says a new government audit.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force's disabled list for major aircraft climbed to 13.9
percent last year, more than double the 6.4 percent listed as ``not
mission capable'' in 1990, according to a study released this week
by the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Grounded planes were, in turn, blamed for curtailing flight
training for pilots. Crews for B1-Bs and F-16s, for example,
reported they completed only 83 percent of training required to be
qualified as combat-ready last year.
</P>
<P>
   The review of more than a dozen Air Force installations provided
new details about a problem that has attracted growing attention on
Capitol Hill. Congress this week passed an emergency spending bill
for the Kosovo air war that includes $2.3 billion for spare parts,
maintenance and training.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO findings indicated that mismanagement was at the root of
the current repairs and maintenance problems. The report faulted
the Air Force for relying on efforts to streamline supply lines
that instead led to more logjams.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO also faults the Air Force Materiel Command at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base near Dayton, Ohio, for delays in
fixing broken parts. ``Although component part shortages have been
a longstanding and well-documented problem, the Air Force Materiel
Command has not yet developed an effective plan to correct the
problem,'' said the study. It said the command suffered from
shortages of both maintenance personnel and materials.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the facility, Dave Levingston, said Friday that
there would be no immediate reaction because top officials were
``involved in meetings keeping supplies flowing to Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Pentagon's response, Under Secretary of Defense William
J. Lynn concurred with the findings and said that a new study of
the problem was under way. ``The Air Force is already taking action
to improve its supply parts availability, `` he wrote, citing plans
to increase funds for the effort starting next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major conclusions of the study, Air Force maintenance
personnel were found to waste thousands of hours removing parts
from one aircraft to use in another. In the case of the B1-B, for
example, the average number of such ``cannibalizations'' was 96 for
every 100 sorties the plane flew last year.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the labor-intensive practice equated to
about 43 people working eight hours a day, five days a week for two
years at two Air Force commands, Langley Air Force Base, Va., and
Scott Air Force Base, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The report also traced a slowdown in repairs to disruptions as
the work was transferred from the San Antonio Air Logistics Center
in Texas to the Warner Robins Air Logistics Center in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
