<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6347 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MADABOUT-LADN     05-21 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MADABOUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REISER, HUNT LEAVING THE PARTY AFTER SEVEN SEASONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Runs with Sidebar slugged MADABOUT- FINALE ). 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Co-creator and co-star Paul Reiser pitched ``Mad
About You'' as having ``the feeling of ... a couple's car ride home
after a party, when you can finally say what you've been thinking
all night.'' It's been a long, strange trip from the show's debut
in 1992: The Buchmans have had fights, adventures and a baby. Now,
they're signing off after seven years on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we kept the show fresh was by keeping it fresh for us.
That, hopefully, keeps it exciting for the audience,'' Reiser said
in a phone interview to discuss the show's final episode, airing
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have complained that the show, once widely heralded
as inventive, has slid in quality during the past season. Reiser
and his co-star, Helen Hunt, defend the show. Reiser admitted that
being ``shuffled around'' in the NBC schedule probably has hurt the
show's ratings but insists that ``Mad'' has remained top-notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both of us feel the shows this year have been as good
or better than we've ever done. The finale is one of the best
things we've done,'' Reiser said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt chimed in that she felt the show had stayed creative
through its entire run. ``I hear on other shows, there are almost
Talmudic discussions about everything, every week,'' Hunt said.
``They're constantly asking themselves, `Is it emotionally true, is
it funny, is it risky?' These things have been there from the
beginning, without a break, for us.''
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of sheer uniqueness, the show's finale is certainly
a success (see accompanying story). The episode was written by
Reiser, Hunt and co-executive producer (with Reiser) Victor Levin;
the story is told in flashback, with the pivotal character of the
Buchmans' grown-up daughter played by comedic actress Janeane
Garofalo, who has never been on the show.
</P>
<P>
   The episode was directed by Hunt, who says she wouldn't be
surprised if not all viewers will react positively to it. ``Our
final episode is bold, it's risky, it's not what people will expect
or will have seen,'' said Hunt, who has become an Academy
Award-winning movie actress while the series has been on
television. ``But by definition, anything artful or risky (is going
to get mixed reaction). It just means you're trying something
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hunt and Reiser say they're looking forward to taking some
time off after seven years of TV work. ``I'd like to do a lot of
new stuff, but also do nothing for a while,'' Reiser said. ``I'm
looking forward to letting the creative well fill up a little bit
again. I'd like to write a couple of screenplays.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt says that after taking ``at least'' the summer off from
work, her long-term goal is to make films. ``I have a company
(Hunt-Tavel Productions, based at Sony) that's trying to make
movies that we love,'' Hunt said. ``I pray for good scripts to
direct, and for wonderful parts to come along.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress did get a great part in 1997's ``As Good as It
Gets,'' for which she won an Oscar as best actress. In fact, she
became the only woman to win both an Oscar and an Emmy in the same
year as best actress: She won the television award for best actress
in a comedy series in 1996, 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she says she'd also like to do some more directing as well
as acting _ though she's finding it harder than anticipated to find
the right projects. ``It's no easier trying to find a good script
you want to direct than it is to find good roles for women,'' Hunt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reiser, on the other hand, has no ambition to direct. ``Let me
tell you something about Paul,'' said Hunt, who has become close
friends with Reiser over the years. ``On one of our first days on
the set, Paul watched our director running around and said, `I
never want to do that.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've remained true to that conviction,'' cracked Reiser.
</P>
<P>
   Both say they'll miss the show. The people working on ``Mad''
have become ``like a family,'' said Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to any guest actor who's been on our show, they
would say, `Where's the yelling?'' said Hunt, describing the
production's collegial atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word got around that it was fun to work on our show,'' added
Reiser. ``I don't think people like Jerry Lewis and Yoko Ono had
done TV comedies before ... we got to work with incredible people.
I think everyone we needed and who's been on the show wanted to be
part of the finale.''
</P>
<P>
   Those stars include Carol Burnett, Tim Conway and Lyle Lovett,
who all returned for the show's final episode. Hunt describes the
last day on the set as sad, yet proud. ``We took time on the last
day to sob a lot and talk about what a great experience it's
been,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Both she and Reiser say they had a sense that they were ending
the show at the right time, after deciding last year to stay with
the show one more season. ``There's really no show we feel we
didn't get to do,'' Reiser said. ``You can't ask for more than
that. That's how you know it's time to close up shop.'' &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
