<HEADLINE>
WILL AUDIENCE BE MAD ABOUT FINAL EPISODE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ How do you write about an episode that's one big
surprise, that the stars say they haven't even told their families
the plot of?
</P>
<P>
   This much we can tell you: Janeane Garofalo plays the Buchmans'
daughter, Mabel, all grown up. She has followed in her father's
footsteps, becoming a filmmaker. She has issues with her upbringing
_ big, thorny issues.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you like ``Mad About You's'' final episode or not may
hinge largely on how much you like the caustic humor of Garofalo,
who has starred in such films as ``The Truth About Cats and Dogs''
and was a frequent guest on HBO's ``The Larry Sanders Show.'' She
comes across as grating for most of the hourlong episode, though in
the end, she and the story may win you over.
</P>
<P>
   The story is told in flashback, with several surprise
revelations of events that occurred in the lives of the characters
between the last regular episode and the 21st-century setting of
this show. Most of the scenes are very funny; a few fall flat.
</P>
<P>
   The final installment of the Buchman saga at least gives more of
a sense of completion than many final episodes, which have left the
future of their characters hanging. If you care about these
characters, it should leave you with a nice feeling. If you don't,
you may be left with the sense that the writers of the show tried
to throw a little bit of everything into the finale, resulting in
an episode that's a little too disjointed and an ending that's a
bit too pat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
