<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-IMPACT-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE WHO CAN LEAST AFFORD THE DAILY LOTTERY PLAY IT THE MOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Special Report)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By BRETT PULLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORANGE, N.J. _ Inside Home Dairy, a sliver of a store that sells
candy, cigarettes and newspapers, people mill around all day
searching for phantom riches: writing down numbers and scratching
tickets in a nonstop frenzy that amounts to $14,400 in average
weekly lottery sales.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the store's name, only a few cartons of milk are sold
each day. More customers come looking for ``dream books,'' which
sell for $3 to $5 and offer advice on what lottery numbers should
be associated with a dream or daily occurrence. If a person dreams
about a cat, one book advises, the number to play is 114. If the
cat is black, the number is 244. And if a person buys a hat, the
book recommends 815 or 816.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the store one evening, Dennis Dutton, a 36-year-old
custodian who bets on numbers every day, explained how important a
lottery jackpot was to his financial planning. Throughout the
month, Dutton said, he intended to bet $15 each day on the number
898. At the time, his telephone was disconnected and he was hoping
that hitting the number _ for winnings of about $2,750 _ would help
pay his bills. ``I wish that 898 would come out,`` he said,
``because it would solve all my problems.'' (It did not.)
</P>
<P>
   In this working-class neighborhood, 18 miles west of Manhattan,
as in similar areas across the country, the state-sponsored daily
lottery is becoming so deeply woven into so many lives that it is a
part of the social fabric. It is a ritual as routine as watching
the nightly news, a practice far more common than voting.
</P>
<P>
   With lottery machines as prevalent as cash registers in the 38
states with lotteries, instant-win tickets hanging behind store
counters everywhere, and $35 billion bet each year across the
country, the most prevalent purveyor of betting games in America is
no longer the street corner sports bookmaker or the Las Vegas
casino operator.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is the state governments _ the same entities that
for years outlawed gambling _ that are now leading the way in
building widespread acceptance of gambling across the country. The
impact that state lotteries are having on communities around the
country has also been a major focus of the National Gambling Impact
Study Commission, which was appointed in 1996 by President Clinton
and Congress to examine the social and economic consequences of
legalized gambling in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which in June is scheduled to release a report
of its two-year-long study, is expected to recommend that state
lotteries curtail their advertising in economically distressed
communities and that they be required to contribute some of their
revenues to research and treatment for problem gambling.
</P>
<P>
   It is in communities like Orange where the lottery is a dominant
force and many poor and modest wage earners are devoted to an
endless search for winning numbers and an unswerving belief that a
jackpot waits for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Players: The Best Customers Can Least Afford It
</P>
<P>
   A close look at Orange, and a New York Times computer analysis
of lottery playing in New Jersey, provide a compelling picture of
just how vital the people who live and work in neighborhoods like
this one are to the lottery business.
</P>
<P>
   Far more than previously known, modest-wage earners, the poor
and less educated people spend a greater percentage of their income
on the lottery than do wealthier residents of the state, the Times
analysis found.
</P>
<P>
   Using 1998 New Jersey lottery data, the analysis found that in
the zip codes where people with the lowest incomes live, the amount
spent per $10,000 of income on lottery tickets was more than five
times the amount spent on tickets by people who live in wealthier
zip codes. The analysis was calculated from information on 48,875
lottery winners and estimates based on census data.
</P>
<P>
   It found that for a chance to cash in on an instant-win scratch
ticket, people living in the 100 lowest average-income zip codes in
New Jersey spent $53 per $10,000 of their earnings. But in the 100
zip codes with the highest-average income, spending on instant-win
tickets was just $12 per $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   And for the Pick 4 game, which can pay as much as $2,788 for a
50-cent bet on the correct four numbers, and is one of the state's
most popular games, people in the 100 lowest-income zip codes spent
$29 per $10,000 income, compared with $5 per $10,000 income in the
100 highest-income zip codes, according to the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, people who are less educated also spend far more
money playing the lottery. In the zip codes with the lowest
percentage of people with college educations, people spent more
than five times as much per $10,000 of income than those in areas
with the highest proportion of college-educated population.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis is consistent with those in other states that have
shown that as a percentage of household income, poorer people in
cities and rural areas alike, spend much more on the lottery than
do people in high-income brackets. Caught in a perpetual state of
living from paycheck to paycheck, they are easily captured by the
notion that the lottery can fulfill their basic financial goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Justification: Little Return Seen in Education Funds
</P>
<P>
   ``The lottery's best customers,'' said Scott Harshbarger, former
attorney general of Massachusetts and a critic of state lotteries,
``are those who can least afford to throw their money away.''
</P>
<P>
   And while these customers put far more money into the lottery,
there is little evidence that they get more back.
</P>
<P>
   The spread of the lottery across the country was propelled
largely by the politically palatable promise to use the proceeds to
help finance education. People might lose their money, the
reasoning went, but they can feel all right about it knowing that
its going to a good cause.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, as in many states, however, the proceeds from the
lottery go to the state treasurer. Although those lottery dollars
are indeed used to augment educational spending, studies have shown
that lotteries have not increased the net amount spent on education
but have only given the states a larger pool from which to allocate
those funds. And areas of the state where large percentages of
lottery revenues are generated do not receive a proportional amount
of state aid in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the money we spend on the lottery,'' said Orange's
mayor, Mimms Hackett, Jr., ``I think we would be in much better
shape if it was equated with the amount we get from the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou Murphy, a spokeswoman for the New Jersey Department of
Taxation, said that although the games may take a larger proportion
of income from poorer people, playing is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state does not ursurp rights and privileges based on
economic status,'' Ms. Murphy said. ``Their chances of winning may
not be very good, but it's an exciting thing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Numbers: So Many Chances, So Many Ways
</P>
<P>
   The statistics come to life here in Orange, where up and down
Main Street and all along the thoroughfares that intersect the
city's thriving business district, the state lottery's familiar
green and yellow four-leaf clover logo is pasted on windows.
</P>
<P>
   On some days, a local storefront psychic adviser hangs a sign
out offering ``lucky numbers.'' And each day inside a check-cashing
store, customers line up in front of one teller to cash their
payroll and Social Security checks, then move a few steps to
another teller to buy instant scratch tickets and daily lottery
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   With its ubiquitous advertisements and tickets on sale all
around them, the lottery is always right there _ whispering in
their ears, reminding them that it only takes one lucky drawing to
finance their retirement, cover college expenses for their
children, or buy the house they have always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You notice in urban areas, there are a lot of people who have
not made it to the top by a certain age,'' Mayor Hackett said.
``The lottery becomes the only outlet for that dream. Success for a
lot of people is predicated on hitting the number.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers underscore the significant role that the lottery
plays in Orange. Throughout New Jersey, where the median household
income is $55,209, there are 8.1 million residents and 6,000
lottery outlets _ about one lottery machine for every 1,350
residents.
</P>
<P>
   But in Orange, where the median household income is $37,529,
there are 30,000 residents and 33 stores selling lottery tickets,
or about one machine for every 909 residents. And while weekly per
capita lottery sales are $3.92 statewide, they are $6.87 in Orange.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of about 30,000 that is 70 percent black, 20
percent white and 10 percent Hispanic, the City of Orange Township,
as this urban-suburban municipality is formally named, has homes
that range from old, well-kept mansions to aging two-family frame
houses and daunting public housing complexes. Bus drivers, office
workers, nurses, police officers and janitors are among those who
regularly line up for lottery tickets here.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the nightly three-digit and four-digit drawings
that are held seven days a week, residents buy tickets for a
five-digit drawing that is held three days a week, a six-digit
drawing held twice a week, and a once-weekly matching game with 21
sets of four numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But even more popular are the dozens of types of colorful
instant lottery tickets, which sell so briskly that lottery
officials have begun placing them in automatic vending machines,
and marketing them as special occasion gifts _ with names like
``Happy Birthday'' and ``Merry Money'' _ and decorative envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   At the Majestic Barber Shop, where the haircuts cost $10, all
three barbers play the numbers every day. In between customers,
Hilliard Kelly runs down to the corner deli to buy instant tickets.
At $1 to $2 each, Kelly buys about four instant tickets a day and
spends about $10 on the daily number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come out behind,'' he said, sitting in his barber chair,
using a coin to scratch a ticket called ``50 Grand.'' (It was a
loser.) ``But I keep going back. Once you get used to playing those
rub-offs, it's hard to walk in a store with money in your pocket
and not buy one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Players: A Way of Life For One Couple
</P>
<P>
   Among the many people who play every day are Emmett and Mary
Newsome. A full-time local bus driver by night, Mrs. Newsome spends
her days operating the Top Chef restaurant, serving takeout soul
food like pork chops smothered in gravy, collard greens and peach
cobbler and sweet potato pie.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Newsome has played the lottery for more than 20 years,
spending about $12 a day all week to play numbers that correspond
with family members' birthdays, home addresses or whatever might
catch her attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play the lottery all the time,'' she said, standing behind
the counter of the sparsely adorned restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has never tallied her total losses against her
winnings, she said she believed she had come out ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like the lottery,'' she said proudly. ``You
can always make a little money from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Newsome is now seeking something that she is certain will
increase her business: a lottery machine. She has applied to the
state to become a ticket agent, and her application is pending.
Agents receive 5 percent of their ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get my own lottery machine,'' she said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Newsome, who works at a nearby powder-coating plant, applying
protective coatings to metal products, has developed his own system
of tracking past winning numbers to determine patterns. In a ritual
that is performed in the family's house each morning, Newsome rises
at 4:30 a.m., puts on his robe and walks downstairs to the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   After turning on a pot of water for his instant coffee, he sits
at the table and in front of him he places several memo pads and
worn file cards that have hundreds of three-digit numbers written
on them.
</P>
<P>
   Painstakingly, Newsome creates charts based on factors like
which lottery hostess on television picks the numbers on which day
of the week. (A lottery drawing is held every day except Christmas
in New Jersey.) Although the drawing is totally random, Newsome is
convinced that there is a pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see here that 994 has come out three times on Sunday,'' he
said as he sat down to make his selections one recent Sunday
morning. Lighting up a Marlboro 100 and scooping four heaping
tablespoons of sugar into a large mug of coffee, he predicted, ``I
think that 994 is going to come back today.'' (It did not.) Based
on the information Newsome compiles each morning, he writes down
his 20 favorite numbers for the day, and leaves a copy on the table
for his wife. She decides which ones she will play.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tally how much the Newsomes spend or win, because
in addition to the game itself, there is a little gamesmanship
between the two. A couple of months ago, Mrs. Newsome played one of
the numbers her husband had suggested and she won more than $300.
When Newsome asked her whether she had played it, she told him she
had not. ``I know he's hitting a lot of times and ain't saying
nothing to me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, according to Newsome's day planner, the couple won on
four consecutive days, for a total of more than $1,000. ``That was
a good week,'' Newsome said. But throughout most of two months
early this year, the Newsomes were playing every day and were not
having any luck.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of one month, Newsome was growing anxious. ``We
could sure use the money,'' he said one evening as he walked up to
the counter at Home Dairy and played 172, 578, 198, and 574. (They
were all losers; the winning three-digit number that evening was
416.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
