<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6354 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTERYIMPACT-3RDTAKE     05-21 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY </SLUG>
 IMPACT-3RDTAKE-NYT  
 ORANGE: was 416.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Suspicions: Black Winners, White Winners
</P>
<P>
   Despite their daily devotion to the lottery, a large number of
the people who play numbers in this city say they believe that the
state lottery is rigged. While they have no proof, they constantly
complain that most winners of big Pick 6 Lotto jackpots come from
areas of the state that are predominantly white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time when I win on rub-offs,'' said Kelly, the
barber, ``I bought my ticket from a white neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia E. Haines, executive director of the New Jersey state
lottery, sighs with frustration when she hears of such suspicions.
Everywhere Ms. Haines goes in the state, she said in an interview
at her Trenton office, people complain that the big winners never
come from their own region.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, statistics show that the number of big winners from a
particular region is commensurate with the number of tickets sold
in that region. For example, Essex and Hudson counties are among
the those with the highest amount of lottery sales in the state.
And since 1996, the two counties are tied for the most of Pick 6
Lotto winners, at 14 each.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Ms. Haines said, the Lotto numbers are selected
randomly, and the instant tickets are dispersed in a manner
assuring that the winning tickets are randomly distributed. Still,
even among the most experienced lottery players, the criticism
persists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't put the Lotto winners in the black areas and they
can't convince me otherwise,'' Myra Russell asserted, speaking of
the ``quick picks,'' in which a player lets a computer select the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ms. Russell, who lives in Orange, has played the
New Jersey lottery since it became computerized in 1975. Back then,
she worked at an Orange liquor store, operating the lottery machine
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started with them and I know,'' she said as she bought her
daily tickets inside a local check-cashing store. ``To me, the New
Jersey lottery is a big joke,'' she snapped _ all the while
stuffing her tickets into her pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Although modern-day lotteries have been legal in New Jersey for
just 29 years, people in and around Orange were betting on illegal
lotteries long before that. As in many poor and working-class
cities around the country, the illegal numbers, which were known as
policy, had flourished for decades. People could play for pennies
and the daily three-digit number was determined by the total amount
of money bet at a specified horse racetrack that day.
</P>
<P>
   Until white residents began moving out in the 1970s, Orange was
largely populated by working-class people of Italian and Irish
descent, and John J. Kunz, a native of Orange and the general
manager of Town Check Cashing, said, ``Everybody played the
number.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jackpot: One City Awaits A Big Winner
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou Williams, who operates the lottery machine at Town
Check Cashing and formerly owned Home Dairy, said many of her
customers had been buying lottery tickets from her for more than
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have a lot of fun selling tickets,'' Ms. Williams
said. ``Now it's much more serious. People are determined they're
going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams does not make as much money from lottery sales as
she once did because there are too many ticket outlets in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays I'm like a spider in a web,'' she said. ``There's one
on every corner.''
</P>
<P>
   While there may be plenty of places to play the lottery in this
city, finding someone who has actually won a big jackpot is not as
easy. When asked whether they could provide any big winners from
Orange, lottery officials said they had winners in surrounding
areas, but none who had actually bought their tickets in Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Photocopies of winning tickets are prominently displayed above
the counter at Home Dairy, but based on the serial numbers on the
winning tickets, they were sold at stores elsewhere in the state.
</P>
<P>
   One recent evening, Stanley Micheaux, 69, who uses part of his
twice-monthly disability payments to play the numbers each day,
gazed skeptically at the winners pasted up inside Home Dairy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, how long have those things been up there?'' Micheaux
asked. ``They make us think we're going to win, but we ain't going
to win a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hopes: A Possible Jackpot Is Always Present
</P>
<P>
   When Emmett Newsome pulls his number-covered file cards from his
wallet, the first thing a person notices is the dirt on the cards,
and then his hands. The skin is dry and cracked, his fingertips are
covered with a greasy film.
</P>
<P>
   They are the hands of a man who labors for a living, and
Newsome, who is 54, hopes that one day he will win a big lottery
jackpot and be able to wash his hands of the more than 20 years he
has worked at metal-coating plants.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the tough Howard Street area of Newark, he has been
involved in the daily numbers since he was a young boy working as a
``runner,'' picking up betting slips for his ``Uncle Soldier,'' who
ran an illegal numbers racket.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Newsome, 51, has been a bus driver for New Jersey Transit
for 20 years, and whether the couple win a big lottery prize or
not, she plans for them eventually to retire from their jobs, sell
the restaurant and move to her native South Carolina. Her only
misgiving about returning to South Carolina is that the state has
no lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame they don't have a lottery because people need to
have some way to try to make a little extra money,'' Mrs. Newsome
said.
</P>
<P>
   [On April 7, however, legislation in South Carolina moved a step
closer to allowing voters to decide in 2000 on whether to establish
a lottery.)
</P>
<P>
   The couple's 15-year-old daughter, Monique, struggles to
understand her parents' obsession with the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I know that sometimes you win, but you also lose,''
she said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
