A6361 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ORCHARD-FASHION-AR     05-21 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ORCHARD-FASHION-ART-$ADV23-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER PUSHCARTS COMES A CATWALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 23)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID COLMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What was the woman in the lime-green and gray suit,
with shoulders sharp enough to poke an eye out, doing in the middle
of Orchard Street?
</P>
<P>
   The suit came from Marcesa, one of the traditional ``I can get
it for you wholesale'' stores on Orchard. But what about the 1,000
Lower East Side young people, in leather, creative facial hair and
tinted sunglasses, who were hooting and hollering at the woman, who
looked like a long-lost daughter of the Carringtons from
``Dynasty''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, she was a fashion model; Orchard Street had been
temporarily fitted with an elevated catwalk, and the garish green
power suit was the tartly affectionate statement of Ben Sturgill, a
participant in the Orchard Street Style Slam last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He and five other stylists who work for avant-garde fashion
magazines like Purple, Surface and Nylon had been challenged to
pick clothes from Orchard Street shops _ both traditional
discounters like Ja-Mil Uniform and Colette Fashion and hip
newcomers _ and to show their looks in the street, before a crowd
responding in the boisterous style of a poetry slam. The unusual
fashion show was the brainchild of Erica Lively, whose Timtoum
store on Orchard, opened in 1997, sells skateboard clothes and
vinyl records. Her goal was to raise awareness of Orchard Street as
a shopping district.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense that the neighborhood is picking itself up by
its bootstraps,'' said Matthew Bauer, the executive director of the
Lower East Side Business Improvement District. ``There's a whole
smorgasbord of shops down here, and I'll tell you, each business
feeds into the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lively, a member of the business improvement district, whose
store is between the older vendors south of Stanton Street and the
modish invaders to the north as far as Houston Street, is a kind of
den mother to the newcomers. They, for their part, have given the
neighborhood a tourist-friendly name in the style of SoHo and
TriBeCa: LuStO, for Ludlow, Stanton and Orchard Streets. Beyond the
racks of T-shirts, baseball hats, fake Prada handbags and leather
coats crowding the sidewalks on Sundays, Orchard Street is now home
to more than a dozen stores showcasing the work of young designers
and vintage clothes at one-third of what such things cost in SoHo.
Xuly Bet, an outpost of a French company, sells shredded Goth
clothing; Cherry specializes in vintage mod wear; Shine has
beautiful vintage evening clothes, and TG-170 has crocheted tops,
straw bags and other must-haves for the Pier 40-meets-Aruba look.
</P>
<P>
   The Style Slam, presented for the second year, was right on top
of a current wave in fashion, the flirtation with notions of value
and cheapness, with polyester fabrics, thrift-shop styles and plain
uniform motifs, all of which have shown up on high-fashion runways.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the 40 stores participating were traditional
neighborhood merchants, which have been bargain hunters'
destinations for years, including Ben Freedman Men's Wear and
Beckenstein's Fabrics. The organizers persuaded them to lend
clothes of the stylists' choosing, though this wasn't always easy.
``It was pretty hard explaining to them what a stylist is,'' said
Karen Levitt, a slam organizer and one of the stylists.
</P>
<P>
   Stylists, for the record, are fashion's foot soldiers, who pull
together accessories, props and the clothes for a magazine shoot or
a designer's runway show. ``They really don't get enough credit for
what they do,'' Ms. Lively said. ``If they want to do blue lips on
a shoot, and the shoot's not about that, then it's no blue lips.''
</P>
<P>
   But last Sunday, stylists' day out, the lips were any color you
like. There were skirts worn as ponchos and wedding dresses made
from the pages of a journal. Diana Oberlander, who showed this
look, explained that her journal pages represented ``the expression
of self,'' and the paper represented ``the temporality of trends.''
The crowd was unimpressed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   It was far more vocal for Sturgill, responding with wolf calls
to an elaborate black, lacy top from Marcesa, worn with the
shortest of jean cutoffs. ``Daisy Duke chic,'' the stylist called
it.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Sturgill's inventive creations was a billowy mauve
flower-print top inspired by a hair scrunchy, one of those
elasticized bands for holding a pony tail, which he bought from a
local discounter.
</P>
<P>
   Sturgill turned out to be one of only two stylists who married
clothes from the old and new Orchard Street shops. Most of the
others simply picked through the newer emporiums, with results that
predictably failed to arouse the crowd, many of whom outshone the
models as sharp dressers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levitt did not use much clothing from the older stores, but
her cunningly contrived, Halston-meets-``Phantom Menace'' looks
were sensuous and dark. Ryan Colby, who showed a series of bland
shirt-and-pants men's wear from the new stores, made it seem as if
he had simply popped into Club Monaco for some trendy basics on his
way to the Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not very creative at all,'' sniffed Francoise
Stevelinck, a Belgian tourist, watching the show with her husband.
She added diplomatically, ``Men's wear is so much harder than
women's.''
</P>
<P>
   The Style Slam was not supposed to be a competition, with a
winner crowned by the crowd's applause. But had it been, there's no
doubt that first prize would have gone to Lisa Von Weise, the last
stylist to show. Her models came out prancing, not stalking or
sauntering, to the energetic, electronic beat of a friend's band,
Fischer Spooner.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes were comically ghoulish, in a nod to ``The Rocky
Horror Picture Show.'' The star was the band's lead singer, Casey
Spooner, his dark pants hanging off his hips, the better to see his
red vinyl briefs.
</P>
<P>
   The audience was united in catcalls and enthusiastic applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to be competitive,'' Ms. Von Weise said later.
``I'm glad people seemed to like it. I just knew when they asked me
to do it that the only way was to make it like performance art.
Otherwise it would just be boring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the last one,'' said an audience member in a recycled
mink tank top, who would identify himself only as KAI. ``It was
cool, strong, exciting, scary and fun. The rest bored me.'' KAI,
who had participated as a stylist in the event last year, described
his profession as ``fashionista.'' Asked to elaborate, he said, ``I
am a stylist, a designer and an architect.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the more conventionally employed denizens of Orchard
Street, most said they were glad to see the crowd in the
neighborhood and hoped it would lead to more sales. They were
careful in their assessment of the fashions presented.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Chen, who watched the event from the doorway of her store,
Fashion and Fashion, which sells the sort of pastel women's wear
that would be irreproachable at a Parent-Teacher Association
meeting, said: ``It was OK The clothes were ...'' Her voice trailed
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interesting,'' she added, breaking into a broad smile. ``And
fashion is what I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
