<P>
   GEORGIA SCHOOL SHOOTINGSHOOT-MAIN _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Main folo
from the courts, cops, hospital and families and students on
Thursday's Conyers, Ga., school shooting that left six students
wounded. This will wrap up the loose ends from Thursday. If suspect
gets a lawyer, etc. (Staff/Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SHOOT-PERP _ CONYERS, Ga. _ More on the suspect. Attitude in
neighborhood about suspect, about media attention and cops
searching the house down the street. Can we find a minister or
other confidant who has talked to parents or suspect since
shooting? (McDonald/Simpson/Sanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHOOT-LAW _ CONYERS, Ga. _ The legal outlook for the 15-year-old
suspect. Does he have a lawyer trying to keep the case in juvenile
court? Does defendant even have a say in that, or is it all up to
DA and judge? What are the range of charges available in this case
or cases like it? What's criteria for move to adult court? What are
maximum penalties in adult vs. juvenile? (Croft/McDonald, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHOOT-HEROES _ CONYERS, Ga. _ More on assistant principal,
teachers (maybe a dad) who talked the suspect into surrendering).
Recreate the scene. (Stafford/Towns, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHOOT-BARR _ Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) says guns are being made a
scapegoat and Republicans are caving in. He's calling for hearings
into whether gun laws already on the books are being enforced.
(Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICTKOSOVO-INTERNET _ TIRANA, Albania _ An
internet cafe has opened in Tirana in the midst of Europe's worst
humanitarian and military crisis since World War II, and it has
become a favorite spot for foreigners who need a fix they can only
get from the Web. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved in both International and Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEE _ Kelmend Hapciu is an ethnic Albanian refugee
from Pristina who has been living and working in Dayton _ very
quietly _ for the past three months. Although 15 members of his
immediate family are here, many other relatives and friends remain
in the Kosovo region and he fears for their safety. Hapciu talks
about the bombing, the possible settlement, the plight of the
refugees, etc. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTONCUBA-JURAGUA _ MIAMI _Cuba and Russia have announced a
deal to resume construction of the long-stalled Juragua nuclear
power plant in Cuba, reviving U.S. concerns over safety. Pentagon
officials already have shelled out $2 million this year to
establish several radiation-monitoring stations around Florida in
case Juragua is finished and has an accident. But many experts,
including a University of Georgia professor writing a book about
the Juragua project, say the two countries simply don't have the
money needed to complete the project. They say the project is
almost beyond the point of rescue. (Emling, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   JURAGUA-TIMELINE _ A timeline of the troubled Juaragua nuclear
plant. (Emling, Cox News Service). 6.
</P>
<P>
   READINESS _ WASHINGTON _ In the latest sign of declining
military readiness, a new government study says that a lack of
spare parts has grounded planes and cost $64 million for the
labor-intensive work of cannibalizing parts from other aircraft.
Pilots are flying only 83 percent of their required training hours.
The General Accounting Office reviewed more than a dozen bases,
including Wright-Patterson, Warner Robins, Moody and Dyess.
(Malone, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RECORDS _ ATLANTA _ Concern over the open records issue is
hitting the state university system, propelled by the board of
regents who are warning university foundations that their donor
lists are subject to inspection under the new Open Records Act. The
regents fear that if donor lists are made public, people will be
disinclined to donate. Trying to determine if this is related to
open records battle between GAAF and AJC. (Turner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE _ Janice Holyfield testified Friday that she
and her estranged husband, heavyweight champ Evander Holyfield,
have had sexual relations four times since he filed for divorce two
months ago. But a Fayette County Superior Court judge says that not
reason enough to dismiss the divorce action. The champ, by the way,
says he can't remember. Also coming out of today's hearing were a
few details about the couple's finances. Her lawyer says they spend
half a million bucks a month. (Ellis, Atlanta Joural-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   FASTRAIN _ Announcement expected Monday on magnetic levitation
train projects to get funding from the federal government. Atlanta
is among the cities to get money. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PRAY _ The federal appeals court ruling this week against
student-led ``messages'' at graduation in Jacksonville, Fla., flies
in the face of growing public sentiment for greater moral emphasis
in schools threatened by student violence, say some First Amendment
experts. Atlanta's 11th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the
messages are unconstitutional attempts to sanction school prayer,
but officials in the sprawling Jacksonville district seem
determined to keep up their fight. We use their decision to take
the case to the U.S. Supreme Court as a peg for a close look at the
current status of the school prayer issue, which continues to crop
up in districts across the country. (MWilliams, Atanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GA-GOP _ Story on first day of GOP state convention in Augusta.
Includes background on state of the Georgia party as well as
afternoon appearances/speeches by outgoing chairman Rusty Paul and
presidential contenders Lamar Alexander and Gary Baur. Newt
Gingrich speaks about 8 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Story will move as soon as possible after Gingrich speaks.
</P>
<P>
   POW-GONZALEZ-VISIT _ Former POW Stephen Gonzalez is expected to
visit the Legislature today to continue his hero's welcome tour
after being (backslash)released by the Yugoslavian army. If we get
a chance, we'll ask if he sees any irony in this adulation for
doing something wrong in the first place. (Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   LOTTO _ A problem you'd love to have _ not getting your Florida
Lottery winnings in a lump sum _ isn't really a problem anymore.
Gov. Jeb Bush signed a bill last week making Florida the 19th state
to allow lottery winners the option of selling suture earnings to
third-party investors for the entire jackpot in cash. (Owers, Palm
Beach Post).
</P>
