A6379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITTANIA-BOOKDEAL-NY     05-21 0265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITTANIA-BOOKDEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIAN SIMON SCHAMA WILL PUBLISH `BRITTANIA' WITH TALK MIRAMAX
BOOKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The historian Simon Schama has signed a deal to publish his next
work of nonfiction with Talk Miramax Books, a division of Talk
Media, which is owned by Miramax Films. The book, titled
``Brittania,'' will be a history of Britain from the time before
the Roman invasion to the year 2000, and it will accompany a
12-part BBC series, directed by Schama, that ABC will broadcast in
the fall of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Talk Media is the publishing group founded by Tina Brown, the
former editor of The New Yorker magazine; the group, in partnership
with Hearst Magazines, will also publish Talk Magazine. The first
issue of the magazine is scheduled to appear on newsstands in
August of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of the book and its publication in conjunction
with an ABC series _ as well as being excerpted in the pages of the
magazine _ point to the ways that collaboration might take place
among the various arms of the Walt Disney Co., which owns both ABC
and Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Burnham, the editor in chief of Talk Miramax Books, has
acquired four book projects to date, including two novels by
Christopher Rice, the son of the novelist Anne Rice, and a book of
photographs and memoirs acquired from the estate of Charlie
Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   Schama, a professor at Columbia University, is the author of
``The Embarrassment of Riches,'' ``Citizens'' and ``Landscape and
Memory.'' His biography of Rembrandt will be published by Knopf
this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
