<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     05-21 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COMPUTER AGE, STATES STICK WITH PAPER TRAIL ON CAMPAIGN
SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN AND CARL HULSE   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With campaign finance reform stalled on Capitol
Hill, one respected watchdog group is pushing states to bring their
own disclosure requirements into the electronic age.
</P>
<P>
   They have a way to go. A report by the Center For Responsive
Politics found that only a handful of states have comprehensive
online campaign finance information available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians of all ideologies pay lip service to the idea of
disclosure,'' said Paul Hendrie, a spokesman for the group. ``The
key to disclosure is timeliness and accessibility to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   If federal lawmakers aren't going to set limits on campaign
spending, Hendrie said it's even more important for states to step
up and help the public understand the political money chase. The
center wants candidates to file campaign information electronically
and then have states post that data on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens can already look at paper campaign reports for
statewide candidates at individual election offices in each state.
But Hendrie said that process is time-consuming and can be
intimidating. Some states, including Florida, require state
candidates to file campaign reports electronically and that
information is then available to the public on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida's been a real pioneer in this area,'' Hendrie.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana also has an electronic filing system, but it is not as
comprehensive. Alabama, South Carolina and Georgia are among dozens
of others lacking any sort of electronic filing system for
candidates. North Carolina is about to implement such a system this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Although federal candidates for Congress file their reports with
the Federal Election Commission in Washington, Hendrie encouraged
state election offices to make that information available on their
own Web sites as well. He noted that the lines are increasingly
blurred between federal and state spending.
</P>
<P>
   GORING GORE
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it seems, Republicans have discovered Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   GOP lawmakers in Congress have become increasingly critical of
the vice president, setting their sights on the Democrats' leading
candidate for president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Rep. Jim DeMint, a freshman Republican from South
Carolina, felt compelled to comment on Gore's recent speech in
Iowa, one where the vice president talked about the importance of
parental involvement, discipline and character in schools.
</P>
<P>
   While the lawmaker applauded some of what Gore said, DeMint
complained the vice president was trying to manage local schools
from Washington. ``His speech used the word `require' four times
more than the word `local,''' DeMint complained.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also ridiculed Gore for his efforts to spend $30
million on a NASA program to take continuous pictures of the earth
and post them on the Internet. They killed that proposal in a
recent vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can already turn on my television and see pictures of earth
from space for free,'' said Texas Rep. Dick Armey, who delighted in
mocking Gore's idea.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS AND POSES
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the Senate were running around in circles over a
series of votes on gun control, reversing themselves at times and
bungling efforts to cast Democrats as zealots.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Southerners in that body, however, showed a remarkable
consistency, rejecting gun-control amendments despite the growing
alarm over gun shootings in schools.
</P>
<P>
   With rare exception, Southern Republicans opposed locks on
handguns. Supporters, who included Republican Strom Thurmond of
South Carolina, described that amendment as a win for child safety.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond joined his Dixie brethren, however, in rejecting
background checks for all firearms transactions at gun shows and
pawn shops, an amendment that ultimately passed with the dramatic
tiebreaking vote of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., spoke for many of his colleagues
when he denounced the amendment as ``an attempt to discourage
law-abiding Americans from owning and purchasing firearms.'' He
called on Congress to crack down on criminals instead.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE'S CLUES
</P>
<P>
   Those blue paws on the World Wide Web don't necessarily belong
to the dog from the popular children's television show; they also
symbolize the Blue Dog coalition, the group of centrist and
conservative Democrats trying to influence congressional policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Dogs just went light speed, launching a Web site to
promote their ideas and let voters get a look at their proposals on
such issues as the budget and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue Dogs are in a very influential position this year
because of the narrow margin between the parties in the House and
we see this Web site as an important tool in helping shape the
agenda,'' said Rep. Bud Cramer, D-Ala., a leader of the group that
counts many Southern Democrats among its members.
</P>
<P>
   The Web address is www.house.gov/john/bluedog for those who want
to visit the electronic dog house.
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
