<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAMPTONS-CELEBS-LAND-     05-21 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMPTONS-CELEBS-LAND-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARD IN HAMPTONS: `THE EARTH MOVED'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the beginning, God created the heaven and the
earth, and the earth was without form ...
</P>
<P>
   To which certain Hamptonites are taking the attitude, ``No
problem!''
</P>
<P>
   All over the South Fork, they are preparing for the summer
season by marshalling an army of front-end loaders, bulldozers and
dump trucks. They're pursuing the area's latest trend: transforming
the area's generally flat topography into rolling hills, ridges and
ponds, in some cases landscapes more typical of an estate in
Greenwich, Conn. or New Jersey hunt country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year it's all about moving the earth,'' said Edwina von
Gal, a landscape designer who is working on more than 15 projects
in the Hamptons that involve sculpturing lawns, heaping up hillocks
and creating levels of terraces on previously flat properties.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the designer Helmut Lang closed on a $15.5
million property on the ocean in East Hampton (outbidding Jerry
Seinfeld, who also wanted it), and within 72 hours the earth movers
were on the site, transforming a flat yard into hillocks meant to
resemble sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is a concept of continuing the dunescape into
the landscape,'' said Lang's landscaper, David Seeler, the owner of
Bayberry Nursery in Amagansett. ``Which means taking what you see
in the natural dune area and bringing it forward into the landscape
of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   The sand dunes that lead from the beach to Lang's door are
covered with rose hips, beach grass and other natural flora. The
dunelike hills he is creating in his back yard will be covered with
sod.
</P>
<P>
   Just down the beach, Christopher H. Browne, the president of the
Tweedy, Browne, the mutual-fund company, recently bought 18 acres
of virgin woodland and began mapping out locations for manmade
hills and ponds. He did this even before beginning the design of
the buildings he plans, which include a main house, pool house and
guest cottage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to stick a house in the middle of a flat field,''
Browne said. ``I want elevation. I want some sort of life in that
flat field.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne, who grew up near Far Hills, N.J., said he loved the
rolling contour of the landscape in the Jersey hunt country, and
wanted to duplicate it on Long Island, which was rendered mostly
flat by glaciers in the last Ice Age about 11,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Browne's new property is not his first venture into
earth-sculpuring. In 1989, he bought eight and a half acres of flat
field from Jann Wenner, the founder of Rolling Stone, on Middle
Lane in East Hampton, and slowly turned it into a wooded, hilly
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Today the property has two man-made ponds, hundreds of mature
specimen trees, including weeping willows, dawn redwoods and cherry
trees and, and an assortment of gently sloping hills and grades. It
is a far cry from the potato fields with their long rows of humble
green plants that typify the native Hamptons landscape, long in
retreat before development.
</P>
<P>
   Although Browne spent half a dozen years developing his acreage,
his house _ a sand-yellow stucco manor in a pre-World War II style
_ was built only three years ago. He plans to sell the property
once his current estate is complete and he moves into the more
desirable, beachfront location.
</P>
<P>
   The architect Richard Meier, assisted by Ms. von Gal, turned the
flat overgrown lawn around his East Hampton house into a sea of
grass-covered hillocks. Influenced by the work of Arthur Edwin Bye
Jr. a landscape architect known for contouring hills to enhance the
play of sun and shadow, Meier did most of the earth moving himself
on a bulldozer.
</P>
<P>
   Best known as the architect of the Getty Center in Los Angeles,
he shaped his lawn a few years back, and so was ahead of the
current trend.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more recent converts are not as hands-on as he _ nor
as patient. ``They come out here, they buy a two-acre potato field
for a couple of million dollars, and within two weeks they want
rolling hills, contoured land and maybe a pond,'' said Seeler, who
has been in the landscape business for 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they write the check, it's the Hamptons, it can be done,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Modest earth-rearranging plus a small pond on that hypothetical
two-acre parcel will cost about $200,000, Seeler said. Without the
pond, it can be done for $175,000. More ambitious projects, like
Lang's, cost over $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the newcomers want rolling hills and they want them by
Memorial Day,'' said Seeler, who had 100 of his workers swarming
over Lang's property on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Frank Newbold, a vice president of Sotheby's International
Realty, who manages the East Hampton office, said that with so many
of the South Fork's most desirable properties with mature plantings
and ocean views already gone, newcomers are buying farmland and
reshaping it to their wills overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instant gratification is certainly a big part of the story out
here,'' he said. ``They don't want to wait to see the small twig
grow. They would rather write the big check and live out their
fantasy of living in the rolling hills of Tuscany.''
</P>
<P>
   The most popular earthworks are long rectangular berms, hillocks
rising six to eight feet, and ponds, sometimes stocked with $300
Japanese koi (much to the delight of Hamptsons seagulls).
</P>
<P>
   On the sloping Sag Harbor property of Lewis B. Cullman, a
philanthropist, Seeler's crews are creating terraces 15 to 20 feet
long at various elevations. ``Imagine a hillside,'' Seeler said.
``We are creating viewpoints on the hillside so you can overlook
the grounds from the points.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Randy Lerner, a securities analyst, was seated atop
a tractor on the 15-acre parcel he bought last fall in Amagansett
next to Alec Baldwin and Kim Basinger. ``My theory was, there are
not a lot of good-sized pieces of property left that represent a
combination of good lands with good elevations so you can see the
ocean,'' Lerner said in a tractor-top cell-phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   After he bought the property, he tore down the main house,
removed a formal circular driveway and moved a two-bedroom cottage
into the center of the land. He likes to do his own earth-moving.
``There was a pond in the back,'' he said. ``It wasn't spring fed.
I pushed the dirt over it. There were big ridges on the side of it
and I filled that back in and it sort of started to look like a
meadow.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other Hamptonites, Lerner's earthworks-in-progress are
aimed at returning residential property to agriculture _ at least
partly. He is thinking of planting cranberries or oats on his front
six.
</P>
<P>
   But Lerner is the exception to the far more popular trend of
adding topography where nature made none. It is a trend that
offends some residents, even those long used to the hubris of the
hyper-privileged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows it's flat out here,'' said Molly Ferrer, a real
estate broker in Sotheby's Southampton office. ``It's expensive to
create hills and it's not a gift from God. You've got to pay for
topography. It's a way of showing you have lots of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert DeLuca, president of the Group for the South Fork, an
organization dedicated to protecting the environment and the rural
character of the area, said: ``The place looks like a cartoon of
what people think a country setting on Eastern Long Island should
be like. The natural landscape is being replaced with the built
landscape at a pace and scale we've never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Vikki Hilles, an environmental educator for the Group for the
South Fork, said that reshaping the earth was not in itself harmful
to natural resources. It's what people are applying to their lawns
that pose a danger, she said; ``The pesticides, the herbicides and
the fungicides affect the quality of your drinking water.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving around the Hamptons last week, Newbold, who has been
selling real estate locally for over 20 years, and Steven Gaines,
the author of ``Philistines at the Hedgerow,'' (Little, Brown,
1998) a social history of the East End, discussed the changing
status symbols in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '60s it was having an outdoor barbecue pit,'' Gaines
said. ``In the '70s it was a swimming pool. In the '80s it was a
must-have tennis court. In the early '90s, it was a full-size
basketball court and this year, for the aughts'' _ his word for the
post-millenium decade _ ``it's changing the topography.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbold parked his Mercedes at Meier's property. ``Oh, and don't
forget the sunken tennis courts,'' he said, leading a tour of the
grounds. Hamptons tennis courts these days are being built six feet
below ground level. ``People don't want to hear the bounce,''
Newbold said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
