<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENAGE-CONSULTANTS-A     05-21 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENAGE-CONSULTANTS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET KARA AND LYNN `MAINSTREAM COOL TEENS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23)  
 (af)  
 By PENELOPE GREEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kara Hamilton, 18, and Lynn Liran, 17, look pretty
much like teen-agers do across the country. On a recent sunny
Monday afternoon, Kara had on scuffed white Nikes, faded Levis and
a cream-colored, knitted Gap shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn wore a lavender tank top of indeterminate provenance, brown
boot-cut Gap jeans, worn brown boots and green eye shadow. The two
best friends, seniors at the Spence School in Manhattan, had their
backs turned resolutely on Madison Avenue and seemed eager to munch
on apple crumb pie at Sarabeth's restaurant and to patiently
discuss subjects both dear and foreign to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really mind being a specimen,'' Kara said graciously.
``That's not necessarily an unpowerful thing to be, and anyway, I
understand that adults are puzzled.''
</P>
<P>
   Kara and Lynn have grown used to expounding on this and that for
grown-ups carrying notebooks and video cameras, and the girls exude
a sort of resigned politeness no matter what you ask them. In 1997,
they were hired by the DuPont Co. to contribute to a panel of
teen-agers the company had assembled as part of a $30 million
promotion of its Lycra fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for new and improved ways to separate teen-agers from
their money, DuPont has moved beyond the typical practice of buying
information on teen-agers' brand, celebrity and sitcom preferences
culled by marketing companies specializing in teen-agers. Like a
growing number of companies, including Levis and M&AMP;M/Mars, DuPont
is hiring teen-agers as consultants.
</P>
<P>
   For manufacturers like DuPont, the stakes are high. Teen
Research Unlimited, a marketing company, estimates that teen-agers
spent $141 billion last year on themselves, plus another $49
billion of their parents' money on groceries. ``We Are Entering the
Age of the Teen Superconsumer!'' is a gleeful headline in a DuPont
handout, The Lycra Teens Research Report.
</P>
<P>
   Kara and Lynn, who just completed their participation on the
panel, were paid $50 for a three-hour session and met about once a
month for a year. ``It was good money just to sit around and
discuss stuff,'' Lynn said. (Like members of Ricky Martin's old
band, Menudo, members of the Lycra panel have a built-in expiration
date _ their 18th birthday.)
</P>
<P>
   And so the girls talked and talked. And they went on shopping
trips, learned fun facts about Lycra _ stretch and recovery! _
talked about their underwear _ wedgies, straps. They also analyzed
a huge number of advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein did not fare well; Kate Moss was deemed too white
and too thin to be appealing. They didn't like an ad for Arizona
Jeans, which, the girls said, blatantly pandered to teen-agers with
copy that reads in part, ``Don't talk down to me.'' Gap was loved
by all.
</P>
<P>
   Since Lycra is an ingredient, not a brand, DuPont can use this
information to court brands the teen-agers did like, including J.C.
Penney, Rampage and Tommy Hilfiger. In essence, DuPont was saying,
``Hey, we can help you with your ads and promotions because we know
what works with these kids, and by the way, use our product because
we've trained these kids to be aware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   DuPont is interested in girls like Lynn and Kara because they
are considered to be, in Teen Research Unlimited's parlance,
influencers, said Michael Wood, a director of the research company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Influencers are the top of the hierarchy,'' Wood said.
``They're the mainstream cool teens, picking up on the trends from
the `edge' teens, the fringe teens like Goths or Skaters, and
broadcasting them.''
</P>
<P>
   So what do average American teen-age influencers like Kara and
Lynn think? Neither really likes shopping or cares about brands.
They are distinguished among their classmates at Spence for a
number of things: they do not diet, or buy DKNY, or live on the
Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   I had brought them magazines, like Mademoiselle, Glamour and
Cosmopolitan. ``Moregasmic?'' Kara said, flicking a Glamour cover
line with her finger. ``Whatever, whatever, I don't concern myself
with these magazines. I don't even buy magazines, though I will
read Lynn's Teen People.''
</P>
<P>
   Kara said she doesn't have a boyfriend because she doesn't
believe that any guy her age can give her what she needs. She uses
the word ``deliberate'' a lot, as in, ``I am deliberate about what
I eat,'' or, ``I am deliberate with my money.'' Kara's favorite
book: ``I Kiss Dating Goodbye,'' by Joshua Harris, a young priest.
Lynn's favorite: ``Crime and Punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lynn's mother and stepfather work in media relations. Kara's
mother is a nurse, and her father works for the New York City
Housing Authority. Kara's favorite television program: anything on
cooking or travel. She is, admittedly, sort of an odd duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like Jacques Pepin,'' she said. Lynn's favorite
program: every one, including ``Sally Jesse Raphael'' and
``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   I also brought them a copy of Rolling Stone _ ``The New Teen
Spirit'' _ which did not tempt them, and a marketing treatise, the
paperback ``Street Trends'' (Harper Perennial, 1998), by the
principals of a marketing company for teen-agers, Sputnik.
</P>
<P>
   This is a thoroughly depressing book, in that Sputnik's authors
describe ``movements'' characterized by a turning away from a large
corporate culture, all for the benefit of exploitation by a large
corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you market to these groups? Be like Sprite, Sputnik
says, because Sprite ads rely on the anti-sell: ``Image is nothing.
Thirst is everything. Obey your thirst.'' The girls loved this ad.
</P>
<P>
   They also liked their consulting gig. ``All these adults are
looking to us for knowledge,'' Lynn said. ``It's a reversal of
roles. And it feels good that they think we have some knowledge to
impart.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's some of that knowledge: Jordan Knight, a pop star, is
O.K., but his videos are too sexual. The Backstreet Boys are more
than O.K. So is Erykah Badu, a soul singer. Neither girl thinks she
has a place in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn isn't sure about God, but Kara definitely is. ``Baywatch''
is funny, but too white and too ``Barbie.'' Fashion magazines
aren't interesting at all, but Teen People is.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie McLean, editor of Stay Free!, a magazine dedicated to an
ad-free world, isn't a fan of the focus group. ``I'm sure
teen-agers are flattered,'' she said. ``It probably makes them feel
more important than selling fast food. But these companies are
basically commodifying these kids' relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McLean's spiritual kin is Kalle Lasn, author of ``Culture
Jam: The Uncooling of America,'' to be published this fall by
William Morrow. Lasn said he gets queasy at the idea that ``cool''
now comes from a company. ``Big companies have also gotten very
good at branding, and I think that this branding amounts to a
creation of cool which the teen-agers seem to be unable to live
without,'' he said. ``In the past we used to create our own cool,
but now the companies are spoon-feeding our culture to us from
above.''
</P>
<P>
   Working for DuPont, however, appears to have nurtured the
nascent ethicist in each girl. ``I'm not buying more stuff than
before,'' Lynn said. ``It's just that I am aware of being marketed
to.'' Kara said: ``I never thought that companies cared so much for
my opinion. The Lycra thing made me think hard about businesses
focused on us, and whether I liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, all the girls attended a trade conference, where
apparel manufacturers were invited to hear what they had to say on
a variety of topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them,'' Kara said dryly, ``that they were welcome to
compete for my limited dollars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANNES-FILM-FEST-565&AMP;     05-21 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANNES-FILM-FEST-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.M.)  
 CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: AT CANNES, SIMPLICITY AND IDEAS ABOUT FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France _ David (``Blue Velvet'') Lynch floored audiences
at the Cannes International Film Festival on Friday with an
eloquently simple, deeply emotional G-rated movie, ``The Straight
Story,'' whose unassuming 79-year-old star gives the best leading
performance to be seen here. And that was only the second-biggest
surprise of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The first involved Harvey Weinstein of Miramax, who is usually
happily orchestrating Cannes brouhaha but has stayed
uncharacteristically far from the spotlight this year. After Kevin
Smith's potentially controversial ``Dogma'' was unveiled Friday
morning, Weinstein found himself in an alley outside the theater,
doing something that is unheard of here: taking part in an
impromptu news conference without benefit of spin.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: Not even Weinstein knows what ``Dogma'' is up
against. All that seems certain about what press notes call Smith's
``comic fantasia'' is that it won't be getting any closer than the
word ``fantasia'' to Miramax's corporate parent.
</P>
<P>
   When Walt Disney Co. discreetly indicated that it did not want
to be fielding anti-``Dogma'' pickets at theme parks, Weinstein and
his brother Bob dropped ``Dogma'' from Miramax's roster, and then
agreed to buy the $14 million film back personally and make other
distribution plans.
</P>
<P>
   Where does it go from here?
</P>
<P>
   Into calmer waters, let us hope. Because Smith's ``Dogma'' is as
smart and articulate as it is wildly irreverent, with characters
who try to make sense of faith just as his ``Chasing Amy''
characters tried to sort out love and sexual identity.
</P>
<P>
   And Smith's fusion of off-the-wall humor with serious debate
never leaves the strength of his religious conviction in question.
``Dogma'' has an outlook best summed up by a character in Smith's
sharp-edged screenplay: ``I have issues with anyone who treats God
like a burden instead of a blessing.'' Even if this is a film that
enlists a silent Alanis Morissette to play God.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Dogma'' winds up offending those who haven't seen it, it
isn't likely to have that effect at closer range. Actually, it's
the rare pop entertainment with a lot on its mind, even if a
meandering second half and a few gratuitous gross-outs dilute its
effect. (Smith, whose cast includes Ben Affleck, Matt Damon, Linda
Fiorentino, Chris Rock and George Carlin, is a much better director
of hilariously stubborn arguments than of action scenes.)
</P>
<P>
   Calling ``Dogma'' anti-Catholic, Smith said Friday afternoon,
``is like calling me anti-New Jersey.'' And he is so fond of his
home state that in ``Dogma'' he shows two travelers who are unable
to buy bus tickets to New Jersey because of high demand.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch's film is also a religious experience in its own way. It
tells the true story of a man named Alvin Straight who rode a lawn
mower from Laurens, Iowa, to Mount Zion, Wis., a considerable
distance, in hopes of visiting a brother from whom he had become
estranged.
</P>
<P>
   The traveler's role is played with immense dignity by Richard
Farnsworth, whose movie roles have been infrequent and never on a
par with this one. Once a stunt extra, Farnsworth drove a chariot
in ``The Ten Commandments'' and carried a sword in ``Spartacus.''
He still lives on a ranch in New Mexico, and looked perfectly at
home in a cowboy hat at the casino in the Carlton Hotel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The Straight Story'' was shot in towns Straight had really
passed through and it has the kind of forthright verisimilitude
that is attained only through careful effort. (Jack Fisk's clean,
unobtrusive production design and Angelo Badalamenti's
uncharacteristically lilting, rustic music heighten the effect.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it may be my most experimental film,'' said Lynch.
This was not an implausible thought. ``Tenderness can be just as
abstract as insanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch lives with Mary Sweeney, who with John Roach wrote a
screenplay that artfully defines a sense of life's meaning through
the stages of Alvin's journey. That's why the director knew about
this story, but not why he chose to film it.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned David Mamet (``The Winslow Boy'') and Pedro
Almodovar (``All About My Mother'') among filmmakers whose Cannes
entries are uncharacteristically gentle. Some of that, he said, may
be because violence and obscene language on screen ``have been
pushed to an absurd extreme, to the point where you don't feel it
any more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really explain it, but I feel a change,'' he added.
``I feel something different in the air.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LESSON-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      05-21 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LESSON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A LESSON BEFORE DYING:' REVELATIONS AND TEARS IN SOUTHERN
PARABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Cheadle has shown film and television audiences his range as
an actor. Among other roles, he has been memorably believable as
the earnest young prosecutor in the series ``Picket Fences,'' as
the volatile psychopath Mouse in the film ``Devil in a Blue Dress''
and as the self-deprecating Sammy Davis Jr. in the television movie
``The Rat Pack.'' Now, in ``A Lesson Before Dying,'' Saturday night
on HBO, he faces the challenge of transforming himself within a
single performance. He succeeds, helping to elevate a tear-stained
parable into an exploration of the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Leading a strong ensemble cast, Cheadle plays Grant Wiggins, a
schoolteacher in rural Louisiana in the late 1940s. Grant, the
first person from his town's black quarter to attend a university,
has chosen to return home as a graduate to preside over the
ramshackle, all-black one-room schoolhouse he attended. In doing so
he is honoring his origins and especially his Tante Lou (Cicely
Tyson), who sacrificed for his education. But he is also forcing
himself to live within a feudal world where he is defined by his
color.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, with more than a trace of self-pity, thinks this is
burden enough. But Lou has another assignment for him. She tells
him he must give private lessons, in a death-row cell, to a young
man named Jefferson (Mekhi Phifer), the godson of Lou's friend Miss
Emma (Irma P. Hall). Jefferson had the fatally bad luck to witness
a shootout involving a white man and two blacks, all of whom died.
The system demands revenge for the white man's death. Jefferson has
been condemned to death for murder despite the public defender's
attempt to save his life by describing him to the all-white jury as
not worth the trouble of executing, ``a fool perhaps . . . not a
man . . . just a poor, darn hog.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant's assignment is to help Jefferson learn, in the short time
he has to live, that he is not a hog, that he is a person of value.
</P>
<P>
   ``How'm I supposed to tell him how a man should die?'' Grant
demands of his girlfriend, Vivian (Lisa Arrindell Anderson), a
teacher in another school. ``I'm still trying to figure out how a
man should live.''
</P>
<P>
   But she won't let him off the hook. ``This isn't about you,''
she tells him sharply. ``You run away from this, you're running
away from your people and from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant does not run away, even though Jefferson at first spurns
the attempts to reach him. What happens from there on transforms
the lives of all the people on the screen. It may also offer some
catharsis to people in the audience, even as they acknowledge that
the fundamental issue of equal justice remains unresolved today.
</P>
<P>
   The film is an adaptation of the 1993 novel by Ernest J. Gaines,
author of ``A Gathering of Old Men'' and ``The Autobiography of
Miss Jane Pittman.'' As the book did, the script by Ann Peacock
explores the many gradations of racism, including prejudice among
blacks toward those with lighter and darker skin, while it grants
its white characters a measure of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Joseph Sargent (``Miss Evers' Boys''), has coaxed
subtle performances from nearly all the players, including Ms.
Anderson; Phifer; Dana Ivey, as the woman in whose home Lou and
Emma were once servants, and the most beautiful collection of
children ever to fill a make-believe classroom. Ms. Tyson, whose
career was propelled by her portrayal of Gaines' Jane Pittman, has
scant chance to excel here in a role that calls for little more
than hectoring. Ms. Hall, however, brings a majestic strength to
the tired old woman who knows she cannot save her beloved
Jefferson's life but won't give up on his soul.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana locations add to the film's authentic feel, as
does the sound of the French-tinged Louisiana accents. Jefferson
refers to Emma as his Nana (pronounced nah-NAH), and everyone
agrees on the benefits of hard ``woik.'' The authenticity, however,
is not served by all the onscreen shedding of tears. Sargent, right
about so much here, should have trusted his audience to know when
to cry.
</P>
<P>
   He does trust Cheadle to tie the film together. When Grant tells
Jefferson, ``No matter how bad off we are, we still owe something
to those who love us,'' Cheadle makes these unsurprising words
sound like a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A LESSON BEFORE DYING'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Saturday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Written by Ann Peacock, based on the novel by Ernest J. Gaines;
directed by Joseph Sargent; Robert Benedetti, producer. Ellen M.
Krass, Joel Stillerman and Ted Demme, executive producers. Produced
by HBO NYC Productions.
</P>
<P>
   With: Don Cheadle (Grant Wiggins), Cicely Tyson (Tante Lou),
Mekhi Phifer (Jefferson), Irma P. Hall (Miss Emma), Brent Jennings
(the Reverend Ambrose), Lisa Arrindell Anderson (Vivian Baptiste),
Frank Hoyt Taylor (Sheriff Guidry), Dana Ivey (Edna Guidry) and
Stuart Culpepper (Henri Pichot).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
