<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, May 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms should affect the northern Ohio Valley and
west slopes of the Appalachians Saturday as a small but powerful
low pressure system pushes through the region. Warm and humid air
from the south, preceding a cold front, combined with cooler air at
18,000 feet will promote these thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Winds from the south in the Ohio Valley are the result of a
strong high pressure system which is anchored just off of the
Southeast coast. This high will provide mostly sunny skies, warm
temperature readings, and higher humidities both on the Northeast
coast and from the Carolinas to northern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front that marks the leading edge of much cooler air will
sweep across the northern Plains and the Great Lakes during the
day. Ahead of this front, showers and thundershowers will develop
from the eastern Great Lakes to the northern Mississippi Valley,
while clouds associated with this front will be extensive over the
northern Mississippi and Red River Valleys. In the wake of low
pressure in the Dakotas, there will be scattered showers in the
Northern Rockies, especially over the higher terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Merging sea-breezes will trigger thunderstorms on both the
eastern and western coasts of Florida once again, some of which
could be rather strong. Onshore flow will persist in Southern
California allowing low clouds and fog to stay inland all day.
Northern California and the Pacific Northwest, however, will be
mostly sunny and much warmer as winds blow down the mountains
toward the Coast, causing the air to warm as it descends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Remarkable Rainfall
</P>
<P>
   A deluge struck Riverton, Nebraska on Thursday. The storm dumped
2.74 inches of rain on the town, which amounts to 70 percent of a
typical May's rainfall. The remarkable aspect of the torrent was
its length. It took only twenty minutes to accumulate nearly three
inches of rain. This was a truly rare downpour since the rate of
rain that fell equaled over seven inches per hour. The world record
for hourly rainfall is 12 inches recorded in Holt, Missouri. While
Riverton's drenching was not a world record, it produced a terrific
flood which washed out numerous roads and railway beds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
