</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, May 23, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   DULL-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ If America wants for bland,
Al Gore is the man. He is considerably less colorful than the man
he hopes to succeed. But many of the hottest politicians these days
are the coldest, perhaps because `boring' can be interpreted as
`reliable' and `no surprises.' California Gov. Gray Davis, New York
Gov. George Pataki and even Texas Gov. George W. Bush are among
successful politicians noted for their blandness. By Richard L.
Berke. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS-REVIEW (Jerusalem) _ The assassination of
Yitzhak Rabin was an undigested trauma for many Israelis, and that
Ehud Barak's victory allowed a kind of public catharsis of
repressed grief over a national martyr whose death at the hands of
an extremist Jew changed the way many Israelis felt about being
Israeli. Now Ehud must depart from the model of his mentor and try
to learn from his mistakes. By Deborah Sontag. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SHIFT-REVIEW (Washington) _ In constitutional law, as in
geology, things can look stable on the surface _ until the tectonic
plates shift underneath. In its decision voiding California's
reduced welfare aid for newcomers to the state, the Supreme Court
used a portion of the 14th Amendment barring states from
restricting `privileges or immunities' of citizens. The sudden
resurrection of this long-neglected clause was one of the most
surprising and most consequential constitutional developments in
years. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEWSHOWS-REVIEW (New York) _ Unveiling next season's network
lineups: what made the annual rite of spring so bleak was the
degree of cynicism and self-satisfaction among TV executives and
writer-producers who proudly showed off their newest sitcoms and
seemed in denial over just how terrible they were. The faint scent
of doom in the air _ that of the networks watching their audiences
erode with the growth of the Internet and cable _ failed to dampen
the strange euphoria. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-YEARBOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Excerpts from the Class of '99
yearbook at Columbine High School, where the shooting masacre took
place in April. Students write that their lives had been profoundly
and irreversibly changed.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-POLITICS-REVIEW _ The new politics of guns, if there is
one. By David E. Rosenbaum. (details to come)
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week, leading
with the revival of whaling by Indians in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   ESPIONAGE-REVIEW (Undated) _ There seems little doubt doubt that
China's theft of secrets from U.S. nuclear weapons labs had led to
spectacular gains by China in creating a modern thermonuclear
arsenal. Yet no one has been charged with espionage or any other
crime. Veterans of espionage investigations offer a variety of
explanations for the government's inability to proceed in the case.
They say that espionage cases have always been among the most
difficult because of the highly covert nature of the crime. By
David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBALIZE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Globalization is thought to be a
new and powerful force that is erasing national borders and linking
the world in an unprecedented web of trade and investments. But
perhaps the greatest myth about globalization is that it is new. By
some measures, its peak occurred a century ago, making the 20th
century memorable in economic history mostly for its retreat from
globalization. In some respects, only now is the world economy
becoming roughly as interlinked as it was more than a century ago.
By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BLAIR-REVIEW (London) _ British Prime Minister Tony
Blair's foreign policies have provoked strong opinions and raised
questions about what is becoming of Britain. Views range from
approval of resurgent British brawn and influence to outright
condemnation of policies seen as fatuous and foolhardy for a
country that no longer has the station or resources to act on its
own and expect others to follow. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HONGKONG-REVIEW (Hong Kong) _ China's newest city is
crowded, expensive, polluted and mired in recession. And yet to
listen to Hong Kong's leaders, every person in mainland China with
the slightest claim to live here would scramble across the border
if the gates were opened. Hong Kong is in a lather over the
prospect that it is about to be inundated by migrants from mainland
China. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-OUTLOOK-REVIEW (Rio de Janeiro) _ The Brazilian financial
crisis seems to have passed, and investors and foreign leaders are
regaining confidence. Still unaddressed, however, is a more
fundamental issue: to what extent did the crisis reflect real
deficiencies in the Brazilian economy and to what degree was it a
self-fulfilling prophecy, brought on by panic and myopia in the
global capital market itself? By Larry Rohter.
</P>
