<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6412 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-INVASION-HNS &LR;      05-21 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-INVASION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PLANNING UNDER WAY FOR POSSIBLE INVASION, PEACEKEEPING FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although NATO has all but ruled out a ground
invasion of Kosovo, the alliance's top commander has told senior
Pentagon officials that planning is nearing completion for a
possible invasion, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, told Defense
Secretary William Cohen and U.S. military leaders in a series of
private meetings Thursday that because there is no guarantee the
air war will achieve North Atlantic Treaty Organization goals by
autumn, ``you have to be open to the possibility of looking at
other options,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The air war against Yugoslavia is nearing the two-month mark
without having achieved the alliance's stated aims of dislodging
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's forces and returning ethnic
Albanian refugees to their villages in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, facing divisions within alliance over the air
campaign, on Thursday insisted that NATO's bombardment was working
and has said troops would not enter Kosovo without a peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials last summer conducted an assessment of how many
troops would be needed to invade Kosovo and repel the Yugoslav
army. The figure then was around 200,000 troops and is likely to
increase in the new assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO leadership about a month ago asked Clark to update
those invasion plans, which are nearing completion, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   The assessment ``will give NATO a better appreciation of the
options it could face,'' said Bacon, adding that Clark is not
advocating an invasion at this point. ``We think that the air
campaign is working extremely well, but you have to be open to
other possibilities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The invasion blueprint is separate from NATO planning under way
to dispatch a 50,000-troop peacekeeping force to Macedonia ``as
quickly as possible,'' said Bacon, in the event of a political
settlement with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the outbreak of conflict March 24, NATO anticipated
sending 28,000 soldiers to enforce a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a province of Serbia, the largest republic in
Yugoslavia. More than 800,000 ethnic Albanians in Kosovo have
poured into to neighboring Macedonia and Albania to flee the
Serb-dominated Yugoslav army and police force.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's senior political body, the North Atlantic Council, is
likely to discuss a plan early next week for an enlarged
peacekeeping force of which the United States is likely to
contribute 7,000 to 8,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The rash of new planning is in large part a function of the
calendar. In the fall, cold, wet weather will begin to settle over
the Balkans, slowing the air campaign, should it drag on so long,
and confounding efforts to shelter the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
