<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBISHOP22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Greek Orthodox Christians celebrating enthronement
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta's Greek Orthodox Christians are
celebrating the enthronement of Bishop Alexios at the Cathedral of
the Annunciation today.
</P>
<P>
   Alexios, who was born on Christmas Day 1943 in Patras, Greece,
has served as archiepiscopal vicar, or temporary head, of the
Diocese of Atlanta since Jan. 1, 1997. The diocese had been vacant
since the death of Bishop Philip of Atlanta on Dec. 28, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   About 20,000 Greek Orthodox Christians are registered in the 65
parishes, four missions and four monasteries of the seven
Southeastern states in the Diocese of Atlanta. Many more people of
Greek Orthodox heritage are not officially members of parishes, the
bishop said, and the Greek Orthodox community is growing in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   During his two years of temporary office in Atlanta, Bishop
Alexios has started three missions. One of them already has grown
to full parish status.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are coming from the North, from New York, from Canada,
retired people,'' he said. ``Also, many people are coming for
business. We have also had some converts through marriage, and some
by choice from different denominations.''
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Christianity, which claims roots with Jesus' apostles,
takes its name from the Greek words meaning ``correct belief.'' For
the first thousand years after Jesus' birth, his followers were
loosely united, but by the ninth century differences started to
grow. By 1054, relations had deteriorated to the point that the
head of the church of Constantinople and the head of the church of
Rome issued anathemas, or formal orders of excommunication, against
each other. That began the branches of Christianity now known as
Catholicism and Orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, Pope Paul VI and Patriarch of Constantinople
Athenagoras I finally canceled the anathemas, but the churches
remain separate.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Alexios says he has the ``same goals the holy apostles
had'' for his tenure in Atlanta, ``to evangelize the people, to
preach to them.''
</P>
<P>
   As bishop of Atlanta, he says, he hopes to build ties with other
Christian leaders. ``I believe there are so many things we can do
together _ like charity,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He also is visiting all the communities in his diocese,
sometimes several within a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to use what the church is offering to people _
love, understanding and patience,'' the bishop says. ``If you do
this, you are going to serve the people. I believe the bishop is
shepherd. He should be with his flock, not with his desk.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
