<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6423 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV23-B     05-21 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV23-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGES TO THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 23, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much has changed in the lives of those born after 1950, but no
difference is more fundamental than the lengthening of the time
they may expect to live.
</P>
<P>
   For their parents, the Biblical three score and ten served as a
realistic statistical goal line. For the current generation, those
who retire at, say, 65, may quite realistically hope to live
another 15 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   And life expectancy is gradually rising.
</P>
<P>
   One result: an enormous amount of crisis-mongering about
unfunded entitlements, of which Peter G. Peterson's ``Gray Dawn''
is perhaps the most apocalyptic. ``There's an iceberg dead ahead,''
writes the 72-year-old investment banker. ``It's called global
aging, and it threatens to bankrupt the great powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another result: individual retirement patterns are quietly
changing in unexpected ways. Already they are far more varied than
the streotypical one-step view of retirement suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The latest development is the emergence of an important category
of ``bridge jobs'' between full-time employment and complete
retirement. Estimates suggest that between a third and a half of
older Americans will work at a bridge job before leaving the labor
force altogether.
</P>
<P>
   That's the conclusion of Joseph F. Quinn of Boston College, one
of the nation's leading experts on retirement behavior. He says
that public policy is changing in ways that make continued work in
life still more likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If employers are willing to provide flexible job opportunities
to meet the needs of these potential employees, then society can
tap a growing pool of older, experienced, and willing workers for
years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The bridge phenomenon is a recent and surprising development.
For more than a century, American men had been leaving the labor
force at earlier and earlier ages _ until the mid 1980s. The trend
abruptly ended then, and now probably has reversed. Older women's
participation rates have increased significantly, too.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who sifts through mounds of data as a fellow of the
Employee Benefits Research Institute, was among the first to
discern the trend and recognize its significance. Since the
mid-1990s, he and a relative handful of other experts have been
working overtime trying to figure out what it means.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened? There are two basic explanations. The first
is that the undisputed reversal in male labor force participation
rates may be nothing more complicated than the business cycle.
Perhaps an unusually long expansion has created jobs for those who
want to keep working.
</P>
<P>
   Something like that happened in the late 1960s, this hypothesis
holds, when the Vietnam War kept unemployment rates below 4 percent
for four years in a row. When the boom ended in the 1970s, elderly
male participation rates plummeted. There was no permanent change
in the taste for leisure.
</P>
<P>
   The other explanation _ the one favored by Quinn _ emphasizes a
number of changes in the retirement environment that ecourage
additional work by older Americans. Congress three times has raised
the age at which manadatory retirement could be required by firms:
to 65 in 1967, then to 70 in 1978, and finally, for firms with more
than 20 employees, to no mandatory retirement in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Social Security rules continue to change in order to
make work late in life more attractive. The normal Social Security
retirement age will rise to 67 for those reaching 62 in the year
2022, for one thing, reflecting widespread agreement that longer
life makes longer work desirable.
</P>
<P>
   For another, the amount of income a Social Security recipient
may earn without losing any benefits is increasing rapidly. Quinn
says that by 2002, recipients will be able to earn $30,000 a year,
without any loss of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Private pension plans have been changing, too, in ways that
encourage working longer. Most defined-benefit plans discouraged
working past a certain age by imposing penalties in the presence of
other work income. The defined-contribution plans that started to
take over in the 1980s contain no such disincentives to work.
</P>
<P>
   The common assumption is that people will not continue to work
unless confronted with dire necessity. Maybe not, says Quinn. The
1998 Retirement Confidence Survey by the Employee Benefit Research
Institute found, however, that 61 percent of current workers expect
that they will work for pay after retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the survey found that for most of those planning to go
on working, financial need was not the chief concern. Only a third
cited the need to make ends meet, and well over half mentioned
``quality of life.'' It long has been an adage that old lawyers die
only when they stop going into their office every day. And there is
evidence that a good proportion of older workers simply trade wage
and salary work for self-employment in some related field.
</P>
<P>
   What about those who choose a new line of work altogether? Is it
degrading to start running a register at McDonald's, say, or
teaching in a day-care center after a lifetime of, say, selling
steel? Like any job, it probably depends on the circumstances. Some
people will enjoy their bridge jobs; others will not.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon discerned by Quinn and others is far too new and
unfamiliar to submit to easy generalizations. The only thing that
seems clear is that changing attitudes towards work are a big part
of it.
</P>
<P>
   The US economy, which over the last 50 years has accommodated
women and teen-agers with surprising ease, now seems ready to make
room for another new group of workers, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
