<HEADLINE>
GERMANY MAKES IT EASIER FOR FOREIGN RESIDENTS TO BECOME CITIZENS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Acknowledging what a mixed society it has become,
Germany Friday adopted a new immigration law that will make it
easier for many of the country's 7 million residents of foreign
origin to become citizens.
</P>
<P>
   After a tortuous and fiercely contested passage through
Parliament, the new legislation was approved by the upper house. It
goes into effect on Jan. 1 and represents a significant shift in
the country's view of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having more foreigners on its soil than any other
European country, Germany had long clung to a view of nationality
based principally on blood lines rather than a liberal, republican
view of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The new law, drafted by the center-left coalition of Social
Democrats and Greens that took office last year, breaks that
tradition. It will enable any child born in Germany who has at
least one parent who has been in the country for eight years to
gain automatic German citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The child will be granted dual nationality until the age of 23,
then must decide which passport to keep. Only in exceptional cases,
such as when ``unreasonable conditions'' are imposed for giving up
a foreign passport, will dual citizenship be permitted.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier draft of the law would have allowed dual citizenship
as a general rule for foreigners' children born here. But after the
opposition Christian Democrats, backed by some far-right groups,
gathered 5 million signatures on a petition against the plan, the
government was forced to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning on the issue, the Christian Democrats took the state
of Hesse in an election in February and so denied the coalition of
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder a majority in the federal upper house.
Only by changing the draft to include an age limit for dual
citizenship was the passage of the legislation Friday assured.
</P>
<P>
   The law also says foreigners who have lived in Germany for 8
years _ rather than the present 15 years _ are eligible for
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   It is Germany's large Turkish community, numbering about 2.2
million, that will benefit most from the new law. The Turks, like
other large groups of immigrants, began to pour into Germany in the
1960s during the country's postwar economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   Cem Ozdemir, a Green Party member of Parliament and a German of
Turkish origin, said the decision amounted to a historic step. ``We
have now signaled that those who have lived here for a long time
belong to us and are part of German society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in practice the prejudices and misunderstandings that have
tended to hinder the integration of large Turkish communities in
cities like Berlin appear likely to persist for some time.
</P>
<P>
   With its efforts to revive the German economy stalled, and
proposed tax laws making little headway, the passing of the new
immigration law amounts to one of the first significant domestic
achievements of Schroeder's coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Kosovo has helped the chancellor's standing and has
tended to distract attention from domestic problems. But the
problems of his coalition _ especially repeated squabbling and an
inability to unite around a policy decision _ have not been
eliminated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
