<HEADLINE>
IN `TRUTH,' MOORE THEN MEETS THE EYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE AWFUL TRUTH 
Produced and directed by: Michael Moore 
On: Bravo 
Date: Sunday at 9 p.m. 
Rating: TV-PG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Moore, the activist gadfly who made the movies ``Roger &AMP;
Me'' and ``The Big One'' and wrote ``Downsize This,'' just won't go
away.
</P>
<P>
   His defunct ``TV Nation'' series first ran on NBC, then the Fox
Network, and now he has another, down the broadcast food chain, on
cable. In midseason on Bravo, it's called ``The Awful Truth'' and
features Moore continuing to provoke the powers that be, gleefully
challenging corporate entitlement to runaway profits and pressing
government to improve its behavior, too. His modus operandi, as
always, is to play a comically rumpled David and ambush and
confront one or another business or government Goliath with
poison-tipped questions.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Roger &AMP; Me,'' you might recall, the filmmaker relentlessly
pursued General Motors Corp. chairman Roger Smith to rake the
automaker over the coals for pulling out of Flint, Mich., and
destroying the fabric of life there. In ``The Big One,'' another
documentary with Moore's distinctive home-made flavor, he collars
Nike boss Phil Knight on camera. He cheerfully reams him out for
refusing to make shoes in the United States and exploiting teenage
Asian workers for peanut pay.
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour ``The Awful Truth,'' airing at 9 p.m. on Sundays,
is more of the same _ and God knows we need it. Moore is one of the
few genuine voices of dissent with a toehold in mainstream media.
Perhaps he gets away with his strong anticorporate and pro-union
politics because he's a jokey fat guy with Woody Allen-ish wardrobe
and demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, given its format, ``The Awful Truth'' is
hit-or-miss. The first few minutes of this week's show, devoted to
ridiculing Secretary of Defense William Cohen for his mawkish
poetry and sensitive-guy persona, seem pointless until the polemic
payoff. But even so, there's something tonic in Moore's sophomoric
high jinks in sight of the Pentagon. They remind us, by contrast,
of how stuffy, prepackaged, and edgeless most American TV news
commentary is.
</P>
<P>
   The meat of the program is a humorously crafted but
deadeyedassault on Manpower International. The worldwide temporary
agency, is, we are told, the single largest employer in the United
States _ robust testament to years of corporate downsizing. By
previously embarrassing Manpower in ``The Big One,'' Moore became
the subject of a widely distributed company memo indicating how to
neutralize him should he reappear at any of the company's offices.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, he and his film crew visit several Manpower
locations to evaluate how well its workers execute the starchy
five-point memorandum. All of this Moore packages as a punchy game
show that he screens, along with other filmed segments, for the
large live audience of ``The Awful Truth'' _ a group he also
entertains with stand-up chatter and comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is not only a skillful guerrilla filmmaker, but also a
deceptively good stage comedian. He may be our sharpest political
comic because of the way he's able to domesticate his message.
Given his klutzy, good-natured beer-bellied image , his tough
left-wing agenda emerges as amusing common sense. In his film work,
sometimes even his victims giggle as he twists the dagger.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are moments when Moore's wit dims and his jovial
persona wears thin. But there he is. Michael Moore just won't leave
us alone, and it's a darned good thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
