<SLUG> BC-TV-CANCELLED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULL THE PLUG: THESE SHOWS DESERVE A GRACEFUL EXIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was time, really. NBC's ``Homicide: Life on the Street,''
which has been chasing its creative tail this year following the
departure of two key cast members at the end of last season,
finally got the ax. The consistently low-rated, high-quality drama
aired its last original episode Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was time, too, for ``NewsRadio,'' a once-terrific sitcom that
lost its way when it lost Phil Hartman at the end of last season.
Skeptics said neither ``Homicide'' nor ``NewsRadio'' would recover
from the cast changes, but that seemed pessimistic: Good writers
can always make up for the loss of good characters by creating good
new characters. Worked for ``Cheers.'' Didn't work for either of
these shows.
</P>
<P>
   For TV fans, it's sad to watch a good show deteriorate. But few
shows know when to quit. ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' is one of
the few examples of quality remaining consistently high until the
plug is pulled. Most linger till they become irrelevant, like this
year's ``Home Improvement'' and ``Mad About You,'' or all but
creatively bankrupt, like last year's seasons of ``Seinfeld,''
``Roseanne'' and ``Ellen.'' Of this year's veterans, only
``Friends'' has had a consistently strong season; ``The X-Files''
and ``NYPD Blue'' both got off to a great start and finished with a
flourish, but their midseason episodes have been merely treading
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Files'' creator Chris Carter has said next season will be
``Files''' last, although we've heard that kind of talk before.
``NYPD Blue'' will come back next year, but it doesn't seem like
it'll withstand another season of Dennis Franz's blustery
interrogations, and the rest of the cast _ even highly touted new
arrival Rick Schroder _ has been left in the dust most of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Even with its late-season surge, the series is showing more than
a few signs of running out of gas. Although it's a likely candidate
for renewal, someone should step up and decide that after next
season, it will bow out gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   The same should be done for these shows:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons'': Even at its worst, this is the funniest show
on TV, and its season-closing episodes were among the best TV this
year. But during the past few years, ``The Simpsons'' has been
about one-third as funny as it used to be, usually reserving its
best jokes for only one of its three acts. In December, the
half-hour series will turn 10 years old. Sign off then, and it'll
upstage ``Seinfeld'' as the show of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly Susan'': Never all that great in the first place,
``Susan'' and similar single-woman sitcoms have been left in the
dust by the more outrageous ``Ally McBeal'' (a show whose
inventiveness is also showing signs of flagging, even as creator
David Kelley pushes for a half-hour sitcom version, the first show
to spin off of itself). ``Susan'' now lives a quiet existence on
Monday night, also known as the Island of Misfit NBC Sitcoms That
Once Followed ``Friends.'' It never should have been moved; it
should have been banished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier'': Once thought of as the most sophisticated comedy on
network TV, the show has reached a point where it's going in
circles: How far will Frasier and Niles take their sibling rivalry?
How will Frasier screw up his latest romance? Will Niles ever win
Daphne's heart? Unless ``Frasier'' pulls a comeback like Kelsey
Grammer's last series, ``Cheers,'' it's time to get off the couch
and turn off this shrink sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly Hills, 90210'': Reportedly, the show will drop its
original cast and pick up a new one. On MTV, they call that ``The
Real World.'' And look how good that show is! Pack it up and move
to a new ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veronica's Closet'': Unlike the other NBC shows on this list,
even ``Suddenly Susan,'' it's impossible to understand how this
poorly written show ever stuck around. NBC just announced that the
show would move to Monday nights. The network should have closed
the closet door.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'': Signs that this medical show is on life support include
the desperate near-fling of Dr. John Carter (Noah Wylie) and his
medical student, Lucy Knight (Kellie Martin), and the burgeoning
relationship between Drs. Mark Greene (Anthony Edwards) and
Elizabeth Corday (Alex Kingston). Eventually, this show's doctors
will bat the romantic cycle, ``Melrose Place''-style, unless
somebody stops them. It's got one good year left, then it needs a
do-not-resuscitate order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago Hope'': ``ER's'' main rival once offered a thoughtful
alternative to the NBC show's fast pace. CBS, however, has never
known what to do with the show, moving it from time slot to time
slot so often that it was never able to develop much viewer
loyalty. The network just announced it's moving ``Hope'' to
``another'' time slot (8 p.m. Thursdays) next year. This may be a
true case of asking for a show to be mercy-killed; its network is
torturing it to death.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot writes on films and TV for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. YOu can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
