<SLUG> BC-GUNS-STRATEGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRESSES FOR PASSAGE OF GUN-CONTROL ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to seize the momentum for gun control,
President Clinton urged House Democrats on Friday to press for
passage of the issue before Congress adjourns for Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats insisted they will push for a vote next week on the
House floor and try to thwart Republican plans to hold committee
hearings next week and vote in June.
</P>
<P>
   The murder of 13 people by two Littleton, Colo., teens in April
and the shooting of six Georgia high school students Thursday has
radically altered the debate over gun control and put gun-control
opponents, especially the National Rifle Association, on the
defensive. The shootings were the latest in a series of school
shootings by disgruntled youths.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also sense a burgeoning political issue.
</P>
<P>
   The school violence prompted the Republican-led Senate to
reverse course this week and adopt a Democratic plan that would
require background checks at gun shows and pawnshops before
handguns could be purchased or redeemed. The provision was part of
a larger juvenile justice bill, later adopted 73-25, that would
make it easier to prosecute youths as adults for serious crimes. It
also would require child safety locks be sold with new handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is demanding action. We can't let the NRA write our
gun laws,'' said Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., one of 15 to 20 House
Democrats who met with Clinton in the White House's West Wing.
</P>
<P>
   The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton flew
Thursday to Colorado to console the victims of the Columbine High
School shootings. The Senate opened debate on the Democratic
proposal just minutes after word of the Georgia shootings reached
the floor and Vice President Al Gore cast the tie-breaking vote to
adopt the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president said very clearly that he wants a memorial for
those victims of Littleton and every other shooting that we've seen
in the schools and houses across the country, and he wants that
memorial to those kids before we go on Memorial Day recess,'' said
Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Senate, the House rules prevent members from offering
nongermaine amendments and advocates of gun control may have little
opportunity to force a floor vote. They may try to hold up Memorial
Day adjournment. Congress planned to leave late next week and
return June 7.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, however, maintained that Democratic leaders
agreed to a timetable and now have reneged. House Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, R-Texas, said House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt,
D-Mo., agreed with GOP plans to hold judiciary committee hearings
next week and hold a floor vote in June. Democrats dispute the
contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all quite surprised that Mr. Gephardt did not stick to
our agreement and, without telling anyone, went to the House floor
to demand an immediate vote,'' DeLay said. ``To address this issue
in a haphazard fashion does not do justice to the victims of
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican aide said House leaders attempted to accommodate
Democrats by excelerating consideration of a gun-control measure to
the second week in June. The aide also noted there are 30 Democrats
who receive high ratings from the NRA who are unlikely to support
their leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to turn this into a partisan issue, and it
isn't,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., already has endorsed
several gun-control issues, such as raising the age for purchasing
a handgun from 18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats contended there have been enough hearings on the issue
of gun control and another is not needed.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., suggested of a delayed vote: ``Perhaps
it's political.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people speculate a delay would give opponents a chance to
regroup and allow some of the public emotion surrounding the school
shootings to lessen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that I can't see anyone who will benefit from
delay except the people like the NRA and those who have opposed
these measures every step of the way,'' said White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
