<SLUG> BC-LLBEAN-STORES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.L. BEAN TO OPEN FULL-PRICE STORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As part of a strategy to reenergize its legend, L.L. Bean Inc.
said Friday it plans to open its first full-price store outside of
Maine next year in suburban Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to boost flat sales, Bean previously disclosed plans to
open four or five stores, some similar to its flagship retail space
in Freeport, Maine, but it had not specified locations for new
stores other than to say they would be outside New England.
</P>
<P>
   Set to open in the summer of 2000, the 75,000-square-foot store
will be an anchor in Tysons Corner Center, a mall in McLean, Va.
Roughly 1.4 million of Bean's catalog customers live within the
trade area of the new store, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem odd for a catalog company to be opening stores at
a time when the retail industry is abuzz about e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But some observers think stores may be an integral part of an
Internet strategy. Many consumers balk at buying expensive items
sight unseen from a Web site operated by a strange retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who have visited a retailer's store are far more
likely to make future purchases from that retailer's Web site, said
Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   As much as a place to sell windbreakers and its famous duck
boots, the new stores will also be a shrine to the Bean brand and
personality, a place where new customers can become as familiar
with the Bean mystique as New Englanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our store will be the catalog come to life,'' said Leon
Gorman, the company's president.
</P>
<P>
   Opening stores may have another benefit. Catalog sales spike
around the holidays. Stores see steadier traffic year-round.
</P>
<P>
   New stores should not be confused with Bean's roughly 10 outlet
stores, which the company operates around the country to liquidate
unpopular merchandise. Last year, sales at privately owned Bean
dipped slightly to $1.03 billion; the lion's share of revenues came
from catalog sales.
</P>
<P>
   Opening stores is part of strategy to regain the double-digit
growth Bean enjoyed for most of the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   A second part of this growth strategy involves a new catalog
called Freeport Studio, a woman's career-wear line that is more
fashionable than the clothing Bean is known for.
</P>
<P>
   Based on early results, Gorman said he projects Freeport Studio
sales of $65 million to $70 million for its first year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POLICY-2TAKES-     05-21 1927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLICY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KOSOVO, CLINTON TRIES TO FIGHT A NEW WAR WITHOUT RISK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN and JOHN BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Between the two options that President Clinton has
declared unacceptable _ doing nothing or all-out war _ the White
House has devised a new kind of warfare for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It is a calibrated war, enabled by high-tech weaponry, guided by
the flickering light of opinion polls and shackled by fear that a
few American combat deaths could turn the public against any
military intervention in an obscure placed called Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The calibrated war is being fought in a kind of policy bunker,
wedged between a Congress where half the members have publicly
declared Clinton unfit for office and a 19-member NATO alliance
bickering over the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials say the president is waging a pragmatic
and moral kind of warfare that pushes military action as far as it
can go, given the hard limits of American public opinion,
congressional dissent and alliance discord.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ``anti-Powell doctrine,'' said one White House
official. He described the new approach as giving the United States
far more flexibility in defending American values than the
all-or-nothing precepts of retired Gen. Colin Powell, the
strategist of the Gulf War who said troops should not be committed
without clear objectives and the military means to achieve them.
</P>
<P>
   A decade that began with Powell's doctrine of going to war only
when victory is guaranteed by overwhelming force is ending with a
protean policy that administration officials call ``coercive
diplomacy.'' The first was designed to crush a foreign enemy; the
second hopes to achieve military and political goals overseas
without losing votes at home.
</P>
<P>
   The president's pollster, Mark Penn, conducts weekly polls for
the Democratic National Committee that periodically sound out
public perceptions of the war, according to Joe Lockhart, the White
House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Limits on action are everywhere, Lockhart said: ``We are
constrained by our allies. Will the public support this? Will the
European publics support this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the war is calibrated, but the rhetoric is
calibrated,'' he said. ``It's a constant challenge to articulate
what the U.S. interest is, why we're doing this, both in terms of
NATO allies and simple right and wrong questions. We look at this
on a daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The military calibration goes on behind closed doors in the
Pentagon and in the White House, but the president's day-to-day
hunt for a middle ground between risky action and humiliating
paralysis can be heard in his own language.
</P>
<P>
   One day, he compares ethnic cleansing in Kosovo to the Holocaust
and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to Hitler. The next, in
almost apologetic tones, he distances himself from the conduct of
the war and makes clear he does not relish commanding troops in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people question what I have done and how I
have done it in Kosovo,'' the president said on Wednesday. ``All I
can tell you is I'm convinced that I've done the right thing in the
best available way.''
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, American and NATO war planners assess the
physical and political damage of the previous night's bombing and
adjust their targeting accordingly. After mistakenly blowing up the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade, allied warplanes avoided all targets
in the Yugoslav capital for four days. After hitting a refugee
convoy three weeks ago, U.S. pilots now have to radio for
authorization to strike if there is any doubt about the target.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the assault on Yugoslavia is driven in large part
by the availability of a new generation of precision weaponry which
allows military planners to select targets with previously
unimaginable accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   These weapons encouraged Clinton to embrace what critics contend
is a fantasy _ long-distance, antiseptic warfare that puts few
American pilots at risk and does not require the use of ground
troops to achieve military objectives.
</P>
<P>
   But Powell asserted in an interview that such one-dimensional
war leaves the initiative in Milosevic's hands. ``He decides
whether it is working or not; he decides when he's had enough,''
the general said.
</P>
<P>
   Why have the president and his advisers chosen a course which
does not ensure victory?
</P>
<P>
   White House advisers say they see a substantial chance of
success and they reject the Powell doctrine as offering what one
termed the ``false choice'' of ground war or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   All presidents, a senior foreign policy aide said, deal with
constraints and must take public opinion and international
realities into account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each challenge presents unique interests and factors,'' he
said, citing the need to maintain NATO cohesion while not
alienating Russia. ``You have to find the best strategy within
those boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell pointed to a simpler explanation: ``I just don't think
Bill Clinton wanted to have a major ground war on his watch,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, if the Clinton administration had slavishly
followed the Powell doctrine in the 1990s, the United States would
never have approved the limited bombing which, when combined with a
Croatian ground offensive, brought an end to the war in Bosnia.
There were no American combat fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   When he ruled out a ground war at the outset and chose to rely
on air power alone in Kosovo, Clinton was being lured down a path
that has tempted nearly every president since before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air power is very seductive to American leaders because it
combines our love of technology with our distaste for the bestial
aspects of land warfare,'' said Rich Dunn, a defense analyst at the
Center for National Security Issues in Virginia and a retired Army
colonel. ``You do it nice and cleanly. Nobody gets their feet
muddy. A pilot flies over at 15,000 feet, kills only those people
that need to be killed, flies homes and has a cold beer with a
beautiful young lady. This is not a new concept.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The notion of winning World War II from the air seduced
President Franklin D. Roosevelt. Gen. George C. Marshall, the Army
chief-of-staff, struggled to convince Roosevelt to balance air,
land and sea forces. Marshall was proved right, as 1940s technology
failed miserably in producing a risk-free war in Europe. More than
34,000 Allied flyers were killed and German industrial production
climbed during the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the bombing of North Vietnam proved ineffective as a
club to coerce the North Vietnamese into abandoning their invasion
of the south. In the Gulf War, ground troops were needed at the end
of weeks of bombing to force Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as the technology of air power advances, so does its
allure. The B-2 Stealth bomber, which is being used for the first
time in combat in Yugoslavia, may well be the most politically
irresistible weapon in American history. The Air Force says a
single B-2 can do what used to take 32 heavy bombers, 16 escort
fighters, four ground-fire suppression aircraft and 15 tanker
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   From an air force base in Missouri, B-2 pilots have been flying
off to Yugoslavia to drop precision-guided bombs through the
clouds. While the bombers stay well clear of enemy fire, their
bombs use satellite guidance to find programmed targets. At the end
of their missions, the B-2's return to Missouri and pilots go home
to their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a different realm now,'' said Air Force Col. Phillip
Meilinger, a professor of strategy at the Naval War College and an
expert on air doctrine. ``We can fight this type of war and we so
totally outclass the enemy. It is astonishing to be fighting for
eight weeks and suffer no casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The only Americans deaths have been two helicopter pilots killed
in Albania in a training accident. After more than 20,000 sorties,
just two planes have gone down in combat and no pilots have been
captured. The scorecard is much more impressive than in the Gulf
War, when 38 coalition aircraft were lost in five weeks of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The wondrous technology, however, has not delivered on America's
primary objective in Kosovo. As Clinton said on the day the bombing
began, the air strikes were supposed to ``protect thousands of
innocent people in Kosovo from a mounting military offensive'' by
Yugoslav army and police units.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the bombing coincided with a massive acceleration of
the Serb offensive. In an explosion of ethnic cleansing that a
former White House official said ``shocked'' the Clinton
administration, more than 750,000 Kosovo Albanians have been pushed
out of the province. Another 600,000 have been driven from their
homes and are living precariously inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In planning the air strikes last year, the White House assumed
that Milosevic would respond to bombing in Kosovo as he responded
in 1995 in Bosnia. Then, a few days of bombing pushed the Serb
leader into peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the analysts felt that Milosevic was unpredictable but
faced with hard resolve he would cut a deal very similar to the
deal he made in Bosnia,'' said Nick Dowling, who until December
worked on Balkan issues in the White House and is now a senior
fellow at the Institute for National Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The general who commanded NATO forces in 1995 argues that the
Clinton administration allowed itself to learn the wrong lesson
from Bosnia, in part because of the political appeal of high-tech
weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have been seduced a little bit by technology rather
than by good professional judgment of what is necessary to win a
war,'' said retired Gen. George Joulwan, who was Gen. Wesley
Clark's predecessor as supreme commander of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Joulwan said bombing was effective in Bosnia because, when it
began, there were 35,000 British and French troops on the ground,
spotting targets and firing artillery. The general said NATO also
was helped by 100,000 Croatian ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, the Clinton administration's bombing strategy was not
designed to protect Kosovo Albanians or drive Serb forces out of
the province, said Dowling, the former White House official.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, it was an indirect strategy, based on the
assumption that Milosevic would surrender Kosovo rather than watch
as NATO bombs destroyed his military. As White House spokesman
Lockhart put it, ``We would continue to degrade what is most dear
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``Say Uncle'' strategy leaves it to Milosevic to decide
when he has had enough. Milosevic has responded in two ways. First,
he directed small, widely dispersed units of Serbian forces to
drive hundreds of thousands of Kosovo Albanians from their homes.
Second, he ordered those forces to lay mines, dig in and fortify
their positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good technology is not a substitute for good judgment,'' said
Sen. Robert Torricelli, a New Jersey Democrat who has been critical
of the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing several weeks ago for Democratic senators,
Torricelli recalled asking National Security advisor Sandy Berger,
``Have you ever met a Serb? Do you understand anything about
Serbian history? You think you are going to bomb these people for
two or three weeks and achieve a political result?''
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey senator said Berger had no answer beyond another
plea for more patience to allow air power to work.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration lost faith in the utility of ground
troops in 1993, after 18 soldiers were killed in a failed raid in
Mogadishu, said Ivo Daalder, who served in the White House in the
mid-1990s as a specialist on Bosnia and is now at the Brookings
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe that Somalia demonstrates conclusively that you
cannot have any casualties,'' said Daalder. ``They take this as a
matter of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   In running NATO's war in Bosnia, Joulwan said he constantly had
to fight Clinton's assumption that a majority of the American
public demanded a zero-casualty war. ``The problem with the White
House is that rather than say why did casualties occur, they just
said we can't take casualties anymore,'' Joulwan said.
</P>
<P>
   Polling data going back to the Korean War suggest the White
House is right to worry about the political costs of casualties,
especially if there are lots of them in an obscure, faraway place.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls on Kosovo show a softening of support for the
bombing campaign and an increased desire for negotiations with
Milosevic to end the war. Given this equivocation, Clinton should
be worried about risking ground troops, said Andrew Kohut, director
of the Pew Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lockhart, the White House spokesman, the findings
of the president's pollster ``are not radically different from what
you see in the public polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohut said that the president, in his equivocation on ground
forces, seems to have found a seat squarely in the middle of public
opinion. ``Clinton is in a quandary, but he has got 200 million
people there with him,'' Kohut said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was advising Clinton, I would be very leery that the
public will follow along in case of casualties,'' said Kohut.
``Without that support, you will have a real nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's quandary is doubly difficult for Vice President Al
Gore, who was one of the administration's most vocal hawks on
Bosnia but whose advisers say he dreads a presidential campaign
while American forces are bogged down in a Balkan quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has opposed the introduction of ground troops and delivered
the administration's strongest public statement opposing their use
in the first days after the aerial assault began.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's critics say the president has the rhetorical gifts to
rally public opinion behind a war in which American soldiers might
die.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, his eloquent speeches on Kosovo have made a
compelling case for the kind of sacrifice Americans made in World
War II, but the president seems unwilling to follow the logic of
his own soaring language.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been telling the story of an American Indian leader
who visited the White House earlier this month. The man said his
great-great-grandfather had been killed by the 7th Cavalry at
Wounded Knee and his two uncles had fought in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have only one son and he means more to me than anything,''
the president said the man told him. ``I would be proud for him to
go and fight against ethnic cleansing in Kosovo. We know what is
right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
