<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6443 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     05-21 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMY'S FRIENDS HELPS STRIPPERS ESCAPE THEIR PAST, COME BACK TO
CHURCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Amy Dupree suffered from low self-esteem. She
felt ostracized from the popular kids at her Texas high school.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, she turned to topless dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me feel beautiful and famous,'' said Dupree, 31, who
said she earned as much as $500 a night in tips dancing semi-nude
in bars around Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   After a time, though, Dupree said she felt even more worthless.
When she tried to escape the sex entertainment business, she turned
to an unusual source for help: the Preston Road Church of Christ in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of other women at the church, she has founded
Amy's Friends, a year-old organization that has helped more than a
dozen women leave topless dancing and other adult entertainment
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Strippers, topless dancers and nude models have been among those
who have called the Amy's Friends crisis line, (972) 520-3400.
Callers are invited to attend weekly support-group meetings at the
homes of church members.
</P>
<P>
   Women who ask for help can receive assistance with rent,
utilities and child care. They also are assisted in finding
different jobs. After three months, the progress of each woman is
evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Towell, a 61-year-old grandmother who spearheaded the
church's effort to begin Amy's Friends, said the project has
mushroomed. A second support group has been established in Euless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of exciting and a little scary, too,'' Towell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Towell said women say they want to leave the business because
it's degrading. ``It's like a big party at first,'' she said, but
then ``it starts to wear on them.''
</P>
<P>
   During support-group meetings, women share their problems and
study Twelve Steps for Christians, a Bible-based program patterned
after the successful 12-step recovery program that originated with
Alcoholics Anonymous. One of the 12 steps of the program requires
members to ``make a searching and fearless moral inventory'' of
themselves. Then it demands that they admit they are powerless to
change. Finally, they humbly ask God to remove their shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Not all who attempt to change are successful.
</P>
<P>
   Dupree, who is married now and is a representative for a company
that supplies pagers to medical personal, said she could never have
left dancing without the church's help.
</P>
<P>
   ``They welcomed me with open arms,'' she said. ``I was so
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Dupree said that during her topless-dancing days, she also
became addicted to drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Although she gave up the drugs and alcohol after going through a
rehabilitation program, Dupree found it hard to leave topless
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried it,'' she said. ``I left for a while and worked at
office jobs, but didn't make much money. I got sick and became
financially strapped.''
</P>
<P>
   She says a friend suggested she go back to topless dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like riding a bicycle,'' she said. ``I went back to
dancing, and I set money quotas for myself. Also, I didn't drink or
do drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was very unhappy. After a year, she tried to get out but
found she was reluctant to give up the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I said, `OK, God, this is enough. If you will help me
get out of this, I will try to help others get out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her fiancee suggested she try going to church to support her
desire to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt either God could help us or no one could,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although apprehensive, they decided to attend the Preston Road
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked in, this little old lady came up to me and told
me, `You are so beautiful. I'm glad you are here,' '' Dupree said.
``She had no idea who I was. I've never felt such unconditional
love.''
</P>
<P>
   Dupree said the church experience was a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought dancing was my whole life,'' she said. ``But it
wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   She began attending a class on changing relationships. Although
she was still dancing at the time, she says no one mentioned it at
the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did what Jesus would do,'' she said. ``They loved me
until I could love myself.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
