<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Mass.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now You See a Pension. Now Maybe You Don't. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 96 percent cut in a pension check would meet almost anyone's
definition of a retirement nightmare. So Hope Walden, who spent 28
years with Pan American World Airways as a flight attendant and
manager, was predictably unhappy to be told recently that it might
come true.
</P>
<P>
   To compound the insult, the news came from the Pension Benefit
Guaranty Corp., the federal agency that is supposed to be
protecting private pensions.
</P>
<P>
   This month, eight years after the collapse of Pan Am, the agency
said it had finally issued most of the 45,000 letters telling the
airline's former workers how much their pensions would be. But some
workers say their notices were not only late, but also wildly
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   The agency told Mrs. Walden, who lives in Cliffside Park, N.J.,
that the $1,265 she has been receiving monthly since she retired in
1991 would be cut in August by 75 percent, to $316, and cut again,
when she turns 65 in a few years and draws Social Security, to just
$44.18.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Welles, a spokeswoman for the agency, said poor records
and mistakes by managers of failed pension plans make it difficult
to determine benefits accurately for such pension plans, which were
taken over because they could not pay all the benefits owed.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Walden's lawyer, Harvey M. Katz of Berlack, Israels &AMP;
Liberman in New York, says that even if the pension agency
calculated correctly (he argues that it was far off the mark), the
delays in sending the letters are harmful. ``If you retire on one
amount, how are you supposed to adjust years later to getting just
a quarter of that?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   David Cay Johnston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soapsuds With a Heart &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a big ``if,'' consumers would rather buy from a company
that is involved in a social or charitable cause, a survey of 2,000
adults suggests. Roper Starch Worldwide in New York did the study
for Cone Inc. in Boston, which does so-called cause marketing,
linking companies to good works.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-six percent of the respondents said they would switch to
products of a company connected with a cause _ like Ford Motor,
which sponsors breast-cancer research, or Home Depot, which helps
with affordable housing _ if the price and quality were equal to
those of rivals.
</P>
<P>
   It may take another study to show how good works rank when a
higher price is also involved, but 61 percent of respondents
thought that involvement in some socially useful activity should be
standard business practice.
</P>
<P>
   Susan J. Wells
</P>
</TEXT>
