<SLUG> BC-INVEST-GEN-Y-STOCKS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE STRATEGY MEANS KEEPING UP WITH THE KIDS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Texas, Calif., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE LEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Cabell Jr. likes to tag along when his daughter, Elizabeth,
14, heads to the mall. That is because Cabell, as co-manager of the
$930 million USAA Aggressive Growth fund, is hungry for insight
into what the under-21 crowd is buying.
</P>
<P>
   Between 3 percent and 4 percent of the fund's portfolio is
invested in companies that focus on Generation Y _ which by its
broadest definition encompasses 60 million Americans ages 4 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   It is an attractive group: Teenage Research Unlimited of
Northbrook, Ill., estimates that the 31 million Americans between
12 and 19 spent $141 billion last year, up from $122 billion in
1997. And the teen-age population is expected to peak at 35 million
in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   But because teen-agers are fickle, Gen Y companies can falter
quickly, and investors can be left reeling. ``This is such a niche
and it's so volatile that it makes Internet companies look like
IBM,'' said Cabell, who is 45. Wall Street is the follower here, he
added, and ``it's the kids who are setting the trends.''
</P>
<P>
   A one-time Wall Street darling, the retailer Gadzooks Inc. of
Carrollton, Texas, is a case in point. Its stock price fell more
than 80 percent from a 52-week high of $29.25 last June, as
teen-agers shunned the private-label clothes it was introducing.
The shares have only begun to recover, and are now trading at
$9.625.
</P>
<P>
   Two other fashion victims were Pacific Sunwear Ltd., a
beach-oriented company in Anaheim, Calif., and Hot Topic Inc. of
Pomona, Calif., which cultivates a bad-boy image. Their stocks fell
55.3 percent and 61.5 percent, respectively, in the fourth quarter
amid disappointing results.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the culprit in both cases was teen-agers' changing
tastes: Young buyers were cool to Sunwear's wide-leg jeans and Hot
Topic's gift offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a dozen public companies _ most of them retailers _ focus
on Gen Y. Others, notably Skechers USA, a shoe retailer with a
streetwise urban look, and Limited Too, a subsidiary of The
Limited, are expected to go public this summer. Gen Y retailers
tend to operate in malls, sell products over the Internet and
market to both boys and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Gen Y companies don't make fashion missteps, they can
experience the volatility characteristic of Internet marketers.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Delia's of New York, a catalogue clothing retailer
that controls 95 percent of Iturf, an on-line sibling, climbed
nearly tenfold between October and April in anticipation of Iturf's
initial offering, hitting a high of $40. But since then, Delia's
has tumbled more than 50 percent. (Iturf closed at $66 on its first
day of trading on April 9, up from the initial price of $22. It now
trades at $25.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``there's significant money to be made from this
demographic segment,'' said Joe Grillo, an analyst at BT Alex Brown
in San Francisco. The trick for investors is to figure out which
Gen Y companies have management that understands fashion and reacts
quickly to change.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Sunwear was able to turn around quickly, offering a
Hawaiian look that has become popular. The stock now trades at
$38.625, well above its low in December of $12.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very nimble, very flexible company,'' said Janet
Kloppenburg, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens, who
says the stock could hit $46 in 12 months. She also says Hot Topic
has already put its line of gift products in order; traditional
retailers might have taken eight months to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed on Friday at $25.0625, more than double its
52-week low of $9.875. She says it could hit $33 in 12 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
