<HEADER>
A6453 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-WITH-STOCKE-AR     05-21 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-STOCKE-ART-$ADV23NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH EVERGREEN SELECT SPECIAL EQUITY FUND'S JOSEPH E.
STOCKE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23)  
(rk) 
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What makes for successful stock-picking? Simple
number-crunching, or the evaluation of more qualitative matters,
like management talent?
</P>
<P>
   Joseph E. Stocke, portfolio manager of the $100.1 million
Evergreen Select Special Equity fund, says he has one foot in each
camp. He starts with a numbers-driven computer model, then uses
more traditional, ``kick the tires'' qualitative analysis to
whittle down his list, which mostly includes small- capitalization
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quantitative approach is very disciplined and the
qualitative is like an art form, so we think it's a very balanced
process,'' he said from his office in Malvern, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Stocke (pronounced STAHK-ee) says the balanced approach has
helped the fund as small-capitalization stocks have sputtered.
Evergreen Select returned 20.1 percent, annualized, for the three
years ending May 14, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago
financial publisher, versus an average of 8.5 for its category of
small blend funds, which own stocks with both value and growth
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Stocke, who bench-presses 165 pounds when he is not picking
stocks, joined Meridian Bank of Reading, Pa., in 1983, and
eventually began managing an institutional fund that was the
predecessor to Evergreen Select. Meridian was bought in 1996 by
Corestates Financial, which in turn was bought in 1998 by the First
Union Corp., owner of the Evergreen Funds.
</P>
<P>
   His starting point is the roughly 5,000 publicly traded American
companies with market capitalizations of less than $2 billion. Then
Stocke, 39, skims off 10 percent of them, using a computer model
that combines elements of growth, value and even momentum
investing. The model seeks out stocks with high earnings growth
rates, low price-to-earnings ratios, high dividend yields, upward
changes in analyst earnings estimates, heavy insider buying and
positive price momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The computer finds those that are reasonably appealing by all
six measures, or those that are very attractive on at least two of
them, ending up with 450 to 500 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Stocke and the six analysts who work on the fund then divide the
list among themselves, by industry. (He takes consumer cyclicals
and health care stocks.)
</P>
<P>
   They review each company, looking at its management, new
products, industry position, research and development and
sensitivity to economic trends. For example, Stocke's team wants
management that owns company stock or whose pay is tied to
performance, and that has a track record in various market and
economic environments. ``We look at anything that would add
value,'' Stocke said.
</P>
<P>
   That allows him to make the final cut, to the 100 or so stocks
that he holds in the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he added to the fund's position in Electronics
Boutique Holdings, a retailer of computer games that he bought for
$14 a share last July, at its initial offering.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in West Chester, Pa., has 528 outlets, mostly
on the East Coast, and plans to open stores in the rest of the
country, he said. It began selling games over the Internet last
month and could profit from demand for computer games tied to the
``Star Wars: Episode I _ the Phantom Menace,'' which opened on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates the company's five-year earnings growth rate at 20
percent. The stock, which now trades at $16, sells for less than 11
times his earnings estimate of $1.50 to $1.55 a share for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Stocke recently added to his stake in Williams-Sonoma, the
kitchenware marketer that also sells furniture and tableware under
the Pottery Barn name. The company should benefit from strong sales
of new and existing homes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Sonoma shares are selling for less than 20 times his
2000 earnings estimate of $1.50 a share. He attributed that ratio
to the company's increased spending over the last few quarters to
upgrade distribution and computer systems, which hurt earnings and
dampened the share price.
</P>
<P>
   But Stocke expects annual earnings growth of more than 25
percent over the next three years. He bought shares last fall at
$22; they closed on Friday at $31.875. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is Gildan Activewear, a Montreal manufacturer
of inexpensive T-shirts and other sportswear. The company has begun
making golf shirts to benefit from the trend toward more casual
wear in offices, Stocke said. ``It's a family-owned business, and
the owners put their heart and soul into the business,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He expects earnings to grow 20 percent annually over the next
five years. The fund began buying the stock at $7 in June 1998; it
closed on Friday at $16.0625, eight times his earnings estimate of
$2 a share for next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
