<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLANDS-THEMEPARK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL READY TO OPEN A NEW FLORIDA THEME PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also ISLANDS-SEUSS)  (lh) 
 By BILL DEAN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Where can you plummet 400 feet in a Spider-Man
cartoon, pet a triceratops getting a veterinary exam, and snack on
green-eggs-and-ham sandwiches?
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds like something out of this world, then the creators
of Orlando's newest theme park couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   Islands of Adventure is the name, and one-of-a-kind thrills is
the game at this new 110-acre wonderland. Cutting-edge technology
combines with beloved characters like the Cat in the Hat to
entrance visitors as they haven't been before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really amazed,'' said Jack Reape, 37, of New Orleans,
who visits different theme parks each year with his wife and three
young children. ``The things here are really new and different.
It's very impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Officially opening May 28 as Universal Studios' second theme
park in Florida, Islands of Adventure divides the fun into five
islands with separate themes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Seuss Landing, where the world of Dr. Seuss comes to life in
the first theme park attraction to feature characters and rides
based on children's books by Dr. Seuss.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Lost Continent, which envelops guests in a mythological
fantasy world, including the Dueling Dragons _ the world's first
inverted, dueling roller coasters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jurassic Park lures visitors through its gates to such
attractions as the Jurassic Park River Adventure, a river-raft
style ride that glides past peaceful dinosaurs before ending in an
85-foot plunge past a tyrannosaurus rex.
</P>
<P>
   _ Toon Lagoon, where cartoon favorites such as Bullwinkle,
Popeye and Dudley Do-Right come to life through such adventures as
a log-flume and white-water raft rife.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marvel Super Hero Island, which contains the park's most
amazing and technologically advanced attractions, the Amazing
Adventures of Spider-Man and the Incredible Hulk Coaster.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for Islands of Adventure was already under way in 1990
when Universal Studios opened doors to its first Orlando park,
Universal Studios Florida. Construction, estimated at $2.5 billion,
took five years.
</P>
<P>
   Islands of Adventure will help Universal's Florida attraction
compete with Disney World and become a total, multi-day vacation
destination instead of just a one-day park. To that end, Universal
Studios has also added the CityWalk entertainment complex, which
opened in February. On-site theme hotels are on their way: the
Portofino Bay Hotel opens this summer, and four more are to follow
by the end of the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the entire complex, which is now called Universal
Studios Escape, Islands of Adventure was designed to complement the
original Universal Studios and to provide guests with thrills they
can't find anywhere else with technology never before used in
theme-park situations.
</P>
<P>
   Colorful characters _ such as the mirthful creatures of Dr.
Seuss' imagination as well as heroes from comic books and the funny
pages _ served as springboards for ideas of what to do with them in
a park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cat in the Hat ride was a natural,'' said Lisa Girolami,
show producer of Seuss Landing. ``The idea was to simply take
guests for a ride through the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Islands of Adventure includes many standard theme-park
attractions, such as log-flumes, free-fall rides and carousels, but
it also adds ground-breaking enhancements to typical park rides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with what was state of the art at the time, and
then we looked at ways to make it better,'' said Mark Woodbury,
vice president of design and creative development for Universal
Studios' Islands of Adventure.
</P>
<P>
   The Incredible Hulk Coaster uses 240 50-horsepower motors to
shoot coaster fans 110 feet in the air _ and from zero to 42 mph in
2 seconds. ``None of those things have ever been attempted before
in a roller coaster,'' Woodbury said.
</P>
<P>
   Poseidon's Fury in the Lost Continent has guests walking through
a tunnel of 17,000 spinning gallons of water before arriving at a
battle between Poseidon, the Greek god of water, and Zeus, the god
of fire. ``It's a pretty stunning piece of work,'' Woodbury said.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive of all, however, appears to be the Amazing
Adventures of Spider-Man, which is equal parts moving-car ride, 3-D
special effects show and simulator attraction all in one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why Spider-Man is so unique is because it combines
a whole bunch of technologies in a different way, and it also
created new technologies to make the experience happen the way it
does or make it as compelling as it is,'' Woodbury said. ``This
includes three-sided rear-projection scenes to a moving audience,
which is pretty significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started that, people said it couldn't be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Guests sampling Spider-Man and other attractions during Islands
of Adventure sneak-previews were glad they did however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' said Katie Everrett, a 13-year-old eighth-grade
student from Jacksonville. ``It wasn't really scary. But it was so
exciting and everything was happening all at once, so it was
really, really good.''
</P>
<P>
   The park's roller coasters, however, are what captivated
32-year-old Ginny LaRose, from Exeter, N.H. ``I liked the Dueling
Dragons and the Hulk, but I would say the Hulk is the best, because
it's totally different,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still other guests preferred the life-size, plant-munching
dinosaurs of the Jurassic Park River Adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jurassic Park is really great,'' said Jacksonville's Cheryl
Searcy, after riding the attraction with her 17-year-old son,
Daniel. ``The scenery was really impressive. And the moving
dinosaurs were state of the art.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a fantasy world,'' adds Daniel. ``It's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
