<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-TERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLING IN ITALY STIRS FEARS OF A REVIVAL OF TERRORIST TIMES PAST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Italians scoured their newspapers Friday with a sickening
sense of deja-vu: blaring headlines about the assassination of a
government official, blurry photographs of the widow leaving the
police station, and a five-pointed star that terrified Italy for
two decades, the emblem of the Red Brigades.
</P>
<P>
   The carefully planned shooting on Thursday of Massimo D'Antona,
51, a labor adviser to the current government, sent a shock
throughout the country, mostly because it was so eerily familiar.
</P>
<P>
   A 28-page statement released by the group claiming
responsibility for the killing was signed ``the Red Brigades,'' the
same name used by the ultraleft-wing organization that was
responsible for dozens of terrorist attacks in the 1970s and early
'80s, including the kidnapping and killing of former Prime Minister
Aldo Moro.
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread anxiety about the killing, few Italians seem
convinced that it signaled a revival of the reign of terrorism that
paralyzed Italy 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Italian society is no longer dangerously
polarized, as it was in the late 1960s when the Christian Democrats
held a lock on power and Marxist ideology flowed freely in
universities, offices and even some Roman Catholic churches. Now a
former Communist heads the government, and there is fair, if
unfriendly, competition between left and right.
</P>
<P>
   But the very fact that society has changed so much has made the
assassination of D'Antona all the more puzzling and frightening.
</P>
<P>
   Italian investigators have said it is unlikely that these new
self-styled Red Brigade terrorists are the same who founded the
original movement. The leaders who kidnapped Moro in 1978 are now
in their 40s and 50s, and most have served out their sentences or
are enrolled in work-release programs, though investigators concede
that some lesser-known members could still be at large. The two
gunmen were described by witnesses as in their mid-20s.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the killing of D'Antona, who took part in the
government's efforts to reform labor laws, was scattered across the
statement of responsibility. It railed against D'Antona as an agent
of ``a neocorporate policy'' sought by ``the imperialist
bourgeoisie,'' and against the Italian government for supporting
NATO and what it called American war-mongering.
</P>
<P>
   D'Antona was chosen as a symbol, but the war in Kosovo seems to
have at least provided a pretext. Since the bombing campaign
against Yugoslavia began in March, D'Alema's political party,
Democrats of the Left, has reported at least 33 attacks on its
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Friday security was tightened at all potential targets, and
police investigators were interrogating anarchists, squatters,
fringe political activists, autonomous union organizers and former
Red Brigade members. They were also reopening years-old cases of
letter bombs and anonymous threats.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no arrests, but some politicians were already
tracing the killing to Belgrade, Yugoslavia. Others were haunted by
the rebirth of an all too familiar extremism.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the cycle of armed violence was absolutely over,
without any chance of reopening,'' said Adriana Faranda, a former
Red Brigades member who served 14 years in prison for her role in
the Moro assassination. ``I cannot understand how there could still
be people who hope to foment a revolutionary process in Italy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
