<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6463 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-BELGRADE-BOS &LR;      05-21 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-BELGRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE STRUGGLES TO SOCIALIZE AMID THE BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ At the National Theater, the old adage that the show
must go on is taken very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   And so it has, despite almost daily bombing of the Yugoslav
capital by NATO warplanes. What began as an expression of artistic
freedom has become one of quiet yet determined defiance and
national pride, as both the performers and their audiences refuse
to give up the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the daily briefings of government ministers, who use
bellicose rhetoric to denounce NATO and extol the virtues of the
Yugoslav nation, the defiance shown at the National Theater is more
subtle and free of overt nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   The theater has continued to put on plays, operas, and ballets
written by those who hail from NATO countries. Shakespeare's ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' was Friday's main show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about politics,'' says Nebojsa Bradic, the
theater's general director. ``This about being true to our
profession and to our audiences. We will not be bombed off the
stage. The audience gives us strength. We give them some kind of
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater has made adjustments, however, the main one being
that all shows are now matinees that finish before nightfall _ when
the bombs begin to fall. When NATO began its operation March 24,
officials canceled the entire schedule. But within days, Bradic and
his staff realized they desperately wanted to keep performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We resumed our performances on March 27, a very symbolic day,
because it is World Theater Day,'' Bradic said, sitting in his
office overlooking Freedom Square. ``We put on Rossini's
`Cinderella' at noon, and the people came.''
</P>
<P>
   They have kept coming, day in and day out.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the early performances were interrupted by air raid
sirens. There are two bomb shelters in the theater, including its
second stage, which is normally used for the plays of contemporary
writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three times we did that, went into the shelter. But now
the audience won't leave the house. It has been a joint decision by
the artists and the audience to see through the performance, even
if we hear the air raid sirens,'' said Bradic.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia has seen its gross domestic product shrink by
two-thirds in the last 10 years, and the war has only increased the
financial hardship of the nation's 10 million people. Belgrade's 2
million people have been hit especially hard.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bombing began, the National Theater has slashed its
ticket prices by at least half, sometimes by much more. A ticket to
Friday's late afternoon matinee, a play about the life of Nicola
Tesla, a Serbian inventor who emigrated to the United States, cost
less than $2.
</P>
<P>
   Vojislav Vasilevic, a doctor, took in the Tesla play, and has
been to several other performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so little now, it is very important to have the
theater,'' he said. ``It is good to do something normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Belgrade's smaller theaters are offering free shows, and
movie houses offer cut-rate admissions. Vasilevic said the
professional standards of the National Theater remain high, and he
gladly parted with 20 dinars for Friday's play.
</P>
<P>
   ``At night, the only thing to look forward to is the bombing,''
he said glumly.
</P>
<P>
   The actors, singers, and dancers are as enthusiastic as the
audiences. Among those performing daily is Natasa Ninkovic, one of
Belgrade's most prominent young actresses. Last year, Ninkovic
played opposite Dennis Quaid in the Oliver Stone-produced film
``Savior,'' about the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, still a bit breathless after playing Helena in ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream,'' Ninkovic stood backstage and
acknowledged that given her Hollywood contacts, she didn't have to
be in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sounds terrible but I have papers, I could go anywhere in
the world,'' she said. ``But this is where I want to be. I feel
like I am helping people here. If my performing makes the day a
little more enjoyable for some ordinary person, then I cannot ask
for anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ninkovic's initial response was that of an artist, she
acknowledges that as the bombing has dragged on her performances
have become an expression of her patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is to show my resistance to NATO, to the crime that
happens every day they bomb civilian targets,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ninkovic said that the NATO bombing has not diminished
her appreciation of western European and American culture. She
would like to do more films and will soon star in the National
Theater's production of ``Popcorn,'' by the contemporary British
playwright, Ben Elton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Ben Elton,'' she said, dreamily.
</P>
<P>
   Bradic said he has purposely chosen to stage mostly comedies and
fantasies. ``In days like these, people need to laugh, to escape,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that there are no plans to stage anything blatantly
nationalistic, and added that the only overtly political statement
made in the theater coincided with the 50th performance since the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said that we were devoting our 50th performance to NATO
because it was their 50th anniversary,'' said Bradic. ``It was done
more in humor than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradic insisted that the daily performances at the National
Theater transcend politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the portraits that hang in our theater,'' he said.
``They are not of politicians, or soldiers. They are of Verdi,
Mozart, Moliere, Shakespeare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
