<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA AND UNION RESUME TALKS IN BID TO AVERT STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After passing through bankruptcy court twice since 1992, Trans
World Airlines, the airline made famous by Charles Lindbergh and
Howard Hughes, is once again at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, federal mediators declared an impasse
between the airline and its largest union, setting off a 30-day
``cooling off'' period that expires at midnight June 10. If TWA and
the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers,
which represents 16,000 of the airline's 21,000 employees, cannot
agree on a new contract by then, the union will be free to walk
out.
</P>
<P>
   Both the union and TWA management agree that the airline, which
has continued to lose money in the midst of an industry boom and
has only $211 million in cash, cannot afford a strike. Indeed, both
sides are concerned that even the current threat of a walkout could
severely damage the carrier because an increasing number of
passengers will stop reserving tickets on the airline as the
deadline nears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few more canceled bookings can have a serious impact,''
said IAM President R. Thomas Buffenbarger in a recent interview.
``Consequently, the closer it gets to that 30-day mark and bookings
dry up more and more, this airline could find itself in a serious
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides returned to the negotiating table Friday after the
union broke off talks Monday. In an update to members, union
leaders said that TWA's last offer was the third in a row that
included ``no significant changes'' and was therefore unanimously
rejected by negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   The company, for its part, said it had sweetened its overall
wage proposal to $320 million over two years from an earlier offer
worth $250 million. The increases for the three major groups of
workers represented by the IAM _ mechanics and ramp workers, flight
attendants, and passenger service employees _ range from 9 percent
to 23 percent, bringing each to 90 percent of the projected
industry average by early 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The union argues that its members deserve more after sticking
with TWA through years of sacrifices, although it would not
publicly specify its demands.
</P>
<P>
   Now the country's eighth-largest airline, TWA has descended a
long way from the days when it and Pan American World Airways
dominated the skies as America's premier international airlines.
The current management has shrunk the airline by trading in its
older, wide-body airplanes for smaller, newer models. It has also
focused on improving operational performance, raising its on-time
record and recently winning the J.D. Power quality award for the
second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   TWA now has a strong hub in St. Louis, where it flies 72 percent
of the scheduled airplane seats, and a weak international and
transcontinental operation based at John F. Kennedy International
Airport in New York. The airline lost $120 million last year on
$3.3 billion in sales, down from $3.5 billion in 1996. Its stock
now trades at less than half its 52-week high, closing Friday at
$5.25 a share, unchanged, on the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to simultaneously shrink and reduce unit
costs,'' said Samuel Buttrick, an airline analyst at Paine Webber
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts and industry executives say TWA has too many
employees and some of the most inefficient work rules in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Buttrick said government figures indicated that TWA's New York
operations had lost $100 million a year over the last five years.
``They need to come up with a viable business plan for Kennedy and
the Atlantic or get out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the current negotiations, TWA has proposed abandoning one of
its two terminals at Kennedy, leaving the union to choose which
one. It has also offered to increase pay in exchange for work rule
changes that would raise productivity. The airline says it can only
afford to raise wages to 90 percent of the industry average because
it generates revenue at about 90 percent of the overall industry
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Buffenbarger termed the company's early offers ``an insult.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is in a good position to judge how much TWA can afford
to pay. In 1992, the union received a large amount of stock in the
airline in exchange for 11 percent wage cuts, and it currently has
three representatives on TWA's 15-member board of directors. All
employees, including the IAM members, now hold about 11 percent of
TWA's shares.
</P>
<P>
   Buffenbarger said the union's goal was to get the company's
last, best offer and then let its members decide whether to accept
it or to strike. ``The employees who belong to the machinists'
union are the ones who will make the final decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But TWA warns that the longer the negotiations drag on, the
harder it may be to reach a deal. ``It is going to be a challenge
for us to pay for a contract even if we don't lose any business,''
said Mark Abels, a TWA spokesman. ``If we start seeing customers
draining off as we get further into a cooling period, we will have
to take another look at the offer because we may not be able to
afford it anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
