<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-PATROL-$ADV23-     05-21 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINY BORDER FORCE BECOMES HUGE AND POWERFUL AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 23)   (ATTN: Arizona, California, Texas) 
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ John Hubert, a senior U.S. Border Patrol agent
here, finds himself compared to reptiles that vanished 65 million
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people consider me a dinosaur,'' Hubert, 52, confided as
his four-wheel drive vehicle rumbled along the edge of this
sprawling city on the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the good old days: getting covered in sweat and dust
when, as a solo agent, he spent hours tracking two dozen or more
illegal immigrants sneaking into the country.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert and those like him are a dying breed as the 2,000-mile
border is more under control than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   New agents often sit in air-conditioned vehicles parked beside
shopping malls or idling along the banks of the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   They radio for backup if they spot even five illegal immigrants
and are more adept at using computers and high-tech scopes than
spotting footprints in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smugglers, drug loads, gunfights: this was a great job,''
Hubert lamented. ``The thrill of the job was the catch.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long road for the Border Patrol, which started as
an obscure part of the U.S. Department of Labor and whose first
batch of officers 75 years ago did not have uniforms. The force is
now part of the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the shadows of the Franklin Mountains in West Texas the
patrol was launched on May 28, 1924. It was also here that a
controversial 1993 stand against illegal immigration _ known as
Operation Hold the Line _ would become a blue print for modern
operations from the Gulf of Mexico to the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 8,000 agents in green uniforms, the largest law
enforcement agency on the border has more manpower than ever. The
increased number of agents and a budget of more than $3 billion has
permitted the patrol to make dramatic changes in the Old West
tactics that made it famous.
</P>
<P>
   As agents trade their uniforms for tuxedos this week to attend
birthday bashes, a fight over the patrol's future is raging in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration says the patrol has reached its limit
for now, and pushing ahead with mass hiring will result in
lower-quality agents and too many rookies in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress, including Rep. Silvestre Reyes who as a
Border Patrol chief in El Paso introduced Hold the Line, contend
the administration shirked its responsibility when it recently
backed away from a congressional mandate to increase the agency's
ranks by hiring 1,000 new agents per year.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers such as Reyes, D-Texas, want the patrol's strength to
increase to 20,000 agents.
</P>
<P>
   Rugged vehicles and a fleet of $1.3 million high-tech
helicopters have all but replaced horses for working the severe
country along the border. Night-vision scopes and underground
sensors that detect movement have replaced watch towers with bells
and strings attached to cans.
</P>
<P>
   The patrol has flexed its new-found muscle to severely limit
illegal border crossing in El Paso and San Diego and is now
focusing its strength in the Rio Grande Valley and near Tucson,
Ariz. Next up is the brushland surrounding Laredo, Del Rio and
Eagle Pass in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, officials believe, they have a shot at
controlling places they long considered a no-man's land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have proven with the right support what was once a distant
possibility is becoming a distinct reality,'' said Gus De La Vina,
national chief of the Border Patrol. ``We are making some huge
strides.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents are stationed in 22 states, but most work along the
Mexican border, where 75 percent of the cocaine and marijuana in
the United States is believed to enter the country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, agents seized more than 11 tons of cocaine and 435 tons
of marijuana. That same year, 1.5 million illegal immigrants were
apprehended along the Southwest border.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's budget of $3 billion today is a far cry from the $1
million with which it started 75 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But critics charge the patrol is growing too fast. They say
agents are trampling on civil rights as towns and cities along the
border become zones of occupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these guys are doing is a raw exercise of power,'' Ray
Gil, a lawyer for the San Juan-based South Texas Civil Rights
Project, has said of the military-like presence that would be
unheard of away from the border.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to patrolling in vehicles, agents walk the streets
and ride bicycles through border cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic heading north is stopped at highway checkpoints where
agents often use drug-sniffing dogs to search vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 Amnesty International report chastised the patrol over
allegations of sexual abuse and beatings of those in its custody.
The agency promised to investigate the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allegations of ill treatment collected include people struck
with batons, fists or feet, often as punishment for attempting to
run away from Border Patrol agents,'' the report noted.
</P>
<P>
   A message scrawled in blood-red pen on a cement levee for the
Rio Grande near downtown El Paso warns ``Ojo Migra,'' Spanish slang
for ``Watch Out Border Patrol,'' along with a telephone number to
report abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have considered them a rough law enforcement
agency, but it is part of their jobs,'' said Pete G. Flores, who is
writing a book dedicated to agents who lost their lives on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have to be a lot more careful than your average
law enforcement agency,'' Flores said. ``They do not know if they
are up against people smugglers or dope smugglers who do not think
twice about exchanging gunfire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During Prohibition, agents, then known as inspectors, chased
whiskey smugglers. As World War II raged, agents took up posts
along the East Coast and watched for German submarines and
saboteurs.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of Japanese subversives led to the roundup of thousands of
West Coast residents of Japanese descent who were shipped inland to
at least three dozen detention camps nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   With the push for civil rights, hundreds of agents in riot gear
were deployed to Alabama and Mississippi in 1961 to guard black
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the windows were broken out in our vehicles,'' recalled
Allen ``Frito'' Fry, a retired agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never been exposed to racism to that extent _ pretty
girls would walk up and call us sons of bitches,'' said Fry, who in
1975 was shot in the stomach while patrolling an area near
Brownsville, Texas, known as the marijuana alley.
</P>
<P>
   A generation later, Fry's son, David, is an agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
