u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLPOX-620&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      05-21 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLPOX-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH GROUP DEFERS ERADICATION OF SMALLPOX STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JUDITH MILLER and LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Prompted by fears of a new outbreak of one of
the world's deadliest scourges, the World Health Assembly in Geneva
effectively decided Friday to defer eradicating the world's known
remaining stocks of the smallpox virus until at least 2002.
</P>
<P>
   While virtually all member states said they remained committed
to the elimination of the smallpox stocks as soon as possible, the
action taken by a key committee acting on consensus, without a
formal vote, reflected widespread agreement that more time is
needed to study smallpox before it is irrevocably destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's recommendations are to be formally approved
early next week, which World Health Organization officials said was
usually a pro forma matter.
</P>
<P>
   In the debate on Friday, many of the 25 national representatives
who spoke affirmed reluctantly the need for a stay of execution for
the virus, the third it has received since the 191-member
organization decided in 1980 to destroy the declared stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution also calls for the creation of an international
committee of experts to advise on whether further research is
needed and if so, what kind, and to devise an timetable for
eradication. It further specifies that the research should be
conducted in an ``open and transparent'' manner.
</P>
<P>
   The decision reflects a major shift in scientific thinking about
the virus since 1996, when the Assembly decided it should be
destroyed at the end of June 1999. It highlighted the existence of
increasingly rare political common ground between the United States
and Russia, the two remaining repositories of the deadly stocks.
Both Washington and Moscow have publicly opposed eradication of the
virus, at least until more research is done.
</P>
<P>
   Though smallpox was officially declared eradicated as a disease
in 1980, most officials now acknowledge that there are probably
clandestine smallpox stocks throughout the world, and that
retaining the virus could speed the development of new drugs to
fight an outbreak that occurred either naturally or as a result of
bioterrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, the U.S. secretary of health and human services,
who led the American delegation at the assembly, said that the
threat of bioterrorism, which was ``obscure'' only a few years ago,
had emerged as among ``the thorniest problems of the post-Cold War
era.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalala, who critics say was somewhat slow to recognize the
threat and the value of postponing eradication, said that the
growing bioterrorism threat required international health officials
to ``change and adapt our response'' and to coordinate efforts to
``prepare for an incident that we hope will never happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A turning point in official U.S. thinking about the virus's fate
came in March, when an independent scientific panel concluded that
research on the deadly smallpox virus could provide important
scientific and medical opportunities that would be lost if the
virus were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   While the committee was not asked whether the virus should be
kept or destroyed, its conclusions strongly influenced President
Clinton's decision to fight for at least temporary retention.
</P>
<P>
   Though almost none of the resolution's 27 co-sponsors mentioned
bioterrorism in their public remarks, fears that the virus might
once again trigger an epidemic in a now largely unvaccinated world
helped produce the new consensus, Western and foreign officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials said that the deferral was also influenced by
recent statements by a senior Soviet defector that the former
Soviet Union had secretly filled warheads of some of its
intercontinental ballistic missiles with smallpox, violating the
treaty it signed in 1972 banning such weapons.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an interview this week in Washington, Lev Sandakhchiev, the
director of Russia's State Research Center of Virology and
Biotechnology, known as Vector, where smallpox strains are stored,
would not comment on the former Soviet Union's germ weapons
programs. But he said he was certain that North Korea, among other
states, was secretly keeping smallpox stocks. Destroying the virus
would complicate efforts to develop new anti-viral drugs to counter
an outbreak, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandakhchiev said that an outbreak last year in the Democratic
Republic of Congo of monkey pox, a virus closely related to
smallpox, was a ``warning signal'' that led the Russian government
to redouble its efforts to defer eradication.
</P>
<P>
   The policy implications of the outbreak of more than 300 cases
of a disease that occasionally strikes humans but has not
traditionally spread quickly among them as smallpox once did, has
been debated by scientists within and outside Russia. The outbreak,
he argued, showed that a new form of smallpox might be evolving and
that it would be ``dangerous'' to conclude that the disease had
been eradicated.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Henderson, a scientist who led the campaign to eradicate
the virus and once served as deputy science adviser to the White
House, did not agree that the outbreak in Congo suggested that
smallpox was making a comeback in a milder form. Many of the cases
in Congo, he said, turned out to be not monkey pox, but chicken
pox.
</P>
<P>
   He and other advocates of immediate smallpox eradication vowed
Friday to ``continue fighting'' for the virus's destruction. He and
other advocates of smallpox destruction argue that while the virus
has been kept in tight security at both Vector and the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta for many years,
relatively little research has been done since the disease was
eradicated.
</P>
<P>
   They discount the notion that governments will spend precious
research dollars on studies of a disease that no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they say, even if the committee of experts that the
World Heath Assembly is supposed to create recommends new
experiments on smallpox, they will be funded at the expense of
research on other lethal diseases like tuberculosis, which is
spreading rapidly in the former Soviet Union, among other places.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
