<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-BIZARRE-TV-NYT     05-21 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BIZARRE-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL CHALLENGES OUTRAGEOUS TV SHOWS ON HUMAN-RIGHTS GROUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ This is a society that prides itself on
having a tolerant, even permissive, attitude about human
predilections. But even in Brazil's liberal climate there are
limits on sex, violence and the bizarre _ and the newly minted
television stars who go by the names Auntie and Little Rat have set
off a fierce national controversy by exceeding them.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, public outrage at the behavior of the two performers,
who appear on separate programs on different networks based here in
Brazil's largest city, has become so intense that the government is
being called on to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   But the Brazilian equivalent of the U.S. Federal Communications
Commission is toothless, and court challenges have thus far come to
naught. So the issue has been taken up by the Brazilian federal
government's human rights ombudsman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is indeed a human rights question,'' said Jose Gregori,
director of the human rights office. ``In terms of formal
democracy, Brazil has reached a satisfactory level. But in regard
to security and cultural marginalization, we need to correct
certain problems, and so my principal concern is to diminish
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Rat, known as Ratinho in Portuguese and Carlos Massa when
he is offstage, began his show less than two years ago. He invites
guests whose cases are more bizarre and pathetic than anything
Jerry Springer could imagine. Constant among them are victims of
unusual physical deformities, like a man with a gigantic tumor that
has grown over his face, or almost unimaginable brutality, like a
woman whose jealous husband had gouged her eyes out.
</P>
<P>
   Competing with the soap operas that have traditionally been the
backbone of prime-time programming in this nation of 165 million,
``Little Rat's Show'' has won its share of high ratings. National
marketing surveys indicate that the program appeals most strongly
to the urban working poor and inhabitants of rural areas, groups
that tend to be less educated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Ratinho because he shows the world as it truly is,''
said Antonio Pereira Ramos, 38, a Sao Paulo sanitation worker who
is a regular viewer.
</P>
<P>
   But Massa's image recently took a tumble when he intervened in
the kidnapping of the brother of a country music star. The singer
had been negotiating his brother's release with the kidnappers, but
when Ratinho began a fund-raising campaign to pay the ransom, they
raised their demand sixfold, to $1.25 million. Also, to demonstrate
their seriousness, they cut off one of their victim's ears and sent
it to a television station that carries the Ratinho program.
</P>
<P>
   Massa later apologized, saying his interference had been ``a
huge stupidity.'' But there have been demands that he be sent to
prison as an accomplice of the kidnappers. There has also been a
chorus of complaints that he will do anything to increase his
ratings, which in fact nearly doubled during the kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   The fuss over Auntie (Tiazinha in Portuguese) is perhaps more
surprising since, in contrast to American fare, prime-time
programming here has included nudity and daring love scenes for
several years. But Tiazinha, whose real name is Suzana Alves, has
built her appeal on a sensuality that goes far beyond what
Brazilians regard as natural or healthy, entering the realm of what
one magazine here described as ``S&AMP;M light.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing skimpy black lingerie and a mask and wielding a whip,
Tiazinha is the star of a peculiar quiz program that requires teams
of young people to answer questions about current events and
Brazilian culture. If they fail to respond correctly, Tiazinha
dances over to a team member _ always male and always bound and
gagged _ and rips hairs from his legs or stomach with tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a matinee as hot as this on Brazilian
television,'' the weekly magazine Manchete reported recently in an
admiring profile of the 20-year-old brown-skinned, dark-haired
model, who has dethroned a long line of blue-eyed, fair-haired soap
opera stars as the country's reigning sex symbol. ``Nobody makes
faces, purses her lips or wiggles, bumps and grinds as lasciviously
as Tiazinha.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alves' popularity is such that in the last four months she
has been the queen of Carnival, appeared in a long photo essay in
Playboy magazine and tried her luck as a singer on a best-selling
CD. But the foundation of her celebrity remains the daily
television program, which offends many.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad enough that activities of this sort should be shown
on television at all,'' said Maria das Gracas Neves Moreira, a
middle-aged housewife here. ``But for this girl to be making such
blatant appeals to base instincts when our children are likely to
be watching is a special disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, experts said, the explosion of outrageous
programming is a direct result of the economic stability and growth
that Brazil enjoyed until the devaluation of its currency in
January. After decades during which prices increased as much as
1,000 percent a year, inflation has dropped to virtually zero in
the last four years, allowing even the very poor to enjoy increases
in real income and save money to buy consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ratinho phenomenon causes perplexity among
intellectuals,'' Culture Minister Francisco Weffort said in a
recent interview, ``but it is only possible because people in the
lower sectors are buying television sets as never before.'' He
added that it was ``principally for them'' that ``programs of this
type'' were made by the nation's five strongly competitive
television networks.
</P>
<P>
   Weffort and other observers also see the proliferation of
Ratinho-style programs as a reaction to restrictions placed on
expression during two decades of military dictatorship, which ended
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together with democratization,'' Weffort said, ``there is a
climate of `anything goes.'''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's constitution, written in 1988, states that ``any and
all forms of political, ideological and artistic censorship are
forbidden.'' But the charter also requires producers of radio and
television programs to demonstrate ``respect for the ethical and
social values of the individual and the family,'' thereby providing
a legal basis for Gregori's campaign as ombudsman.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mission is not to impose any kind of censorship or
monitoring,'' he said. ``I just want the networks to pay attention
to the terms of their contract, which is a public concession that
requires them to contribute to the well-being of the citizenry, and
take steps themselves to improve the quality of their
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are also those who see the phenomenon primarily as an
expression of racial and class consciousness. Wagner Bezerra, a
media consultant and author of a new book called ``Manual of the
Dissatisfied Television Viewer,'' is one of them, noting that about
two-thirds of Brazil's population can be classified as black or
mulatto.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soap operas are full of rich white families in fancy cars,
and I think the population is tired of that,'' he said. ``Those
programs are saying, `You don't exist' to the dark-skinned
majority, and so they are seeking other options they can identify
with, that reflect their sentiments, even if they are negative and
bizarre.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
