s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-GRIPE-SITES-$ADV2     05-21 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-GRIPE-SITES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARD IT ON THE PC GRAPEVIVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Wash., Calif.)   (af)  
 By GEANNE ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When employees gossip about their jobs at the proverbial water
cooler, the atmosphere is often one of hushed tones and
over-the-shoulder glances. But no such discretion applies at the
Electronic Watercooler, an on-line network of uncensored bulletin
boards intended to attract employees and job seekers at more than
800 companies.
</P>
<P>
   The bulletin boards display office rumors, fears of layoffs,
complaints about work hours and pay and responses to applicants'
queries about salary and work life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we all realize that we'd be making at least twice as much
$$ if we went to Goldman?'' asked one writer, identified as a
Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell lawyer. ``We would definitely NOT be working
any harder at Goldman than we do here.''
</P>
<P>
   The network was started in March by Vault Reports, a New York
company, to attract visitors to its Web site, which also offers job
listings and employment matching services. To advise job hunters,
Vault also sells books and reports on specific companies _ all of
which are represented on the bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   The postings, which can be reached at www.vaultreports.com, have
been coming in fast and furious, with more than 5,200 so far,
including more than 1,000 in the last week. Some of the more active
boards include those on Goldman Sachs, Andersen Consulting, Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, Merrill Lynch, Microsoft and Procter &AMP; Gamble.
There are also more general ones for industries or types of
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically trying to take an age-old concept of gossiping
at the office water cooler and exploding it globally,'' said Samer
Hamadeh, co-founder of Vault Reports.
</P>
<P>
   The messages on the boards are generally anonymous _ often,
authors say, to avoid retribution. But the anonymity allows anyone
to pose as a company employee, job applicant or even a competitor.
Visitors can only hope that some postings are fictional, like one
person's score card of purported sexual exploits at a company
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Employment experts said the site should not be taken too
seriously. ``It's really not the water cooler,'' said Mark A.
Rothstein, a professor at the University of Houston Law Center who
is an expert in employment law. ``It's almost like the bar across
the street from the plant gate, because it involves not only people
who are currently working at the company but former employees and
total strangers, and there's really no way to verify whether these
people have the insider information that they pretend to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are not amused. In fact, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter blocked the site from office computers. In response, Vault
Reports parked a truck outside Morgan Stanley headquarters in
Manhattan and distributed fliers that described a different route
to the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanmarie McFadden, chief spokeswoman for Morgan Stanley, called
the site ``not conducive to the work environment.'' But she
conceded that companies would not be able to stop employees from
visiting the site from outside the office.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in fact, the site received many messages about Morgan
Stanley's widely publicized racial discrimination dispute with
Christian Curry, a dismissed employee. Some postings, representing
their authors as co-workers and Morgan Stanley clients, expressed
outrage at the firm's actions, including a supposed $10,000
payment, under investigation by the Manhattan district attorney's
office, to a police informant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really disgusted,'' one message said.
</P>
<P>
   But some messages challenged the authenticity of others _ one
contended that those supporting Curry had been written by the same
person. ``Just look at the writing style,'' it said, ``and the
common words and expressions.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley had no further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The risks of such sites include libel, breaches of privacy and
damage to corporate recruiting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Someone identifying herself as a Procter &AMP; Gamble job seeker
asked on the bulletin board if the company's culture required
``marriage to the corporation and family last.'' After several
responses, she resurfaced with the message: ``Think I'll hold off a
bit on accepting the P and G offer. Who needs the stress?''
</P>
<P>
   Employees who post damaging messages do so at their peril. ``If
employers are able to determine who is actually posting the
information, there would probably be little to stop the employer
from taking action,'' Rothstein said.
</P>
<P>
   What are the chances that a company can track down senders of
anonymous E-mail? ``Oh, we do it all the time,'' said John Jessen,
president and chief executive of Electronic Evidence Discovery
Inc., based in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Companies can easily monitor employees' on-site Internet
activity, and employees have been fired. Edward Jones, the
brokerage firm, recently dismissed 19 people who it said had failed
to admit that they had sent pornography or off-color jokes over
internal e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   But even some company managers see an upside. While surfing the
Web, Ed Collins, a senior vice president in Young &AMP; Rubicam's
office in Irvine, Calif., learned about the forums at Vault Reports
and posted a message saying, ``I think it's a great tool to post
information that you'd like to have people respond to'' and invited
employees of the advertising agency to chat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
