<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories and photos on the
continuing crisis over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Diplomatic developments on Kosovo.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICY (Washington) _ Between the two options that
President Clinton has declared unacceptable _ doing nothing or
all-out war _ the White House has devised a new kind of warfare for
Yugoslavia. It is a calibrated war, enabled by high-tech weaponry,
shaped by the flickering light of opinion polls and shackled by
fear that a few American combat deaths could turn the public
against any military intervention in an obscure place called
Kosovo. By Blaine Harden and John Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The Yugoslav foreign minister
insists that the United Nations, not NATO, be the key player in
settlement. He says: ``Read my lips. It's not about NATO, it's
about U.N.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Tirana, Albania) _ The Kosovo rebel group, the
KLA, which says that Russians are fighting in Kosovo, announces
that it has killed one and shows his body, according to Russian
television. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ NATO warplanes attacking a
military compound in northwestern Kosovo struck what Yugoslavia's
official news agency described as a prison, killing at least 19
inmates and guards. The strike came as NATO faced mounting concerns
about its targeting, even from within the alliance. NATO's attacks
nevertheless resumed a furious pace Friday after intermittently bad
weather severely hampered strikes. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Plus this story for the Culture Desk's Ideas Page:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOOK (Undated) _ How do books influence public
policy, or more specifically, how do some books come to be read by
policy makers while others are not? Consider the case of President
Clinton and Robert D. Kaplan's ``Balkan Ghosts,'' a book that the
writers Richard Reeves and Elizabeth Drew say profoundly shaped the
President's thinking on the limitations of intervention in a part
of the world where ethnic feuds have deep roots. By Michael T.
Kaufman. (1000 words)
</P>
