<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-CARR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTLOOK NOT HEAVENLY FOR CARR VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oba Carr says God will intervene on his behalf
Saturday night when he tries to take the World Boxing Council
welterweight title away from Oscar De La Hoya at the new Mandalay
Bay Resort Events Center. If God does, He may have to beat the
referee to it.
</P>
<P>
   Carr is a more than competent prize fighter, arguably one of the
half-dozen best 147-pounders in the world. Because of that, he is
being given his third chance to win a welterweight title.
Unfortunately for him, few observers of matters fistic believe this
opportunity will end any differently than his previous two, unless
a higher power has cable and tunes it to HBO around 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In those earlier fights, Carr had his moments, putting both
International Boxing Federation champion Felix Trinidad and World
Boxing Association champion Ike Quartey on their backs. He knocked
two of the three best welterweights in the world flat, which is an
accomplishment of some note, but it must also be noted that both
got up and one, Trinidad, went on to knock Carr cold, while the
other, Quartey, survived an 11th-round knockdown to win a majority
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, Carr has an unblemished record (48-2-1) and
that is what has brought him the opportunity to become the first
man to fight De La Hoya, Trinidad, and Quartey and if he can drop
De La Hoya as he did the others, he would have an odd trifecta,
being the only fighter to accomplish the feat. What he must avoid
however _ and what he believes God has assured him _ is becoming
the only fighter to lose to all three as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to a mesmerizing fight,'' the born-again
Christian told the world this week. ``I had a vision about fighting
Oscar De La Hoya several years ago. That vision has been consistent
ever since. Soon the vision will come true in a supernatural way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victory is already done in heaven. Now it just has to be
done on earth. Ever since I left Don King and turned my life to the
Lord, He has blessed me. People just do not understand. I've shown
the world I can box. People just haven't seen the other side of me.
I am going to drop the bomb. I have been resurrected. I will
resurrect boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is right and his God is a boxing fan, Carr may have to
resurrect sports books all over Las Vegas as well because they have
universally installed him as a 10-1 underdog against the undefeated
De La Hoya (30-0). If Carr can overcome those odds, he not only
will have beaten a fighter many consider the pound-for-pound best
in the world, but he will have beaten the town that has broken more
hearts than the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya patiently listened Thursday afternoon as Carr stood
at a press conference pulpit and preached the word as he understood
it. The word he'd heard was that there was big trouble coming
Saturday night at the Mandalay Bay Events Center after the first
bell sounds, and De La Hoya agreed. The source of the trouble was
the only issue in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are going to be the first to witness the old but also
the new Oscar,'' De La Hoya said. ``I have returned to my old
style. Enough with all the boxing stuff. Let's just take care of
the job and fight. Let our fists do the talking.''
</P>
<P>
   The normally soft-spoken De La Hoya has been threatening to go
on the offensive more for nearly two months, claiming he, too, had
a dream a while back. There was no hint of divine intervention in
his dream, however. His was about something more basic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just hit me,'' De La Hoya said. ``What am I doing boxing
these guys? I'm not a boxer. I'm a fighter. What am I doing boxing
guys like Pernell Whitaker and Ike Quartey? I was not fighting my
own style. I should be the leader in that ring but I was adjusting
to them, not them adjusting to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was I doing talking about losing before the Quartey
fight? I decided to listen to myself and be what I want in the
ring. This fight, you'll see a big difference. I'm going to become
more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's critics have noted his knockout percentage has
dwindled since he began moving up in weight from his original 130
pounds to 135, then 140, and now 147. Although he has 24 knockouts
among his 30 victories, he was taken the distance in four of his
last eight fights and has not had a spectacular knockout against a
true challenger in several years, unless you disagree with the
widely held belief that the Julio Cesar Chavez he stopped twice was
an aged and fragile shadow of his former self.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the lightweight division, De La Hoya has been
taken the distance by Whitaker, Quartey, Miguel Angel Gonzalez, and
Hector Camacho and was beginning to feel the dread opponents once
had for him had waned. He blames this on the parade of trainers he
brought in at other's insistence over the past few years, dating to
the importation of a Mexican aluminum siding salesman and defensive
genius named Jesus Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera improved De La Hoya's defense but blunted his offense and
although Emanuel Steward reversed that, he could not survive in the
Hispanic world of advisers who surround De La Hoya and he soon was
cut loose in favor of Gil Clancy and De La Hoya's boyhood trainer,
Robert Alcazar.
</P>
<P>
   That chorus of voices is allegedly going to change after this
fight, the champion has said, and there are rumors Clancy will be
jettisoned along with a number of the growing retinue that
surrounds the young champion.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not the cacophony of voices vying for his attention
that will be on his mind Saturday night. Saturday night Oscar De La
Hoya's mind will be filled with thoughts only of Oba Carr and an
urge to prove the only intervention that will be able to save him
will have to come from a quick-thinking referee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was losing total respect, the respect I had four years
ago,'' De La Hoya said of the less aggressive style he plans to
abandon Saturday night. ``I lost respect every single fight the
last three, four years. I used to walk through my opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``My last few fights people tried to make me a boxer but that's
not my style. I'm not a boxer. I'm a slugger. I'm going back to
what got me here.''
</P>
<P>
   What got Oscar De La Hoya world titles in four weight classes
was aggression. What Oba Carr believes will get him his first is
divine interventio. Carr may be right, but in boxing it's safer to
bet on the guy doing the punching than the guy doing the praying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
