<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMOTERS AGREE ON DE LA HOYA-TRINIDAD FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Much more will be riding on the outcome of
Saturday's fight with Oba Carr than Oscar De La Hoya thought. Like
another $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of blustery negotiations, promoters Don King and
Bob Arum reached agreement Friday on the terms of a De La
Hoya-Felix Trinidad welterweight unification fight Sept. 18 here at
the Mandalay Bay Resort Events Center. The two had been negotiating
for weeks, with Arum finally offering Trinidad a $10 million
guarantee through King a week ago that carried with it a Wednesday
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   When King countered with his own offer Tuesday, the two began to
talk again with HBO Sports senior vice president Lou DiBella. Late
Thursday, they agreed on the financial terms after Trinidad
demanded an additional $1 million in guaranteed money and an
increase of his share of the pay-per-view sales.
</P>
<P>
   Arum will pay King $10.5 million for Trinidad's services, with
an additional $500,000 believed to be coming from other sources,
while the number of pay-per-view sales required for Trinidad to
begin seeing an upside above his guarantee was cut from Arum's
original stipulation of 1 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, who will be guaranteed $16 million and is likely to
make at least $20 million, has never done more than 750,000
pay-per-view sales and Trinidad has done nowhere near those
numbers, so the 1 million figure almost ensured Trinidad would see
no additional income beyond his guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the money was agreed to, Arum, who will be the lead
promoter, refused to sign until King informed him how many hotel
rooms and tickets he would seek. That remained the sticking point
until midday Friday, when the sides finally agreed on all points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's done,'' Arum said before Friday's weigh-in for the
Carr-De La Hoya fight. ``We jiggled the upside some and I'm
guaranteeing Trinidad $10.5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Some insiders believe King agreed to the deal because his
contract with Trinidad requires he guarantee the International
Boxing Federation champion more in purses than the fighter can
generate on pay-per-view on his own. So by making this deal, it
eases the financial burden on King, win or lose. If Trinidad loses,
the value of his contract is lessened considerably. If he wins, he
becomes the instant king of the division as well as a likely
candidate to fight De La Hoya again for an even bigger payday in a
rematch, although there is no rematch clause in the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wins, he's on top of the world,'' Arum said of King.
``If he doesn't, Trinidad becomes more manageable for King.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
