<SLUG> BC-MA-JOBLESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE   UNEMPLOYMENT RATE RISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Massachusetts jobless rate rose slightly last
month, but 5,900 new jobs added in April pushed the number of
people employed in the state to yet another record.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate rose one-tenth of a percentage point to
2.9 percent in April, the Massachusetts Division of Employment and
Training said Friday, in its monthly report.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of 5,900 new jobs were in the services sector,
especially business services. A slight rise in the jobless rate was
caused by an expansion of the labor force. The number of residents
working in all jobs statewide hit 3.18 million in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the third month in a row, the number of people employed is
at a new high,'' said Elliot Winer, the division's chief economist.
</P>
<P>
   The job gains in Massachusetts are only part of the story of a
prosperity that is spreading throughout New England. Strong job
growth and low unemploymentin April saw Vermont's jobless rate fall
to 2.6 percent from 3.1 percent, and New Hampshire's to 2.4 percent
from 3.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time New England had three states under 3 percent was
in July 1988,'' said Denis McSweeney, regional commissioner of the
federal Bureau of Labor Statistics. At that time Connecticut, New
Hampshire, Rhode Island, and Vermont all had rates below 3 percent.
Massachusetts had a 3.3 percent jobless rate in July 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
