<HEADER>
A6515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITAMIN-ROCHE-525&AMP;ADD     05-21 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAMIN-ROCHE-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP ROCHE EXECUTIVES SAY THEY'RE BLAMELESS IN PRICE-FIXING SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Germany and Switzerland )(ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASEL, Switzerland _ One day after admitting that some senior
executives were ringleaders in a nine-year price-fixing cartel for
vitamins, the chairman and the chief executive of Roche Holding AG
pronounced themselves blameless and clueless Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will understand that this was not part of our
responsibility,'' said Franz B. Humer, the chief executive. ``It is
certainly not easy to understand the reasons for actions of
employees who in secrecy organized a conspiracy of this kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Roche, a pharmaceutical conglomerate based here, was by far the
biggest player in what the U.S. Justice Department has described as
a sophisticated cartel to fix worldwide vitamin prices as much as
25 percent above the market level.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Roche agree to pay $500 million to settle charges
with the Justice Department. Two of its top executives resigned,
and one of them agreed to serve a four-month prison sentence in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, at a news conference at company headquarters, both the
chairman and the chief executive were almost completely at a loss
to explain how the wrongdoing could have happened _ or what they
would do to keep it from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Roche was not alone. BASF AG of Germany agreed to
settle similar charges by paying $225 million in fines.
Rhone-Poulenc &UR;  &LR; of France, which was also part of the cartel but
provided crucial information to prosecutors, was allowed to escape
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   But Roche was the undisputed heavyweight, controlling about 40
percent of the worldwide vitamin market. It also had a history of
price fixing: in 1997, the same division that was implicated
Thursday had to pay a $14 million fine for its involvement in
fixing the price of citric acid and lysine, which are food
additives.
</P>
<P>
   The potential liabilities of Roche and BASF were clearly on the
minds of investors. Roche shares fell 330 Swiss francs, or nearly 2
percent, to close at 16,670. BASF was down 0.05 euros, to 39.25,
while Rhone-Poulenc was up 1.44 euros, to 48.39.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Roche case most remarkable is that the executives
embroiled in the last round of price-fixing were apparently
involved in the latest one as well _ even as Roche was vowing to
clean up its practices.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Humer attributed the wrongdoing to what he called the
secret machinations of the implicated executives. He insisted that
the company had ``never tolerated practices of this kind.'' He
vowed to start a ``vigorous information campaign'' that would tell
all employees about ethical practices.
</P>
<P>
   But even as they promised to restore Roche's credibility with
its corporate customers _ a number of whom have filed suit _ the
Roche executives could not explain what had happened or why.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know what they did,'' Fritz Gerber, Roche's
chairman, said. The problem, he said, was that the most important
source of information was the Justice Department and that Roche did
not have access to the government's evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that there was an elaborate conspiracy that was
kept entirely secret by a small group of employees,'' Humer said.
But, he said, ``we are very reliant on what the Justice Department
has published.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By all accounts, the conspiracy was sophisticated and global.
Roche, BASF and Rhone-Poulenc control more than 80 percent of the
world vitamin market.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies have admitted forming a cartel in 1990 that
lasted until this year and that included most of the world's
smaller producers.
</P>
<P>
   In its indictment, the Justice Department said that executives
from the companies met secretly to set prices and carve up the
market. According to the government, the conspiracy involved people
at many levels of management and was operated with the smoothness
of a single company _ ``Vitamins Inc.,'' in one government
characterization.
</P>
<P>
   The big question Friday was how Roche, which had already run
afoul of the Justice Department, could let such a thing happen.
</P>
<P>
   The costs will almost certainly be much higher than the $500
million that Roche agreed to pay to the U.S. government. All
companies in the cartel face class-action lawsuits from the
companies that bought their vitamins, which are produced for human
uses as well as fed to animals.
</P>
<P>
   Both Roche and BASF have announced plans to seek out-of-court
settlements on the lawsuits, but those could cost hundreds of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also face possible fines from the European
Commission's competition authorities, who are looking into the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   By Roche's reckoning, the central villains were Roland
Broennimann, head of the Vitamins and Fine Chemicals Division since
1989, and Kuno Sommer, head of marketing for the vitamin division
from 1994 until 1997, when he was promoted to chief executive of
Roche's flavors and fragrances subsidiary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sommer, 43, pleaded guilty to violating antitrust laws and to
obstruction of justice. As part of a plea bargain, he will serve
four months in prison. Bronnimann is still under investigation and
may yet face indictments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sommer apparently distinguished himself as a star performer.
Sales jumped from 3 billion francs to 3.8 billion francs between
1995 and 1997, and Roche rewarded him by putting him in charge of
the flavors and fragrances business and by elevating him to the
management board, known as the Corporate Executive Committee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roche executives refused to say where either of the two departed
executives were Friday. Roche said neither man would receive any
special severance package, though they would be entitled to their
accrued retirement benefits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can surely understand, we are extremely angry,'' Humer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerber, who took over as chairman in 1978, just two years after
the European Union imposed huge fines for illegal pricing
practices, said he was upset as well. ``It is most unpleasant for
me personally,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
