<HEADLINE>
OLD COLORS WON'T FADE IN TRACTOR DEAL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)   (af)  
 By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind the Wall Street reaction. When two big farm equipment
makers, New Holland NV and the Case Corp., announced last week that
they would merge, one question seemed to be on every customer's
mind: What color?
</P>
<P>
   As in, will the merged company's products be painted in New
Holland's signature blue or Case's trademark red? Or will they mix
them into _ gasp _ purple?
</P>
<P>
   It's not as trivial a question as it might seem. Brand identity
in farm equipment has long been defined by color. For decades,
farmers across the Midwest divided into ``green guys'' who owned
John Deere equipment, ``red guys'' who preferred International
Harvester and ``blue guys'' who bought Ford. On the Great Plains,
the combine color code can be read for miles.
</P>
<P>
   Changes of ownership in the 1980s created a new scorecard: Case
adopted the red when it acquired IH. The original blue, Ford,
acquired New Holland, but Fiat of Italy then bought most of the
combined operation; it will also be majority owner of the New
Holland-Case combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Color loyalty is serious business,'' said Lynn Haseley, who
grows corn and soybeans in Beason, Ill. ``My father was a red guy
and my grandfather was a red guy. I grew up with red. I'm a
die-hard red fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Armstrong, host of a daily radio show for farmers on WGN, a
Chicago station that reaches much of the Midwest, said the merger
was the talk of his audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy called in yesterday; he was all lathered up about
it,'' Armstrong said. ``It's just too weird to imagine an IH
combine anything but red.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who grew up on a farm (red), could recall
grade-school fights over whether red or green was superior. ``Of
course, if they weren't red (italics)or(end italics) green, well,
we just felt bad for those poor kids.''
</P>
<P>
   What do the merging companies say? That the old color scheme is
safe. ``Our brand is our color,'' said Bill Masterson, a Case
spokesman. ``The color identity of our products is so important
that we are going to create a multibrand company,'' retaining both
Case red and New Holland blue.
</P>
<P>
   But what if a future corporate reshuffler decides that one color
is plenty? ``Boy,'' said Haseley, blanching at the thought of
himself atop a Case-IH tractor painted blue. ``Well, I guess we'll
just have to find a way to get through it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
