</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PENNIES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENNIES FROM HEAVEN (OR JARS)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good news for merchants in southeastern Missouri: the Great Cape
Girardeau Penny Shortage is over.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the outlook was grim. Penny supplies were running
low at the Mercantile Bank, which provides coins to many local
retailers, including local Sam's Club and Wal-Mart stores. And the
bank was told that new shipments from the Federal Reserve Bank of
St. Louis could not be expected before June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that people tend to throw their pennies in a jar at home
rather than spend them, the Mercantile Bank's president, Lowell
Peterson, decided to lure some out of hiding by posting a note on
the bank's front door starting last Monday. It offered $1.10 for
every 100 pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Word got out _ in the local paper, then local television, then
national news wires _ and soon set off ``a phenomenal nationwide
outpouring of copper,'' Peterson said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy called wanting to drive up 700 miles from Louisiana with
$1,000 worth,'' he said. ``We heard from a grade school in
Pennsylvania, from a radio station in Spokane.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first few hours, local people brought in more pennies
than the bank knew what to do with, so Peterson took down the note
and spent the rest of the week politely disappointing out-of-town
callers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crisis averted,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
