<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6522 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCSALAD-TEST-WRITETHR     05-21 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCSALAD-TEST-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALAD IN A CUP MAY SHAKE UP FAST-FOOD WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, corrects missing first reference to Lopaty) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ McDonald's has come up with something new for a
car's cup holder: tossed salads.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-food giant is selling McSalad Shakers, a 21 oz.
salad-in-a-cup, in Los Angeles-area restaurants in a test run that
began last week. Customers buying McSalads just pour dressing over
their salad, pop the domed lid onto the clear plastic cup, and do
the James Bond thing _ shake it, don't stir.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a portable tossed salad, with the dressing
distributed across the salad and coating the sides of the cup. It's
served with a longer-than-usual plastic fork.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cup itself fits into most cup holders in the car,'' said
Lisa Dellerson, regional marketing supervisor at McDonald's Corp.'s
San Diego office. ``You hit the brake and you don't have salad and
packaging flying around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an evolution in salads.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers can choose between a garden, chef, or chicken Caesar
McSalad Shaker. Dressings are Caesar, ranch, light vinaigrette,
light French, Thousand Island, and honey mustard. Prices range from
$1.89 to $2.59.
</P>
<P>
   Oakbrook, Ill.-based McDonald's Corp. also is selling the salad
in a test run in Salt Lake City; Columbus, Ohio; and
Raleigh-Durham, N.C. Some of the cities have had the product for as
long as two months, Dellerson said.
</P>
<P>
   Though in the testing stage, the Shakers are likely to become a
permanent fixture on local menus, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very confident it will do well and we'll keep it, if
it's what our customers need and satisfies them _ and we believe it
definitely will,'' Dellerson said.
</P>
<P>
   The salads have been released without the usual McDonald's
fanfare, so far. The only notice of their availability are small
signs and a display bin inside each store.
</P>
<P>
   But an advertising blitz is scheduled to start May 28. and all
600 or so Los Angeles-area McDonald's will be equipped to prepare
and sell the new salads, Dellerson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles region, which includes parts of Ventura and
Orange counties, was an ideal testing ground for the new product
for several reasons, according to Dellerson.
</P>
<P>
   First, Southern California practically invented the healthy
lifestyle. And the automobile craze. Plus, Angelenos eat out
frequently and are looking for dining options, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a diverse customer base here and we're pretty
confident that Southern California is a good salad market,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Miller, a spokeswoman for Miami-based Burger King Corp.,
said the company does not comment on competitors' products.
</P>
<P>
   However, she did say that the Burger King chain for several
years had required that all its restaurants carry salads.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, the chain left it up to local restaurants to
decide whether to carry the product when it became apparent that
salads didn't sell well in every market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had spot success in some markets that performed very
well,'' she said. ``And in some, consumers didn't make a special
trip for the salads.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McSalad Shakers are selling quite well at the five
Los Angeles-area franchises that Keith Lopaty owns and operates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably selling six times what we were selling of the
old salads, and this is without any type of advertising,'' Lopaty
said. ``They're very tasty and there's a lot of different
ingredients that go into the chef salad and garden salad that we
weren't putting in the old chef salad and garden salad.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the McSalad should appeal to the parent who
takes a youngster in for a Happy Meal but who might not otherwise
eat at McDonald's, Lopaty said.
</P>
<P>
   And they're perfect for the on-the-go diner, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cup allows the salad to be totally portable,'' Lopaty
said. ``It's as easy to walk around with as a drink.''
</P>
<P>
   The salads attracted the attention _ and curiosity _ of Jack
Dennison, a West Hills resident who dropped by a Woodland Hills
McDonald's on Thursday with his wife, Rosemary, for a burger and
soda.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he wandered over to the glass case sitting on the
counter containing the freshly mixed salads.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you eat it?'' he asked, examining the long cups.
</P>
<P>
   After being assured that the longer forks reach all the way to
the bottom of the cup, Dennison said he would have bought one had
he only spotted them before he ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Dennison immediately recognized how the McSalad could
appeal to the harried, hungry commuter. ``It makes it easier when
you're in a car.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
