<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6530 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-2TAKES-     05-21 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORROWING SENATE STRATEGY, HOUSE DEMOCRATS PRESS FOR GUN-CONTROL
MEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fresh from their victory on gun control in the
Senate, Democrats on Friday trained their attention and oratory on
the House, calling for a gun-control vote within the next week and
lambasting Republican leaders for laying out a less immediate
course.
</P>
<P>
   In making that demand, House Democrats were plucking a page from
the play book of their Senate counterparts, who greeted every
Republican concession on gun control over the past two weeks with
the charge that it was too little, too late and still out of step
with public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, who had promised on Thursday to allow a vote
on gun-control measures by the middle of June, accused Democrats of
engaging in political theatrics. But even as the two sides sniped
at each other about timing, they agreed that the House would
probably pass at least a few new restrictions on firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be some aspects of what the House does
which will include making it more difficult for teenage kids to get
ahold of guns,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida, the Republican
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee's subcommittee on crime.
McCollum's juvenile crime bill would be the likely vehicle for
those measures.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen House Democrats met with President Clinton at the White
House Friday afternoon to plot their strategy for making sure the
measures succeed. The plan, they said, was to use whatever bully
pulpit they had to persuade Republican leaders to act now, before
conservatives in the party or gun lobbyists disrupted the momentum
of events in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make our voices heard every day,'' said Rep.
Nita M. Lowey, D-N.Y., after leaving the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lowey, who is expected to run for the Senate next year if
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton does not, added, ``I wonder if
all those people afraid to send their kids to school want to see us
debate this issue for the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Republican leaders could bring the bill passed by the
Senate to the floor immediately, it would be highly unusual.
Instead, they intend to let a similar House bill proceed through a
House committee and then come to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The pledge by Republican leaders to let a debate on gun control
occur indicated an unequivocal alteration in the political climate,
just as the bill passed by the Senate on Thursday night had.
</P>
<P>
   That legislation, approved by a vote of 73 to 25, contained an
array of new regulations, such as a requirement that licensed gun
dealers include child safety devices with every handgun they sell,
restrictions on the possession of semi-automatic assault rifles by
those under 18, mandatory background checks on all buyers at gun
shows and a ban on the import of high-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   None of those measures represented monumental shifts in public
policy. But, taken together, they were arguably gun control
advocates' biggest victory in Congress in half a decade.
</P>
<P>
   If the House passes similar measures as part of its own juvenile
crime legislation, the House and Senate bills would then go to a
conference committee to reconcile any differences. A final vote
would be held before sending the measure to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Already, House Republicans have signaled more receptiveness to
gun control, though they have also exhibited a nervousness about
the debate being forced on them too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, as the Senate was passing its legislation, both the
House Appropriations and Judiciary committees postponed hearings to
finalize two separate bills after Democrats threatened to try to
attach gun-control amendments. One of those bills was McCollum's,
which Republicans had been insisting was not an appropriate vehicle
for gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois, and the Democratic
minority leader, Richard Gephardt of Missouri, met Thursday
afternoon to decide how and when to deal with the gun-control
measures the Senate had passed.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said that the measures could indeed fold into McCollum's
bill and suggested a vote in the middle of June. But when Gephardt
presented that plan to fellow Democrats a few hours later, many of
them pronounced it unacceptable. Gephardt then appeared on the
House floor and called for a vote next week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom Delay, R-Texas, released a statement
Friday denouncing Gephardt's speech, which Delay said contradicted
the satisfaction that Gephardt had expressed with Hastert's
timetable in a meeting with Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all quite surprised that Gephardt did not stick to our
agreement,'' Delay said, adding that Gephardt must not have been
able to sway other Democrats to his viewpoint. ``It is troubling to
witness that Gephardt seemingly does not have the confidence and
trust of his caucus.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sue Harvey, a spokeswoman for Gephardt, said Friday that he
had made no agreement before consulting other House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democratic aides conceded that there was indeed a rift
among House Democrats in terms of strategy, with some finding
Hastert's timetable acceptable and others intent on rejecting it.
Technically, the Democrats are virtually powerless to force a vote.
</P>
<P>
   A crime subcommittee hearing on gun-control amendments to
McCollum's bill is scheduled for Thursday; in two weeks, the full
House Judiciary Committee is expected to finalize and vote on that
bill.
</P>
<P>
   It could wind up including one gun-control measure _ a raise, to
21 from 18, in the minimum age for the legal purchase and
possession of a handgun _ that is not in the Senate bill. Early
this week, Hastert announced support for raising the age for
purchases, but not possession.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who spent 18 years in the House,
said Friday that gun control is usually a tougher sell there. But,
he said, ``The actual measures we passed in the Senate were modest,
and there has now been a change in public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., one of the House's staunchest
opponents of gun control, agreed with the second half of Schumer's
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Barr added, ``There will be some members who will be swayed by
the president's browbeating and Mr. Gephardt stamping his feet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
