<HEADER>
A6533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTDRIVE-MUSTANG22-C     05-21 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-MUSTANG22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mustang not stuck in sand
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe the folks at Ford who created the '99 Mustang
have been out in the sun too long, perhaps testing their
convertible. Or maybe they're so caught up in the ongoing
fascination with things Egyptian that they really think it makes
sense to say that the new 'Stang is visually comparable to a
pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Those Egyptian pyramids, they should remember, have been stuck,
immovable and immutable, in the sand for millennia. They hardly
invite Ford design chief Doug Gaffka's comment that the Mustang
design is ``based on the most stable geometric form _ the
pyramid.''
</P>
<P>
   Stable? At speed, that's a good thing, and the new Mustang is
just that. But enthusiasts also want a Mustang that comes off the
line spinning its tires and feeling akin to a horse that has taken
the bit in its mouth and is going to break away unless its driver
really takes control.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, the new Mustang can do that _ sensibly and with an
impressive degree of built-in safety. There's a tweaked 4.6-liter
V-8 engine that, mated with a five-speed manual transmission, can
bolt off the line, and, for control and safety, there's power
anti-lock disc brakes and a switchable traction control.
</P>
<P>
   ``More controlled and comfortable, but certainly not hobbled,''
says AutoWeek. ``Meaner, faster, edgier,'' says Motor Trend. Solid
_ OK, stable _ and sometimes sluggish in handling and acceleration,
a test drive reveals.
</P>
<P>
   But the bright-yellow test car, a 3,100-pound GT coupe totaling
$24,495, was clearly hobbled by its four-speed automatic. Even with
the engine working toward its maximums of 260 horsepower at 5,240
rpm and 300 pounds-feet of torque at 4,000 rpm, the GT was slow on
starts.
</P>
<P>
   But get it up to expressway speed, and the Mustang is nicely
responsive with power for passing and a striking level of ride
comfort. The steering provided a bit of feel at center and good
inputs in turns. But that long front end feels heavy and wants to
push out instead of lithely turning in. (Time for throttle-steer,
the buff books recommend, and while goosing the gas and swinging
out the rear end is good on test tracks, it isn't acceptable on
highways.)
</P>
<P>
   The power anti-lock disc brakes are another strong feature, with
good pedal feel and serious stopping capability (60 mph to zero in
about 125 feet). That area of performance, along with the
bump-smoothing nature of a suspension compromised between handling
and ride, is notably improved.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively unchanged interior has supportive, easily
adjusted front seats with a rear for kids or cargo. The
instrumentation and controls, like the V-8 engine, are basic and
work well.
</P>
<P>
   As for the looks, it's a matter of personal preference, although
few are likely to be impressed by the Mustang's faux air scoops.
And while the test GT drew admiring comments and nods of approval,
absolutely no one likened it to a pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Ford Mustang GT rear-drive coupe
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $24,495 (base price: $20,870)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, power anti-lock disc brakes,
optional traction control ($230)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 4.6-liter V-8 engine (260 horsepower), optional
four-speed automatic transmission with overdrive lockout ($815)
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: upgraded stereo system, $395;
17-inch forged aluminum wheels with 245/45ZR17 tires, $500; package
with power driver's seat, cruise control, rear defroster, front
floor mats, $550; leather interior, $500; lighted visor mirrors,
$95; cigarette lighter and ashtray, $15
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 17 mpg regular unleaded city, 27 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
