<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELLUCCI-GEORGES-BOS &LR;      05-21 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLUCCI-GEORGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCI NOD TOWARD GEORGES BANK ENERGY DRILLING DRAWS FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Breaking ranks with other Massachusetts politicians on
a volatile international issue, Governor Paul Cellucci has
cautiously endorsed oil and gas exploration on the Canadian side of
the Georges Bank fishing ground, drawing criticism from fishermen
and environmentalists on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian government, under pressure from major oil
companies, is considering reopening its side of Georges Bank in
January 2000 after a 10-year moratorium. Although the US side would
remain closed, opponents say a spill on the Canadian side could be
swept by the currents to US fishing grounds.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci, in Nova Scotia last week on a trade mission, told
newspaper editors there that he would support lifting Canada's
moratorium on oil and gas exploration as long as there were enough
environmental safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are resources there, I think we would want to get
those resources,'' Cellucci told the Halifax Herald.
</P>
<P>
   The comment marked Cellucci's second controversial insertion
into Canadian affairs. Last year, many Canadians were upset at
remarks that seemed to support independence for Quebec. Cellucci
later said he was only expressing ``enthusiasm'' for continued
business dealings with the province.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of oil and gas exploration on Georges Bank had hoped
that the newspaper account was wrong, but Cellucci's aides
confirmed this week that the governor supports a re-evaluation of
the safety of oil and gas drilling in one of the world's richest
fishing grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that there are significant resources that could
have a significant impact on energy costs in Massachusetts, which
are among the highest in the nation,'' spokeswoman Ilene Hoffer
said. ``They are at the same time contained within a fragile
ecosystem. He wants to look at whether or not it is possible to
harness those resources without disturbing that ecosystem.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's remarks stunned critics of oil and gas exploration,
which came as Massachusetts members of Congress increased efforts
to block exploration. US Representative William Delahunt, for
instance, was scheduled to be in Montreal Saturday to lobby members
of parliament to keep the bank closed. In fact, Cellucci's own
representative to the Canadian hearings last winter warned that the
potential risks of exploration might outweigh the regional
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a shock and disappointment,'' said Angela
Sanfilippo, president of the Gloucester Fishermen's Wives
Association. ``After talking with the people in Canada . . . and
guaranteeing to them that the Commonwealth of Massachusetts was
behind them, we don't know what to say to those people.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Wells, a former member of Canada's Parliament who is
directing much of the opposition to lifting the moratorium, said
Cellucci had given comfort to oil companies by showing division
among Massachusetts officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major, major issue up here and, as soon as he breathes
that, he's totally against everything coming out of New England,''
said Wells, coordinator of NORIGS 2000, a coalition of fishing,
environmental, and municipal groups that opposes oil and gas
exploration on Georges Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Shelley of the Conservation Law Foundation, a Boston-based
group that has fought oil and gas drilling on Georges Bank since
1977, said Cellucci seems to be reversing a Massachusetts position
held for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden for the governor of the state to come out,
without any consultation, and undercut a pretty clear understanding
of what the state's position was, and to do it in a Halifax
newspaper, that's not how I'd like to hear this,'' Shelley said.
</P>
<P>
   Georges Bank, a vast underwater plateau 100 miles off the coast
of New England and Nova Scotia, was long a mainstay of the region's
economy, producing abundant cod, haddock, and other catches until
fishing pressure caused a collapse in the early 1990s. The
Canadians control less than a third of the bank, but it includes
vital cod spawning areas.
</P>
<P>
   Oil and gas companies covet Georges Bank for the deposits
beneath the seabed. Three energy companies _ Chevron, Amoco, and
Texaco _ all have proposed drilling in a fingertip of the bank off
the coast of Nova Scotia, according to the Canadian Association of
Petroleum Producers.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci told Halifax Herald editors that he hoped ``a middle
ground could be found'' between the fishing and energy interests.
He said he was impressed with the environmental safeguards at a new
Nova Scotia gas drilling project outside of Georges Bank. If
similar steps were followed on the bank, he said, oil and gas
drilling could go forward.
</P>
<P>
   That view contrasts with the Massachusetts testimony in Nova
Scotia last winter. Peg Brady, director of the state office of
Coastal Zone Management, urged federal and provincial regulators to
consider extending the oil and gas moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our opinion that the potential risks of lifting the
moratorium to oil and gas exploration may outweigh the regional
benefits and jeopardize the restoration efforts now under way,''
Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, Hoffer said Cellucci was not changing state
policy, noting that Brady's testimony left the door open for oil
and gas drilling at some point. She said more study would have to
be done before Cellucci could say conclusively that the bank could
sustain oil and gas drilling.
</P>
<P>
   In response, representatives of the Massachusetts Fishermen's
Partnership, a large fishing group that opposes oil and gas
drilling on Georges Bank, sent a letter to Cellucci's top
environmental official asking for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very confused by his comments,'' said David Lincoln of
the partnership. ``We are quite concerned that he seems to be
ignoring all of the efforts that have been made to protect Georges
Bank over the last 20 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
