<SLUG> BC-BULLOCK-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLOCK SPEAKS OUT ON HATE-CRIMES BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sitting on the sidelines of state government for
the first time in decades, former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock said Friday
he's not sure he would have resorted to his legendary bullying
tactics on hate crimes were he still running the show in the Texas
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The polls showed that the majority of Texans did favor the
bill,'' Bullock said Friday, ``And so many other states have one.
But I must admit that I have wondered from time to time whether
(hate-crimes legislation) was needed, because murder is murder, and
rape is rape ... whether it's a Chinese woman or a white woman.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he never read the bill that the Texas House passed,
which would have expanded the existing hate-crimes law to enumerate
specific groups that would have garnered extra protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it would have had to have been crafted very cleverly to
not leave one person out'' for him to have let the bill through
under his watch.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and Bullock's successor, Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry, have been criticized by proponents of the legislation for
failing to show leadership in getting a compromise through the
Senate this session.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, who retired last December after eight years as
lieutenant governor and 16 years as state comptroller, was known
for his mercurial personality and his frequent strong-arm tactics _
even to the point of telling senators how they were to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I twist an arm when I needed to?'' Bullock said about his
style. ``Hell yes, I did. If there was a school bill I needed to
pass, I'd break an arm if I had to. ... Would I kick somebody in
the seat of the pants? Hell yes, I would _ all the way over to the
Capitol.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry, the first Republican to serve in that post since
Reconstruction, has a different style, and lawmakers have been
quick to smile about the differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Rick's style to dictate as Bullock would have on what
to do,'' said Democrat Ken Armbrister of Victoria, who served under
Bullock and Bullock's predecessor, Bill Hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullock was an expediter,'' Armbrister added. ``And Rick likes
to see coalitions built. He recognizes the merits of what you're
trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
