<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-AOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TRIES TO USE AOL EXAMPLES TO REBUT ANTITRUST CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Midway through a deposition Friday, American Online
chairman Stephen Case looked quizzically at the Microsoft lawyer
who was questioning him and asked, ``Did I wander into the wrong
room?''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. deposed Case on Friday morning as part the
company's preparations for the rebuttal phase of the antitrust
trial against the software giant, which is scheduled to resume June
1 after a three-month recess. Many of the questions centered around
America Online's Internet business strategy, leading Case to wonder
aloud what on earth any of it had to do with the anticompetitive
charges against Microsoft that are at issue in the case.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, he said, has no intention of competing with
Microsoft's core business in personal-computer operating systems.
Case also denied, in answer to a question, that America Online
planned to build and sell an ``AOL PC'' that would compete with
computers running the Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft lawyers tried to argue that some of America
Online's plans would in fact threaten parts of Microsoft's
business. This was intended to bolster the company's argument that
America Online's purchase of Netscape Communications Corp.
undermined the government's case by demonstrating a robust
competitive environment in the personal computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at one point Microsoft's lead trial lawyer, John
Warden, asked Case about America Online's recent purchase of an
online calendar and personal organizer service. Case said he hoped
that would be a popular feature with his customers. Later, a
Microsoft lawyer noted that Microsoft sells scheduling software.
</P>
<P>
   The government, he noted, had argued earlier in the trial about
how hard it was to enter the software business without writing
programs for Windows. ``But what happens to this when the residence
of this software shifts from the machine to the Web, with no
connection to an operating system?''
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers called all of this irrelevant. The case, said
David Boies, the lead government lawyer, was really ``about the
monopoly power Microsoft exercises over PC operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing AOL has done threatens that power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also pushed Case to offer support for Microsoft's
assertion that America Online had plotted with the government to
conceal the company's planned purchase of Netscape until AOL and
Netscape executives had finished testifying at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Case called that allegation ``ridiculous,'' though he did
acknowledge that an AOL lawyer had advised Boies in October that
the online service was involved in sensitive business discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck me as a reasonable thing to do,'' Case said. ``It
was a complicated three-ring circus to coordinate. We didn't want
any premature disclosure to leak out'' as a result of an
inadvertent question posed by Boies.
</P>
<P>
   Case insisted that the lawyer did not elaborate and said Justice
Department lawyers seemed genuinely surprised when they were
formally told of the deal in late November.
</P>
<P>
   But the Microsoft lawyer said he found it curious that
government lawyers never tried to find out what the secret talks
were about, since executives from both companies were testifying as
government witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Boies noted that Microsoft's lawyers could have asked their own
questions on this subject when an America Online executive was on
the stand and the courtroom was closed for discussion of sensitive
business matters. ``They certainly knew about this at the time,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Boies added, all of this is simply ``a sideshow, an
effort to deflect attention from the central issues in the case.''
That comment is in line with the general government view that
Microsoft's apparent line of argument for the rebuttal case is far
afield from the principal issues of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's lawyers seem particularly confident about their
rebuttal case and say they have acquired a valuable trove of
documents from America Online and Netscape that they will use to
good effect when the trial resumes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
