<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-COMMUNITY     05-21 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-COMMUNITY-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBINE COMMUNITY STRUGGLES TO RECLAIM ITS PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By SARA RIMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ As graduation at Columbine High School
approached, Sara Martin, a senior and one of the commencement
speakers, said, ``I hope it's not going to be televised.'' Her
speech was personal. ``I don't want to be saying it to people in
Chicago. I want to be saying it to people in the front row and the
back row. There just needs to be a time when we can be ourselves
again.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But graduation will be broadcast live on Saturday, by CNN, as
has almost everything to do with the school since Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold began shooting classmates on April 20 and the first
news helicopters hovered overhead, showing students running and
diving for safety.
</P>
<P>
   As Columbine approaches the end of the school year, the
community finds itself struggling not only with its tragedy, but
also with how to reclaim its privacy. For on April 20 Columbine was
invaded not just by two troubled students, but also by nearly 1,000
journalist from around the world, so many that they quickly swamped
Denver's telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   In a drill made all too familiar by previous school shootings,
the news media not only set about reporting what had happened, but
also asking the victims, witnesses and their families to help
explain why. Columbine was a public tragedy, and there were
expectations: that those in its grip would open their lives and
talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   The expectations were not solely those of the news media. In
many cases they were shared by Columbine students and their
families, some grateful that people wanted to share their anguish,
others feeling their pain validated by the nation's attention,
still others feeling an obligation to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers found eager listeners, whether they were talking
through their own fears or praising slain friends. They also met
talk-show bookers, supermarket tabloids willing to pay the gunmen's
friends $10,000 for their ``personal stories,'' reporters offering
$500 for their yearbooks.
</P>
<P>
   The media outlets included networks, news magazines and large
newspapers (The New York Times sent several reporters), Rolling
Stone, ``Entertainment Tonight'' and MTV, small papers from other
states looking for ways Littleton was like home, media from Europe
and Asia reporting what the violence said about the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For residents who had been riveted to their own televisions
during other people's disasters _ the school shootings at
Jonesboro, Ark., the Oklahoma City bombing _ it was an eerie
reversal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know how those poor people in Oklahoma felt,'' said Lee
Andres, the high school's assistant vocal director. ``It's so weird
and surreal. You can't believe it's your school.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbine was a television event from the beginning; some
students trapped inside the school during the shooting called
television stations on their cellular phones. And from the
beginning that had positive and negative aspects for the
participants.
</P>
<P>
   As news helicopters hovered overhead, Steve Broder, a sophomore,
was in a room where students were trying to save the life of a
wounded science teacher, Dave Sanders. The helicopters, he said,
added to the general terror, because the students feared they would
immediately show any ``help'' signs they put up on windows _ and
the gunmen might be watching the televisions in classrooms
throughout the school.
</P>
<P>
   But across the community, parents and relatives depended on
television for information. Abby Chism, a junior at another high
school whose sister was a Columbine freshman, said she was grateful
for the television cameras, at least at first. ``I saw Amber
running out of the school on TV,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The needs of the community and the media began colliding in the
first hours. Gail Schneider, a mother who waited four and a half
hours before being reunited with her daughter, recalled leaving the
meeting place.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we were leaving, this lady said, `Ma'am, ma'am, I'm on
deadline, I need a few comments,' '' she said. ``I said, `I've been
waiting four and a half hours. There are no comments.' ''
</P>
<P>
   By the next morning, Clement Park, next to the high school, had
become a gathering spot for students. Because of that it was also
media headquarters. Satellite trucks were parked in rows, and
reporters and photographers roamed in search of interviews and
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers grieving mingled bizarrely with journalists working.
Here and there ranks of photographers focusing on one group of
crying students, or 8 or 10 reporters surrounded a single student.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for the students and their families, there was something
familiar as well as surreal about the scene. And some welcomed the
opportunity to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe they were there,'' Kevin Koeniger, a
junior, said of the network anchormen at the park. ``Dan Rather
doesn't really leave the studio unless something huge happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Koeniger said he was pleased that Rather wanted to interview
him. ``He was really cool,'' he said. ``He said he was sorry for
what happened. He really cared. I wanted to talk. I wanted to tell
the story of what happened to people who cared.''
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship between the teen-agers and the media was
complicated. ``Some people didn't give much sympathy,'' Mr.
Koeniger said. ``They just started talking. They didn't identify
themselves. They didn't even ask you if you want to be
interviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that news coverage swelled sympathy for the
school and helped make Clement Park a memorial, it also turned
ordinary hopes and dreams upside down for many people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted Columbine to be famous,'' said Andres, the
choir assistant, who graduated from the school in 1980 and whose
father is the chairman of the music department.
</P>
<P>
   Famous for what?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, anything, I just wanted it to be famous for
something good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of great kids. You want to be known. You don't
want anyone to think of it as a symbol of tragedy and sadness.
That's just a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the sort of celebrity many wanted. Sara Martin, the
senior speaker, was interviewed by Time. ``At first I thought,
`This is really cool, I'm going to be in Time.' '' she said. ``Then
I realized, `I'm going to be in Time because they shot my
friends.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the students were in charge. Devon Adams, a friend
of Dylan Klebold, said she did interviews with Time, The New York
Times and CNN because she thought they were reputable and she
wanted to get out her message: Columbine was a good school. She did
not talk about Klebold, she said, because that would not have been
right.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Adams said she turned down scores of other requests,
including one by the ``Today'' show. Her mother, Bee Adams, an
artist, admitted to a twinge of disappointment over that decision.
``She's more mature than I am,'' Mrs. Adams said. ``I would be
swayed by the `Today' show.''
</P>
<P>
   As reporters knocked on front doors and appeared at funeral
services, and anyone thought to know anything about the gunmen was
besieged by phone, a backlash set in. Families posted ``No Media''
signs on front doors, left ``No Media'' messages on their answering
machines, changed phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   By then, familiarity was teaching other lessons. Some people
were upset at inaccuracies, misspelled names or wrong ages of their
friends. Many thought that the Columbine High School they read and
heard about, as the media tried to explain the shootings, was not
the school they knew.
</P>
<P>
   Alisha Basore, a senior whose close friend Rachel Scott was
murdered, had gone on ``Larry King Live'' and participated in a CNN
town meeting and had been pleased with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I got to reach a lot of people,'' she said. ``I
wanted to talk about the experience of it, the stupidity of it, the
shock of it. I got to tell everyone how I felt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miss Basore was furious when she encountered cameras at Miss
Scott's funeral. ``My best friend was killed,'' she said. ``It's
not a media event.''
</P>
<P>
   With the end of the school year approaching, the reporters began
returning. There was so much media interest in the Columbine
graduation that school officials decided to allow pool coverage,
including CNN, according to a district spokeswoman, Marilyn
Saltzman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the television cameras, however, and the moment of
silence that will be observed for Lauren Townsend and Isiah Shoels,
the two seniors who were slain by the gunmen, and for Sanders, the
science teacher, the seniors are determined that their graduation
be a celebration, not another memorial. They have turned down
offers from Chuck Norris and Bill Cosby, among others, to speak at
graduation. They also turned down an offer from Hootie and the
Blowfish to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Columbine concert choir will sing, as it does every
year, and the speakers, according to tradition, will be two
seniors, Sara Martin and Jennifer Wallick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
