<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6546 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUNG-WHISTLEBLOWER-BO     05-21 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNG-WHISTLEBLOWER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUNG DISEASE RESEARCHER SAYS HE MAY QUIT FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. David Kern of Brown University, a hero among occupational
health specialists for publishing his discovery of a new workplace
lung disease despite efforts to muzzle him, now says he will
probably leave the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be a martyr. I have family responsibilities,''
Kern said Friday while he was in Boston attending a meeting on
threats to academic freedom sponsored by the American Association
of University Professors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I leave the field, it suggests we lost in more ways than
one,'' Kern said. ``It's an ongoing injury to the workers of Rhode
Island and the faculty of Brown University. So it's with great
angst that I face this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Kern has been engaged in a bitter, three-year battle over his
right to publish data on a new lung disease over the objections of
a Pawtucket, R.I. textile company, Microfibres Inc., and his
employer, Memorial Hospital of Pawtucket. Nine cases of ``flock
workers' lung'' have been diagnosed among workers at the Pawtucket
plant, and federal investigators last year faulted Microfibres on
workplace safety.
</P>
<P>
   When Kern gave a public presentation of his findings on
Microfibres workers in 1997, the hospital fired him from his job as
director of Rhode Island's only occupational health clinic, and
said it would not renew Kern's contract as a staff physician when
it expires next month.
</P>
<P>
   If Kern abandons occupational health, it will send ``a very
chilling message'' to others in the field and to young doctors who
might choose the specialty, said Dr. Barry Levy of Tufts University
Medical School, a leader in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at Dr. Kern's case, a young academic might say, `I'm
not going to risk my career and the well-being of my family,' ''
Levy said. ``Unless new policies arise out of this, it will signal
to other universities that when it's occupational health findings
vs. corporate interests, they can do the same thing Brown
University did.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy was referring to the university's refusal to support Kern
in his fight to keep his job at Brown-affiliated Memorial Hospital.
Brown officials said in mid-1997 that the hospital was within its
rights to terminate his contract.
</P>
<P>
   About 120 members of the Association of University Professors
are scheduled to debate Saturday a proposed position defending
academic freedom in medical schools. Mary Burgan, the association's
general secretary, said the statement will be put to a vote next
month at the group's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The association acts as a bargaining agent for about half its
44,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Burgan said the group decided to formulate a position on the
academic freedom of medical researchers largely in response to
Kern's case and several other recent instances in which scientists
faced severe pressures when they attempted to publish results that
corporate research sponsors wanted to suppress.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nancy Olivieri of the University of Toronto was fired from
her job as director of a blood clinic at the Toronto Hospital for
Sick Children after she defied a drug company's order not to
disclose data on the safety and effectiveness of a drug it funded
her to study. She was later reinstated after intercession by
academic groups and leaders in her field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an isolated incident and neither is David
Kern's,'' Olivieri said. ``This is an ongoing scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto episode underscores ``just how badly things can go
wrong'' when corporate and academic interests collide, Dr. David G.
Nathan of the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute and Dr. D.J. Weatherall
of the University of Oxford wrote recently in The Lancet, a British
journal.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan and Weatherall said the Olivieri case shows that medical
researchers ``must have the freedom'' to warn patients and other
scientists about deleterious effects of a drug or procedure. If a
company ``takes legal action or otherwise harasses a scientist,''
they added, the hospital or its associated university ``must
immediately offer its support.''
</P>
<P>
   Although occupational health leaders supported Kern, he said he
is disheartened by the response of many colleagues. ``There were
courageous folks who stood up for me, but most looked the other
way,'' he said. ``I'm mightily discouraged by the failure of the
community to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Association of University Professors did not come to Kern's
aid when he was struggling with Memorial Hospital and Brown
University, although the organization cites his case now. ``The
ball was dropped,'' Burgan acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   An effort is under way to secure state funding for a new,
independent occupational health clinic to replace the one that
Memorial Hospital closed, according to George Nee of the AFL-CIO of
Rhode Island. Dr. Michael Fine, who is involved with that effort,
said it might be hard to recruit a specialist to head that center
because ``the environment is quite poisoned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
