A6549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-LOTTERY-IMPACT-ART     05-21 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-LOTTERY-IMPACT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A SMALL MIDDLE-CLASS TOWN, BIG LOTTERY SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with LOTTERY-IMPACT)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BRETT PULLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGDALE, N.J. _ The municipal building in this central New
Jersey community is an old white clapboard house. The mayor is a
retired doctor who practiced here for 44 years and now walks to his
office each day, dressed casually.
</P>
<P>
   The children, who perform well above state averages on school
tests, ride bicycles along the sidewalk on Main Street, stopping at
the ice cream shop or convenience store. And the pharmacist, a
jocular Brooklyn transplant, knows his customers by ailment and
first name.
</P>
<P>
   But if this apple pie of a place sounds like some syrupy relic
of a bygone America, there is at least one thing that very much
connects this one-half-square-mile bucolic borough to the world
outside its boundaries: the New Jersey State Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Although only 1,400 people live in Farmingdale, there are five
outlets that sell lottery tickets, amounting to one lottery outlet
for every 280 residents. And while lottery agents here do not ring
up nearly as much in sales as their counterparts in large cities
around the state, the lottery is just as prevalent in people's
lives.
</P>
<P>
   According to state lottery statistics, weekly per capita ticket
sales in Farmingdale are $6.92, compared with $3.92 statewide.
Lottery agents here point out that some tickets are sold to people
passing through or coming to Farmingdale but that many of their
customers are local residents.
</P>
<P>
   Solidly middle-class with professional and blue-collar workers
alike, Farmingdale is more than 95 percent white, has a median
household income of about $45,000, and is situated in Monmouth
County, a Republican stronghold. The mayor, Dr. Edward Schauer, who
describes himself as ``very conservative,'' believes that much of
the interest in the lottery in his town has to do with the economic
realities of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would presume that the well-to-do in this town gamble other
ways, but a lot of families have two people working,'' Schauer
said. ``I think those people play because they don't know of any
other way to get a lot of money. I think if they didn't have to
worry about the next payment on the car or the mortgage, they'd be
less apt to gamble on the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to filling prescriptions, Farmingdale Pharmacy owner
Joseph Palumbo sells gifts, collectibles and lottery tickets. His
average weekly lottery sales total about $700, for which he earns 5
percent, or $35. But Palumbo is convinced that having the lottery
machine in the store helps him sell other merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got our regulars who play $10 or $15 a day,'' Palumbo
said. ``That can translate to sales of other merchandise for us.''
</P>
<P>
   One regular customer, Jim Karos, who works at the post office
across the street, comes in each day to buy instant tickets, and
daily pick-three and pick-four tickets. Twice a week, he pools his
money with 10 co-workers to play the Pick 6 game, and three times a
week he and 9 co-workers bet on the Pick 5 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work so I can buy lottery tickets,'' Karos half-joked while
recently buying his tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Karos, 54, decides what numbers to play by using things like the
postal meter totals for the day, or the total amount of express
mail sent out for the day.
</P>
<P>
   As Karos left the store, Palumbo said: ``This is serious for
him. It's important for him to see if he can make some money on the
lottery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
