<HEADER>
A6554 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV23-NYT &LR;      05-21 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Supply and Demand &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ireland is a conservative Catholic country with a liberal
national health system: Among other benefits, approved prescription
drugs are dispensed by doctors at no cost to patients.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, this raises ticklish questions in Dublin, like what
to do about Viagra, Pfizer's anti-impotence pill. Would approval of
the drug appear to be encouraging licentiousness? Would rejection
be seen as obstructing the biblical imperative to be fruitful and
multiply? And on top of that, Pfizer makes ingredients for the drug
in Ireland, at a plant in Cork.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cowan, the health minister, announced a Solomonic solution
last week: Irish men in need could get free Viagra, but only four
pills a month. The limit was set ``to reduce the possibility of
inappropriate usage,'' Cowan told reporters. (No special provisions
were announced for months with five Saturday nights.)
</P>
<P>
   The limit did not bother Pfizer, which said some American
insurers had similar rules. Though couples with free access in
clinical tests tended to use about seven a month, according to
Mariann Caprino, a Pfizer spokeswoman, official recognition of
erectile dysfunction as a serious medical condition was
satisfaction enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6555 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESIDENTIAL-PAY-0524     05-21 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENTIAL-PAY-0524-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRESIDENCY SLATED FOR FIRST RAISE IN THREE DECADES
 &HT;    FOR USE MONDAY, MAY 22
 &HT;    NOTE TO EDITORS: IN THIRD GRAPH: DOLLAR AMOUNT IN LIGHT'S QUOTE
ON EISNER COMPENSATION PACKAGE IS ABOUT WHAT OTHERS HAVE ESTIMATED
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is about to double the president's pay to
$400,000 a year, the first hike in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   It would not benefit President Clinton, because the Constitution
forbids an increase for a sitting president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that the president deserves more,'' says
Paul Light, a scholar at the Brookings Institution, in testimony
prepared for a congressional hearing Monday. The president's
current $200,000 salary ``would put him at No. 785 on the list of
the 800 highest paid corporate chief executive officers, well below
Walt Disney's Michael Eisner, who receives a package worth $589
million,'' he is to say.
</P>
<P>
   If the president's pay had been indexed for inflation, he would
be earning $915,000 by now, Light will tell members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Although the current administration is keeping mum on the
subject, a line-up of senior aides to former presidents going back
to Lyndon Johnson is expected to support the pay raise in a hearing
before a House Government and Reform subcommittee. There appears to
be little opposition to the idea in either the House or Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was quietly inserted into a House spending bill by
Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., after he examined the pay of foreign
leaders. His staffers discovered that Singapore pays $465,000,
Taiwan $303,000, Japan $378 and Switzerland $230,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no request from the White House (on the issue),''
said a spokeswoman for Kolbe
</P>
<P>
   The timing appears right. With Clinton's term expiring and his
successor unknown, this year provides an opportunity for action
without regard to the party or the person in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea is not without critics. Gary Ruskin, director of
the liberal group Congressional Accountability Project said he
plans to pan the pay raise at Monday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president doesn't need a raise because he's got a
$200,000-a-year salary plus generous perks,'' Ruskin said. ``This
is mostly driven by desires of Congress and federal judges to get a
raise, and they don't need one either.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the push for the president's pay raise is to make room
for increases in other senior-level salaries without coming too
close to that of the chief executive. Already, the vice president's
$175,000 salary, which goes up when congressional pay increases, is
bumping up close to that of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sepp, spokesman for the National Taxpayers' Union, opposes
a presidential pay hike. ``Certainly (the president should) not
have a penny more for salary until the over-generous pension system
is addressed,'' Sepp said.
</P>
<P>
   Although presidents have relatively low salaries compared with
corporate chiefs, basketball players and even many college coaches,
they enjoy extensive benefits in retirement, including a
taxpayer-paid office staff, rent payments, and travel expenses,
plus $150,000 a year in retirement pay.
</P>
<P>
   But complaints by critics of a pay raise do not dissuade Don
Simon, acting president of Common Cause, a watchdog for ethics in
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the level of pay is a statement of how we think about
the office,'' he said. ``It is the most important job in
government, and the pay should be commensurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing that view, Light said that after the controversies
surrounding the Clinton presidency, ``this is a good way to send a
signal to the next president that this is still an important
office.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
