<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-21 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Yeltsin Takes a Vacation
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin went to the Black Sea resort at Sochi
for an unscheduled two-week holiday as his new prime minister,
Sergei Stepashin, continued the sensitive work of forming a
Cabinet. As expected, the president signed a decree reappointing
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   France: Suspected Terrorist Extradited
</P>
<P>
   Hans-Joachim Klein, 51, a German suspected in a 1975 terrorist
attack in which 70 people were taken hostage during a meeting of
oil ministers in Vienna, was sent to Germany for trial. Klein was
arrested in Normandy, were he had been living under an assumed
name. The police have described him as an accomplice of Illich
Ramirez Sanchez, known as Carlos the Jackal, who is serving a life
sentence in France for murder.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Three Jailed in Bomb Plot
</P>
<P>
   Three Irish university students believed to belong to splinter
paramilitary groups opposed to the Northern Ireland peace
settlement were convicted of conspiracy to set off bombs in London.
Anthony Hyland, 26, was sentenced to 25 years in prison; Liam
Grogan, 21, and Darren Mulholland, 20, were each given 22 years.
They were arrested in police raids in July that confiscated Semtex,
an explosive, and firebombs and maps identifying shops in Fulham
Broadway, in West London, as targets.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Colombia: Rebels Keep Haven
</P>
<P>
   The government's chief negotiator in peace talks with the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, Victor Ricardo, announced
that a Switzerland-sized ``safe haven'' ceded to the left-wing
rebels would remain under their control indefinitely. The
government withdrew all troops from the area in November in what
was envisioned as a temporary arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Official Quits in Scandal
</P>
<P>
   Labor Minister Antonio Erman Gonzalez resigned after it was
disclosed that he was receiving an $8,000-a-month pension in
addition to his $9,700-a-month salary. Aides to President Carlos
Saul Menem had defended the minister, but in the wake of
congressional criticism, Menem demanded his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Cabinet Shift
</P>
<P>
   Diodoro Carrasco Altamirano, a former governor of Oaxaca, has
been named interior minister, the top position in President Ernesto
Zedillo's Cabinet. He replaces Francisco Labastida Ochoa, who
resigned to start his campaign to become the governing party's
presidential candidate in elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Expelled Leader to Form Party
</P>
<P>
   Sharad Pawar, who was expelled from the Congress Party on
Thursday, said he would form a new party within a week. Pawar, who
has a substantial electoral base in Maharashtra, was ousted by the
Congress Party for opposing the candidacy of Sonia Gandhi in
national elections because of her foreign birth.
</P>
<P>
   Nepal: A Solid Majority
</P>
<P>
   Election results have given the Nepali Congress Party a majority
in Parliament. As votes continue to be counted, the party is
assured of at least 104 of the 205 seats, according to the Election
Commission. Krishna Prasad Bhattarai, the party's prime
minister-designate, said he expects to be sworn in within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia: Police Chief Faces Trial
</P>
<P>
   The former police chief who beat jailed opposition leader, Anwar
Ibrahim, giving him a much-photographed black eye, will stand trial
Sept. 20, exactly one year after the incident. The officer, Abdul
Rahim, who pleaded not guilty, faces up to 3 1/2 years in jail if
he is convicted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Amnesty in Killings
</P>
<P>
   The Truth and Reconciliation Commission granted amnesty to 13
former members of the police and army for several killings in 1986,
including those of Fabian Ribeiro, of the African National
Congress, and Piet Ntuli, a minister in a black homeland. The
victims included 10 young black men who, duped into thinking they
were crossing the border to join a guerrilla army in Botswana, were
arrested, drugged and burned to death in their minibus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
