<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAILROAD TYCOON II GIVES PLAYERS A REASON TO UPGRADE COMPUTERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many years ago, before computers had all the bells and whistles
they do today, there was a computer game that had a bell and
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   The two were attached to a train, and players set about to build
a railroad. And then they worked to expand the railroad into a line
serving a few cities. Next came a regional line, and if they were
careful, competitive and cutthroat, they could weave a rail network
that captured a nation.
</P>
<P>
   They'd become a railroad tycoon. Which, by the way, was the name
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Railroad Tycoon'' was a wonderfully done game that simulated
the days when people came out of their houses to watch passing
trains, when trains moved more goods than trucks, and when
passengers were able to eat sitting down in a dining car instead of
from a fold-down tray attached to a seat back. (Please return all
trays to their upright positions.)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a reader called wondering where he could buy the
Railroad Tycoon program, which, if I remember correctly, didn't
take much more than a computer using the now archaic 486 chip _
which, the reader lamented, was all he had brought to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, the sequel, ``Railroad Tycoon II,'' presented
our hobo reader with a reason to upgrade his computer. The sequel
took advantage of a new generation of computer with better graphics
and stronger game play. Players build railroads, buy engines, bid
for hauling goods and buy and sell stock.
</P>
<P>
   There are 60 engines from which to choose. In addition, the game
has several difficulty levels, including one that allows players to
build and run trains like they did when they were kids: put the
track together, put a train on it, and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   For players who have the ``Railroad Tycoon II'' game comes
``Railroad Tycoon II: The Second Century.'' The expansion pack
takes railroad barons to the next era with new maps to develop and
new segments of the economy to control.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion has new features and graphics, and covers the
years 1939 into the future. A company spokesman said railroad
builders can build all over the world and will face ``world
catastrophes such as World War II, the Cold War, and global
warming, and must solve modern problems such as the increasing
demand for mass transportation in major cities.''
</P>
<P>
   The disk has 15 stand-alone maps that allow railroad builders to
play against savvy computer-run players or other humans. Several
new engines are also included: the French TGV bullet train, the
Brennar 412, the Eurostar, and the German DB18-201 (a contemporary
steam train), and new cars such as Metra passenger cars, troop
transports and weapons flatbeds.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new challenges for players:
</P>
<P>
   World War II and Aftermath (1939-50): Gamers help guide the
Allies to victory in World War II by managing the British railroad
system through the Blitz and by hauling supplies from Russia to the
western front to hold off the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   After the war ends, gamers enter the Cold War phase and must
build railroad systems to deliver critical supplies to West Berlin
before Russia cuts the region off from the non-communist world.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Era (1950-2005): After the war, America's economy and
population booms. Players need to meet the transportation demands
of the rising population and build a high-speed rail connecting Los
Angeles and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Players can now manage the Chunnel between England and France
and build a light-rail system for Seattle and Munich.
</P>
<P>
   The game needs a Pentium computer (133 MHZ processor or better)
with 16 megabytes of RAM and 150 megabytes of free hard-drive
space. And of course, buyers must own the original ``Railroad
Tycoon II'' to play.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
