<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO RELEASES AID FOR CHIAPAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ An American aid volunteer whose school bus, laden
with wheelchairs and food donations, was stalled at the Mexican
border for three weeks said Friday that he had delivered his
shipment to Chiapas state.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteer, Patrick Young, director of the Wheelchair Project
of Fresno, Calif., said he had been allowed to cross the border at
Reynosa early last week. Mexican authorities agreed he could give
the goods to Caritas, a Roman Catholic charity.
</P>
<P>
   The agency distributed the goods and food worth $3,000 that
Young had bought in Mexico to two rural Indian communities in
Chiapas, including one controlled by anti-government Zapatista
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Young said he did not go to the communities to photograph the
deliveries, as he usually does, because he feared violating
restrictions that immigration officials had written into his visa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
