<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SPRINGTIME FOR CAMPAIGN REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, May 22:
</P>
<P>
   The time has come for House Republicans to save Speaker Dennis
Hastert from humiliating himself. Even Dick Armey, the grumpy
Republican majority leader and no fan of cleaning up campaign laws,
apparently agrees that it looks appalling for Hastert to fight the
will of the majority of House on campaign finance reform. Armey
wants to schedule a vote and get it over with. Friday, Hastert
again said the issue could not be taken up until the fall, which is
his way of burying it. Republican reformers, who have been
dithering over whether to confront Hastert, have no choice but to
sign a petition forcing legislation to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The basic principle here is whether Congress, before the next
election, will stand against the corruption of the political system
by special interests using a loophole in the campaign laws. Most
senators and representatives have said ``yes.'' Their leaders say
``no,'' because they haul in money from the oil, tobacco, gambling
and other industries and, in return, pass laws that help their
benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   The bill sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays of Connecticut and
Martin Meehan of Massachusetts would end unlimited contributions to
parties from business, unions and rich donors, and the use of this
money for ``attack ads'' by independent groups two months before an
election.
</P>
<P>
   House approval is certain _ if the House gets to vote. Knowing
that, Hastert wants to postpone a vote until it is too late for the
Senate to act. He promises to bring it up the third week of
September. But that promise is disingenuous and premised on a false
argument, which is that the House has too much else going on now.
In fact, the House is working short days this spring, and Hastert
has even scheduled an extra vacation week because there is so
little to do. The speaker also knows that September is exactly the
wrong time to bring up campaign reform, because by then the House
will be caught up in budget battles.
</P>
<P>
   Last year House members defied Newt Gingrich by signing a
petition forcing campaign financing to the floor. They can do it
again. The Democrats have a shot at getting 200 signatures. If a
little more than half of the 34 Republican sponsors of the
Shays-Meehan bill sign on, reform will have its day.
</P>
<P>
   We appeal to sponsors in the New York area to do so _ Shays and
Nancy Johnson of Connecticut; Bob Franks, Marge Roukema, Frank
LoBiondo, Rodney Frelinghuysen and Jim Saxton of New Jersey, and
Sue Kelly, Michael Forbes, James Walsh, Sherwood Boehlert, Amo
Houghton and Benjamin Gilman of New York. Their constituents should
tell them that lip service to this cause is not enough.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
