<SLUG> BC-TRIE-DONATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGTIME CLINTON FRIEND PLEADS GUILTY IN FUND-RAISING
INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
 (rm) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Democratic fundraiser and longtime Arkansas
friend of President Clinton pleaded guilty Friday in a federal
court in Little Rock, Ark., to two political fund-raising charges
and agreed to cooperate with the Justice Department's long-running
campaign finance inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser, Yah Lin Trie, was one of the first major
Democratic figures from Clinton's re-election effort to be charged
in an indictment in January 1998. Trie was one of a small group of
Clinton associates who used his contacts in Asia to help seek money
for the Democrats, ultimately raising more than $1 million for the
party's national committee and Clinton's legal defense fund.
</P>
<P>
   In the plea agreement, the government said it would dismiss all
charges against Trie in Little Rock and Washington in return for
his guilty plea to a felony count of causing false statements to be
made to the Federal Election Commission and to a lesser misdemeanor
charge.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty plea, along with a federal appeals court's decision
earlier this week to reinstate charges against another fund-raiser
rejuvenated the 3-year old investigation into how the Democrats
financed Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement after his plea, Trie said that he wanted to end
the long legal battle that had consumed his life. ``After three
years of constant struggle, my physical and spiritual resources to
resist are exhausted,'' Trie said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the government agreed to dismiss all charges
against Trie in Little Rock and Washington in return for his guilty
plea to a felony count of causing false statements to be made to
the Federal Election Commission and to a lesser misdemeanor charge.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart said Friday that he
had no comment on Trie's guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   For Trie, a Taiwan-born naturalized American citizen known as
Charlie, the guilty plea resolved legal problems that in recent
days had seemed to mount against the former Little Rock
restaurateur, who parlayed his friendships with Clinton and the
president's inner circle into an international import-export
business.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the District of Columbia Circuit unanimously reinstated five of six
criminal charges against another fund-raiser, Maria Hsia. Similar
charges had been thrown out in Trie's case, and the ruling meant
they were certain to be reinstated.It was to one of those charges
that Trie pleaded guilty Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement was reached as Trie had ended the first week
of a federal trial in Little Rock on charges that he obstructed
justice by ordering an employee to destroy documents subpoenaed in
1997 by a federal grand jury and the Senate Government Affairs
Committee. Those charges could have resulted in a sentence of up to
five years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had presented one damaging witness, the manager of
Trie's Little Rock office, Maria Mapili. She testified this week
that Trie directed her to dispose of documents sought by the Senate
investigating committee. Ms. Mapili said she threw away some papers
but hid others that were later seized or turned over to the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For prosecutors, the deal provides a witness who could open a
window on the murky world of the fund raising they are
investigating, a prospect that prompted prosecutors to offer Trie
immunity and a recommendation that he be sentenced to three-years
probation if he cooperates fully. If not, he faces a maximum
sentence of six years in prison and a $350,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They will be able to plumb Trie's knowledge on several fronts.
For example, investigators are likely to enlist him to unravel the
activities of another important fund-raiser, John Huang, who has
long been a focus of inquiry in the fund-raising affair but has
never been accused of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional investigators reported that Trie brought in
$230,000 helping Huang raise money for the Democratic National
Committee's Asian-American dinner on Feb. 19, 1996, at the
Hay-Adams Hotel in Washington. At the dinner, Trie and his Macau
financial partner, Ng Lap Seng, were rewarded with a seat at the
head table next to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But when the campaign finance scandal ignited after Clinton's
re-election, the contributions that Trie helped bring in were
immediately suspect. The Democratic National Committee returned
$645,000 that he solicited and Clinton sent back the $639,000 that
Trie raised for the president's legal defense fund.
</P>
<P>
   Senate investigators later traced more than $1 million wired to
Trie from Asia, including $470,000 from Ng. Justice Department
investigators have long wanted to know more about the source of the
money. Trie could potentially assist that inquiry, although his
lawyers have said the money was for legitimate business
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities are not alone in their eagerness to question
Trie. Congressional investigators also want to interview him, and
federal marshals Friday served Trie with a subpoena to appear on
June 10 before the House Government Reform Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
