<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIE-DONATE-HUGHES-NY     05-21 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIE-DONATE-HUGHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTE HINTS FUND-RAISER KNEW OF BRIBERY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
(DW) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department has obtained a note from the
Little Rock office of Yah Lin Trie, a Democratic fund-raiser, that
suggests he was aware of a bribery problem.
</P>
<P>
   The note, handwritten in Mandarin on stationery from a Hong Kong
hotel, is cryptic but intriguing, according to officials who are
familiar with its contents.
</P>
<P>
   The note lists a number of items. The first three items mention
``Hughes'' and the U.S. government, export licenses and a bribery
problem, the officials said. It is not clear who wrote the note,
which was obtained by the Justice Department in a search of Trie's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox committee, a select House committee investigating
China's acquisition of sensitive U.S. technology, learned of the
note during its investigation. The committee, according to
officials familiar with its investigation, believes the use of the
word ``Hughes'' may be a reference to Hughes Electronics, the
satellite-maker and subsidiary of the General Motors Corp. Hughes'
dealings with China are the subject of a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The note is not related to the charges against Trie that stem
from his activities as a fund-raiser for President Clinton and the
Democratic Party in the 1996 election. Trie, who is known as
Charlie and is a longtime Arkansas friend of Clinton and his wife,
Hillary, pleaded guilty Friday in a federal court in Little Rock,
Ark., to two campaign-related charges and agreed to cooperate with
the Justice Department's campaign finance inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes has denied any wrongdoing. But the select committee found
that Hughes had intentionally ignored federal export license
requirements in its dealings with Chinese scientists in 1993 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, Hughes officials were helping China fix problems
with rockets that failed while carrying Hughes satellites.
Documents obtained by the Cox committee suggest that a Hughes
official in China, Bansang W. Lee, was recommending that the
company curry favor with the Chinese in 1993 by softening its
criticism of Chinese rocket failures.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, Central Intelligence Agency officers in China
reported that Lee, who left Hughes in 1995 and went to work for
another American satellite company, had made payments to Chinese
officials in the hope of getting contracts for American aerospace
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyer, Brian O'Neill, has said his client ``never made
any unlawful or improper payments of any kind to any Chinese
official.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear why Trie might have kept a note relating to
export issues and Hughes. But Trie was closely involved in export
issues and China. He served on a presidential trade commission
trying to open Asian markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6577 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-VACATION-640&AMP;     05-21 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VACATION-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 THE CLINTONS' VACATION HAS POLITICAL OVERTONES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, as he is fond of reminding
everyone from time to time, cannot run again for re-election, which
frees him from certain political calculations. One of these, you
would think, would be where to spend his summer vacation, a
decision that in the past has been so fraught with image-conscious
polling that he went off twice to Wyoming just to please the
environmentalists, when he really wanted to go back to Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with his wife edging closer to running for the Senate from
New York, the summer vacation is still in the balance. And although
administration officials caution that a final decision may be
dozens of permutations away, one thing seems likely: It will be in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The first couple, these officials say, for the first time in
their lives, are exploring the recreational options across the
Empire State. The choices have apparently narrowed, they say, to
the Adirondacks or Shelter Island, although Marsha Berry, the first
lady's spokeswoman, was noncommittal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that you can narrow it down to two, or rule out
Martha's Vineyard,'' Ms. Berry said. She noted that the Clintons
were planning a five-day Florida vacation next week, where Mrs.
Clinton will focus on her decision about whether to run for the
Senate. ``That's as far as they're planning, in terms of
vacation,'' Ms. Berry said. The annual vacation decision, she said,
``is one of the hardest things to pin them down on.''
</P>
<P>
   Other officials say the Adirondacks and Shelter Island are under
close study. The two spots, at different ends of the state, make
entirely different political statements, and each has its
drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The rustic, woodsy Adirondacks, spread out across 6 million
acres in northern New York, make a nice setting for the outdoorsy
look. But the area is remote and short on the kind of socializing
that the Clintons favor.
</P>
<P>
   It may be telling that when one administration official was
asked whether the Clintons might pick the Adirondacks, his first
response was ``How far is that from New York City?''
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Too far for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Shelter Island, tucked between Long Island's North and South
Forks, is quaint _ it has no traffic lights _ while still easily
accessible to the Hamptons area and its trunks of campaign cash.
But constant shuttling over to Steven Spielberg's estate could
suggest a certain elitism that Mrs. Clinton, if she runs for the
Senate, would probably want to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Morris, the former White House consultant, has in the past
steered the Clintons toward places that have a populist appeal to
middle-class families _ the suburban swing voters who frequently
decide elections. It was Morris who convinced the Clintons in 1995
and 1996 to drop the glitz of Martha's Vineyard and head for
Jackson Hole.
</P>
<P>
   As he writes in his memoir, ``Behind the Oval Office,'' Morris,
with the help of pollster Mark Penn and an elaborately refined
polling grid, found that people whose votes are up for grabs tend
to like baseball, hiking, camping and technology. ``I urged that he
take a mountain vacation, that he hike and camp out in a tent'' and
publicize the high-tech gear he was using, Morris wrote, admitting
that he was carrying his belief in polling to ``a mindless
extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton was not happy,'' Morris continued. He asked Morris
whether, for example, if he wore a baseball cap he could still go
golfing. ``What if I hike, set up my campsite and go fishing but I
don't catch anything?'' an irked president asked the consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his irritation, the president and the first lady went to
Wyoming, and they did camp and hike. But then, after the
president's re-election, they went back to Martha's Vineyard in
1997 and 1998 _ ever nomadic in the summer, having no family
retreat like a Kennebunkport or Hyde Park to call home.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Morris, now widely loathed within the administration, laughed on
Friday when informed of the New York options. ``That's
ridiculous,'' he said, branding their sudden interest in a New York
vacation ``totally and completely phony.'' He said the Adirondacks
were ``derivative of my advice to go to the Rockies'' and that
Shelter Island was ``derivative of Martha's Vineyard, which is
where they really want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   On reflection, he thought the Adirondacks would be a better
choice than Shelter Island. ``Swing voters like camping, hiking and
fishing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While a visit to the woods might have broad appeal, it is
unclear whether this would help with the Adirondack locals, who
tend to vote heavily Republican. Gerald Solomon, who represented
the Adirondacks in Congress for 20 years before retiring last year,
said in an interview Friday, ``The natives would welcome them, but
they certainly wouldn't vote for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said that Mrs. Clinton's advocacy of gun control would
be particularly troubling. He received much attention for his
forceful denunciation of a gun-control measure in 1996, when he
said his wife, who lived alone in Glens Falls while he was in
Washington, needed her rifles for protection.
</P>
<P>
   But he also acknowledged that the seasonal Adirondack economy
could use a boost from the money that a presidential visit would
bring in. ``Their entourage would be most welcome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the Clintons wind up, they are not likely to bump into
New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Mrs. Clinton's likely
competitor in a Senate race. The mayor makes a point of not taking
vacations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
