<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-MYTH22-COX     05-21 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-MYTH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `The Phantom Menace': Movie or myth?
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ From Odysseus and King Arthur to Luke and Anakin
Skywalker, the story remains the same: A young man realizes the
hero within through a journey that involves trials, temptations and
transformation. It's what Joseph Campbell, author of ``The Hero
With a Thousand Faces,'' called the ``mono-myth.''
</P>
<P>
   At its most basic, the ``Star Wars'' saga is a simple tale of a
hero's quest, with the timeless theme of good vs. evil. In creating
his modern-day legend, which will eventually encompass six films,
George Lucas has tapped into myths that have been repeated
countless times in every culture, and drawn on age-old archetypes
found in ancient fairy tales. There's the beautiful princess in
distress (Princess Leia); courageous knights (Luke Skywalker and
Han Solo); the wise old man (Obi-Wan Kenobi); a dark knight (Darth
Vader); and the powerful evil ruler (Emperor Palpatine). Aliens and
'droids fill the standard roles of ogres and dwarves.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Star Wars'' films have struck a chord deep within people
all over the world. The method of conveying the story has changed
with the times, with the added twist of astonishing special
effects. But as with fairy tales, people never grow tired of
hearing _ or seeing _ the same essential story.
</P>
<P>
   The latest chapter, ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' which opened Wednesday, presents a new cast of similarly
archetypal characters. The new film goes a step further by
introducing seemingly overt references to Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   During the three years he developed the original ``Star Wars''
and its prequels and sequels, Lucas worked toward making it a
modern mythology. He'd been a social-science major who studied
anthropology before he got into film, and discovered Campbell's
works in a mythology class.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to do `Star Wars,' I went back and started doing
more research before I wrote the screenplay,'' Lucas said last week
during a news conference in New York City. ``I re-read `The Hero
With a Thousand Faces' and quite a few other things (Joseph
Campbell) did.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas met the mythology expert after he completed 1983's
``Return of the Jedi.'' They became friends until Campbell's death.
``In that part, he actually was a mentor,'' Lucas said. ``He was an
amazing scholar and an amazing person, and I was privileged to be
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell demonstrated how many folkloric and religious figures,
from the fairy tale Frog King to Buddha, simultaneously enacted the
same phases of their common story. He transformed the way scholars,
historians and psychologists view mythology by interweaving
traditional wisdom with the modern struggle for identity and
spiritual depth.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas imbued his myth with bits of popular culture:
Saturday-matinee adventure serials, movie westerns, swashbucklers
and Japanese samurai epics. Adhering to Campbell's doctrine, he
also reflected the times in which the films were made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars,'' released in 1977, was a reaction against
Watergate, Vietnam and other periods of domestic turmoil that
undermined the concept of the hero for disillusioned Americans.
Lucas reportedly patterned Emperor Palpatine after Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' also speaks to the moment. The villains
are a corporate dictatorship known as the Trade Federation, which
invades Naboo. The Federation viceroy is named Nute, as in
Gingrich. His ally in the Galactic Senate, who ties up Naboo's
call-to-arms in committee, is Lott _ like the U.S. Senate Majority
Leader. The Jedi attempt to stop the invasion, as NATO has done in
countries such as Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The one-with-the-universe concept of the Force has been likened
to Eastern religions. ``The Phantom Menace'' seems to draw more
directly from Christianity with the revelation that Anakin is
apparently a virgin birth _ the ``chosen one'' who will free his
people and bring balance to the Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a virgin birth in every mythological story in every
culture,'' said Irish actor Liam Neeson, who plays Jedi Knight
Qui-Gon Jinn. ``Sometimes people just attribute it to Christianity,
but it's not, really. It's ancient.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Neeson admits that he and Pernilla August, the Swedish
actress who plays Anakin's mother, Shmi, had a few giggles when she
had to deliver the line about there being no father. ``And when it
came to my close-up, I thought, well, how do you play this? A
double-take? You could say, `So, you're still a virgin?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas has been conscious about not making the ``Star Wars''
movies religion-specific. He said when the original was released,
many religions used it to demonstrate their beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of Immaculate Conception is a motif that goes
through all religions,'' Lucas said. ``It's a motif that goes
through all stories about the local deity or the local hero. It's
the same thing with Hercules. Most heroes are conceived in an
unusual way. And in this particular case, it's actually not
Immaculate Conception. It's conception by metaphor, I would say,
more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker said he was trying to take the idea of symbiontic
relationships that underscores ``The Phantom Menace'' and
demonstrate it in a more concrete way. The ``midi-chlorians'' that
are unusually abundant in Anakin's blood and that connect us to the
Force are a loose depiction of mitochondria, according to Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Mitochondria are microscopic structures in cells, containing
genetic material and enzymes important for cell metabolism. Lucas
supposes they had something to do with the beginnings of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a way of saying that we have hundreds of little
creatures that live on us, and that without them, we'd all die,''
he said. ``There wouldn't be any life. They are necessary for us;
we are necessary for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas uses them as a metaphor for society _ saying that we must
all get along with each other _ as well as for the planet. ``We
must treat the other creatures on this planet with respect,'' he
said. ``Otherwise, the planet will die.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
