<HEADLINE>
BEHIND-THE FENCE ACTOR LAMENTS  QUIET `HOME IM PROVEMENT' FINALE  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the big hype-o-meter in the sky, TV series finales will be
forever judged against last year's ``Seinfeld'' sign-off.
</P>
<P>
   If that fevered extravaganza of hubbub rated a 10, Tuesday's
``Home Improvement'' hits only about a 6. There's been very little
fuss over the departure of one of the most successful sitcoms of
this or any other era.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the arrival of Darth Maul has something to do with that,
but it still doesn't seem right. Even to show insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it was underrated by the critics,'' said Earl
Hindman, who plays eccentric, unseen neighbor Wilson to Tim Allen's
ever-affable Tim Tyler. ``I do feel that in about 10 years, that
people will look at the show and go, `My gosh, it really was a good
show in terms of total honesty.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched every show, and there are always bummers in a body
of work, but this was a very good show. I think it will be as
lasting as the so-called cult shows _ the ``Seinfelds,'' your
''Cheers,'' ``MASH'' and such. I think those will go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was undervalued by the audience. We've always
had the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York-based theater actor who did a decade on the ``Ryan's
Hope'' soap, Hindman had no idea the series would become an
eight-year success when he originally auditioned, via videotape,
for the Al Borland role, eventually filled by Richard Karn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it would be a pilot, one show, in there and out of
there, a quick $13,000,'' said Hindman, calling from his
Connecticut home. ``But everyone kept telling me this was a
can't-miss proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know anything about this stuff. You know, make a
pilot, make a few bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to a time slot in the gravitational pull of the
then-huge ``Roseanne,'' the series became the most successful debut
of the 1991-92 TV season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I said, `Hello, we may be here for a while,' '' he said.
``Watching the ratings, I realized, `Oh, I signed my life away.
They got me cheap.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hindman didn't meet series star Tim Allen, from whose stand-up
comedy the show's premise was born, until the first read-through of
the pilot episode. He knew Allen was one of the many comics then
getting TV deals, but that's about all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really know his act,'' Hindman said. ``I'd seen him
in a commercial, but I had no idea who he was.'' During a break,
Allen introduced himself by saying he had watched Hindman on
``Ryan's Hope.'' Odd as it seems today, Hindman remembers Allen as
``shy'' in their first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim has been like our guru,'' said Hindman. ``The whole cast
is fun. A lot of shows are real rough, there's sometimes a lot of
tension on the set. We're fun and games, and you can see it on the
air. Our show has always been loose, and it comes directly from
Tim.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Improvement'' has made Hindman, now 56, financially
comfortable for life, but he doesn't intend to do a slow fade to
where-are-they-now specials on high-dial-position cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't just retire because the show is off the air,'' he
said. ``I will, of course, continue to work.''
</P>
<P>
   He plans to pursue his career as ``freelance actor'' and is
currently negotiating to act in a Broadway project he can't yet
reveal.
</P>
<P>
   And he may spend some more time in his home state, Arizona.
Hindman grew up in Bisbee and studied drama at the University of
Arizona and said he still has family in-state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is my home, my heart,'' he said, noting that he
celebrated the recent University of Connecticut NCAA basketball
championship, but retains the UA Wildcats as his sentimental
favorite. ``Arizona is my team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
