<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO STRIKES INCREASE AS CONCERN RISES OVER ACCURACY OF ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO warplanes assigned to attack a military
compound in northwestern Kosovo Friday struck what Yugoslavia's
official news agency described as a nearby prison, killing at least
19 inmates and guards.
</P>
<P>
   The strike came as NATO faced mounting concerns about its
bombing accuracy, even from within the alliance. Germany's foreign
minister, Joschka Fischer, said Friday that NATO should urgently
reconsider its process of choosing what to bomb, though NATO
officials said Germany had not requested a formal review.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's attacks nevertheless resumed a furious pace after
intermittently bad weather hampered strikes. In the 24 hours
leading up to Thursday morning, NATO forces struck only three major
targets including a fuel depot in Belgrade, a missile site near the
Batajnica airport and another fuel facility in Sombor, the Pentagon
said.
</P>
<P>
   But through the day Friday a flurry of strikes was reported
throughout Yugoslavia, including the military compound near the
prison, in the town of Istok, which was hit early Friday and again
Friday night. A television and radio tower and fuel tanks were also
attacked in Smederevo; while bridges, factories and fuel facilities
were hit in Uzice, Pozega and Bor, according to Yugoslavia's news
agency, Tanjug.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances surrounding the bombing of the prison in Istok
remained murky. NATO and Pentagon officials confirmed that allied
aircraft have struck a military compound in Istok on several
occasions, including Friday. However, they said they could not yet
confirm that any NATO bombs or missiles had struck the prison
itself.
</P>
<P>
   One NATO official said the compound was used as a staging area
for Yugoslav Army and police units operating in Kosovo. A Pentagon
official said the prison was near the compound, but was not
targeted in the strikes, which hit two military barracks across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists traveling with a U.N. mission reported seeing
several dead bodies inside the prison's grassy courtyard. Inside
one of the buildings, rubble filled a stairway, and walls were
pock-marked with shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
   The prison's governor, Aleksandar Rakocevic, said his deputy had
been killed and a warden was badly wounded, adding that he believed
three or four prisoners had escaped out of the 1,000 inmates. Many
of them were in for ``terrorist'' offenses, meaning association
with the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   A Serbian official accused NATO of targeting the jail in a bid
to free the prisoners, adding: ``One thousand prisoners _ a perfect
army.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana, apologized Friday to
the governments of several countries whose embassies or
ambassadorial residences were damaged by NATO strikes in Belgrade
Wednesday and Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   The force of blasts at army barracks and a petroleum facility
blew out windows and caused other damage to the homes of
ambassadors from Sweden, India, Norway, Spain and Hungary. The
embassies of Libya and Israel were also slightly damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The residence of Switzerland's ambassador was hit during a
diplomatic dinner with ambassadors from Sweden, Slovakia and the
Vatican. A strike against a fuel depot shattered windows just as
dessert was served. No one was injured in any of the raids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these governments understand fully well that this
damage, if it does occur at all, is wholly unintentional and that
we are making every effort to strike military targets with the
accuracy that you would expect from this alliance,'' NATO's
spokesman, Jamie P. Shea said in Brussels Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, NATO forces bombed and severely damaged China's
Embassy, killing three people. The diplomatic reverberations of
that attack are still being felt. China announced Friday a ban on
port calls in Hong Kong by American Navy ships. The White House,
meantime, said it planned to send a special envoy to China to try
to assuage China's anger over the attack.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, however, the State Department warned other
countries that the safety of diplomats could not be guaranteed in
the middle of a conflict. ``I think any diplomat who is aware of
the situation knows that Yugoslavia is a dangerous place,'' the
department's spokesman, James P. Rubin, said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite NATO's efforts to minimize unintended damage from its
air war, the errors have exposed tensions in the alliance and
increased political pressure to end the bombing, which has now
lasted nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's foreign minister, Robin Cook, said Friday that the
allies remain strongly united behind the effort to reverse
President Slobodan Milosevic's expulsion of hundreds of thousands
of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. He said the airstrikes were
gradually grinding down Yugoslavia's resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any sign that the Yugoslav army at the present
rate of attrition is going to hold out until August or September,''
Cook said during a visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With the summer months approaching, the Pentagon announced that
the Clinton administration was pressing its allies to move quickly
to deploy 45,000 to 50,000 troops to the borders of Kosovo so that
a peacekeeping force would be in place once a settlement is
reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now at least some hint that we may be closer to an
agreement today than we were a month ago, and certainly two months
ago or three months ago,'' the Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth H.
Bacon, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Pentagon continued to build up its air forces,
announcing the activation of another 1,022 members of the Air Force
Reserve and Air National Guard, bringing the total number activated
so far to 5,000. The Pentagon also dispatched 26 more KC-135 aerial
refueling planes to support the airstrikes.
</P>
</TEXT>
