<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-ITALIA-2TAKES     05-21 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-ITALIA-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVETTI VICTORIOUS IN UNPRECEDENTED TAKEOVER OF TELECOM ITALIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on chronology of takeover battle is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Olivetti SpA, the former typewriter manufacturer that
transformed itself into Italy's No. 2 telephone company, triumphed
Friday night in the biggest hostile corporate takeover ever,
gaining control of Telecom Italia, a rival more than five times its
size.
</P>
<P>
   In a David-vs.-Goliath struggle reminiscent of the
American-style takeover brawls of the 1980s, Olivetti lured enough
Telecom Italia shareholders with a $65 billion package of cash and
securities to gain at least 51 percent of Telecom Italia's stock.
Friday was the deadline for shareholders to accept or reject the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   The victory wrecked Telecom Italia's main anti-takeover defense,
a hastily arranged marriage proposal to Deutsche Telekom, Germany's
biggest phone company. That $81 billion all-stock deal was worth
far more than Olivetti's bid on paper, but was plagued by doubts
since the companies first announced it exactly one month ago.
</P>
<P>
   `'I am proud of the response of the market to our offer,'' said
Olivetti chief executive Roberto Colaninno. `'I am content.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the victory signaled the ``beginning of a great new
industrial story.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight over Telecom Italia is expected to send a wakeup call
to Europe's clubby business world, where deals are often struck in
friendly fashion behind closed doors, and where fewer than a dozen
hostile takeovers have succeeded in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that Olivetti succeeded in such a flamboyant
fashion is a measure of the changes overtaking Corporate Europe, as
industries globalize and the Continent unifies under a single
currency.
</P>
<P>
   Colaninno, 55, has pledged to restore direction and purpose to
Telecom Italia, the former national telephone monopoly, which has
struggled since the government took it public last year.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's victory was a stunning defeat for Franco Bernabe, the
Telecom Italia chief executive who had fought stubbornly to thwart
the Olivetti bid. He said, ``It will now be for the shareholders to
decide the future affairs of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Telecom Italia employees effectively conceding
defeat, Bernabe said that Telecom Italia ``emerges from the affair
stronger and more credible. Its international visibility and
notoriety are enhanced.''
</P>
<P>
   The first signs of a probable Olivetti victory emerged early
Friday, when one after another of the major institutional investors
that formed the ``hard core'' of Telecom Italia's shareholder base,
including the big Generali insurance company, the San Paolo-IMI
bank, and the IFIL holding company of the Agnelli family of Fiat,
announced they were tendering their shares to Olivetti. The
defection of San Paolo, Italy's biggest bank, was particularly
bitter for Telecom Italia, since its IMI investment banking unit
was among Bernabe's advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Alone among the core shareholders to cast their vote for Bernabe
was Credit Suisse-First Boston. But Credit Suisse also numbered
among the investment banks advising Bernabe.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, it was Gianni Agnelli, Fiat's honorary chairman and
a longtime financial kingmaker, who gave the first indication of an
Olivetti victory. ``For us, this adventure is over,'' he told
reporters in Turin this evening. But there was an undercurrent of
grudging bitterness, given the Agnellis' support for Bernabe and
opposition to Olivetti. Agnelli heartily congratulated Olivetti,
adding: ``It's a difficult business, with a great future. Heavily
indebted.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti had offered shareholders 11.50 euros, or $12.19, in
cash, bonds and stock for every Telecom Italia common share. Though
it remained unclear Friday night when an official tally would be
available, officials involved in the counting estimated that
Olivetti had obtained roughly 51 percent to 53 percent of Telecom
Itala shares.
</P>
<P>
   Though Olivetti's offer was less than what Deutsche Telekom was
willing to pay, investors were evidently swayed partly by Italian
government objections to the partnership with Deutsche Telekom,
which remains 72 percent controlled by the German government.
Moreover, while Olivetti promised 60 percent cash, Deutsche Telekom
offered its own stock. A final push may have come from the
conviction that merging two big former state phone monopolies was
hardly likely to produce a nimble competitor in the fast moving
world of modern telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Roe, a telecommunications analyst at Paribas Capital
Markets in London, said Olivetti could be satisfied with the
result. ``They want to see the field clear to do something definite
and dramatic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that Olivetti could still face major problems,
notably from ``a lot of disgruntled shareholders'' who did not
tender their shares to Olivetti, including holders of savings, or
non-voting Telecom Italia shares.
</P>
<P>
   The victory promises to boost America's large investment banks,
for whom the deal represented their shot at breaking into the
European market and drawing attention.
</P>
<P>
   `'It is great for Olivetti, it is a victory for Colaninno,''
said Richard Blakesley, head of telecommunications mergers and
acquisitions at Chase Manhattan, which was among the investment
banks advising Olivetti. Others included Lehman Brothers and
Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of unintended consequences of the victory will be
the creation almost overnight of a major European market for
corporate bonds. To help finance the takeover, Olivetti will issue
bonds worth up to $24 billion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The deal will go far in shaking up the Continent's phone
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be major repercussions all across Europe,'' said
Holger Grawe, telecommunications analyst at the German brokerage
firm West LB Panmure.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia's brief and unsuccessful flirt with Deutsche
Telekom so enraged France Telecom, a partner of the Germans in
several ventures, that it is threatening to sever its business
ties.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Deutsche Telekom will find itself facing an even
stronger European competitor on its own home turf. The reason is
that under the terms of the Olivetti takeover, Mannesmann AG,
already Germany's largest mobile phone operator, will end up with a
similar position in the fast growing Italian market. Now that
Olivetti has succeeded, Mannesmann will acquire all of Infostrada
SpA, the second biggest Italian fixed network operator after
Telecom Italia, and a controlling 55 percent stake of Omnitel
Pronto Italia, Italy's second biggest mobile phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom spokesman Hans Ehnert said the company would
``discuss and analyze the results internally in our management, and
then with Telecom Italia, and draw the necessary consequences.''
But he said Deutsche Telekom would stick by its strategy of
international growth, suggesting that the company would seek other
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's victory is also a deep personal triumph for
Colaninno, the aggressive former auto parts manufacturer who became
chief executive of Olivetti in 1996 after the company had been
shaken by losses and investigations by prosecutors into possible
bookkeeping irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   After working as chief executive of Fiaam SpA, a maker of oil
and air filters, Colaninno started a a finance firm in 1980. Carlo
De Benedetti, the Olivetti chairman and a leading financier, then
bought Fiaam and ran it until De Benedetti tapped Colaninno to save
Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia, measured by market capitalization, is more than
five times the size of Olivetti, the 90-year old former typewriter
company that nearly went bankrupt in the mid-1990s before
reinventing itself as a telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   For Bernabe, the three-month struggle to repel Olivetti is a
humiliating loss. The 50-year-old executive, who took over
management of Telecom Italia late last year, was unable to convince
the large institutional shareholders who controlled Telecom Italia
to remain loyal.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to the employees, Bernabe said the fight with
Olivetti had known `'difficult moments,'' but that he had always
conducted it `'with maximum transparency and loyalty to the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe, who ended a six-year tenure as chairman of Eni, the
Italian energy giant, to run Telecom Italia, was credited with one
of the most dramatic turnarounds while at Eni, which had been
shaken by the Italian corruption investigations of the early 1990s.
He transformed it into one of Italy's most profitable corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dissenters from Olivetti's celebration was Nerio Nesi,
the economics spokesman for the Party of Italian Communists, a
leftist splinter group. Calling Friday `'the blackest of days,''
Nesi said Olivetti's victory likely meant ``thousands of lost
jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
