<SLUG> BC-NJ-LOTTERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTTERY COST IS HEAVIEST FOR THE POOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FORD FESSENDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a method of producing income for New Jersey, the lottery is
far less equitable than other historical sources of government
revenue, an analysis by The New York Times has found. At a time
when tax-conscious politicians are searching for ways to reduce
taxes on income and property, lotteries represent an inviting
option.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey income tax, for instance, was designed so that
tax rates rose as income rose. And state property taxes, although
not based on income, tend to reflect income and wealth. Residents
in the 100 highest-income ZIP codes paid income taxes of about 3
percent, triple the rate of those in the 100 lowest-income ZIPs,
according to the analysis of state tax data.
</P>
<P>
   Even the property tax was somewhat progressive, the analysis
showed, with effective tax rates in the highest-income areas about
10 percent higher than those in the lowest-income areas.
</P>
<P>
   But in an analysis of lottery and household-income data, the
analysis found that people in the lowest-income ZIP codes spent
more than 1 percent of their income in 1998 on lottery games _ not
including Pick 3, which could not be analyzed _ while those who
live in the 100 highest-income ZIP codes spent less than 0.25
percent of their income on the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very regressive,'' said Charles Clotfelter, a Duke
University researcher and author of ``Selling Hope,'' a 1989 book
on state lotteries. ``The percentage of a poor person's income that
this kind of tax takes is much greater than for middle- and
upper-income people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
