<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 23)  
(Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet, the SEC and Stock Giveaways
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission may be trying hard to
keep up with what is happening on the Internet. But the Internet
seems to be falling behind on what is happening at the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the view of Stephen Schulte, a securities
lawyer at Schulte Roth &AMP; Zabel in New York who specializes in
Internet issues. As evidence, Schulte points to the continuing
proliferation of ``free stock'' programs on the Net despite clear
SEC warnings that such giveaways risk running afoul of federal
securities laws.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 1998, when Travelzoo.com offered free shares to
people who registered on its Web site, stock giveaways have become
the rage. There is even a Web site
(www.che.wsu.edu/fountain/contents/stock1.htm) devoted to tracking
the other Web sites offering free stock.
</P>
<P>
   Giveaways have been the subject of SEC attention since at least
the 1970s. Consumers getting such shares usually run no risks. But
the companies issuing them are not so lucky. In its older cases,
the commission's legal staff has determined that securities offered
in exchange for something of value must be registered, unless the
company fits within certain limited exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the SEC has issued ``no action'' letters
advising several young Internet businesses that shares offered to
those who visit their Web sites are not really ``free,'' as that
term is defined in federal securities laws. Some of those companies
have put their offers on hold while their lawyers negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   If the commission's advice wasn't clear enough, Schulte said, a
senior SEC staff member told a conference in late February that
```free' stock is a misnomer'' because ``registration with a Web
site provides value to the site's owner and therefore involves
consideration.'' Thus, Schulte added, the SEC staff ``has sent a
clear message'' that unregistered stock giveaways are probably a
no-no.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, this may be a case of message sent, but not
received,'' Schulte said. True, he acknowledged, some companies say
they have suspended their programs ``pending SEC clarification.''
But he added, ``What further clarification do they need?''
</P>
<P>
   _ DIANA B. HENRIQUES
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH
</P>
<P>
   An Oppenheimer Manager Smiles at Buffett's Investment
</P>
<P>
   No, Frank Jennings did not raise a toast to Warren Buffett last
Tuesday, when news surfaced that Berkshire Hathaway, Buffett's
company, held a 2.2 percent stake in the liquor giant Allied
Domecq.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged, ``It cheered me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings is manager of the top-performing Oppenheimer Global
Growth and Income fund, which has held the stock for more than
three years but has barely seen it budge. When Buffett's move was
reported in The Guardian, a British newspaper, Allied Domecq shares
rose 25 pence, or 4.7 percent, to close at 555.5 pence.
</P>
<P>
   According to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher,
Jennings' $576 million fund at last count held the biggest
concentration of Allied Domecq shares of any U.S. offering, at 4.1
percent of total assets.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, who says run-ups of other holdings have recently cut
his Allied Domecq stake to slightly more than 3 percent, is still
bullish on the stock. He figures that Allied Domecq, whose liquor
business includes Ballantine's Scotch whisky and Beefeater gin,
should rise 25 percent annually over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   His math is pretty simple: Allied Domecq stock yields about 5
percent. The company's earnings should grow 10 percent a year on
what he calls a ``normalized basis,'' that is, assuming that Allied
Domecq takes the steps to maximize returns. As earnings grow, the
P/E should rise 10 percent a year as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings expects Allied Domecq to sell its chain of 3,600 pubs,
already on the block, and perhaps its Baskin-Robbins ice cream and
Dunkin Donuts food chains, using the proceeds to buy more liquor
brands as well as its own shares.
</P>
<P>
   A fairly conservative manager, Jennings describes himself as a
``Muld'' investor _ for ``Massive Upside, Limited Downside.'' He
added, ``I'm always looking for a reason not to lose my shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the paltry returns of his Allied Domecq stake so far, he
said he is patient. He added, ``Buffett is willing to wait _ I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
