<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6604 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV2     05-21 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ASSETS PUMPED UP, FEW WORRY ABOUT INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., N.Y., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23)  
 (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inflation is back: Not rising prices, except for an
uncharacteristic spurt in April, but the perennial debate about the
sacrifices that must be made when inflation does turn into a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is premature. The 0.7 percent jump in the Consumer
Price Index last month appears to have been an anomaly, reflecting
a set of circumstances not likely to be repeated in May. But the
April jump was the largest for a single month in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   And the Federal Reserve compounded the alarm by announcing last
Tuesday that, while it was not yet raising interest rates to slow
the economy and head off inflation, it was leaning that way,
``concerned about the potential for a buildup of inflationary
imbalances.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, then, a debate has revived that had lain dormant
during more than two years of very modest inflation. But the terms
of the debate have changed; the issues are different, and the
public's perception of inflation is drastically altered.
</P>
<P>
   The old alarm is missing, for one thing. The CPI may have jumped
in April, but Americans took no notice, according to the University
of Michigan's consumer surveys. ``They don't think any price
increases will stick,'' said Richard Curtin, director of the
surveys. He added that people are more relaxed about inflation than
at any time since the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   That is a considerable change. Three years ago, there was talk
among policy makers of reducing the annual inflation rate to zero,
even if that meant suffering higher unemployment. And people
listened respectfully.
</P>
<P>
   Now that talk is gone. An inflation rate of 1.5 to 2 percent
(the CPI's range for most of the past year) makes no one nervous
today, and a rise to 3 percent seems tolerable to the public, if
not to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   After all, no homeowner _ and most of the nation's families are
homeowners _ is complaining about housing prices, which have been
rising briskly in most regions. Or, as Curtin put it, ``An
important element of the strong consumer confidence today is this
rise in the value of physical assets.''
</P>
<P>
   The revived inflation debate is also taking place in an altered
context. Inflation in America is no longer viewed as a national
phenomenon, but seen as a global one. The American economy can
indeed operate full-blast without the shortages that push up
prices, as long as enough other countries can supplement American
production by diverting their unsold merchandise and their idle
labor to America's needs.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian crisis and its aftermath have forced that perception
into everyone's consciousness. Faced with recession and weak
consumer demand at home, companies in Asia, Europe and Latin
America have been sending their wares to the United States at
discount prices.
</P>
<P>
   And, gradually, officials and economists are coming to the view
that without this flood of imports, the inflation rate in the
United States could not have remained so low through three years of
expansion and the labor shortages it produced.
</P>
<P>
   Excess global capacity is the new buzz phrase, representing a
concept that three years ago most economists and policy makers
thought impossible. Supply used to be considered something that
rapidly fell in line with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Now oversupply _ caused by excess capacity, if not in the United
States, then somewhere else _ is recognized as a persistent
problem. And deflation, a word shunned in the old inflation debate,
is a common concern in the new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The global economy has become the new wild card in making
policy to control inflation,'' said Stephen S. Roach, chief
economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   This new emphasis showed itself last Tuesday in the reaction of
the National Association of Manufacturers to the Fed's inflation
concerns. The manufacturers, who often complain that they cannot
raise prices because of global competition, urged the Fed to hold
interest rates steady because of ``the general weakness of global
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, when the Commerce Department announced that the
trade deficit had widened in March, because of a big jump in
imports, some Wall Street economists welcomed the news instead of
wringing their hands as they once would have. The former thinking
was that trade deficits pull the United States deeper into debt to
foreign lenders who finance the nation's excess spending on
imports.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually this borrowing can depress the dollar, and a weaker
dollar then makes imports more expensive for Americans, pushing up
the inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
   That may yet happen. But it was not uppermost last week in the
minds of the economists at Bankers Trust. They applauded. ``A
burgeoning trade deficit continues to act as a safety valve for the
U.S. economy,'' they told clients, ``siphoning production away from
potentially overheating domestic industries and thus helping keep
inflation tame.''
</P>
<P>
   The new inflation debate is fundamentally altered in another
way. Nothing used to be of greater concern than the trade-off
between domestic unemployment and domestic inflation, a concept
embodied in the acronym NAIRU, short for nonaccelerating inflation
rate of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   When the unemployment rate fell too low, the theory said, labor
shortages would put upward pressure on wages, forcing employers to
increase prices. Nairu refers to the level of unemployment below
which this effect kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   But where is NAIRU, exactly? The common wisdom as recently as
1996 put it at 6 percent, or perhaps a bit lower. But the jobless
rate dropped below 5 percent nearly two years ago, and inflation
kept falling.
</P>
<P>
   Many explanations are offered for this uncoupling: job
insecurity, weak labor unions, temporary workers, a more productive
labor force, the global economy. Whatever the cause, NAIRU has lost
its clout in the new inflation debate _ ``sublimated by the
marvelous combination of low unemployment and low inflation,'' as
Alan Blinder, a Princeton University economist, put it.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve, in these new circumstances, is much more
constrained. Labor shortages are no longer a persuasive reason for
raising interest rates to head off inflation. And when the Fed does
finally act, the communique will have to take a world view _
explaining convincingly how the global economy is now fomenting
inflation in America instead of stifling it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
