</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-HATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFEDERATE SYMBOL BE COMES FLAG OF HATE  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - To carry the Confederate battle flag onto the fields
of the Civil War was to take the death march.
</P>
<P>
   Blinded by the smoky fog of 19th-century warfare, Union soldiers
aimed for the bearer of this banner as it hovered above the haze.
Thousands of men and boys died under it, while rallying around it,
and even on top of it, shielding their treasure from bullets with
their brave, bloodied bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet today their banner has become a bullet _ a bullet of hate.
</P>
<P>
   It evolved from a patriotic token hand-stitched by Virginia
women in the 1860s into a threat waved over the beaten bodies of
Blacks by the Ku Klux Klan in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a cherished symbol of Southern courage also is a racist
symbol used by White supremacist teens in Gilbert, Ariz. It
represents a shot of pain to Blacks, who once again are finding
themselves staring down a barrel of bigotry _ the weapon now buried
in the folds of a flag.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out over the campgrounds at the Country Thunder music
festival in Queen Creek, Ariz., a few weeks ago was like looking
over a Civil War battlefield of old: Confederate banners studded
the fields, flying high over the masses of trucks and tents.
</P>
<P>
   What was once a striking red, white and blue design now carries
many shades of gray.
</P>
<P>
   One group of music fans who flew the flag at Country Thunder saw
it as a symbol of simple rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not racist, just rebels,'' said Scott Taylor of
Cornville.
</P>
<P>
   Another teen was embracing his roots and the legacy of
Confederate bravery and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are from the South,'' said Gordon Miller of Mesa,
Ariz.``To me, that's what it means.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet other campers admitted freely that they were picking up on
the prejudices of the Civil War era, carrying the flag to express a
deep hatred of Blacks based simply on their race.
</P>
<P>
   It's this message that has Blacks, such as Oscar Tillman, the
leader of the Arizona NAACP, who grew up in North Carolina in the
heart of the civil rights movement, shrinking from the flag upon
sight, as if it were a loaded gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the flag is a constant reminder of drinking at the
colored water fountains or waiting at the colored section of the
bus station where I grew up,'' he says. ``It's a constant reminder
of sitting in the house with the lights out, hiding as the Klan ran
up and down the road while flying the flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant reminder of seeing the cross being burned as a
kid, the flag flying over the smoke. It's a constant reminder of a
very dark past that in 1999 we are working not to ever have to deal
with again.''
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of the flag is chiefly in the eye of the beholder,
says Tony Horwitz, who covers the South for the ``Wall Street
Journal'' and is the author of the recent ``Confederates in the
Attic: Dispatches from the Unfinished Civil War.'' And this varied
lot of beholders has kept the debate over the flag burning long
after the smoke from the war cleared in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very powerful symbol in completely different ways,''
Horwitz says. ``It's revered to many White Southerners, and to many
Blacks, it's a swastika. That's why it's such an explosive issue:
There really is no middle ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Confederate battle flag glares from myriad places
with myriad meanings. It threatens from armbands on skinheads at
heavy metal concerts, appears as an adopted logo of country band
BlackHawk, and was flown as a symbol of rebellion by East Germans
as the Berlin Wall was ripped asunder.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate over which of these places is appropriate has
been heating up lately, as national events create groups today that
are as angry and divided as the North and South of old.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Black men who saw the flag as a threat gunned down a
Tennessee man partly because he flew the flag from his truck. In
1997, a Kansas seventh-grader was suspended for sketching a flag in
math class; also that year, fiery tempers erupted over the South
Carolina government's decision to leave the flag flying above the
state Capitol. And just recently, a South Carolina teacher was
fired over his refusal to hide his support of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   The issue smolders in Arizona, too. Country Thunder isn't the
only conduit for the Confederate flag here.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a ``White power'' group at Highland High School in
Gilbert, which police estimate is nearly 300 strong, told police
that they call themselves ``Confederates,'' which led
administrators to ban the increasingly obvious flag from campus.
When asked what the difference between their group and the KKK was,
the youths said ``nothing,'' adding that many members of the group
hope to one day join the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   It is this type of group that the flag's defenders say scar the
symbol's pure intent.
</P>
<P>
   To Chandler, Ariz.'s Tom Jacks, commander of the local Sons of
Confederate Veterans group, it's a symbol of his heritage,
desecrated by those who use it as a symbol of hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my duty to condemn those who, by their use of the
Confederate flag as a symbol of hate, have maligned and disgraced
the flag and the people who fought and died under it,'' he says.
``It's just a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   But Blacks like Phoenix's D.J. Jackson, who demonstrated for
civil rights here as a teen, view the flaunting of the banner as a
threat to their hard-won equality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts,'' he says. ``It hurts to know that you still have
people that don't see the light. There's bad in every race, good in
every race, there's everything in every race. Nobody's no better
than everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   But what puzzles him most is this:
</P>
<P>
   ``My ancestors were slaves, and every time I bring this up and
talk about what's happenning, I'm told to forget the past. But I
can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Horwitz, the central problem boils down to the
tendency of each side to split the flag's ``two histories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have one history without the other,'' he says. ``You
can't isolate them; it's an issue of context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since the Civil War, there's been an attempt by
Southerners to distance the Confederacy from slavery. People want
to say Confederate symbols don't have connotations of slavery. We
can debate it till we're blue in the face, but we would not have
had the war without slavery. You can't separate the two.''
</P>
<P>
   This argument also benefits most of those who fly the flag as a
symbol of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though they try to separate the flag from its racist
connotations, you would find that they themselves would certainly
not see it as a racial symbol,'' Horwitz says. ``But they are still
proud of their ancestors who fought bravely, and no one wants to be
told to spit on their ancestors.'' This, Horwitz says, is what the
protesters and defenders alike must understand in order for this
issue to cool off.
</P>
<P>
   Those who see the flag as a symbol of the South must respect the
fact that it carries many more meanings, some of which are
offensive. Likewise, groups that the flag offends must understand
that not all of those who fly the banner are espousing racist
views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racially, we've come a very long way, but we're still debating
race and trying to work it out. We have to recognize that we still
have a long way to go,'' Horwitz says.
</P>
<P>
   Banning the flag altogether is not the answer, he says. Doing so
would be to commit an act of historical heresy to groups on each
side of the Mason-Dixon line. It would obliterate a relic fought
for by Southerners and defy a Constitution fought for by our
forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   Those that have adopted the flag as a message of hate must
simply be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing to do is to ignore it,'' Horwitz adds.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McMasters, defender of the First Amendment for the Freedom
Forum in Washington, says a ban would be a gross violation of the
First Amendment and perhaps a move that would turn an issue of
hurtful yet free expression into the explosive, angry weapons we so
fear today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the speech of the individual and the minority group that
must be protected by the Constitution. That includes the speech of
the revolutionary, the radical, the rascal and, yes, the racist,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that one of the lessons of the (Littleton, Colo.,
school shooting) is that we have to worry about how our school
officials are retreating behind closed doors so that kids are left
to work these things out by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more speech with our kids, not less. We need more
speech among our kids, not less, and more avenues of expression,
not less. As long as people are talking, we can deal with it. But
when those feelings turn inward and explode, we see why our
Founding Fathers put so much faith in freedom of expression.'' &QL; 
Jaimee Rose can be reached at at jaimee.rose(at)pni.com via e-mail.
Story includes information from Republic wire services and ``The
Damned Red Flags of the Rebellion'' by Richard Rollins. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
