The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Saturday, May 22. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
INS BUST (Phoenix) - Federal authorities on Friday claimed they had
taken new ground in the battle against illegal immigration by
dismantling a Phoenix-based smuggling ring that brought to Arizona
and sent them on to destinations across the country. According an
official of the Immigration and Naturalization Service, undercover
investigators infiltrated the ring's operations in Honduras,
Guatemala and and El Salvador. By JERRY KAMMER. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COHOUSING (Prescott, Ariz.) - Picture the shared meals,
environmental sensitivity and fuzzy friendliness of a hippy
compound. Then add private homes and residents heading off in suits
and ties to typical jobs. The unlikely combination _ known as
``cohousing'' _ is the 21st century answer to the commune. It's a
group of a few dozen households, who own a huge ``common house''
for the community but also individual residences for each.
Arizona's first cohousing project is going up in Prescott, and two
others are in the works in Tucson. By KATHLEEN INGLEY. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Phoenix) - On the big hype-o-meter in the sky, TV
series finales will be forever judged against last year's
``Seinfeld'' sign-off. If that fevered extravaganza of hubbub rated
a 10, Tuesday's ``Home Improvement'' hits only about a 6. There's
been very little fuss over the departure of one of the most
successful sitcoms of this or any other era. ``I do think it was
underrated by the critics,'' said Earl Hindman, who plays
eccentric, unseen neighbor Wilson to Tim Allen's ever-affable Tim
Tyler. ``I do feel that in about 10 years, that people will look at
the show and go, `My gosh, it really was a good show in terms of
total honesty.' '' By DAVE WALKER. Story moved in the ``E''
category. Embargoed for Sunday, May 23. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FLAG-HATE (Phoenix) - To carry the Confederate battle flag onto the
fields of the Civil War was to take the death march. Blinded by the
smoky fog of 19th-century warfare, Union soldiers aimed for the
bearer of this banner as it hovered above the haze. Thousands of
men and boys died under it, while rallying around it, and even on
top of it, shielding their treasure from bullets with their brave,
bloodied bodies. Yet today their banner has become a bullet _ a
bullet of hate. By JAIMEE ROSE. Story moved in the ``A'' category.
Embargoed for Sunday, May 23. &QL; 
