<HEADER>
A6617 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-PERP22-COX     05-21 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-PERP22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neighbors in demand for media interviews
 &HT;    By Michael Weiss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ Skip Morgan and his friends shot hoops in his
driveway, watching the cars cruise into the quiet cul-de-sac, gaze
for a moment at the house at the end of the road, and then drive
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been doing it all day,'' he said. ``They just want to
see it, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The stately brick home, shaded by decades-old trees and blocked
off by a stretch of yellow crime-scene tape, has turned the quiet
subdivision into quite a draw. It belongs to the family of the
teen-ager accused of opening fire on a crowd of fellow students at
Heritage High School on Thursday, and it's become a magnet for
those wanting to know more about him.
</P>
<P>
   An armed sheriff's deputy kept everyone away from the home, even
neighbors who wanted to bring water to the suspect's pet beagle,
Gerald, moaning to the crowds from the hot cement driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Curiosity-seekers simply glanced at the two-story house with
broad windows and a winding drive for a moment before turning
around. Reporters _ though kept away from the home by the deputy _
stayed a bit longer, searching for neighbors who have talked to the
suspect, even for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon, Skip had talked to so many reporters that
he believed it when his father called him to the phone, saying
anchor Bernard Shaw from CNN was on the line. It was really Skip's
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must have been 20 or 25 of them already,'' said Skip,
17, sipping a soda from a McDonald's cup. ``It got so busy, I had
to take a lunch break.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip and the 15-year-old suspect carpooled to summer school and
he was in the basement when the suspect proudly showed off his
parent's wood-and-glass gun cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect kept to himself, rarely hanging out outside his
home, Skip said. He had a basketball hoop at the end of his
driveway, but he never used it. He played baseball in a rec league
but wouldn't join neighborhood kids for games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just played on the Internet all the time,'' Skip said.
``His line was always busy when my sister would call his sister.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone who knew the suspect thought he was that
different.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Vander Meer, now a 17-year-old sophomore at Heritage
High, considers herself a friend of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock,'' she said. ``I started crying really bad
because I couldn't believe it was (him). ''
</P>
<P>
   Vander Meer said her friend was doing poorly in school, but
showed no signs of being seriously troubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know him; I can't even fathom why he did this,'' she said.
``I didn't want people to just think he always thought about this
stuff when he didn't really show any signs to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Other teens in the neighborhood had less contact with the
suspect. Heritage senior Mike Bouchard, 18, remembered the suspect
trying out for band as a freshman. He played with the drum line for
no longer than a couple of weeks, always standing in the back,
before quitting without a word to anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard didn't even know the suspect lived in his subdivision
until after the shooting, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schroeder, 14, rode the bus with the suspect every morning,
including Thursday. As always, he said, the suspect climbed onto
the bus and walked straight to the back, not talking to anybody. In
retrospect, he said, the teen seemed a little pale.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I really didn't notice anything,'' he said. ``It
just felt different.''
</P>
<P>
   Even people who barely knew the suspect attracted reporters.
Next-door neighbor Sue Kelly, a real estate agent for the
subdivision, spent several minutes with an NBC camera crew even
though she barely saw the families since selling them the home and
its acre-and-half lot a little more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked them for neighbors,'' she said. ``Otherwise I wouldn't
have sold them the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer R. Robin McDonald contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
