<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA, US DEADLOCK OVER TROOP USE IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Three weeks of diplomatic efforts to end the
Kosovo conflict stalled Friday as Russia and the United States
failed to resolve a fundamental dispute over the role of NATO and
Serbian forces in a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic deadlock came as NATO continued its air raids on
Yugoslavia, killing at least 19 in a series of attacks on a jail in
Kosovo, according to Serb officials.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's chief Balkans envoy, former prime minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin, abruptly canceled negotiations with American and
European envoys, observers expressed growing pessimism over chances
for a diplomatic breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any breakthroughs or any breakdowns,'' said UN
special envoy Carl Bildt, Sweden's former prime minister, noting
that negotiations are expected to resume next week in Moscow. The
European Union's Kosovo envoy, Wolfgang Petritsch, said it is
likely to be ``several months'' before the bombing campaign ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meetings in Moscow have not yet delivered any positive
results,'' added Vladimir Lukin, head of the Russian parliament's
foreign relations committee. ``The US continues to take a very
stubborn, negative stance.'' He said NATO's demand that Yugoslavia
pull all its forces from Kosovo is ``tantamount to detaching the
province from Serbia. It means Yugoslavia's full capitulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia and Western powers agreed on a blueprint for peace on May
6. The so-called Group of 8 accord, which has been endorsed in
principle by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, calls for
withdrawal of Serb forces from Kosovo and the deployment of an
international security force to oversee the return of more than
800,000 refugees. Russia's acting foreign minister, Igor Ivanov,
said differences remain over the timing of a Serb withdrawal and
the composition of the force. Washington wants NATO to form its
backbone while Moscow wants the United Nations to select the
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, diplomats said there were increasing
signs that Milosevic's forces may be planning a military overthrow
of the pro-western Yugoslav Republic of Montenegro. Petritsch, an
Austrian ambassador, said Montenegro was ``moving closer'' to
falling victim to a ``creeping coup.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1,000 and 5,000 residents of the Montenegran town of
Cetinje held a demonstration Friday to protest the arrival of
hundreds of Yugoslav troops in their town. On Thursday, the
Yugoslav army sealed off Montenegro's border with Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The siege is tightening around Cetinje, but they will not
frighten us,'' the town's mayor, Savo Paraca, told the crowd. ``We
are telling the army today that it is not welcome in our city.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Milosevic insisted that the flight of hundreds of
thousands of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo in recent months was
prompted by NATO's bombing campaign. He said mediation efforts
should be handled by the United Nations, a move opposed by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calls for a peaceful and political solution, which Yugoslavia
supports, would prevail over the dictates of force,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a week-long lull, a new wave of some 3,700 refugees
crossed the border from Kosovo into Albania Friday. They denied
that NATO bombs caused them to flee, telling reporters and UN
officials that Serb forces had come knocking on their doors and
commanding that they leave.
</P>
<P>
   The Dubrava jail in Istok, Kosovo, was bombed six times Friday,
Yugoslav media reported. Prison Governor Aleksander Rakocevic said
prisoners and guards were among the casualties of one of the
daytime attacks. NATO planes targeted the prison again on Friday
evening but there were no immediate reports of further injuries or
damage at the complex 45 miles west of the Kosovo capital Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Serb officials said the 1,000-inmate prison held mainly
supporters of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army. In Brussels,
Belgium, NATO officials said bombers were targeting a ``security
complex'' in Istok but had no word on casualties or other details.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO military spokesman in Brussels said Yugoslav special
police used in Kosovo were based at the prison complex and that it
was a staging point for both police and Yugoslav Army units
operating in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin Friday accused
Milosevic of seeking to deprive the United Nations of full access
to the more than 700,000 Kosovars driven from their homes inside
Kosovo by Serb authorities. He said a UN mission that arrived in
Yugoslavia last week to assess the humanitarian tragedy in the
region had been forced to spend most of its time investigating NATO
bombing sites in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential that the United Nations not allow itself to be
forced into cooperating with his agenda to use the mission to
generate favorable propaganda,'' Rubin said, noting that the team
had been allowed to visit Kosovo for only three days. ``It is
obvious that President Milosevic does not want the international
community to bear witness to events in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's ambassador to the United Nations, Sergei Lavrov,
condemned NATO's bombing of a hospital Wednesday night and
suggested that NATO's renewed air strikes on Belgrade may be aimed
at scuttling peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``These so-called mistakes occur now daily and the only way to
stop this tragedy is to stop the bombing,'' said Lavrov. ``Just as
we try to achieve a settlement the bombing intensifies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this is not a deliberate attempt to undermine the
political settlement efforts,'' he added. ``What is going on in the
skies over Yugoslavia not only doesn't help but makes those efforts
much more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The sharp Russian response represents a serious challenge to US
efforts to prevent a deterioration in relations between Moscow and
Washington over the Kosovo conflict. ``The Clinton administration
thought it could bring the Russians onboard,'' said Gary Dempsey, a
Balkans analyst at the Cato Institute in Washington. ``That's
clearly not happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, meanwhile, said he and
Finnish President Martti Athisaari plan to return to Moscow next
week to resume negotiations with Chernomyrdin. The US ambassador to
the United Nations, Peter Burleigh, also assured Russia that
Washington ``is committed to a peaceful settlement'' of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials insisted that accusations of reckless NATO
targeting is unfair, noting that only 12 of the alliance's 10,000
fired missiles have gone astray. But NATO political spokesman
Jaimie Shea said NATO would not let up on its military campaign,
adding that the 19-nation alliance's unity is ``rock solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea, hinting at a potential buildup of NATO forces in the
Balkans, warned that nothing short of total capitulation to NATO's
demand by Yugoslavia would halt NATO bombings. Shea said NATO's
13,000 troops in Macedonia have been freed from humanitarian relief
duty, adding that an additional 3,000 would be in Macedonia within
two weeks. There have also been reports that NATO's commander, Gen.
Wesley K. Clark, has asked NATO to let hm assemble of force of up
50,000 troops along Kosovo's borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a capable so-called enabling force, advance guard
force,'' said Shea. He said it was up to NATO political leadership,
which will meet on the issue next week, to decided ``whether that
force is going to need to be reinforced in the near future to be
fully ready for the mission.''
</P>
<P>
   A debate in NATO over a the prospect of a land invasion has
driven a wedge between NATO's hawks and doves. While Britain has
pressed for NATO to prepare for a possible ground war, Germany and
others have openly opposed the plan. Clinton said he would rule
nothing out.
</P>
<P>
   Germany political leaders joined Italy Friday in calling for
greater caution in the NATO bombing operation, which has
accidentally struck hospitals, foreign embassies and ethnic
Albanian and Serb civilians since the conflict began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright and
British Foreign Minister Robin Cook issued a joint denial that
there is a rift between Washington and London.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said any decision on sending ground forces
into Kosovo needs to be resolved in the next three weeks.
Otherwise, the allies will be unable to return the refugees to
their home before the Spring of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to have a decision on ground forces by the middle of
June,'' said Ivo Daalder, a former Balkans expert in the US
National Security Council. ``It takes two months to get the forces
in and one month to conduct the operation. By mid-September, you
have to start winterizing the camps. The refugees won't be able to
come back until the following spring.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
