<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE FOREST RESOURCE IGNORED, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Forest covers more than 60 percent of Massachusetts,
but no one plans for the future of what may be the state's most
valuable natural resource, according to a new Harvard University
report. This results in woods that have little public identity,
reduced value to wildlife and limited lumber production.
</P>
<P>
   The report, warmly received by a legislative panel in Gardner
Friday, calls for more active management of the 3 million acres of
woodlands in the state, including logging to improve wildlife
habitat, a bigger wood products industry, and land set aside to
become the ``old growth'' forests of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is almost entirely a lack of attention to management or
any kind of evidence that people are putting the forest to work in
a systematic way,'' said Charles H.W. Foster, co-author of the
report, ``Thinking in Forest Time.'' ``We have a resource that in
many ways is lying fallow.''
</P>
<P>
   State Environmental Affairs Secretary Robert Durand praised
Foster's work, and he promised to ``lead the effort'' to begin
better managing both public and private land.
</P>
<P>
   ``In planning discussions in the past on environmental issues,
it was easy to neglect the forests because they don't have a
constituency,'' said Durand, a longtime champion of forest causes.
``I think we've finally got the right mix of decision-makers . . .
to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has completed a remarkable forest turnaround since
1860 when nearly 70 percent of the state was cleared for
agriculture. With the decline of farming, many fields have reverted
to forest, and today the US Forest Service estimates that 62.5
percent of the state is covered with trees.
</P>
<P>
   However, Foster and fellow Harvard Forest ecologist David R.
Foster argue that the return of the woods has been almost entirely
unguided, creating problems that most people don't even notice. For
instance, there are relatively few young forests in the state,
depriving animals that prefer forest clearings, such as many
songbirds, of their habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Durand was so concerned about the increasing density of the
state's forests that, while a state senator, he succeeded in adding
$10 million to the 1996 open space bond to pay for habitat
improvement projects such as forest thinning.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also suggest that the Massachusetts woods don't
produce nearly the amount of forest products they could, forcing
the state to import more from areas that may not have as stringent
environmental standards as Massachusetts. Underscoring that point,
the researchers delivered their findings in Gardner, the state's
furniture capital, at Wachusett Community College, which is seeking
new markets for Massachusetts wood.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Foster and David Foster called for the state to produce
30 percent of its own lumber, paper and other wood products,
compared to only a few percent of locally grown wood products
today. To discourage logging in ecologically valuable woods, the
researchers called for the state to buy timber rights on private
land.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers want a forest plan that allows for a mosaic
of forest types, including more land set aside to mature into old
growth forest. Currently, the state has barely 1,000 acres of old
growth that somehow avoided the woodsman's ax since the first
European colonists.
</P>
<P>
   And the researchers want a plan that private land owners will
follow, not just governments and land trusts. They pointed out that
private owners in one region of the state, the 1,800 square miles
on the north end of the Quabbin Reservoir, already follow a common
strategy to preserve the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a crucial point in time,'' said Charles Foster. ``We
have a chance for the first time in history to plan intelligently
for the forest.''
</P>
<P>
   Adopting the Harvard approach will mean more chainsaws in the
Massachusetts woods, but the researchers say the public needs to
understand that a managed forest is better for nature and the
economy as well, avoiding a binge of logging later when the state's
forests reach old age en masse.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the average citizen, the prospect of harvesting trees
triggers instant environmental concern, notwithstanding the fact
that carefully managed forests tend to provide more uses, values
and benefits than those lacking responsible stewardship,'' the
report concludes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
