<HEADLINE>
FENWAY OPPOSITION OUT IN LEFT FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where have you gone, Ted Mack? Please come back, Gene Jones,
wherever you are. For those of you who don't go back to black and
white television, Ted Mack was the host of the ``Original Amateur
Hour,'' which featured guys playing the clarinet with their left
ears, or someone with no fingers catching knives under his armpits.
Gene Jones was the local version of Mack, hosting ``Community
Auditions,'' which wasn't supposed to be hilarious but was, just as
it has been this week watching seemingly every citizen in these
parts have his say about Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about amateur night. Let's start with this one-liner. One
of the group wanting to preserve old Fenway (which doesn't look
like the new Fenway when you see the model) was asked where the
team would play while the park is being renovated. ``Can't they
just take the year off?'' Sure. The players will gladly sit out and
donate their salaries to the cause. And the American League will be
glad to have one team every day with no one to play. Great idea.
</P>
<P>
   How about this one, on the same subject, to the same group.
``What's wrong with playing in Foxborough?'' Isn't that a side
splitter. No way Jose. Playing in Foxborough, we might disturb the
people in the trailer park who want to die there. Seriously, where
do these people come from? Do they have no life?
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the question of the neighborhood and how it
will be affected. Consider that the Red Sox play 81 home games a
season. There are 365 days in the year. That means only one day out
of nearly every five is there a game in Fenway Park. On an average
game day, the neighborhood is impacted for about six hours tops.
It's been that way for close to 100 years and the new ballpark
isn't going to change it.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway Park was up and running before anyone in the neighborhood
who wants to gripe about it moved there. They had to know it was
there. I don't think anyone forced them to live there, and very few
of them own property there. Some of the best interviews come from
the property owners. All of a sudden Yawkey Way is Newbury Street,
our version of the Gold Coast. Of course this has nothing to do
with them trying to drive up the price when it comes to the land
being purchased. Example: Chuck Schmidt of the Detroit Lions said
Thursday that when his team first starting looking at land in
downtown Detroit for a stadium site, the cost was $15 per square
foot. By the time they went to eminent domain proceedings, and
court, it was up to $75 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   And I love all the talk about parking. The Yankees have been
playing in the Bronx forever, in a stadium that once held 70,000
and now holds 55,000, or 11,000 more than a new Fenway would seat.
There is next to no parking at Yankee Stadium. Yet they survive,
and the neighborhood is intact. The Red Sox have been around for
nearly a century. They have never gotten a cent off the city or
state, even though over that period they have meant hundreds of
millions of dollars to the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   This is not about some millionaires getting richer off the
public. Fifty-five percent of the money that will come from the
sale of the team, and the park, when it is completed, will go to
charity. That is written in Mrs. Yawkey's will. It has to happen.
This is a unique situation. Over the long haul, a new Fenway Park
will give a lot more back to the community than the community will
give to it. Meanwhile, let's hope we've had enough of the clown
shows. We went through this with Boston Garden. It's now a parking
lot and somehow we have survived. The economy of the state has not
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In spite of all his promises to be good and take football
seriously, it seems Terry Glenn is back to his old form. Sources
tell me he made it to four of his offseason workouts at Foxborough.
The same people say he ran well in those workouts but it seems
working out at a high level is not among his top priorities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What great fans those Chicago Bulls supporters turned out to be.
Once the show was over, attendance dropped an average of 6,600 per
game this year. Just like the Lakers when Magic left. Say one thing
for Celtics fans: Even when the team stunk, they still showed up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One national report had the Patriots talking trade for Barry
Sanders. ``First I heard of it,'' says Schmidt. ``We haven't talked
to the Patriots or anyone else about trading Barry, and we won't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden on the rest of the
Stanley Cup playoffs: ``I think Buffalo will knock off Toronto and
Colorado will beat Dallas. Both will be tough series, and in the
end, I think it will be Colorado. They have two of the best lines
in hockey, and (Patrick) Roy beat Detroit almost by himself. How
about Detroit? Everyone was saying how great the Red Wings were and
how smart they were to wrap up the Cup by getting (Chris) Chelios,
(Ulf) Samuelsson, and (Wendel) Clark just before the trading
deadline. That will cost them millions and they got nothing out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celtics coach Rick Pitino on the NBA playoffs: ``I felt before
the season started that Indiana would win it all, and I haven't
changed my mind. I think the Pacers have the best 10-man team in
basketball and depth is the key factor. No matter who they play out
of that top 10, there is almost no dropoff. Jalen Rose doesn't even
start and he's become one of the most explosive players in the
game. I like Utah and their experience to make it from the West,
but Indiana to win it all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations to Reggie Dupard, the Patriots' first-round pick
in 1986, for going back and getting his degree from SMU 13 years
after the fact. ``I'm sorry things didn't work out with the
Patriots,'' says Dupard, who now heads up a youth ministry in
Dallas. ``I injured my big toe the second week of camp and was
never the same. Something like Deion Sanders is going through down
here right now with the Cowboys. And with the Patriots I partied to
much. Never focused on football the way I should. I liked coach
(Raymond) Berry but playing on that team was like being in a Club
Med. A lot of parties and not enough focus on football. I played
five years in all, the last two in Washington, and then I gave it
up. Pro football for me was never what I hoped it would be. Now I'm
very happy with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cleary has no one in mind to be the next head coach of
Harvard hockey. ``We had to put it out to bid and go through the
process. I've had a lot of calls from people who are interested.
When Ronn Tomassoni was here, I just never gave much thought to a
next hockey coach. We want a good person. We want someone who
understands what being involved with Harvard is and what it takes
to make this a successful program.'' My nominee is Ben Smith, a
Harvard man who coached the US women's team to the gold medal in
Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How can anyone connected with the Patriots say they are
interested in running back Lawrence Phillips after taking such a
high road when they dumped his former teammate, Christian Peter,
two years ago. Phillips, with all his troubles, makes Peter look
like a saint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox CEO John Harrington on the appraisals of major league
teams released by Forbes Magazine this week: ``They are not even
close. They don't know what they are talking about. A couple of
times a year these business magazines come up with these numbers
and what they have is ridiculous. No one should pay any attention
to them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Syracuse running back Rob Konrad from North Andover, was
in Miami shopping for a new car this week. Shortly after he left a
dealership, he got a call on his cell phone from a Miami agent,
asking if he was happy with his agent. Konrad had to laugh because
he was sitting with Mike Clohisey, who works with agent Jack Mula
in Boston. Seems the dealership was tied to the Miami agent, who
has a reputation for trying to steal other agent's players.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of that, the going rate for college juniors who figure
to be first-round picks in the NFL is $1,500 a month, under the
table, from an agent, until the player is drafted. Meanwhile,
college coaches look the other way when the kid comes back to
school for his senior year wearing a $3,000 watch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, combined scoring for NBA games averaged 198 points.
Forty years later, the average NBA game totaled 156 points. So much
for playing above the rim.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
