<HEADER>
A6633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-HERO22-COX     05-21 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-HERO22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Task at hand deflected possibility of death for faculty hero
 &HT;    By Leon Stafford and Nathanial W. Cook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ The assistant principal the nation is calling a
hero didn't realize how close he came to death until he lowered the
hammer of the loaded .357 Magnum that minutes before was pointed at
his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the gun cocked after he handed it to me, I knew it
was serious,'' Cecil Brinkley said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Heritage High School administrator had just coaxed the
weapon from a 15-year-old student who had briefly terrorized the
suburban Rockdale County campus. ``That's Cecil. If there was a
fight, he was always the first one there,'' said Jerry Johnston,
who worked with Brinkley at Heritage and has known him for 19
years.
</P>
<P>
   Students know Brinkley as a disciplinarian, said Jason McElroy,
a student at Heritage. While Brinkley is quiet and minds his own
business, the youngster said, students know they are in trouble if
sent to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you mess up, you're gonna pay,'' McElroy said. ``But he's a
good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley, a father of two and grandfather of six, is retiring in
September after 40 years in education. He is an avid reader and has
earned a reputation as one of the best gardeners around, said his
son Matt Brinkley, 30. Not surprisingly, since he grew up in a
farming family of 13 brothers and sisters in Greensboro, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Brinkley's family moved to Rockdale County in 1975. Both
of his children are Heritage High graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always consistent and has always known the difference
between right and wrong,'' Matt Brinkley said. ``A friend of mine
called me and said, 'That's what I expected your father to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Brinkley spent Friday in a whirlwind of interviews with
local and national news media. Dressed in a blue sportcoat and
khaki pants, he smiled shyly and spoke softly before the cameras,
downplaying his role in defusing the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just doing my job'' was his familiar refrain.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday started out like any other day, Brinkley recalled. He
sat down with his wife, Elizabeth, to eat breakfast around 5:50
a.m., stopping to say a prayer of thanks before enjoying his Basic4
cereal. They talked about her students at Salem High School, the
end of the school year and her impending retirement from teaching
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Brinkley kissed his wife, said goodbye and slid behind the
wheel of his beloved 1969 Buick station wagon, a vehicle known to
every student at Heritage High. It was 6:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:03 a.m., Rockdale police said, a 15-year-old sophomore
began spraying bullets at his classmates milling in the school's
common area before classes began.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley was in his office. He had already checked his mail,
grabbed the morning paper and run errands around the building. When
he heard a popping sound like firecrackers, his first thought was
that seniors were playing a prank again, like the crickets they
unleashed in the hallways the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I saw the students running in a panicked state and I knew
this was serious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley ran across the common area and out the door where the
armed student had apparently fled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked to the left and saw him near the entrance to the
school, on the sidewalk, kneeled down,'' Brinkley said. ``He had
placed the pistol barrel in his mouth. I didn't know what he was
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy was about 40 to 50 feet away. Brinkley darted back into
the building and sped down a hallway parallel to the sidewalk. As
he came out of another door, he was within 10 feet of the student
with the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pointed his pistol towards me,'' Brinkley said. ``I said,
'Give me the gun. Give me the gun.' He seemed nervous, but I knew I
needed to get the gun away from him. I kept saying 'Give me the
gun,' as I walked towards him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tense moments later, the boy finally lowered the barrel of the
.357-caliber handgun and placed the weapon in Brinkley's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got his pistol, he grabbed me and gave me a great big
bear hug, and he said, 'I'm scared.' He wasn't really crying, but
his voice was unsteady,'' Brinkley said.
</P>
<P>
   The assistant principal said the deadly violence a month earlier
at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., never entered his
mind while he was disarming the Heritage student.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ... see a situation that is so serious that something has
to be done, that you know you have to do what has to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
