<HEADLINE>
MOORE WILL BE BACK ON FAMILIAR TURF AGAINST CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the desolate expanses of Oklahoma were producing millions
of barrels of oil in the 1970s, there were few indications the
region would ever produce soccer players. But when the North
American Soccer League created the Tulsa Roughnecks franchise, it
attracted an investor named Carl Moore, whose son would go on to
become one of the US national team's top goal scorers.
</P>
<P>
   Joe-Max Moore's interest in soccer began in Tulsa, where he
learned from watching the Roughnecks. But the NASL dried up by 1985
and the Moore family moved to Mission Viejo, Calif., where Joe-Max
could continue his soccer education. His competition would include
an obscure high schooler named Nomar Garciaparra, and one of his
major influences would be Sigi Schmid, his coach at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Moore is preparing to return to Southern California,
leading the Revolution into Sunday's match against the Los Angeles
Galaxy, now coached by Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sigi will prepare them well, no question,'' Moore said. ``He
will be an excellent professional coach. I wish the best for him,
but I have a job to do as well.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Moore will be on a goal-scoring mission. The Revolution
have not scored in 250 minutes of play, since Moore converted a
free kick in a 2-1 loss to Colorado May 1. Only one of his three
goals has been scored in the run of play. And the Revolution
haven't produced enough of the free kick chances Moore and Edwin
Gorter can convert.
</P>
<P>
   Simply, the Revolution have become a resourceful team
defensively. But they have yet to achieve a balance of defense and
offense. Once the defense broke down in last week's 2-0 loss to
Columbus, the Revolution did not seem dangerous enough to
retaliate, though they controlled the tempo for much of the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we're getting there as a team,'' Moore said. ``At
the beginning of the year, we were more a defensive and
counterattacking team. Against Columbus, we had more possession.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore has 26 goals in 58 games for the Revolution, a strike rate
of .448, among the best in Major League Soccer. The Revolution
could have one of the more potent attacks in the league with Moore
and Giovanni Savarese, who has 43 goals in 91 MLS appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gio and myself should have done more with what we got against
Columbus,'' Moore said. ``With me, it's a personal thing. I need to
focus a little more. We are creating opportunities, and it's a
matter of time before we put a couple of goals in and start
building confidence within the team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This will only be Moore's second game for the Revolution at the
Rose Bowl. He missed previous games with injuries and national team
commitments . . . The Revolution fell twice to the Galaxy by 5-1
scores last year. After the second defeat, Walter Zenga replaced
Thomas Rongen as head coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
