NYT-05-21-99 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      05-21 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN, SACHS HIRED TO HANDLE SALE OF THE JETS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The estate of Leon Hess announced Friday that it was
selling the Jets and had hired the investment firm Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co. to handle the process.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement had been expected since Hess died on May 7,
because people familiar with his wishes said he did not want to
pass the team on to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Jets issued a statement regarding the estate's sale
of the team, Hess' will has not been filed in Surrogate's Court.
</P>
<P>
   The attractiveness of the Jets as a National Football League
team in the country's largest market is likely to yield a sale
price of at least $500 million, sports finance experts say. Hess
invested $250,000 in the team in 1963 with four other partners. He
bought out his last partner in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gutman, the team's president, will work with Goldman,
Sachs. The team emphasized that Coach Bill Parcells continues to
have ``complete authority'' over football operations and has the
full support of the Hess estate.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tagliabue, the NFL commissioner, discussed the estate's
plans earlier this week with John Hess, Leon's son. ``And he will
have further discussions with John,'' said Greg Aiello, a league
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets set no deadline, but if last year's sale of the
Cleveland Browns is a guide, the process could be completed before
the season starts. It may go quickly, especially because John Hess
is not expected to bid to keep the team in the family, as John Kent
Cooke did during his recent failed bid to buy the Washington
Redskins from his father's estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the wish of the New York Jets, the Hess family, and the
executors of the estate, that the 1999 season be dedicated to the
memory of Leon Hess,'' the Jets said in a statement announcing the
team's sale.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Goldman, Sachs is not surprising. It oversaw
the sale of the Browns last year for the NFL. Eric Grubman, a
managing director of Goldman, Sachs, managed the Browns' process,
has done investment work for John and Leon Hess at the family's
Amerada Hess oil business, and is expected to run the Jets' sale.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs is very likely to establish deadlines; produce a
prospectus for interested buyers; handle contacts with all bidders
and produce the highest price, and present the bids to the estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought my team through Goldman, Sachs, and they did an
excellent job,'' Robert K. Kraft, the owner of the New England
Patriots and chairman of the NFL. finance committee, said Friday.
``They extracted every bit and then some. They're very professional
and know all the nuances of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft said his personal wish was that the team not be sold and
for John Hess to own the Jets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
