<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-REBATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC TO OFFER REBATES IN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Bell Atlantic Corp. Friday said that its three million
Massachusetts customers will share $38 million in rebates and rate
reduction this summer following a controversial state regulatory
decision on Wednesday that the company was no longer required to
pay fees for local calls headed to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the money already in escrow, Bell Atlantic Friday
said it will provide customers with a one-time $4 credit for each
telephone line and cut the cost of touchtone telephone service to
49 cents per month from 98 cents a month. Both pricing changes are
expected to take effect sometime this summer, a Bell Atlantic
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The lower telephone costs stem from a 3-2 vote by the
commissioners of the state Department of Telecommunications and
Energy over whether local calls to the Internet are truly local. If
a local call goes to an independent phone company, Bell Atlantic
has been paying fees, called recirprocal compensation to complete
the call.
</P>
<P>
   Three commissioners sided with Bell Atlantic's position that
Internet calls are very different from voice calls, because they
first are routed to an independent phone company, and then to an
Internet service provider which connects the customer to the
Internet. Thus, Bell Atlantic should not have to pay recirporocal
compensation, the company maintained.
</P>
<P>
   Two commissioners, including chairwoman Janet Gail Besser, sided
with independent telephone companies, which maintain the calls are
local and therefore they should receive reciprocal compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The DTE decision surprised some indpendent phone companies like
RNK Inc., a Stoughton, Mass. carrier that transfers Bell Atlantic
calls. Richard Koch, company president said the DTE decision will
sharply impact his business. He maintains his firm is owed $688,000
in reciprocal compensation from Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public deserves to get the $38 million, but Massachusetts
is the only state to have done this and it's wrong,'' said Koch. He
points to nine other states that have dealt with the same
reciprocal compensation issue and ruled in favor of independent
phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic officials maintain that the DTE's decision plugs a
``loophole,'' in no longer requiring middlemen, like independent
phone companies, to collect reciprocal compensation fees for
terminating calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the DTE not closed this loophole our ratepayers would have
been faced with a substantial annual rate increase to cover the
cost of these fees,'' said Robert Mudge, Bell Atlantic vice
president-Massachusetts. ``The consumer has clearly won with this
ruling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
