<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE LAWYER DISPUTES LEWIS EARNINGS TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Had he lived, Celtics star Reggie Lewis would have
earned at least $117 million in his lifetime from playing,
endorsements, and broadcasting jobs, a sports agent testified
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Lewis's career were cut short by a medical condition
_ such as the heart problem that killed him _ he still could have
made more than $41 million through coaching, marketing, and sports
commentary, agent Arn Tellem said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie Lewis had a brilliant career ahead of him as a
basketball player,'' said Tellem, testifying Friday in the medical
malpractice trial stemming from Lewis's death. ``There was no
reason to believe his career wouldn't have gone on for a long time
where he could have earned huge sums of money.''
</P>
<P>
   But an attorney for Lewis's chief cardiologist, Dr. Gilbert H.
Mudge Jr., called Tellem's estimates wildly inflated, noting that
Lewis's off-the-court earnings were negligible before his death,
and arguing that his medical troubles would have dramatically
reduced his value as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team isn't going to be as willing to pay large dollars to
someone who might be at medical risk,'' Dailey said in
cross-examining Tellem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a history of illness or injury, that will be a
factor in what you're able to negotiate for, isn't that right?''
Dailey asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there's no dispute,'' said Tellem.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis's projected financial worth will be critical information
if jurors find Mudge liable for malpractice and award damages to
his widow, Donna Harris-Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven weeks after Lewis was discharged from Brigham and Women's
Hospital, where he was diagnosed by Mudge with a benign fainting
disorder rather than a potentially lethal heart condition, he
collapsed and died while shooting baskets at Brandeis University.
He was 27.
</P>
<P>
   Called as an expert witness by lawyers for Harris-Lewis, Tellem
_ whose client roster includes Red Sox star Nomar Garciaparra,
Baltimore Orioles slugger Albert Belle, and Los Angeles Lakers
guard Kobie Bryant _ described Lewis as ``one of the best players
in the NBA,'' and said the former Celtics captain was ``entering
the prime of his career'' at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Given Lewis's athletic talent, good looks, charisma, and
philanthropy, ``If handled right, there's no doubt in my mind he
would have reaped tremendous benefits . . . over the course of his
life,'' Tellem said.
</P>
<P>
   Tellem said his ``conservative'' estimate of Lewis's projected
earnings as an NBA player included about $100 million in salary
through 2005, when Lewis would have been nearly 40.
</P>
<P>
   Tellem also figured in $13.2 million in endorsement and
marketing revenues, such as product pitching, book deals, speaking
fees, and memorabilia sales, and $3.5 million in broadcasting jobs
after his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis's health forced him to retire early, Tellem estimated
he could still make $25.6 million as an NBA coach if he held that
job at least until 2003, plus $12 million in broadcasting, and $3.5
million in endorsements and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   But Dailey was skeptical of Tellem's calculations, noting that
the salaries and endorsement fees paid to several other well-known
NBA players and coaches are well below what Tellem estimates Lewis
would have earned.
</P>
<P>
   Tellem retorted that other players' earnings or average NBA
salaries is ``of no relevance to what Reggie Lewis would make as a
player today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie Lewis was not an average player. That's an insult,''
Tellem said. ``He was an extraordinary player, and extraordinary
players are not compared to average players.''
</P>
<P>
   Dailey also questioned whether Lewis would have continued
playing basketball until age 40, noting that only about 32 percent
of NBA players are over 30, and that only about 8 percent are over
35.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that while Tellem estimated Lewis could earn in
excess of $13 million in marketing deals in his lifetime, the
player had earned less than $400,000 in endorsement fees in the
course of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey also observed that several sports memorabilia and
merchandise companies have gone out of business in recent years,
and that Reebok _ which had an endorsement deal with Lewis _ has
begun terminating contracts with athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some companies have had problems recently . . . but others
have stepped in to pick up the slack,'' Tellem responded. He also
said the ``explosion in the '90s of technology and television
revenues and fan interest'' had to be considered when estimating
Lewis's future earning potential.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith instructed jurors that Tellem's
estimates were based on the assumption that ``Mr. Lewis, if
properly treated, would have been able to continue his basketball
career at the same level. . . . In other words, he would not have
been disabled by his medical condition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
