<SLUG> BC-MASS-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO SUITS AIM AT ADVERTISING CURBS NEAR SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA MASSEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Several of the nation's largest tobacco companies
filed suit in federal court Friday in an attempt to block the state
attorney general's consumer protection regulations aimed at curbing
cigarette advertising near Massachusetts schools.
</P>
<P>
   William Porter, deputy chief of the consumer protection and
anti-trust division of the attorney general's office, said Friday
night that he received copies of complaints filed by two of the
companies, Philip Morris Inc. and Lorillard Inc., late Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints allege that the attorney general's regulations
issued in January violate first amendment rights by ``severely
limiting the company's ability to communicate with adult smokers
about its products.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philip Morris complaint also claims that federal laws such
as the Cigarette Labeling Act include provisions prohibiting state
regulations such as Reilly's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general plans to actively and vigorously defend
these cases.'' Porter said. ``We'll do everything we can to keep
these rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11 regulations, which were issued under the state's consumer
protection statute by former Attorney General Scott Harshbarger,
aim to curb sales and ban outward-facing tobacco billboards and
store ads at retail establishments within 1,000 feet of elementary
and middle schools, parks and playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Harshbarger said the new rules would ``end the
deceptive tactics used to market, sell and distribute tobacoo
products to our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Slated to take effect Aug. 1, the program has been praised by
anti-smoking forces as a potential national model for
tobacco-control.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Porter said the complaints come as no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was expected that the tobacco companies would challenge the
regulations,'' he said. ``It's not uncommon for them to challenge
anything that affects their business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Porter said he believes the allegationss will prove false.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general knows that his regulations are lawful,''
he said. ``They are not unconstitutional and they are not prempted
by federal law.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he had not seen copies Friday night, Porter said two
other tobacco companies, R.G. Reynolds and Brown and Williams, told
lawyers for Phillip Morris that they planned to file suit Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for R.G. Reynolds confirmed Friday night that the
company had filed a complaint, but declined to discuss details of
the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at Foley, Hoag and Elliot, the Boston firm representing
Brown and Williamson, were unavailable for comment Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are the four largest in the country and
manufacture such brands as Marlborough, Camel and Newport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
