<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deciding the Destiny Of a 23-Acre Universe &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that George Lucas has released yet another film about the
struggle for hegemony over the universe, he can turn his attention
to his own battle _ for control of a 23-acre patch of a San
Francisco park.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it is any old park. It is the Presidio, an urban
retreat twice the size of New York's Central Park, with miles of
hiking and biking trails, cliffs, beaches, a Redwood forest and a
hodgepodge of historic buildings.
</P>
<P>
   A panel appointed by President Clinton to turn the 223-year-old
former military garrison into a self-sufficient national park plans
to pick a developer on Thursday for the Letterman Hospital site _
with the choice now down to Lucas and San Francisco's
father-and-son developers, Walter and Douglas Shorenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas says he wants to build ``the world center for the digital
age,'' moving his Industrial Light and Magic special effects shop
and other businesses into the Presidio. The Shorensteins, with the
Interland Corp. of San Mateo, plan public attractions including an
American Indian Museum, with the Internet company Cnet Inc. as
their anchor tenant.
</P>
<P>
   Some nearby residents worry that ``Star Wars'' cult followers
will swarm to the park if Lucas, who released ``The Phantom
Menace'' last week, wins the contract. But Lucas has his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost 3,000 lunches a week when the Army left,'' said
Patricia Vaughey, a restaurant owner. ``We think there'd be more
money for us if Lucas comes.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sasha Cavender &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating Women's Success &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once the women numbered only eight. This week, 800 were at the
annual Financial Women's Association dinner at the Grand Hyatt
Hotel in Manhattan, honoring Abby Joseph Cohen, who as Goldman,
Sachs' chief United States market strategist is Wall Street's most
influential bull, and Charlene Barshefsky, the United States Trade
Representative.
</P>
<P>
   Founded 43 years ago by the eight _ the (italics)only(end
italics) eight women on Wall Street then, said Lenore C. Albom, a
vice president at Chase Securities and the group's president _ the
association began as an alternative to the Men's Investment Club,
which had denied them membership.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Men's Investment Club no longer exists, and the
women's association is selling fund-raising tables at $5,000 a
clip.
</P>
<P>
   Both honorees wore their trademark silk scarves and both
presented rosy views of the American economy. Ms. Cohen was chosen
as a symbol of women's hopes and frustrations: long denied a
partnership at Goldman, Sachs, she finally gained one last year.
</P>
<P>
   In an introduction, Elaine Kloss, an agent with the New York
Life Insurance Co., repeated a favorite quip of Ms. Cohen's: ``I
believe that every male chief executive should have a working
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen's perspective on attaining that partnership? ``It was
not the defining moment of my life,'' she said, ``but it was very
pleasant.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Wayne &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Tele-Miscommunications Deal &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jack Grubman, the telecommunications research
analyst-cum-investment banker at Salomon Smith Barney, brooks no
challenges to his status as one of the most influential analysts on
the Street. For starters, Grubman, also one of the best paid, has
the ear of Bernard J. Ebbers, MCI Worldcom's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, in voice-mail messages to clients, he made
it clear that he regarded the circumstances surrounding the
collapse of merger talks between Nextel Communications and MCI
Worldcom as an affront.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the other side kept their trap shut, this would have been a
normal process,'' Grubman said, referring to news accounts about
the negotiations. ``We don't do that, and our clients don't do
that. Unfortunately, that's not true for other people on the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, in Grubman's view, was the fact that Walter Piecyk,
a former Nextel employee who is now an analyst at Paine Webber,
told his own clients that the Nextel-MCI Worldcom talks might be
revived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is dead,'' Grubman said, challenging Piecyk's intelligence
in insulting terms before saying that he was in some of the talks
but Piecyk wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Grubman said he merely wanted to correct some
investors' impression that Piecyk's career at Nextel had given him
some inside information about the company's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Piecyk basked in the attention. ``We continue to stand by our
call,'' he said. ``I'm flattered by the concept that I could have
that large an impact on Worldcom, a stock I don't even cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Seth Schiesel &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
