<SLUG> BC-SIMMONS-100TH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMMONS COLLEGE OBSERVES ITS 100TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In the 1800s, John Simmons became one of the country's
richest men from the suits sewn by his women employees in Quincy
Market.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Simmons, the inventor of ready-made clothing, left
his fortune to create ``Simmons' Female College.''
</P>
<P>
   While other women's colleges modeled themselves on the
classical, liberal arts education provided to men at Harvard and
Yale, Simmons wanted his college to be the MIT for women. At a time
when most women didn't work, he wanted them to leave college with a
career, not just a diploma, suitors and good-lady etiquette. He
wanted them to be able to earn their own living.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred years later, the mission hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This educational institution is absolutely grounded on the
current reality of work,'' said senior vice president Lisa
Chapnick.
</P>
<P>
   The first four-year women's college to combine liberal arts with
career preparation celebrates the 100th anniversary of its charter
signing on Monday. Next Friday, Governor Paul Celluci will declare
``Simmons College Day.'' His wife, Janet, graduated from Simmons'
library school in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in the Fenway next to the Isabella Stewart Gardner
Museum, Simmons is described by its president Daniel Cheever Jr. as
a ``small university'' with its all-women undergraduate college and
four graduate schools.
</P>
<P>
   While many women's colleges are struggling to define their
mission and hold onto their enrollment, Simmons has kept its
reputation as a school where its graduates are prepared for the
working world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we do well in,'' Cheever said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the practical aspect of Simmons that appealed to junior
Ramsey Alwin, who is majoring in education and sociology with a
minor in political science.
</P>
<P>
   ``The academic knowledge and vocational training skills are good
complements,'' said Alwin, who plans to teach for a few years
before going on to law school.
</P>
<P>
   The competitive academics at Simmons ``has made me concentrate
on my education,'' said Marie Celestin, 23, who decided to transfer
from the University of Massachusetts-Boston last year after helping
plan a conference on women at Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simmons forces me to look at myself as a priority,'' said
Celestin, who is originally from Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons has distinguished itself with such career-oriented
programs as its highly ranked Graduate School of Library and
Information Science, one of the first of its kind. In 1904, the
Graduate School of Social Work became the first
academically-affiliated school of social work in the nation. The
Graduate School of Management is the only business school in the
world designed exclusively for women.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever, who has been president for the last four years, said
the college had been in a slump before his arrival. Enrollments at
some of the schools had dropped, faculty had been cut and the
operating budget had lost money for the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not large amounts, but they were running deficits. There was a
big backlog of projects. Capital improvement projects that needed
to be attended to. The nine residence halls all needed
renovation,'' Cheever said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, the school is thriving, with rising enrollment and
``modest financial surpluses.'' said Cheever. Simmons has about
1,200 undergraduate women and almost 2,200 graduate students. The
graduate schools are co-ed, with the exception of the business
school. Its endowment has almost tripled over the last decade to
$147 million today.
</P>
<P>
   The school has ambitious plans to expand. Last week, the
president presented to the board of trustees a strategic plan that
calls for eight new degrees and programs by 2003, including a new
bachelor's degree in social work. Also included is one of the
nation's first clinical doctorate programs in physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Simmons will add 13 accelerated bachelor's/master's
degree programs. ``A bachelor's degree used to be enough. Now in
many areas, a master's degree is required,'' Chapnick said.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Cheever says he will present a plan to renovate
three residence halls and student center.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the school's troubled years, ``the faculty and
programs were very solid.'' It was a college adviser, Margaret
Hennig, who inspired Ann Fudge, executive vice president of Krafts
Foods and president of the Maxwell House division, to pursue a
career in business. Fudge credits Simmons for her position as one
of the highest-ranking women in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably wasn't able to appreciate the value of Simmons
until I was in Harvard Business School,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
