<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIGEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG EAST LIKELY TO GET VIRGINIA TECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Big East is about to get bigger. The question is will it be
better? Most seem to think not.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is the inclusion of Virginia Tech as the 14th member
of the basketball conference, a topic that will be debated the next
few days at the annual spring/summer meetings in Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Although it won't be voted upon this week _ that must be done at
the presidential level _ there seems little question that Tech,
already a member in football but playing in the Atlantic 10 in
other sports, will be added as the 14th basketball member.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't make any formal decision,'' said Big East
commissioner Mike Tranghese. ``But we are clearly going in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But why? When asked what the urgency was of adding Tech to a
basketball league that most feel has too many teams already, no one
had a reasonable explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is courting them, so I don't know why the Big East is
doing this,'' said an official familiar with the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Adding Tech would cause some major reshuffling in a league that
has grown from 10 to 13 teams in the past five years and is still
having trouble adjusting to the addition of West Virginia, Rutgers,
and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we have to do is go to two seven-team
divisions, and make a lot of changes in scheduling,'' said
Tranghese, who has successfully fought for a reduction in the
number of league games from 18 to 16, which will start next season.
``And the other thing that is clear is that not everyone is going
to New York (for the conference tournament). There isn't a format
that makes any sense that can make a 14-team tournament bracket
work. Someone is staying home.''
</P>
<P>
   More than someone. Tranghese would like to leave at least four
teams home, creating a more workable 10-team bracket in which the
top six have opening-round byes.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Big East gives first-round byes to the top three
teams and has a five-game schedule on the opening day of the
tournament, an arrangement that requires the first game to be
played at 11 in the morning, with a game going well past 11 at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving teams home will be a touchy issue. ``It's very
sensitive,'' conceded Boston College athletic director Gene
DeFilippo. ``A lot of our fund-raising in basketball is predicated
on that trip to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, DeFilippo feels a sense of loyalty to Virginia Tech,
which has been a solid member of the eight-team football league and
recently has represented the conference in Bowl Championship Series
games in the Sugar and Orange Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Located in Blacksburg, Va., Tech is not near a major media
market. No other leagues are chasing the school and even if they
were, Big East football could survive the loss of Tech much easier
than it could handle being without Syracuse or Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to deal with it sooner rather than
later,'' said Tranghese, who must reconfigure basketball
regular-season schedules to preserve traditional rivalries in a
two-division league. ``If we don't do it now, the presidents will
do it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   That will happen sometime before the end of the summer and
beginning with the 2000-2001 basketball season, Virginia Tech will
likely be a full member of the Big East Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that will be a long-term benefit for a league remains to
be seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
