<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOTTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SURPRISES IN NBA LOTTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's NBA lottery is better known for what it hasn't than
what it has.
</P>
<P>
   There is no franchise or impact player. There is not even a
center by conventional standards. There is no Sunday television
audience. There are also three teams who have already traded their
picks and a fourth _ the Celtics _ who will likely surrender theirs
once the Ping-Pong balls tumble and the logo cards are unveiled.
</P>
<P>
   Everything will be known by Saturday _ 6:30 p.m. is when things
begin _ and shortly thereafter, barring a mathematical miracle, the
Celtics will say bye-bye to their pick and send it to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Boston isn't hoping to get into the top three
spots, the only ones selected by lottery, and thus save their pick.
(They keep it if it's 1-3.) The Celtics have a 3.7 percent chance
of landing the top pick, a 4.28 percent chance of getting the
second, and a gaudy 5.06 percent chance of picking third.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Chris Wallace and basketball operations
assistant Jeff Noyes will represent the Celtics in lovely Secaucus,
N.J. Wallace will get the face time on NBC while Noyes, accompanied
by a few good luck charms, including a 3-foot carved statue of a
leprechaun, will be in the back room where the numbered balls fall
and determine the fate of franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rick Pitino has predictably downplayed the whole thing
ever since he reluctantly traded Boston's pick to the Cavaliers as
part of the deal to acquire Vitaly Potapenko. He hasn't had much
luck at the lottery since taking over; his first lottery was when
San Antonio got Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland and Toronto could end up with two lottery picks
apiece. The Raptors have their own as well as that of Denver, part
of the Chauncey Billups trade. Phoenix has Dallas's pick from the
Steve Nash deal. Minnesota also will be a participant, owning the
Nets' choice as a result of the Stephon Marbury trade.
</P>
<P>
   After the first three spots are chosen, the teams then line up
in reverse order for drafting position. The Grizzlies finished with
the worst record in the league (8-42) and have the best
mathematical chance of getting the first pick _ 25 percent. The
Clippers (20 percent) and Bulls (15.7) have the next best chance.
Chicago is in the lottery for the first time on its own. It
previously took part with a New Jersey pick in 1989 and selected
Stacey King.
</P>
<P>
   The team with the best mathematical chance, however, rarely
comes up with the first pick. Denver was by far the worst team last
year _ winning 11 games _ and was shut out of the top two spots.
The Clippers, who had the third-worst record, got the first pick,
and Vancouver, tied for the fourth-worst record, got the second
choice. The last team to get the No. 1 pick and have the worst
record was the 1990 Nets, who took Derrick Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus No. 1 this time around is Lamar Odom, the
multitalented 6-foot-9-inch forward from Rhode Island. Others who
figure to be considered near the top are Duke's Elton Brand and
Maryland's Steve Francis. The Clippers might go local with UCLA's
Baron Davis if they pick near the top.
</P>
<P>
   Those four all are underclassmen coming out early, an unending
trend. The top seniors are Wally Szczerbiak, Andre Miller, and
Jason Terry. High schooler Jonathan Bender, a 6-11 center from
Picayune, Miss., is also considered a lottery pick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-ETHNIC-BOS &LR;      05-21 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-ETHNIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS IN ATLANTA SEE TURNABOUT IN LATEST SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When a teenage gunman stormed his high school earlier
this week, transforming a quiet community into a symbol of
inexplicable violence, another nearby community had a few questions
to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Why did rich white suburbanites think they were so special? That
was what one black radio listener wanted to know in neighboring
downtown Atlanta, just 20 miles away, where weapons once pervaded
the public schools, and where inner-city minorities have long been
considered the most troubled youths around. Did suburban residents
like being cast as monsters? Didn't whites know that the black
community had faced up to the problem years ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a turn-the-tables kind of thing,'' said Royal
Marshall, a talk-show host at WCNN radio in Atlanta, where several
black listeners aired their views in the hours after the shooting.
``I don't want to quote Malcolm X all the time, but it is the
chickens coming home to roost. We should have been looking for
solutions all along.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the recent school shootings have been committed by
reasonably affluent young white males, raising questions across all
communities about why privileged children go astray. All have
defied the basic socioeconomic principle: poverty breeds violence.
</P>
<P>
   But never have the differing perceptions of black urban and
white suburban school violence been as striking as it was on
Thursday in Conyers, Ga., just minutes from the former violent
crime capital of the United States. The proximity of the two
communities has made residents of both wonder: Will suburbanites
ever let go of the perceptions that their neighborhoods are
completely safe and that the cities are hotbeds of crime?
</P>
<P>
   School crime has dropped within Atlanta in recent years,
mirroring trends in city schools nationwide. According to school
officials in Fulton County, where the 59,000-student population is
90 percent black, assaults declined 12 percent from 1988 to 1999;
robberies during that period dropped a full 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   School officials say improvements result largely from years of
practice in handling crime, as well as tough security measures. All
high schools and middle schools in Atlanta are equipped with metal
detectors; according to news accounts last year, students are even
offered a reward for turning in peers carrying weapons or illegal
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our numbers are coming down,'' said Lisa Smith, spokeswoman
for the Fulton County school system, whose domain includes Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the image of urban blight stubbornly persists. No
politicians were outraged by the 20 handguns found in city schools
last year. No headlines blared ``IT HAPPENED HERE'' _ as one did
Friday on the front page of the Atlanta Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if when crime occurs among black students in Atlanta
schools, Smith said, ``that's what everybody expects.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment may, in part, stem from Atlanta's
tale-of-two-cities sort of atmosphere, as a modern urban metropolis
surrounded by the rural traditions of the deep South. It may also
account for Atlanta's famously crowded suburbs, both black and
white, swelled from decades of flight from urban crime.
</P>
<P>
   So many residents live in the suburbs that Atlanta has
difficulty maintaining population; the highways leading in and out
of the city are so constantly jammed with commuters that Atlanta is
widely considered the worst traffic zone in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Thursday's shooting, several residents of Conyers,
whose racial composition is relatively mixed, said there was good
reason for the psychological barrier between Atlanta and its
environs.
</P>
<P>
   A white student who witnessed the shooting, William Britt, said
that if there was a turning of the tables, he believes that it was
because so many urban blacks had started to move into the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're experiencing what they've been experiencing all
along because they're coming down here,'' Britt, 18, a junior,
said. ``It's a chain of events.''
</P>
<P>
   And Brian Barnhardt, who was shot in the right buttock during
the rampage, said no comparison could be drawn between his hometown
and the neighboring metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not even close to Atlanta like that,'' Barnhart, 16,
said Friday after returning home from the hospital. ``We're a small
town. We're a small county...I never thought it would happen
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that persistent interpretation of the suburbs _ even
though all of the high-profile school shootings in the last two
years have occurred outside cities _ will remain rooted in the
national psyche is impossible to tell, according to several
sociologists and health workers in Atlanta. Most were pessimistic,
partly because because the statistical picture remains: more
violent crime occurs in the city than in the suburbs. More urban
students are poor. And although there have not yet been any mass
shooting sprees, more urban students are caught with guns than
their suburban counterparts each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not as many die at once, but people are getting shot
right here (in Atlanta), right now,'' said Downa Fuqua-Whitley, a
senior research associate at the Emory University School of Public
Health.
</P>
<P>
   But reflecting the complexity of the problem, she noted,
``Certainly in the Atlanta area, we've seen a decrease in some of
our rates, but people's perceptions have not gone along with that.
There's a `them' and an `us,' urban and suburban, and I don't know
if they could even breach that gap because they so strongly
dissociate themselves from other people.''
</P>
<P>
   After last month's school shooting in Littleton, Colo., in which
15 people died, Fuqua-Whitley conducted one of her regular focus
groups with city school children to discuss violence. None of the
children was surprised by, or wanted to dwell on, the Columbine
High School attack, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to talk about what was going on here in Atlanta,''
she said. ``But one or two in the group did express that when the
kids are white and rich and suburban, it gets a lot more
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, such public scrutiny has led not to widespread fear of
suburban life. Nor will it necessarily lead to a change in
perception of urban crime, according to Emory Professor Jennifer
Obidah, who conducts studies on urban youth and violence.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, Obidah said, is that suburban shootings are
portrayed as aberrations, not as part of a ``culture of violence,''
as black crimes were during the early 1990s when urban violence
peaked. Rather than comparing the circumstances of urban and
suburban crime _ holding them up to one another, for example, to
see whether all violent students feel alienated at home _ the
gunmen in each case have been scrutinized for what makes them
different from the rest of the suburbs, to allow everyone else to
feel safe, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're touching on issues of class and race,'' Obidah said.
``The good parents are the ones that go to work and provide for
their children. If you say these children are neglected, you're
undermining the whole conversation about who these parents believe
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the urban-suburban conversation was largely confined to
WCNN on Thursday, where no one was more eager to foster the debate
than the host. Marshall began the two-hour show with his own view:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad what happened at Columbine High School, the magnitude
of what happened,'' he said. ``It's sad what happened in Rockdale
County. It's terrible. But unfortunately...we saw this stuff
happening in the black community first. And now that it's
spreading, now we want gun control. Now we want to start praying.
Well, hell, we should have been praying 15 years ago when black
people died.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
