<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-MAIN22-COX     05-21 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-MAIN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Compassionate' move makes final exams optional
 &HT;    By R. Robin McDonald and Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ Responding to a panicked and anguished community,
Rockdale County has effectively ended school for many students at
Heritage High School by making final exams optional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how difficult this has been. We want to be
compassionate,'' said school Superintendent Don Peccia.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage's principal will make the offer to students during
Monday announcements, when they return for classes for the first
time since six students were shot there Thursday. Students happy
with their grades so far will be excused from the finals planned
next week.
</P>
<P>
   The wild confusion of gunfire, bloodshed and frightened students
diving for cover has ended, but for many the terror continues. Some
700 people attended a meeting Friday morning at Heritage Hills
Baptist Church near the high school. People baffled and horrified
by the attack hugged and comforted each other as counselors and
school officials tried to answer questions. One wounded student,
Ryan Rosa, came on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Clark, a 16-year-old sophomore, said the morning bloodshed
at school revisited her in her sleep. ``I actually had a dream that
I got shot,'' she said. ``We were walking around school and a guy
came in shooting everybody, and we all died.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in school as little as possible,'' said junior
Randy Norman. He has asked his girlfriend, who attends a separate
high school in the county, to beep him after every class.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage High will be open today from 8 a.m. to noon so students
can pick up belongings and talk to counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say they have finished investigating the school
scene, which was littered with a trail of hastily discarded book
bags when panic turned to pandemonium Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the shooting suspect, a Heritage High School
sophomore, had sawed most of the stock off a .22-caliber rifle and
strapped it inside his pants leg. A .357 magnum was stuffed in his
bookbag.
</P>
<P>
   He fired 14 shots, 11 from the rifle and three from the handgun,
as he shot six students in the school lobby near the cafeteria,
said Rockdale County Sheriff Jeff Wigington.
</P>
<P>
   As the students fled through doorways and scattered along halls,
teacher Carol Ingle hustled some into a closet. She calmed them by
quoting from the Book of Psalms.
</P>
<P>
   No one was critically injured, and all but two victims had been
released from hospitals Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the youth had broken into a locked gun cabinet in his
basement to get the guns. Authorities have traced the two weapons
from their point of purchase, though they declined to offer
details.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the troubled teen say he was distraught over a failed
romance. His targets seemed random, said witnesses, and the six
victims were all struck in the waist or below, leading some to
speculate that he was not aiming to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in this community, which has seen great growth but
retains much of its small town charm, said the fact that no one
died took some edge off the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, now they have a hero, Assistant Principal Cecil
Brinkley, who disarmed the youth.
</P>
<P>
   After the teen stopped shooting, he backed out of the building,
fell to his knees and placed the handgun in his mouth. For several
minutes, teachers and counselors tried to talk him out of killing
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ten feet from the suspect, Brinkley asked the 15-year-old to
hand over the weapon. Instead, the youth directed the gun at him.
Brinkley walked forward and repeated his request.
</P>
<P>
   The student handed over the gun, and they hugged. With a shaky
voice, the young man said, ``I'm scared.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Brinkley shared his thoughts during those tense
moments. ``It's not heroic,'' he said. ``At that moment I just
needed to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The youth has been charged with aggravated assault. Rockdale
District Attorney Richard Read said he wants to try him as an
adult. That could mean the difference between life in prison or
mere probation. A county judge in juvenile court will make the
decision. The suspect faces a detention hearing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   People offered mixed opinions about the former Boy Scout. Some
described him as a quiet, churchgoing youth, while others said he
was obsessed with guns and seemed suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   For the victims of the attack, time will heal their bullet
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Laster, 15, was recovering Friday from the gunshot
wound she suffered in the Thursday shooting. Her room at Hughes
Spalding Children's Hospital was flooded with cards, flowers and
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Barnhardt's wound is in his right buttock. He is a pitcher
on the Heritage High baseball team, and there's some concern since
he uses his right leg to push off when he throws. More than
anything, he's mad. When he saw a picture of the shooting suspect,
he said he thought, ``That guy? I could beat up that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   His thoughts are not on forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't forgive him. He shouldn't have done something like
this,'' said Barnhardt as he was being released from Rockdale
Hospital on Friday, his parents by his side.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year-old Cania Cullins, who plays the clarinet in the
school's marching band and is known for her beautiful hair and
perfect nails, was shot in the knee. Despite her injuries, Cania
has compassion for her classmate, said her pastor, Bishop Jim
Swilley of the Church in the Now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish that he could know I forgive him, and I'd love for him
to come to church,'' she told Swilley.
</P>
<P>
   But the discussion goes beyond Rockdale County. The shootings
have placed the middle-class county in the spotlight of a national
dialogue on school safety and the behavior of young people. The
attack was the sixth mass shooting at an American high school or
middle school since October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   If the shootings at Columbine High School in Colorado a month
ago ignited such discussions, then the Heritage High School
incident has inflamed them. The shootings occurred hours before the
Senate debated legislation that would toughen background checks for
gun buyers. The measure passed after Vice President Gore cast the
tiebreaking vote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
