<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS FOCUSING ON SCHOOL KILLERS' FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ One month after the Columbine High School massacre, 80
law enforcement investigators are planning to labor through the
summer trying to determine if any friends of the two school gunmen
aided them or knew about the attack beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   With seniors preparing to graduate Saturday, such basic
questions remain unanswered as detectives studied e-mail, 15
personal computer hard drives, video rental records, and
conflicting stories from the 1,400 interviews conducted so far.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic technicians are trying to match hundreds of bullets and
casings to the guns used by law enforcement officials and by the
two high school seniors, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. Unmatched
bullets could indicate that a third gunman participated in the
shooting, which left 15 people dead, including Harris and Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that the two teen-agers could have carried in the
51 bombs that were found in and around the Littleton school, said
Larry Bettendorf, a spokesman for the Bureau of Alcohol, Firearms
and Tobacco. He said that most of the bombs were either small
carbon dioxide cartridges filled with black powder or medium-size
bombs filled with homemade napalm. The largest bomb, made from two
propane tanks, was found in a duffel bag in the school cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   After several house searches and lie detector tests, one
acquaintance of the gunmen has been arrested. Mark Manes, 22, a
computer technician, was charged with providing a handgun to a
minor.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Anderson, Klebold's 18-year-old prom date, bought two
shotguns and a semiautomatic rifle for the two boys last fall from
unlicensed dealers at a gun show near Denver, Bettendorf said. Had
she bought the guns from a federally licensed dealer, she might
have faced federal charges of acting as a ``straw purchaser'' for
minors, but sales by unlicensed dealers are not covered by the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking very carefully to see if any federal laws were
violated. We are looking at the chain of the sale of the weapons,''
said Tom Strickland, the U.S. attorney based in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge amount of evidence that is being
investigated,'' Strickland said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson County Sheriff's Office plans to return control of
the high school to the school district June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Near the school, the last memorials honoring the victims have
been removed from Clement Park. Last week, a tractor trailer truck
carried the offerings eight miles north to a federal warehouse,
where they fill 40 rooms, or 21,000 square feet. This summer, a
committee is to evaluate proposals for a permanent memorial in
Clement Park. The memorial could include some of the offerings of
photographs, flowers, poetry and placards.
</P>
<P>
   The victims are being remembered by more than flowers. Donations
totaling more than $3 million have been received by 15 charitable
funds. The Healing Fund, administered by the local United Way, has
already distributed almost $400,000, including $5,000 to each of
the 38 families.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the neediest cases is Lance Kirklin, 16, who was shot
five times. Kirklin, who does not have medical insurance, faces $1
million in medical bills and at least five more facial surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Two other boys, Richard Castaldo, 17, and Sean Graves, 15, are
suffering from lower body paralysis that doctors hope will be
temporary. Patrick Ireland, 17, who crawled out of a window into
the waiting arms of law enforcement officials, also remains
hospitalized. So does Mark Taylor, 16, who is in serious but stable
condition. The one girl still in the hospital, Anne Marie
Hochhalter, 17, is in fair condition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the month since the shootings, some parents have channeled
their grief into action.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Castaldo, father of Richard, has started to campaign to
shield minors from violence and pornography on the Internet. Tom
Mauser, whose son Gary, 15, was killed, has helped found Sane
Alternatives to the Firearms Epidemic (SAFE), a state lobby for gun
control. This political action committee is chaired by former
Colorado Govs. John Love, a Republican, and Richard Lamm, a
Democrat turned independent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
