</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBUFFING GOP MODERATES, HASTERT DEFERS VOTE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Mass., Conn., Calif., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his first confrontation with Republican
moderates, House Speaker Dennis Hastert has spurned their request
for an early vote on campaign finance legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's decision to schedule the debate for mid-September,
which was relayed to the Republicans late Thursday, has now left
them with a stark choice: acquiesce or break with their party and
sign a Democratic petition intended to force the bill to the House
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays of Connecticut, the chief Republican
sponsor of a bipartisan bill to ban the unregulated and unlimited
donations to political parties that are known as soft money,
indicated he would sign the petition. ``For me I just think that
it's absolutely imperative that the legislation come before the
August break,'' Shays said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill that Shays sponsors with Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass.,
passed the House by a decisive vote of 252-179 last year but died
in a Senate filibuster. Its proponents say that to have any success
this year they need a House vote before the August recess, and
maybe even before Memorial Day, to allow pressure to build on the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Friday how many of the 30 other Republicans who
supported Shays' bill would follow his lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have gathered 196 signatures on the petition, 195
Democrats of the House's 211 Democrats and one independent. They
need a majority of the House, or 218 signers, to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   But discharge petitions are usually considered an extreme act of
dissent because they take the majority's control over the
legislative calendar and hand it to the opposition party. Last
year, 12 Republicans broke with their party and signed a similar
petition only after then-Speaker Newt Gingrich blocked the bill
from the floor. Once those 12 signed, Republican leaders scheduled
the debate but kept it going for weeks in odd hours in a new effort
to slow or kill the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Shays said he viewed the decision on whether to sign the
petition as a ``conscience vote for every member because it does
put you in the hot seat with your colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Brian Bilbray of California, one of the 12 Republicans,
said he was organizing a meeting of the Republicans for Tuesday to
seek a consensus on how to proceed, particularly now that gun
control has unexpectedly moved to center stage in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten the speaker committed to September, not July,''
he said. ``Then we get blind-sided by the gun issue. Do we push
forward even though we're going to be eclipsed by the gun issue?''
he asked. ``What's the best timing? Timing is everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., who signed the discharge petition
last year, has indicated that he will not do so again out of
deference to the new speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The choice these Republicans make has potential ramifications
beyond this one issue. In their drive to pursue their own agenda,
the Democrats have been pushing hard for moderate Republicans to
break ranks with their party. Minority Leader Dick Gephardt renewed
that call Thursday, saying ``if they are really for campaign
reform, now is the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, fearful they could lose their majority in 2000,
have put a countervailing premium on party unity this year. And
many Republicans have made clear that they would view it as an act
of disloyalty if some of their colleagues bolted over the campaign
legislation, which is opposed by the majority of their party.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the speaker, 100 Republicans led by Rep. John
Doolittle of California urged him not to heed the supporters of the
Shays-Meehan legislation. They wrote that ``we urge you to
disregard the threat of discharge petitions and other tactics
designed to distract Republicans _ and you in particular _ from
accomplishing our shared goals.''
</P>
<P>
   John Feehery, a spokesman for Hastert, said the speaker was
trying to balance between these two groups of Republicans by
allowing a debate on the campaign finance issue but not until
mid-September, after the annual spending bills are considered.
``The vast majority of our members don't want this on the floor,''
Feehery said. ``We're trying to balance both of these concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   But advocacy groups fighting to overhaul campaign finance
legislation said the speaker was stalling to kill the bill. ``This
is the precise same manipulative game plan they used in the last
Congress to try to maintain the corrupt status quo,'' said Fred
Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, a group devoted to
overhauling the campaign finance laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the ferment on the issue, another set of
Republicans led by Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas reintroduced an
alternative campaign finance measure this week that would ban the
national political parties, but not the state parties, from
collecting soft money. It would also bar federal candidates from
holding soft money fund-raisers and it would bar soft money raised
in one state from being used in another.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson argued that it was time to try a different approach
to the issue, because the Shays-Meehan bill had died repeatedly in
the Senate. ``There's an old Southern saying,'' he said. ``You
don't learn much from the second kick of the mule.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
