<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY'S STAR ON THE RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ A year ago, he was a darkhorse who drove a black
car.
</P>
<P>
   Times have certainly changed _ for the better _ for Greg Ray,
the dashing 32-year-old Texan from Plano who last year stunned
everyone at Indianapolis Motor Speedway by qualifying second
fastest during Indy 500 time trials in his underfunded car.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at him now.
</P>
<P>
   In one short year, Ray has gone from pauper to prince.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, a heavy favorite to win the pole for the 83d
Indianapolis 500 in Saturday's time trials. Ray, who led for 18
laps last year and finished 18th when he was forced out because of
a gearbox problem on Lap 167, parlayed that run into a ride with
John Menard's well-heeled outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk up and down the pits and ask any driver what team
he'd like to be with and this is the team, I'll guarantee you,''
said Ray. ``It's an honor to drive for this team so, yeah, what a
difference a year makes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the fabled Brickyard swung open its gates a week ago,
Ray has been consistently fast in his Team Menard-prepared
Oldsmobile Aurora-powered Dallara. Thursday, Ray toured the
2.5-mile oval at 227.192 miles per hour, marking the fastest
unofficial lap of the week, bettering Tony Stewart's 226.683
Wednesday. Then Friday, Ray gave another glimpse of his
pole-winning potential when he went 227.175 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels nice to be this consistently quick with this group
(of drivers),'' said Ray, who turned the fastest unofficial lap
during an open test last month at the Speedway with a 227.072. ``We
regard our competitors very highly. We're not taking anything for
granted by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who will be gunning for Ray are Stewart, who had to
win a court decision against former boss Menard in order to drive a
Home Depot-sponsored car he co-owns with Larry Curry; CART driver
Robby Gordon; A.J. Foyt drivers Billy Boat, who Monday crashed the
car with which he won last year's pole, and Kenny Brack, the
defending Indy Racing League champion; and the retiring Arie
Luyendyk, a two-time Indy 500 winner who set an official one-lap
track record of 237.498 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although this year is my last year as an active driver, I will
still be working with the Treadway Racing team and maybe doing some
broadcasting,'' said Luyendyk. ``I do not feel dramatic toward
leaving because I'll still be here. I never thought I would hold
the speed records I have. In order to be successful you need the
right crew and engineers that you can work with. And you need the
right chemistry together.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything will have to go perfectly for Stewart, who will need
to qualify before 1:30 p.m. in order to ensure he makes the window
of opportunity to qualify for the NASCAR Winston Cup race in
Charlotte, N.C., Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't feel any pressure,'' said Stewart, who put his
team behind the 8-ball Thursday when he crashed his primary car
into the wall between Turns 3 and 4. ``I only have one lap to
qualify in other (NASCAR) races I do. You won't have to hold your
breath for these four laps. I can screw one up and still make up
for it in the three I have left.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ray, ``Every corner is different on every lap. Holding your
breath for 40 seconds is one thing. Holding your breath for 3 1/2
minutes is another. I don't know who's going to win the pole, but
whoever it is they're going to have to work for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
