<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ASSISTED-LIVING-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW AN ANALYST CHILLED A GROWTH SECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, May 23)  
(DW) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time Sheryl R. Skolnick sneezes, some investors may
want to run for cover. On Feb. 4, Ms. Skolnick, a BancBoston
Robertson Stephens managing director, dropped her ratings on four
stocks in the assisted-living care sector, citing the possible
effects of an impending General Accounting Office report on the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Such a wide-ranging move, virtually unheard of on Wall Street,
was enough to send the four stocks to the cellar. Shares of
CareMatrix, one of the largest companies in the group, dropped 22.4
percent that day, to $18.625. Alternative Living Services drooped
15.7 percent, to $21.9375, while Sunrise Assisted Living fell 8
percent, to $38.25. Balanced Care slid 7.4 percent to $6.25, a
price that must now look like a fortune. It closed at $2.125 on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts now believe that the selloff was too severe, leaving
the sector, which provides housing and services to elderly people
who need only minimal assistance, a prime buying opportunity. Even
the stingiest value investor might do a double take at the prices.
CareMatrix and Alternative Living Services are trading at a mere
13.8 and 11.9 times 1998 earnings, compared with a price-earnings
ratio of 33.5 for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Skolnick re-established ratings on the battered
group two weeks later, after she learned more about the report's
likely contents, the stocks have not fully recovered. As it turned
out, Ms. Skolnick had more influence on the sector than the
government. When the report was issued late last month, it
primarily suggested making more information available to consumers
and did not propose, as some had feared, Federal regulation of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The report had almost no effect on the group's stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, an industry trade group, the Assisted Living
Federation of America, was livid when Ms. Skolnick removed her
ratings, calling the move ``irresponsible'' and ``an extreme
overreaction and possible misrepresentation'' of the government's
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say there are important lessons here _ that thinly
traded stocks are subject to abrupt and severe gyrations, and that
those moves can be prompted by obscure forces like the negative
vote of only one analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors may believe the bull market has been so robust
that it has eliminated some of the risks inherent in many stocks.
Or they may believe that the relatively attractive valuations of
some small-cap stocks insulate them from major downdrafts. The
debacle in the assisted-living sector shows otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I have done anything differently?'' Ms. Skolnick asks
herself months after making her research calls. ``No. I would have
still warned investors that this event was out there,'' she said,
referring to the government report. ``But clearly the land of
illiquid stocks is not for the faint of heart, never has been.''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, the assisted-living stocks appear especially
vulnerable to volatility. Even the larger companies in the group
have meager floats _ the number of shares available for trading to
the public _ so a very small number of investors can move the
price. Alternative Living Services and CareMatrix have floats of
only 18 million and 9.8 million shares, respectively. Johnson &AMP;
Johnson's float, by comparison, is 1.3 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Further aggravating matters, many investors may not have a sound
grasp of what assisted living is, despite the fact that big hotel
companies like Hyatt and Host Marriott have become major players in
the business. One myth has it that assisted-living facilities are
nursing homes with a fancier name, with most of the industry's
revenues coming from Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Assisted-living facilities care for elderly residents too frail
to live alone but too healthy for nursing homes. Almost 88 percent
of industry revenue comes from private payers, according to the
Assisted Living Federation.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be no shortage of potential residents. Analysts
predict that the industry will grow from $14 billion this year to
$20 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   CareMatrix and Alternative Living Services are expected to notch
earnings gains next year of 25 percent or more. Care-Matrix, for
example, more than doubled its capacity last year and expects to
have an additional 3,500 residents in its facilities before
year-end.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long term, the assisted-living stocks are definitely
undervalued,'' said Ms. Skolnick, who has ``buy'' ratings on
CareMatrix and Sunrise. ``Many of them are excellent companies. But
there are times when an excellent company is not an excellent
stock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
