<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-RAPIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIVED METROSTARS OFFENSE IS LOSING HURTADO, AT LEAST FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After their best production of the season last Saturday in a 3-2
victory over Miami, the MetroStars will clash with the Colorado
Rapids in Denver on Saturday night with renewed spirit, even though
they will play without Eduardo Hurtado, one of the league's most
efficient goal scorers.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado aggravated a hamstring injury against Miami and will
miss at least Saturday night's game against Colorado (5-2). His
position will be filled by Nansha Kalonji, the team's discovery
player, who will be making his first start after four appearances
as a substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to play,'' Kalonji said after a two-hour practice in
the rain Wednesday at Kean University in Union, N.J. ``I've been
feeling good in practice, and every practice is like a game. The
way you practice is the way you play.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bora Milutinovic, who took the team to Denver for a
practice Friday, had no hesitation about his choice of a
replacement for Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be Sasha,'' Milutinovic said, referring to Kalonji.
``I think he'll do OK He's learning every day.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the attack for the MetroStars (4-4) will be Roy
Myers of Costa Rica, with Mark Chung playing on the left side of
the attack. Chung played that position against Miami last Saturday,
and he scored the first goal and assisted on the other two, earning
player of the week honors in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurtado and Myers are two different players,'' said Kalonji,
who played with Myers in three of his four appearances as a
substitute and scored a goal against D.C. United. ``I know how to
work with Myers, but Hurtado can hold two or three players. He
attracts attention and takes the pressure off me.''
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars seem to be improving with every game. Milutinovic
works with them on the field sometimes for more than two hours at a
time and spends additional hours showing his players films of
themselves and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bora gets his message across,'' said Mike Sorber, the
MetroStars' defensive midfielder, who started all four games for
the United States when Milutinovic was the coach of the 1994 World
Cup team. ``The thing is that we always play the same way. We try
to keep possession and attack at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Corrales, who played for the U.S. Under-23 team in its
1-1 draw with Canada on Wednesday and missed three days of practice
with the MetroStars, will play at his left fullback position
against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Arley Palacios, Mark Semioli and Mike Petke will be the other
defenders, and Mike Ammann will be in goal. Billy Walsh, Miles
Joseph and Sorber will be the midfielders.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars and Colorado have met eight times since the start
of the league four years ago, and each team has won four times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-PRAY22-COX     05-21 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PRAY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School violence revives controversy over prayer
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ There haven't been any shootings in this
sprawling city's schools, but students and parents fear the
violence that erupted in Colorado _ and now Georgia _ may touch
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before the Rockdale County, Ga., shooting, hundreds of
people packed an emotional school board meeting here, most of them
pleading with officials to allow students to pray at their high
school graduations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the difference that a thing as small as a prayer can
make,'' Lisa Dugger, a 15-year-old high school sophomore, told the
Duval County School Board. ``If we remove God entirely from our
lives and our schools, I believe what happened at Columbine could
happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an argument many are making as the nation struggles to
understand the rash of school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Many trace the upswing in violence to society's moral decay, and
experts predict the steady trickle of school prayer cases appearing
in the courts over the past few years will grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the school shootings, it's become much more of an
issue,'' said John Ferguson, a researcher at Vanderbilt
University's First Amendment Center, which tracks the issue and has
helped mediate school prayer disputes around the country. ``A lot
of people believe these shootings happen because we've taken God
out of the schools. I believe that is an oversimplification, but
it's a growing perception.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jacksonville, the 6-year-old controversy shows no sign of
fading.
</P>
<P>
   This week, board members voted 4-3 to appeal last week's ruling
by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta that held the
district's policy of allowing student-led graduation ``messages''
was unconstitutional because it amounted to an official endorsement
of prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the policy argued the court's ruling was a
clear-cut repudiation and the board has no business spending
precious funds on such a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission as a board is education,'' said member Gwen
Gibson, who voted against the appeal. ``We have to set priorities.
I have to balance spending $200,000 on this against student needs.
That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, though, the principle is too important to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a national issue that has to be addressed,'' said
member Stan Jordan, who voted to appeal. ``It's a bigger issue than
Duval County. I think we may be of service to the nation if we go
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle over religion in the public schools goes back to a
1963 U.S. Supreme Court ruling that declared school-sanctioned
prayer an unconstitutional violation of laws that separate church
and state.
</P>
<P>
   Schools may teach religion and Bible history, the court ruled,
but they must do so objectively, as an academic subject.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and administrators must remain neutral and avoid
endorsing any particular religion, the court held.
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars believe many people _ including school officials
_ have overreacted to the ruling, believing wrongly that the court
aimed to eradicate all traces of religion from the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are misinformed,'' Ferguson said. ``Students
are allowed to pray at school on their own, but teachers can't lead
them in prayer. People believe no one is allowed to say anything
religious in school.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two decades, a growing number of cases have appeared
in the courts as districts across the country, often prodded by
religious activists, have tried to bring prayer and religious
observance more directly into school life.
</P>
<P>
   A number of districts have tried to come up with legally
acceptable forms of prayer by making the activities student-led, or
voluntary. In Jacksonville, students were given the right to vote
first on whether they wanted a graduation message, and then on
which student would give the message. The content of the messages
was left completely up to the chosen students, with no review by
school officials.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say such approaches are often nothing more than bald
attempts to circumvent the Supreme Court ruling and put officially
sanctioned prayer of the dominant local religion back in the
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with prayer,'' said Ken Hurley, a
Jacksonville resident whose son was one of the students who
challenged the Duval policy. ``It just can't represent only one
group. Here it is the Christians. There are no Buddhists or Muslims
(represented) here.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, religious activists argue that their rights are
being curtailed by the ban on prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to force religion on anybody,'' said Caroline
Weidner, who was to have given one of the ``messages'' at a
Jacksonville high school. ``I feel this is taking away my rights,
not only my freedom of religion, but also my freedom of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the intense emotions generated by the controversy, some
legal scholars believe the courts have been moving toward a
consensus on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus seems to be that if you pick the kids by
objective criteria and let them say what they want, it's OK if that
happens to be a prayer, if they don't ask for audience
participation,'' said Oliver Thomas, special counsel for the
National Council of Churches, who is also affiliated with
Vanderbilt's First Amendment Center. ``The key is the district has
to be neutral. They can't wink and nod and set it up so that the
kids know they're being allowed to pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas fears the recent ruling in the Jacksonville case may send
a chill through school districts that were struggling to find a way
for students to pray without offending their classmates or
violating the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when districts see this ruling, there could be a real
reaction, that some districts might censure graduation speeches,''
he said. ``I'm afraid this will confuse thousands of schools that
were trying to resolve the issue in good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has read the 11th Circuit ruling in the Duval County
case, and believes the court felt the Jacksonville district was
actively trying to encourage prayer instead of leaving it up to the
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that's true, but I think the court didn't believe
the district was neutral,'' he said. ``I think they were saying,
`We're not buying that the Duval Board didn't try to rig this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates on both sides of the issue predict the matter will
eventually reach the U.S. Supreme Court. Neither side seems likely
to concede what each believes to be bedrock principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is clearly against student-initiated prayer,'' said
Barry Lynn, executive director of Americans United for Separation
of Church and State, which argues for preserving the constitutional
ban on officially sanctioned prayer in schools. ``It's still a
captive audience at an official event.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sekulow, chief counsel for the American Center for Law and
Justice, a conservative group founded by religious broadcaster Pat
Robertson, believes the trend is just the opposite _ toward
allowing student-initiated, student-led prayer. But he agrees on
one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately the Supreme Court will have to delve into the
issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
