<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6698 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-AVS-MIRRORS     05-21 1575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVS-MIRRORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRROR IMAGES: STARS, AVALANCHE LOOK A LOT ALIKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
Reflections can be funny. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They can waver and flicker across the ice, distorting shapes.
They can smile back from the morning mirror, suggesting unlimited
potential. They can bounce off opponent's eyes, right back into our
own, giving us pause as to how others see us, how we want to be
seen, how we see ourselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think ego is a big part of sports,'' Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk said, perhaps reflecting on his freshman psych classes
at Cornell University. And I think at times when we're most
competitive, we do compare ourselves to others, we do want to win
little battles as well as big ones. I think that's just part of the
game.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Stars, meet your mirror. The Colorado Avalanche will
stand across the ice from the Stars at 6:30 tonight at Reunion
Arena and begin what could be the most important playoff series in
Stars franchise history. To get where the Stars want to go, to get
a chance to win the first Stanley Cup in the 31-year history of the
franchise, they must defeat the Avalanche in the best-of-seven
Western Conference finals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And to beat the Avalanche, the Stars might have to become the
Avalanche. To win the Western Conference finals, Stars players will
look across from themselves the next two weeks and see their own
reflections. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The comparisons seem uncanny. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Mike Modano will likely be matched up against
Avalanche center Peter Forsberg in a battle that each of their
coaches believes his guy'' will win. Stars goalie Ed Belfour will
stare down at the other end of the ice and covet the thick coat of
respect that Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy wears like a royal cloak.
And Nieuwendyk will square off against old pal Joe Sakic in a
rivalry in which most outsiders would pick Sakic, but most insiders
know the passionately competitive Nieuwendyk has won time and time
again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I want to beat Sakic; he's a great player,''
Nieuwendyk said. But I also want to beat him because I know that
will help our team win this series, that scoring a goal or a
winning a key faceoff against him could help change the
playoffs.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are those who call the Western Conference finals the real
Stanley Cup championship. There are those who point to the West's
ability to win the past three Cups in sweeps, who summon pictures
of the NFC's dominance over the AFC in Super Bowls before a
Coloradan named Elway burst through the looking glass. There are
those will heap even more pressure on this series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if the Stars need any motivation to stay within themselves,
to forget the overwhelming burden and concentrate on the simple
task, a look across the ice might provide just the right tweak to
the ego. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You look at both teams, and they were built in similar ways,
getting similar players to do similar things,'' said Stars winger
Brent Severyn, who played with the Avalanche two seasons ago. And
maybe the most interesting thing about all that isn't just the
similarities on the outside, but the similarities on the inside.
Both teams are competitive teams, character teams. They want to
prove themselves.'' &QL; 
Offense &QL; 
What better way to win a championship than cracking your mirror
image? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Modano has been fighting to become more like Forsberg for the
past three years _ to become the ultimate mechanism of offensive
skill and defensive responsibility. And Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
pays Modano the ultimate compliment when he matches him up with
Forsberg, apparently believing Modano will win or neutralize in the
long run, that the Stars' first line will outscore the Avalanche's
first line, even if it's only 1-0. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We just feel playing Modano and \RJere\S Lehtinen against
anybody is a good matchup,'' Hitchcock said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen is the wild card in the Modano-Forsberg battle. He's
the best defensive forward in the NHL, and the Avalanche have no
mirror image of him. What's more, Lehtinen, as a Finn, has had a
natural rivalry with Forsberg, a Swede, for much of his life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars win that battle, the scope turns to Sakic and
Nieuwendyk. Both are willowy centers with long skating strides,
wicked wrist shots and astounding ability in the faceoff circles.
They're like twin brothers of different mothers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both benefit from having another great center on their teams, a
diversion that often allows them to find open space while the more
electric Modano and Forsberg attract the primary attention of
opponents. In this series, Sakic and Nieuwendyk won't be so lucky.
They face each other. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the matchup has been one that Nieuwendyk has
won. Over the past two seasons, in head-to-head games, Nieuwendyk
has three goals and three assists and is plus one, while Sakic has
one goal and two assists and is minus one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's something we'd like to use to our advantage,'' Nieuwendyk
said at midseason, almost prophetizing the showdown to come. I
think if we did meet in the playoffs, it'd be nice to have \Rthe
statistical advantage\S out there to give them something to think
about.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And if those are merely subtle fighting words, the two teams
have the ability to deliver much stronger personal blows. Just ask
Claude Lemieux of the Avalanche and Pat Verbeek of the Stars. Each
is what is called an agitator,'' the type of player that can get in
the face and under the skin of an opponent. Both also can score
goals. Lemieux has 1,494 career penalty minutes and 325 goals.
Verbeek is even more annoying with 2,665 penalty minutes and 478
goals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And if those two aren't going at each other, fans can check out
the showdown of the graybeards _ quite literally _ in 39-year-old
center Guy Carbonneau of the Stars and 38-year-old center Dale
Hunter of the Avalanche. Both are known not only for their
defensive ability, but also for their chippiness. Carbonneau is not
nearly as penalized as Hunter, but he's just as effective at
delivering a subtle message with his stick. &QL; 
Defense &QL; 
On defense, Avalanche stopper Adam Foote's minutes and
responsibility have increased in the playoffs. Foote and Sylvain
Lefebvre will be on the ice against the Stars' best offensive
players, just as Hatcher and his partner, Richard Matvichuk, will
draw the responsibility of facing Forsberg and linemates Lemieux
and Valeri Kamensky on most shifts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When each team needs offense from the blue line, it will call on
a steady-handed European defenseman to create open ice. Sergei
Zubov is the Stars' Russian point guard, the controller of tempo,
the power-play quarterback, the man who creates a different way of
looking at the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zubov's mirror is Latvian defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh, whose
influence has been documented. When he held out for a new contract
at the beginning of the season, the Avalanche struggled. Once he
was signed, the Avalanche ran off a season-best 12-game winning
streak. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The third and fourth lines are a little more nebulous in their
comparisons. But just as Grant Marshall, Mike Keane and Benoit
Hogue have proved they can add offense, grit and versatility up and
down the lineup for the Stars, Adam Deadmarsh, Chris Drury and
Milan Hejduk have done the same for the Avalanche. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think I can look at Deadmarsh and what he does for them and
want to do the same thing,'' Marshall said. Obviously, I have to
just play my own game, but there are similarities to how that can
effect each team.'' &QL; 
What's more, each team has a hired gun. In the off-season, the
Stars bought Brett Hull's services. The Avalanche traded for Theo
Fleury in February. Both have proved dangerous scorers, and both
could be key at key times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think the thing you can say about both of them is they have
the ability to come up with big plays, big scoring plays, when
their teams need them,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. &QL; 
Goalies &QL; 
But the biggest battle will come between two goaltenders. Roy is
the winningest playoff goalie in NHL history with 107 career
victories. He has won three Stanley Cups, including the 1996 title
with the Avalanche. Belfour has 53 career playoff victories, but
has played in the Stanley Cup Finals only once. And lost. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think what you see between those two is an absolute
competitive will to win,'' Severyn said. They both want it badly,
and they both aren't afraid of showing it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belfour is more conservative; Roy more risky. There are subtle
differences, just as there are subtle difference in each of the
matchups. As much as each player has his mirror, each refracts as
much as reflects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars win with great defense, the Avalanche with great
offense. The Stars have become a team that can win a high-risk,
high-scoring game if they need to. The Avalanche has embraced the
defensive philosophy of rookie coach Bob Hartley. Each team, in
fact, has smoothed out its respective differences in the past
month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder they're where they are now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Obviously there are different ways to build winning teams and
there are different ways to win hockey games,'' Stars general
manager Bob Gainey said. But there are also common elements to
winning teams. And while those elements can be individual players,
I think the thing you can find most is how teams adapt to
challenges, how they adapt to what another team is doing. That
might be the most common thread.'' &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
