</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS DON'T MIND UNDERDOG STATUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coming to Reunion Arena tonight, Game 1 of what eventually will
be a terrific Western Conference finals. The winner of this one
kisses silver in mid-June. The Stanley Cup stops here.
</P>
<P>
   But is it just me, or has the hype factor for Stars-Avalanche
been sorta subdued this week?
</P>
<P>
   Even the two teams have seemed to size up each other with a
ho-hum attitude of ``oh, it's only you.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may be a natural reaction to the sudden demise of the
Detroit Red Wings, and also a credit to what the Wings stood for.
The Stars had spent two years building a team that could dethrone
Detroit. Then along comes Colorado this week and does it for them,
which might have caused a temporary emotional sinking spell for the
Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Both clubs, however, will have emotional motors revved up once
the puck drops tonight. Just wait _ this series will end up a
dandy. And already, there's been one surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Out in Vegas, the Avalanche is posted as the favorite in this
best-of-seven set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Told you so,'' said Stars coach Ken Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   And he did. The Avalanche-Wings handshake line was still in
progress at Joe Louis Arena on Tuesday night when Hitchcock, who
had been watching on TV, proclaimed, ``We're the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to stop it with the coach-speak, Hitchcock answered, ``No,
we're not going to be favored in this one.'' And he also couldn't
be happier it turned out that way.
</P>
<P>
   Those 114 regular-season points, signifying the best
regular-season record in the NHL, apparently meant nothing. Neither
did the spotless 5-0 home-ice record in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Las Vegas put up a wagering line for the Western
Conference finals that once again reflected a ``Detroit thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Colorado not only knocked off the defending champ, it also won
that series going away,'' Hitchcock said yesterday. ``Once that
happened, the people who decide on a favorite are naturally going
to lean that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing that became relevant in making that decision
is Colorado had an easier time with Detroit than we did with St.
Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock obviously does not argue with the conclusion. In fact,
expect to hear ``we're the underdog'' brought up many times as the
series progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, just what the Stars should want for the Avalanche
series is a repeat of the St. Louis round. Low-scoring games that
require patience and discipline to win. It is their strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with that,'' added Hitchcock, ``we have to elevate our
overall commitment and game. They have very strong offensive
players who can't be turned loose. A Wild West shootout is not what
we want here.''
</P>
<P>
   In 10 playoff games thus far, the Stars have graded superior in
two areas _ goaltending with Eddie Belfour and penalty killing.
Those two areas are also where Stanley Cups are won.
</P>
<P>
   But the Avalanche can match Belfour with Patrick Roy, while the
penalty killers regrouped against Detroit and finished very well.
In a shock, the Red Wings became a disorganized, undisciplined
mess, while Colorado transformed itself into, yes, a Stars carbon
copy.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie head coach Bob Hartley finally got his message across.
And he will be asking for more of the same against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny that Hitchcock is now the grizzled veteran of NHL
coaching ranks, while Hartley is where Hitchcock was four years
ago. He was an unknown from the minors when hired, and he came in
trying to sell a certain system to veteran players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both came up the same route,'' Hitchcock said of Hartley.
``We both earned our spurs by riding a lot of buses in the
minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock stopped short, however, of saying Hartley was
borrowing a coaching page from his tenure in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more a case of when a team reaches a certain
level in the playoffs, the talent factor is obviously involved,''
he said. ``But I do know this _ to reach the final prize it takes a
combination of talent and a 100 percent commitment to a defensive
philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Hitchcock ``sold'' his philosophy to players once
reluctant to buy. Because of that, and Belfour, make this series
the Stars in six. The `'underdog'' wins while the Red Wings watch
on TV.
\Ntagtop:Randy Galloway's ``Sports at Six'' can be heard
weeknights, 6-8 p.m., on WBAP NewsTalk 820.
\Ntagbottom:rgalloway\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
