<HEADER>
A6701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASTRAIN22-COX     05-21 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASTRAIN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta gets on board effort to build futuristic train
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta, founded on 19th-century railroads, will get a
crack at developing a train for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Regional Commission has won federal funding to study
how it might deploy, finance and market the nation's first magnetic
levitation train, said Pamela Berry, a spokeswoman for the Federal
Railroad Administration in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetic waves propel and levitate futuristic ``maglev'' trains.
Though companies in Germany and Japan have run test trains at
nearly 300 mph, the technology represents a financial risk since no
such railroad is in commercial service anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent of Congress was to see if someone could prove the
feasibility of maglev technology on U.S. soil,'' said ARC Director
Harry West. ``Hopefully, this means we're one of the half dozen or
so places that can try.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the federal rail agency will review maglev studies
from the Atlanta group and six others. By summer, it will reward
the top project $950 million to build a demonstration track.
</P>
<P>
   The catch: Congress still must appropriate the money _ a
longshot, some planners say.
</P>
<P>
   If the Atlanta Regional Commission wins funding for an
experimental track, the test segment might cover about 40 miles,
reaching Acworth or Cartersville.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the regional agency foresees a 110-mile route from
downtown Atlanta to Chattanooga. If it works, such a train could
take a rider from Atlanta and into Tennessee in about 22 minutes _
quicker than a perfect rush-hour drive from Cobb County to downtown
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of Transportation Rodney Slater will announce the
study grants Monday afternoon at Baltimore's B&AMP;O Railroad Museum.
Maglev applicants in Pittsburgh and Baltimore and two applicants in
California also won grants, Berry said. And railroad and
transportation analysts said groups from New Orleans and the
Florida Space Coast also made the cut. ``Money for each region is
still being worked out,'' Berry said. ``No one knows how much
they'll be getting.''
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, state transportation Commissioner Wayne Shackelford
has committed $1 million to be coupled with an anticipated federal
grant of $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
