<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6706 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE22-C     05-21 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wife loses round in her bid to stay married to Holyfield
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Janice Holyfield testified Friday that she and her
husband, heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield, have had sexual
relations four times since he filed for divorce March 26.
</P>
<P>
   The champ said he can't remember whether they had or not.
</P>
<P>
   Fayette County Superior Court Judge Ben Miller said it doesn't
really matter, because he doesn't think sexual relations
necessarily equal marital reconciliation. Miller denied Janice
Holyfield's motion to dismiss the divorce action.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's ruling was unusual because many other divorce cases in
Georgia, including Holyfield's first divorce, have been derailed
when the couples had sexual relations between the filing of the
complaint and the judge's final approval. Case law says a marriage
is not irretrievably broken if the parties are engaged in acts of
reconciliation, including sex, said John Mayoue, Janice Holyfield's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Mayoue said Janice Holyfield wanted the case thrown out because
she still loves the champ and thinks they have a chance of
reconciling.
</P>
<P>
   She filed an affidavit saying she and Evander Holyfield had
sexual relations April 16 in a house she lives in that is on the
grounds of his mansion in north Fayette County. They had sex at
least three other times, she said, and the boxer said he still
loved her.
</P>
<P>
   The champ took the stand and said he remembers saying he loved
Janice Holyfield, but can't remember if they actually had sexual
relations those times.
</P>
<P>
   Mayoue said he may appeal. Jim Thomas, one of Evander
Holyfield's lawyers, said the ruling made sense because Holyfield
would just refile for divorce if the case were dismissed. ``What
would be accomplished?'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The divorce case now heads to mediation. A lot of money is at
stake. The champ grossed $92 million in prize money alone from five
fights since marrying Janice Holyfield in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McGough, one of Evander Holyfield's divorce lawyers,
complained Friday that Janice Holyfield has violated a restraining
order regarding the couple's finances. McGough said she'd taken
$1.1 million out of joint accounts and put them into accounts she
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Mayoue said Janice Holyfield would return the money. He said she
panicked upon looking at the couple's accounts and seeing $20
million in recent activity that she couldn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   She was upset because her husband was refusing to pay some of
her bills, including medical expenses for their 8-month-old son,
Elijah, Mayoue said. One Emory Clinic bill for $148 was sent to a
collection agency. Mayoue said the couple spent about $500,000 a
month, though he didn't detail the expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing that you and I can relate to,'' Mayoue told the
judge. ``If you and I are spending $20 or so, they're spending
$20,000 or $200,000. You just put a few zeros in it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6707 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE22-C     05-21 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLYFIELD-DIVORCE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
