<HEADER>
A6709 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      05-21 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER'S PLEA OFFER REJECTED BY PROSECUTERS IN TORTURE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors have refused a plea deal sought by the
police officer charged with torturing Abner Louima in a restroom of
a Brooklyn police station, people close to the case said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the plea offer was made and rejected on Thursday,
the day after a police sergeant provided devastating surprise
testimony against the officer, Justin A. Volpe, saying the officer
had boasted to him that he had committed the torture.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Volpe offered to provide the prosecutors with new
information about the case in return for leniency, according to the
people close to the case, but the overture was rebuffed because the
prosecutors did not believe that he could provide credible
information.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted at the trial under way in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn, Volpe could receive a sentence of up to life in prison
without the possibility of parole for what prosecutors say was his
brutalization of Louima at the 70th Precinct station house in
Flatbush in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, declined Friday to comment
on the reports that he had unsuccessfully approached the
prosecutors on Thursday, saying only, ``At the present time we're
not taking any plea.'' He refused to discuss the possibility of
future attempts to gain leniency through other methods during the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   One such option would be for Volpe to interrupt the trial to
plead guilty to all the charges against him without the benefit of
a deal with prosecutors, and to throw himself on the mercy of the
court. If that occurred, the trial would most likely continue for
the three other officers and a sergeant who are his co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility would be for Volpe to take the witness stand
and confess to a lesser role in the reported assault on Louima, in
the hope that the jury would not convict him of the most serious
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg declined Friday to discuss these options, saying, ``I
can never speak for the future _ who knows what the future will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Consideration of Kornberg's possible defense strategies arose
after the lawyer, in a reversal of his stated plans to vigorously
cross-examine the witness, Sgt. Kenneth Wernick, instead said he
had ``no questions.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the sergeant had told the jury that on the morning
prosecutors say Volpe tortured Louima with a stick in the station
house restroom, Volpe bragged that he had shoved a stick ``five or
six inches'' into Louima's rectum, and had then shown the sergeant
the stick.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the case said Kornberg did not know about the
extent of that testimony until Monday, when he received prosecution
documents related to Wernick's coming appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The people who reported Kornberg's unsuccessful plea offer would
not describe what new information Volpe said he could provide.
</P>
<P>
   But a history of the case suggests that it could be information
implicating additional police officers in a cover-up of the
reported attack on Louima, or that it could be a new version of the
events involving the four other defendants on trial.
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely that prosecutors would be skeptical of any
attempts by Volpe to give information either increasing or reducing
the level of involvement that prosecutors ascribe to the other four
defendants, coming two weeks after testimony in the case began and
so soon after Wernick's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution declined to comment Friday on the reports of
Kornberg's plea offer or on any other matters related to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not commented on the trial before and I will not
comment on it now,'' said Zachary W. Carter, the U.S. attorney in
Brooklyn, whose office is prosecuting the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that increased racial tensions in the city when it
became known two years ago, Louima, a 32-year-old black man, was
brutalized by Volpe and three other white officers after being
arrested in a street melee outside a Flatbush nightclub, Carter's
office says.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors say that Volpe and the other three _ Charles
Schwarz, Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder _ beat Louima in a police
car, and that Volpe and Schwarz then attacked him in the station
house restroom. They say that Volpe rammed part of a broken stick
into Louima's rectum and then his mouth, causing major damage to
his rectum and bladder, while Schwarz held him down. The four men
are charged with federal civil rights violations. The prosecution
says the officers erroneously believed that Louima had punched
Volpe during the street disturbance. The fifth defendant, Sgt.
Michael Bellomo, is charged with trying to cover up the alleged
beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the other officers declined Friday to comment on the
reports of a plea offer by Kornberg. They said their clients were
not seeking any such deals and they expressed confidence that the
jury would acquit their clients. The trial was in recess Friday and
is to resume on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg, while declining to comment on the reports that he had
approached the prosecution on Thursday, did say that he had not
sought a plea deal for Volpe between his indictment by a federal
grand jury in February 1998 and the start of the trial, for which
jury selection began nearly two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe and Bruder could get sentences of up to life in prison
without parole if they are convicted of violating Louima's civil
rights in actions that included a sexual assault, which is how the
indictment defines the alleged attack with the stick.
</P>
<P>
   If Volpe pleads guilty, Judge Eugene H. Nickerson has the
discretion to reduce his sentence on the ground that he has
accepted responsibility for his crime. Lawyers estimate that such a
reduction could mean a sentence of about 30 years, with the
possibility of reducing that term by 15 percent through good
behavior in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese and Bruder would face up to 10 years in prison if
convicted of violating Louima's rights by beating him in the police
car, and Bellomo would face the same maximum if convicted of trying
to cover up that offense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
