<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-CARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARR IS NOT DISSUADED BY BACKSEAT TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oba Carr feels like the forgotten man in his world
championship bout with Oscar De La Hoya, the World Boxing Council
welterweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   Carr's likeness does not even appear on the posters advertising
his fight Saturday night at the Mandalay Bay Resort. Instead, the
face of Floyd Mayweather Jr., the WBC junior-lightweight champion
and rising Top Rank star, graces the corner of the poster opposite
De La Hoya. Mayweather is fighting on the undercard.
</P>
<P>
   And with the news that a deal for a bout between De La Hoya and
Felix Trinidad, the International Boxing Federation welterweight
champion, is complete, Carr slipped further into the background
today.
</P>
<P>
   When the two meet on HBO's ``World Championship Boxing,'' Carr
will now simply be a tuneup for De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Carr, the WBC's No. 1 contender, does not see himself
in that role. He said he has had a ``consistent vision'' for the
last two years that he is going to defeat De La Hoya and become a
world champion.
</P>
<P>
   Carr has twice fought for world titles _ against Ike Quartey and
Trinidad _ but he lost both times. This time Carr, who is very
religious, believes his vision will come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put my heart and soul in this fight,'' he said. ``God has
blessed me in this moment. To take his title I'm going to have to
be 100 percent, mentally, physically and spiritually.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr added: ``The victory is already done in heaven. We just
have to make it work on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be a problem considering that De La Hoya, a superb
ring tactician and hard puncher, has rededicated himself to being a
knockout artist. De La Hoya, who will earn $5 million for the bout,
said he will be going for the knockout against Carr, who will make
$350,000.
</P>
<P>
   What if it does not happen in the early rounds? Will De La Hoya
abandon the strategy and just fight to assure the victory?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to press and press and press until he can't take it
anymore,'' De La Hoya said. ``I guarantee that no fighter can last
if I hit him with my hardest shots.''
</P>
<P>
   A knockout victory over Carr will not prove anything to anyone
except De La Hoya, who seems to need the reassurance that he is a
magnificent boxer. That yearning for respect has led him to give
Bob Arum, his promoter, a mandate to make the best fights possible.
</P>
<P>
   It was De La Hoya who asked for a bout against Quartey, whom he
defeated in a 12-round decision. And it was De La Hoya who has made
the necessary concessions to get Trinidad in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya cannot believe that he allowed himself to be called a
chicken for not stepping up sooner and fighting the top
welterweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those guys saying they wanted to fight me; it was all a
bluff,'' he said. ``They were always putting the ball in my court.
They were making me look like I was the one who was scared. Now
that I'm accepting the challenge, they're the ones who are scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight with Trinidad will happen, not because of Trinidad's
people, but because of me. I want this fight. I will do what I have
to do to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears De La Hoya will get his wish on Sept. 18 at the
Mandalay Bay's 12,000-seat arena. Arum and Don King, Trinidad's
promoter, completed the deal Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for De La Hoya to earn $15 million and Trinidad
to earn $11 million. No contracts have been signed. King said that
all he has to do is get Trinidad's father, Felix Sr., to sign off
on the deal and it will be sealed. King has not been an impediment
concerning the fight, even though he is risking one of his top
money-making champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fight that everybody wants to see,'' King said.
``I'm not going to do anything to stand in the way of it happening.
If it doesn't happen, it won't be because of anything I've done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
