<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-RECORDS22-COX     05-21 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RECORDS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia colleges warned not to close records
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A firestorm erupting over new open records legislation
has singed the state University System's private foundations, many
of which are concerned about keeping the names of their anonymous
donors private.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia State University's nonprofit foundation earlier this
week passed a resolution spelling out its belief that anonymous
donors are protected under the privacy exception in the Georgia
Open Records Act.
</P>
<P>
   When it looked as if some other universities were on the verge
of passing similar resolutions, Board of Regents Chancellor Stephen
Portch warned university presidents in a memo Thursday not to
challenge the tough new amendments to the act, signed by Gov. Roy
Barnes earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to be challenging the governor's bill,''
Portch's memo states. ``The regents have been portrayed as opposed
to open government in the past. For an institution founded to
pursue truth, that doesn't ring well.''
</P>
<P>
   Portch apparently was responding to concern in the governor's
office about a movement afoot in the regents' Advisory Committee
for College and University Advancement to take legal action against
any requests for private donor information.
</P>
<P>
   James B. Osborne, head of the Medical College of Georgia's
foundation and chairman of the advisory committee, had proposed
that the foundations form a consortium and hire a law firm to
represent the first foundation receiving a request.
</P>
<P>
   The universities are concerned that the new legislation would
make donor lists more readily available to the public. They fear
the release of that information would lead to a decline in private
financial contributions, the lifeblood of many universities and
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   However, that plan concerned the governor, a major proponent of
open records legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big concern of donors is making sure their contributions
go to further education,'' said Bobby Kahn, the governor's chief of
staff, ``instead of being spent on lawyers' fees for attempts to
illegally elude public scrutiny that are destined for failure. This
is precisely the kind of behavior that prompted the governor to
strengthen the Open Records Act, and it's truly disappointing to
see that these people have not gotten the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes is supporting the state attorney general and local media
organizations seeking lists of donors and other financial
information withheld by the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation,
which wants to keep records of the Atlanta Olympic bid committee
private. Barnes said he believes the GAAF is subject to the open
records law, while the foundation's attorneys contend it is not.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne said the university and college foundations were not
trying to break the law, only seek a legal interpretation of the
privacy exception in the law.
</P>
<P>
   However, some advancement committee officers decided Wednesday
against forming a consortium. ``We met and concluded everyone is so
different that each nonprofit foundation has to deal with the issue
individually on a case-by-case basis,'' Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   The GSU foundation passed its resolution Wednesday _ before
Portch's memo was circulated _ and no other foundation has followed
suit. The University of Georgia foundation board met Friday, but
the issue was not on the agenda. The Medical College of Georgia's
foundation board declined to pass the resolution, but agreed to
seek a legal opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6715 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-RECORDS22-COX     05-21 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RECORDS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia colleges warned not to close records
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A firestorm erupting over new open records legislation
has singed the state University System's private foundations, many
of which are concerned about keeping the names of their anonymous
donors private.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia State University's nonprofit foundation earlier this
week passed a resolution spelling out its belief that anonymous
donors are protected under the privacy exception in the Georgia
Open Records Act.
</P>
<P>
   When it looked as if some other universities were on the verge
of passing similar resolutions, Board of Regents Chancellor Stephen
Portch warned university presidents in a memo Thursday not to
challenge the tough new amendments to the act, signed by Gov. Roy
Barnes earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to be challenging the governor's bill,''
Portch's memo states. ``The regents have been portrayed as opposed
to open government in the past. For an institution founded to
pursue truth, that doesn't ring well.''
</P>
<P>
   Portch apparently was responding to concern in the governor's
office about a movement afoot in the regents' Advisory Committee
for College and University Advancement to take legal action against
any requests for private donor information.
</P>
<P>
   James B. Osborne, head of the Medical College of Georgia's
foundation and chairman of the advisory committee, had proposed
that the foundations form a consortium and hire a law firm to
represent the first foundation receiving a request.
</P>
<P>
   The universities are concerned that the new legislation would
make donor lists more readily available to the public. They fear
the release of that information would lead to a decline in private
financial contributions, the lifeblood of many universities and
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   However, that plan concerned the governor, a major proponent of
open records legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big concern of donors is making sure their contributions
go to further education,'' said Bobby Kahn, the governor's chief of
staff, ``instead of being spent on lawyers' fees for attempts to
illegally elude public scrutiny that are destined for failure. This
is precisely the kind of behavior that prompted the governor to
strengthen the Open Records Act, and it's truly disappointing to
see that these people have not gotten the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes is supporting the state attorney general and local media
organizations seeking lists of donors and other financial
information withheld by the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation,
which wants to keep records of the Atlanta Olympic bid committee
private. Barnes said he believes the GAAF is subject to the open
records law, while the foundation's attorneys contend it is not.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne said the university and college foundations were not
trying to break the law, only seek a legal interpretation of the
privacy exception in the law.
</P>
<P>
   However, some advancement committee officers decided Wednesday
against forming a consortium. ``We met and concluded everyone is so
different that each nonprofit foundation has to deal with the issue
individually on a case-by-case basis,'' Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   The GSU foundation passed its resolution Wednesday _ before
Portch's memo was circulated _ and no other foundation has followed
suit. The University of Georgia foundation board met Friday, but
the issue was not on the agenda. The Medical College of Georgia's
foundation board declined to pass the resolution, but agreed to
seek a legal opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
