<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-720&AMP;ADD     05-21 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO INSURGENTS REPORT KILLING RUSSIAN OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ In a development that could complicate
Russia's role in the Kosovo crisis, rebels fighting for the
territory's independence claim to have killed a Russian captain in
a battle with Serbian troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army said that the dead
man was just the latest in a list of Russians who have been killed
in Kosovo, and that they had known for months that Russian officers
and soldiers were fighting with Serbian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel group claims that Russians' fighting makes Moscow's
role in peace negotiations impossible and denies Moscow the right
to take part in any future peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough evidence to prove that the Russians are
supplying the Yugoslavian army with arms and with soldiers,'' said
Jakup Krasniqi, chief spokesman for a group called the Interim
Government of Kosovo, which is closely linked to the Kosovo
Liberation Army. ``After that, how can we trust them?''
</P>
<P>
   Russian television showed a videotape of the dead soldier
dressed in a Serbian uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials in Moscow confirmed that an officer of the
name given by the Kosovo Liberation Army had been enlisted in the
ranks of the Russian Emergency Situations Ministry, which generally
handles fire and emergency rescues. But they said the man, Vitaly
Bulakh, who was 34, was given a medical discharge in 1997, and was
then assigned to the Khabarovsk military district as a retired
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army suspects that Bulakh was sent to
Kosovo on official duty, but it is also possible that Russian
mercenaries are entering the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels said that according to documents found on the man, he
graduated from a Russian military academy in 1996. They added that
he had 3,500 Russian rubles with him.
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi of the Kosovo Liberation Army said Friday afternoon
that a strong letter of protest had been sent to the Russian
Embassy in Tirana, in which a ransom of 5,000 firearms, with
ammunition, was demanded in exchange for the return of the
officer's body. As of Friday night, there had been no response from
the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of Russian participation in Serbian military maneuvers,
if corroborated, would buttress information provided by several
rebel officers and soldiers over several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Nexhmedin Kastrati, a commander in the Kosovo Liberation Army,
said in an interview last week in northern Albania that his troops
had encountered Russian officers and mercenaries in combat in
Kosovo. He said his men had also intercepted radio calls in Russian
and recovered military documents written in Russian and containing
Russian names.
</P>
<P>
   Kastrati, who said he served with the Yugoslav army from 1991 to
1998 and fought in Croatia and Bosnia, said the Russians were few
in number but exerted substantial influence over training and
tactics of Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are free to act as they choose,'' Kastrati said in an
interview at a Kosovo Liberation Army office in the Albanian town
of Kukes. They are often at the forefront of an attack, he said,
adding, ``On the front lines we can hear the exchange of words and
the swearing, all in Russian.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebel fighters have reported that Russian soldiers treated at
hospitals in Kosovo had to use translators to speak to doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Several rebel fighters also reported seeing or hearing Russians
in Kosovo. One, Sabri Popaj, interviewed two weeks ago, said that
in combat in southern Kosovo near the villages of Zerze (the
Albanian name for Zrze) and Bellacerka (Bela Crkva), he had heard
commands in Russian. He said his fighting group, the 124th Brigade
of the Kosovo Liberation Army, had also intercepted radio
communications in Russian.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of Russians' fighting in Kosovo come at a delicate
moment. Russia's special envoy to the Balkans, Viktor Chernomyrdin,
has been working, with the support of Washington, to broker a deal
with President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to stop the
fighting and withdraw Serbian troops from Kosovo so that hundreds
of thousands of Albanian-speaking refugees can return.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicions could affect the makeup of peacekeeping forces in
Kosovo. Many Albanian-speaking Kosovars distrust Russians and say
they would not return home if Russians were stationed there as
peacekeepers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Russian casualty appears to be bolstering the Kosovo
Liberation Army, which in recent weeks has been trying to
professionalize its ranks and improve its image, which is that of a
disorganized and weak force.
</P>
<P>
   After the NATO bombardment began March 24, the rebels issued a
general mobilization call. Recruits flooded into Albania from as
far away as the United States and Canada, and from all over Western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel officers say they now have enough troops to start a major
offensive, even if the U.S. Army does not employ its anti-tank
Apache helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   But the rebels still lack sufficient arms, particularly
anti-tank weapons and heavy artillery. ``The main reason why we
started the mobilization campaign was to get weapons,'' the
commander said. ``It is a lot easier for people coming from
America, Europe and Albania to pick up weapons along the way to
Kosovo than it is for those of us inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week the rebel army's top command was reshuffled, and a
veteran officer, Agim Ceku, who was a brigadier general in the
Croatian army, was named chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   In Kukes, the officer in charge of rebel recruitment has
reportedly been reassigned after several instances in which young
Albanians from Kosovo were grabbed off the street and forced to
join the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plenty of people who want to join the KLA, but we
cannot afford to sign them up,'' Kastrati said. ``Our first
priority is people who are prepared mentally and physically to go
into Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Popaj, the rebel fighter, who said two of his sons, two of his
brothers and a nephew were killed by Serbian troops in Bellacerka
in March, said the Serbs had used civilians as shields to protect
themselves from attack, and now traveled in cars and trucks taken
from civilians rather than in their own vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel fighters said they sometimes redeployed troops during a
NATO attack, when the Serbs were taking cover and often were
separated from their equipment and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Popaj said the Serbs' front-line forces wore a kind of
bulletproof trench coat, which could not be pierced by automatic
rifle fire. ``They advanced without fear,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
