</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NOT TOO SOON TO PREPARE FOR PACERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks wake up Saturday morning sitting on top of
a new world in the National Basketball Association. They overcame
Miami in Round 1 and hold a 2-0 lead against Atlanta in Round 2
with a chance to close the Hawks out in Games 3 and 4 on Sunday and
Monday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   This peaceful interlude seems an appropriate time to introduce
that cloud on the Knicks' horizon, speak the word no one likes to
speak. I'd like to introduce the dreaded P word: Pacers. The
Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Players and coaches may not look ahead, but fans do. And Knick
fans have already begun wringing their hands over the prospect of
meeting Indiana for the Eastern Conference title.
</P>
<P>
   Too early, you say, to look ahead nervously? Not for this team,
not for these fans. The Knicks, for all their rapid transformation
in the last few weeks, must prepare for the Pacers in the manner
that a runner prepares for the marathon. The Pacers _ more than the
Heat or even the Bulls _ have been the Knicks' nasty nemesis of the
'90s. Four seasons ago, Indiana handed the Knicks their most
devastating loss of the decade when Reggie Miller scored 8 points
in the final 16 seconds to send the Knicks to a 107-105 loss in
Game 1 of a second-round series, a series the Knicks eventually
lost when Patrick Ewing's Game 7 finger roll went in and out of the
basket in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last season, the Pacers, using a typically punishing
inside attack, again tossed the Knicks from the playoffs in the
second round and all but said, ``And stay out!''
</P>
<P>
   Can these new, lighter Knicks defeat Indiana? Of course they
can.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are not the team they were last season, when they
took Chicago to seven games in the conference finals. And the
Knicks are not the team the Pacers knocked out of the playoffs.
Indiana made the mistake the Knicks did not make during the off
season: Indiana stood pat. The Knicks added two crucial pieces:
Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby. Sprewell has been a genie, and
now coach Jeff Van Gundy has to only free Marcus Camby. I thought
we had already turned that corner, but apparently not. Van Gundy is
still making Camby pledge. In Game 1 against Atlanta on Tuesday,
Camby had a weak 10 minutes. He sat down and never played again,
but no matter, the Knicks won going away, thanks in large part to
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2 on Thursday, the Knicks, in their typically
inconsistent style, went flat. But Sprewell and Camby saved the
day. Sprewell, moving with the ball, scored 31 points, and Camby,
moving without it, scored 11 points, grabbed 13 rebounds and
created havoc. Together, they turned a 13-2 first-quarter deficit
into a 38-36 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The post-game spin was that the psychology of not playing in
Game 1 had motivated Camby in Game 2. Nonsense. Had he had a second
chance in Game 1, Camby would have been a force and the Knicks
might have won by 50 points. It's time for these regular-season
mind games to stop. Either Van Gundy has faith in Camby or he
doesn't, but things are likely to go better for the Knicks if Van
Gundy puts Camby back in the game in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the Knicks have retreated into that defensive mode of
old, they have lost. Atlanta was bracing for the Knicks to come
rumbling by ground; instead, the Knicks arrived speeding by air.
Indiana is even better on the ground, but not so great in the air.
With the exception of Jalen Rose, the Pacers' answer to Sprewell,
Indiana is not that versatile. Reggie Miller can't beat you without
screens, and the same goes for Chris Mullin. But if the Knicks slug
it out with the Pacers, Indiana wins.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell and Camby are safety locks that prevent the Knicks from
sliding back into the past. Without Sprewell and Camby this season,
the Knicks are out playing golf right now and Van Gundy is probably
out of a job. Without Camby, the Knicks are not in the playoffs,
not past Miami and not up by 2-0 in the second round after two road
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has done a superb job getting the Knicks to buy into
the team concept. Now he has to determine what Camby has done, and
the coach should buy into that. Camby's ability to turn a game
around should be enough of a sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, the Knicks have had four shots at Indiana: they
beat the Pacers in 1992-93 and 1993-94 under Pat Riley and then
lost in 1994-95 and 1997-98 under Riley and Van Gundy. Now, as the
Knicks prepare for another encounter with the Pacers, the challenge
for Van Gundy is to turn the guys who aren't his guys into his
guys. As it turns out, they hold the key to the Knicks' vast
horizons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
