<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-ACCOUNTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL EXECUTIVES GROUP OPPOSES SEC PROPOSAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's largest group of corporate financial officers is
lobbying to quash a plan that would make it easier for directors of
public companies to know when managements are being too loose in
the way they tally profits.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the Financial Executives Institute said it
opposed a proposal that would require outside auditors of public
companies to tell members of the audit committee each year whether
management was being aggressive or conservative in its accounting
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, a group of more than 14,000 financial executives,
said it feared the plan would allow auditors to ``second guess''
corporate management's decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The financial executives were responding to proposals made
earlier this year by a committee appointed by Levitt after a string
of high-profile cases in which companies including Cendant, Sunbeam
and Livent disclosed that they had mislead shareholders by
reporting results that were wrong by tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the committee released its recommendations to make
corporate audit committees better watchdogs for shareholders and to
help prevent what Levitt has referred to as ``accounting
shenanigans'' by public companies. The commission and the nation's
stock exchanges are now considering the committee's
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the institute's letter, Lynn E. Turner, the
commission's chief accountant, said Friday that regulators would
still press for new rules requiring an annual discussion between
auditors and the audit committee about the ``quality'' of the
company's financial reporting and how aggressive or conservative
management was being in applying the accounting rules.
</P>
<P>
   But Turner said that he agreed with the financial executives
that management should be included in those discussions.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter, the financial executives also said they were
opposed to the plan that would require audit committees to write a
letter to shareholders each year saying that they had talked to the
auditors and were comfortable with the company's financial
statements. The executives said the plan would make the audit
committee legally liable for the accuracy of the company's
financial statements _ a responsibility better left to management
and the auditors.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said they did not agree with a proposal to
require auditors to review companies' quarterly financial
statements and to talk to audit committees about those quarterly
reports. That plan would cost companies too much, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A requirement to have a meeting or a telephone conference,
whether or not there are any items to discuss, seems bureaucratic
and unwarranted,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   But Turner said Friday that he believed that both those plans
were good ones. ``I don't think there's a lot of cost'' to a
quarterly discussion, he said. ``It only needs to be a phone
call.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
