<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SENATE-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SENATE WOULD ALLOW LICENSED FIRMS TO DISPOSE OF NUCLEAR
WASTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Vt., Maine) 
 
By KATHY WALT 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Senate on Friday approved the
licensing of private companies to dispose of low-level nuclear
wastes.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers, over the objections of sponsor Sen. J.E.
``Buster'' Brown, R-Lake Jackson, also drastically reduced the
potential for nuclear waste dump sites to proliferate in Texas by
stipulating that such graveyards could be located only in Andrews
County, northwest of Midland.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to do is make it where we can get the best
available technology and the best minds working to bring about a
site but also have limitations ... (on) what comes in,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, House Bill 1171, must go back to the lower chamber.
The Senate version contains two key differences from the
House-approved plan: the provision that allows private companies to
be licensed and another that prohibits private license holders from
accepting nuclear waste from states other than Texas, Maine and
Vermont. Texas has a long-term interstate compact with Maine and
Vermont to accept their waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is that your legislation would make Texas the
outdoor privy for low-level nuclear wastes,'' said Sen. Carlos
Truan, D-Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Attorney General John Cornyn issued a legal
ruling on the privatization issue, saying such a move would force
Texas to accept shipments of waste from the federal government's
nuclear weapons industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown said the U.S. Department of Energy already has the
authority to license private companies to dispose of nuclear waste
in Texas if it wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the bill contains safeguards to prevent massive
amounts of radioactive wastes from flowing to Texas. For example,
he said, the bill would limit the waste a private company could
accept from the federal government to no more than 20 percent of
what it expects to get from Maine and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also contend that the state's ability to regulate the
disposal sites would be diminished under privatization. Brown,
though, said his bill would ensure the government's right to
regulate disposal sites and would require companies to post surety
bonds or set aside sufficient cash reserves to indemnify the state
from liability.
</P>
<P>
   The House version would restrict licensing to government
entities but would allow government entities to then contract with
private companies to actually manage a dump site.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews County right now is the only county whose residents have
asked to have a nuclear dump in their own backyard and the only
county whose commissioners also have approved of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said his only concern about restricting possible nuclear
waste disposal sites to Andrews County is if the county somehow
fails to get a permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If for some reason it fails, somebody in this Legislature is
going to have to come back next session and pick another county,''
Brown said. In trying to fend off the Andrews County amendment by
Lubbock Republican Sen. Robert Duncan, he reminded lawmakers of the
feud over the state's attempts to place the dump in Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Natural Resources Conservation Commission last fall
rejected the Hudspeth County site, which Gov. George W. Bush also
had opposed. That tossed back in the Legislature's lap the problem
of trying to find where to send contaminated items from nuclear
power plants in Texas, Vermont and Maine, as well as waste from
hospitals and universities and other low-level nuclear waste from
household items like luminous watch dials and smoke alarms.
</P>
<P>
   Since Texas created the Low Level Nuclear Waste Disposal
Authority in 1981, the agency has spent $53 million and has yet
been able to get a site in Texas licensed as a permanent storage
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Friday also approved a bill that would require state
officeholders and candidates to file their campaign finance reports
electronically.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which must win one more House vote before it can be
sent to the governor, ``opens the door on Texas government and
allows all Texans to pass through,'' said its sponsor, Sen. Mike
Moncrief, D-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who raise at least $20,000 would be required to file
their reports of campaign contributions and expenditures with the
Texas Ethics Commission electronically, and the commission would
have to post them on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Paper reports also would continue to be available for viewing or
copying at the commission's offices in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Moncrief said 14 other states already require electronic filing.
State officials and candidates already can voluntarily file their
reports electronically in Texas, but only 16 percent do so, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, approved on a voice vote, was amended by Sen. Troy
Fraser, R-Horseshoe Bay, to also require legislators and
legislative candidates to more quickly report large donations they
receive in the closing days of a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Present law requires legislators and legislative candidates, but
not statewide officeholders, to report contributions of more than
$1,000 received within nine days before an election to the Ethics
Commission within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser's amendment would require lawmakers and candidates for
their offices to report large contributions received within 14 days
before an election to the commission within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Steve Ogden, R-College Station, unsuccessfully tried to
amend the bill to require candidates to fully report all
contributions and expenditures each week during the last month
before an election.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden said his amendment was necessary to uncover late donations
that can be crucial to a campaign's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is if you don't have any trouble spending it, you
shouldn't have any trouble reporting it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to spend it,'' retorted Sen. Jeff Wentworth,
R-San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the bill earlier this session but will have
to consider it again because of Senate changes.
</P>
<P>
   In other action:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Senate approved, 26-4, a bill to clarify that self-help
legal books and related materials, which help people prepare their
own wills and other official documents without a lawyer's help,
don't constitute the practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, House Bill 1507, which now goes to the governor,
was designed to address questions that have been raised about the
legality of such self-help materials.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Barefoot Sanders of Dallas last month banned
the distribution in Texas of self-help legal software distributed
by Parsons Technology Inc., whose materials had been challenged by
the state's Unauthorized Practice of Law Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Another publisher, California-based Nolo Press, also is involved
in a similar fight in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Senators approved House Bill 926 to increase the penalty for
tampering with the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills test.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative action follows several reported incidents of
tampering with the tests in some school districts. The bill would
make tampering, which is now a misdemeanor, a third-degree felony,
punishable by two to 10 years in prison and as much as a $10,000
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Tampering with the intent to defraud would be a second-degree
felony, punishable by two to 20 years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now goes back to the House for consideration of Senate
amendments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
