<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND GRANTS TYSON PAROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tyson, the former world heavyweight champion, was granted
parole Friday by the state of Maryland and will be released from
the Montgomery County jail no later than June 4.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has served four months of a one-year sentence for
assaulting two elderly motorists last Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to complete his sentence under a supervised
house-detention program instead of in a halfway house. The parole
board, which granted parole on a 5-1 vote, said one factor in its
decision was that Tyson would be supervised upon his release. If
Tyson completed his sentence in September, he could not have been
placed under the supervisory terms of parole.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor was that the two motorists, Abmielec Saucedo and
Richard Hardick, supported Tyson's release. At the sentencing
hearing Feb. 5, Saucedo and Hardick said through their lawyers that
Tyson should not be sentenced to prison.
</P>
<P>
   But Montgomery County District Court Judge Stephen Johnson
sentenced Tyson to a one-year term. Tyson had pleaded no contest to
two counts of misdemeanor assault and faced up to 10 years in
prison on each count.
</P>
<P>
   When he entered jail Feb. 5, Tyson was still on probation in
Indiana for a 1992 rape conviction. Judge Patricia Gifford, who
presided over Tyson's rape trial, granted an appeal by Tyson to
modify his probation so that he could serve the rest of it in the
Montgomery County jail. Gifford added a 60-day sentence to Tyson's
time, which amounted to 30 days with good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, 32, has been undergoing psychological counseling, taking
an antidepressant and working on his high school equivalency
diploma. He threw a television against a wall in a recreation room
and spent five days in solitary confinement before a disciplinary
panel decided that he should not be punished. Tyson said prison
authorities took away his medication, because they wanted him to
see a jail psychologist as opposed to his own psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson knocked out Francois Botha in the fifth round Jan. 16 and
three weeks later was sentenced to jail. If he can get himself in
condition, Tyson could return to the ring in August. Showtime,
which has a contract with Tyson, has an Aug. 21 date that it can
use for Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't want to talk about anything with Mike Tyson
until after he is released from jail,'' said Jay Larkin, senior
vice president of programming for Showtime. ``The instant he is out
we'll sit down and talk plans, times, dates and opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's incarceration did not stop possible opponents from
positioning themselves. His first bout could be against Axel
Schulz, and Shannon Briggs is angling for a December bout. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
