<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6742 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-JARWARS22-CO     05-21 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-JARWARS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jar Jar in `Phantom Menace' gets in way of story, critics
contend.
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The critics have not been kind to Jar Jar Binks.
While reviews of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' have
been widely mixed, film pundits are united in their dislike of the
unintelligible, computer-generated Gungan.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Turan of the Los Angeles Times called the overtly cute
sidekick to Jedi Knight Qui-Gon Jinn the film's biggest
miscalculation. ``Looking like a large and ungainly sea horse, Jar
Jar, who inexplicably speaks in a kind of Caribbean patois, is a
major miscue, a comic-relief character who's, frankly, not funny,''
Turan wrote. ``The Gungan as a whole prove very difficult to
understand, and when you can make out what they're saying (`You're
in big do-do this time') you wish you hadn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment Weekly's Owen Gleiberman described the character
as ``a rabbit-eared mascot ... whose goofy tongue-twisting patois
renders him a nuisance within 30 seconds.'' Some have also found
Jar Jar's silly manner of speaking offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Susan Wloszczyna of USA Today who offered what may be
the most prescient appraisal, especially for parents of young
children: ``Jabbering annoyance that he is, ... this frog-faced
galoot and his ``me-sa, you-sa, we-sa'' pidgin English is in the
grand tradition of Chewbacca and C-3PO. Jar Jar will be the action
figure most likely to cause you to trip on your kid's bedroom
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   From prissy robots and growling Wookiees to cuddly, teddy
bear-like Ewoks, the ``Star Wars'' films have always held strong
points of appeal for children. Series creator George Lucas, who
wrote, directed and executive produced this first of three planned
prequels, which opened Wednesday, said that fans who grew up with
the original trilogy have gotten older and that the new film is
really for young people.
</P>
<P>
   But is Lucas at risk of alienating his core audience to attract
new fans?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way,'' said ``Phantom Menace'' producer Rick
McCallum, ``for those people that are perhaps a little more bitter,
mean-spirited or twisted, you're not going to like it as much. It
won't be the same thing. You won't have the same expectations. But
it is ostensibly a kids' movie, and they're coming to it in a
completely different, new light. And hopefully, they'll live
through it just like perhaps you did when you were younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its preteen target audience, McCallum said the film is
trans-generational, and will be easier for parents to sit through
than most movies made for kids. ``I really do think there's a new
generation out there that's ready and hyped and excited about
seeing the film,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace's'' younger focus is probably the result of
Lucas' newfound role as the single father of three adopted
children. The 55-year-old filmmaker had his adopted son, Jett, then
6, with him constantly on the set. Jett reportedly coined the word,
``Gungan,'' using it at age 2 to describe heavy machinery. The
Gungan language is a mixture of patois and childish malapropisms
(``Exsqueeze me'').
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Lucas said the new movie is no more kid-friendly than any
of the previous ``Star Wars'' films. ``When I did the other films,
I said, this is a film for 12-year-olds, and it's a kids' movie. At
the time, everybody said fine, and that was I think one of the
reasons we got a lot of bad reviews. They said this is just a
Disney movie. But then somehow over the years, people have sort of
drifted away from that and tried to make it into something other
than what its actually is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, speaking last week at a press conference at the Regency
Hotel, used the uproar over the announcement of ``Episode I's''
title as an example. ``The fans had sort of decided that the title
was going to be something significant, and I said this is a
Saturday-afternoon serial for children. ``The Phantom Menace'' is
the perfect title for a film like this,'' he said. ``It has a
roll-up, it has `Episode I.' People forget what the movies actually
are.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the heavily merchandized Jar Jar seems befuddled by his
dialogue. ``Me gods! What is me-sa saying?'' he asks at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Best, the former ``Stomp'' performer who created Jar Jar's
movements for computer animators and provides his voice, told one
publication that the first dialogue he saw for the character looked
like a sentence full of typos. Yet the cast members are quick to
defend Jar Jar's role in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of adults have been complaining about Jar Jar being so
stupid,'' said Jake Lloyd, the 10-year-old actor who plays young
Anakin Skywalker. ``I think a 10-year-old would like it.'' Lloyd
said that without Jar Jar, the human characters would have no
relation to the Gungans, an amphibious race that figures
prominently in the film's climactic battle sequence.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interview, Best said the much-maligned character
represents the innocence and honesty of the film. He was aware of
the early hits Jar Jar has been taking from fans and critics.
``Whether or not the fans will dig him, I don't know,'' Best, 25,
said. ``I dig him. I guess that's what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being difficult to understand, Jar Jar has been
criticized for his Caribbean-flavored accent. Entertainment Weekly
described him as ``the gene-spliced love child of Roger Rabbit and,
so help us, Stepin Fetchit.'' Other alien characters are also
drawing some fire for perceived racial stereotyping. The
Neimodians, who launch a surprise attack on Naboo, talk like
Asians. Watto, the hovering blue junk dealer who likes to haggle,
sounds like an Arab.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no accent,'' Best said, regarding Jar Jar. ``I guess
there is an accent _ I mean, you guys have all been hearing an
accent, but it's completely unintentional. I'm Caribbean, but there
was no Caribbean in it. Jar Jar's from Naboo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' is heavy on lighthearted kid appeal, but
the series will inherently grow darker over next two prequels, as
Anakin is seduced by the dark side of the Force and becomes Darth
Vader. ``I think it's a different world for kids now,'' said
McCallum, a father of four. ``It's no longer black and white _ it's
gray. And we're really going to get into the grayness of it for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning once again to the critics, Todd McCarthy of Variety
offers the perfect summation: ``So while the new picture may not
deliver everything the original fans have been fantasizing about
for most of their lives, Lucas may again assert his status as the
shrewdest marketeer among filmmakers, if he can capture the new
generation for his fresh trilogy while still taking old-time fans
along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
