<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LEGIS-PAY-NYT &LR;      05-21 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-PAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEZE ON N.Y. LAWMAKERS' PAYROLL IS RULED UNCONSTITUTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A state judge ruled Friday that a new law
withholding state legislators' pay until a budget is passed is
unconstitutional. His decision dealt a blow to an attempt to speed
the state's notoriously lethargic budget process.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said they
would appeal the ruling. Both camps in the case have agreed that
the ruling will not go into effect while an appeal is pending, so
it may be months before the legislators see new paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   The 211 members of the Assembly and the Senate have not been
paid since March 31, the last day of the old fiscal year, and some
say they are beginning to have financial trouble. ``Let's just say
that my landlord is happy at the thought of my getting paid
again,'' said state Sen. Thomas Duane of Manhattan, one of 14
legislators, all Democrats, who sued to challenge the law.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs took heart from the strongly worded decision by
Justice Richard Huttner of state Supreme Court in Brooklyn. He
found that the law gives the governor a coercive power over the
Legislature that curbs its power and independence, in violation of
the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``When even one legislator, by dint of economic circumstance, is
coerced into passing a budget that may require him or her to
sacrifice conscientiously held beliefs, then the entire process is
tainted,'' Justice Huttner wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The state budget is 51 days overdue, there are no serious
negotiations under way, and the Republicans who control the Senate
and the Democrats who run the Assembly are blaming each other for
the lack of progress. Republicans say Democrats have dawdled,
pinning their hopes on the court case, while Democrats have accused
the governor of waiting for them to crumble under the pressure of
working unpaid for months.
</P>
<P>
   In the icy atmosphere of the Capitol, where even civil talk
among the powers has become rare, the dispute over pay has deepened
the animosity between Pataki, who continues to collect his salary,
and the Assembly Democrats, including Speaker Sheldon Silver of
Manhattan. And it has heightened tensions between Silver, who did
not take part in the suit but looked favorably on it, and state
Senate Republican Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, who first proposed
the law withholding pay.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has proposed a $72.7 billion budget, while the Assembly
Democrats want to spend $2 billion to $4 billion more, and the
Senate Republicans' plan falls between the other two proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Cases turning on constitutional questions can sometimes be
appealed directly to the Court of Appeals, New York's highest
court, bypassing the Appellate Division, but it remains unclear
whether that will happen in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Huttner ruled that the withholding law, known as Chapter
635, violated both the separation of legislative and executive
powers implicit in the state constitution, and an explicit
provision barring any change in a legislator's pay during a
two-year term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chapter 635 flies in the face of that prohibition,'' he wrote.
``By enacting Chapter 635, those legislators who voted in favor
improvidently and unconstitutionally incapacitated the Legislature
from performing its duty as a representative body.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Richard Gottfried of Manhattan, who has taken the
lead in the suit, said: ``The court's analysis is quite plain, and
doesn't leave much room for argument. I know we're not going to get
paid, but I'm very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver could not be reached by telephone because he was
observing the Jewish holiday of Shabuoth.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno issued a statement saying: ``This entire issue can be
easily resolved by passing a budget. It is long past time that the
Assembly join with the Senate and the governor in adopting a
prudent, responsible budget that meets the needs of the people of
this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, Pataki's communications director, expressed
confidence that the law would be upheld. The plaintiffs' pursuit of
the case, she said, ``proves that they're not interested in doing
the people's business, only in getting paid.''
</P>
<P>
   The withholding law was rooted in the legislators' deep desire
for a pay raise, which Pataki had opposed for years. In December,
he relented and signed a bill increasing state elected officials'
salaries by 38 percent. Legislators now earn $79,500 a year, plus
stipends for leadership and committee positions that raise the
average close to $90,000. The governor earns $179,500.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki insisted that a withholding law be part of the price
the Legislature would pay for his agreement to the raise.
</P>
<P>
   In April, 11 Assembly and Senate Democrats who had voted against
the law, and three who first took office in January, after it was
enacted, sued to overturn it. Many Republican legislators are
sympathetic to their cause but have not spoken out, unwilling to
risk the ire of Bruno, Pataki or the public. And some lawmakers in
both parties voted for the law, believing that it would be struck
down in court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
