<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS IS 2 OVER, WITH A NEW HIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVONDALE, Pa. _ He hit some good shots, he hit some poor shots,
but for Jack Nicklaus, it was another mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   After a 10-month absence from competitive golf, and hip
replacement surgery on Jan. 27, Nicklaus returned Friday, shooting
a two-over-par 74 in the opening round of the Bell Atlantic
Classic. Nicklaus was tied for 37th place in the field of 77
golfers, eight strokes behind the first-round leader, Frank Conner
(66), who was two shots better than three others in the field.
</P>
<P>
   But for Nicklaus, Friday was about more than posting a score. It
was another step in his remarkably swift recovery, a return to
tournament golf weeks faster than his doctors had projected. And at
59, it was a chance to reacquaint himself with all the things he
missed during his recuperation _ the competition, the gallery, the
adrenaline rush of hitting a shot just the way he envisioned it.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus played down his expectations before Friday's round, but
the competitive fire that helped him win 18 professional majors
switched on when he stepped onto the first tee at Hartefeld
National Golf Club, surrounded by the largest gallery among the
tournament crowd estimated at 25,000. There were several highlights
during Nicklaus' round, which included three birdies, three bogeys
and a double-bogey. He had a 12-foot birdie putt at No. 2, a
terrific bunker shot at No. 8, which led to another birdie, and a
great approach shot at the par-4 No. 15, leading to a 12-foot
birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus' left hip was pain-free, despite his making his return
on one of the Senior PGA Tour's hilliest courses. Carts are
available for senior players, but Nicklaus walked the course, using
the cart only on two occasions to speed up play.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Nicklaus was not satisfied with his 74,
despite the circumstances. But that is part of what makes him Jack
Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to shoot a 65 Friday, but I would've liked
to,'' Nicklaus said. ``I did exactly what I expected to do. I
didn't break 70 in any of my practice rounds. My concentration and
focus was fine. My conditioning was fine. It's a start for me. My
body is better now than it has been in three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I hit some good chip shots, but as many as I had, some
were bound to be good. I'll get better, and I'll do better playing
myself back into shape than I will sitting at home. The galleries
weren't too big in my backyard. Playing in front of people, I don't
want to embarrass myself, so coming out will motivate me to work
harder. And I had been home long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, Nicklaus will be host of, and compete in, the
Memorial Tournament, and he will also play in June's U.S. Open.
Though Nicklaus doubts he will play in this year's British Open, he
plans to compete in the remaining two Senior Tour majors, the Ford
Senior Players Championship in June and the U.S. Senior Open in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus had been dealing with severe hip pain for more than two
years, but after his successful surgery, Nicklaus is optimistic
that he will be able to compete as often as he wishes. Nicklaus has
not won on the Senior Tour since 1996, but as recently as last year
he finished tied for sixth place at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Nicklaus shot a 38 on the front nine, including a
double-bogey on the par-3 No. 9, but he shot a 36 on the back nine,
and he was looking forward to Saturday's second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved the game, and I've always loved to play,''
Nicklaus said. ``I didn't think that I would be playing golf all my
life, but I am. But I also love to do other things. That's why the
hip operation was important, so I could do the things I love.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
