<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-PRINT PROVISIONS OF GUN BILL PLEASE FEDERAL OFFICIALS BEST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A handful of relatively little-noticed provisions in the crime
bill passed by the Senate on Thursday may do as much or more to
curb the flow of illegal guns to criminals and juveniles than the
much-debated measures that require child safety locks and
background checks at gun shows, senior Treasury Department
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   These provisions would make it easier to prosecute gun dealers
who sell firearms to straw purchasers on behalf of criminals,
increase sentences for people convicted of selling guns to
juveniles and require dealers at gun shows to record the serial
numbers of all guns they sell, including used guns.
</P>
<P>
   Currently gun dealers have to report only the sales of new guns,
making it very difficult for the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms to trace guns that have been resold and then used in
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Taken as a whole, the bill's provisions are incremental and
might not have prevented the recent school shootings that helped
propel its passage in the Senate. But the new enforcement measures,
combined with the bill's provision for mandatory background checks
of buyers at gun shows, would go a long way toward closing some of
the loopholes in gun laws that firearms agents, prosecutors and
judges have long said make them difficult to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these changes significantly increase law enforcement's
ability to identify illegal gun traffickers and attack the way the
guns are supplied to criminals and particularly to youth,'' said a
senior official at the Treasury Department, which oversees the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. ``Yesterday's vote was a
breakthrough, a real watershed.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Rifle Association, Bill Powers, did
not return repeated telephone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Rand, a lawyer for the Violence Policy Center in
Washington, a research and advocacy group, said she particularly
welcomed the imposition of background checks at gun shows, calling
the measure ``the most important step we've taken in regulating the
secondary sales market, where 40 percent of guns are sold.''
</P>
<P>
   The secondary market includes all sales by private individuals,
rather than Federally licensed firearms dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The number of gun shows has increased significantly in recent
years, to about 4,000 a year, especially after a 1986 law
effectively allowed individuals to sell large numbers of guns at
gun shows without being considered dealers, who need Federal
licenses. In practice, agents of the firearms bureau say, this has
allowed large numbers of guns to be sold to people without
recording the sales or the buyers' identities.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require a private or individual seller to get a
federally licensed dealer at the gun show to perform the background
check on a prospective buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Delfay, the president of the National Shooting Sports
Foundation, the largest gun industry trade organization,
acknowledged that allowing people to buy guns at gun shows without
them undergoing the same kind of inspection required at gun stores
was a loophole. But, he said, ``I think they fixed the loophole not
wisely, but too well.''
</P>
<P>
   Delfay said the new provision would require dealers at gun shows
to send a record of each sale to the firearms bureau. Dealers now
keep these forms and send them to the bureau only when they go out
of business.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle association and its supporters have worried that such
records could be the first step in a national gun registration
system, which they oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill contains several other provisions that did not
figure prominently in the debate on gun shows but may have an
impact on gun trafficking. One directs U.S. attorneys to focus more
attention on firearms enforcement, which is often overlooked by
federal prosecutors, firearms agents say.
</P>
<P>
   Another requires the attorney general to make regular reports on
gun prosecutions. At the moment, agents say, reporting is
impossible because the firearms bureau has been kept on such a
small budget by the gun lobby's supporters in Congress that it does
not have computers to enter data on prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Still another provision would ban the sale of guns to anyone
with a serious juvenile conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Garen Wintemute, director of the Violence Prevention
Research Program at the University of California at Davis, said a
study he conducted found that people who had been convicted as
juveniles were more likely to be charged with new crimes as adults
than handgun buyers with no criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   Pawnshops also were part of the debate. Used guns sold and
redeemed through pawnshops are believed to play a significant role
in firearms-related crimes. ``As you can imagine, a lot of
criminals have an occasion to pawn their guns,'' said Dennis
Henigan, a lawyer with Handgun Control.
</P>
<P>
   The pawnshop provision in the Senate bill, however, simply keeps
in place a requirement for background checks of anyone redeeming a
gun at a pawnshop, preventing the reopening of a loophole that
existed until a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision of the bill concerns gun safety.
</P>
<P>
   Gun safety advocates have long been concerned that some 150
children are killed each year when children pick up loaded guns and
accidentally shoot themselves or playmates. In response to
legislative pressure last year, most gun manufacturers voluntarily
agreed to include some type of safety device, such as a trigger
lock or a locking box, with each new gun they shipped.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate proposal, all new guns would have to be sold
with such devices.
</P>
<P>
   But there is debate even among gun-control advocates about the
effectiveness of the requirement. Handgun Control, for example,
supports it as sending an important safety message. Others believe
that those who store firearms unsafely or feel that they need ready
access to their weapons for self-protection will not use a lock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
