<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   30-YEAR TREASURY YIELDS DECLINE TO 5.75 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond declined this week from a
1999 high of 5.92 percent on May 14. It closed Friday at 5.75
percent. Treasury bond prices held onto strong gains as jitters
about emerging markets caused flight-to-quality buying while the
expiration of June options increased purchases of bond futures.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Federal Reserve Board policy-makers said that they
were leaning toward raising interest rates to slow economic growth
and curb inflation. Although they did not raise their interest-rate
target, which is now 4.75 percent, the warning is now official.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE BANKS REPORT BIG LOSSES
</P>
<P>
   Japan's eight largest banks have reported steep fiscal-year
losses. The poor performance largely reflected efforts by the banks
to clean their books by writing off bad loans. The losses, however,
were still larger than expected. The main reason is that the banks
must follow stricter rules for evaluating bad loans and creating a
deeper cushion of money in the event that good loans go bad.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT CONTINUES ITS DEPOSITIONS
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of America Online, Stephen Case, gave a deposition
as part of Microsoft's preparations for the rebuttal phase of the
antitrust trial against it, which is scheduled to resume June 1
after a three-month recess.
</P>
<P>
   FCC IS ORDERED TO REVIEW A RULING
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia Court of Appeals ordered the Federal
Communications Commission to review part of a 1997 decision that
resulted in lower long-distance phone bills for millions of
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER ISSUES LEAD STOCKS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell, led by computer-related shares, as investors
shifted from large companies that gained the most in recent years
to laggards, including small stocks and utilities. The
technology-laden Nasdaq composite index slumped 22.09 points, to
2,520.14. The Dow Jones industrial average declined 37.46 points,
to 10,829.28, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slipped
8.54 points, to 1,330.29.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORIAN SIGNS NEW BOOK CONTRACT
</P>
<P>
   The historian Simon Schama has signed a deal to publish his next
work of nonfiction with Talk Miramax Books, a division of Talk
Media, which is owned by Miramax Films. The book, titled
``Britannia,'' will be a history of Britain from the time before
the Roman invasion to the year 2000, and it will accompany a
12-part BBC series, directed by Schama, that ABC will broadcast in
the fall of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE PASSES SATELLITE TV BILL
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has approved legislation aimed at helping
satellite-television companies compete more effectively against
cable-TV providers by carrying local TV channels. The House has
already approved a different measure.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL GROUP OPPOSES AUDIT PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The United States' largest group of corporate financial officers
is lobbying against parts of a plan from an SEC-appointed committee
on how companies calculate their profits.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. JOINS LAWSUIT AGAINST VENCOR
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has joined a whistle-blower suit against
Vencor that accuses the struggling hospital and nursing-home
company of overbilling Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   AK STEEL TO ACQUIRE REST OF ARMCO
</P>
<P>
   AK Steel, the owner of the flat-rolled steel plants originally
built by Armco Steel, agreed to acquire the rest of the company,
now called Armco, for $842 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT SUISSE APOLOGIZES TO JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse Group apologized to Japanese regulators for
obstructing an investigation that threatens to stunt its growth
there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
