<HEADER>
A6752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEE22-COX     05-21 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fear clings to Kosovar
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Kelmend Hapciu is an ethnic Albanian refugee from
Pristina who has been living and working in Dayton _ very quietly _
for the past four months. Although members of his immediate family
are here, other relatives and friends remain in Kosovo or in the
refugee camps in Macedonia or Albania.
</P>
<P>
   He fears for their safety.
</P>
<P>
   He watches the news on television, scanning the faces of
refugees streaming across the border. Ask if he recognizes anyone,
and he sadly nods his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pristina is a small place, perhaps 250,000,'' he said. ``I
lived there all my life; it is possible that I know every one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hapciu asks that relatives who remain in Kosovo not be
identified in this article, fearing possible retribution by the
Serb police force. He has not heard from them since the bombing
began in March.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last month, however, Hapciu has been joined here by
his wife and two children, but their escape was harrowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they walked across the border they had to bribe a
policeman,'' he said. ``Just after they crossed the border, it was
closed.''
</P>
<P>
   A journalist who is currently on a fellowship at the Kettering
Foundation, Hapciu knows first-hand the terror imposed on his
country by the Serb army and police force.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Pristina, you never voluntarily said you were a
journalist,'' he said. ``You said you were unemployed or working in
some other profession. The journalists were among the Serbs' first
targets. The fear of being stopped by a policeman and asked if you
were a journalist was very real.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1982 to 1990, Hapciu worked as an international news editor
for the Albania daily newspaper, Rilindja. But in 1990, Serbian
President Slobodan Milosevic abolished Kosovo's autonomy and the
Serbian parliament banned the newspaper. It was shut down and its
property and printing presses seized. Hapciu moved to a weekly
newspaper, but it too was banned last December with the adoption of
the Serbian Law on Information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been going on for many, many years,'' he said.
``Albanians have learned to live with the fear. I have heard that
there are between 500 and 600 villages that have been completely
burned down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hapciu believes the NATO bombing campaign was necessary, but
that ground troops also should have been used to prevent the flood
of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing has been effective and it had to be done if you
were going to try to save the lives of the people,'' he said. ``One
can argue about the timing. It should have been done much sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Hapciu thinks the problem of Kosovo and the ethnic Albanians
should have been dealt with during talks that led to the Dayton
Peace Accords in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't tackled then and somebody had to pay the price,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hapciu has doubts about a possible settlement, even with Serbian
forces pulled back and a NATO-Russian peacekeeping force in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of Milosevic is going to be one of the crucial
questions that will decide that agreement,'' he said. ``But how can
you negotiate with a man you have called a war criminal?''
</P>
<P>
   Albanians, he said, have a strong attachment to their land, but
he does not see a quick return of the refugees, even with a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can only imagine what those people who fled are going
through,'' he said. ``I don't see a single one returning without a
very, very strong international force.''
</P>
<P>
   Hapciu said his wife and children talk constantly of Kosovo and
someday returning to Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I want to return as quickly as possible,'' he said.
``That is my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
