<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAN SANDERS, A TEACHER AND A LABOR LEADER, DIES AT 69  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Brazil)   By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dan Sanders, a former executive vice president of the
New York State United Teachers and a principal architect of the
teacher labor movement in the state, died on Thursday at the
Veterans Affairs Medical Center in the Bronx. He was 69 and had
lived in Putnam Valley, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He died of complications from Alzheimer's disease, said his
wife, Elaine.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, Sanders directed the New York State United
Teachers' legislative program in Albany and Washington. He also
served as a vice president of the American Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was born in the Bronx. He received a bachelor's degree
from the City College of New York in 1951 and a master's degree
from the City University of New York in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   From 1952 to 1962, he taught social studies in New York City and
the Lakeland school district, in Yorktown, N.Y. He was a founder of
the Northern Westchester Federation of Teachers, a forerunner of
the Lakeland Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1960s, as regional director of the Empire State
Federation of Teachers, he coordinated the negotiations for the
first collective bargaining agreements for teachers in New
Rochelle, Mount Vernon and Yonkers. In 1971 and 1972, as executive
director of the United Teachers of New York, he was a key figure in
negotiations leading to the merger of that organization with the
New York State Teachers Association, which produced the New York
State United Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected executive vice president of the organization in
1978. He retired nine years later.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is survived by his wife; his sons, Robert, of Geneva,
and William, of Recife, Brazil; a brother, Sidney, of Great Neck,
N.Y., and a sister, Ruth Mellet of San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
