A6758 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN--LOPEZ-HNS &LR;      05-21 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN--LOPEZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
LA using mirrors in bid to land team
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Probably all of us have those little projects we've been putting
off _ maybe some landscaping, adding a deck or even a Jacuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   But it never fails. There's never time to get started and every
time we look up there's not so much as a weed pulled.
</P>
<P>
   We mention this because if we were smart we would tell our
Household Commissioners (i.e. significant others) we are much
further along than it appears.
</P>
<P>
   Much like Los Angeles has been telling the NFL, there's lots
going on behind the scenes. It will all come together. Trust us.
And if you think nothing's happening, you're just not looking deep
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the NFL expansion meetings in March, when Bob
McNair's sure-thing NFL bid was spurned in hopes of Los Angeles
getting its act together, the league has wanted a commitment of
public support from LA.
</P>
<P>
   But it's just not there. The response from LA's bid leaders _
Eli Broad, Ed Roski and Michael Ovitz _ has been that the support
is there if you look hard enough. The LA bidders point to
infrastructure the city provided long ago in the form of parking
spaces in the Coliseum area and street, utility and underground
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, LA bidders say it's more than $120 million worth of
support. Eureka! Let the bulldozers roll.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that also means our patio projects are only a
heartbeat away from popping up before our eyes, too.
</P>
<P>
   Using LA's reasoning, delivery trucks will have to park in our
cul-de-sacs. That's infrastructure, baby, at least a couple-hundred
thou worth. Certainly, Home Depot trucks will have to drive on
highways. That puts us at least another couple of million ahead of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Here we thought we weren't making progress. Here we thought Los
Angeles was as unprepared and ambiguous today as it was in March,
when Roski announced to many a raised eyebrow, ``We're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, they're in the weeds as much as our back yards.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners will convene again Monday, with some of the meeting
in Atlanta dedicated to hearing progress reports on LA's bid. The
NFL wants solid business models and site-development plans laid out
in detail. It wants to see bonds, public money.
</P>
<P>
   Even if commissioner Paul Tagliabue again ignores the gaping
holes in the LA bid, even if he continues to bend over backward for
Los Angeles _ extending the Sept. 15 deadline for LA will be Tags'
next move _ owners will continue to be played like fools. McNair
and his locked-in bid will continue to play a frustrating waiting
game.
</P>
<P>
   But at what point does it fall apart for LA? The reasons for
wanting Los Angeles have not changed and they are good ones. It is,
after all, Los Angeles. It has 20 million potential television
viewers and is a worldwide media hub.
</P>
<P>
   But since the March meetings in Phoenix, Los Angeles not only
has failed to answer NFL questions, it has raised more.
</P>
<P>
   When NFL officials recently visited LA to examine progress,
bidders included some 9,000 parking spaces on the USC campus as
part of its required 26,000 spaces necessary for the bid. The NFL
deemed those spaces inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, at next week's meetings, Ovitz will detail an elaborate
plan to construct 10,000 parking spaces _ underground _ at an
estimated cost of $100 million. No one has volunteered to chip in
that $100 million. Details. And presumably, Ovitz will skim over
that San Andreas fault thing under LA, too.
</P>
<P>
   But is this even Ovitz's project to take over? When Ovitz
dropped his Carson, Calif., idea and joined Broad and Roski in the
Coliseum proposal weeks ago, it was hailed as a victory.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the NFL will not give the bid to a Broad-Roski-Ovitz
team. It will support only one side or the other, meaning
Broad-Roski is fighting Ovitz as much as ever. They're just now
fighting over the same turf.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the issue of public support. The NFL realizes the
huge flaw in LA's argument that existing infrastructure counts
toward the bid. If there was such a thing, we all could claim
multimillion-dollar patio projects.
</P>
<P>
   NFL executive Roger Goodell, who has aspirations of succeeding
Tagliabue as commissioner and once was LA's loudest trumpeter, is
distancing himself from the LA bid. The NFL wants to see new, solid
Los Angeles dollars committed to the project.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated cost of the LA project is nearly $1 billion. No
NFL owner likely will support that kind of privately funded
project, because they realize it is cost-prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue wants the NFL in Los Angeles so bad, he can't see
straight. But you have to figure someday the owners will. And they
just might come out of the weeds in support of Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
