Emmett Newsome in the kitchen with his lottery number picking
sheets. Newsome, who works at a nearby powder-coating plant, has
developed his own system of tracking past winning numbers to
determine patterns. ``I see here that 994 has come out three times
on Sunday,'' he says. ``I think that 994 is going to come back
today.'' (Mike Peters/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 23 --
BIZ-PROFILE-TRUJILLO, 5-21 -- Venturing away from the sidelines at
the corporate dance, Solomon D. Trujillo, chairman and chief
executive of US West, is leading his company into a merger with
another telecommunications giant, Global Crossing Ltd. ``This
merger brings together the first mile, the last mile and everything
in between,'' says Trujillo, 47. ``It opens up a new world of
advanced communications services to local customers across the
globe.'' (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) DEARBORN, Mich. -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 23
-- RENAULT-NISSAN, 5-21 -- Ford's well-traveled executives have
been a big asset in Japan. Mazda President James E. Miller's
predecessor, Henry D.G. Wallace, a Scot, now runs Ford's
Asia-Pacific operations. (Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) STUDIO CITY, Calif. -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 23 -- BIZ-ANIMATION-FILMS-2, 5-21 -- Thad Beier, left, and Dan
Chuba, both of Hammerhead Productions, say their independent
production company is expanding at a feverish pace, working on
feature films, special effects and Internet sales. ``The studios
are leveraged out,'' says Chuba. ``But people still need the
product. Someone has to do it, and it's creating all sorts of
opportunities for independent players like us.'' (Kim Kulish/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 23 --
TEENAGE-CONSULTANTS, 5-21 -- In 1997, Lynn Liran, left, and Kara
Hamilton were hired by the DuPont Co. to contribute to a panel of
teen-agers that the company had assembled as part of a $30 million
promotion of its Lycra fabric. Like a growing number of companies,
including Levis and M&AMP;M/Mars, DuPont is hiring teen-agers as
consultants. (Rebecca Cooney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
23 -- HAMPTONS-CELEBS-LAND-3, 05-21 -- Potato fields, like this one
on the South Fork of Long Island, are being transformed into
rolling hills, ridges and ponds. ``Everyone knows it's flat out
here,'' says Molly Ferrer, a real estate broker for Sotheby's in
Southampton. ``You've got to pay for topography. It's a way of
showing you have lots of money.'' (Maxine Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
23 -- HAMPTONS-CELEBS-LAND-2, 05-21 -- Christopher H. Browne mapped
out hills and ponds for his 18 acres of Hampton's woodlands even
before planning his house. The reinvention of the generally flat
topography of the South Fork into rolling hills, ridges and ponds
is the Hampton's newest trend in landscaping. (Maxine Hicks/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
23 -- HAMPTONS-CELEBS-LAND-1, 05-21 -- Workmen excavating the
backyard of a property to build slate walls and a deep pool. This
is an example of the area's latest trend: transforming the
generally flat topography of the South Fork into rolling hills,
ridges and ponds, in some cases landscapes more typical of an
estate in Greenwich, Conn. (Maxine Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 23 --
NITEOUT-KIMHEIRSTON, 05-21 -- Uniting art with its new owners, Kim
Heirston bids at Sotheby's. ``Some people don't like the auction
room,'' says Ms. Heirston, 35, an art adviser who coaches the rich
on how to best spend their fortunes on fine art. ``They don't want
people to know their business, or they're afraid they'll go
crazy.'' (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 23 --
NY-ORCHARD-FASHION-2, 05-21 -- A hair scrunchy inspired a Ben
Sturgill blouse design, one of the fashions greeted boisterously at
the second annual Orchard Street Style Slam. Sturgill, one of six
stylists featured at this year's Slam, married clothes from both
old and new Orchard Street shops. (Frances Roberts/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 23 --
NY-ORCHARD-FASHION-1, 05-21 -- Fashions parade down the runway in
Manhattan's Lower East Side during the Second Annual Orchard Street
Style Slam. This unusual fashion show was the brainchild of Erica
Lively, whose Timtoum store, opened here in 1997, sells skateboard
clothes and vinyl records. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 23 --
CARS-STAMPS, 5-21 -- PSSST! Wanna buy a nice old car - cheap? The
Post Office has, from left, some Model T Fords, half a Duesenberg
and some well-finned 1950s models including a turquoise '57
Chevrolet Bel Air cream puff, all going for 32 or 33 cents. The
United States Postal Service is issuing a series of ``Celebrate the
Century'' stamps, 15 for each decade, with each stamp highlighting
a different bit of history. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
23 -- BIZ-ANIMATION-FILMS, 5-21 -- Carl Rosendahl of Pacific Data
Images, left, says big Hollywood studios have lost their
distinctive identities. ``The identity of the studios used to be
strong in the '30s and '40s,'' he says. ``MGM did musicals, another
did monster movies, Disney did Walt's movies. But now they don't
have it. Disney isn't even doing its own best work.'' (Dan
Krauss/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 23 --
ABOUT-CARS-MAXIMA-2, 5-21 -- The Nissan Maxima received a major
face lift along with big changes under the skin. The styling of the
Japanese-built 2000 Maxima, though no match for the cool postmodern
designs coming from Europe, will turn a few heads. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- May 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 23 --
ABOUT-CARS-MAXIMA-1, 5-21 -- The Nissan Maxima received a major
face lift along with big changes under the skin. The Japanese-built
2000 Maxima is a world-class, no-compromise sport sedan and a
marvelous bargain to boot at $21,569. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- May 21, 1999 --
ALFRED-APPRECIATE-BOS, 05-21 -- Faye Dunaway stands with William
Alfred in the doorway of his home in 1996. Alfred, a playwright,
poet, scholar and Harvard College professor whose observations
about Irish-American life graced Broadway, died at his home on
Wednesday. He was 76. ``I just latched onto him and wouldn't let
go,'' Ms. Dunaway said in a 1996 interview with the Boston Globe.
``He taught me how to work.'' (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- May 21, 1999 -- OBIT-ROBINSON-SCHWARTZ-B&AMP;W,
05-20 -- Betty Robinson Schwartz poise at the starting line in
1929, one year after the Amsterdam Olympics. Mrs. Schwartz, who in
1928 as a 16-year-old high school junior became the first woman to
win an Olympic gold medal in track and field, died Tuesday in
Colorado. She was 87. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) KELLER, Texas -- May 21, 1999 -- SCHOOL-COLA-2, 05-20 --
A student at Keller High School walks by two Coca-Cola machines in
the hall of the school. With 50 million children of school age
spending at least $50 billion each year, some companies are
interested in capturing that market early through exclusive deals
like the one Coke has signed with Keller. (Mark Graham/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEWARK, N.J. -- May 21, 1999 -- SCHOOL-COLA-1, 05-20 --
Dan DeRose, at right, a marketing consultant, addresses a Newark
school committee on how best to structure an exclusive soft-drink
contact. One of the best-known consultants in a rapidly growing
specialty, DeRose, who is based in Pueblo, Colo., says he has
obtained exclusive contracts, or is negotiating them, for 63 school
systems nationwide. (Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times Photo)
</P>
