<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Semifinals: Pick a goalie, please
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NHL playoffs are down to four teams. Maybe that
should be, down to four goalies.
</P>
<P>
   The goaltender is the centerpiece of any hockey team, and this
season the NHL is left with its most elite conference championships
in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often easy to pick a series winner as you look at
strengths and weaknesses of each team. And then sometimes you find
yourself just saying, `Well, that team has the better goalie,'''
said Ken Dryden, Toronto Maple Leafs president and a Hall of Fame
goalie. ``But this year, it's hard to find a difference in the
teams because of their goaltending.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference finals that begin tonight, Colorado's
Patrick Roy faces Ed Belfour of Dallas. Roy is the league's
all-time leader in playoff wins. Belfour started for a team that
allowed the fewest goals this season and earlier in the playoffs
had a shutout string over seven periods.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eastern Conference finals, Buffalo's Dominik Hasek
opposes Toronto's Curtis Joseph. Last year, Hasek reaffirmed his
status as the globe's best goalie after leading an undermanned
Czech Republic team to the Olympic gold medal. Joseph, who signed
with the Leafs as a free agent, is second only to Hasek with a
playoff saves percentage of .930.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas led the league in wins, and Colorado is coming off four
consecutive playoffs wins over two-time defending champion Detroit.
They generally are considered more talented and deeper than either
Buffalo or Toronto. But because a goalie can have a greater impact
on his team than any single athlete in the four major sports,
handicapping this ``Frozen Four'' is problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goaltending is an odd position, in that it's so important
whether the goalie is good or not good,'' said Dryden, who won five
Vezina Trophies as the league's best netminder and played on six
Stanley Cup teams with Montreal. ``The closest thing you can come
to that is the pitcher in baseball. If he's a 20-game winner or a
four-game winner, he has great influence on how your team does.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, a finalist this year for the Vezina and Hart (MVP)
awards, has led a eam of modest talent to the conference finals for
the second year in a row. But he has been overshadowed of late by
Roy, who made 71 saves in the Games 5 and 6 wins over Detroit and
stopped 210 of 224 (.937) in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we feel we have the best in the game, especially
this time of year,'' Avalanche center Joe Sakic said, alluding to
Roy's record 107 playoff wins. ``But it's no coincidence that the
four best goalies are all in the finals right now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
