</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CAPSULES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playoff capsules
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service ATLANTA _ WESTERN CONFERENCE
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO VS. DALLAS
</P>
<P>
   _ Resumes: Colorado finished the regular season 44-28-10, first
in the Northwest Division, and has eliminated San Jose (4-2) and
Detroit (4-2) in the playoffs. Dallas finished 51-19-12, first in
the Pacific Division, and has eliminated Edmonton (4-0) and St.
Louis (4-2).
</P>
<P>
   _ Season series: Colorado won 2-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the '90s: Colorado won the conference finals over Detroit
and the Stanley Cup over Florida in 1995-96 and lost in the
conference finals to Detroit in 1996-97; Dallas lost to Detroit in
the conference finals last year. As the Minnesota North Stars, they
defeated Edmonton in the conference finals in 1990-91 and lost to
Pittsburgh for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   _ Update: With four consecutive wins over the defending Cup
champions, some perceive the Avs as the favorites in this series.
They are deep at forward with the addition of Theo Fleury (five
playoff goals) and return of Valeri Kamenski from an injury. Goalie
Patrick Roy is playing as well as in Colorado's title year, making
71 saves in the last two games against Detroit and stopping 210 of
224 (.937) in the series. Dallas has been just as strong in goal,
with Ed Belfour, but has struggled offensively. Brett Hull, demoted
from the Stars' top line during the St. Louis series, was back with
center Mike Modano in Game 6 and responded by setting up Dallas's
tying and winning goals in a 2-1 OT win. Hull's goal scoring will
be needed in this series for the Stars to keep pace. Dallas coach
Ken Hitchcock said five of his players were bothered this week by a
viral infection, but he did not identify them and expected all to
be ready for the opener.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quote, unquote: ``We've beaten the `B' team but we haven't
beaten the `A' team.'' _ Hitchcock, noting that the Stars' only win
this year came before Colorado's second-half surge and acquisition
of Fleury.
</P>
<P>
   _ By the numbers: 6-0. Colorado's road record in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: Colorado in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO VS. TORONTO
</P>
<P>
   _ Resumes: Buffalo finished the regular season 37-28-17, fourth
in the Northeast Division, and has eliminated Ottawa (4-0) and
Boston (4-2) in the playoffs. Toronto finished 45-30-17, second in
the Northeast Division, and has eliminated Philadelphia (4-2) and
Pittsburgh (4-2).
</P>
<P>
   _ Season series: Buffalo won 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the '90s: Buffalo lost to Washington in the conference
finals last year. Toronto lost in the conference finals in 1993 to
Los Angeles and 1994 to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   _ Update: These teams have had a long-running border war but are
meeting in the playoffs for the first time. Toronto was the
league's highest-scoring team this year but managed just 10 goals
in five meetings with the Sabres, with Dominik Hasek stopping 153
of 163 shots. Hasek leads playoff goalies with a .942 saves
percentage, but the Sabres also have been getting excellent play
from center Michael Peca (11 points), who has scored the first goal
in three postseason games. The Leafs are far deeper offensively
than Buffalo, and goalie Curtis Joseph (.930, 1.81 goals against in
12 playoff starts) has been nearly as strong as Hasek. But the
Sabres appear to have a huge edge on the power play, having
converted 10 of 44 chances (22.7 percent) in the postseason. The
Leafs have struggled at 12-for-57 (10.5 percent) and were only
1-for-23 (4.3) this year against Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quote, unquote: ``I barely remember being in the organization.
I had years of therapy to erase that from my memory.'' _ Buffalo
winger Dixon Ward, who played 22 games with Toronto in 1994-95 and
later was released.
</P>
<P>
   _ By the numbers: 32. Number of years since the Maple Leafs last
appeared in the Stanley Cup finals. They defeated Montreal in an
all-Canadian series in 1966-67.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prediction: Toronto in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
