<HEADER>
A6772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES22-CO     05-21 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earnhardt Inc. grabs Andrews for crew chief
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Paul Andrews' unemployment on the Winston Cup
circuit was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, fired three days ago as crew chief for Jeremy
Mayfield's No. 12 Ford, was hired Friday by Dale Earnhardt Inc.
Andrews, a 12-year veteran on the circuit, will head the No. 1
Chevrolet of Steve Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw (Andrews) in the unemployment line, grabbed him by the
arm and told him we needed to go talk to Dale,'' Park said. ``We
had him hired in two minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, 42, worked at Penske-Kranefuss Racing since December
1996. The Maine native spent nine seasons with the team formed by
the late Alan Kulwicki before joining Penske-Kranefuss, where he
also worked with driver Geoffrey Bodine.
</P>
<P>
   While with Kulwicki, Andrews won five races and the 1992 Winston
Cup title. This will his first time working on a Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen very quickly in this sport and I'm not just
talking about the action on the track,'' Andrews said. ``One of the
first phone calls Wednesday was from (Park's team). I visited DEI
Wednesday and talked to Dale for a long time and he made me feel
wanted again.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, 31, of Islip, N.Y., is 31st in Winston Cup standings after
11 races, trailing leader Dale Jarrett by 756 points. Park hasn't
had a top-10 finish this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez lands a job
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Lopez, who was fired as Park's crew chief May 11, was
hired by Darrell Waltrip's No. 66 Ford team on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, 36, of Verdun, France, worked with Waltrip last year when
he was a substitute driver for the injured Park for 13 races.
Waltrip had a fifth and sixth-place finish in the Earnhardt-owned
car, his best finishes of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Philippe earlier this year,'' Waltrip said. ``I
said, `Now, look, I'm not trying to lure you away by any means
because we've got a lot
</P>
<P>
   of work to do here and I don't even know if you'd want to come
to work for us right now.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But things didn't work out well (with Park) this year and he
quit. When he did that, I said, `I know who I'm going to get for my
crew chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Carter, who co-owns Waltrip's car, was the interim crew
chief after Donnie Disharoon quit after only three events.
</P>
<P>
   Bad deal for Burton
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton didn't finish qualifying after he missed his pit
stall during the mandatory two-tire change stop in Friday night's
The Winston qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, making his fourth start in the all-star event, was
disqualified and will start 20th. After Burton missed his stall,
car owner Bill Davis waved him by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had a tire going down,'' Burton said. ``I about
lost it going into (turn) 1 and I about lost it going into 3.
Coming down pit road, I was afraid to shift down and the rear tire
was hopping. It wasn't a tire, so I'm not sure what the deal was.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd also had problems on pit road, qualifying 19th after
he spun out after a 10.742-second stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot more respect for the drag (racing) boys,'' Rudd
said. ``I stayed on the concrete trying to build speed and it was
working good, but I got my right-rear tire just off the edge of the
concrete. Next thing I know, the thing just did a loop.''
</P>
<P>
   Said enters The Winston Open
</P>
<P>
   Craftsman Truck driver Boris Said, a former road-course racer,
entered tonight's The Winston Open in a car co-owned by Winston Cup
regular Ernie Irvan. If all goes well, Irvan-Sirmo Racing may enter
the car in next week's Coca-Cola 600.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking it one event at a time and learning as much as
we can,'' crew chief Frank Kimmel said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
