<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-SULLIVAN-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES' GM REBUFFS SCHILLING'S ACCUSATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Philadelphia Phillies general manager Ed
Wade was upset with pitcher Curt Schilling's comments last week
that the club's ownership was not committed to winning.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling said the Phillies need one more big-name pitcher to
get the team over the top, but the club was unwilling to acquire
one. Wade strongly disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to upgrade our rotation since the end of
last season, and we will continue to try,'' Wade said Friday, ``We
haven't turned down any trade for starting pitchers because of
dollars. We've asked about every pitcher Curt mentioned \RBrad
Radke and Kenny Rogers\S and quite a few who he hasn't mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trading for starting pitching is difficult, not because of
dollars, but because there aren't very many available pitchers, and
the talent that the other club is looking for is either too
significant to give up, or you just don't have the right match.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade isn't saying anything that Doug Melvin hasn't already said.
There isn't much starting pitching out there.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling is right when he said the Phillies need another
starting pitcher. But Wade thought it was a little ridiculous when
Schilling criticized them for not pursuing Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Astros made a huge offer to try and keep him with club,''
Wade said. ``But Johnson chose to sign with his hometown team, the
Diamondbacks. Where does Curt think the Phillies would have been in
that pursuit, coming off a 75-win season?''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies have done a good job getting younger and better.
For too long they tried to stay with the veterans that caught
lightning in a bottle in 1993, and they suffered for it. But of the
25 players who were with the team at the end of the 1997 season,
only seven remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got tired of spinning our wheels trying to keep the 1993
club alive,'' Wade said. ``One of the reasons that Curt wants us to
go out and get someone is that we have come pretty far, pretty
quickly. But it's wrong to say we have not been committed to
improving the team.''
</P>
<P>
   They have a pretty good nucleus of young players, including
infielders Scott Rolen, Desi Relaford, Marlon Anderson and Rico
Brogna, outfielders Bob Abreau and Doug Glanville and catcher Mike
Lieberthal. They also have two young pitchers who have a chance,
Carlton Loewer and Paul Byrd. But they need one more starter, and
they're hurting at closer.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing the job will be hard, and what the Phillies do with
Schilling could make the difference. He's obviously the No. 1
starter that every contender needs, and the Phillies are reluctant
to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   But if Wade made a shrewd trade that brought the right package
of young players, it could be just the deal that finishes a
well-done rebuilding effort.
SPOTLIGHT ON CAL RIPKEN JR.
Bill Janscha Cal Ripken Jr. is batting .333 with three homers and
eight RBI since coming off the disabled list.
Time on disabled list refreshing for Ripken
Cal Ripken Jr. deserves at least one mulligan.
</P>
<P>
   Way too many people were suggesting he should retire after he
went on the disabled list with a bad back last month. But Ripken
may end up fooling everybody.
</P>
<P>
   He's been playing great since his return, hitting .333 with
three homers and eight runs batted in going into the weekend series
with the Rangers. He's also showing much more mobility in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken's time off not only allowed him to rehabilitate a bad
back that's been bothering him for several years, but it also
allowed him time to heal the pain of his father's death in spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a silver lining to the injury,'' Ripken said. `It
gave me time to heal mentally and physically. I jumped right back
into baseball because I thought it was the best thing to do after
my dad's funeral. Maybe it was a little too soon. Maybe I should
have taken a little time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a matter of being able to concentrate and see the
ball clearly. \RHitting\S requires a good, clear head and good
focus. The things that bother you affect your focus. I'm playing
with a clear head right now, and it feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Chasing DiMaggio Never say a record will never be
broken. Cal Ripken Jr. proved no record is unreachable. But here's
why Joe DiMaggio's 56-game streak is so incredible.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez's hitting streak came to an end after 30 games,
making him only one of 37 players in major-league history to hit
safely in at least that many consecutive games. The second-longest
streak of his career is 23 games.
</P>
<P>
   Add them together and they equal 53, three short of DiMaggio.
Stan Musial, one of the greatest hitters of all time, had a 30-game
hitting streak in 1950 and a 24-game streak in 1952, a combined two
short of DiMaggio.
\Nsubheds:Coors power surge Some numbers from the Reds' 24-12
victory against the Rockies on Wednesday at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams combined for 81 total bases, a major-league record.
The old record was 79, accomplished by St. Louis (41) and
Philadelphia (38) on May 11, 1923.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' 15 extra-base hits were one short of the National
League record.
</P>
<P>
   The teams scored 36 runs, the most in Coors Field history.
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined for nine homers that traveled 3,604 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds tied a 97-year-old franchise record with 28 hits and
amassed the second-highest total of runs in franchise history;
their 55 total bases were a club record and three shy of the
big-league mark.
\Nsubheds:Short hops
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Devil Rays have the first pick in the amateur
draft and are looking at three players: Josh Hamilton, a
pitcher/outfielder from a high school in Raleigh, N.C.; Robbie
Beckett, a pitcher from Spring; and Eric Munson, a catcher from the
University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Three young players have the Royals over .500: center fielder
Carlos Beltran, second baseman Carlos Febles and right fielder
Jermaine Dye, who is finally starting to hit as expected two years
after being acquired from the Atlanta Braves. They're also getting
good pitching from Jose Rosado, an all-star in 1997 who had fallen
off, and Jeff Suppan, a former top prospect from the Red Sox who
was a disappointment in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were off Monday, and yes, Kevin Brown did take the
Fox company jet back to Florida to see his family.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians are on a pace to score 1,199 runs. The
record is 1,067 by the 1931 New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Mets pitcher Rick Reed was miffed when Brewers manager Phil
Garner accused him of scuffing the baseball. Said Reed, ``I don't
even know how to cheat. The only thing I can say is if that guy
thinks I'm cheating, he's got the wrong stats. I came in with a
7.48 ERA.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams are showing less patience with struggling young players.
The latest was Expos first baseman Brad Fullmer, who was sent back
to Triple A last season. Said manager Felipe Alou, whose entire
team was struggling: ``Maybe some of the guys should look at it as
a message.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays have good young pitching, but they need
much more from David Wells, 36, who is 1-4 with a 7.68 ERA in his
past six starts. Those contract-extension talks suddenly went on
pause.
</P>
<P>
