<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blister puts Hudek on DL
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To make room for Bruce Chen on the roster, the Braves
put reliever John Hudek on the 15-day disabled list Friday because
of a blister on his pitching hand. The move allows Atlanta to keep
Justin Speier, who has pitched more consistently than Hudek.
</P>
<P>
   Hudek, who is out of minor-league options, said he has no
problem with the move and will agree to go to the minor leagues for
a rehabilitation assignment as soon as he can pitch without wearing
a bandage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they had to make a decision with three guys _ (Kevin)
McGlinchy, Speier and me,'' said Hudek, who hasn't pitched in a
week because of the blister. ``McGlinchy can't go with what his
role is; Speier, he can go more innings right now. ... It worked
out. It's fine. There could be other things, worse things.''
</P>
<P>
   Since coming to the Braves from the Reds in the Mark Wohlers
deal on April 16, Hudek has been the last reliever out of the
bullpen. He has a 9.35 ERA in eight games for the Braves, highest
on the staff. He has eight walks in 8 2/3 innings pitched. Speier
has a 3.65 ERA with only four walks in 12 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pitching so far has been either real good or bad,'' Hudek
said. ``The margin of error for me is very minor.''
</P>
<P>
   This will buy him some time to prove to the Braves that he can
get back to the way he pitched last year for the Reds when he went
4-2 with a 2.43 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Hudek said when asked if he'd go on a
minor-league assignment. ``What else am I going to say? It'll
benefit both of us. They can see when I'm getting back and it'll
benefit me to see hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs acquire closer Aguilera from Twins
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs traded two minor-league pitchers to bring Twins veteran
closer Rick Aguilera to Chicago and bolster a shaky bullpen that
recently lost closer Rod Beck to the disabled list with a bone spur
in his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs gave up right-handers Kyle Lohse, 20, and Jason Ryan,
23, to bring in Aguilera, a 37-year-old with a 3-1 record, a 1.27
ERA and six saves in 17 games for Minnesota this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were one of the teams Twins general manager Terry
Ryan contacted regarding Aguilera, trying to unload his $3.25
million salary, but Braves general manager John Schuerholz said his
discussions with Ryan never entered the ``meaningful'' stage, that
player names were never exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not motivated to do what they were asking,''
Schuerholz said. ``We didn't see there was a need and there has
become less of a need as our bullpen has shown what it can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood finding his old form
</P>
<P>
   Since his bad outing in Los Angeles when he gave up four runs in
3 1/3 innings to fall to 1-2, Kevin Millwood has been a different
pitcher _ a lot like his old self.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had to be better than I was last year,'' said
Millwood, who was 17-8 with a 4.08 ERA and moved into the No. 4
slot in the rotation this year. ``If I go out and pitch the way I
did last year, I don't see why I have to ask anymore out of myself.
Last year was a pretty good year. Nobody's going to be happy doing
the same thing every year, but maybe I was putting a little undue
pressure on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, 3-3 with a 3.60 ERA, makes his ninth start tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
