<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-GRADS-ART-335&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLETON MASSACRE ECHOES IN COMMENCEMENT SPEECHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YONKERS, N.Y. _ The school massacre in Littleton, Colo., last
month has emerged as one of the more poignant reference points this
commencement season.
</P>
<P>
   In her address on Friday celebrating diversity, Joanne Braxton,
a professor of American studies at the College of William and Mary,
told Sarah Lawrence graduates that the atmosphere of ostracism that
the two gunmen had felt was something very foreign to this
Westchester County campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Littleton, Colorado, would never happen here, because it's
safe to be different,'' said Dr. Braxton, who graduated from Sarah
Lawrence in 1972. ``Maintain that difference. Keep all the
passionate discussion when you leave here.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous speakers are weaving recent shooting incidents at
American high schools into their commencement talks, from Attorney
General Janet Reno at Wilkes University to Bill Bradley, the
Democratic presidential candidate, who spoke of ``the pressure on
our families and our children'' at the University of North Carolina
at Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In a commencement address at American University, the filmmaker
Barry Levinson warned about blaming television and the media for
the shootings, yet acknowledged that ``television breeds a certain
degree of cynicism.''
</P>
<P>
   In her speech on Friday, Dr. Braxton used Littleton as a
metaphor for the dangers of conformity and intolerance. ``The
violence in Littleton, Colorado, is symptomatic of larger disorders
in our society,'' said Dr. Braxton, who has written extensively
about the trans-Atlantic slave trade and is co-editor of ``Wild
Women in the Whirlwind: Afra-American Culture and the Contemporary
Literary Renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The embrace of diversity must form in order to make homes and
families safe,'' she said. ``We must communicate, not isolate. If
we must be intolerant of something, let us be intolerant of
intolerance itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 330 undergraduate and graduate students received degrees
Friday at Sarah Lawrence's 70th commencement exercises.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Juilliard School
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When introducing Patrick Stewart at Juilliard's 94th
commencement exercises on Friday, Joseph Polisi, the school's
president, gave details about Stewart's distinguished career as a
Shakespearean actor. But he could not resist quoting the famous
lines of Capt. Jean-Luc Picard of the Starship Enterprise,
Stewart's best-known role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make it so,'' Polisi said to the cheering audience at Alice
Tully Hall at Lincoln Center. ``I wish I could say that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to the graduating class of 220 actors, musicians
and dancers, Stewart said: ``Audiences want to be moved, excited,
terrified, amused, shocked, changed. That is our job as artists _
to give people an experience they will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the recipients of honorary degrees was the choreographer
Bill T. Jones, who burst into an impromptu dance step after
receiving his Doctor of Fine Arts degree, inspiring the other
honorees _ Peter Paine, the philanthropist, and Harvey
Lichtenstein, outgoing president of the Brooklyn Academy of Music _
to do the same as they returned to their seats. Beverly Sills, the
president of Lincoln Center, who also got an honorary degree,
refrained because of a broken toe.
</P>
<P>
   Under a cloudless sky, at a reception after the ceremonies on
the theater balcony, Stewart stood for photographs with graduates
and their families. As the crowd thickened around the actor, Polisi
whispered to him, ``I really do wish I could say, `Make it so' the
way you do, you know.'' Stewart answered, ``I wanted to say it in
my speech, but I thought you did it so well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
