A6793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTO22-COX     05-21 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTO22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill lets lottery winners collect kitty all at once
 &HT;    By Paul Owers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The payment possibilities for Florida
Lottery winners, while not endless, certainly are improving.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush signed a bill last week making Florida the 19th
state to allow winners the option of signing over future lottery
payments to third-party investors for immediate cash.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, about 500 Florida Lottery winners have had no choice
but to accept jackpots paid out over 20 or 30 years _ a real bummer
if a winner was, say, 75 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Congress gave states the OK to offer lump-sum
awards, but once winners selected a payment option, they were stuck
with it. The state legislation, which takes effect in September,
now lets recent and future winners change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those who collect the kitty all at once get about
half the jackpot because the lump sum doesn't include interest
earned over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK, I'll take the cash up front,'' said Richard
Ellington of West Palm Beach, who bought 20 tickets this week in
hopes of winning tonight's $66 million jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd invest it myself, pay off a few debts and maybe retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Even given a choice, about 40 percent of the winners since
November still have opted for the deferred payments, said Ed
George, spokesman for the Florida Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there could be a change in their situation _ like a
divorce _ and this gives them more flexibility,'' said Robin
Shapiro, general counsel for Singer Asset Finance, a Boca
Raton-based company that has been pushing for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Asset has worked with lottery winners in other states,
financing the amounts however they choose. It profits if the
interest rate at which it sells pooled jackpots is less than the
rate it pays to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   States had no idea of the problems the previous payment
restrictions might cause when they drafted the lottery statutes,
Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no winners (to learn from),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Rep. George Bense (R-Panama City),
creates several safeguards, such as requiring winners to get a
spouse's consent and a judge's approval before selling future
lottery payments to third parties.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
