<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-SWEATSHOPS-NYT     05-21 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-SWEATSHOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IMAGES SHOW THE REALITIES BEHIND LABELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ivelisse Reyes once thought designer labels conferred
instant status. Now she has been thinking about the status of the
people behind the labels. She realized that some big-name labels
rely on poorly paid, no-name workers to make shoes and shirts
coveted by her classmates at Manhattan's High School of Graphic
Communication Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' Ivelisse said. ``Image is such a big deal. How you
look. What you wear. Inside every one of us is some little vanity.
We like to look good. We're just concerned about what we wear and
we forget who made it and where it came from.''
</P>
<P>
   It has become harder to forget, thanks to the images she and 41
other high school students recently created. With help from
teachers and union officials, they visited several local sweatshops
to find the grime behind the glamour. The results of their own
labors now hang inside a gallery at the headquarters of 1199, the
health-care workers union, which helped create the show.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, as people packed the gallery for the show's
opening, some of the students recalled the factories they had seen
a few streets away in the garment district. The thought of one
factory that Lisa Bertorelli visited made her grimace at the
recollection of worn-out workers and decrepit, stench-filled
hallways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down one block is Modell's or Nike,'' said Lisa, a student at
Art and Design High School. ``Up the block you have a sweatshop.
You see where the money is. Then you see the people making the
clothes aren't making the money. Everybody comes here for a
so-called better life. Then they end up in a sweatshop.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience was not new for several students, who had met at
the gallery before the opening reception. Clement Gomes, who
attends Art and Design, reminded his friends that if they thought
what they saw in New York was bad, they should see working
conditions in his native Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled how in one town he saw workers sitting in an
open-air pavilion sewing clothing whose spotless white fabric was
in stark contrast to their own ragged, dirty clothing. Still, some
of the places he visited in New York were unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incomprehensible to think something is made in America
like that,'' he said. ``I have no words to explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as difficult to explain for some of the young artists was
the appeal of high-priced gear made by companies that have long
been criticized for their overseas labor practices. Nike, a
perennial target that has tried to respond to its critics with a
series of reforms, was mentioned often for its Michael Jordan line
of sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not buying clothes, we're buying names,'' said Analisa
Biel, a student at Washington Irving High School. ``We're dumb for
buying them. Everybody knows Michael Jordan comes out with the same
pair of sneakers. Same style. Different color. Now they're coming
out with a pair at the end of the summer that are just like the
first ones. We had those when we were 11. Jordan doesn't care. Now
he's making mad dough. It's all about money.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklyn Pelaez's mother, Gilma Paredes, understands that, since
she spent eight months in a Brooklyn sweatshop in the early 1990s,
sewing collars on blouses for 10 cents a dozen, 12 hours a day, six
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   She had no other choice, since she was both father and mother to
the boy, now a student at Washington Irving. Nor did she have any
child care, so she took him to the factory, where he played with
the fabric scraps piled up on the floor, bundling them together
into make-believe igloos.
</P>
<P>
   Franklyn recreated that makeshift playroom for the exhibition.
At the opening reception, his mother stood in wonder before his
drawing, which he had stitched onto a sweatshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes me remember everything,'' she said. ``Thank God, I
don't have to work there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   She now has a better-paying job as a fur finisher. Franklyn
wants to go to college and become a commercial artist. As visitors
complimented him on his artwork, his mother only hoped he would
find a good, secure profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask God each day for the strength to keep working,'' she
said. ``I tell my son: `Franklyn, look how hard I had to work. I
don't want you to go through that in your future. You have to
study.' He thinks I'm crazy. But he will understand later.''
</P>
<P>
   She stood near Franklyn's study of her old workplace, a sad
scene of cracked walls, cramped tables and weary faces. Every
single detail proved that he understood her better than she
suspected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TV-AD-SCENE-NYT &LR;      05-21 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TV-AD-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE MY SHOWS, PLEASE: NETWORKS PEDDLE FALL TV LINEUPS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Irwin Gotlieb was being up front about the up-fronts,
the television networks' annual May ritual that is one part Madison
Avenue salesmanship, one part Las Vegas-style showmanship and one
part revival-meeting discipleship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many more components to manipulate now,'' said
Gotlieb, sounding like an advertising executive who had gone
through this ritual before, which he had; 28 times, every year
going back to 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The up-fronts _ called that because advertising agencies commit
themselves to buying commercials up front, rather than waiting
until after the television season begins in the fall _ used to be
so much smaller, he said. Just a handful of advertising agency guys
on one side of a conference table and a single network executive on
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Those days, like ``Love, American Style'' or ``My Three Sons''
or ``Gunsmoke'' and other programs that were first seen at
up-fronts back then, are gone forever. As the networks demonstrated
this week, the up-fronts have evolved into presentations as slick
as the prime-time sitcoms and dramas they introduce.
</P>
<P>
   With big-screen graphics more elaborate than the ones their own
news anchors stand in front of every night, network executives
summarily dismissed the notion that network television has become a
dinosaur in an era of who-knows-how-many cable channels and
ever-more-powerful computers. Even so, it hardly seems accidental
that the up-fronts have become carefully choreographed stage shows
that play once and only once (no reruns, thank you very much) in
some of the great cultural temples of New York: Broadway theaters,
Lincoln Center, even Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after network executives had spent long hours sharing the
stage with high-kicking dancers and a magician in a coffin, or
poking fun at their rivals with a parody of ``Star Wars,'' the
crowds adjourned for canapes under canopies, brie in Bryant Park,
Tanqueray and tonic at Tavern on the Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's turned into a week of party time,'' said Robert P. Walsh,
a vice president with R.J. Palmer Media Services. ``Mardi Gras
time.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was a week of hype and hoopla, with scores of agents,
stars, producers and financial analysts under the up-front tent.
Literally, in the case of NBC and Fox, which rented the same tent
at Lincoln Center on different nights, and ABC, which covered over
a part of Bryant Park. (CBS rented Tavern on the Green.)
</P>
<P>
   But the old-timers do not sound terribly comfortable about
rubbing elbows with all those newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This party's not for us now,'' said Gotlieb, the president and
chief executive of the company responsible for arranging to run
commercials for companies like Procter &AMP; Gamble, under the ABC
tent. ``We are the least of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks disagree, of course. They say the four-day
extravaganza was all about executives like Gotlieb and the huge
advertising budgets he commands. But it was also about that most
valuable of commodities in New York, buzz; about what people like
Gotlieb say, and how that can contribute to the success or failure
or a single program or an entire schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really about glitz,'' said Tom Kenney before the ABC
up-front began. Kenney is the president of For Kids Entertainment,
a company that produces programs, arranges licensing agreements and
buys commercial time. ``No one's going to make a big decision on
the basis of this presentation. It's strictly feel-good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But the up-fronts can be headache-inducing, and there are no
commercials to give one time to go to the kitchen and grab a beer
or to the medicine cabinet for an over-the-counter drug. Up-front
watchers see snippets of more shows in a few days than most couch
potatoes see in a month of channel surfing. How can one keep the
new shows straight?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all meshing into one program in my head,'' said Walsh
of R.J. Palmer. ``But I know the programs by network.''
</P>
<P>
   Another vice president from R.J. Palmer, James E. Watson, said
that even that was difficult this time around. ``ABC had WB-like
shows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the up-fronts are confusing: six essentially similar
presentations, by each of the major broadcast networks, are packed
into four days. Like a sitcom or a murder mystery, they tend to
follow a formula: the same old projections of younger and younger
audiences (because advertisers like younger and younger viewers),
followed by the same old promises of higher and higher ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year at this time I tell you I'm excited,'' began Marvin
Goldsmith, the president for sales and marketing of the ABC
television network. ``This time, I'm really excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Drew Carey put it at the same presentation, ``Isn't it
amazing how every year, the world gets saved by a prime time
schedule?''
</P>
<P>
   Wait. This is television, so miracles do happen. CBS, which once
broadcast the New York Philharmonic from Carnegie Hall, rented
Carnegie Hall for a presentation that included an elaborate parody
of ``Star Wars'' that included the destruction of NBC by CBS
programmers.
</P>
<P>
   NBC rented Avery Fisher Hall and had the instantly recognizable
voice of Don Pardo booming through the loudspeakers. He sounded, as
he always does, as if he had just finished a Christmas pudding, and
all he was saying was, ``Ladies and gentlemen, our show is about to
begin. Please take your seats.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks were ``investment spending, shall we say,'' said
Tim Spengler, a senior vice president who is the general manager of
the national television division of Western International Media
Corp. From his chair in a box in the first tier at Carnegie Hall,
he looked down at the red-velvet orchestra seats as the CBS
presentation began and said, ``There's a lot of money in the seats
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the money was in the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat up in the balcony,'' J. Andrea Alstrup said after the
ABC presentation. ``I could care less where I sit.'' She is a vice
president for advertising of Johnson &AMP; Johnson, the pharmaceuticals
maker, which is the third-largest advertiser on network television.
</P>
<P>
   But others sounded dismayed at having been relegated to
second-class status in nosebleed seats at the ABC presentation.
Take the man in Row D, Seat 14: Kenney of For Kids Entertainment
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked at the card and it said `balcony seating,' I
knew there was caste seating,'' he said. ``They cater to the bigger
agency shops. The treat the little guys as second class, and they
try to please all those big agencies with the big media money.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the presentations even joked about the money. NBC
prefaced one part of a night-by-night rundown of its schedule with
a jingle that said: ``Get out your checkbooks, it's Thursday.'' The
audience giggled. But no one in Avery Fisher Hall needed to be
reminded that NBC'S powerful Thursday night lineup includes
programs like ``ER,'' which draw the biggest audiences and command
the highest prices for commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alstrup, who said that she has attended up-fronts since
1976, said there was a kind of etiquette for watchers. ``You don't
laugh too loudly, and you don't applaud,'' she said. ``You don't
want the price to go up if the network thinks you like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
