<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-LEETCH-NY     05-21 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-LEETCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR-YEAR EXTENSION KEEPS LEETCH WITH RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the specter of free agency looming, Brian Leetch
and the New York Rangers were not playing games during contract
negotiations. So, Leetch will be wearing a Blue Shirt for at least
the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a resurgent 1998-99 season in which he finished fifth
among defensemen in scoring and first in body checks and blocked
shots, Leetch, the 31-year-old captain, will earn between $8
million and $9 million a season on a four-year contract extension.
The Rangers were originally offering about $7 million and Leetch
was seeking about $10 million. The length of the contract is
probably shorter than Leetch preferred, however.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract has not been signed by Leetch, who is out of
town, and will not be announced until he returns. People close to
the negotiations said that Leetch would sign the contract this
weekend and that there would be a news conference on Monday or
Tuesday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   By not signing Leetch last summer, the Rangers may have cost
themselves millions of dollars, because the value of a player of
Leetch's caliber only increases as the deadline approaches. His
salary next season will be a record amount, both for the Rangers
and for National Hockey League defensemen. (Wayne Gretzky made
$6.75 million for the Rangers in 1997-98, and Ray Bourque of the
Boston Bruins will make $6 million next season.)
</P>
<P>
   Rangers president and general manager Neil Smith declined to
comment Friday. Jay Grossman, who represents Leetch, also declined
comment.
</P>
<P>
   By getting the deal done before the July 1 deadline for free
agency, the Rangers avoided the possibility of losing Leetch _ the
way they almost lost goalie Mike Richter last summer, and the way
they did lose Mark Messier, then the Rangers' captain, two summers
ago when he wound up with Vancouver. So quick and decisive moves
toward resolving Leetch's contract were essential to Smith's
credibility with fans and his own Rangers players.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the circumstances surrounding the negotiations with
Leetch were different from those with Richter and Messier. Richter
and his agent, Herb Pinder, played coy until the bitter end,
attempting unsuccessfully to drive up the goalie's price. Messier
did not have support from everyone in the Rangers' organization.
</P>
<P>
   But with Leetch, the lines of communication between Grossman and
Smith were open from the day the season ended. Recently, they had
several face-to-face meetings. And there were no internal whispers
questioning Leetch's ability to lead the Rangers into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Rangers can focus on other things, like pursuing other
teams' free agents.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
