<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO STOP SPREWELL, ROADBLOCK IS NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two games too late, Latrell Sprewell finally showed up
on the Hawks' radar screen Friday. And that was during a film
session at practice.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell has been almost unstoppable coming off the bench for
the Knicks in the Eastern Conference semifinals. He has poured in
62 points in a series that will shift to Madison Square Garden for
Games 3 and 4 on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks, desperate after losing the first two games at home,
must control the scoring sprees of the potent sixth man. It has
become a win-or-clean-out-your-locker proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to guard him,'' Mookie Blaylock, the Hawks' struggling
point guard, said. ``That's pretty much it. He's not trying to get
anyone else involved. The job is just to stop him and get the ball
out of his hands. In two ball games, we've just been letting him do
what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been running out in the open court and beating us down
the floor. It's not like other people are hurting us. In fact,
sometimes you think he's out there playing by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith, who is slumping with 8-for-33 shooting in the
series, said: ``The thing he's doing smart is when the shot is
going up, he's just taking off. Whoever is guarding him has got to
be smart enough not to go rebound, but stay back with him. Stay
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are acting like he's been a role player all his life.
He's a guy that's been an All-Star and all-pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring 31 points in each game, Sprewell has become a
basket-hanging player at the park waiting for the fast break to
begin. He gambles defensively and sprints upcourt ahead of the
fray. Many of his points have been scored in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens, the Hawks' coach, is hoping to limit Sprewell's
effectiveness by making him work harder on defense and also by
having his players remember where Sprewell is on the floor on
offense. More double-teaming is also expected. Anything to control
the tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the Hawks needed to do about Sprewell, Dikembe
Mutombo said, ``I don't guard him.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter replied, ``Nobody guards him,'' Mutombo nearly
bent over laughing from the remark. Half-kidding, he added, ``Oh,
don't be so cold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to try to force him to beat us from the outside,''
Mutombo said. ``I think that's what we have to do. I don't think he
can beat us from the outside. He's playing a West Coast game where
it's just put your head down until you hit something. Try to go
straight to the basket. If you don't feel nothing, go ahead and
finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell has found nooks and crannies in Atlanta's defense and
exploited them. His play has the Knicks within two games of playing
for the right to go to conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have predicted that last month?
</P>
<P>
   ``No great adjustments,'' Blaylock said. ``We just have to guard
him.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   DIKEMBE MUTOMBO is drawing on experience to help his team
recover from it 0-2 deficit. When he played for Denver, the Nuggets
trailed Seattle, 2-0, before becoming the first eighth-seeded team
to knock off a No. 1-seeded team in the first round. ``I've been in
a situation against Utah when we were down, 3-0, and I ended up
pushing a Game 7,'' he said of a Western Conference semifinal with
Utah. ``I don't look at myself as a finished guy. Anything is
possible. I believe we will come out with a win in New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
