</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POW-GONZALEZ-VISIT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scholarship program honors Texas POW
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Army Spc. Steven Gonzales, one of three
Americans held captive by Serbian forces, on Friday told Texas
lawmakers he will pursue his dream to be an engineer if they
approve a state scholarship program in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great honor that is going to help me fulfill a dream of
mine,'' said Gonzales, accompanied by his parents from Huntsville.
``I do plan to return to Texas A&AMP;M and major in engineering. I
can't wait to get back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old specialist, who grew up in Palestine, was
captured March 31 by Serbian forces along the Yugoslavia-Macedonia
border. Staff Sgts. Christopher Stone and Andrew Ramirez were
captured with him. All were freed May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Eddie Lucio (D-Brownsville) said he sponsored the Steven
Gonzales Prisoner of War Higher Education Act ``to send a clear
message to the people of Texas and our country that we appreciate
the dedication and perseverance our American men and women go
through in service to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would create a scholarship allowing released prisoners
of war to attend college for free. Gonzales is the only person who
would currently qualify under the bill, which is applicable to POWs
taken captive after Jan. 1. The scholarships would be financed
first by private money before using state dollars. Twenty-six
senators co-sponsored Senate Bill 1902 with Lucio, and it is now
under consideration by the House.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative policy group, the Texas Public Policy Foundation,
opposes the bill, saying it creates a bad precedent.
</P>
<P>
   But Lt. Gov. Rick Perry said the idea is a good one. ``I support
these efforts because those who have served and sacrificed for this
nation should be recognized for their bravery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales said he left college to join the military for the
Army's educational benefits and because he wanted to travel. His
tour of duty ends in March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In a quiet voice, Gonzales told lawmakers of his fears, as well
as the lessons he learned from captivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I remember the most is the fear of the unknown. It was
one of the biggest factors throughout our captivity,'' he said.
``It's really important to take notice of everything that's
important to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
