<HEADER>
A6811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXLEGIS-ABORTION-BIL     05-21 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXLEGIS-ABORTION-BILL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House votes yes to parental notification bill
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a vote belying the intensity of the debate,
House lawmakers on Friday tentatively decided 111-30 to require
Texas doctors to inform parents that their minor daughters are
seeking abortions before proceeding with the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over parental notification never hinged on whether
parents should be involved in the decision facing their young
daughters. Even those who voted against Senate Bill 30 largely
support that.
</P>
<P>
   The four hours of intense and emotional debate instead focused
almost exclusively on how girls could get around having their
parents notified, especially girls who come from families that
aren't ``perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   As tentatively passed, the bill would allow girls to go to a
judge to bypass the notification requirement. The judge would have
two days to determine whether the girl was mature enough to make a
decision on her own, whether notifying her parents or guardian
wouldn't be in her best interest or whether notifying her parents
or guardian would lead to abuse. If a judge didn't decide within
two days, the girl would be allowed to have the abortion without
her parents being notified.
</P>
<P>
   The bill faces a final House vote today before going to the
Senate to consider House changes. The Senate is expected to approve
the House changes, sending the bill to Gov. George W. Bush as early
as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a front-runner for the GOP presidential nomination, is
certain to tout the passage of a strict notification law in his bid
for the presidency, should he decide to run. He said he believes
the bill will reduce the number of abortions and better involve
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to final legislative approval and the
opportunity to sign parental notification into law,'' he said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill argued that the judicial bypass is the
only exception necessary. Opponents said getting through the
judicial system is too difficult for scared teen-agers. They said
girls from abusive or neglectful families need other alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Several attempts to allow notification to be made to any adult
family member _ or adult family members older than 25 in limited
circumstances _ failed.
</P>
<P>
   The debate and votes largely split along party lines, but some
Democrats, particularly those with religious convictions against
abortion, voted against expanding the avenues around notification
and voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who pushed additional bypasses said opponents were
ignoring reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``These girls need support and sometimes cannot get that from
their parents,'' said Rep. Helen Giddings, D-Dallas, who voted
against the bill. `` `Leave it to Beaver' is gone. This parental
notification bill is not going to cause abortions to be fewer or go
away. Abortion simply goes underground.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters argued that the bill doesn't stop girls from getting
advice and assistance from other family members who could help them
navigate the court system if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   They also argued that to allow other family members to be
notified would invite girls to have friends pose as adult family
members.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Debra Danburg (D-Houston) said that invitation also comes
from the bill as it was voted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict that before this House of Representatives adjourns
today, most of the sexually active teen-agers will know that they
just have to have a fake name and address (to which the
notification will be sent),'' said Danburg, who voted against the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires doctors to give parents notice by telephone or
in person and then wait two days. If a parent or guardian can't be
reached, the doctor would have to notify them by letter and wait
two days after mailing the letter.
</P>
<P>
   In a change to the bill, affidavits given by doctors stating
that notice had been given wouldn't provide conclusive proof of
notification. Without the affidavit being conclusive proof, doctors
could more easily be sued over whether they provided notice, some
Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   Danburg said with the change, abortion opponents could pressure
district attorneys to prosecute doctors over whether they provided
notification. To perform an abortion on a minor without notifying
her parent or having judicial authority to bypass the notification
would be punishable by up to a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there is public pressure out there to
prosecute,'' said Rep. Warren Chisum, R-Pampa, author of the
change.
</P>
<P>
   Twice during the debate, Democrats unsuccessfully tried to
remove the bill from House consideration by raising technical
errors in the process by which it was brought up. Such an error
killed a similar bill two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Rep. Harold Dutton (D-Houston), successfully
raised a technical issue that forced the bill back to committee.
The State Affairs Committee quickly convened Wednesday afternoon,
fixed the technical error and got the bill back before the House.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton, who raised another point of order Friday, said he
opposed the bill because it didn't allow girls enough avenues
around notifying their parents. He also said the bill was given
special treatment and rushed back to the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bastardizes our process,'' he said, questioning why the
bill was pushed ahead of others awaiting House consideration. Today
is the last day for the House to consider Senate bills for the
first time. Hundreds of bills aren't likely to be heard and were in
line before Senate Bill 30, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a governor who is running for president. Maybe that's
why we have to vote on this bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The session ends May 31. Substantive work on all bills must be
completed by May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
