</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HITCHCOCK-PROFILE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTHUSIASTIC STARS COACH STRIKES HEALTHY BALANCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the recent Stanley Cup playoff series against St. Louis,
coach Ken Hitchcock of the Dallas Stars grew displeased with the
play of Brett Hull, one of his sharpshooters. So he demoted Hull to
a checking line and cut his ice time.
</P>
<P>
   And when Sergei Zubov turned over the puck to help create a
winning goal by the Blues in overtime, Hitchcock was publicly
critical of the defenseman who quarterbacks his power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have that,'' Hitchcock said of the mistake. ``He
knows it. We all know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many coaches would be less harsh with their top players,
particularly at such a sensitive time of the year. But Hitchcock is
not a stereotypical NHL coach, and his team is not an average team.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 27 franchises, only four remain, and Hitchcock's team is
one of them. The Stars will face the Colorado Avalanche in the
best-of-7-game Western Conference final series that begins Saturday
night in Dallas. The winner will move to the championship round to
play the Toronto-Buffalo winner from the East.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock never played professional hockey, which makes him rare
among his peers, and there are other unusual things about him. No
other coach has reduced his weight from almost 500 pounds a decade
ago to about half that today.
</P>
<P>
   No other coach, especially one from Canada, has been known to
dress up in the blue uniform of a Union soldier to participate in
battlefield re-enactments of the U.S. Civil War. And how many men
would consider his wife's ex-husband as ``one of my best friends''?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a unique family situation, which I really treasure,''
said Hitchcock's wife, Nancy Bruce, who was a television news
anchor in Kalamazoo, Mich., where she met Hitchcock in 1994. ``My
ex-husband, David, is part of the package because we work very hard
to be good friends and create a situation for our children that
makes us both accessible. I made that clear when I met Hitch.''
</P>
<P>
   They were married in 1996. Hitchcock and his wife agree that
family life with her children has helped him curb his tendency to
become obsessed with his job and his hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   ``His life had become lopsided in many ways before he kind of
integrated into a family atmosphere,'' his wife said. ``Hitch gets
carried away with life.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of his life is devoted to hockey, and Hitchcock's season
runs longer than most. This is the second consecutive season that
his team has reached the NHL final four after winning the regular
season championship. Last season, Dallas lost in the third round to
Detroit, which went on to win its second consecutive Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, 47 years old, is from Edmonton, Alberta. He dropped
out of college to pursue a coaching career. One of his first
players was 14-year-old Mark Messier.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hitchcock has matured, he does not apologize for his
personality. ``Obsession is fine; we're all obsessed,'' Hitchcock
said. ``But to be a good coach, you have to have balance in your
life. My wife has brought me into that reality.''
</P>
<P>
   As a coach, he admits he has a voracious appetite for knowledge,
devouring it from people he meets in his job. He started doing this
25 years ago, at clinics, even when he was still selling hockey
equipment at a sporting-goods store in Edmonton while coaching
youth teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been an information gatherer,'' he said. ``I've
always asked tons of questions. I've always wanted to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock spoke early one morning at the practice facility in
suburban Dallas, hours before his players would arrive. He flipped
off a television showing videotape from the previous night's
victory. He spoke with vivid facial expressions, hand movements and
the persuasive vocal cadence of a salesman.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hitchcock said he does not like to compare coaching
hockey with waging warfare, because war involves great loss of
life, the analogies are irresistible when he starts discussing the
similarities between his two passions. He played the part of a
soldier until 1996 at battle re-enactments; now he attends summer
historical conferences about the Civil War. When asked who he would
like to emulate from that conflict, Hitchcock cited Ulysses S.
Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went about it methodically,'' Hitchcock said of Grant.
``When they lost a lot of men, in the Battle of the Wilderness,
pretty dramatically, he just dusted his army off and pointed it
south again. I feel that's how you have to be as a coach. You have
a lot of tough times. How does a coach deal with tough times? Does
he dust his players off and go back into the fight again with even
more passion? Or does he wallow?''
</P>
<P>
   Of his own team, with its core of veterans and stars in their
prime, he said: ``Our team has tremendous resiliency. We're really
going to need it as we go along in the playoffs. There are going to
be lots of bumps. Lots of adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock often says that a coach does not have to be liked and
that a player does not have to be happy, and he certainly seems to
have established both as policies in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano, the alternate captain and star center, said
anything less than full effort ``is unacceptable'' to Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Derian Hatcher, the captain and star defenseman, was asked early
in Hitchcock's tenure if the players respected him. ``He tends to
yell a lot and get on guys' cases,'' Hatcher said, ``and, from time
to time, guys don't like it. But, obviously, it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock is in his fourth season with Dallas, his first NHL
team. He worked his way up methodically by coaching in the minor
leagues, by serving as an assistant in the NHL at Philadelphia,
and, before that, by building a powerful junior team at Kamloops in
the Western Hockey League from 1984 through 1990.
</P>
<P>
   People respected his record, but some had a hard time taking him
seriously because of his appearance. His father died when Hitchcock
was 14, and the teen-ager gradually became estranged from his
family. His weight gain began then and never stopped until he was
almost 40 and a doctor friend took him on a golf course for a long,
hot day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no carts,'' Hitchcock said, recalling the day. ``He
made me walk the course. I think he did it on purpose. I was dying
at the end. And he said: `You ain't gonna make it if you don't
change your life. You won't make two more years.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
