</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HITCHCOCK-PROFILE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: more years.''' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he altered his habits, giving up fatty, fried
foods and alcohol while beginning an exercise program of about two
hours a day. He uses machines in the gym and goes for outdoor walks
of four to six miles when his team is on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it to be the best time of the day for me,'' he said.
``I'll walk at a hard pace. I find, with the solitude and the
thought process, I can visualize and think as I do this exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Another change in his life came in 1994, when he was coaching a
minor league team in Kalamazoo for the Dallas farm system. While
doing charity work in the community, he met Bruce, who was divorced
with three children. She holds master's degrees in literature and
history from Western Michigan University.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about what attracted her to her husband, she chuckled
and replied: ``He's not the cutest guy that walks the earth. But
you know what? He's such an optimistic, positive person who just
really regards life as an adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce said that, as a former television journalist, she
understands why stories about Hitchcock use the obvious hooks of
his weight loss and his Civil War interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make him an interesting person and they are easy to latch
on to,'' she said. ``But they are small parts of the person. He's
very, very energetic. His sense of competition is unnatural. It
just drives him to want to be the best or maybe drives him to
extremes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
