<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-BUSH-NYT &LR;      05-21 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI'S BIG ANNOUNCEMENT IS SAID TO BE BUSH ENDORSEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No, it seems, Gov. George Pataki is not going to
resign. He apparently is not going to declare his candidacy for the
U.S. Senate, either. He won't announce that former Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato is getting back in the game, or even endorse the Long
Island congressman who may fight Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for the
Republican Senate nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery that Pataki built around a political announcement
scheduled for Monday morning melted away Friday, as people planning
the event said he intended to do precisely what many Republicans
have expected him to do for months: to join the long list of
Republicans who have endorsed the presidential bid of Texas Gov.
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   As political events go, it is hardly the earthshaker Pataki and
his aides hinted at in the five days since the governor disclosed
that he had summoned Republican leaders to Manhattan for a major
political announcement. Indeed, the only surprise is that Pataki
managed to keep it secret so long, and that he managed to stir such
frenzied speculation among other politicians and in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Barring some last-minute change of heart or other unlikely
twist, Pataki will become the 16th Republican governor to support
Bush's presidential bid. The Texas governor has become something of
a consensus choice for much, though certainly not all, of the
Republican establishment.
</P>
<P>
   So Pataki is jumping onto the back of a very crowded train.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's aides refused to confirm the decision Friday, and
were clearly upset that what they had viewed as a major event for
Pataki had apparently leaked out on a Friday night for publication
in Saturday newspapers. (As a rule, the Saturday newspapers, which
are not particularly well-read, are a favorite repository for news
that politicians  &UR; don't &LR;  want to get much attention.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment on any of the scenarios that are
being discussed,'' said Zenia Mucha, the governor's senior adviser.
``The governor will make his announcement on Monday as planned. He
has the right to make his announcement on his own timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   From a national perspective, Pataki's announcement is likely to
fuel the sense, encouraged by Bush's advisers, that his nomination
is inevitable even though Bush has yet to announce officially that
he is running. For Pataki, the announcement will be seen as an
unofficial concession that he will not emerge as a long-shot
candidate for president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki still has hopes of being considered as Bush's
running-mate, and the extensive staging of the event seems designed
to impress the Texas governor. Pataki has summoned Republican
leaders from across the state to the ballroom of the New York
Sheraton, suggesting that Pataki is hoping to deliver the party of
the nation's third largest state to Bush. There are even plans for
a balloon drop.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, though, how well the upstate Republican
leaders will take to the announcement. They responded eagerly to
Pataki's invitation, many of them paying their own way to New York
City for what had promised to be a dramatic announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything except that the governor has asked us to
be present, so I am coming down,'' David W. Brenner, the chairman
of the Otsego County Republican Committee, who is bringing his wife
for the 370-mile round-trip drive from Oneonta, said before news of
Pataki's intentions began to emerge. ``And that's that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said they had no comment on Pataki's big
announcement. But unlike Brenner, Bush is going to be spared the
expense and time of a trip to New York for the big Pataki speech,
according to people planning the event. Bush will be able to accept
the endorsement via a satellite television-hook-up that will beam
his image into the hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
