<SLUG> BC-BOX-OSCAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR REVERTING TO HIS TAKE-CHARGE STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oscar De La Hoya fidgeted incessantly as others
spoke at a news conference to promote his title defense here
tonight, obviously dying to take care of pending business.
</P>
<P>
   That business? Oba Carr.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the WBC welterweight champion from East L.A. is
particularly interested in beating !ital!Carr.!off! Oba Carr,
Obi-wan Kenobi ... the champ doesn't care who he defeats at the new
Mandalay Bay Events Center.
</P>
<P>
   It's how he gets the job done that matters tonight.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, self critical about his tentative fighting style the
past few years, promises to thrill his fans by tearing through his
opponents like the Golden Boy of old from now on.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with Carr.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be the first to witness the old-but-new Oscar De La
Hoya,'' he said in such an intensely serious manner that it's
difficult to doubt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going back to my old style. Enough of this (technical)
boxing stuff ... I'm gonna go in and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   And, if that's not enough motivation for De La Hoya, the fight
also officially became a prelude to the matchup he and the boxing
world have long yearned for: Bob Arum, De La Hoya's promoter,
announced Friday that De La Hoya and Felix Trinidad have come to
terms on a Sept. 18 bout in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Carr, the only thing standing in the way of the dream fight,
won't spoil the moment if De La Hoya picks up where he left off.
</P>
<P>
   In his last fight against Ike Quartey in February, De La Hoya
(30-0, with 24 knockouts) fought defensively before finally
abandoning caution and outslugging his challenger in an
unforgettable 12th round to win the fight and drive the crowd into
a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, the champion realized he should never have
allowed his handlers to hold him back and decided to revert back to
the aggressive fighter who won an Olympic gold medal in 1992 and
knocked out 20 of his first 22 opponents at lower weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my style all my life, an aggressive style'' De La
Hoya said. ``I've never been a boxer, fighters have never made me
move backward like they have recently. I've lost respect in the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have big punching power. I should use it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, should Carr (48-2-1, 28 KOs) be pitied?
</P>
<P>
   If utter lack of respect is an indication, yes. He's a 10-1
underdog, he's being paid only $350,000 (to De La Hoya's $5
million) and he's been almost entirely overlooked amid the talk of
a De La Hoya-Trinidad fight. He isn't even on the official fight
poster plastered all over town, which has photographs of De La Hoya
and WBC super featherweight champion Floyd Mayweather, who also is
fighting on the card.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not everyone is ready to dismiss Carr.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Steward, the only one to have worked with both fighters,
believes the challenger is not the pushover everyone seems to think
he is.
</P>
<P>
   Carr, only 27, was a marvelous amateur fighter before turning
pro at only 17. At that time, Steward, who worked primarily as his
manager, predicted greatness for the quick and highly skilled
Detroit native.
</P>
<P>
   However, he strayed from his roots and never evolved into the
fighter he might have been.
</P>
<P>
   First, he left Steward and handed the reins to his career to
trainer/father Eddie Carr. Then he left his !ital!father!off! for
Mike Tyson's handlers when Don King waved a bundle of money in
front of his face, a move he realizes now he should never have
made.
</P>
<P>
   Carr got two title shots with King _ he was knocked out by
Trinidad in the eighth round in 1994 and was outpointed by Quartey
in 1996 _ but was lost without his dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me everything I know,'' Carr said. ``It was like
being half a man without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr left King after the Quartey fight and returned to his
father. He also found God and stability, which he believes makes
him a better man and a better fighter than the one who lost to
Trinidad and Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   Since he left King, he's 9-0-1. He easily beat former champion
Frankie Randall in his last fight to earn a shot at De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about being overlooked,'' he said. ``Those
are the two champions (on the fight poster). In order to have my
picture up there, I have to prove myself. It doesn't bother me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I beat De La Hoya, the whole town will have pictures of
Oba.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward won't make that prediction but gives Carr a chance.
</P>
<P>
   He said Carr's hand speed could confound anyone and has more
courage than people realize. He might go down tonight but he won't
do it willingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oba will fight all the way to the wire,'' Steward said. ``That
right there means you gotta give him a shot in this fight, more
than people give him credit for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that Oscar is as fast as Oba and he's much
stronger. His strength and power give him a definite edge.''
</P>
<P>
   That and a few other things.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
