<HEADER>
A6829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REDS-LEASE22-COX     05-21 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDS-LEASE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials promise park will be tops for players, affordable for
fans
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Hamilton County and Cincinnati Reds officials made
several important promises Friday after announcing a 30-year lease
agreement on a new $297 million riverfront ballpark due to open in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the best stadium in Major League baseball, capable of
generating enough additional revenue to help make the team a World
Series contender. And coming to the park will be affordable for
fans.
</P>
<P>
   At a sun-splashed news conference near home plate at Cinergy
Field, county Commissioner Bob Bedinghaus, commission President Tom
Neyer, Reds Managing Executive John Allen and team General Manager
Jim Bowden trumpeted the ``rebirth of the riverfront'' with the new
venue for baseball's oldest franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The yet-to-be-named ballpark will have 45,000 seats, 51 luxury
boxes, 3,500 parking spaces and a grass playing surface. It will
slightly overlap Cinergy Field and be located just east of the
Bengals' $403 million Paul Brown Stadium, due to open for the 2000
NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've struck a deal that works not just for the team, not just
for the government of Hamilton County, but most importantly for the
citizens of Hamilton County and this entire region,'' Neyer said.
``It will provide prosperity for the Reds, pride for the community
and a home for the fans who have been following Cincinnati baseball
for more than a century.''
</P>
<P>
   Bedinghaus is credited with conceiving the idea of two new
stadiums from the kitchen table of his Delhi Twp. home four years
ago, then selling the idea to county voters, who approved a
half-cent increase in their sales tax in March 1996 so the stadiums
could be built.
</P>
<P>
   He said the riverfront's rebirth ``serves as a catalyst for
taking this community a giant step forward. We are truly the envy
of cities our size and much larger. People are coming here to find
out how we get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Although architects are still working on the ballpark's design _
the final drawing is expected this summer _ Allen set a high
standard for the Reds, who will contribute $30 million to the
project on top of the county's $235 million. The Reds annual rent
will be $2.5 million for the first nine years and $1 per year the
next 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reds are committed to working hard to design and build the
best stadium in all of baseball.'' Allen said. ``We want a stadium
that will make us all proud. As the oldest franchise in baseball,
we'll be able to combine the best of modern technology along with
our wonderful history and tradition to build the best stadium there
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said keeping ticket prices affordable is a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reds organization does not want to scare people away,''
Allen said. ``It's very important that we have a tiered price
structure so that it's affordable for everybody. You'll see that
tradition we've had for years _ of being an affordable family
entertainment facility _ continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (private seat licenses) are used at all, it will be on
ultra-premium seating. Your average seat ticket holder that's
supported us all these years will not have to pay a fee just for
the privilege to buy a season ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is excited by the prospects of the new stadium bringing a
reported $24 million per year in additional revenue to help the
Reds field a quality team in one of baseball's smallest markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big,'' Bowden said. ``If you don't have a new stadium,
you won't be able to compete at all, so this gives us a chance to
compete. I can see Cincinnati turning into what Cleveland is now. I
can see sellout crowds every game down the road. It's a very
exciting time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never asked to be able to put the same payroll on the
field that Atlanta does or the Yankees, but just put us in the
ballpark. Give us a chance to be two or three players short of what
they can do financially and not 15 players short.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said fans can expect a ``short right field porch.'' He
wouldn't reveal any other cosmetic aspects of the ballpark except
to say that everyone in Reds' baseball operations from coaches,
players and player development personnel has had direct input with
architects and designers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
