<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HMO-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SAYS POTENTIAL PITFALLS PLAGUE HMO INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ State officials, fresh from the chore of
cleaning up the bankruptcy and liquidation of HIP Health Plans of
New Jersey, said this week that the rapidly evolving
health-insurance industry could still present new problems.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying Thursday before the Senate Health Committee, Jaynee
LaVecchia, the commissioner of the Department of Banking and
Insurance, said that she was beginning to see deals that were
disturbingly similar to the one that brought on the demise of HIP,
which had been the state's fourth-largest health maintenance
organization.
</P>
<P>
   And, she said, even some of the new regulations and legislation
that state regulators have proposed in the wake of HIP's failure
may not be enough to prevent future problems. ``It's evolving and
we haven't seen by far how creative the industry can be,'' said Ms.
LaVecchia. ``Right now the law is not ready or able to keep pace
with the changes.''
</P>
<P>
   At hearings this week, Ms. LaVecchia and other state regulators
publicly discussed the HIP debacle in detail for the first time.
They acknowledged that they had neither the legal authority nor the
staff to prevent what happened to HIP. They said their overriding
desire had been to save an insurer that looked as if it had ``lived
past its nine lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. LaVecchia said that her agency had ``tried valiantly'' to
get HIP to improve management practices, but did not have the
enforcement and monitoring tools to do so.
</P>
<P>
   So when the for-profit company Pinnacle Health Enterprises came
forward with a merger plan that promised to infuse new capital into
the sagging insurer and institute more efficient screening and
management techniques, she said, regulators jumped at the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   HIP, said Acting Attorney General Paul Zoubek, ``was an entity
in financial distress, and that framed the whole consideration of
the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar problems and frustrations were expressed by state
officials in interviews last December with The New York Times. At
that time, the merger arrangement was unraveling into insolvency
and bankruptcy, imperiling the coverage of 194,000 policyholders.
HIP Health Plans of New Jersey closed its doors on March 31, and
most of its policyholders switched to other insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Its problems began more than two years earlier, when its system
of clinic-based care was having trouble competing with the networks
of private doctors offered by newer HMOs. Revenues declined, and
HIP cut premiums to well below costs in an effort to hang on to
policyholders. It also began shopping around for a merger partner.
</P>
<P>
   That partner turned out to be Pinnacle, which paid HIP $73
million to acquire its clinics and policyholders. Pinnacle proposed
new management systems and said it would create a network of
private doctors, lower costs and improve services.
</P>
<P>
   The deal received the blessing of state regulators despite their
inability to examine Pinnacle's finances carefully. It was also
approved even though Pinnacle was not licensed by the state, so it
could not be compelled, as other insurers were, to maintain
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of future situations like the failure of HIP, the
administration of Gov. Christie Whitman has proposed new
regulations that would prohibit licensed insurers from transferring
so much of their responsibilities to unlicensed companies. The
Assembly has begun to examine the parts of the proposals that
require legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   In her testimony, Ms. LaVecchia cited recent actions by the
state that prevented United Health Care, a Medicare HMO, from
transferring management to Heritage New Jersey Medical Group.
Heritage is a subsidiary of a national company that specializes in
medical management of elderly Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the experience with HIP and American Preferred,'' said
Ms. LaVecchia, referring to another insurer that became insolvent,
``I haven't allowed that anymore and I have only allowed those
companies to be third-party administrators. But the industry is one
where, increasingly, slivers of the HMO responsibilities are being
delegated out to other entities.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thomas Nagle, executive director of Heritage New Jersey, a
subsidiary of a 21-year-old medical group founded in California,
confirmed that the state had blocked its deal with United Health
and had limited an arrangement that it sought last September with
Oxford Medicare Advantage, another HMO in the state.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the commissioner had unilaterally changed state
law. And while he said he understood the sensitivity wrought by the
HIP experience, Nagle said it was unfair to assume that Heritage,
which he said had a good record in four states, would present
problems for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Langenvin, the executive director of the New Jersey
Association of Health Plans, which represents HMOs, said that some
of the state's proposed changes were unfair, and singled out the
ban on a practice known as transferring risk.
</P>
<P>
   That involves a company taking on, for a flat rate, patients or
services that could end up costing more than the flat rate pays.
The company bets that it will earn profits anyway by shifting those
costly patients. For example, diabetic patients could be
transferred to a medical group that specializes in diabetic care.
That group's experience with diabetics would, in theory, allow it
to provide more efficient care than an insurer could.
</P>
<P>
   Langenvin said that without risk transfers, the industry would
be robbed of one of its main cost-control measures. ``The theory is
that these groups understand these medical and management issues
better and that they are the experts in the area,'' Langenvin said.
</P>
<P>
   In her testimony, Ms. LaVecchia also seemed to have concerns
about how the state's reaction to the HIP insolvency has led her
department to tamper with market forces. But she also sounded as if
she had no choice. ``I don't know whether we can continue to do
what we are doing in New Jersey and keep the state competitive for
HMOs,'' she said. ``But the law in New Jersey has to change,
because it permitted what happened with HIP.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
