<HEADER>
A6836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-WELFARE-REPORT-     05-21 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-WELFARE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 PANEL SAYS AGENCY LAGS IN ASSESSING CHILDREN'S NEEDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City's child welfare agency often fails to
assess the needs of abused and neglected children promptly and to
find the most appropriate foster homes for them, a panel of
national experts responsible for evaluating the agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, which released its findings in a 30-page report, said
child abuse investigators often neglected to gather and pass along
crucial information about the children, their needs and their
relatives to workers responsible for finding foster homes. The city
too often failed to rely on relatives as caretakers or supports for
children who must be removed from their parents.
</P>
<P>
   But the child welfare specialists commended the agency, the
administration for Children's Services, for recognizing the
problems and working to correct them. Hoping to improve the flow of
information and to assess initial foster care placements promptly,
the city last year began bringing together workers, parents,
relatives and foster parents to discuss each individual case three
days after a child is placed in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings, known as 72-hour conferences, now take place in
Queens and Manhattan, city officials said. The experts urged the
city to expand these conferences citywide by December, and to hold
additional meetings 30 days after each foster care placement by
April.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, created last year to resolve a federal lawsuit
against the city, cannot compel the city to follow its
recommendations. But under the agreement that resolved the lawsuit,
it can find that the city has acted in bad faith, which would allow
lawyers for foster children to renew litigation, using the experts
as witnesses. The lawyers had sought to replace the city, which
runs the Administration for Children's Services, with a
court-appointed receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which focused on the placement of the roughly 11,000
children who enter foster care each year, was the second of five
studies to be issued this year by the panel of former child welfare
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   The panel includes Doug W. Nelson, president of the Annie E.
Casey Foundation; John Mattingly, a senior program associate at the
Casey foundation; Judith Goodhand, a consultant at the University
of North Carolina, and Paul Vincent, who works with a nonprofit
child welfare group. The first report assessed the city's efforts
to find permanent homes for the 40,000 children now in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   In the study released Friday, the child welfare specialists
urged the city to provide counseling and other services to
stabilize and support children once they land in foster care. They
emphasized the importance of promptly involving parents in their
children's lives, urging city officials to permit visitation
quickly when appropriate and to tell parents promptly what they
need to do to get their children back.
</P>
<P>
   The specialists also urged the city to rely more on
well-trained, well-supervised workers _ and less on computers _ to
find good foster homes for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the panel's recommendations build on initiatives that
ACS has already begun,'' Nicholas Scoppetta, the commissioner of
the Administration for Children's Services, said in a statement.
``Some of the panel's other suggestions for improving services will
require further study by ACS, and we look forward to working with
the panel as we focus on how best to address their
recommendations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
