<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-STRATEGY-N     05-21 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENCH PLAYERS FOR KNICKS IMPROVISE WAY TO SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chris Childs is glad for the company. For so long, he
was alone in performing an improvisational act on the floor that
was frowned on by a Knicks team that was once as stuffy as a
butler.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are the free-spirited Marcus Camby and Latrell
Sprewell to ad lib with him. Now, there are partners to sprint
ahead as he pushes the ball up the court without a map. The three
did not need one during Game 2 in Atlanta as they wore on the
patience and will of the elder Hawks and took a commanding 2-0 lead
in their second-round series.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Thursday night, Steve Smith, Dikembe Mutombo and
Mookie Blaylock were like frazzled parents shouting to the Knicks'
threesome: ``Turn down the music!'' Childs, Camby and Sprewell just
rocked on as a part of a bench that has been vital to the Knicks'
playoff success. In Games 1 and 2, the Knicks' bench outscored the
Hawks' bench, 84-54, and outrebounded them, 38-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps when those guys can come off the bench and do the
kind of damage they did,'' said Don Chaney, an assistant coach.
``It says something about our depth. If we want to win, we have to
have depth.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would want to look ahead of the Hawks, particularly not
the Knicks' squeamish coach, Jeff Van Gundy, but the Knicks' bench
may be as thick as that of the Indiana Pacers. In fact, the Knicks'
bench may be even better than the Knicks' starters. At least in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The starters don't even want to play us anymore,'' Camby said,
joking. ``The second unit always wins. Jeff has to call us off.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has to calm them down during games, too. Sometimes,
they are so energized on offense, they get careless on defense.
Sprewell is prone to make a spectacular shot one minute, miss one a
little later and be slow to get back on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they just throw caution to the wind and play without
regard to a plan, for better or worse. Childs can spot Camby
cutting to the basket for an alley-oop but is still prone to
getting frazzled with some of his decision making. Faults aside,
the bench has delivered when the starters have not, as it did when
the Knicks began Game 2 in a 13-2 hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we come off the bench, we pick up the pace,'' Childs
said. ``As soon as we take the ball off the rim, we fly down the
court. We just play basketball. We go out and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of that fun begins by getting a defensive stop or grabbing
a long rebound off a Hawks miss. Then they attack an Atlanta
defense that needs to set up to be effective. If the Knicks can
beat the Hawks down the floor, that's when the playground shots
begin.
</P>
<P>
   During Game 2, Childs stripped Smith for a steal, caught
Sprewell out of the corner of his eye sprinting down the floor and
found him in stride for a vicious fast-break dunk. A few minutes
later, Camby lifted off on a mark nine feet from the basket,
levitated above the elbows of the finger-wagging Mutombo and threw
down a one-handed dunk that deflated the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus had that one bottled up for some time,'' Larry Johnson
said. ``It was good he was able to get it out of his system.''
</P>
<P>
   All three of the bench stars have felt restrained at some point.
Childs signed as a free agent with the Knicks three years ago and
was labeled their point guard of the future. But that outlook grew
hazy when Charlie Ward, a point guard better suited for Patrick
Ewing, took over as the starter last season. Camby and Sprewell
also arrived with expectations of starting only to end up waiting
impatiently on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to start,'' Sprewell said. ``It's just
something you have to deal with when you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sprewell has been vocal about his distaste for the
situation, Camby has taken his disappointments quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 15 or 20 games, Marcus didn't get a whole lot of
playing time,'' Johnson said. ``But during the last month or so
that I've seen him, he's been the MVP of this team. I think he's
grown a hell of a lot. In order to get to where we want to get, No.
23 is going to have to be a cornerstone for us. He's done his job
and done it well. What he did on that dunk over Dikembe, that was
unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of play seldom seen from a player in Knick blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What New York doesn't understand is that what they're seeing
just scratches the surface,'' Camby's agent, Alex Johnson, said.
``The rest hasn't been let out, yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is left to tap from Camby, Childs and Sprewell, the
Knicks will need it for Games 3 and 4 Sunday and Monday at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be hungry, so we can't let up,'' Camby said.
``We always thought we were a good team. Now we're showing it with
everything jelling, especially in transition. We're getting easy
buckets. That's something I've never seen a New York team have
since I've been watching basketball. But the look is definitely
changing, especially with our bench.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks trail a playoff series, 2-0, for the 14th time. They
have never recovered from such a deficit. But Knicks coach JEFF VAN
GUNDY was taking little comfort in his team's commanding position
with a chance to sweep the series with victories in Games 3 and 4
at the Garden. ``I've been on a team that was up, 2-0, and gotten
beat,'' said Van Gundy, alluding to the Knicks' 1993 playoff series
with Chicago. ``I'm one of the statistics. I know how that can
happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
