A6841 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-GOP22-COX     05-21 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-GOP22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NRA chief gets OK to speak from GOP
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ After a day of soul-searching, Georgia Republican
leaders decided today's speech by a top official of the National
Rifle Association will go on as planned, despite concerns that it
might inflame tensions following the school shooting this week in
Rockdale County.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the right thing to do,'' state GOP Chairman Rusty Paul
said of continuing the speech by NRA Executive Vice President Wayne
LaPierre. ``We can't be panicked into making a decision. We need to
have this discussion more than ever now.''
</P>
<P>
   Party officials were told to expect several hundred NRA
supporters in the Augusta Civic Center's guest area to hear
LaPierre's five-minute address.
</P>
<P>
   Paul was wavering on the issue Thursday after a Heritage High
School student opened fire on campus, injuring six. Several key
congressional leaders said they were prepared, if asked, to
recommend that the speech be canceled for a variety of reasons. But
after consulting other GOP leaders, Paul said LaPierre can add to
the search for solutions and should not be muzzled.
</P>
<P>
   The speech that has divided the Georgia GOP ranks comes amid a
growing national debate over guns and school violence, one destined
to spill over into Georgia following Thursday's shooting. But many
Republicans, including fomer House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who built
a dinner speech around the topic, said blaming guns is ``a very
nice self-serving smoke screen for liberals who don't want to face
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a decay in the land, but the elite liberal media
can't look honestly at the mess its values have created, so they
yell `gun control' to block thinking,'' Gingrich said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of attacking guns, Gingrich said leaders should focus on
cutting taxes, getting back to school basics and holding Hollywood
and the makers of violent video games responsible for corrupting
the youth.
</P>
<P>
   Two presidential candidates who addressed the GOP's sparse
turnout Friday condemned the incident at Heritage High as part of a
long string of shootings. But former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander
and Christian activist Gary Bauer blamed parents who spend too
little time with their children and on a society that's shunned
religious values such as the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing for kids to read `Thou shalt not kill,'''
Bauer told the applauding crowd. ``How many more bullets have to
fly before we can agree on that?''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates paused for 30 seconds out of respect to the Conyers
families involved in Thursday's shooting. But several Republicans
said the party's sensitivity to the issue should have extended to
canceling LaPierre's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy's come to Georgia,'' said former state Sen. David
Ralston of Blue Ridge. ``For us to give such prominence to a group
that has such a special interest in that issue is a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the controversy for Georgia Republicans isn't just about
guns. As much as anything, it's about how the NRA, with a powerful
constituency in Georgia, treated key candidates in last fall's
elections. Ralston, a candidate for attorney general, and the GOP
nominee for governor were both bypassed by the NRA, which endorsed
Democrats for those seats.
</P>
<P>
   Binding up those sore spots will be among the first tasks a new
state chairman of the GOP will have to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who served for four years, leaves today after up to 2,000
convention delegates select his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Far more pressing than the intraparty rift and possible public
relations fallout from the NRA appearance, though, is the task of
reinvigorating a party that until last fall appeared poised to make
good on promises to seize control of the state's power seats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
