<SLUG> BC-CORPSE-IN-COOLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE PODIATRIST ARRESTED AFTER SISTER-IN-LAW'S BODY FOUND IN
COOLER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J., Conn.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Jersey City, N.J., podiatrist whose sister-in-law's body was
found stuffed into a plastic cooler this week was arrested Thursday
night on a fugitive warrant in Pennsylvania, and the authorities
said they were investigating her in connection with the death.
</P>
<P>
   The podiatrist, Dr. Elain Witterschein, 48, was arrested by the
Pennsylvania State Police at a substance abuse clinic in
Wilkes-Barre, said Edward DeFazio, an assistant Hudson County
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Witterschein was admitted to the clinic last week after she
was arrested in Jersey City on a stolen-passport charge. A judge in
New Jersey Superior Court allowed her to check into the clinic as
an alternative to bail, DeFazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The body of her sister-in-law, Mary Ann Witterschein, was
discovered Monday in a vacant lot across the street from Dr.
Witterschein's apartment. The body was handcuffed and zippered
inside a garment bag that had been placed inside a cooler.
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio said that, according to police reports, the cooler had
previously been kept for months in a storage area accessible only
to the podiatrist and her live-in companion, Stanley Eldrige, in
the basement of their apartment.
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio said Eldrige moved the cooler into the vacant lot on
Monday and called the police to report it.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy determined that the woman died between six and nine
months ago from a blow to the head and asphyxiation. She was the
widow of Edward Witterschein, a retired Jersey City police
lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio said that neither Dr. Witterschein nor Eldrige, who
could not be reached for comment, had been ruled out as a suspect
in the death.
</P>
<P>
   Trooper Tom Jordan of the Pennsylvania State Police, who
arrested Dr. Witterschein, said officials of the clinic, Clear
Brook Manor, called a nephew of hers to report her missing about 3
p.m. on Thursday. The nephew called the police, who began looking
for her as a missing person. But the search intensified and a
fugitive warrant was issued after officials learned through a
computer databank check that she had been charged in the passport
case.
</P>
<P>
   Trooper Jordan said clinic officials later called the police
when Dr. Witterschein returned after spending several hours in a
wooded area near the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``She walked out on her own and basically just stayed in the
woods,'' Trooper Jordan said. ``She just told me she was
depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio said Dr. Witterschein was also charged Thursday night
with trying to use the stolen passport to cash forged checks. He
said the passport did not belong to the dead woman. Dr.
Witterschein was being held in the Luzerne County, Pa., jail on the
fugitive charge. Bond was set at $500,000. DeFazio said his office
would seek her extradition to face theft and fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio said Dr. Witterschein had not practiced medicine for
some time. Her lawyer, Brian Stapleton of Stamford, Conn., is not
listed in the phone book, and has no telephone number in the state
bar's directory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
