<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC COUNCIL SPEAKER SAYS LOSS OF COMMUTER TAX MONEY COULD FORCE
LAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City Council Speaker Peter Vallone warned Friday that
the loss of up to $360 million a year in commuter tax revenue could
force the city to lay off workers at some point in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a group of labor leaders, Vallone said the state
Legislature's decision last week to abolish the income tax paid by
nonresidents who work in the city had created a ``perpetual hole''
in the city's $35 billion budget. The impact could be more serious
in future years, he said, when the economy might be weaker and the
city might not have a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quickest way of saving money is not to hire,'' Vallone, a
Democrat, told about 50 labor leaders, who had invited City Council
members to a luncheon to discuss concerns about Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's spending plan. ``And who gets hurt first? The little
person gets hurt first.''
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Vallone told reporters that the repeal of the
commuter tax _ which was 0.45 percent of taxable income for most
wage earners _ had forced the mayor and the council to reconsider
their spending priorities as they figure out how to make up for the
anticipated loss of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is back on the table,'' Vallone said, adding that
council members would discuss spending priorities Saturday in a
special meeting at City Hall. ``We were able to get through the
worst of times without laying people off, but we were never faced
with this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, aides to both Vallone and Giuliani said
layoffs in the coming fiscal year were highly unlikely, because the
city had a record $2.1 billion surplus. A more likely strategy for
dealing with the lost commuter tax revenue would be to abandon some
of the tax cuts that the mayor and the speaker had proposed, the
aides said. Giuliani has proposed $405 million in tax cuts, while
Vallone has called for more than $800 million in cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year there is a surplus, so we're just going to have to
make some choices regarding the tax cuts,'' said Carolyn Daly, a
spokeswoman for Vallone. ``But in years where there is no surplus,
those are the years where you will start considering layoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lhota, the deputy mayor for operations, said Vallone was
justified in worrying about the long-term effects of the commuter
tax repeal, because the city anticipates sizable budget deficits in
the next few years. The Giuliani administration is predicting a
$1.6 billion budget gap in the 2001 fiscal year, and a $1.7 billion
gap in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the size of our out-year gaps, layoffs are an option,''
Lhota said. ``It's one of the many things we will consider as we
move forward to close the budget gaps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
