<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL OFFICIAL CHARGED WITH MOLESTING STUDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An assistant principal at Stuyvesant High School was
arrested Friday and charged with molesting a student who was
working as his assistant, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Plass, 55, who has worked at Stuyvesant for the last 16
years and taught in the city school system for 33 years, was taken
into custody Friday morning at his home in Queens, said Edward
Stancik, the special commissioner of investigation for the New York
City schools. Plass was charged with sexual abuse and endangering
the welfare of a child, Stancik said.
</P>
<P>
   The student, a 15-year-old girl whose name was not released, was
assigned to Plass' office and given administrative tasks,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The abuse, they said, took place last year, while the student
was working alone with Plass in his office at the school, in
Battery Park City in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   During the first alleged encounter late last year, Plass
conspicuously viewed pornography sites on the Internet while the
girl was in his office, Stancik said. Later Plass rubbed her leg
and then tried to hug her, Stancik said. The girl told
investigators that she consistently rebuffed Plass' advances.
</P>
<P>
   On other occasions, Stancik said, Plass masturbated in the
girl's presence and tried to touch her genitals.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators learned of the incident from a teacher who read a
journal that the girl was keeping as part of a class. In her
entries, which were made last February, the student wrote about the
incidents as if they were happening to a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, an investigator posing as the student's older brother
confronted Plass and asked him whether the stories he had heard
from his sister were true. With a hidden device recording the
conversation, Plass admitted to the conduct, and said the girl had
instigated the sexual encounters, the authorities said. Because of
her age, they said, it would not matter whether the girl consented
or not.
</P>
<P>
   Plass had no previous arrest record, Stancik said, adding that
his office was investigating previous complaints about Plass made
by students at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators seized a computer in Plass' office on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who answered the phone at Plass' home in Queens on
Friday night declined to comment on the allegations. Plass is
married to a mathematics teacher who works at a public school in
Queens. The couple have two sons.
</P>
<P>
   Most students interviewed Friday night said they had just
learned of Plass' arrest and were stunned by the news. ``If the
allegations are true, they should be dealt with, but I hope this
doesn't overshadow all the great things about the school,'' said
David Meadvin, 18, a senior who is president of the student body.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Plass, who is also a biology teacher, is best known for
encouraging students to enter the annual Westinghouse science
competition, recently renamed the Intel Science Talent Search. For
the past 16 years, he has pushed students to enter the contest and
then shepherded their projects through the entry procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Stuyvesant High has long been known for producing a trove of
finalists each year, helping to fortify its reputation as one of
the finest public high schools in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Although some students described him as a caring, nurturing
mentor, others said Plass was not always approachable. ``He was not
someone that people felt comfortable going to with their
problems,'' said Micah Lasher, 17, a senior. ``Most students did
not look to him as a friend or someone who could be supportive of
their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The school's principal, Jinx Cossi Perullo, could not be reached
for comment Friday night. Chiara Coletti, a spokesman for the Board
of Education, said that Plass would not have any contact with
students until the investigation was completed. ``Everyone took the
appropriate action, and now we have to wait and see what the
investigation bears out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 interview with The New York Times, Plass talked about
his passion for education and his devotion to his students. ``This
is the best job in the country,'' Plass said. ``I am really doing
what I want to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
