r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LITES-TEX     05-21 1661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LITES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITES BREAKS THE MOLD AS TEAM EXECUTIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ There was a time when the Detroit Red Wings
stunk.
</P>
<P>
   The hockey franchise made great by Gordie Howe and Ted Lindsay
had hit rock-bottom in the early 1980s when Jim Lites took over as
club president. They had missed the NHL playoffs in 10 of the
previous 11 seasons, most of the talent was old and worn out, they
had traded away No. 1 draft picks and they didn't have much money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a pretty bad franchise,'' Lites said. ``For all
intents and purposes, an expansion franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Wings came up with a daring plan, one that would
bring out the no-holds-barred competitiveness within Lites. The Red
Wings decided to sneak behind the Iron Curtain and see if they
could steal away some of the best amateur hockey talent in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were with the Red Wings, and even here with the Stars,
we always thought a little out of the box,'' Lites said. ``You do
whatever it takes to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of man that owner Tom Hicks has picked to
replace Tom Schieffer as the Rangers' president, someone who won't
let something as trivial as the Soviet Union's communist empire
stand in the way of making his hockey team better.
</P>
<P>
   After all, why worry about an international incident or a run-in
with the KGB when you can snatch away a guy with a ferocious slap
shot.
</P>
<P>
   So the Red Wings drafted 18-year-old Czechoslovakian Petr Klima,
a superstar on the Czech national team, in the fifth round of the
1983 draft, deciding he was as good as any first-round pick that
year.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Jim Devellano made that assessment, not Lites.
What Lites did was physically go get Klima, taking the same
attitude he did in Dallas when Stars general manager Bob Gainey
recommended signing free agents Ed Belfour and Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim was not the one reading the scouting reports,'' said Jeff
Cogen, marketing boss for the Stars and the Rangers and Lites'
right-hand man for more than 13 years. ``But when it comes time to
get something done, he's a can-do guy. He says, `I'll get it done.'
He has a very aggressive mind-set.''
</P>
<P>
   In Klima's case, Lites said bluntly, ``We decided we'd do
whatever it took to get the guy to jump. We made contact with Klima
clandestinely through an interpreter we hired, and he indicated to
us a willingness to jump.''
</P>
<P>
   It took 18 months, but Klima finally agreed to come to the
United States during a late-night meeting with Lites deep in the
woods of the Bavarian Alps in West Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary because they were traveling with armed Russian
guards. It was the first time the Czech team had ever trained
outside Czechoslovakia,'' Lites said. ``We were right over the
border in West Germany. We made contact with him on a Friday night
in the middle of the woods, as scary as can be. He said, `I'll meet
you here Sunday night, same time, if you can get my girl friend out
of Prague in those two days.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We had met _ for lack of a better word _ some Czechoslovakian
profiteers who were basically smugglers. We gave them $5,000, and
they drove into Prague, got the girl and moved her to Budapest. She
called Klima on Saturday, told him she had left _ we didn't know it
at the time _ and he went back on Sunday, said you got her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left with us that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Klima has been a good player in the NHL but nothing exceptional.
The Red Wings had much better success seven years later with Sergei
Federov, the Russian star whom Lites helped sneak out of a hotel
room during the middle of the Goodwill Games in Seattle in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same thing,'' Lites said. ``Hire funny people, get
them to make contact with the player, then I went over and met
them, did all sorts of things to facilitate him leaving. Cash
payments ... you do what you've got to do to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings did. Federov and two other Russians, Slava Kozlov
and Vladimir Konstantinov, helped the Red Wings win the past two
Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty cutting edge,'' Hicks said. ``But you look
what he did with the Stars as well. When he came here six years
ago, he didn't know anybody, and he pretty much had to start all
over. But he helped promote the franchise, sell more tickets, more
advertising and sponsorship and really built things up. I thing
he'll bring some of those same things with the Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lites was named Rangers president, he insisted that general
manager Doug Melvin would be in total charge of the baseball
operation, just as Gainey runs the Stars' hockey operations.
</P>
<P>
   But club presidents who sneak through Bavarian forests with
sacks of money trying to lure Czechoslovakians to defect don't
appear to be the kind of executives who sit back and let others do
the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really the facilitator of what the general manager wants
to do,'' Lites said. ``In Bob's case, he tells me what he needs,
and I think I have a pretty good understanding of hockey. I know
the players. I know the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``In baseball, I don't know the players, but what I have to do
is work with Doug Melvin to try and protect the development of our
young players, which is the key to our success. But my main role
here is to run the business. I do run the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites immediate concern is not to parachute into Cuba and kidnap
international superstar Omar Linares but to get more people to The
Ballpark in Arlington. The Rangers finished their last homestand
averaging 34,478 fans per game, trailing the Cleveland Indians
(44,828 through Thursday), the Baltimore Orioles (40,358) and the
New York Yankees (36,674).
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we need to do is fill more seats,'' Hicks
said. ``Attendance has been very good, but it can be better. If it
gets better, that helps us get more resources to put a better team
on the field. Right now, we don't have the resources of our main
competitors, Cleveland or Baltimore or the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites acknowledged that the best marketing plan can't make up
for a bad team. It's Melvin's job, he said, to supply the talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we can be more aggressive in the way we promote
the team,'' Lites said. ``I think we can make the show better, jazz
it up a little, make the entertainment experience seem quicker. I
don't like dead time. I don't think people come to sit. I like to
fill it up without becoming hucksterish.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites is not a baseball novice coming in from hockey without a
clue about the sport's ancient traditions. He was a Detroit Tigers
fan growing up in Michigan. His favorite players were Al Kaline and
Bill Freehan, and he played catcher through high school. He and his
father spent many afternoons together at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't kept him from introducing a taste of The Late
Show with David Letterman to The Ballpark in Arlington, music
bursts between pitches, sound bites while the opposing manager
visits the mound and the sound of glass shattering when foul balls
go flying into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   He was told when he came into hockey that you had to have an
organist. He didn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear that all the time,'' Lites said. ``Where's the organ?
Every old hockey team has an organ. Every new hockey team doesn't.
Hockey has changed itself, modified itself completely. The
experience in Dallas is as hip as you can get. People like it, they
like the action and what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighteen- to 40-year-old men and women are used to a lot of
stimuli. They grew up with television, rock videos, computers.
They're used to a lot of stimulation, and baseball has to react to
the fact that's how people are now. Baseball has to recognize that
or become a dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars general manager Bob Gainey, as old-school as they come in
hockey, wasn't thrilled with all the marketing innovations
introduced by Lites and his assistants.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged, ``We had to find some new things,
especially when we came down here. We have a group of people whose
job it is to try and judge what our fan base enjoys. There are
compromises that we all have to make. The league is different than
it was 10 years ago. It's different than it was five years ago, and
anyone who wants to stay in this business better be ready to adapt
and compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites still realizes he must tread lightly on hallowed ground.
The Red Wings were terrible when he took over in Detroit. The Stars
had just arrived in Dallas when he took over six years ago, and
relatively few people in North Texas knew anything about hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't even understand the rules,'' Lites said. ``You
could be as irreverent as you wanted because you didn't have a
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are different. They have been here 28 years, won two
division titles in the past three years and drew almost three
million fans last season. Certain goals haven't been reached, most
notably a World Series title, but this franchise is also one of the
strongest in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is certainly bigger than hockey,'' Lites said. ``It's
a bigger part of the community and probably draws from a greater
cross-section of the community. Television numbers are higher. For
every person who comes to a Stars game, there are probably four or
five people who come to a Rangers game. You have three million
people coming to the game. They must like it or they wouldn't come.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I'm a little reluctant to perform major surgery. So,
you've got to walk a fine line between respecting the sport and
knowing you've got to reinvent yourself or fall off the cliff. But
you also can't just sit back and think just because three million
people came last year, they'll come again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lites rarely sits around, unless it's on a tree stump in the
middle of a Bavarian forest trying to convince a Czech teen-ager
that Detroit is really the place he wants to be. \Ntagtop:T.R.
Sullivan, (817) 390-7760
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
