<SLUG> BC-BKN-JACKSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON'S ONCE-BRIGHT FUTURE DIMMED, BUT NOW HE'S SHINING AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Four years ago, Jim Jackson's future in
Dallas seemed so simple, so perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a breakthrough season in which he averaged 25.7
points per game, scored 50 points in one game and earned All-Star
consideration, he was the Mavericks' starting shooting guard and an
integral prong of the Three J's foundation that was poised to lead
Dallas back to the playoffs. Jackson had a popular local radio
show, a national television commercial and prompted Dallas Mayor
Ron Kirk to proclaim a ``Jim Jackson Day'' in appreciation of his
tireless charity work.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Jackson has finally made it to the postseason _ but
without the high scoring average, the national respect, the
starting job, or his original employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't exactly how I first envisioned it,'' said Jackson,
now a key reserve for the Portland Trail Blazers. ``Like everybody
else, I thought we'd grow together and make the playoffs in Dallas.
It's been like a roller-coaster ride. I wasn't always sure how I'd
get here, just that I would get here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the way to a dynasty in Dallas, there was a gruesome ankle
injury in '95, a controversial feud with Jason Kidd in '96 and,
finally, an unceremonious dumping in '97 by new general manager Don
Nelson. Traded three times in a year to lottery regulars New
Jersey, Philadelphia and Golden State, the former No. 1 pick in '92
was a mediocre free agent looking for work last summer when Trail
Blazers general manager Bob Whitsitt had a flashback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a borderline All-Star in Dallas, and if the team would
have had success, he probably would have been an All-Star,''
Whitsitt said. ``We saw a player who is still young (28), still
physically gifted, and who has his head on straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Accepting a job as Isaiah Rider's backup, Jackson signed a
three-year, $5.7 million contract that required him to reinvent
himself. Instead of a crunch-time shooter, Jackson has become the
team's defensive stopper at small forward and a second point guard
on the floor focusing on passing to Rider, Walt Williams or post-up
scorers Brian Grant and Rasheed Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Suns in the first round, it was Jackson who harassed
Phoenix sharp-shooter Rex Chapman into 23-percent shooting. And in
last Thursday's crucial Game 2 victory in Utah, it was Jackson who
bothered John Stockton's potential game-tying layup in the final
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a mature, experienced pro,'' said Portland coach Mike
Dunleavy. ``He can do a little bit of everything for us from bring
the ball up, to posting up, to taking big shots, to shutting down
Bryon Russell. Best of all, he won't complain. I think he's seen
enough of losing situations and he's really enjoying winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he still lacks his preinjury explosiveness and had only
two 20-point games this season, Jackson quickly evolved into a key
ingredient of Portland's mix. With him on the court in the regular
season, the Blazers outscored opponents by 291 points compared to
only 46 with Rider in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Dunleavy and Whitsitt give Jackson credit for
Rider's improved behavior and play, highlighted by a career
playoff-high 27 points in the Game 2 victory. A player who for
years held his team hostage via irrational behavior, tardiness and
legal troubles, Rider has been a better person and a better player
with Jackson pushing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't measure what he's done for Isaiah,'' said point
guard Damon Stoudamire. ``If \RRider\S screws up, we know and he
knows there's a veteran waiting in the wings.''
</P>
<P>
   A career 19-point scorer, Jackson said it hasn't been easy to
turn into an eight-point role player.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not in a winning situation, people often don't
recognize your good qualities,'' said Jackson, who has played for
nine head coaches including Richie Adubato, Gar Heard, Quinn
Buckner, Dick Motta and Jim Cleamons in Dallas. ``I'm scoring less
than ever, but I'm happier than ever. Some people in Dallas were
convinced that wasn't possible, so they traded me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson still bristles at how he was shipped from the Mavericks
to the Nets in the nine-player swap. Nelson, after just two weeks
on the job, said Jackson was a locker-room distraction who didn't
play hard and was a ``crybaby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wanted to clean house, it's his prerogative,'' Jackson
said of Nelson. ``But he didn't have to taint the guys he traded in
order for a trade to look good. And that's what he did. He tainted
the five guys by saying the locker room and the practices were in
disarray. But Don Nelson never attended a practice and didn't come
to the locker room when we were there, and he didn't sit down and
talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   From the supposed tug-of-love with Kidd over singer Toni Braxton
that he still says never happened, to his one-two scoring punch
with Jamal Mashburn, Jackson says memories of his days with the
Mavericks have grown foggy. Thinking he's finally found a home,
Jackson even chose No. 19 with the Blazers _ 1 the beginning and 9
the end _ and got a Chinese proverb tattooed on his right arm: ``He
who knows a man is wise, he who knows himself is enlightened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, when I look back at it, I'm glad I went through it,
because I never had to struggle with basketball my entire life
until the last two and a half years,'' said Jackson, who still
splits the off-season between Dallas and his hometown of Toledo,
Ohio. ``It's taught me a lot. It's taught me how to handle things
the right way, and now I'm in a situation where I'm finally on a
great team.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
