<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAVIN'S 64 LEADS RUN OF SUB-PAR ROUNDS AT COLONIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Pity the poor folks who put in a half-day at work
before heading to yesterday's second round of the MasterCard
Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived in time to see plenty of birdies, but missed any
meaningful shots by the leaders. That's because the dew-sweeping
duo of Corey Pavin and John Cook secured their spots in today's
final group of the third round in time to grab a late lunch and
watch a matinee movie.
</P>
<P>
   Pavin rolled home the last of his seven birdie putts in a round
of 64 before the 2 p.m. group teed off, boosting himself to 7 under
par for the tournament. He stands a shot ahead of Cook (6 under),
who finished 10 minutes before Pavin and collected six birdies,
including a chip-in from a greenside bunker at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Scott Hoch, a fellow morning starter who stands at 5
under, they did it the old-fashioned way, at least in terms of the
1999 Colonial: They survived 20 mph wind gusts that subsided as the
day progressed.
</P>
<P>
   As wind speeds diminished, so did the Colonial scoring average.
After yielding only 15 sub-par scores in Thursday's opening round,
players logged 51 yesterday _ the biggest one-day increase in
tournament history. Most of those were collected in the afternoon,
when Phil Mickelson blistered the course for the tournament's
lowest score (63) and moved to 5 under, two strokes off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Mickelson marveled more at the scores posted by Pavin
and Cook than at his own 22-putt round or 336-yard driving average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who teed off early were at a disadvantage, yet our
leaders are from that group,'' Mickelson said. ``That just shows
you how well they played.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, no one played better yesterday than Pavin. The
two-time Colonial champ proved to be an early starter in more ways
than one. He collected birdies on his first three holes, draining
consecutive 20-footers at No. 2 and No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, Pavin had split 13 of 14 fairways and
found 15 of 18 greens in regulation. He saved pars from both sand
traps he visited and drained four birdie putts of 12 feet or
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just played very solid golf. There wasn't very much I did
wrong out there,'' said Pavin, whose 64 marked his second-best
round on the PGA Tour since the 1996 season. The best came last
week, when Pavin shot a 63 in the opening round of the GTE Byron
Nelson Classic en route to finishing 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, when I shot 7 under, I thought, `Wow, where did
that come from?' '' said Pavin, who has not cracked the top 155 on
the season money list since 1996. ``That was a pleasant surprise.
This was not. I put myself in position to make birdies, and I
thought my way around the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Cook, who collected four birdies on the back nine,
including a bunker blast at No. 10, a 30-footer at No. 12 and two
short birdie putts at No. 16 (4 feet) and No. 18 (8 feet).
</P>
<P>
   Cook checked in with a second-round 66 on a day when the
Colonial scoring average (69.93) was more than two strokes per
player lower than Thursday (72.38). Cook was joined in the
turnaround by playing partner Hoch, who emerged from a bogey-free
tour of Colonial bemoaning the birdies that got away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't in jeopardy of making a bogey out there,''
said Hoch, who made only one birdie putt longer than six feet.
``The wind was a lot more consistent. It was much easier to pull
the right club. The last two holes, if I'd hit my putts harder, I
had them right in the jar.''
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, Hoch is one of 29 players under par through 36
holes and one of 79 players who survived the weekend cut of 4-over
144. Those seemed like unlikely figures after only 15 players broke
par in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Pavin, until recent weeks, seemed like an unlikely
leader at a PGA Tour event. Now, he's making noises about picking
off his third plaid jacket and breaking a three-year victory
drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectations are a little bit higher now,'' said Pavin, who
ranks No. 68 on the season money list ($270,029). ``They're not
through the roof or anything. That's one thing I still have to be
very careful about. When your expectations get really, really high
and then you don't have great rounds, you feel kind of bad about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavin, however, was all smiles after yesterday's 64. Just like
most of his fellow competitors who extracted second-round revenge
after opening-day struggles at Colonial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
