<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MAYOR STONEWALLS, AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, May 22:
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's instinct is to stall
investigations into any aspect of his administration. He has
already lost court battles to deny information to Public Advocate
Mark Green and State Comptroller Carl McCall. Now he is refusing to
cooperate at this time with state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer's
investigation into the stop-and-frisk policies of the New York
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Corporation Counsel Michael Hess makes the lame excuse that
Spitzer's probe is burdensome and redundant. There are indeed
several probes about the department's practices going on. But
Spitzer, who is responsible for enforcing the state's civil rights
laws, has a right to seek answers, regardless of who else may be
asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   When Spitzer announced in March, after public protests over the
Amadou Diallo shooting, that his office would conduct an
examination of the police stop-and-frisk record, the mayor
recognized his right to do so and the police department pledged to
cooperate fully. Now, when the political heat has been lowered, the
administration is brushing off Spitzer's request for basic data
about police searches on the street. Spitzer wants to review forms
that officers fill out on those searches to see whether proper
guidelines were followed.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, Hess claims he is not actually denying Spitzer's
request, only putting it off indefinitely. The Giuliani
administration would serve itself and the public better by
cooperating instead of turning this dispute into another showdown
in court.
</P>
</TEXT>
