<SLUG> BC-ISLAND-SEUSS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEUSS LANDING IS TRULY `SEUSSIAN' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By BILL DEAN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Like Horton who heard a Who, Dr. Seuss himself
might have heard a ``snort'' _ if he could have visited Seuss
Landing, says the widow of Theodore Geisel, Audrey Geisel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was pleased with something, he didn't laugh as perhaps
you or I would laugh, he would sort of `snort,''' Geisel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a thing in the back of his throat. And so,''
she said as tears welled in her eyes, ``when I walked into Seuss
Landing, I think I heard a snort.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``snort'' at Islands of Adventure, however, almost wasn't to
be.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, Geisel was as opposed to the idea of her
husband's characters taking up residence at a theme park as Horton
was about giving up the Whos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally, `Thank you, but no thank you,''' Geisel said.
Finally, she agreed to fly from her home in La Jolla, Calif., to
Orlando to hear exactly what the creative team of Islands of
Adventure wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than just set up the Cat in the Hat, Sam-I-Am and the
Grinch in tacky, ultra-commercial settings, they wanted no less
than to create a total Dr. Seuss environment: Everything would be
``Seussian'' _ from the wavy lampposts and bent palm trees to the
Green Eggs and Ham Cafe, and the Sneeches-on-the-beaches beach.
</P>
<P>
   The team showed her detailed drawings and three-dimensional
models of everything from the Cat in the Hat ride to the
Caro-Seuss-el.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted guests to feel like they just walked into all the
books that they'd ever read,'' said Lisa Girolami, show producer of
Seuss Landing. ``And we won her over by getting really serious
about it and showing her that we could do it, and do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   When Geisel saw that Seuss Landing would be a painstaking
creation true to the spirit and zany reality of the books, she
began to be impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I was saying `You can do this?' And they were saying
`we can do this,''' Geisel said. ``They showed me sections, and the
sections were absolutely Seussian; they had a complete handle on
it.
</P>
<P>
   Once Geisel gave her approval for the park itself, then she had
to consider the merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   That was another big ``no'' _ at first. Why, the Grinch would
rather stop Christmas from coming after all than have Sam-I-Am
reduced to an ashtray.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the merchandising, I was a problem,'' Geisel said. ``But
their know-how in doing this was so fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to be Seussian. It had to be in excellent taste and it
had to be quality controlled; no jim-cracky things. And so,
everything coming out of Seuss Landing is very, very special.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
