<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6980 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-2NDLD-WR     05-21 1689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON BACKING BUILDUP OF NATO TROOPS AT KOSOVO BORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Inserts new 4th graf beginning ``About 13,000.'' Changes the
following graf. Minor changes in wording elsewhere.)  (lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration announced Friday that
the United States would press its allies to move quickly to deploy
what was described as a peacekeeping force of about 50,000 troops
on the borders of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After recent days of public debate and private planning, NATO is
now likely to take up the issue as early as next week. The forces
are intended to be used to help return the Kosovar Albanian
refugees and to police any agreement reached with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO and the Pentagon have left open the possibility that
the troops could enter Kosovo without the permission of President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia. In that sense, the Pentagon's
announcement of support for such a force, which would include about
7,000 Americans, represented an effort to put pressure on
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   About 13,000 NATO troops in the region are considered the
vanguard of a possible peacekeeping force. But thousands of other
troops are also in Macedonia and Albania, including 5,000 Americans
attached to a fleet of Apache helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO weighs the new deployment, officials said the United
States was negotiating with Russia on concessions that would allow
Milosevic to keep some forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic talks in Moscow between Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott and the Russian envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, Thursday
and Friday have centered on the NATO peacekeeping force going into
Kosovo in exchange for permitting some forces, under the control of
Slobodan Milosevic, to stay, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   That would represent a significant shift from one of NATO's key
conditions for a peace agreement, that Milosevic must agree to his
soldiers and police leaving Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said as recently as
Thursday that one of NATO's war objectives was the departure of
``all'' of Milosevic's forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But a Clinton administration official suggested this position
would be finessed by ``all'' Yugoslav army and Serbian police
forces having to leave the province as part of a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Serb soldiers and police would then be allowed to
return in designated numbers to protect religious sites, serve as
tax and customs officials at the border and perhaps, to work in
limited numbers in a newly formed Kosovo police force.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott ended a round of talks with the Russians Friday and left
Moscow to spend the weekend in Washington. He said he would return
next week.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my talks here in Moscow this time have been
significantly constructive and serious to justify my coming back
yet again next week,'' Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, he met with Igor Ivanov, who was reappointed by
the new Russian government as foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On NATO's military front, the alliance's chief decision-making
body, the North Atlantic Council, is expected to meet early next
week to authorize the expanded peacekeeping force of about 50,000
and its earlier than expected formation.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain will argue that time is running
out for the positioning of the force if it is to be effective
before the winter arrives in October.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the U.S. forces, together
with other NATO country soldiers, would initially move into
Macedonia. They would go ``as quickly as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration made the announcement after NATO's commander,
Gen. Wesley Clark, spent a day at the Pentagon this week outlining
what he saw as the need to act now.
</P>
<P>
   The acceleration of the peacekeeping force, officials here
emphasized, did not signal any change in the willingness of the
United States or NATO to mount a land war to drive out Yugoslav
forces. Bacon said Clark had discussed the possibility of ground
troops for an invasion force as one of several options he had been
asked to reassess. He cautioned the leaders at the Pentagon on
Thursday that such a force would have to be larger, and would take
considerable time to assemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said that if you look down several months out into the
future, and you reach a point in August or September or October
where we might want to deploy ground troops, what is the type of
planning time frame that would be necessary in order to position
NATO to do that,'' Bacon said. ``He wanted to make sure that no
decisions were made by default, and that everybody be aware of the
type of planning and, potentially, training that would be required
for a future movement of forces. '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even for the smaller peacekeeping force, if NATO waits on
deployment, it could take several weeks to build up, potentially
leaving a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take some time to move them down there,'' Bacon said.
``To the extent that some countries could move in relatively
quickly, light forces in the area, such as the 26th Marine
Expeditionary Unit from the United States, it could be done
rapidly. If people decide to move in very heavy forces from other
parts of Europe, it will take more time.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that NATO's leaders would have to approve the exact
size, composition and mission of the force before setting a date
for the troops to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of diplomatic activity was accompanied by deepening
divisions among NATO members, reflecting a growing nervousness that
the air campaign has not achieved the alliance's goals and dismay
over mistakes like the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade
and missile attacks that have killed civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Britain kicked off the public feuding at the beginning of the
week with its renewed promotion of ground troops that could invade
Kosovo once Serbian forces are weakened. Those sentiments were
flatly rejected by Germany, which said it would veto ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   And Britain's push apparently irritated President Clinton, who
tried to patch over the NATO differences by saying he had not ruled
out the use of ground troops as an option but preferred to allow
the air campaign to continue. By week's end, Italy had called for a
bombing pause, Greece was refusing to allow Turkish planes taking
part in NATO airstrikes to fly over its air space and the German
foreign minister appealed to the alliance to avoid civilian
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has argued that congressional approval would not be
needed if he decided to send in ground troops, although the White
House said recently that he would seek congressional support for
such an operation.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives voted last month to bar the White
House from sending ground troops without its approval, but the
administration said such approval raised a host of constitutional
questions. Both the House and the Senate approved an emergency
spending bill of $15 billion in part to pay for the Kosovo
operation, and Clinton signed it into law Friday.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has said that 7,000 U.S. soldiers would participate
in the new force. Before the airstrikes began, the Pentagon
announced 4,500 Americans would be included in a smaller
peacekeeping force of 28,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   About 13,000 NATO troops, largely French and British, are
already in Macedonia as a vanguard for the peacekeeping force that
NATO wants to patrol Kosovo once the airstrikes end.
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 American troops are in Albania accompanying a fleet
of Apache helicopters and 8,000 Italian soldiers are also based in
northern Albania, working mainly on helping the ethnic Albanian
refugees expelled from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In tandem with the military moves, the administration appeared
to be pushing the diplomatic talks along.
</P>
<P>
   The White House wants to have a peace settlement on hand that
the Yugoslav leader will acquiesce to once he ``cries uncle,'' as
administration officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   To make this strategy work, the White House has bet on bringing
the Russian government as close as possible to NATO's demands and
then taking an agreement worked out with NATO and the Russians to
the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution passed by the Security Council would give a U.N.
mandate to a Kosovo peace agreement and isolate Milosevic,
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration wants to have the U.N. resolution passed in
time for the summit of the leaders of the seven industrialized
countries and Russia _ known as the G-8 _in Cologne, Germany, on
June 18.
</P>
<P>
   The concession by the administration on allowing some Serb
forces in Kosovo hinges on the recognition by NATO at its summit
three weeks ago that after the war is over Kosovo would remain part
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sore point for the ethnic Albanians, on whose behalf
NATO has largely conducted its air war.
</P>
<P>
   For the ethnic Albanians who made up more than 90 percent of the
population of Kosovo before the airstrikes and about half of whom
have been forcibly expelled by the Serbs, a goal of the airstrikes
is the eventual independence of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russians argue, according to an administration official,
that since NATO has agreed that Kosovo will remain a part of
Yugoslavia, Milosevic must be allowed ``expressions of
sovereignty'' within the police, military and border guards working
in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott was attempting to keep the scope of Milosevic's Serb
military presence on ``more of a model of park rangers than the
VJ,'' an administration official said, referring to the Yugoslav
army.
</P>
<P>
   It would be unacceptable for NATO for Serbs to serve as border
guards, the official said. But there were other functions at the
border _ such as customs and tax collection _ that the Serbs might
be able to do, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians were ``trying to save face out of all this'' for
Milosevic, the official said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But for Milosevic to be allowed to keep some military or police
in Kosovo would present a major obstacle to one of NATO's war aims:
the return of the more than 700,000 ethnic Albanian refugees who
have been expelled from Kosovo by the Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has repeatedly stressed that an unnegotiable goal of the
war was for the ethnic Albanians, now stranded in Albania and
Macedonia, to return home.
</P>
<P>
   But the refugees, many of whom have been radicalized by the
terror and brutality of the Serbs, would be deterred from returning
if armed Serbs remain in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the presence of Milosevic's forces, no matter how
minimal, would make it highly unlikely that the guerrillas of the
Kosovo Liberation Army would agree to such a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership of the guerrillas have already said that they
will not disarm, a demand laid down by the group of seven
industrialized countries and Russia in Germany two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The basic aim of the guerrillas is the independence of Kosovo
and an agreement that solidifies Kosovo in any way as part of
Yugoslavia would represent a repudiation of those aims.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks Friday, Cook said the shape of the peace
settlement being fashioned has as its base line the agreement from
Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   In that agreement, the Serbs were allowed to have 2,500 police
and 2,500 soldiers of the Yugoslav army. The administration wanted
to keep the number of Serb and Yugoslav forces below those figures,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Kosovo Liberation Army signed onto an agreement that
permitted even a minimal number of lightly armed Serbs or Yugoslav
soldiers in Kosovo, there was a high potential for violence between
the two groups, an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a concern on our part that you don't put people there
as invitations for retaliation,'' the official said. ``We would
like to have as few as humanly possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping force would probably have a role in protecting
the Serb and Yugoslav forces and keeping them apart from ethnic
Albanians, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
