<SLUG> BC-ABUSE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida man charged with abuse, torture of children
 &HT;    By Brian D. Crecente and Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ A Port St. Lucie woman whose children
were allegedly tortured and raped for almost two years by her
live-in boyfriend was afraid to report him to police because she
feared he would be free to come after them again.
</P>
<P>
   He told her he had avoided conviction on more than a dozen
previous criminal charges, according to police and court records.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, police in Tennessee charged Steven R. Jentsch, 36,
with six counts of aggravated child abuse through malicious
punishment and torture and capital sexual battery. The capital
charge allows prosecutors to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Jentsch, who moved to Seymour, Tenn., with the woman and
children prior to his April 30 arrest, was extradited Tuesday to
the St. Lucie County jail, where he is being held without bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of my years of police work, this is probably the most
callous case of child abuse I've ever heard of,'' said Port St.
Lucie police spokesman Chuck Johnson. ``Had he not been taken into
custody, there is a good chance someone might have been killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jentsch beat, kicked and systematically tortured the five
children who lived with him, according to an arrest affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who is the mother of three of the children, told
police that Jentsch abused her and said police couldn't help
because he had gotten out of all of his previous charges. He told
her if she went to police, he would hunt her down and kill her and
the children.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, Jentsch was charged with five
misdemeanors and 10 felonies, including several sexual battery and
kidnapping charges, over the past 15 years. He was found guilty of
only a 1997 driving under the influence charge.
</P>
<P>
   A former neighbor told police Jentsch bragged about convictions
he avoided. Police say he told his wife that he had a 40-year
sentence for a 1993 charge of sexual battery and kidnapping removed
from his record.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, Jentsch pleaded guilty to the 1993
charges, partly because of the testimony of his then-wife and a
videotape which showed the two of them engaging in bestiality and
bondage and Jentsch apparently torturing her. He was sentenced to
serve 40 years with all but eight years of the sentence suspended.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, Jentsch's wife recanted her testimony and the
judge released Jentsch and purged the plea from his record.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half later, Jentsch moved into a Port St. Lucie
house with two of his children, a girlfriend and her three
children.
</P>
<P>
   Police say his abuse of the group started shortly after that,
including incidents where Jentsch allegedly:
</P>
<P>
   _ Grabbed the 9-year-old girl by the hair, whirled her around
and slammed her into a refrigerator, tearing a ``huge'' clump of
her hair out of the back of her head.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forced the 9-year-old girl to sit in a large red ant hill
until she was covered in ant bites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lifted the 9-year-old girl above his head and threw her, head
first, into a wall. The force of the blow dented the wall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forced the 4-year-old to eat a hamburger covered in hot sauce
until he threw up and then forced the child to eat the vomit.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents continued until an investigator with the
Department of Children and Family Services inspected the home in
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jentsch told investigators he lined the children up and spanked
them with a belt, but because there was no longer any evidence of
abuse, the investigators closed the case, according to police
reports. The woman told police Jentsch stopped his attacks on the
children after that because he was afraid of another inspection.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, Jentsch moved the woman and children to Tennessee
where, police say, the abuse resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Jentsch bought a trailer home on a hill with only one way on and
off the property in case the police came. Police say he placed
55-gallon drums filled with gasoline around the trailer and trained
the children to act as human shields to thwart any attempts to
arrest him. He told the woman that he wouldn't go peacefully if
they came for him.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the woman escaped with her children.
</P>
<P>
   and went into hiding at her sister's home in Port St. Lucie.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the sister went to police and reported the abuse.
Tennessee authorities were able to arrest Jentsch without incident.
His two children were placed in the care of their grandmother,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Lead investigator Detective Todd Schrader said Jentsch didn't
manipulate the system; he was just lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no one's fault,'' he said. ``He just slipped through
the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
