<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH TRIES TO WORK THROUGH SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Chuck Knoblauch remembers the day, remembers the play
and remembers the player. It was May 6, it was a crushing collision
at second base and it involved Minnesota's Corey Koskie. How could
Knoblauch forget?
</P>
<P>
   When Koskie roll blocked Knoblauch while trying to break up a
double play two weeks ago, the second baseman crumbled to the
ground and Yankees initially feared that he might miss an extended
period. Miraculously, Knoblauch only had a seriously bruised lower
left leg and he returned to the lineup after missing three games.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch, who was slumping before Koskie rumbled into him,
thinks he is still feeling the effects of missing four days because
he has slumped even more since the play occurred. Knoblauch is
searching for reasons why a season that looked so rosy has
deteriorated and his search curiously settled on that memorable
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is not like riding a bike where you get off it and
get right back on,'' said Knoblauch. ``I think it did have some
effect on me. When you're on a roll, the last thing you want to do
is miss three games in four days. It certainly didn't help me. It
definitely wasn't a good thing for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch and the Yankees have to wait until Saturday to
play the White Sox because Friday night's game was postponed by
rain. Roger Clemens, who has not started since April 27 because of
a strained left hamstring, will oppose John Snyder in the first
game of a doubleheader at 4:05 p.m. and Andy Pettitte will face
Mike Sirotka in the second game.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has won 17 straight decisions and is aching to pitch,
but he said one more day of waiting is inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to talk about,'' said Clemens. ``Just go out
there tomorrow. It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Knoblauch rejoined the Yankees, he is 4 for 36 with seven
strikeouts, two runs scored and no runs batted in. Knoblauch was
already 1 for 15 before the play so he has been mired in a 5 for 51
drought that has dropped his average from a league-leading .381 to
.274.
</P>
<P>
   The 107-point plummet is precipitous and Knoblauch claimed that
it could be related to missing time and disturbing his continuity.
``I came out of that all right, but from a baseball standpoint it
wasn't good,'' said Knoblauch. ``You get out of that rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's troubles have extended to defense. He has already
committed seven errors in 35 games after making 13 in 150 games
last season. When Knoblauch was asked if the jarring collision had
influenced him mentally and contributed to his slides, he said,
``It was all physical. I didn't get caught up in any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have scored only 14 runs in their last eight games
and manager Joe Torre has emphasized how critical it is for
Knoblauch to remain patient and consistently reach base because the
leadoff man must be an energizer. Despite batting .265 last year,
Knoblauch was important to the Yankees because he usually took
several pitches and set the tone for the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important because if he gets on, all of a sudden,
pitching to the middle of the lineup is not so easy to the
opposition,'' said Torre. ``There's no place to put them. When you
have hitters that are anxious and you don't have to pitch to them,
it's going to prolong their problems. So the top of the order is
very important to us or to any team for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Knoblauch has shown mild signs of emerging from his
prolonged funk with three hits in his last eight at-bats, including
a modest three-game hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   Torre gushed about how Knoblauch got on base three times in a
3-1 victory over the Red Sox on Thursday, acting as if Knoblauch
had belted three homers. It was a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to stay away from driving yourself nuts,'' said
Knoblauch. ``Sometimes it's hard in this game. That's the last
thing you want to do is flip on the TV and see the guys running
around the bases and doing their thing and we're trying to score
one run.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 2, no one in the American League had a higher average
than Knoblauch. Less than three weeks later, Knoblauch is trying to
discover what he once had.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to try and right everything,'' explained Knoblauch.
It's a long season, individualized and team-wise. You really can't
get hung up in today. You have to focus on today, but there's still
a big picture of so many games left and so much work to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
