<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HOUSE BACKS PARENTAL NOTIFICATION BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After a tense and often emotional four-hour
debate, the Texas House voted 111-30 Friday to require parents be
notified when minors seek abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to kill the bill with the parliamentary procedure known
as a ``point of order'' were overruled by House Speaker Pete Laney,
D-Hale Center. The measure is a high legislative priority of Gov.
George W. Bush, who said he intends to sign it to ``reduce the
number of abortions in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 30 faces a final vote Saturday before being sent
back to the Senate, which approved the measure in March.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Florence Shapiro, R-Plano, the measure's sponsor, said she
will accept the House version, which is similar to her own bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud that the House overwhelmingly agreed with the
Senate bill. I think it's a great day for the parents of Texas. The
parents are well served because they are now back in the loop,''
Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   While opponents cast the issue as part of a socially
conservative effort to eventually stop abortions altogether and
even contraceptives, supporters say they are trying to restore
parental rights.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said she accepts a change that would waive a two-day
waiting period in cases where a parent brings a girl for an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the focal point of the House debate was whether to
allow other adult relatives to be notified instead of parents. In
the end, the chamber struck that idea down, but not without
powerful speeches in which Democratic members railed against the
bill for giving girls the only other option of appearing before a
judge.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barry B. Telford, D-DeKalb, hushed the chamber with a
speech in which his voice literally shook as he imagined his own
daughter becoming pregnant and being afraid to tell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am far more concerned that if my daughter gets into this
situation, she goes to someone who gives a damn,'' Telford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would it surprise you to know that it's a lot more important
for me that my daughter gets love and forgiveness and support
instead of condemnation? For once we've got an opportunity to adopt
something that has some semblance of family values.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the debate Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston, told of her
teen-age son having major problems, which he shared with an aunt
rather than tell his parents.
</P>
<P>
   The aunt managed to find a way to let the parents know without
breaking the teen's confidence, but Danburg said if he hadn't
gotten that help, ``he would have committed suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, those opposed to allowing adult siblings, aunts, uncles
and grandparents to ``bypass'' the parents question whether a
grandparent in a nursing home or sibling just a few years older or
uncle in a distant location could truly offer the help a parent
might otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill, the way I see it, is about parental notification,''
said Rep. Fred Hill, R-Richardson. ``The parents still have rights.
The right is nothing more than to be notified. They don't even get
a chance to make a decision. They just get a chance to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to notify other relatives failed, but another to
let relatives be notified in special cases cropped up.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patricia Gray, D-Galveston, had argued that in cases where
children had not lived at home for 30 days, often because the
parents are abusive or just don't care, another relative could be
told.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual twist, the conservative Republican Rep. Warren
Chisum of Pampa, backed Gray's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a reasonable additional bypass to the
courtroom. It doesn't throw it wide open,'' he said, arguing with
those who are often allied with him.
</P>
<P>
   Although that proposal also went down, two others succeeded. The
bill now no longer includes a jail term for doctors found guilty of
violating it. Instead they will face a maximum $10,000 in fines.
Meanwhile, affidavits placed in patients' files to establish a
defense for the doctor would no longer prove a ``conclusive''
defense but rather a ``presumed'' one.
</P>
<P>
   In a move highly disturbing to abortion rights advocates and
family planning groups, the House also changed committee wording of
how an abortion is defined. That wording, by Rep. Steve Wolens,
D-Dallas, had made clear the definition did not apply to
contraception and also deleted language defining what a fetus is.
By returning to Shapiro's language, argued Danburg, the bill could
be interpreted to outlaw contraception such as the IUD or the
``morning-after'' pill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Talmadge Heflin, R-Houston, who brought the amendment that
anti-abortion groups had sought, said Danburg is wrong. He also
denied criticism from Rep. Domingo Garcia, D-Dallas, that he was
``trying to make this into an abortion bill.'' Heflin said he
simply wanted wording that the U.S. Supreme Court had judged
constitutional in another state's law.
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote on the bill itself, Rep. Irma Rangel,
D-Kingsville, talked of the days when she handled rape and incest
cases as an assistant district attorney. She spoke of seeing
horrible things, such as the body of a young woman who had killed
herself by attempting an abortion with a coat hanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know their parents,'' she said of the types of girls
who might be endangered. ``We don't know anything. How dare we go
and try to intrude on a family we know nothing about? We know
little and yet we have the audacity to tell a young child what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
