<HEADLINE>
CERNER DESERVES THE UPTURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been a hectic time for Cerner Corp. lately, and frequent,
candid communication has been chief exec Neal Patterson's key
defense against sagging staff morale. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A missive he particularly prizes, however, was one he received
rather than sent. It was from a relatively new employee describing
a medical crisis involving her 84-year-old grandfather and his
chaotic emergency room visit. He was treated by three different
nurses, all of whom asked the same questions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not believe how unorganized it was,'' she wrote.
``Here was an older man trying to hang on, and they couldn't get
his paperwork right ... All I could think about (was how they
needed) a Cerner system.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The testimonial sheds light on why Cerner was chosen by Fortune
as one of the 100 best companies in America to work for. This was a
mission statement as well as an expression of employee devotion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who's suffered an extended bout with myriad health-care
providers can appreciate Cerner's mission. It has spent two decades
developing information management tools to make medical facilities
work better for both patients and caregivers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A facility using a Cerner system doesn't force its users through
the rigmarole of providing the same information during each initial
contact in the process. Physicians, nurses and clinicians are all
able to tap into needed data on new and old patients alike. As
pressures intensify to contain health-care costs, demand for
Cerner's wares is bound to soar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Cerner occasionally falls victim to the same
unkind marketplace vagaries that invariably befall all
entrepreneurial ventures. In early February, for instance, the
company's stock plunged nearly 30 percent in one day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When something like this happens, Cerner is particularly
vulnerable to morale problems because of its somewhat unusual
practice of offering stock options to every category of employee,
no matter how far down the pecking order. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things were looking up, though, during a visit to the corporate
campus Thursday. Wall Street apparently is now viewing Cerner's
situation with more equanimity. This was reflected in the stock's 3
5/8-point pop that day, which lifted it to 23 1/2, or about where
it was in early February. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patterson had warned analysts that 1999 would be a year of
shrinking markets, because existing and prospective clients would
focus more on fixing Y2K problems than buying new stuff. That
wasn't what Wall Street wanted to hear, so when these caveats
proved prescient, Cerner's stock got hammered, along with other
industry players. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things are improving. Not only is the core business regaining
its strength, but Cerner also has initiated strategic moves to
broaden its revenue base. Patterson is acutely aware of the need to
rebuild shareholder value, but he's confident the restructuring of
recent years will ensure this. Moves that previously slowed growth
will turbocharge Cerner's results entering the next millennium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A critical component, in fact, is dubbed the HNA Millennium.
It's the result of more than $130 million in capital outlays since
1993, all made in the name of Cerner taking medical information
management to new levels. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990521.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6995 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAPE-YOUTHS-KAN &LR;      05-21 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPE-YOUTHS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE BOYS CHARGED WITH RAPING TWIN 6-YEAR-OLD GIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN T. DAUNER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four 13-year-old boys and an 11-year-old boy were charged Friday
with multiple counts of aggravated criminal sodomy and rape in the
sexual assault last Saturday of twin 6-year-old girls at a Kansas
City, Kan., day-care facility.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon, police had four of the boys in custody
and were seeking the fifth. A sixth boy who was present but not
involved was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   Wyandotte County District Attorney Nick Tomasic said the boys
repeatedly assaulted the girls in the early afternoon while the
day-care operator, 55-year-old Margaret Hardridge, was on the
premises.
</P>
<P>
   One of the twins was severely traumatized, the other less so,
the district attorney said. The girls were treated Sunday evening
at the University of Kansas Medical Center after being picked up at
the day-care center for the second time in two days. They did not
tell their mother about the assault until Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasic said he had seen many cases over the years where
children were the victims of serious crimes and added, ``This is as
bad as any I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the five boys has serious juvenile records, said
Assistant District Attorney Vicki Meyer, chief juvenile prosecutor.
Two had been charged with shoplifting and went through a diversion
program.
</P>
<P>
   The boys are charged as juveniles, but under a 1998 law, youths
10 and older can be ordered to stand trial as adults. ``We haven't
decided, but it is a possibility that one or more of the boys will
be waived to adult status,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tomasic released the names of the children who were
charged, The Kansas City Star generally does not publish the names
of alleged offenders younger than 14. The newspaper's policy allows
for naming juveniles in selected cases, such as when public safety
is threatened, or if further developments in a case warrant
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasic said the twins were at the day-care facility, located in
large, side-by-side houses at 926 and 930 Ann Ave. from 6 a.m. to 4
p.m. Saturday. The assault occurred in the afternoon, first in a
shed in the backyard and then in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a day after the alleged assault was reported in the
media, some parents continued to take their children to the
day-care facility. On Wednesday, however, the state Department of
Health and Environment ordered the facility closed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The house at 926 Ann is a two-story brick structure; the one at
930 is a two-story frame house, with shingles on the sides. Slides
and swings and other playground equipment are in the back yards. On
Friday afternoon, there was no sign of activity outside either
house.
</P>
<P>
   Tax records show that Margaret Hardridge owns 930 Ann and the
other is rented.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasic said that before the assaults, the boys were playing
basketball in the back yard and the girls were swinging. About a
dozen children were in Hardridge's care, Tomasic said, and
Hardridge might have been indoors when the girls were assaulted in
the shed.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasic said it was possible that another adult was somewhere on
the premises but that no one was supervising the children outside.
</P>
<P>
   Police Detective J.B. Smith, who interviewed the six boys
Wednesday and Thursday, said, ``Two were remorseful and knew
something very bad had happened. One couldn't have cared less. He
was a smart-aleck teen-ager. The others ... answered our questions
politely.''
</P>
<P>
   Once arrested, the boys will be held in juvenile custody until
detention hearings next week. At the hearing, Meyer said, the
district attorney's office will ask that they be detained as
dangers to the community.
</P>
<P>
   When the girls told their mother Sunday that they had been
attacked, she took them immediately to the medical center, which is
near their home in the Armourdale area of Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   They were examined and treated by a doctor, who called police.
Physical evidence of rape and sodomy was recovered during the
examination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
