<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI MAN SENTENCED TO PRISON FOR SEXUAL ENCOUNTER WITH
13-YEAR-OLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As supportive family members looked on and his wife sobbed, a
Belton, Mo., man was ordered to prison Friday for a sexual
encounter with a 13-year-old girl he met on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   John Michael Wells, 30, will have to serve about five years of
the 70-month sentence before he can be released.
</P>
<P>
   He will also be required to register as a sex offender after he
leaves prison and provide a DNA sample for police files.
</P>
<P>
   The victim and her family were not in the Johnson County, Kan.,
courtroom Friday, but Brenda Cameron, assistant district attorney,
said the ``cheerful, bubbly, kindhearted'' girl had to be
hospitalized because of the emotional trauma of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her father wants you to know the complete devastation this
man's actions have had on the family,'' Cameron told District Judge
John Anderson III.
</P>
<P>
   Wells and the girl developed a relationship through Internet
chat rooms last year. He drove to her Overland Park, Kan., middle
school to meet her in October.
</P>
<P>
   They drove to a nearby parking lot, where the sexual activity
occurred. The girl's friends told police, and Wells was arrested
when he returned to the area to meet her again.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded guilty in March to felony charges of aggravated
indecent liberties with a child and aggravated indecent
solicitation.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Carl Cornwell, said Wells had never evaded his
responsibility or tried to shift blame to the victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will do whatever he can to make sure this problem is not
going to happen again,'' Cornwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells choked up as he apologized to everyone he had hurt. ``I'm
here to accept that responsibility,'' he told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson followed plea negotiations in imposing the sentence.
Cornwell and Cameron recommended the 70-month sentence. Cornwell
did not request probation for Wells, who had no prior criminal
record.
</P>
<P>
   Wells could have faced more than 16 years in prison if he had
been convicted of the rape charge originally filed against him.
Cameron dismissed that charge in exchange for his guilty pleas to
the other charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
