u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-CLELAND     05-21 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-CLELAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL SHOOTINGS CHANGED A SENATOR, AND A CRUCIAL VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As someone who once had to carry an assault rifle
in his job, losing an arm and both legs when he was a soldier in
Vietnam, Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., has always thought deeply about
the role guns play in American life.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, he tended to view the issue in Second Amendment
terms, giving heavy weight to the rights of gun owners in the
debate over how much blame easy access to weapons ought to shoulder
for mindless violence.
</P>
<P>
   But the succession of school shootings that have left dozens of
students around the country dead or wounded in the last year and a
half has recast the terms of the argument for many people,
including, Cleland said in an interview Friday, himself.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a strong conservative base in Georgia that opposes
new restrictions on gun ownership, his shift in outlook ultimately
led him to change his vote Thursday to support a measure that would
require background checks on all people who buy firearms at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The vote by Cleland, a first-term Democrat who opposed similar
legislation just last week, set up a 50-50 tie on the measure,
allowing Vice President Al Gore to cast a tiebreaking vote in favor
and making the provision an amendment to the juvenile-crime bill
that the Senate passed Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened has touched a raw nerve, and people have
reached the point where enough is enough,'' Cleland said Friday,
referring particularly to the shootings last month in Littleton,
Colo., and on Thursday morning in the senator's own state, where a
high school sophomore in the town of Conyers wounded six students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate connected with that nerve,'' Cleland said, ``and
found the courage and the momentum to deal with it. The normal gun
politics of pro-gun, anti-gun are not going to be looked at as
connecting with anyone. Now we're talking about children getting
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   When the background-check amendment was first offered last week
by Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., it was defeated by 51-47, with
Cleland and Sen. Max Baucus of Montana the only Democrats against
it. Cleland said Friday that he had found the mandatory nature of
the background check ``too heavy-handed'' and felt it would drive
guns into a black market and the unregulated sales venue of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, proposed voluntary
background checks, which Cleland preferred. But Cleland opposed
other provisions of Craig's proposal, like one that would have
shortened, to 24 hours from 3 days, the length of time given the
seller to perform the check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig had loopholes that turned the law backward,'' Cleland
said. ``I never intended for that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Craig amendment passed Thursday, only to be overtaken later
that day by a newly shaped Lautenberg proposal, backed by Cleland.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland said it was the tightening of the Craig proposal's
loopholes that had won his support for the Lautenberg amendment.
But he acknowledged that news of the shooting in Conyers, less than
10 miles from where he was reared in Lithonia, Ga., had been a
clincher, leaving him in no doubt that the Senate had to do
something to tighten gun controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely taken aback by something like this happening
so close to where I grew up _ that made it solid for me,'' said
Cleland, who must use a wheelchair because of his war injuries.
``When I went into the Senate, rolling down the aisle, I caught the
eye of the clerk and realized I made up my mind. I knew I had to do
the right thing. When the vice president voted, I felt an epiphany
because this was an issue I was struggling with.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleland said more needed to be done to control the flow of guns,
and a hard fight is ahead, he said, with the growing popularity of
the Internet. A measure introduced this week by Sen. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., that would have regulated Internet sales was
defeated. But Cleland said Schumer had drawn attention to an
important issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty percent of the country is online now,'' Cleland said.
``In 10 years, it will be 60 percent. We have to do more than just
look at gun shows; they're a convenient target. The Net _ that's
where the problem in the future lies, with the unregulated sales of
guns, explosive devices, you name it. That's something we're going
to have to get a handle on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
