<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF COURSE RICE WANTS BALL MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The question almost didn't need to be asked,
and the answer came as predictably as it has for the last four
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Glen Rice thinks he needs to be more involved for the Los
Angeles Lakers to reverse their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Rice has made this plea before. After a three-game losing streak
in late April. After a loss to Houston in the first round of the
playoffs. Truth is, he's grown weary of making the point.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is, he's right. The Lakers were 12-4 in
regular-season games in which Rice took at least 14 shots. And Rice
plays at his best when the Lakers' ball and player movement is at
its best.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers' offense has been stagnant in two straight losses
to the San Antonio Spurs, and though Rice is averaging 15 shots a
game, the lack of movement and screen-setting has him slumping at a
40 percent clip. He scored just 16 points in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone back to the point where I'm just standing, buried
out on the wing or buried deep in the corner,'' Rice lamented
Friday. ``I think we're making (the Spurs) job a lot easier than it
should be. I think anytime you put a defender on me and he has to
just guard me when I'm just standing, it's going to make their job
a lot easier. And we don't want to make anyone's job easy.''
</P>
<P>
   With Shaquille O'Neal blanketed by 7-foot defenders, the Lakers
need an offensive jolt from Rice and Kobe Bryant to get back into
this best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to get him the ball,'' O'Neal said, referring to
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   As for a greater role in Games 3 and 4, Rice said: ``You would
hope so.'' But he's not going to ask coach Kurt Rambis to change
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we're not talking about it. I'm done talking about it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for why the Lakers have reverted to a stand-around-and-watch
offense, Rice said, ``I have no idea. That's a question for the
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Spurs have noticed the lack of plays for Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're going to get Glen Rice involved a little
more,'' said Mario Elie, who has been guarding him. ``It's been
surprising to me that they haven't been going to him more.''
</P>
<P>
   No excuses: J.R. Reid said there was some confusion in the
huddle before the play in which Tim Duncan sank the game-winning
jumpshot in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was guarding Duncan on the play and failed to foul him,
even though the Lakers had a foul to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many things were said. I remember (coaches) saying we have
a foul to give, but we didn't know when we were gonna use it or
whatever,'' Reid said. ``But I should have done a better job of not
letting him catch it so deep in the paint.... You can always go
back and say things should have been done differently, but it's
just the way it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry knows the reason for the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That comes from when you've got too many people in the huddle
talking,'' he said. ``The last couple games, we've been having too
many people talk, saying stuff.... The communication is not
heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie, a nine-year veteran, said the Lakers' mental mistakes were
typical of a young team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've just gotta concentrate for a 48-minute game. They
played a terrific 46-minute game, but the last two minutes is where
you've gotta get it done,'' he said. ``If they keep making the
mistakes, that's fine with me. They'll be out of the series.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Kobe: Just how rare were Bryant's two missed free throws
in the waning seconds of Game 2? Pretty rare.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant has generally been at his clutch-shooting best late in
games. This season, he made 86.2 percent of all second-half free
throws _ 87.3 percent in the third quarter, 85.6 percent in the
fourth. By comparison, he hit only 79.6 percent of first-half free
throws.
</P>
</TEXT>
