<SLUG> BC-INS-ARCHIVES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE'S SUMMIT FACILITY TO HOUSE IMMIGRATION RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The paper trail on all immigrants in the United
States will lead to Lee's Summit, Mo., when the federal Immigration
and Naturalization Service opens a huge underground records center
in September.
</P>
<P>
   The service will send 25 million immigration files from 80
offices around the country to a new facility in limestone caverns
south of Interstate 70 on Lee's Summit Road.
</P>
<P>
   The General Services Administration signed a 20-year lease with
Space Center Kansas City Inc., for the 200,000-square-foot
location. A formal announcement is planned for early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Locations nationwide were considered for the records center,
generating some strong competitive pitches from congressional and
local delegations in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news for the Kansas City area,'' said Bob
Marcusse, president and chief executive officer of the Kansas City
Area Economic Development Council. ``The 400 new jobs will
reinforce our area's position as the Midwest's fastest growing job
market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a big opportunity for us,'' said Curt Wenson,
assistant to the Lee's Summit city administrator. ``For one thing,
having a positive relationship with the federal government is
always a plus. The jobs are what we are really excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   About 150 people will work at the center initially, involving 80
federal employees and about 70 contract labor employees, federal
officials said. Within a few years, the total staff is expected to
number 400, most expected to be from the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican, and U.S. Rep.
Karen McCarthy of Kansas City, a Democrat, both took partial credit
Friday for the selection of Lee's Summit as the site. Ashcroft
serves on a committee that oversees the immigration service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Ashcroft has been closely involved in this for a year and
a half,'' spokesman Steve Hilton said. McCarthy also has been
involved in meetings on the center, spokesman Phil Scaglia said.
</P>
<P>
   The central location of Kansas City and the underground storage
capability worked strongly in favor of the Lee's Summit proposal,
immigration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Space Center Kansas City has about 1.4 million square feet of
underground space in Lee's Summit and 4.5 million more in
Independence, Mo., company vice president Charlie Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County, Mo., the state of Missouri, the National
Archives and the Social Security Administration have records stored
underground with Space Center, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a constant temperature and humidity control, so
operating costs are very, very cheap,'' he said. Underground
storage gives records greater protection from decay, natural
disaster or theft, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The new records center mostly will house records of living or
recently deceased immigrants, but records dating back to the 1950s
are being sent to the National Archives storage center already in
Kansas City-area caverns.
</P>
<P>
   Counting the archives files, 50 million immigration files will
end up in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, records kept on people's entry into the United
States, their marriages, naturalization proceedings or other
changes in status are kept in offices in the region where the
people live.
</P>
<P>
   Finding records on people can be difficult when they move around
a lot, said Elaine Komis, spokeswoman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service. Sending all records to one place will be
much more efficient, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we will cut retrieval time to a matter of a few days,
and now it can take months or weeks,'' Komis said. ``That will
result in a more timely application process.''
</P>
<P>
   The records center will not be a public facility where families
can do genealogy research, Komis said. Records are restricted to
internal use, but people may seek records on themselves and
relatives through written requests, as they do now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
