<HEADLINE>
CAN CLIPPERS PULL OFF REPEAT IN LOTTERY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chris Ford can be seen on national TV today,
performing a duty that seems as impressive as becoming
valedictorian of summer school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm the guy,'' said Ford, sounding very much like a guy
who would have preferred to be the guy somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Clippers coach happens to be in Secaucus, N.J.,
assigned as a representative for his team in the NBA's draft
lottery derby, an upgraded-for-TV event that will occur at halftime
of the Spurs-Lakers playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Clippers didn't qualify for the playoffs, they and
12 others are eligible to acquire the first pick in the NBA Draft,
held June 30 at Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, who selected center Michael Olowokandi with the
first pick last year, hope to equal this season's high-water mark
for consecutive victories by winning their second lottery in a row.
Ford said he will not be toting any good-luck charms.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's not much to see. The 13 poor souls
representing the non-playoff teams will be introduced by
commissioner David Stern. Then the process of using Ping-Pong-ball
combinations to determine the first three picks will be explained,
and simulated drama may be whipped up before the draft order is
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Ping-Pong balls numbered 1 through 14 are loaded into the hopper
with 1,001 four-ball combinations divided up and issued to each
team, the number of possibilities corresponding to the franchise's
1999 on-court futility. The Vancouver Grizzlies, eligible for the
No.1 pick for the first time, have 250 four-ball combinations. The
Charlotte Hornets, best among the NBA's bad teams, have just five.
That's five chances out of 1,001 to score the first pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers have 200.
</P>
<P>
   A statistic that could make the process a bit more dramatic:
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, only two teams with Ping-Pong supremacy going
into the lottery came out with the top pick _ Philadelphia in 1996
(Allen Iverson) and New Jersey in 1990 (Derrick Coleman).
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Boston Celtics and new coach Rick Pitino
seemingly had a lock on No. 1, but slipped to No.3 when the
Ping-Pong dust settled. Tim Duncan was taken with the top pick that
season by San Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2337EDT &QL; 
