<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATS STAY HOT AS METS HOLD OFF PHILLIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For most of this season, the New York Mets have been
the opposite of what they were a year ago. Their revamped offense
has been productive, but their starting pitching has yet to come
around.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night at Shea Stadium, however, almost everything came
together for the second consecutive game, everything, that is,
until the bullpen provided a little scare.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not only did an offense led by John Olerud, Mike Piazza
and the rookie surprise Benny Agbayani pound out 13 hits against
five Philadelphia pitchers, but Orel Hershiser turned in his
strongest performance of the season in a 7-5 victory over the
Phillies _ one that needed to be saved by Armando Benitez and John
Franco after Turk Wendell allowed three eighth-inning runs without
getting anyone out. Benitez and Franco struck out five of the six
batters they faced, with Franco picking up his 13th save.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud drove in three runs with a single, home run and double to
extend his hitting streak to 11 games. Piazza homered in his fourth
consecutive game, a feat last accomplished with the Mets by Bobby
Bonilla in 1992. Agbayani was 3 for 4 with a stolen base, a run
scored and a run batted in and now has 13 hits in his last 17
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   And then, after the Phillies had rallied from 7-0 down to 7-5
with a runner on third and none out in the eighth, Benitez came on
to strike out Mike Lieberthal and Desi Relaford, before
pinch-hitter Alex Arias grounded to second to end the threat. Then
Franco finished.
</P>
<P>
   After a 4-9 slide, the Mets (24-18) have won three straight
games to pull two games ahead of the third-place Phillies in the NL
East.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, meanwhile, tossed six scoreless innings before tiring
in the seventh. In his longest outing of the season, Hershiser
(3-4) allowed two runs and six hits in 6 2-3 innings with three
walks and four strikeouts. He departed after 110 pitches, 67 of
them strikes, and with a 7-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   His last time out, Hershiser tossed five scoreless innings in
Philadelphia only to surrender four sixth-inning runs in what
turned into a 5-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Hershiser took a 7-0 lead into the sixth inning.
But only when the Phillies loaded the bases with two out did
manager Bobby Valentine have somebody up in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's faith in Hershiser paid off when Hershiser caught
Ron Gant looking at an 87 mile-an-hour 1-2 fastball for the final
out. And when the Phillies finally knocked Hershiser out in the
seventh, the pitcher made his way to the dugout to a strong
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser even helped himself at bat, singling in a run and then
hustling home from first on an Edgardo Alfonzo double for the final
run of a three-run third that gave the Mets a 6-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had taken a 3-0 lead in the third on consecutive home
runs by Olerud and Piazza off Philadelphia right-hander Carlton
Loewer. Roger Cedeno had opened the inning with a single and then
his hard slide at second helped foil an attempted double play.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud then hammered Loewer's next pitch off the base of the
scoreboard in right for his eighth home run. Three pitches later,
Piazza homered to the opposite field in right _ his eighth of the
season, too _ to become the sixth Mets player to homer in four
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, things were busy for the Mets, too. They will
most likely activate Rickey Henderson from the disabled list before
Saturday afternoon's game, Valentine said before Friday night's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson has been out since May 3 with a right knee sprain. He
said his leg feels about 85 percent. ``I've been with other clubs
that have said my 85 percent is better than someone else's 100
percent,'' Henderson said Friday before running the bases during
batting practice. ``But the way Roger and Benny are playing, they
really have given us a chance to let it heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Cedeno, whose favorite player while growing up was
Henderson, began Friday night's game tied for the N.L. lead in
stolen bases with a career-high 21. Agbayani, meanwhile, has been
an even bigger surprise. The former replacement player is batting
.529 since his contract was purchased from Triple-A Norfolk on May
12. In nine games overall, he is 18 for 34 with three home runs and
seven runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing the job,'' Henderson said. ``So I don't have to
rush it too much.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
