<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOM-WATSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING CHAMP WATSON MAKES COLONIAL CUT, DELAYS SENIOR SWITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Tom Watson, the once freckled youngster who knocked
off the Golden Bear, is entering the Golden Age. Unfortunately, his
erratic game looks to be following him.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Watson dazzled fans and proved, at 48, he could still
win on the PGA Tour by winning the MasterCard Colonial. Now
approaching 50, Watson's announcement on Wednesday that this
Colonial will be his final regular PGA Tour event before joining
the Senior PGA Tour in September seems a rational decision.
</P>
<P>
   Watson finished yesterday with an even-par 70 to go 4 over par
for the tournament. Near the bottom of the leader board, he found
himself on the brink of elimination. Four hours after Watson walked
into the clubhouse he learned his two-day total of 144 was good
enough to qualify for the final two rounds of the 53rd Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Watson struggled in shooting a 74 during Thursday's gusty
opening round, then used a tip he received during dinner with Byron
Nelson to shave four strokes yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Byron said he noticed something on TV about my swing. So he
gave me a quick lesson, and it helped a little bit on some
swings,'' Watson said. ``But I'm still struggling to make cuts.
That's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson plans to compete in two major championships, the U.S.
Open and British Open, before becoming a full-time player on the
50-and-over circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Watson tried to downplay the sentimental angle after completing
yesterday's round when it appeared he had played himself out of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking that this would be my last tournament,''
Watson said. ``I'm still going to be out here some. This isn't like
a real goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   While Watson tried to stay alive down the stretch by shooting a
33 on the back-nine, he watched his two playing partners, John Cook
and Scott Hoch, contend for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cook shot 66 and finished at 6 under, one stroke behind leader
Corey Pavin. Hoch also shot 66 to move to 5 under par and into a
four-way tie for third.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said the playing partners never focused on the possibility
of it being Watson's final round at a regular tour event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played a lot of my best golf when I've played with him,''
Cook said. ``To have another chance to play with one of the
greatest players of all time was really special. We'll all miss
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since turning pro out of Stanford in 1971, Watson has 34
tournament victories, his last coming at the 1998 Colonial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2348EDT &QL; 
