<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Homers in 9th batter Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The biggest Turner Field crowd of the year showed up
Friday night to watch the Braves and rookie Bruce Chen see what
they could do with the Cubs, while John Smoltz watched from the
dugout on the disabled list with a sore elbow.
</P>
<P>
   What the crowd of 48,315 watched ended up looking a lot like
what the 38,588 fans saw the night before _ a late rally by Chicago
for a 8-4 win _ and another loss credited to Atlanta rookie Kevin
McGlinchy.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves clawed back from a scary first inning for Chen and
evened the score 4-4 on a two-run homer by Brian Jordan and
run-scoring doubles from Chipper Jones and Javy Lopez. But a
leadoff walk to Tyler Houston on four McGlinchy pitches to start
the ninth inning, followed by a two-run homer by Henry Rodriguez
had the Cubs beating Atlanta for the fourth time in the five games
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club is battling their rear-ends off, we could easily
have two wins,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``We needed to rest
some guys. Obviously, it looked like McGlinchy could have used some
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Three batters after Rodriguez, Jeff Blauser slammed a two-run
homer to left field to insure the Cubs of their fourth consecutive
win in Atlanta dating back through last July's two-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We match up against the Braves pretty well for some reason,''
said Blauser, who had his first home run since last August and
second ever against his former team. ``It's nice to hit a home run,
the fact that it came against the Braves is secondary. All the
credit goes to Henry.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the same Cubs lineup that's given Greg Maddux, Tom
Glavine and Smoltz fits over the seven days, Chen found his own set
of problems when Gary Gaetti welcomed him back to the big leagues
with a grand slam in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Chen retired 16 of the next 19 batters he faced, giving up only
a walk and two singles, and used some well-placed fastballs to
match his career-high with seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
