<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOOK FOR WINNING FORMULA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In order for the Los Angeles Dodgers to put
together an impressive winning streak they must first put together
a winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers may have entered Friday's game with the St. Louis
Cardinals a game behind first-place San Francisco in the loss
column, but they also went into the three-game series looking for
back-to-back wins for the first time in May.
</P>
<P>
   It's got management shaking their heads, namely because the
Dodgers are losing games in so many ways.
</P>
<P>
   One loss could be blamed on baserunning. Another on poor
starting pitching. Another on fielding. Another on a lack of timely
hitting. Another on poor relief pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, it's something different each night,''
Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. ``If it was one thing,
we could fix it. At some point, it's got to end. This team cares.
It wants to win. We'll figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone was careful to mention that there were still more than
120 games to play. But he also said he wasn't pleased with the way
the Dodgers, who were 21-19, were playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As poorly as we've played at times, we're still in the hunt,''
Malone said. ``Maybe that's a cheap perspective. (But) it's a true
statement. I think we can only play better. If we stay healthy, we
have to play better than we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Individually, the Dodgers' position players have performed well
offensively. Raul Mondesi's 15 homers led the NL, Gary Sheffield
and Adrian Beltre were hitting above .300 and Eric Young has 20
stolen bases. And Young and Mark Grudzielanek have been sharp
defensively through the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves the pitching. The bullpen has been above average
but the starters, outside of Kevin Brown and Ismael Valdes, have
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put it all together and it should equate to more wins,''
Malone said. ``We haven't played up to our capabilities ... We
haven't played our best baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to make us tougher in the long run. We're not
content. We're not pleased with where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   A look back: Lost in the Dodgers' 4-3 loss Thursday to Houston
was the outing of right-hander Chan Ho Park, who allowed one run in
seven innings and eased his psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Admonished by Dodgers manager Davey Johnson for not using, nor
trusting, his fastball in his past few starts, Park mixed his
mid-90 mph fastball with offspeed pitches to hold the Astros, the
NL's best hitting team, to five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw a little more offspeed pitches early and then the
fastball,'' Park said. ``They're good fastball hitters. I threw
offspeed for a lot of strikes. If I throw a strike with the
offspeed pitches, it's really easy to get confidence with the
fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Keepin' the faith: When the Dodgers sent outfielder Trenidad
Hubbard to the minor leagues the day before the season began, it
stunned him. Hubbard, who hit .298 with the Dodgers last season and
thought he had the fifth outfielder's job won, said it took a lot
of gumption to remain focused at Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of talking to myself to keep the right
mindset, the right focus,'' said Hubbard, who was recalled Tuesday.
``It was difficult to muster up energy to play at (that) level.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: The weekend series with the Cardinals is
sold out, which should increase the Dodgers' standing as the NL's
leader in attendance. They drew 797,715 in their first 21 games....
Todd Hundley threw out Joe McEwing trying to steal second in the
fourth inning. It was the third of nine would-be base stealers
Hundley's thrown out after beginning the season by allowing 26
steals in 28 attempts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-21-99 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
